<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-JOHNSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REV. ROBERT ROSS JOHNSON, 79, FIRST PASTOR OF QUEENS CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rev. Robert Ross Johnson, a leading clergyman in Queens for
nearly four decades and a former chaplain for the New York City
Department of Correction, died on March 29 at a hospital in
Atlanta. He was 79 and had moved to Atlanta in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   He suffered a long illness, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the founding pastor of the St. Albans Congregational
Church, which was established in 1953 and thrived in a black
middle-class neighborhood of Queens. Its A-frame structure on
Linden Boulevard was designed by Frank Lloyd Wright, and Johnson
preached from its pulpit until retiring in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Long active in civic and community affairs, Johnson was a prison
chaplain for 23 years and was on his local school board. In 1969,
Mayor John V. Lindsay appointed him to the city's Board of Higher
Education.
</P>
<P>
   He founded the Human Relations Center of St. Albans to serve
southeastern Queens with cultural and social programs. The center
is now known as the Robert Ross Johnson Family Life Center.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Spokane, Wash., Johnson majored in social science with a
premedical minor at Whitworth College in Spokane, from which he
graduated in 1943. He received a Master of Divinity degree from
Colgate-Rochester Divinity School in 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was pastor of the Second Baptist Church in Le Roy, N.Y.,
and co-minister of the interracial South Congregational Church in
Chicago. He came to Brooklyn in 1952 to lead the Nazarene
Congregational Church in Bedford-Stuyvesant but was asked the
following year to start a Congregational church in St. Albans.
</P>
<P>
   He was a founder of York College in Jamaica, Queens; a founding
director of the Queens Inter-Faith Clergy Council; a former
director of the NAACP and YMCA boards; and a member of the National
Conference of Christians and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is survived by his wife of 54 years, Ernestine Norwood
Johnson; a daughter, Michele J. Tompkins of Atlanta; two sons,
Stephen R., of Manhattan, and John E., of Atlanta; and three
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
