A8506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-TRANSPLANTS-NYT &LR;      04-06 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TRANSPLANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TRANSPLANT POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Thursday, April 6:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's sensible plan to ensure that human
organs donated for transplants are allocated according to medical
need, not geographic happenstance, encountered a new roadblock on
Tuesday. By a vote of 275-147, the House approved legislation that
would move authority to decide how organs are distributed across
the country from the Department of Health and Human Services, where
it belongs, to the private agency now under contract with the
government to coordinate distribution, the nonprofit United Network
for Organ Sharing.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is the latest turn in a fierce turf war with
potential life-or-death consequences for the estimated 68,000
Americans who are currently waiting for a heart, lung, liver,
kidney or pancreas. If enacted, it would nullify a federal
regulation that directs the network to revise its allocation system
so that organs are shared broadly across regional lines to allow
them to reach the neediest patients. President Clinton is right to
threaten a veto.
</P>
<P>
   The existing system directs most organs to be used in the local
area where they are donated. If a matching patient is not found,
the organ is then offered regionally, or in rare instances
nationally. The unfortunate result is waiting times that vary
greatly from region to region, and unfairness to desperately ill
patients who have the misfortune of residing outside the
procurement area.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to a more rational distribution system stems from
fears that it would put small transplant centers out of business
and discourage organ donations if they might end up outside the
local community. These concerns were judged to be overblown by the
Institute of Medicine, a branch of the National Academy of
Sciences, in a 1999 report commissioned by Congress. That report
affirmed the good sense of sharing organs across wider regions and
the need for active federal oversight of the sort the House has now
voted to remove.
</P>
<P>
   (sw)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
