<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS SEE LEGISLATORS IN INACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BY E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - In broad daylight Wednesday, April 5, a group of
suspicious-looking characters armed with highly explosive ideas,
hair-trigger convictions and fully loaded brains slipped right
under the noses of police and security personnel and onto the
grounds of the state Capitol.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exactly how a security breach of this magnitude could have
occurred is currently un der investigation, especially be cause the
suspects not only were younger and better looking than everyone
working at the Capitol, but quickly re vealed themselves as
political outsiders by speaking in com plete sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there they were _ stu dents.
</P>
<P>
   They'd come to the Capitol to rally in favor of additional edu
cation funding. It is their belief, they say, that Arizona's Instru
ment to Measure Standards, or AIMS test, is not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the young people be lieve our tax money might be better
spent on higher pay for teachers or expanded facilities for schools
or broader opportu nities for pupils.
</P>
<P>
   They contend that such poli cies would go further toward lifting
Arizona from the bottom of the national rankings in edu cation than
would cheesy gim micks or lip service.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing these eager, in telligent, dedicated youngsters,
I'm convinced Arizona legisla tors will get the message.
</P>
<P>
   They'll see that, in spite of their best effort to deconstruct
the public school system and completely demoralize educa tors,
Arizona schools continue turning out young people who aren't as
stupid as our politi cians would like them to be.
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. The legislators will keep working on it.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, they've tried to build on statistics show ing
Arizona to be worst in the Union when it comes to high school
dropouts.
</P>
<P>
   When the legislative session began, Senate Appropriations
Chairman Randall Gnant told a reporter, ``Education requests are
important, but so are a lot of other issues. Get in line and make a
case.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a philosophy places edu cation issues somewhere behind
proposals to build a stadium for fat cats, closing down strip bars
and seceding from the Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always hear the talk from the politicians about edu cation,
but we never see the walk,'' said Mickey Goldman, one of the
organizers of the student demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, a senior at Thun derbird High School who plans to
attend Arizona State Univer sity, added, ``The legislators don't
want to deal with the issue,and we thought a student-organized
rally could help. Who better to rally in support of education than
the students, who deal with it every day?''
</P>
<P>
   He's correct.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, when students visit the Capitol and have a chance
to speak with elected officials, they quicklylearn there's no AIMS
test for legis lators.
</P>
<P>
   They also find out that just about all of our politicians would
be capable of passing a political GAMES test, in which officials
avoid dealing with edu cation problems by proposing such idiot
schemes as allowing guns in city parks and play grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Students discover as well that legislators would ace any BLAME
test by aggressively pointing the finger at each other or the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   And that our elected officials would do very well on a false
CLAIMS test, during which they would contend it's the other guy
who's stalling reform, not them.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable lesson taught by a visit to the Capitol,
however, is that Arizona politi cians would score an absolute zero
on the SHAME test.
</P>
<P>
   They have none. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Montini at &QL; 
Ed.Montini &LR; ArizonaRepublic.com or (602) 444-8978. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
