<HEADER>
A8511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-LEGAL-NYT &LR;      04-06 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LEGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TEST CASE FOR EQUAL JUSTICE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial of Thursday, April 6:
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has accepted a case that will decide the
constitutionality of a critical element of Congress' harshly
punitive attack on the federally financed legal services program,
which assists poor people with legal problems. The court's ultimate
ruling will say much about the justices' commitment to free speech
and equal justice under law.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is whether Congress violated the First Amendment in
1996 when it limited the sorts of arguments that lawyers supported
by the federal Legal Services Corp. can make on behalf of clients
seeking welfare benefits. Poverty lawyers whose offices receive
federal money may seek welfare benefits for individual clients but
may not file suits seeking to ``amend or otherwise challenge'' the
statutes or regulations that prevent their clients from gaining
benefits. That is particularly onerous in the new era of welfare
reform experiments by the states when poorly conceived provisions
may harm the poor unless changed.
</P>
<P>
   Last year a federal appeals court in New York correctly struck
down the provision because its attempt to ``discourage challenges
to the status quo'' amounted to impermissible ``viewpoint
discrimination'' by the government. But the Clinton administration
is defending the restriction, arguing that government has broad
leeway to attach strings to the use of federal money. The
administration cites a regrettable 1991 Supreme Court decision that
upheld a ban on counseling about abortion in family planning
clinics receiving federal money.
</P>
<P>
   That argument too willingly accepts the restriction's affront to
free speech and ignores the larger assault on justice when lawyers
for poor clients are barred from using the same advocacy tools that
private lawyers use. The net effect, as New York University's
Brennan Center for Justice aptly observed in its brief, is to place
``low-income legal services clients at a substantial disadvantage
as they seek to vindicate their rights.''
</P>
<P>
   (sw) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
