A8514 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MCPORK-AZR &LR;      04-06 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCPORK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN HITS `PORK' FOR ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 BY BY JEFF BARKER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
 Republic Washington Bureau 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
WASHINGTON _ While Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., was crusaded to halt
``pork-barrel'' spending, his state's congressional delegation
doubled its haul of pork projects for the folks back home,
according to a new report.
</P>
<P>
   As its members gained seniority and power, Arizona's delegation
tapped into the tempting windfall of the budget surplus to deliver
nearly $100 million in specially targeted money for all kinds of
home-state projects that critics dubbed ``pork.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the projects _ ranging from downtown Yuma improvements
to an Army wastewater treatment plant _ were passionately defended
Wednesday, April 5, by the Arizona members who sponsored them in
the 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Their protests pitted them at least indirectly against McCain,
who appeared at a news conference Wednesday to support a watchdog
group in the release of its annual report chiding Congress for
``unnecessary and wasteful'' spending.
</P>
<P>
   The group, Citizens Against Government Waste, said lawmakers
brought home 4,326 pork projects nationwide costing a record $17.7
billion. To dramatize their point, McCain and the group's
president, Thomas Schatz, stood next to a 200-pound Vietnamese
potbellied pig that stood in a trough and rooted around in fake
dollar bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fiscal 2000, Congress went whole hog, porking up the
various spending bills with billions of dollars in worthless
earmarks,'' Schatz said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona's total bounty was double the $49 million it raked in
during fiscal 1999, moving the state from 48th in the nation in
``pork per capita'' to 28th, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   The report said the Arizona pork in this year's budget includes
$11.6 million for family housing at the Yuma Marine Corps Air
Station, $150,000 for a downtown Yuma rejuvenation project, $1
million for a science center in Tempe, and an unspecified amount
for University of Arizona research on raising shrimp, research that
is being shared with four other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know there was enough water in Arizona for
shrimp,'' Aaron Taylor of the citizens' group said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's battle against wasteful spending was a centerpiece of
his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's self-appointed role as fiscal watchdog has occasionally
antagonized members of his own delegation and the Senate Republican
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Although he never made an issue of it publicly, Rep. Bob Stump,
R-Ariz., is still sore about the ``pork'' label attached to $10
million in funding for a land purchase a few years ago at the Barry
M. Goldwater Range.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens' group, backed by McCain, included the range
funding in its 1998 ``Pig Book'' because the project wasn't
requested in advance by the Air Force and didn't appear in
President Clinton's budget plan. McCain insists that federal
agencies or military include its pleas for funding in the
president's budget so Congress doesn't add projects later that
aren't really needed.
</P>
<P>
   Stump said, ``Citizens Against Government Waste often identifies
spending as pork simply because it was proposed by Congress rather
than the president.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the range funding, Stump said a presidential
budget request would have been impossible because the land was
still the subject of a legal dispute between the federal government
and the state of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Stump was the only Republican in the state's House delegation
not to endorse McCain's presidential bid. While the pork dispute
may have helped create distance between the two, Stump has said it
wasn't the reason for not backing McCain. Stump says he simply
wanted to stay neutral during the primaries.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., said Wednesday's report cited as
``pork'' an ambulatory health care center and a family housing
project he fought for at Davis-Monthan Air Force Base. The report
said the projects hadn't been requested in the president's budget,
as required.
</P>
<P>
   But Kolbe said the center replaced trailerlike facilities on the
base and the housing was needed because the units were obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``No apologies,'' Kolbe said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not return calls to his office seeking comment. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Jeff.Barker(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
1-(202)-662-7264. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
