<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES SHUT OUT METS, 4-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If a pitcher's success is determined by how well he
spots his pitches, Bobby J. Jones would have gotten progressively
better as Wednesday night went on.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets right-hander worked a 1-2-3 first inning against the
San Diego Padres, but he felt his fastball was too high in the
strike zone. He improved on his location the next two innings, but
the results were drastically different: the Padres scored four runs
and Jones was gone before the final out of the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes good pitches get hit,'' he said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   In his first start since last May, when he was sidelined with
bursitis in his pitching shoulder, Jones fell to the Padres, 4-0.
The outcome displeased the right-hander, but the way he pitched did
not discourage him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're never happy with a loss,'' said Jones, who allowed four
runs on six hits in two and two-thirds innings, ``but I look back
and they weren't hitting balls in the gap all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine removed Jones after a bases-loaded walk
to Bret Boone forced in the Padres' fourth run. Jones had been
getting ahead of the hitters, and threw 49 strikes among his 74
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said he could have left Jones in longer, but decided
against it because it was Jones' first start and the weather was so
cold. It was 41 degrees at game time, but it felt colder; several
Mets said they saw snow flurries on their way to the park, and some
wore ski caps during pregame warm-ups. Far fewer fans than the
announced crowd of 17,585 showed up at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jones walked Phil Nevin to lead off the second, and Boone drove
him in two batters later with a double to the right-center warning
track. Ruben Rivera followed by blooping a double down the
right-field line, scoring Boone. After Carlos Hernandez's chopper
deflected off Jones' glove for a single, Rivera scored, and the
Padres led, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Mets starting pitchers had allowed only three runs in the last
21 innings before Wednesday night; Jones permitted that many in a
span of five hitters in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The final run came in the third on the walk to Boone, who fought
back from an 0-and-2 count and took first base on a slider that
just missed the strike zone. Jones had also gotten to 0-2 against
the previous hitter, Eric Owens, who fouled off two pitches before
eventually topping a curveball to third. Robin Ventura was playing
back to keep a hit from going through the hole, and his throw to
first arrived too late to get Owens, prolonging the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' offense, which has only 10 runs while batting .185
over four games, had several opportunities against the Padres
starter Woody Williams. But the Mets stranded 11 runners, seven in
scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating,'' Mike Piazza said. ``I think we have to be
a little more disciplined and swing the bats better. We're getting
into situations where we're overswinging and not getting good
pitches to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' best chance came in the fourth, when a single by
Ventura and back-to-back walks loaded the bases for Rey Ordonez.
But he swung at the first pitch, popping up to second, and the
pinch-hitter Jon Nunnally followed with a strikeout. Rickey
Henderson grounded sharply to first, but Ryan Klesko fielded the
ball and beat Henderson to the bag, ending the inning and keeping
the Mets scoreless.
</P>
<P>
   Williams allowed no runs on five hits and was removed for Carlos
Almanzar to start the seventh. Almanzar allowed a leadoff double to
Edgardo Alfonzo in the eighth, and with runners at first and second
and one out, Derek Bell struck out looking on a pitch that appeared
to be well outside.
</P>
<P>
   Bell returned to the dugout with eyebrows raised, in obvious
disagreement with Umpire Wally Bell's call. Todd Zeile, who had two
hits (including a double for the second game in a row), ended the
inning with another strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, who is making the transition from third base to first,
committed his second error of the season last night. He drifted
back on a pop-up by Williams in the fourth. The second baseman,
Alfonzo, raced over and had a better angle on the ball, but Zeile
was calling for it all the way, and it dropped just behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Williams advanced to second on a single by Al Martin, but the
reliever Pat Mahomes escaped the jam. Mahomes, Rich Rodriguez, Turk
Wendell and Dennis Cook provided scoreless relief over six and
one-third innings for the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   (sw)
</P>
</TEXT>
