<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLANETS-ALIGNMENT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANETARY ALIGNMENT TO BEGIN TODAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``a'' national news file.) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Look to the western skies tonight to see a rare
clustering of three planets and the crescent moon, a 20-year event
that some fear is the beginning of the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   It all will start about 8:15 tonight when Mars, Jupiter and
Saturn will bunch up next to the moon. And it will all climax when
Earth, Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn align with the sun
between May 5 and May 16, an occurrence some predict will trigger a
stock market crash, unleash earthquakes and cause all manner of bad
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all lined up in Taurus _ that's the monetary, that's
the stock market. Things are getting crazy already,'' said Carol
Krause, owner of Astro Connections, an astrology shop in Sherman
Oaks. ``Whatever happens is going to make a lot of noise.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers, however, view the alignment with a cosmic yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scientists have no interest in it at all,'' said John Mosley,
an astronomer at the Griffith Observatory. ``The only way we know
about it is because people ask.''
</P>
<P>
   One demonstrable effect of six planets falling in line with the
sun is that Earth will experience greater gravitational stresses.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers said that influence will amount to just about zip,
however. On Earth, where the moon alone lifts tides as much as four
feet, the tug of the assembled planets will lift them
three-thousandths of an inch more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be looked at in perspective. There's not going to be
any catastrophes,'' said Roger Sinnott, associate editor of Sky and
Telescope magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsayers believe the pull of gravity will set loose a swarm of
quakes and more activity on the sun's surface, causing Earth's
poles to shift.
</P>
<P>
   In anticipation, author Richard Noone issued a warning in his
book, ``5/5/2000 Ice: The Ultimate Disaster,'' in which he predicts
bizarre weather and general calamity. On his Web site he offers his
book, a survival catalog, for $2 and ``Basic Preparedness,'' a
how-to book, for $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   Magazine editor Sinnott said the alignment of planets has long
intrigued people and crept into popular mythology and even the
language, as those experiencing good luck, bad luck or general odd
situations have attributed it to planetary alignments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Astrology for thousands of years has been concerned with
planets being lined up. I'm sure that's how the expressions have
crept into the language,'' said Sinnott, whose magazine is devoting
the bulk of its content to the alignment.
</P>
<P>
   Alignments, which take place about every 20 years, have been as
good a reason as any for soothsayers past and present to predict
the worst, never the best.
</P>
<P>
   If alignments haven't influenced history significantly, they
have at least influenced historic figures. Sinnott notes that Nazi
Rudolph Hess timed his moves by planetary alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One was right in the middle of World War II, when Rudolph Hess
flew to Scotland,'' Sinnott said. ``He picked the date of early May
1941 to escape Germany, based primarily on the advice of his
astrologer.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mosley's money, tonight's spectacle, when the three planets
are bunched tightest, is the more important event _ if for no other
reason than it is visible.
</P>
<P>
   Patient viewers will have a chance to observe something most
people have to wait years to see: the movement of planets. Mars
will spend the next few nights drifting past Jupiter and then
Saturn before all set in the western sky. Normally, such easy
reference points are not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see three planets that you can cover with your outstretched
hand, that's pretty cool,'' Mosley said. ``A lot of people don't
look at the planets at all, so this will be significant.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
