<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-PACERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACERS DEFEAT NETS, 105-101 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Depleted by injuries and deflated by the
realization that they are not going to make the playoffs, the New
Jersey Nets showed some courage on Wednesday night. They fought
back from a 20-point third-quarter deficit and threw a scare into
the Indiana Pacers here at Conseco Fieldhouse before losing,
105-101. It was the fourth consecutive loss for the Nets (31-44).
</P>
<P>
   The Nets, who trailed by 79-59 late in the third period, rallied
to come within 98-97, with 47 seconds to play, on a 3-point basket
by forward Keith Van Horn, who had 26 points. But they could not
overtake Indiana. The Nets had a defensive lapse and left Pacers
forward Dale Davis alone under the basket with 33 seconds to play.
He scored on a layup to make it 100-97. Nets forward Scott Burrell
then missed a driving baseline layup, and New Jersey was forced to
foul the Pacers to get the ball back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're out of the playoffs, but we still have to come
out and be professionals and work,'' said guard Kendall Gill, who
had 14 points.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that three of the Nets' starters were on the
bench when the team started its furious rally. Point guard Stephon
Marbury did not play because of a painful left knee. He will have a
magnetic resonance imaging scan on Thursday when the team gets back
to New Jersey. Marbury could very well be lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Marbury, 23, is dreading the MRI because he fears what the
doctors may find. But he will not gamble on his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play if my leg is hurting like this,''
Marbury said before the game. ``There's no sense in me being out
there if I can't blow by nobody and can't play defense. That's no
fun. What makes basketball fun for me is to be able to dominate my
position.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles, the Nets' other starting guard, was also on the
bench. He was limited to 21 minutes tonight because of a sore right
knee. He will have the knee examined by the team doctor, Michael
Kelly, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   And the Nets' starting center, Evan Eschmeyer, left the game
early in the second quarter because of a severely sprained left
ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Nets Coach Don Casey was very pleased with the effort that he
got from guard Johnny Newman, who had 20 points, and Elliot Perry,
who had 14 points and helped the team get back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hanging with the best even on the road in one of the
worst situations,'' Casey said. ``That's what I said about these
guys. They can regroup and come back even with limited forces.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey mixed and matched players through out the game. Everyone
played except Marbury and Jim McIlvaine, who has missed the last
seven games because of a bulging disk in his back.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers (50-24) went right after the Nets in the first half,
feeding the ball to center Rik Smits in the lane.
</P>
<P>
   Smits had 17 points in the first quarter. But Smits was quiet in
the second half, particularly in the fourth quarter, when he failed
to score as the Nets rallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we would have been able to control Rik Smits in the first
half, it might have been a different game,'' Van Horn said. ``You
know great players like Reggie Miller and Jalen Rose are going to
get their shots. We can't let someone like Rik Smits, a
second-option guy, hurt you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
