<HEADLINE>
KOBE SAYS HE WON'T APPEAL FINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Kobe Bryant's suspension wasn't all bad. He caught a
movie (``Romeo Must Die'') and got a good night's rest, and in
between he watched his Lakers teammates pull out a dramatic victory
at Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard,'' Bryant said of his forced day off, ``but it
wasn't as hard as I thought it was going to be. I knew they were
going to pull it out. I had complete confidence in them, so I
wasn't biting my nails or anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   With another day to think about his Sunday-afternoon fight with
New York's Chris Childs, Bryant said he'll ``absolutely'' respond
differently if provoked in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd probably put my arms to the guy's throat, so he couldn't
throw a punch. Punches wouldn't be thrown,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Childs, who as the fight's instigator got an even heavier
punishment _ two-game suspension and $15,000 fine _ is appealing
the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's agent, Arn Tellem, reportedly said he would appeal
Bryant's one-game suspension (which cost him $109,756 in pay) and
$5,000 fine as well. Bryant said that's not the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Tellem) mentioned it to me, but I said I really don't want
to,'' he said. ``I don't really care about that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The day off did make Bryant a little antsy for Wednesday
morning's shootaround and the coaching staff got his attention
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Assistant coach) Frank Hamblen said that he thought (Warriors
guard) Larry Hughes picked him up with his own chauffered limousine
at the airport, so he could play against him; I think Kobe perked
up a little bit,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``He knows that
(Hughes) got one game here at Golden State that he'd like to redeem
himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Responded Bryant, who gave up 41 points to Hughes last time
here, ``Phil is always doing something like that, man.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Down time: Ron Harper played 39 minutes at Phoenix, and that
earned him a night off here Wednesday. Harper stayed in street
clothes and the Lakers listed him as having a sore left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that after 39 minutes of a hard game, this is
the kind of game that we can avoid at this time,'' said Jackson,
who's been looking for opportunities to rest the 36-year-old
veteran. ``If he was in uniform, the temptation to play him would
be too great.''
</P>
<P>
   Harper said he didn't need the rest, ``but I can use off this
game. We've got a large game (against San Antonio) in two days.
This rest will help.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great, though . . . . I could have played easily
tonight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after watching Harper miss two crucial free throws at
Phoenix, Bryant endorsed the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he stepped to the free-throw line at the end, I said
there's no way in hell he's gonna make this,'' Bryant said with a
laugh. ``He's too tired, man. That ball's not going in the hoop.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
