<HEADLINE>
DISARCINA SAYS THIS IS BEST TIME TO MEET EAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Angels opened the season with three games
against the defending champion New York Yankees, and after today's
off day will take on the Boston Red Sox and Toronto Blue Jays, two
more teams expected to compete for playoff spots.
</P>
<P>
   One school of thought is the Angels would prefer an easier
schedule to open the season, so they could get a few wins and build
confidence after last season's disaster. But that's not their
thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to face those guys some time,'' shortstop Gary
DiSarcina said. ``It might as well be now. Maybe they don't have
their act together yet coming out of spring training. Playing them
in the middle of the season might be a tougher task.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played very competitive games against the Yankees,''
left fielder Darin Erstad said. ``The games could have gone either
way, it's not like we didn't have opportunities. We can play with
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Heart stopper: The heart of the Angels' lineup _ Mo Vaughn,
Tim Salmon and Garret Anderson in the Nos. 3, 4 and 5 spots _ were
a combined 4 for 27 with eight strikeouts in the first two losses.
Offense was the club's biggest on-field problem last season, but
manager Mike Scioscia isn't worried about his big guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys are going to hit,'' he said. ''You think, out of
all the things on the club that could go wrong, those three are the
last thing you have to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Short hops: Pitcher Ramon Ortiz is expected to pitch seven
innings for Single-A Lake Elsinore tonight in the Storm's season
opener. Ortiz, who says he feels no pain despite a small tear in
his shoulder tissue, is expected to make his season debut Tuesday
at home against the Blue Jays. . . . The Yankees will wear black
armbands for the 2000 season to honor former manager and Hall of
Fame pitcher Bob Lemon, a Long Beach native.
</P>
</TEXT>
