<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOTECH-REPORT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 REPORT ON GENETICALLY ALTERED FOODS HIT AS PRO-AGRIBUSINESS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A scientific panel that waded into the debate over genetically
engineered foods drew fire Wednesday from environmental opponents
for taking a narrow, pro-industry view of the possible human and
environmental risks posed by gene-splicing technology.
</P>
<P>
   In a 261-page report issued Wednesday, a 12-person National
Research Council panel said it ``was not aware of any evidence
suggesting foods on the market today are unsafe to eat as a result
of genetic modification.''
</P>
<P>
   Genetic engineering involves the transfer in a laboratory of
genes from one plant or animal into a crop. Traditional plant
breeding tries to introduce new genes through pollen transfer, or
sexual reproduction, from one plant to another.
</P>
<P>
   The panelists, who spent a year hammering out a consensus
report, said the Environmental Protection Agency should revise, and
then implement, a genetic plant review process that it proposed in
1994 but has not completed.
</P>
<P>
   The suggested revision involves EPA's proposed exemption of
plant breeders who use sexual reproduction to introduce alien genes
into a crop. The panel questioned why the review process focused
solely on gene-splicing.
</P>
<P>
   The panel also said the EPA needed to work more closely with the
Department of Agriculture and the Food and Drug Administration, two
other agencies involved in the review process, to improve safety
testing and alleviate concerns that genetically modified foods
might pose health or environmental risks.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists acknowledged that their report focused on only
gene modifications that make plants resistant to pests and
diseases. It did not study other common types of alterations, such
as adding genes to make plants herbicide-resistant or to improve
their vitamin content.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the report discuss whether genetically modified foods
should be labeled, a move opponents have demanded to alert people
who may be afraid of allergic reactions to new genes or who simply
do not like the technology.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the report was issued, environmentalists complained
that the committee was stacked to favor agribusiness. The
committee's original staff director, for example, is now a lobbyist
for the Biotechnology Industry Organization in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the conflicts of this study, this is not credible as an
independent scientific report,'' said Joseph Mendelson, legal
director of the Center for Food Safety in Washington, D.C. His
group has filed federal lawsuits challenging the FDA and other
regulatory agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio, and Rep. Jack Metcalf, R-Wash.,
co-authors of bills to force the labeling of genetically modified
foods, also accused the panel of pro-industry ``bias.''
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference where the report was released, panel
Chairman Perry Adkisson, an entomologist and chancellor emeritus at
Texas A&AMP;M University, stressed that the report reflects a consensus
view that included the opinions of Rebecca Goldburg, a scientist
with Environmental Defense in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the extraordinarily strong feelings on all sides ...
it's not surprising that our work has come under such strong
scrutiny,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But while Goldburg acknowledged that ``the committee members
worked hard to get out a consensus recommendation,'' she declined
to give the report a ringing endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should look at the criticisms and look at the report
and draw their own conclusions,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The report is available at  &UR; www.nas.edu. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8531 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLA     04-06 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPOS MANAGER MAKES HIS POINT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Montreal manager Felipe Alou didn't appreciate
Dodgers pitcher Orel Hershiser hitting Vladimir Guerrero with a
pitch high on the shoulder, and Dodgers manager Davey Johnson
didn't particularly care for Alou's finger-pointing reaction to it.
</P>
<P>
   The ire of both managers was evident after the Expos' 6-5 win
Wednesday at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a right to believe that he hit Guerrero purposely,''
Alou said. ``I have a right to believe it. If I'm wrong, I already
asked God for forgiveness. I also believe that at my age (64) I
have the right every once in a while to become what I became. I
really lost my head. I really did and I was not inviting anyone to
fight or anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just saying, `This is between you and I.' Sometimes you
think you're right to lose your top when something like that
happens. I don't want anyone hitting my kid because he's having a
good night or a good series, and at that time I thought Guerrero
was hit purposely. I have a right to believe that because I've been
in the game more years than Hershiser is old (41).''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who had thrown behind the head of Expos pitcher
Javier Vazquez, hit Guerrero with a pitch with runners on first and
second and two out in the fifth. Hershiser quickly walked toward
home plate to apologize and Guerrero said he was fine and went to
first.
</P>
<P>
   Alou met Guerrero at first base. But before returning to the
dugout, Alou yelled at Hershiser and pointed his finger. Once back
in the dugout, Alou continued to holler at Hershiser. Second-base
umpire Jim McKean issued a warning to both benches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alou precipitated that, it was uncalled for,'' Johnson said.
``Here's a guy (Guerrero) hitting good, trying to throw the ball in
on him and nicked him . . . . pointing his finger. I don't like to
see the second-base umpire call it, but he really had no choice
after what Alou did. He had to put a warning after that. I didn't
appreciate the whole thing. I thought it was awful. We're not
trying to hit, we're trying to pitch him in tight. Here's a guy
hitting .700.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said the only intention was to pitch Guerrero inside
to set him up for the rest of the at-bat. Guerrero's 6 for 9 with
two homers and five RBI in the first three games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to hit him, I'm just trying to throw it up and
in to get him off the pitches,'' Hershiser said. ``It's pretty
obvious during the season he's been hitting the ball away very
well. You don't think anyone is going throw the ball on the outer
half of the plate without setting him up a little.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hundley, Mills progress: Todd Hundley could have played and
Alan Mills might be ready to pitch tonight, both good news for the
two injured players.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Johnson feared Mills, one of four right-handed
set-up men in the bullpen, could be heading for the disabled list,
but Mills' injured right ankle progressed to the point where he did
agility running in the outfield before the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trainers did a great job,'' Mills said. ``It's just about
ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who injured his right knee when he spike caught in the
dirt, said he's relieved and raring to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I woke up (Tuesday), I was worried it was a broken leg,''
Hundley said. ``Luckily, it turn out like this. But the clay (in
the infield) here is brutal. It's the worst in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Lost in Monday's opener was Hundley's final
at-bat, a right-handed single through the middle. It was his first
hit right-handed since July 18, 1999, at Pittsburgh. ``How `bout
that. It's a new year, bro. Hitting 1.000 from the right side,''
Hundley said. . . . Johnson worked Todd Hollandsworth and Jose
Vizcaino into the starting lineup for the first time in place of
Devon White and Kevin Elster, respectively. Johnson said he wanted
White to get a day off the turf and give Elster a chance to catch
his breath.
</P>
</TEXT>
