<HEADER>
A8535 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-ECONOMY-CLINTON-SFCHR     04-06 1014
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, ECONOMIC STARS TALK STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ President Clinton hosted a star-studded White
House conference on the ``new economy'' Wednesday, headlined by
soothing, albeit cautious, comments by Federal Reserve Chairman
Alan Greenspan and Goldman Sachs market-mover Abby Joseph Cohen.
<P>
   The timing was exquisitely coincidental, coming the day after
$1.19 trillion in stock value nearly evaporated before the markets
staged an astonishing recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We meet in the midst of the longest economic expansion in our
history and an economic transformation as profound as that that led
us into the Industrial Revolution,'' Clinton told leading
economists, Cabinet secretaries, Wall Street investment bankers and
high-tech titans gathered in the ornate White House East Room.
</P>
<P>
   Seating arrangements delivered additional ironies, with Clinton
next to Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates. Clinton gave a warm
introduction to Gates, draping his arm over the software
billionaire just two days after his administration won a stinging
antitrust verdict against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the ``phenomenal commitments'' of Gates and his
wife, Melinda, to donate $750 million to fight global poverty and
health problems, while Gates provided assurances that the
technology boom ``has really just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   The super-seminar in economic policy mirrored a similar
conference Clinton held in December 1992 in Little Rock, Ark., just
before first taking office as president. But while that conference
focused on budget deficits and unemployment, Wednesday's explored
how to keep the record-setting expansion running even longer.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan called the economic expansion ``without precedent in
our annals,'' fueled by a boom in high-tech investment and a
consequent surge in worker productivity.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be little doubt,'' Greenspan said, that the growth
in productivity ``has continued to rise, with scant evidence that
it is about to crest ... I see no reason that productivity growth
cannot remain elevated, or even increase further, to the undeniable
benefit of American businesses and workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Greenspan cautioned that ``some misalignments have
arisen,'' citing high stock and real estate prices that are fueling
consumer spending well beyond the capacity of the economy to
satisfy without igniting inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But while Greenspan noted that ``inflation has remained largely
contained,'' he cautioned that the two ``safety valves'' that have
kept inflation at bay despite rapid growth _ a large pool of
available labor and cheap, abundant imports _ will not remain open
forever.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan warned that the overall pool of available labor has
been falling steadily and is now at the lowest level as a percent
of the population since such measurements started in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   If labor shortages develop, Greenspan said, they will ``almost
surely'' make wages rise faster than productivity and produce
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   He also warned that the rising trade deficit could reach a point
where foreigners are no longer as willing to hold U.S. debt. ``At
that point,'' he warned, ``the safety valve of net imports could
narrow or close.''
</P>
<P>
   Investment banker Cohen, whose consistently bullish forecasts
for technology stocks have made her a star on Wall Street, was
likewise optimistic but cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of you know that my day job is as a stock market
strategist,'' Cohen said. ``For the past decade, we have been
enthusiastic about the outlook for stock prices in the United
States, and we remain so.''
</P>
<P>
   But at a later session on risks facing the economy, Cohen
repeated earlier warnings _ which had already rocked the markets _
that the Standard &AMP; Poor's stock market average is no longer
undervalued, and that she has ``less and less confidence in the
relative value of technology stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft chairman Gates, who in the afternoon found himself
wrapped under one of Clinton's arms (the other rested on World Bank
president James Wohlfenson) had paid a visit to Capitol Hill
earlier Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Gates met privately with five groups of lawmakers, including
Senate Democrats and House Republicans, as well with Arizona Sen.
John McCain, who has suspended his bid for the GOP presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Members said Gates was relaxed and confident that his company
will ultimately prevail on appeal in the government's antitrust
suit.
</P>
<P>
   Gates did not talk with reporters, but his visit was swiftly
followed by a blistering statement from House GOP conference
chairman J.C. Watts laying the blame for Tuesday's near-crash of
the stock market on the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dive in the Nasdaq market is a direct result of the
Clinton-Gore administration meddling with the private sector,''
Watts said. ``The Justice Department has demonstrated that, with
one major decision, they can send the entire world's economy into
disarray ... If the United States is to be a player in the
high-tech world, the federal government is going to have to step
aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leading San Francisco Bay Area economists attended the
conference, including Stanford University economist John B. Taylor,
who broadly agreed during his presentation on economic risks with
Greenspan's focus on inflation threats.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said every recession since World War II started with a
run-up of inflation that led inevitably to rising interest rates
and an economic slowdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest risk is still letting inflation rise,'' Taylor
said. ``I do not see a stock market correction as a risk. If
anything, it would reduce the pressures'' in the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Bay Area economists and industry leaders
participated, including Hal Varian, dean of the School of
Information and Management at the University of California at
Berkeley; economists Nada Eissa, Bronwyn Hall and Janet Yellen,
also of UC Berkeley; and E. David Ellington, co-founder and chief
executive officer of NetNoir, headquartered in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
