<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOM DIMAGGIO DOESN'T NEED MO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SAN FRANCISCO _ So Joe DiMaggio's family doesn't want his name
on North Beach Playground?
<P>
   So sayeth Joe's attorney, Morris (Joltin' Mo) Engelberg, who
demands a bigger memorial and threatens to sue the city.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe's only living brother, Dom, says baloney.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city has been very good to my family, starting with my
immigrant parents and continuing to this day,'' says Dom DiMaggio,
also an ex-big league star. ``As far as I'm concerned, the city can
determine for itself the way in which it wants to honor its native
sons.''
</P>
<P>
   Dom, 84, said he and Joe spent countless hours chasing fly balls
at that playground, developing into All-Star center fielders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that Joe would favor the playground memorial,'' Dom
said, ``especially if lending his name would bring with it a city
commitment to modernize the playground for kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Say, this Dom sounds like a classy guy. How about some kind of
local tribute to him, too?
</P>
<P>
   And Supervisor Gavin Newsom says the city isn't backing down to
Engelberg, but is seeking the best legal way to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   MORE DiMAGGIO: It's not surprising that Dom and Mo don't see eye
to eye. When Joe was hospitalized before his death, Engelberg kept
visitors away from Joe's bedside. Including Dom.
</P>
<P>
   Dom and Mo actually scuffled in the hallway outside Joe's
hospital room.
</P>
<P>
   And even though Engelberg zealously guards against those who
would slap the DiMaggio name on just any old thing, there is an
office building in Engelberg's own Hollywood, Fla., named Yankee
Clipper Center.
</P>
<P>
   The building's owner: Joltin' Mo Engelberg.
</P>
<P>
   THE MAN gets around.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Brown is on billboards and on a million taxicab roofs.
Hey, he's a photogenic guy.
</P>
<P>
   And now he stares into the Chronicle newsroom 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   A mural featuring Brown touting the census has been painted over
the historic Hotel Chronicle sign (no connection with the
newspaper), just across Mission Street from this newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   There's Willie, peering approvingly into the third-floor
newsroom as the world's hardest-working editors and writers crank
out another sparkling edition.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, just about wherever you are, Little Brother is watching
you.
</P>
<P>
   IF WALLS could talk, maybe the mayor would explain how it is
that a trucking company that was rejected for the city's minority
contracting program under a previous mayor got a golden pass under
Willie.
</P>
<P>
   Krystal Trucking was granted minority status and access to huge
contracts, with Brown's apparent blessing. This despite a strongly
worded independent report that Krystal is controlled by a
white-owned company, as reported in Sunday's Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Krystal was admitted to the minority program at Brown's apparent
urging, and after a couple of meetings in Brown's office. If the
mayor was not aware of the independent report exposing Krystal's
bogus claim of minority ownership, he should fire the person who
kept that information from him, a person whom Brown subsequently
promoted.
</P>
<P>
   If murals could talk, maybe Mayor Brown would explain why this
isn't a case of laws and ethics being broken, ignored and twisted
to benefit the mayor's friends and campaign contributors, at the
expense of the minorities whom the program is designed to help.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, but how can I be mad when I see that smiling face across the
street?
</P>
<P>
   WANT GIANTS' TICKETS? No problemo!
</P>
<P>
   Want seats in Pac Bell Park? That's a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Ticketvision.com, a ticket sales site not affiliated with the
Giants, posts a current Giants' schedule and a seating chart _ of 3
Com Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's an overflow plan for cheapskate Candlestick
nostalgia buffs,'' says Doug Wilkins.
</P>
<P>
   NOT A TOPIC for Jerry Springer, but a real-life San Francisco
story: ``My ex-wife found me a new bride.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Stanley Mayerson and former city Supervisor Carol Ruth
Silver were amicably divorced several years ago. And a few years
later, Carol Ruth said to Stanley, ``Have I got a girl for you.''
</P>
<P>
   And she did, and Stanley and Irene were married last Sunday
aboard the Larkspur ferry to San Francisco, by the ship's captain.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TAX TIME, and Ted Helman owes a bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing unusual there, but Helman is a Muni driver on the 22
Fillmore, and he found a fat wallet with $1,300 in cash outside his
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Helman instantly gave it to the cops, who returned wallet and
cash to owner.
</P>
<P>
   Ted got a nice commendation from Muni, but no reward from the
wallet owner. Hey, I got a buck for Ted, and if anyone wants to
match it, send it along.
</P>
<P>
   ASSORTED PEOPLE: Yes, that familiar face strolling the Union
Square area was Robert Kennedy Jr., in town to give a speech. ...
And yes, that guy working out with a babe at Gold's Gym on Brannan
was Gregory Hines, a recurring guest star on ``Will and Grace,''
though none of the 200 gay men in the gym seemed to notice. ... And
FYI, the big utility board member who abandoned her car with the
keys in it when she couldn't find a parking place, and had it
stolen _ it was  &UR; not  &LR; anyone associated with the PUC.
</P>
</TEXT>
