<HEADLINE>
PALFFY MAKES PROGRESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER _ Bryan Smolinski is gone for the season with a knee
injury and it appears Nelson Emerson (broken finger) won't be back
until the second round of the playoffs if the Kings are around.
</P>
<P>
   But the team is getting healthy. Slowly.
</P>
<P>
   Ziggy Palffy had his most rigorous workout since spraining his
right shoulder March 15 in Anaheim. He will undergo a strength test
today at the team training facility in El Segundo and probably
won't return until the playoffs start Wednesday or Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   `'We'll know more after the test,'' Kings coach Andy Murray
said. `'The question is whether it will do more good to hold him
out of those few days between the end of the regular season and the
first round ofthe playoffs. But he is making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake, sidelined the past two games with a bruised
knee, will skate today for the first time since getting injured
last Saturday against the Mighty Ducks. It is uncertain whether he
will be ready for Friday's game against the defending Stanley Cup
champion Dallas Stars at the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Emerson, injured March 23 on a slash by Philadelphia's Daymond
Langkow, will remain in a cast for the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   __ Reinprecht debuts: Steven Reinprecht, signed last week as a
free agent from the University of Wisconsin, made his NHL debut
Wednesday. He played on the fourth line with Brad Chartrand and
Jason Blake.
</P>
<P>
   Reinprecht, 23, led the nation in scoring this season with 26
goals and 66 points and is a finalist for the Hobey Baker Award as
the top player in college hockey. He was the Badgers captain the
past two years but went undrafted several years ago because of a
broken leg.
</P>
<P>
   Because he signed after the trade deadline, Reinprecht is not
eligible for the playoffs. But coach Andy Murray wanted to get him
into a game before the end of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   `'I told him to call his parents and tell them to set the VCR,''
Murray said. `'We watched him in practice and he has more speed
then we thought. He looks like he could be a good one.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Kings allowed Blake to play in the season
finale after he was signed out of the University of North Dakota.
Like Reinprecht, Blake was a Hobey Baker finalist. Blake had a goal
in his NHL debut.
</P>
<P>
   Reinprecht was called for a hooking penalty early in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quick whistles: It probably wouldn't hurt to have back Len
Barrie, the Vancouver-area resident who was waived by the Kings
last month. Barrie, who scored a goal for the Kings in a 5-2
victory here on Feb. 25, has scored four goals in 12 games since
getting picked up by the Florida Panthers. Barrie had five goals in
46 games for the Kings.
</P>
</TEXT>
