<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER SAYS ELIAN'S FATHER IS HEADED TO THE U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for new 9th and 10th grafs with reaction of Elian's Miami
relatives; subs 11th graf for rewriting)  By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The father of Elian Gonzalez will travel to the
United States from Cuba on Thursday morning to reclaim his son, a
lawyer for the boy's father announced Wednesday night after
returning from Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement sets the stage for a final legal showdown over
the boy, who has been in the custody of relatives in Miami since he
was rescued clinging to a rubber inner tube in November.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, the Washington lawyer who represents Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, the boy's father, told reporters that he expected
Attorney General Janet Reno and the Doris Meissner, the
commissioner of immigration, ``to take immediate action aimed at
reuniting Elian with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig, who traveled to Havana Wednesday night to consult with
Gonzalez and Cuban government officials, said that the father, his
new wife and 6-month-old baby will arrive in Washington Thursday
morning. His comments suggest that he was able to persuade Cuban
authorities to allow the father to come to the United States even
though the State Department had not provided visas for all 27
people the Cuban government wanted to accompany Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan Miguel has now been separated from his 6-year-old son for
over four months,'' Craig said in a statement read to reporters in
front of his office building in downtown Washington Wednesday
night. ``This separation occurred through no fault of his own and
has continued against his wishes. It is time for the reunion to go
forward and he has come here and is prepared to stay here until he
has achieved that objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials, who have said they want to
reunite the boy with his father, have hoped for Gonzalez to come
here to help strengthen the case against the Miami relatives, who
have been taking care of Elian and insist the boy should remain in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``For many weeks, people have asked why the father has not come
to the United States to take custody of his son,'' Craig said.
``For just as many weeks, Juan Miguel has stated that he would
happily travel to the United States and was fully prepared to do so
if he could be assured that, when he came here, he would in fact be
given custody of his son.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig said that he and the father were now both satisfied that
the immigration service would immediately begin to transfer legal
custody of the boy from his great uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, who has
cared for him in the Little Havana section of Miami, to the father.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing that the father was expected to arrive in the
United States, Elian's Miami relatives invited him and his family
to their house in Little Havana to try to ``work this out as a
family,'' said Armando Gutierrez, a spokesman for the relatives.
``He's welcome in this house,'' Gutierrez added.
</P>
<P>
   Gutierrez said the two sides should have a meal and work out
their differences without lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said the reunion could take place as soon as
Thursday. A physical transfer of custody would occur soon after,
the officials have said.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has granted special visitors visas to
Gonzalez and five others. But the Cuban government has asked that
22 others be allowed to come, including Ricardo Alarcon, the
speaker of the national assembly and a robust critic of the United
States government.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the State Department spokesman, said Wednesday
that officials believed that ``the six visas we have provided are
sufficient to provide an environment appropriate for the child in
this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussions between Justice Department officials and Elian's
relatives in Miami were expected to resume on Thursday morning at
the offices of the chief federal prosecutor in the Miami area.
Justice Department officials have insisted that the only issue open
for discussion is how the family will surrender Elian to the
father. The relatives are still arguing for ways to keep custody of
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many Cuban-Americans in the Miami area have
been conducting regular demonstrations outside the home where Elian
is staying, vowing they would not allow federal officials to take
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was rescued in the Atlantic off Florida on Thanksgiving
Day. His mother was among 10 people who died after their boat sank
while crossing from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great tragedy when a young child loses a parent as
Elian did during his trip to the United States,'' Craig said. ``But
it is an equal tragedy for any parent to face the loss of a young
child.'' (JT) &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
