<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THROWN AWAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Everything was nice and cushy for the Dodgers. They
pitched well and although they had made a few mistakes, it was
nothing Dave Hansen couldn't overcome with a pinch-hit homer in the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Then . . . oops. The defense everyone questioned in spring
training turned downright ugly.
</P>
<P>
   With two gaffes already on their record this game, the defense
completely collapsed and allowed Montreal to score twice in the
ninth to win 6-5 Wednesday at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   First, with everyone expecting a bunt, Montreal's Peter Bergeron
dragged one between pitcher Jeff Shaw and first baseman Eric Karros
to put two runners on. Then, a perfect double-play grounder was
hitto Mark Grudzielanek at second, but he fumbled it trying to flip
it to shortstop Jose Vizcaino and everyone was safe.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of two outs and one on, bases were loaded with none out.
Then, Rondell White singled to center to score two and give the
Dodgers their first loss in three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``No excuses, I lost the game,'' said Grudzielanek, playing his
third career game at second. ``By not making the play, I lost the
game. My feet were in bad position on the play. I have to get a
little more comfortable. I was leaning the wrong way. I hate to do
that. It (stinks). I just need to make the play. I should have
taken my time and just got one out.''
</P>
<P>
   It put Shaw in the miserable position of having to face White
with hot-hitting Vladimir Guerrero on deck and looking for payback
after getting hit by a pitch, which drew the ire of Expos manager
Felipe Alou.
</P>
<P>
   Shaw was ahead in the count 1-2 to White but couldn't get the
strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed a (strike) out there and I wound up with a flat
slider,'' Shaw said. ``Once you get two strikes on Rondell, and you
know Guerrero's on deck, you have to go for the punchout.''
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-inning fielding blunders weren't the only woes the
Dodgers experienced in the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Guerrero singled but twisted his ankle
rounding first. He was caught off the bag with Dodgers third
baseman Adrian Beltre in possession of the ball. However, Beltre,
worried about Jose Vidro at third, quickly threw to second hoping
to get Guerrero in a rundown and that allowed Guerrero time to
hobble safely to first.
</P>
<P>
   And the Expos were aided by more miscommunication on a Bergeron
bunt when they scored two runs in the fifth. The speedy leadoff
hitter placed the ball between pitcher Orel Hershiser and Karros to
put runners on first and second with none out.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Stevens hit a two-run single to make it 4-1 and then went to
second when Vizcaino failed to look in that direction when the ball
was thrown in from left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baseball really didn't go our way and we didn't execute
perfectly and we end up losing,'' said Hershiser, who admitted to
being surprised by the bunt. ``If we execute at the level we could
have, then even the baseball breaks probably wouldn't have beat
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansen momentarily rendered the mistakes inconsequential when he
hit a three-run homer off Montreal closer Ugueth Urbina in the
eighth to give the Dodgers a 5-4 lead, but neither Shaw nor the
defense could make it hold up.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's harder to watch it fall apart than actually getting the
hit,'' Hansen said. ``We still had six more outs to get (after the
homer). It obviously doesn't mean anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0121EDT &QL; 
