<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS HAVE SINKING FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For the better part of seven seasons, Guy Hebert has
played well when the Mighty Ducks needed him. But on Wednesday
night, the Anaheim goalie was a no-show in the team's biggest game
of the year _ a 5-2 loss to the Chicago Blackhawks before 15,112 at
United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert gave up three goals on shots of more than 40 feet and was
easily beaten by Bob Probert on a breakaway. Meanwhile, Chicago
goalie Jocelyn Thibault's 27 saves put the Ducks' Western
Conference playoff hopes on life support.
</P>
<P>
   With two games to play, Anaheim (33-35-12-2) needs help, and
lots of it, after it was unable to help itself against a Chicago
team it had beaten eight times in the previous 10 meetings (8-1-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goalie and the goal posts were the difference,'' said
Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg, who watched as Paul Kariya hit the
post twice in a game that was up for grabs until the middle of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who was a threat each time he stepped on the ice, beat
Thibault with a backhander at 9:40 after taking a breakaway pass
from Teemu Selanne to tie the game 2-2. Suddenly it looked as if
there was a real chance the Ducks might pick up two points on
Edmonton, which had lost to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 38 seconds later, Jean-Yves Leroux wristed a 40 footer
from the top of the left circle that beat Hebert and give the
Blackhawks a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be our game, then boom, the next
shift it's 3-2,'' said Selanne, who assisted on both Anaheim goals.
``We had great scoring chances and they throw a puck at the net and
it goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroux's goal was the third of three 40-foot-plus shots that got
by Hebert, who continues to suffer through the most inconsistent
year of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sullivan beat him with a long one-timer at 14:47 of the
first period and Kevin Dean's harmless looking wrist shot slipped
past him at 5:32 of the second to give the Blackhawks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   There was some traffic in front of Hebert on two of the goals,
but Hartsburg was in no mood to defend his veteran goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't score from there at this time of year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, as they have in so many games the second half of the
season outchanced their opponent, but goals, not chances, go up on
the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because they are scoring on what aren't even
scoring chances,'' said Hartsburg, whose Ducks outshot the
Blackhawks 29-22. ``It's not like there are guys standing alone in
front of the net. We have to get a breakaway and make a great play
(to score) and they wrist one and it's in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Probert did break in all alone when Oleg Tverdovsky and Steve
Rucchin got tangled up at the Chicago blue line as the Ducks were
desperately pressing to score the tying goal. Hebert could have
kept the Ducks in the game with a big save, but instead Probert
made it look easy, beating him on the stick side at 16:37 of the
third period to give Chicago a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Amonte scored his 42nd goal of the year into a empty net at
18:54.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's goal was his 20th, but realistically the Ducks were
done in by two players scoring their third goals of the year (Dean
and Leroux) and one scoring his fourth (Probert).
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set in the first period when Thibault stopped
Kariya in the first 30 seconds, made a fine stop on Antti Aalto and
an even better one on Selanne's one-timer from the left circle
while Anaheim was on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the first wave of attack the Blackhawks took a
1-0 lead when Sullivan beat Hebert cleanly from the top of the left
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya hit the first of his two post just over two minutes into
the second period and a Tverdovsky's bid was turned aside by
Thibault before Dean's floater from the blue line gave the
Blackhawks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The goal put the Ducks in a desperate situation and less than a
minute later a gamble by Ruslan Salei paid off. The Anaheim
defenseman jumped into the play deep in the Chicago zone and was in
position to pick up a deflected Selanne pass in the left circle and
beat Thibault on the glove side at 6:26.
</P>
<P>
   The goal gave the Ducks a ray of hope, but their playoff hopes
are fading fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     04-06 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ In the days preceding this season-opening series,
several Astros referred to the Pittsburgh Pirates as the scariest
team in the National League Central.
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the first two days of the season are any indication, no one
has more reason to be afraid than Pirates manager Gene Lamont, who
has watched his team blow up twice.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Lamont's pitching staff went wild with its
generosity, walking seven batters in the Astros' 11-2 victory
Wednesday at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lamont doesn't have a contract beyond this season, and his
pitchers haven't done anything to help his cause. The Pirates have
issued 13 free passes in two games, and nine have led directly to
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might get us one or two times through the order,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said. ``But eventually, we'll get you.
If you give us a chance with walks, we'll hurt you.''
</P>
<P>
   With the count in their favor most of the night, Astros hitters
churned out 10 hits, four for extra bases. They turned the score
lopsided with a six-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to that, they kept the Pirates at a safe but
still-threatening distance behind Jose Lima, who overcame a shaky
start. The Pirates scored in the first inning as Lima was trying to
acclimate himself to the chilly conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have any feeling in my hands in the first inning,''
he said. ``I'm not making any excuses; I just had to make some
adjustments. I'm from the Dominican; cold weather is not my
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither is Tony Krizmanich, the official scorer.
</P>
<P>
   Lima made a bid to match his RBI production for the entire 1999
season in his first at-bat of 2000. But his smash to the right side
of the infield, which scored two runners as it glanced off the
glove of first baseman Kevin Young, was ruled an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed they didn't give me a base hit,'' said
Lima, a career .106 hitter. ``I guarantee you that if one of (the
Pirates' pitchers) had hit that ball, they would have called it a
hit. I'm not going to say anything else about it, but everyone who
was watching the game knows that was a base hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima's teammates no doubt appreciate his competitive juices
regarding the credibility of his offensive statistics; what they
welcome most is what he does on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Lima's quick-working style is a thing of beauty to a fielder
when the temperature is in the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get my guys off the field as fast as I could,''
Lima said. ``They made some great plays behind me, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pirates starter Kris Benson hardly resembled the pitcher most
considered the top rookie in the NL in 1999. Although he was
responsible for only two walks, he struggled with his location from
the beginning, and the Astros made him pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really like Benson,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said.
``But it was his first start of the season, and there was a little
more emotion involved. I would have to guess by watching his
control and by seeing him last year that he was probably a little
more up for this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't show his emotions outwardly the way Lima does, but
I'm sure he was probably feeling it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lima found himself in an early hole after he allowed the Pirates
to load the bases in the first. Two runs scored on Aramis Ramirez's
ground ball to the left of second base. Shortstop Bill Spiers got a
glove on the ball but couldn't make a play on it.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros took the lead with three in the third, two of them on
the questionable error charged to Young.
</P>
<P>
   So potent is the Astros' lineup that Richard Hidalgo, who drove
in five runs Tuesday, was slotted seventh in the batting order
Wednesday. He was pushed down one spot by Daryle Ward, who was
2-for-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no easy outs in the lineup, and that's a good
feeling,'' Bagwell said. ``That gives your pitchers confidence and
makes them feel like all they have to do is keep you in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like 1998 when we didn't care if we were losing in
the fifth or sixth inning, because we always felt we could come
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward's two-out homer capped a two-run third inning for the
Astros. The offense then went silent until the eighth-inning
explosion, which was aided by three walks and highlighted by
Spiers' three-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   By winning Wednesday, the Astros already have won more games
(two) at Three Rivers Stadium than they did in six tries last
season.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
