<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8548 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BLAZERS-H     04-06 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-BLAZERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PORTLAND, Ore. _ It says ``Rose Garden'' on the marquee outside the
Portland Trail Blazers' palace, but you'll have to excuse the
20,384 fans in attendance Wednesday night, and quite a few of the
Trail Blazers themselves, if they thought it was the ``Morose
Garden.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indeed, in the wake of the Rockets' stunning 118-105 victory,
what else could be said?
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets entered the game with a nine-game road losing
streak, and the Blazers, one of the Western Conference's top
contenders, came in with a three-game string of wins.
</P>
<P>
   But as has happened so many times for the Rockets in this
upside-down season, they tossed expectations out the window _ or,
more to the point, they flat-out ignored them _ and cruised to a
victory that could only be called unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest road win of the season for us,'' said
Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich. ``We hadn't beaten a contender,
even though we've been close. And we haven't had a road win in a
long, long time. This is a young, inexperienced team, and we let a
lot of games get away from us this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But these guys have progressed, as you can tell by how we
played tonight. We made play after play, and that's how you win on
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   It helps when Shandon Anderson simply decides that the Rockets
aren't going to lose, no matter who they are playing. Anderson
zipped through, around and over the Blazers for a game-high 30
points, making 10 of 12 shots along the way, and added 10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Even more delightful to Houston fans was the fact most of
Anderson's work came against Scottie Pippen, who had just 15 points
while shooting 5-of-14 from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our rotations were tremendous,'' Tomjanovich said. ``And
Shandon was tremendous. He did it in all areas _ from the outside,
inside, on the offensive boards, defense. He just gave us an
all-around game.''
</P>
<P>
   They all did, as evidenced by the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Playing one of the best defensive teams in the league, the
Rockets shot 62 percent from the floor _ 73.5 percent in the second
half, and a staggering 84.6 percent (11 of 13) in the fourth
quarter. And playing one of the biggest teams in the league, the
Rockets fielded a team that looked more like a 6-6 and under squad,
yet they still managed to hold their own on the boards, with
Portland finishing with a slim 35-34 edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it was a very disappointing loss for us,'' said
Portland coach Mike Dunleavy. ``Their one-on-one players took over
the game in the second half. Houston just played a marvelous game.
It's a big win for them, but a lot of teams in their position can
come in here with nothing to lose, and we have to be ready for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   So, how did the Rockets manage to pull it off?
</P>
<P>
   Well, one reason was the Rockets' game plan _ make the Portland
big guys play like little ones, and make Houston's relative runts
play like big men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just a great scheme the coaches came up with,'' said
Steve Francis, who added 18 points, seven assists and a pair of
steals. ``That was the best thing we could possibly do. We knew
that the only way they thought they could stop us was to
double-team our isos (isolation plays), trying to limit our
mismatches.
</P>
<P>
   ``They double-teamed, but that took their guys away from the
bucket and we were able to get Shandon cutting to the bucket and
Cuttino (Mobley) out there hitting from the outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, in particular, took advantage of the open lanes to the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Rasheed Wallace leaves the basket, then there's nobody
you really look at and you're not afraid to go in there,'' said
Anderson, who scored 15 points in the third quarter. ``They have
some guys who can get off the floor, but when Rasheed leaves, their
biggest guys are Scottie and Detlef (Schrempf), and they're not
intimidators when you want to go to the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 53-50 at the break, the Rockets opened the third
quarter with a 17-2 blitz, coming out with an aggressive,
to-the-basket attack that put the Portland defenders on their
heels. And when they got the Blazers to collapse around the basket,
the Rockets often found wide-open 3-point shooters, who were more
than happy to knock down the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson began his assault with 8:35 remaining in the quarter,
driving to the hoop to give the Rockets a 60-55 lead. The shot
sparked a brilliant run in which Anderson scored 15 of the Rockets'
20 points, allowing them to build an 80-67 lead with 2:48 to play
in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But Steve Smith (24 points) went to work, scoring seven straight
points to quell the Rockets' run, and Portland crept within 85-80
at the close of the period on a hook shot from Wallace with 3.4
seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than fold, however, the Rockets took every punch the
Blazers dealt and came back with a counter.
</P>
<P>
   Portland managed to pull within 93-90 with 7:41 left in the game
on a pair of free throws from Smith, but again the Rockets
withstood the hit. They put together a 13-3 run to boost the lead
to 106-93 and cruised from there, laughing all the way to the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fun, fun team,'' Tomjanovich said. ``It's a real
positive group of guys. This is just like planting seeds and
watching them grow. This is the closest team I've been around in a
long, long time. We have a good feeling about the future here.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
