<HEADER>
A8553 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-ELIAN-VISITOR-LADN     04-06 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-VISITOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-TIME CHILD DEFECTOR VISITS CUBAN BOY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT HALLERAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ (Editor's note: Glendale, Calif., resident Scott
Holleran, a freelance writer and frequent contributor to the Los
Angeles Daily News, traveled to Miami over the weekend to cover a
meeting between Elian Gonzalez and Walter Polovchak, who 20 years
ago was a child refugee seeking political asylum in the United
States from communism in his Ukrainian homeland. Holleran was the
only journalist allowed inside the home of Elian's Miami
relatives.)
</P>
<P>
   The house where Elian Gonzalez lives might seem an unlikely
flashpoint for a philosophical conflict over a little Cuban boy.
</P>
<P>
   But, in many ways, Lazaro Gonzalez's small, two-bedroom house,
where he lives with his wife, Angela, his daughter, Marisleysis,
and his great-nephew, Elian, is a powerful reminder of the nature
of the struggle.
</P>
<P>
   It stands as a monument to the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   It is Sunday afternoon in Miami's Little Havana, where Elian
Gonzalez has become the personification of Cuban-Americans'
struggle against the communism of Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa music blasts from a neighbor's home on the street where
Elian lives with his great-uncle, Lazaro.
</P>
<P>
   The block is full of tightly packed homes and late-model cars.
The modest Gonzalez home sits in the middle of the narrow street
behind a fence on a small lot with a back yard the size of a small
truck.
</P>
<P>
   An army of TV broadcasting trucks lines adjacent streets,
leading to a police car and a barrier. At the street's entrance, a
tented media camp stands to the left and Elian's quiet, gated home
is on the right.
</P>
<P>
   Dead ahead is another barricade - where hundreds of
demonstrators stand vigil over the small slice of Miami that has
become Elian's corner of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Elian is inside taking a shower after a day at the fair. He is
tired but also curious to meet a special visitor who has come to
proclaim support for Elian's freedom. As Elian prepares, with help
from Marisleysis Gonzalez, the 21-year-old cousin who has become
his surrogate mother, Lazaro Gonzalez entertains family and a few
guests on the patio, extinguishes his cigarette and greets a man
named Walter Polovchak.
</P>
<P>
   Polovchak was once the world's most famous young defector. He
ran away from his Ukrainian parents at age 12 and refused to return
to the Soviet Union. He fought his parents in court - opposed by
the American Civil Liberties Union and the Soviet Union - and lived
with the constant threat of KGB kidnappers while he was moved among
numerous foster homes. The boy's defiant declaration of
independence became famous across the globe:
</P>
<P>
   ``Never I go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 32 and the father of a boy Elian's age, he decided to travel
from his home outside Chicago, where he is an office manager, once
it became clear the government intended to return Elian to his
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom is a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity for this boy - it
is more important than a family. If his family really loves him,
they will understand,'' he said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While waiting on the patio to meet the 6-year-old boy whose
mother drowned trying to flee to America with her son, Polovchak is
flooded with the memories of his own struggle.
</P>
<P>
   He is wearing a short-sleeve shirt with an emblem of the
American flag and sipping a Cuban coffee. Seeing that Lazaro lights
a cigarette, Polovchak lights up, too, and the men discuss their
common bond through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Elian bursts from the house with the boundless energy of a child
unleashed on a playground. Followed by Marisleysis, Elian runs
about the yard, eventually obeying his cousin's requests that he
come meet the man whose story is not unlike his own.
</P>
<P>
   When Polovchak meets Elian, who moves close to Marisleysis at
the prospect of meeting the pale-skinned outsider, Polovchak tells
the child that his son, Alec, is the same age and wants to say
hello.
</P>
<P>
   Elian runs from the patio to ride in his motorized race car
without so much as an acknowledgment of Polovchak's greeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very shy in the beginning because he didn't know if I
was coming to help him or take him away,'' Polovchak said later,
after they met privately. ``But he warmed up to me and allowed me
to play with him and throw him up in the air. Marisleysis explained
my story to him in Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   As Elian leaps, tumbles and runs in the back yard, Polovchak
watches him carefully and talks with Marisleysis. The boisterous
boy who played with his puppy, Dolphin, who Elian named after the
dolphins that he said surrounded him and protected him from sharks
at sea, is genuinely spontaneous out of the camera's range.
</P>
<P>
   A guest is taking pictures of Elian - whose behavior ranges from
a chronic refusal to wear his shoes to a carefully executed effort
to reach the box of chocolate that sits in the kitchen cupboard
above his reach - and he suddenly runs over, snatches the camera
and, aware that everyone is watching him, takes a picture - of
himself.
</P>
<P>
   For the boy who is perhaps the most photographed child since
Shirley Temple, it is either the mischievous act of a young boy or
a bold demonstration that, despite the hordes of cameras that
transmit his every move outside these boundaries, he is in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the depth of his understanding of the past four months'
dramatic events, he is off and running and trying to run over the
guests in his race car.
</P>
<P>
   Before Polovchak boards the plane back to Chicago, he walks over
to the demonstrators, tells them about his own fight against
communism and rallies them with the cry: ``Long live freedom!''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheers wildly at Polovchak's words - some have offered
him Cuban sandwiches and water and others tell him to continue the
fight for Elian's freedom - and shows him their rosaries, Virgin
Mary icons, posters and placards.
</P>
<P>
   A weary-looking Cuban exile holds the handwritten sign:
``Elian's Right 2 the Persuit (sic) of Happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving the house, Polovchak says goodbye to Elian. After
hearing Polovchak's story, the Cuban boy, who has settled down and
returned to the patio to bid his visitor farewell, quietly asks
Marisleysis whether the visitor's story means that he, too, can
stay in America.
</P>
<P>
   Polovchak, who knows that public opinion, many newspaper
editorials and the U.S. government think he should be returned to
his father, seeks to reassure the boy that the world is a wonderful
place and that Elian belongs in it.
</P>
<P>
   As Polovchak crouches before Elian and looks him in the eye, a
hush falls over the guests and family and all eyes are on the man
once known as the ``littlest defector'' and the child who is heir
to his legacy. Elian, still and serious, listens to the stranger.
</P>
<P>
   In a solid Chicago accent that bears no trace of the Ukrainian
language of his youth, Polovchak tells Elian: ``Hang in there, stay
strong and this will end soon. One day, you can come up to Chicago,
visit me and my son and play with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian says he would like that and, remembering their
introduction, asks Polovchak to say hello to his son for him.
</P>
<P>
   Polovchak promises that he will. The little boy walks Polovchak
through the front yard to the padlocked fence that could become the
point of entry for those who would return him to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian waves good-bye to his new friend.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
