<P>
   DRUG-PRICES _ The political potency of high prices for
prescription drugs is powerfully demonstrated on two fronts. Slade
Gorton of Washington, a mainstream Republican senator, is
complaining about the disparity between prescription drugs in
Canada and the United States. Although Democrats have been making
this point for months, the drug lobby is in a panic now that
Republicans are adding a voice to the criticism. And in the Senate,
Democrats have forced a symbolic vote on the issue as an amendment
to a budget resolution. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE _ The general accused of sexual harassment in
1996 by the Army's highest-ranking woman was appointed last August
to be the service's deputy inspector general, an officer
responsible for investigating accusations of wrongdoing, including
sexual misconduct, Pentagon officials said Wednesday. The movement
of the officer, Maj. Gen. Larry G. Smith, into that job has been
frozen while the Army's inspector general investigates the
accusation by Lt. Gen. Claudia J. Kennedy that Smith made an
unwanted sexual advance in her office at the Pentagon, the
officials said. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-POLITICS _ Leaders of both parties are wooing Rep.
James Traficant Jr., a blustery former sheriff who is, by his own
admission, about to be indicted and who over the years has been
scorned by his colleagues as often as he has been courted. By David
E. Rosenbaum.
