<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE E SURVIVES A SCARY CRISIS OF CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the euphoric rush surrounding his first NASCAR Winston Cup
victory Sunday, Dale Earnhardt Jr. disarmed himself long enough to
give us a glimpse of what it's really like to be Little E.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it's more than a little scary.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Earnhardt Jr.'s life wasn't going to be worth a flip
until he won that first Winston Cup race somewhere. And after 11
non-winning Cup starts heading into Sunday's DirecTV 500 at Texas
Motor Speedway, Earnhardt Jr. had begun hinting that his
25-year-old life had become borderline miserable.
</P>
<P>
   There was a 29th-place finish at Atlanta Motor Speedway, where a
broken part had hurled Earnhardt Jr. into a wall.
</P>
<P>
   A week later in the garage area at Darlington Raceway, Earnhardt
Jr. _ without naming names _ criticized crew chief and ``second
father'' Tony Eury Sr. for keeping him on the track in a car so
loose he eventually lost it and crashed-out en route to a
40th-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Racing at Bristol Motor Speedway the following Sunday, Earnhardt
Jr. joined his famous father, seven-time Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt, as one of six cars involved in a crash on Lap 2 of the
scheduled 500. His red-and-black hot rod and psyche damaged,
Earnhardt Jr. rolled home 38th, a mere 99 laps behind winner Rusty
Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   That was the most visible baggage Earnhardt Jr., a
third-generation driver, carried into Fort Worth last week.
Mercifully, most early media attention at the racetrack here
focused on the Cup debut of Adam Petty, NASCAR's first
fourth-generation driver, and a member of perhaps the only family
that could relegate the Earnhardts to sidebar status.
</P>
<P>
   That's because during the past two years, of course, Little E
has grown accustomed to making headline news. He won a combined 13
races on the way to NASCAR Busch Grand National Series
championships in 1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The victory-starved executives at Anheuser-Busch were so
enamored that they signed Earnhardt Jr. to a reported $10 million
sponsorship deal to get Budweiser baseball caps back into Victory
Lane for the first time since September 1994.
</P>
<P>
   His Cup debut at Lowe's Motor Speedway last May was preceded by
a mass-marketing blitz, posing a distraction that might have cost a
lesser young man and his team that second BGN championship.
</P>
<P>
   Little E's fans, including crossovers from his daddy's camp and
those merely looking for someone to swift-kick Jeff Gordon while
he's down, were multiplying exponentially.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Earnhardt Jr. began beating up on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to think,'' Earnhardt Jr. said on Sunday
evening, after he had bellowed an obligatory ``Wassssuuuupppp'' _
his sponsor's chic slogan _ into the TV cameras. ``You put yourself
in position to win. You put yourself in position to lose. You put
yourself in position to wreck. I felt like I still had control and
could have made a difference the past three weeks. But you can beat
yourself up only so much before you take a lot of confidence away
from yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   His famous father/car-owner apparently up to his elbows in
``Fortune 500''-related business, Earnhardt Jr. first sought out
buddy and BGN regular Hank Parker Jr. for counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hank has been through some stuff is his racing career, like
me,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``Talking to him ... makes you chill out
and get ready to go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Earnhardt Jr. sat down and spoke with Gary Nelson,
the NASCAR Winston Cup Series Director. Nelson's job puts him into
close proximity with every template in the garage area. But
Nelson's status as a former trend-setting crew chief has allowed
him to deal with every type of driver's temperament, every type of
troubled driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though a lot of good things have happened to me in my
career,'' Earnhardt Jr. said, ``I sometimes need to be told that
I'm a good race car driver. When we crash out of a race or
something, I go to the house and the phone don't ring. You sit
there and wonder if anybody gives a damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson told Earnhardt Jr. to forget about that, that he knew he
was going to make it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't heard that from anybody else,'' Earnhardt Jr. said.
``To hear it from somebody like Gary Nelson, who can't play
favorites and who has nothing to gain by telling me that I'm going
to make it, that sounds pretty good to me.''
SPOTLIGHT ON Wood Brothers working to ease Sadler's pain Seven
races into their 50th anniversary season, the Wood Brothers had
assumed they had witnessed every act of weirdness possible in
NASCAR Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   And then the left rear tire on Elliott Sadler's car shredded and
began attacking the second-year driver during the DirecTV 500 at
Texas Motor Speedway last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler's car was hit by Sterling Marlin's on a restart on Lap
120. The impact flattened Sadler's left rear Goodyear Eagle radial,
with the damaged bodywork on the No. 21 Citgo Ford Taurus acting
like a knife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kept on cutting it \Rthe tire\S and cutting it, and just
made it like a whip,'' Sadler said. ``I could feel it barely
hitting me and then it really came apart all at once and hit me
four or five times on top of the shoulder before I could get the
car stopped. It was hitting me every time the tire rotated.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said the shredded rubber slapped its way through two
layers of metal before reaching him inside the protective roll
cage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt like a sledgehammer hitting me on top of the
shoulder,'' Sadler said. ``It was so powerful that it ripped the
roof off the car _ and that's the first time I've ever seen that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said he suffered ``a mild separation'' of his left
shoulder, as well as lacerations and bruises. The affected area
measures approximately three inches wide and eight or nine inches
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``It starts on the top of my shoulder and goes all the way to
about the middle of my back,'' said Sadler, who has been treated by
his doctor since Sunday night. Undaunted, Sadler plans to drive in
the appropriately named Goody's Body Pain 500 at Martinsville (Va.)
Speedway this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler said he and crew chief Mike Beam have been looking at
ways to prevent a repeat of such a freak occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We run a safety net on the left side, but it's real
straight,'' said Sadler, a native of Emporia, Va., who is adamant
about driving at his home track. ``We're thinking about curving it
behind the seat to form like a wall, or put up some more aluminum
or another roll bar or something right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Car co-owner Eddie Wood said his crew hopes to fabricate a
protective ``steel net.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like mesh, an eighth-of-an-inch thick,'' Wood said.
``Welding it from the roll bar all the way back across behind the
seat would keep anything from coming up in there. Fortunately, he
wasn't hurt any worse than he was and now maybe it should be made
mandatory to make some kind of thing around the driver right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, 24, said he won't need a second opinion on that
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit the wall many a time in racing, and I've had
surgeries and everything else,'' Sadler said. ``But I've never had
anything that painful. I don't wish that on anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Force backs off Bowing to pressure from his peers and fans,
nine-time and reigning NHRA Funny Car champion John Force has
canceled plans to field a third car this season.
</P>
<P>
   Force said his impetus behind a third car, with Tommy Johnson
Jr. the most likely driving candidate, was to provide aspiring
drivers and crewmen a chance to learn professional drag racing.
Force, driver of the Castrol GTX Ford Mustang, said the perception
was that he and teammate Tony Pedregon were trying to kill off the
competition, round-by-round, by adding another team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the competition doesn't get us and we're lucky enough to
win a 10th championship, I don't want to hear that it was because
of a third car,'' Force told ``National Dragster.'' ``It's about
what I feel in my heart is right. We're trying really hard to grow
this sport, and I don't want to be one of the guys who muddies the
water.'' Papis pumped for Naz Buoyed by his first CART FedEx
Championship Series victory, Team Rahal's Max Papis figures to be
flying during the Bosch Spark Plug Grand Prix this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Given the confines of the cramped 0.946-mile Nazareth (Pa.)
Speedway, that's mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Papis, winner of the season-opener at Homestead, Fla., will take
a 20-16 points lead over Roberto Moreno of Patrick Racing into
Round 2 of the 20-race schedule. Papis has finished fourth or
better in his past five Championship Auto Racing Teams starts
dating to last year at Laguna Seca, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came to Team Rahal \Rin 1999\S we were happy to
finish in the top 10, and we hoped to finish higher,'' said Papis,
driver of the No. 7 Miller Lite Ford/Reynard. ``Now we expect to
run in the top-five, and have raised our expectations to the
podium.'' Valvoline tops air-time Mark Martin won only two NASCAR
Winston Cup races and finished third in the points championship in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   But Martin and the No. 6 Valvoline Ford Taurus emerged as the
undisputed champions in network TV exposure for the seventh
consecutive year, accumulating nearly $49 million in value.
</P>
<P>
   That figure was compiled from research provided by ``The
Sponsors Report'', which documents advertising exposure on national
sports telecasts. Total value for all Winston Cup sponsors topped
$1.4 billion last year, up from $1.2 billion in 1998. Martinsville
digs in Martinsville (Va.) Speedway often is mentioned as a likely
candidate to lose one of its two NASCAR Winston Cup dates to newer
and bigger facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Campbell, president and general manager of NASCAR's
oldest-sanctioned racetrack, begs to differ. Management of the
0.526-mile, paper clip-shaped oval have no intention of giving
NASCAR an easy-out.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sheppard, Martinsville's director of corporate
communications, said 5,000 seats have been added for this weekend's
Goody's Body Pain 500. In addition, eight suites, a new press box,
new concessions stands and restrooms have been constructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clay builds from 2,000 to 7,000 seats a year, depending on
demand,'' Sheppard said. ``We try not to overbuild. We already have
plans for more seats between Turns 1 and 2.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheppard said that negotiations are under way to move the
railroad tracks that run past the backstretch grandstands, and have
prevented expansion in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you moved the railroad tracks, you could put another 40,000
seats back there,'' Sheppard said, ``as much as the frontstretch.''
Last words ``I was talking to \Rcar owner\S Roger Penske and he
said that statistics are all nice, but you've got to remember that
the most important thing is the very next race.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Rusty Wallace, on making his 500th career Winston Cup start
this weekend
</P>
</TEXT>
