<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8557 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF--ROBERTSONCOL-HNS     04-06 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--ROBERTSONCOL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Until recently, trying to predict the winner of any
golf tournament was foolish exercise. We writers, presumed experts
that we are, would take our stabs because people expected us to,
but the exercise has always been pure guesswork.
</P>
<P>
   In a game between two teams, you have a 50 percent chance of
being right. Here at the Masters, in contrast, maybe 20 guys would
tee off Thursday with a realistic shot at visiting Butler Cabin in
Sunday's twilight. Hence, the odds of a prognosticator being right
dropped to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, in Jack Nicklaus' prime years, and there were about
two decades' worth of them, he won four green jackets (his other
two were claimed as long shots). Yet he probably went out as the
consensus Masters betting favorite at least 15 times. So the
prevalent notion that Tiger Woods is a slam-dunk, lead-pipe cinch
of a lock to finish first this year ranks somewhere between
ludicrous and preposterous, right?
</P>
<P>
   Definitely. Nonetheless, he's my pick in a nanosecond. Woods
will live up to the overwhelming burden of expectations with which
he has been saddled. He will win the 2000 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Not easily, perhaps. He'll blow a putt or two on the glassy
greens. He'll get himself in trouble on one of the six holes with
the skinnier fairways and the more intrusive rough. Somebody
somewhere in the field will make Tiger sweat, although he probably
won't let us see the perspiration. But in the end, nobody will
possess either the shots or the guts to beat him.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, he's that good right now. And accordingly, that confident.
You would be, too, if you were 77 shots under par barely three
months into the new PGA Tour season and had placed worse than
second once in seven events.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nobody else is either that good or that confident.
</P>
<P>
   While Hal Sutton tried to rally the PGA's also-rans a couple of
weeks ago at The Players Championship, exhorting his peers to stop
deifying Woods, then actually beating him in a head-to-head
showdown, all that really accomplished was to harden Woods'
resolve. He wants this Masters in the worst way, and we saw three
years ago what can happen at Augusta National when Tiger shows up
with the eye of same.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, there's not a fellow former champion in the field
who can touch him. Most of that group, in fact, wouldn't be allowed
anywhere near Magnolia Lane if not for the Masters' quirky
qualifying rules. Last year's winner, Jose Maria Olazabal, is all
over the place with his driver, and he can't buy a putt once he
does finally locate the green. Still, the Spaniard looms as the
only one of the 22 besides Woods with a prayer.
</P>
<P>
   As for the wannabes
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson comes in hot, arguably slightly hotter than
Woods, and he draws mention for being the best player never to have
won a major. But there's a reason why he hasn't, and it will bite
him again this week. Also, being that he's a lefty, history isn't
his friend here. None has won the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval contends that being a semi-forgotten figure, with a
trimmer figure to boot, helps his cause. Of course, the reason he's
no longer touted as a would-be peer of Woods is because he isn't in
the ballpark. Duval hasn't won a tournament since last April, 10
fewer than Tiger over the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia appeared to be Woods' worthiest new foil when he
made his swashbuckling charge at the PGA last summer, but he, too,
has faded. The charming Spanish Wunderkind we recall
scissor-kicking across the Medinah fairway has turned sullen,
frustrated by a faulty swing and overburdened by his own heavy
potential.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie, in turn, is due, given that he has never won
on this side of the pond, and he did place third at The Players
Championship. Previously, however, his play had been middling to
mediocre, and he has heretofore failed to crack the top 10 at the
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   We could go on, but why?
</P>
<P>
   Tiger's the man. That's just how it is. His game is made for the
Masters _ with the changes to the course, hitting the ball long and
high has never been more requisite _ and his game is now the likes
of which we have rarely, if ever, seen. Nicklaus never mounted a
run on par with the one Woods brings to Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been targeting this,'' Tiger said, a statement that could
traumatize the rest of the pack. ``I'm excited to be here. I've
been getting better week by week. It's nice to see the fruits of
good, hard labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Nice for him, maybe. Bad for anyone who thinks a golf tournament
should be a crapshoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if he's going to win,'' Garcia argued, revealing
his youthful naivete. ``Nobody knows that. Some guys have beaten
him. We realize that he is beatable.''
</P>
<P>
   Not this year, in Augusta, he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
