<HEADER>
A8558 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT &LR;      04-06 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT YANKEES, 12-6 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ A dejected David Cone surrendered the baseball
to his manager on Wednesday night, arm extended, like a defeated
general handing over his sword. Many times in his career Cone has
argued to stay in the game, but there was no reason to debate Joe
Torre over this decision. Cone was terrible in his first outing of
the season, and he knew it.
</P>
<P>
   He jogged off the field and into the New York Yankees' dugout,
where the coach Don Zimmer rose off the bench and onto his
surgically replaced knee to greet Cone. Zimmer patted Cone on the
back and offered an encouraging word as he passed, and then sat in
the far corner of the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Cone was charged with eight runs in two and
two-thirds innings as the Yankees lost, 12-6. The Angels' Darin
Erstad had five runs batted in and the lumbering Mo Vaughn stole
his first base since May 26, 1997, in the midst of the onslaught,
more than offsetting Jorge Posada's four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Having won two games in this three-game series, the Yankees will
take a day off Thursday before starting a three-game series at
Seattle on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cone had looked ahead to this start with enthusiasm, mentioning
Tuesday how he and Roger Clemens had talked about how modern
hitters dive over the plate so much and make themselves vulnerable
to breaking balls on the inside corner. A key to his pitching, Cone
said, was in varying the velocity of his pitches _ his fastball
might travel 90 miles an hour and his slow curveball goes 70
m.p.h., and the change of speed can deceive hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's radar gun readings were fine tonight, his fastball
reaching 90-91 mph consistently, and his slow curve checked in, as
he said, about 70 mph But Cone's command _ particularly his control
of his fastball _ was awful, and he never developed a suitable
secondary pitch, like a consistent slider or split-fingered
fastball, to compensate. He had no weapons and he was pounded, from
the start.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the first inning for Anaheim and with the count 2
balls and 2 strikes, Cone tried to sneak a slider over the outside
corner. Catcher Jorge Posada set his target on the edge, Cone threw
and the ball drifted over the middle of the plate, Erstad blasted
it deep into the right-center-field stands. One batter in the new
millennium, one home run.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out the next batter, Adam Kennedy, but struggled to
do so, Kennedy fouling off five pitches during the at-bat _ the
first of 16 fouls hit against Cone, most of them rapped sharply,
the Anaheim swings aggressive and sure. The inning ended when
Garret Anderson blistered a line drive to first baseman Tino
Martinez, and Cone's shoulders sagged before he returned to the
dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked Troy Glaus and Gary DiSarcina, the No. 9 hitter, in
the second; Cone snapped at the return throw from Posada after the
second walk, frustrated. Erstad was next and with the count at 2-1,
Cone threw a benign splitter and Erstad ripped a double into
right-center, two more runs scoring.
</P>
<P>
   American League hitters gripe privately that Cone receives an
additional fraction of space on the edges of the strike zone and
uses it to his advantage, spinning sliders over the expanded
corners.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone certainly did not receive any help on the fringe on
Wednesday night. Paul Schrieber, an umpire affiliated with the
National League, called a strike zone from the textbook, without
fringe benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Having worked in the other league, Schrieber does not know Cone
and Cone does not know him, and there were crucial moments when the
Yankees' right-hander would fire a ball just off the edge and hold
his pose for just a moment, emphasizing his desire to have that
pitched call a strike. He got nothing. It is one byproduct of the
new system of umpire rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's night of work concluded before the end of the third
inning. Vaughn dropped a single in front of right fielder Paul
O'Neill, Tim Salmon walked for the second time _ Cone pausing to
glare at Schrieber briefly after an unfavorable ball-strike call _
and Anderson singled, scoring another run. Glaus walked, and Allen
Watson started warming up in the bullpen. After Scott Spiezio flied
out and there was a fielder's choice, DiSarcina hit a single and
Torre was coming out to get the ball.
</P>
<P>
   As Cone watched silently from the corner of the dugout, seeing
the two runners on base come around to score after Erstad smacked
Watson's first pitch for a two-run double, he might already have
been thinking about his next start. Cone is coming to grips with
the reality that every time he pitches poorly, speculation mounts
about how much longer his career will last. He might pitch a
perfect game, finish second in the league in earned run average,
but the questions will persist because he is 37.
</P>
<P>
   He uses this to motivate himself. The inspiration will come in
handy before he pitches in the Yankees' home opener on Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
