r s BC-HKN-DUCKNOT-LADN-(SLA     04-06 0349
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TVERDOSVKY RIPS LACK OF FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Ducks might have outshot and outchanced the
Blackhawks on Wednesday, but several players weren't thrilled with
the way Anaheim played in such a crucial game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played only one period, they played better than us, it's as
simple as that,'' said Oleg Tverdosvky, who felt the Ducks weren't
as prepared to play as they should have been. ``We were losing all
the battles. We have to play all 60 minutes; you don't beat people
by playing 15 minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya didn't think the Ducks played poorly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't awful,'' he said. ``We had good intensity but not
the kind of intensity you need to win must-win games. We didn't
really let it all out until the third period and then the third
goal really took the wind out of our sails.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Not converting: The Ducks have outshot their last four
opponents (Phoenix, the Kings, Nashville and Chicago) 130-81, but
they have been outscored 11-10 and are 2-2 in the four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks were unable to take advantage of three power plays in
the game, but it wasn't because they didn't have any chances.
</P>
<P>
   Teemu Selanne appeared to have a wide-open shot on Anaheim's
first opportunity 3 minutes into the game, but Jocelyn Thibault
made a sliding two-pad save on the winger's one-timer from the left
circle.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:11 of the second period, Kariya ripped a one-timer from the
slot off the right post. Kariya, who also hit the right post in the
third period, thought it went in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's possible for it to hit the post like that
and not go in,'' said Kariya.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into Wednesday, the Ducks' power play had converted 25
percent, scoring goals in 21 of 29 games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Back on the ice: Fredrik Olausson returned to the lineup
Wednesday after missing Monday night's game with the flu, but it
wasn't a night to remember for the veteran defenseman _ Olausson
was on the ice for four of Chicago's five goals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
