<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8583 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-CELTICS-PISTONS-BOS     04-06 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-PISTONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PISTONS BEAT CELTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUBURN HILLS, Mich. _ The Celtics' much-heralded and, lest we
forget, guaranteed playoff berth became officially lost Wednesday
night. Picking up where the Bradley campaign left off, Rick Pitino
&AMP; Co. dropped their ninth straight game to officially drop out of
the postseason picture.
</P>
<P>
   The score, opponent, and site were, of course, incidental, for
this one was predetermined at least 10 days ago. It was the Pistons
and Grant Hill who got to preside over the mercy killing in a
half-filled arena, with Hill scoring 27 points in a 111-106 Detroit
victory. Pitino can now save owner Paul Gaston some money by going
for the nonrefundable fare to Secaucus, N.J., next month for the
draft lottery.
</P>
<P>
   This one looked a lot like many of the previous eight defeats.
Boston stayed close, led in the second half, but eventually
succumbed. Wednesday night, the villains were Hill and free throws.
The Pistons, as the Hornets did the night before, feasted at the
free throw line, attempting 56 freebies to the Celtics' 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a tough mountain to climb and get over,'' said Pitino,
whose team had seven more field goals and four more treys but still
couldn't get it done. ``We played a good, hard basketball game. But
our margin of error is so slight. All this is a very good learning
experience for next season.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it: next season. The Celtics knew it was going to
come to this since their devastating, double-overtime loss in
Philadelphia March 24. But they were mathematically alive until
now. They will miss the playoffs for the fifth straight year and
now need to win their remaining seven games (six at home) to pass
Pitino's first team in total wins. The nine-game losing streak is
the fifth worst in franchise history and longest since a 10-gamer
in March-April 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit, now 11-5 under George Irvine, put this one away with a
34-21 advantage in the third quarter. Hill (10-of-17 shooting) got
rolling in the quarter after what had to be a pointed halftime chat
by Irvine. The Pistons, who had lost three straight at home,
trailed by 4 at the break and could ill afford to let this one slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We allowed them to score too many points (38) in the second
quarter,'' said Jerry Stackhouse. ``I guess we had a mental
letdown. Things were kind of easy (23-12 after one quarter), and we
started to coast a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Lindsey Hunter, ``Coach wanted us to get the game back
under control, and I think we did a good job of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill poured in 13 points in the quarter and the Detroit defense,
such as it is, surfaced in spurts. The combination was enough to
give the Pistons an 80-71 lead after three quarters. From there,
Detroit went into its Constitutional Defense _ preserve, protect,
and defend _ and had enough, barely, to hold off the Celtics in a
fourth quarter that lasted longer than the Oscars.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics trailed by 12 with 2:34 to play, but made it
interesting with a hail of treys down the stretch. But all that
succeeded in doing was getting more Pistons free throws and more
timeouts. Detroit attempted 22 freebies in the fourth quarter
alone, making 18. They made 43 in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Anderson led the Celtics with 24 points, including four
treys. Paul Pierce added 20 points but had no luck getting to the
line, which Pitino duly noted afterward (but in a diplomatic way,
of course).
</P>
<P>
   Stackhouse suffered through a miserable shooting night (5 of 19)
but still had 22 points thanks to 10 freebies. Hunter added 18
points, including four treys.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics had hoped that this season-ending home stretch would
be meaningful for them. For a while, it looked like it would be. No
one could have envisioned nine straight losses after the buoyant,
back-to-back road wins in Atlanta and Dallas last month.
</P>
<P>
   They're still waiting for their next win. Whenever it does come,
it may well be at the expense of someone who needs it more. The
Celtics still can have a say in the race, albeit a muted one. That
wasn't the plan, but results sometimes get in the way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0227EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
