<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8584 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-REDSOX-MARINERS-BOS     04-06 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS BEAT RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MARINERS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A day after Bud Selig and Pedro Martinez made their
pitches, the official opening of Panic Season arrived Wednesday
night, just about the time they were wrapping up the 11 p.m. news
back home.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Martinez made the 261st start of his big-league career,
and it was the shortest of any in which the 13-year veteran was not
injured or warming up for a playoff start. It lasted only four
outs, at a cost of seven runs, four walks, a hit batter, and a
monster home run by Jay Buhner.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's performance in Wednesday night's 9-3 loss to the
Seattle Mariners was positively Rappian and reinforced all the
nagging doubts from spring training that the rotation is one part
Pedro and four parts prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Before the night was over, six home runs _ three by the
Mariners, two by the back-to-bashing Brian Daubach and one by John
Valentin _ also punched a crater-sized hole into the theory that
long ball in the Northwest died when the Kingdome went kaboom.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, Alex Rodriguez, and returning native John Olerud went
deep on successive Sox pitchers _ Martinez, John Wasdin, and Tim
Wakefield. Thursday night, the Mariners turn their sights on former
Mariners lefthander Jeff Fassero, who last season gave up 35 home
runs, a total eclipsed by only Rick Helling of the Rangers (41) and
Pedro Astacio of the Rockies (38).
</P>
<P>
   Ramon the Elder has had shorter outings only twice before. On
April 6, 1996, in Chicago's Wrigley Field, Martinez lasted just an
inning before straining his groin attempting to field a ground ball
and missed the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Then, on the last day of the '96 regular season, Martinez
pitched only an inning against the Padres because he was scheduled
to start the first game of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in 49-degree weather Wednesday night, it was obvious
from the outset that Martinez was laboring. Mike Cameron lined his
first pitch to left for a single, Mark McLemore walked on four
pitches, and Martinez hit Rodriguez in the left elbow with an 0-2
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Olerud followed with a sacrifice fly to make it 1-0, John Mabry
blooped a single to make it 2-0, and Buhner _ who sat out the
opener because he had eight whiffs in eight at-bats against Pedro
the Younger _ smoked an opposite-field home run deep into the
right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   It was no better in the second inning. Martinez walked the first
batter of the inning, Carlos Guillen, on a full count. Cameron
popped out, but McLemore walked on four pitches and a full-count
pass to Rodriguez loaded the bases. Jimy Williams lifted Martinez
for Wasdin, who walked in two runs before getting out of the
inning, then gave up a long home run to Rodriguez to start the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox answered only with the bases-empty home runs by Daubach,
in his first two at-bats of the season, and Valentin's solo shot in
the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach's home runs came off Freddy Garcia, the Venezuelan
righthander who came to the Mariners from the Astros in the Randy
Johnson deal two years ago. Johnson pitched two months for the
Astros before signing with the Diamondbacks as a free agent.
Garcia, meanwhile, went 17-8 as a rookie last season. How
impressive is that? The last Sox rookie to win as many as 17 games
in a season was Dave Ferriss, who went 21-10 in 1945, when many
big-leaguers were away at war.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle reliever Kazuhiro Sasaki made his big-league debut in
the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who had seven hits in their 2-0 win in the opener, had
nine Wednesday night, or one more than the Sox pitchers issued
walks.
</P>
<P>
   But for the second straight game Nomar Garciaparra went to bed
without one. Garciaparra went hitless in back-to-back games only
four times last season. He lined out in his first two at-bats
Wednesday night, the second time into the glove of the leaping
Rodriguez, who turned what could have been a hit into an
inning-ending double play in the third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8586 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-NULAKERS-LADN-(SL     04-06 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NULAKERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ...WRITETHROUGH 
LAKERS CLINCH HOMECOURT ADVANTAGE
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ Another season-defining moment was on the agenda
Wednesday night, but as usual, the Lakers were in no rush to
embrace it. Heck, they weren't even in a rush to win the game.
</P>
<P>
   While the Lakers took their time putting away the Golden State
Warriors at the Arena in Oakland, their closest rivals, the
Portland Trail Blazers, were losing to the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blazers fell, the Lakers automatically clinched the
NBA's best record and homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Lakers, unaware of events in the Pacific Northwest, were
not celebrating the occasion, and the only things chilling on ice
in the fourth quarter were Robert Horry's gimpy knees.
</P>
<P>
   And they labored through three quarters before deciding to put
the game away and make it all official. With a patchwork lineup, 49
points from Shaquille O'Neal and a strong finish, they did, with a
111-104 victory over the Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   At 64-12, with six games to play, no one can catch them.
</P>
<P>
   But that's been the case all season for the Lakers, who have won
11 straight and 30 of their last 31 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew tonight was a clincher, so we just had to come out and
do the job,'' said O'Neal, 19 of 27 from the field and 11 of 16
from the line. ``We didn't do the job at all in the first half, but
we were able to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, they took a minute to note their achievement, but
that was it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just business,'' Derek Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   A moment to celebrate? ``No,'' O'Neal said. ``No, no. Never
that. It's not over. . . . It means that we've done our job in the
regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   They finished it off without Horry, whose tendinitis kept him
off the floor for the final period, and without Ron Harper, who got
the night off. And they did it for most of the night without Kobe
Bryant, who struggled in his first game back from a one-game
suspension and finished with 16 points and 11 assists.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the heroics came from rookie Devean George, whose
eye-opening performance netted him 14 points on 5-of-6 shooting,
including 4 for 4 from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's nice to have that one over with and to go on home
and take a day off,'' said coach Phil Jackson. ``(The league's best
record) is what we went after this year and we finally got it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   For a second straight night, there was little support from the
supporting cast: Glen Rice got six points, Horry just two, and
without O'Neal, the Lakers shot 40 percent. So the Lakers just kept
pounding the ball inside to O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just about carried us all year,'' Fisher said of O'Neal.
``He's done more than be the MVP of this league. You can't really
say enough about him.''
</P>
<P>
   Donyell Marshall's 32 points paced the Warriors, who with a
spirited effort took a 10-point lead in the second quarter and held
the advantage throughout the second and third.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers didn't take the lead back until Bryant hit a
3-pointer with one-tenth of a second left in the third quarter, for
a 77-75 lead to head into the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Shaw and George opened the final period with back-to-back
3-pointers, and the Lakers raced to a 10-point lead, 87-77. The
Warriors mounted a late charge that cut the deficit to 102-98 with
less than three minutes to play, but the Lakers held off the
charge, with nine points from Bryant and O'Neal down the stretch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
