<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8587 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-NUANGEL-LADN-(SLA     04-06 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NUANGEL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD STAYS ON TEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ After being mesmerized by Orlando Hernandez one night
and stifled by Roger Clemens the next, the Anaheim Angels hitters
took out their frustrations on David Cone and a slew of New York
Yankees relievers Wednesday night before 24,560 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels failed to score in only one of the first seven
innings, finished with 12 hits and won their first game of 2000,
12-6, over the defending champion Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``They threw some pretty good pitchers at us in this series,''
Angels manager Mike Scioscia said. ``For us to jump on a pitcher of
Cone's caliber is a big plus for us. They know how to pitch. It was
a real well-played series by both clubs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Scioscia's first win as a major-league manager and he had
a bottle of champagne sent to him by former Dodgers teammate Don
Sutton waiting to be opened. But Scioscia wouldn't call it ``his''
first win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You keep saying it's my first win, my first win . . . it's not
my first win,'' Scioscia said. ``Those guys did it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those guys'' included Scott Schoeneweis, who went six innings
and got the victory in his first career major-league start. And
Adam Kennedy (Cal State Northridge) and Mo Vaughn, who had two hits
each. But no Angel is off to a better start to 2000 than Darin
Erstad, who went 4 for 5 Wednesday, including a home run, two
doubles and a career-high-tying five RBI. He had three hits in the
season opener Monday, two more Tuesday and is hitting .643 (9 for
14). Not a bad beginning, considering he had been in a slump since
being named to the All-Star team in the summer of '98.
</P>
<P>
   But Erstad, despite his desire to redeem himself, said there
isn't a need to put up big numbers early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care about statistics,'' he said. ``As long as I'm
feeling good and hitting the ball hard, it doesn't matter if I'm
getting hits or making outs. I don't need to get off to a fast
start to give myself confidence. If I'm executing, that's all that
matters because hits come and go.''
</P>
<P>
   They're coming now.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games, all five of Erstad's hits were singles,
and all of them were hit to the opposite field or up the middle.
Wednesday, he got his first extra-base hit, leading off the game
with a home run to right-center field off Cone, the ninth leadoff
homer of his career.
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, he hit the ball into the right-center
field gap for a two-run double. In the third, he pulled the ball
down the right-field line for another two-run double. He got his
fourth hit of the night with a single up the middle in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You gotta use the whole field to hit,'' Erstad said. ''You
take what they give you.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's success rubbed off on the rest of the team in the third
inning Wednesday when they knocked Cone out of the game and scored
six times. Vaughn began the inning with a single and eventually
scored on a single by Garret Anderson. Scott Spiezio drove in the
second run of the inning with a sacrifice fly, and one out later
Gary DiSarcina singled home another to make it 6-1. That was it for
Cone.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Angel Allen Watson entered the game and allowed Erstad's
two-run double. Kennedy followed with an RBI single but was caught
rounding first too far and was thrown out to end the inning but not
before the Angels had taken a 9-1 lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
