<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A-ROD POISED TO FORGE NEW MARINERS TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking out across the infield at Safeco Wednesday night, Nomar
Garciaparra looked bulkier than usual. His legs were one thing, the
way the thighs stretched the limits of the Red Sox uniform
doubleknit.
</P>
<P>
   It was the shoulders and upper arms that were a dead giveaway,
though, like the guy swallowed a set of barbells.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me about his workout routine,'' said Alex Rodriguez,
himself no slouch when it comes to off-season conditioning. ``It
sounds pretty intense.''
</P>
<P>
   Not intense if you are Garciaparra, though. During the
off-season, the Boston shortstop was apparently hellbent on using
his Navy Seal training regimen to whittle his ``doughboy-esque''
5.5 percent body fat down to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else can you say about him?'' Rodriguez said. ``He's a
future Hall of Famer. The guy's flawless.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the triumverate of American League shortstops who are all
on the trail of Hall of Fame inductions, World Series rings and
glossy magazine covers, there is no jealousy. Not even the annual
All-Star vote race can't dent the loyalty the Three Amigos feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who gets the most votes. I won twice. Nomar
won. Derek (Jeter) is going to win. I don't know who is the most
deserving between us and it all depends on whose fans are dialing
in,'' Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to the psychology of being in the gang that is
made up of Garciaparra, Jeter and A-Rod, very little escapes the
attention of the other two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's some healthy competition going on,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we motivate each other in a way where we're trying to
subconsciously try and out-do each other. It's fun. Those guys are
great competitors, great team players and more than anything, the
common denominator is we're all focused on the 24 guys on our
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that, after a good night at the ballyard, A-Rod hasn't been
above leaving a message on Jeter's answering machine, telling the
Yankees shortstop to tune into ``SportsCenter'' for the highlights.
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly an uncommon topic, this Gang of Three Shortstops
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is interesting, peculiar almost, that on the Mariners'
opening homestand _ the start of the season in which Rodriguez's
fate and future will be determined _ Garciaparra and Jeter are
trotting through Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Rodriguez and his agent, Scott Boras, waded through a
series of meetings with Mariners officials, the crux of which was
to determine whether the team should trade Rodriguez or wait.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Garciaparra and Jeter squared off in the American
League Championship Series. They were under the lights, on display
and loving it.
</P>
<P>
   With Garciaparra and Jeter right in the thick of things, the '99
ALCS was a fitting collision between the Yankees and Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one thing Rodriguez knows about Seattle and the
Mariners, it is the relative absence of that kind of tradition. And
with the Mariners' move to Safeco Field, the franchise has an
especially blank sort of slate on its hands.
</P>
<P>
   The Kingdome and its quirky place in time has been frozen in
memory. The Mariners' '95 run seems a streaky bit of magic that
dissipated with the club's inability to take the next step in time
to build on that energy and momentum.
</P>
<P>
   This is where A-Rod comes in. This is why he was not traded. It
is his role to figurehead this new era. He and the Mariners were
eager for A-Rod to play this role in the first post-Ken Griffey,
Safeco Field season.
</P>
<P>
   Bless Rodriguez for attempting to put the franchise on his back.
It is a noble task and one the smooth 24-year-old seems to be
taking seriously.
</P>
<P>
   He calls the infield at Safeco the best in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   He is taking leadership responsibility, more visibly now whereas
before it was a behind-the-scenes variety.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to commence a new era of baseball in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to be the one to kickstart tradition, a winning one,
something that will set a standard for the Mariners for the future,
even if it seems a very tall order, even for A-Rod.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone, Garciaparra holds the Mariners shortstop in high
esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love watching him play,'' Garciaparra said. ``He's got all
the tools. He's got a great arm. He can steal bases. He's
unbelievable offensively. He can hit for power, average. He's got
all the tools you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez may have all the tools you need upon which to build a
franchise but Rodriguez has an eye for the big picture. He has an
eye for looking out to the infield this week and seeing his two
shortstop peers and knowing where they were last October and what a
Red Sox or Yankees uniform means in the historic context of things.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez fashions himself the kind of player who can be the
foundation. He also wonders if there is another cap that would be a
better fit for the bigger plans he has. He isn't jealous of
Garciaparra and Jeter. It doesn't mean he isn't extremely curious.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
