<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS HAVE SINKING FEELING
</HEADLINE>
 ... WRITETHROUGH (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ For the better part of seven seasons Guy Hebert has
played well when the Anaheim Mighty Ducks have needed him.
Wednesday night the Anaheim goalie was a no-show in the team's
biggest game of the year _ a 5-2 loss to the Chicago Blackhawks
before 15,112 at United Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert gave up three goals from over 40 feet and was easily
beaten by Bob Probert on a breakaway, while Chicago goalie Jocelyn
Thibault's 27 saves put the Ducks' Western Conference playoff hopes
on life support.
</P>
<P>
   With two games to play, Anaheim (33-35-12-2) needs help, and
lots of it, after it was unable to help itself against a Chicago
team it had defeated eight times in the previous 10 meetings
(8-1-1).
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks fell to 10th place and lost any chance of catching San
Jose, which clinched a playoff spot with a victory over Dallas on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's faint hopes of catching eighth-place Edmonton now
depend on ninth-place Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks must win their two remaining games and hope the
Canucks defeat Edmonton on Friday and then loss to or tie the
Sharks on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their goalie and the goal posts were the difference,'' said
Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg, who watched as Paul Kariya hit the
post twice in a game that was up for grabs until the middle of the
third period.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who was a threat each time he stepped on the ice, beat
Thibault with a backhander at 9:40 after taking a breakaway pass
from Teemu Selanne to tie the game 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, it looked as if they was a real chance the Ducks might
pull within two points of Edmonton, which had lost to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   But 38 seconds later Jean-Yves Leroux wristed a 40 footer from
the top of the left circle that beat Hebert to give the Blackhawks
a 3-2 lead and likely end any dreams of postseason hockey in
Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was going to be our game (after Kariya scored his
39th goal of the year), then boom, the next shift it's 3-2,'' said
Selanne, who assisted on both Anaheim goals. ``We had great scoring
chances and they throw a puck at the net and it goes in.''
</P>
<P>
   Leroux's goal was the third of three 40-foot plus shots that got
by Hebert, who continues to give up soft goals at an alarming rate
as he suffers through the most inconsistent year of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Sullivan beat him with a long one-timer at 14:47 of the
first period and Kevin Dean's harmless looking wrist shot slipped
past him at 5:32 of the second to give the Blackhawks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   There was some traffic in front of Hebert on two of the first
three goals, but Hartsburg was in no mood to defend his veteran
goalie.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't score from there at this time of year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Hebert was healthy the coach said, ``If he wasn't 100
precent healthy, he wouldn't have been in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, as they have in so many games in the second half of
the season, outchanced their opponent, but goals, not chances, are
what count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating because they are scoring on what aren't even
scoring chances,'' said Hartsburg, whose Ducks outshot the
Blackhawks 29-22. ``It's not like there are guys standing alone in
front of the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get a breakaway and make a great play (to score)
and they wrist one and it's in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Probert did break in alone when Oleg Tverdovsky and Steve
Rucchin got tangled up at the Chicago blue line as the Ducks were
desperately pressing to score the tying goal. Hebert could have
kept the Ducks in the game, but Probert made it look easy, beating
him on the stick side at 16:37 of the third period to give Chicago
a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Amonte scored his 42nd goal of the year into a empty net at
18:54.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's goal was his 20th, but realistically the Ducks were
done in by two players scoring their third goals of the year (Dean
and Leroux) and one scoring his fourth (Probert).
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set in the first period when Thibault stopped
Kariya in the first 30 seconds, made a fine stop on Antti Aalto and
an even better one on Selanne's one-timer from the left circle
while Anaheim was on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   Having survived the first wave, the Blackhawks took a 1-0 lead
when Sullivan beat Hebert cleanly from the top of the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya hit the first of his two post just over two minutes into
the second period and a Tverdovsky's bid was turned aside by
Thibault before Dean's floater from the blue line gave the
Blackhawks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The goal put the Ducks in a desperate situation and less than a
minute later a gamble by Ruslan Salei paid off. The Anaheim
defenseman jumped into the play and was in position to pick up a
deflected Selanne pass in the left circle and beat Thibault at 6:26
of the second.
</P>
</TEXT>
