<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUHNER BLAST IGNITES MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Opening day for many of the Mariners was Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   For Jay Buhner, it was Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And if the evening wasn't accentuated by the rockets' red glare
of the traditional pre-opener fireworks, no problem.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner came prepared. He brought his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the lineup Wednesday night against Boston's Ramon Martinez
after being relegated to the bench against Ramon's brother Pedro
Tuesday, Buhner rid himself of some of the last two seasons' worth
of frustration with a three-run homer in his first at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   With Buhner lighting the torch and leading the parade, the
Mariners scored five runs in the first inning en route to a 9-3 win
over the Red Sox that was as comfortable as your daddy's old
beat-up recliner.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, plagued by injuries that even now have him talking about
post-2000 retirement, drove in four of the runs himself, adding a
second-inning bases-loaded walk to the homer. He also singled to
continue where he left off in the spring _ leading the Mariners
with seven homers while driving in 23 homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay took charge and got us going,'' manager Lou Piniella said.
</P>
<P>
   With that lead suitably Buhner-ized for him, Seattle starter
Freddy Garcia survived a couple of Brian Daubach solo homers to
pilot the Mariners home to their first victory of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting five runs like that, you want to stay in the game,''
said Garcia, who battled his control throughout his five innings.
``I had trouble finding my focus, but it helped having those
runs.''
</P>
<P>
   It was clear from the start that Red Sox's starter Ramon
Martinez, a once-dominant pitcher who has had success leeched from
him by a series of injuries, wasn't going to match the panache
displayed by his brother, Pedro, a night earlier.
</P>
<P>
   A Mike Cameron single set the play in motion, and soon the stage
was set with runners all around after Martinez walked Mark McLemore
and hit Alex Rodriguez. John Olerud brought the first run of the
Seattle season home with a run-scoring fly ball to center, and an
instant later it was 2-0 on an end-of-the-bat flare by John Mabry.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Buhner. Exit baseball. For the last two years Buhner has
battled upper body _ right elbow ligament replacement _ and lower
body _ arthroscopic surgery on his left knee _ ailment that have
cut the heart of what should have been two of the most productive
seasons of his career.
</P>
<P>
   After half a year of determined rehabilitation, Buhner says he
feels great. His bat is punctuating that message.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who rose to prominence last year on the strength of an
iron-willed fastball and 17 subsequent wins, didn't have the kind
of command that shows him at his best. Even so, he was more than a
match for the Red Sox's offense, which blitzed him twice in the
person of Daubach, but was otherwise docile.
</P>
<P>
   ``My fingers felt a little fat tonight,'' Garcia said when asked
about the chilled air of Safeco Field. ``I was behind in the count
a lot. I wasn't that sharp.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston leadoff hitter Jose Offerman reached base three times
against Garcia, but he got no support from the batters behind him
and was left stranded in scoring position each time.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia was pulled after 92 pitches and five innings, enough to
qualify for the win on a night when the evening started at a brisk
49 degrees and tailed off. He was relieved by Frankie Rodriguez,
Arthur Rhodes and Kazuhiro Sasaki, the all-time Japan saves leader,
who pitched the ninth inningin making his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to see (Rhodes and Sasaki) do what they did in
the last two innings,'' Piniella said. Past Mariner bullpens had
had troubles with leads, but the Mariners have high hopes that's
all behind them. ``We've had real nice pitching the first two
games. I'm just hoping it stays like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle padded its early 5-0 lead with a couple of runs in the
second inning. Well, the Mariners didn't have as much to do with it
as did the out-of-control Martinez and his replacement, John
Wasdin.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez was unceremoniously shown the door after walking three
of the first four men he faced. Wasdin, brought into a reliever's
no-man's land _ the bases loaded _ walked Olerud, the first man he
faced, and Buhner, the third, to bring the Seattle runs home and
get the lead fluffed up after Garcia had allowed a Daubach bomb to
land in the right field seats.
</P>
<P>
   Daubach was back at it in the fourth, mangling a Garcia serve in
classic style, wresting the ball out over the center field wall.
But Rodriguez was able to answer for Seattle in the bottom of the
inning with his first homer, to right-center.
</P>
<P>
   The teams weren't done decorating Safeco with baseballs. Olerud
his hit first homer out to right in the bottom of the sixth to run
his RBI count to three, and Boston third baseman John Valentin
countered with his No. 1 to left field in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached
</P>
<P>
   at 206-448-8004 or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
