<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS COULD BE THE YEAR FOR DAVID DUVAL AT AUGUSTA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Inside these secretive, hedged walls, where
golfers such as Arnold Palmer and Jack Nicklaus have been afforded
a fountain of youth, where golf fans are so desperate for
admittance they will pay anything, where no stray blade of grass or
piece of trash is permitted to skip freely through the grounds, you
search for a sign. You search vainly for the anointed one.
</P>
<P>
   The favorite rarely wins here. And if he does, often a huge toll
is extracted.
</P>
<P>
   How else do you explain Larry Mize, Ian Woosnam and Jose Maria
Olazabal (twice) shyly pulling on green jackets when others seemed
so deserving?
</P>
<P>
   Or a graybeard Nicklaus prevailing at 46 and a fresh-scrubbed
Tiger Woods having his way at 21?
</P>
<P>
   Or the sudden, almost cruel banishment of Nick Faldo, Sandy Lyle
and Seve Ballesteros from the throne room, or Greg Norman's
complete isolation from southern glory?
</P>
<P>
   Augusta National chooses its victors carefully, almost with
religious rite.
</P>
<P>
   Say a golf prayer for David Duval. This week, it might be
answered.
</P>
<P>
   This message was personally delivered to him late Tuesday
morning, as wind whipped through the pines and intermittent rain
made everything a little fresher and greener. The greatest player
to have never won a major was playing alone, just him and a crush
of spectators, when he stepped off the 18th tee and someone
whispered anonymously from the crowd:
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon, David.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida native and former Georgia college student never
looked up as he strode up the fairway, 10 yards behind his caddie,
lost in his thoughts. But that doesn't mean he wasn't listening.
Minutes later, Duval was reminding a somewhat skeptical press corps
of the vast possibilities that once surrounded his career, now
seemingly swallowed up by the seductive power of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, the rest of the PGA Tour has kowtowed to its marquee
draw, surrendering before the first divot is drawn. For a change,
the normally staid Duval, an 11-time winner, is pushing himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think any event he plays in is Tiger's event to win,
which not too long ago was the case with me,'' Duval said. ``I
think this is my event to win or lose this week. Point being, it's
not going to change, no matter what anybody else feels.''
</P>
<P>
   His thought process might remain unaltered, but not so his body
tone. Duval has gone through a physical transformation not unlike
an Augusta National fairway _ once frumpy now almost anorexic. He
weighs about 175 pounds, down 15 or 20. But he claims he's fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's beneficial to my golf,'' the former Georgia Tech
player said. ``I don't think there's any way it can be harmful. So
I'll continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval has not won in 12 months, since capturing the BellSouth
Classic the week before last year's Masters. But he has four top-10
finishes in nine events this season, lending credence to his
contender status. And he points out his victories weren't all that
long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't take them away,'' he said. ``You know, I know how
to do it. I've been there a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas Duval went with shrinkage, Woods has picked up
weightlifting and tried to bulk up. What we're left with, of
course, is Beauty and the Beast.
</P>
<P>
   To pick another trip to the coatroom for Woods would almost be
too easy, but it can't be discounted. He has won or nearly won
every tournament he has entered since the turn of the century. He
has won wire to wire, won walking a tightrope wire.
</P>
<P>
   And with each nearly unchallenged step, he has kept the Masters
in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been targeting this,'' Woods said. ``My game has been
getting better week by week. I'm excited about some of the shots
I'm hitting now and the control I have. I've been working hard to
get to this point, and it's nice to see the fruits of good, hard
labor.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods also has witnessed Augusta National tinker with its layout
every year since his 12-stroke victory in 1997, attempting to make
the course ``Tiger-proof.'' So far, this has worked.
</P>
<P>
   There is 1{-inch rough where once there was none. Fairway
landing areas have been altered, sloped to send dead-center tee
shots rolling unheeded into the higher grass. Trees have been
moved. New pin placements promise to have even his Stripeness
chasing his own tail.
</P>
<P>
   Players say the biggest change comes with the 485-yard 10th
hole, a par 4 that serves as the gateway to Amen Corner. The green
was rebuilt, with new pin placements to the front and rear. And
rather than funnel the ball into the fairway, a tee shot hit long
and right will end up in deeper rough on a hillside.
</P>
<P>
   The 430-yard ninth hole also pulls fairway balls into the right
rough, a departure from the downhill straightaway it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   The aim has been to neutralize the longer hitter, to update the
course against the modern player. Outwardly, Woods seems unfettered
by it all, offering a mild protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's such a great golf course, I don't see the need to
always have to change it every year,'' he said. ``They always add a
little something here and there. I guess that's something they like
to do around this place. I don't know. Maybe they get bored.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people seem to be getting tired of Tiger. People other than
Hal Sutton.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he considered Woods the Masters favorite, Spaniard
Sergio Garcia responded, ``I don't know if he's going to win. This
course is a tough course. Anybody in this field has a chance of
winning. I don't think you need to focus on one guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, two players who used to own the spotlight, Palmer
and Nicklaus, won't win this week. But every April, they show up _
one 70, the other 60 _ unable to cut their ties to Augusta magic.
</P>
<P>
   In this land of a thousand red-brick churches, Duval could be
the subject of Sunday's sermon. He's been mentioned before.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Duval finished second by a stroke, beaten by Mark
O'Meara's final-hole birdie putt.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Duval was sixth, five strokes behind the winner,
Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger or no Tiger, the lean one looks relaxed. He feels good.
He's not afraid to share this with anyone either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm confident and I think I'm going to have a lot of good
things happen this week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
