<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-CO     04-06 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Destroying reputations in cyberspace
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, April 9, 2000.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bad news travels fast, getting faster. In these days, it travels
at cyber speed. And as we have learned when things travel too close
to the speed of light, they can become bent and distorted.
</P>
<P>
   It is not news that lies and misinterpretations corrupt the
Internet. It is a regular occurrence, one that confounds
authorities. Last year at this time, e-mail messages poured
chain-like to people informing them that fashion designer Tommy
Hilfiger had slurred Jews and African-Americans on the Oprah
Winfrey show. Despite the fact that Hilfiger had not, in fact had
not even appeared on the Winfrey program, there were incessant mass
e-mail messages calling for a boycott of Hilfiger products.
</P>
<P>
   Now, such a thing is happening to Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site purveyor of books, music, videos and just about
anything else, is under fire principally by Jewish people for
offering for sale the notoriously anti-Semitic book ``The Protocols
of the Elders of Zion.'' This book, allegedly authored in Russia at
the turn of the last century, has had a long shelf life among those
who would foster anti-Semitic feelings.
</P>
<P>
   None other than the openly anti-Semitic Henry Ford was one of
its most arduous circulators in the 1920s through a newspaper he
published in Dearborn, Mich. Now, decades later, mass mailings of
e-mail messages are pouring across the Internet calling for a
boycott of Amazon.com based on ... what?
</P>
<P>
   Ah, that's the issue: What?
</P>
<P>
   In all the messages, it is acknowledged that Amazon.com has a
perfect right to sell this scurrilous book, just as it does other
objectionable material. One in case is Joseph Lewis's 1926
anti-religious diatribe ``The Bible Unmasked.'' Amazon.com also
offers that book, but I do not see a similar reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Then why should there be a call to boycott? Well, as best I can
tell, the originator of the ``Protocol'' e-mail complaint alleged
that Amazon.com wrote a favorable review of the book. Anyone who
knows Amazon.com's Web site knows that Amazon.com does not write
reviews of any books; instead it opens its site for readers to
write reviews, and also carries the reviews of the book's
publishers _ in this case, Book Tree Press, a house that claims to
specialize in publishing controversial books.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the wave of e-mail response to the reaction caused
the Anti Defamation League of B'nai B'rith to offer a review of its
own, and for Amazon.com to publish a disavowal of any approval of
the book on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, the e-mail message continues to circulate.
</P>
<P>
   And the question remains. If no one is calling for a book ban _
all citing speech freedoms _ and if Amazon.com did not favorably
review the book, then why is the message continuing to circulate
calling for a boycott of Amazon.com?
</P>
<P>
   It's because it's like a runaway freight train; no one knows how
to stop it. That's what happens with the Internet. There are no
checks and balances. Likely, there are people all over the world
still harboring a notion that Amazon.com wrote a favorable review
and should be rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   It is frightening how a person or company can be destroyed
simply by posting something harmful about them in cyberspace, even
if it is untrue. The message, if it plays properly to the
sympathies or vagaries of its recipients, can become an evergreen,
constantly there to unfairly damage its target.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
