<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0058 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 09:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8643 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX     04-06 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The case against the case against Gore
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The case a former top federal prosecutor made for the Justice
Department appointing a special prosecutor to investigate Al Gore's
political fund-raising turns out to be just about as good a case
for Attorney General Janet Reno's decision not to.
</P>
<P>
   We have testimony for that from no less than the prosecutor
himself, Charles LaBella. Well, after a fashion.
</P>
<P>
   While you've been idling away the time with trivialities like
keeping body and soul together these last few years, the LaBella
memo has been a particularly noisy sideshow on the midway of
Washington's Scandalrama.
</P>
<P>
   LaBella had argued strongly, it was widely said, for the
appointment of a special prosecutor. But he had been quashed and
his memo with him. To all in the Vast Right-Wing Conspiracy, Reno's
disagreement and the fact that Justice kept the memo private were
more evidence of a cover-up by the criminal Clintons and their
underworld lackeys.
</P>
<P>
   But it turns out that the author himself sees no cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking recently on ``Meet the Press,'' LaBella said, ``I
really don't believe the attorney general in any way, shape or form
was protecting anybody, or anybody else at the Justice Department
was politically protecting anybody.'' The issues, he said, were
bureaucratic, not partisan.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, LaBella doubts any prosecutions would have
resulted from an independent counsel's investigation. ``It's a long
shot,'' he said, ``of whether or not charges should be filed,
whether or not anything really happened that was wrong, illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBella felt unanswered questions justified a special prosecutor
and that if exoneration followed, it would be more credible from an
independent investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a jump ball _ it's too close a call for us to make,'' he
said in the TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   Let's freeze-frame the ball in midair.
</P>
<P>
   At that crucial moment, Reno has already sicced special
prosecutors on the president and three Cabinet officers. Kenneth
Starr's supposed Whitewater investigation has metastasized into
several White House operations _ and we haven't even come to Monica
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ceaseless opponents have mastered the trick of
boosting obscure charges against him into the media and then using
their very presence in the media to clamor that only the
appointment of special prosecutors could clear the air. They've
been shopping for ways to get the vice president in similar hot
water.
</P>
<P>
   On the one side, a premier Justice Department attorney holds
that referral to a special prosecutor is justified and called for,
in part for appearances' sake _ though, we now know, he doubts that
much, if anything, would come of it. On the other hand, we have the
prospect of an already spreading legal chaos surging from the
presidency to the vice presidency, and on iffy grounds, in effect
placing the whole executive branch of government in custody.
</P>
<P>
   Reno knew she'd be slammed for it by the Clinton-hunters, but
more and more it looks as though she was right to go for the jump
ball.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 0917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i PM-ELIAN-0406-COX     04-06 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 PM-ELIAN-0406-COX &HT;    ELIAN'S FATHER ARRIVES IN U.S. TO CLAIM HIS 6-YEAR-OLD SON
 &HT;    With Rick McKay Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: For PMs of Thurs., April 6.
 &HT;    By ANDREW ALEXANDER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The father of Elian Gonzalez arrived in America
Thursday morning to claim his son, accusing Miami relatives of
exploiting the 6-year-old boy and demanding a halt to ``endless,
confusing procedures'' in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I will soon be able to embrace my son,'' Juan Miguel
Gonzales said in what he called a ``message to the American
people'' delivered on the tarmac shortly after arriving at Dulles
International Airport outside Washington. ``I am confident that the
U.S. authorities will not allow my child to continue to be hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   The father's arrival is a dramatic turn in the custody battle
for Elian, who saw his mother and 10 others drown off the Florida
coast last November as they fled Cuba on a small boat for the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was subsequently placed in the care of Miami relatives,
who are expected Thursday to return to negotiations with U.S.
immigration officials over the terms of his possible return to his
father. A psychologist is also expected to visit with Elian and the
family to counsel them on the possible trauma of separating them.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder told reporters in Washington
this morning that federal authorities will continue to seek a
``cooperative arrangement'' by which Elian would be transferred to
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father and the son need to be together,'' Holder said,
``and in the coming days, we will do everything we can to see that
that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department has allowed the Miami relatives to retain
custody of Elian while they appeal a U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service ruling that they boy should be returned to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The 31-year-old father was accompanied to Washington by his wife
and 6-month-old son. They arrived from Havana about 6:30 a.m. EST
on a private, U.S.-flagged Learjet along with a small group of
Cuban officials that included Fernando Remirez, the head of the
Cuban Interests Section in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   They will stay at the Remirez residence in suburban Bethesda,
Md., while the negotiations over Elian's transfer continues.
Remirez is temporarily moving out of his home and waving its
diplomatic immunity, reportedly to lessen the appearance that the
father is under the control of communist Cuban authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``As if his mother's disappearance before his eyes and the
miracle of his arrival have not inflicted enough damage,'' the
father said, Elian ``has had to spend time under the temporary
custody of some distant relatives who had never seen him before.''
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzales, speaking in Spanish through an interpreter,
said it has been an ``agonizing experience to see my son submitted
to cruel psychological pressures aimed at influencing his
personality, already weakened by the terrible trauma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Worse still, Elian's been paraded and exhibited in public
rallies and by the media with a clear intent to obtain political
advantage from this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian was seen this morning playing in the yard of the Miami
home where he has been staying. He reportedly had not been informed
that his father had come to the United States on a mission to take
him back to his home in Cardenas, Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere in Miami's Little Havana neighborhood remained
tense, as some in the Cuban exile community vowed to form a human
chain around the house in an attempt top prevent Elian from being
removed.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise in Washington, there was a visible police presence
around the home where the father will be staying. As he delivered
his remarks at Dulles Airport, a handful of protestors could be
heard shouting: ``Welcome to freedom.'' The father appeared to hear
their chants, but did not acknowledge them.
</P>
<P>
   For months, many members of Miami's politically influential
Cuban exile community have vowed never to allow the boy to be
returned to what they view as the oppressive regime of Cuban
President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   But Ramon Saul Sanchez, a spokesman for the anti-Castro
Democracy Movement in Miami, sounded conciliatory when interviewed
this morning on CNN. He spoke of the need to negotiate a peaceful
``transition'' to the father.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear when a reunion between father and son might take
place, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cannot happen in one or two days,'' Linda Osberg-Braun, a
lawyer for the boy's Miami relatives said on the NBC ``Today''
show. ``That would be like Elian losing his mother a second time.''
</P>
<P>
   In his comments, Juan Miguel Gonzales said he is ``truly
impatient to have (Elian) returned to me as soon as possible and go
back to Cuba together immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   However, in recent days INS officials have indicated they will
seek to have Elian transferred to the custody of his father and
then have them both wait in Washington until appeals are exhausted
in U.S. courts.
</P>
<P>
   (Andrew Alexander can be reached by e-mail at:
andya(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:10 </DATE_TIME>
