<HEADLINE>
CHRISTMAS IS OVER, FOLKS, NO MORE EXCUSES 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toysrus.com ducks an e-mail message. Eddie Bauer's Web site
grinds to a near halt. And at Lands' End's Internet call center, a
busy representative gets testy. The Christmas-time crunch?
</P>
<P>
   Nope. It was March, one of the slower selling times for
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   According to the conventional wisdom, consumers who shop during
off-peak periods should be able to experience a smoother and less
glitchy shopping experience. But so far, analysts say they aren't
convinced that Web merchants are making good on their promises to
beef up customer service _ whether it be via phone, email or simply
making it easy to buy things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a lot of religion that came after
Christmas,'' said Gina Paglucia Morrison, an analyst with the
Cambridge, Mass. Internet consulting firm MainSpring. ``But I don't
know if too many dollars went toward that.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, some Internet merchants appear to be placing a
greater emphasis on improving customer service. In an informal
survey of 14 Web stores by The Boston Globe, the Gap Inc. and
800.com Inc. showed they could both operate speedy sites and
respond quickly to even the most offbeat customer questions.
</P>
<P>
   In eight minutes, the Gap's Melissa Hare responded to an
electronic message requesting help finding a children's sweater in
pink, suggesting a blend of ``mohair/wool/cashmere/silk.''
</P>
<P>
   It took three hours for 800.com, an online retailer of music,
videos, and consumer electronics, to respond to an e-mail. But an
employee not only explained to us the reason why the price of the
``Sixth Sense'' videotape was more than quadruple the cost of the
DVD equivalent _ but also gave us skinny on the movie industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The studios mark the price up high so that people will rent
the videos from rental stores instead of purchasing them first,''
the employee wrote. ``The reason that DVDs are so much cheaper when
first released is because the rental demand at this point is very
low.''
</P>
<P>
   In sharp contrast, Toysrus.com and 1800flowers.com did not
respond to e-mail questions. Other Web retailers, like bookseller
Borders.com and online education store SmarterKids.com, took
several days to return e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like, thank God you don't need an ambulance,'' cracked
Adam Phillips, a vice president with the online florist
Geraldstevens.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Phillips isn't laughing too hard. When informed that his
company took six hours to respond to an e-mail question _ a time
that he says should be shortened. To hear that, he said ``is
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, busy customer service employees didn't seem interested
in helping. Reached by telephone, an abrupt Lands' End
representative told us we needed to look up stock numbers for cuff
links before she could answer questions about the items.
</P>
<P>
   At eddiebauer.com's call center, an employee claimed she knew
nothing about the catalog retailer's Internet store. CDnow Inc., an
Internet music and video store, placed its toll-free telephone
number in a tiny corner of its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the retailer did not want to hear from customers,
an employee giggled. ``Sometimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say online retailers seem to be spending more time on
developing features that allow consumers to virtually try on
clothing, listen to music, or personalize Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   The latest craze _ trying to improve sales by predicting
customers' likes and dislike and suggesting suitable purchases _
can have unexpected results. Order a California guide for a
vacation, and Amazon.com keeps recommending books about that state.
Tell 800.com that you adore Nina Simone, the Dave Matthews Band and
Sarah McLachlan _ and the retailer informs you that you may enjoy
listening to the Butthole Surfers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest aggravation is the increasing demand for passwords in
order to make a purchase. E-merchants argue that it allows them to
better serve you. But busy consumers aren't looking for another
password. And who needs the extra steps when all you really want is
to have the flowers arrive on time?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE SHOPPING SITES, RATED &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   www.amazon.com
</P>
<P>
   800-201-7575
</P>
<P>
   Description: One of the most experienced online stores,
Amazon.com has morphed into a shopping mall, offering everything
from books to home theater systems to auctions.
</P>
<P>
   Ease of use: Speedy and easy-to-navigate Web site. Amazon.com's
one-click buying process is a plus for busy consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone response: Polite and knowledgable response. Customer
service representative picked up on first ring.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail response: Received 13 hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Features: Based on your shopping history, Amazon.com makes what
it hopes are good buying suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Pet peeve: Bad buying suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   Shipping: Standard shipping within seven business days. $2 to
$4.95 per order, depending on item, plus a charge of up to $1.25
per product.
</P>
