<HEADLINE>
REINVENTING THE TELEPHONE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the hoopla over high-speed-Internet this and wireless
that, a lot of American businesses would still love to just find a
better, cheaper, and more flexible office telephone system.
Innovations in ``plain old telephone service'' are what they are
looking for, and two area companies are among those aiming to meet
the demand.
</P>
<P>
   BizFon of Salem, N.H., recently began offering a $1,500 box that
provides all the services associated with big-company phone
systems, including voice mail, five-way conferencing, and even your
own selection of music on hold.
</P>
<P>
   MCK Communications Inc. of Needham, Mass., meanwhile, has just
rolled out a product called Extender 100 that turns a
telecommuter's laptop computer into an extension of the home-office
switchboard. That allows users to answer their office line from
whatever phone they have plugged into the computer and use the
company's outgoing long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies are targeting what are estimated to be big
markets. As of two years ago, 90 percent of US small businesses had
no automated phone system, according to Framingham, Mass.
researchers International Data Corp., largely because there were
few low-end, do-it-yourself options available from telecom giants
like Lucent Technologies or Nortel Networks.
</P>
<P>
   And within three years, the number of US telecommuters is
expected to reach 40 million, according to the Gartner Group, a
leading telecommunications consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   In both cases, the companies are selling products that can be
set up by anyone who can plug in a telephone, record a voice-mail
greeting and, in the case of the MCK product, use a computer
keyboard to dial phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The basic $1,500 BizFon box, which can also be leased for $80 a
month, supports up to six incoming lines fed out to eight office
lines. Up to four boxes can be stacked for companies that need 25
to 32 phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've plugged in the phone lines, a simple press of a
button launches the BizFon 680. The base unit supports up to 100
minutes of recorded voice mail, with plug-in ``Voice Vault'' cards
available for $300 to add another 120 minutes and $400 to add 240
minutes more. And you can also record your own on-hold music from a
compact disc as an alternative to Muzak.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's basically been designed as a consumer product,'' said
BizFon engineering vice president Bob Laroche. ``We're trying to
take the mystery out of office telephony and keep you from needing
the guys who show up in a white truck to install it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some special features: By dialing extension 299, anyone who has
bought the box is instantly connected to BizFon customer service.
And extension 290 is an in-house conference call bridge, so you
don't have to pay AT&AMP;T or another carrier a dollar a minute to put
together a multiparty conference call.
</P>
<P>
   The BizFon device can also turn remote lines (like a home office
phone) into the functional equivalent of another office extension,
so a telecommuter can reach other people by dialing their extension
and answer calls to their office line as if they were right there.
</P>
<P>
   MCK's Extender 100 uses a connection to a telecommuter's laptop
to link whatever phone they are using to the office switchboard, as
long as they have a high-speed data connection such as a cable
modem or digital subscriber line.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that takes some adjustment is that you have to
click on an icon on your computer desktop to open a program to use
it, then dial all your calls from the laptop screen. When the
product is in use, the telephone connected to the laptop becomes
just a ``dumb handset'' through which you speak, although coming
versions will allow you to dial on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   The Extender 100 runs $400 per individual using it, plus another
$3,900 or $4,900 for a box at the company offices to support eight
to 12 off-site users. Your company has to pay for a daylong phone
call to where you are working to keep you connected, even during
times when you are not using the phone.
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston uses an MCK system for graveyard shift clerks to work
from home without having to schlep downtown, while Circuit City
uses a version to route tech-support calls to people scattered all
over the country.
</P>
<P>
   MCK officials see their products as being an especially useful
bridge between conventional ``private branch exchanges,'' or PBXs,
the lifeblood of a big company switchboard, and devices now hitting
the market that will link all voice calls into a data switch. PBX's
are the devices that allow people within a company or organization
to dial each other by extension number and pools outgoing
long-distance calls to save money, among other functions.
</P>
<P>
   While converged voice-data systems are widely expected to render
obsolete the millions of old-fashioned PBX's in use, in recent
years the number of traditional voice-circuit PBX's has still been
growing by over 1.5 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really think PBX's are nowhere near dead,'' said MCK's Al
Brisard. ``As new devices come along, we will plug right in to the
next generation. We think we are in a good place, because nobody's
today really giving you an idea of how you will get from the old to
the new.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices, weather forecasts and traffic reports may be handy
things to get from your wireless phone, but for some people far
less compelling than the Holy Grail: A Saturday morning golf
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   As the wireless industry races to make you see your cell phone
as an indispensable Internet tool, a Billerica, Mass. company is
rolling out a new service for golf nuts to beat the midweek rush
for a prime weekend tee time.
</P>
<P>
   Later this spring, CSP Inc.'s ModComp subsidiary will unveil a
system allowing members and guests of the Club Henri Chappelle in
Belgium to use their wireless Net phones to book foursomes. By
using the phone to visit a special Web portal set up by the club,
golfers can scroll through a list of available times on selected
days and enter a confirmation number to book a time.
</P>
<P>
   One obvious question is: Who would want to go through the hassle
of maneuvering around a tiny phone screen to reserve a golf time
when you could just use the phone to call the pro shop and ask,
``Do you have a time for four Saturday at 8 a.m.?''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander R. Lupinetti, chairman and chief executive of CSP,
said, ``If it was easier doing it some other way, you'd do it some
other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The wireless system could be a way around the mad pro-shop phone
crush on Wednesday or Thursday mornings when many courses begin
taking reservations for the weekend. And while many US golf courses
use automated voice-response systems that respond to touch tones to
reserve times, Lupinetti thinks many golfers would find it faster
and easier to scroll through a list of times directly. Plus,
golfers would be able to call any hour of the week.
</P>
<P>
   The software necessary to run the system, which supports a wide
range of other transaction- and inquiry-oriented business purposes,
starts at about $5,000, and the overall cost of launching a
wireless phone reservation system would likely run less than
$20,000 per club, Lupinetti said. So after the first, say, 100
foursomes at $50 a head used the service who might otherwise go
elsewhere, a club could quickly make more money by filling up
unused tee times.
</P>
<P>
   Lupinetti said the company has no current sales prospects in New
England. Within the next three years, as many as 700 million
Internet-capable wireless phones are expected to be in use around
the world, but Lupinetti said how soon New Englanders can make tee
times wirelessly is ``all a function of how quickly these phones
will become available here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
