<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN TECH INVESTOR SHOWS HOW TO KEEP COOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a guy with a good chunk of his money in technology stocks,
Steve Demirjian didn't look too ruffled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   That is probably because Demirjian has been investing in
technology for the past 17 years, first at Essex Investment
Management and for the past four years at Westfield Capital
Management in Boston. Westfield manages about $2.1 billion for
institutions and wealthy individuals. Last year, riding the tech
wave, many of its accounts were up better than 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   We sat down with Demirjian Wednesday to sort out this
topsy-turvy week in technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Have you been doing a lot of buying and selling this week?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think in a market like this the best thing to do is
nothing. You have to know what you own and not get swayed one way
or another. These short-term moves can be scary, and you can lose a
lot of money very quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you own the stocks that have gotten creamed this week?
</P>
<P>
   A. Fortunately, we didn't own the high-flying, big-momentum tech
stocks that had no earnings. We didn't own Akamai, Amazon.com,
Navisite. We didn't buy companies whose absolute losses were
growing fast.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Wait a minute. Are you saying that earnings matter?
</P>
<P>
   A. Right. I think investors now are going to focus on companies
that have earnings, companies that will be around in two to three
years, companies that are not just a flash in the pan. Take a
company like drkoop.com. It went public, was a high-flier, it got
jacked way up, and the next thing you know there are questions from
its auditors about whether it is viable as a going concern.
</P>
<P>
   Q. It sounds as if you were not a big investor in e-tailing.
</P>
<P>
   A. E-tailing is a low-margin business with low barriers to
entry. The companies are burning up cash, and there are more
competitors coming in all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do you think what we've been through the past six months
would qualify as a mania?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. We had a lot of uninformed investors. There was a lot of
cocktail chatter. You see your friend on the street and he tells
you he made 50 percent in no time. It used to be that if you made
50 percent in two years it was a great investment. Now if you don't
make it in two weeks there is something wrong with the company.
People got greedy and their expectations got too high.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Would you level most of the blame for the big swings on
individual investors?
</P>
<P>
   A. That would be unfair. Wall Street got greedy, too. Wall
Street said we want more deals, and investment banks were happy to
bring out as many deals as they could. There have been 400 Internet
IPOs since Netscape went public in August '95. There are 155
Internet companies in registration right now. There is a lot of
supply still coming. That is going to put a cap on any big moves
up.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Has anything fundamentally changed about the technology
business?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. The fundamentals are still very strong. Internet growth
is still extraordinary, both here and overseas. The addition of
more bandwidth to homes is going to cause more people to spend more
time online. We still think technology is the best place to be for
the next five to 10 years. People are not going back to the old way
of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What kinds of technology investments do you like?
</P>
<P>
   A. We like the infrastructure companies. Companies that do Web
hosting, application service providers, telecom equipment, cellular
phones. It is a cliche, but if this is a war, we want to buy the
guys who supply the ammunition, because they don't care who wins.
</P>
<P>
   Q. If people are going to stay invested in technology, are they
going to have to learn to live with volatility?
</P>
<P>
   A. Technology is inherently a volatile sector. Why? Because
there are a lot of companies, and there is always a competitive
threat. Someone is always coming up with a technology that is
faster or better. There are going to be companies that do well and
companies that go bust.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the one thing that worries you most in the short run?
</P>
<P>
   A. I think there is still a lot of complacency out there on the
part of the individual investor. I don't think people have been
scared enough. Eventually, there will be a time when it won't pay
to buy on the dips, because we will get a correction where stocks
don't just snap back. People are still complacent about technology
and the new economy. They don't know as much as they think they
know.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
