<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-OMEARA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA FEELS GAME IS WITHIN HIS GRASP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It was a small step, nothing that made headlines,
but when Mark O'Meara finished tied for ninth at The Players
Championship two weeks ago, it was cause for celebration.
</P>
<P>
   A small one, that is.
</P>
<P>
   It was O'Meara's first Top 10 in a year, or since he finished
tied for sixth at the 1999 TPC. ``The last 10 months have been a
little bit of a battle,'' said O'Meara. ``I haven't played as well
as I've liked to.''
</P>
<P>
   Having just turned 43, there was speculation that O'Meara was in
cruise control, that he didn't have the drive or ambition anymore
to keep pace on the very deep and talented PGA Tour, that after his
two-major campaign of 1998 he was too comfortable to care.
</P>
<P>
   There is some truth to all that, he said, but some
misconceptions, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``1998 certainly was a fantastic year. Two majors. I knew 1999
would be tough, and certainly it was, but there were a lot of
opportunities out there at 42, 43 (years old) to take, and I did.
But I traveled a lot in 1997, too, and throughout my career.''
</P>
<P>
   So it wasn't the overseas appearance money, he said, but more a
question of mental attitude. ``My confidence wasn't very good.
There would be strides on the practice tee, but then I'd get on the
course and wouldn't believe it. I'd hit some bad ones, and
self-doubt would creep in.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what plummeting to 45th on the money list (his $868,796
in earnings a big drop from three consecutive million-dollar
campaigns) will do for you. He had just three Top 10s (none after
March) in 19 starts, after having had 29 in the previous four
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Mark O'Meara who got beat, 1 up, by Padraig Harrington in
last September's Ryder Cup was nothing like the Mark O'Meara who in
1998 won both the Masters and British Open. But the Mark O'Meara of
1998, he said, wasn't necessarily the best he's ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had years when I have struck the ball better (than
1998),'' said O'Meara. ``But in 1998 I was just the best at certain
times when I had to be. Like the last five at Royal Birkdale and
the last four or five holes at Augusta, when I hit really great
shots, hit clutch putts.''
</P>
<P>
   None was more clutch than the birdie at the 72d hole to win at
Augusta. It is just such a memory, said O'Meara, that lifts his
spirits as the first major of the season prepares to tee off. He
has found himself thinking back to the days that led to his 1998
triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1998 I didn't play that well in the practice rounds at
Augusta. Sometimes when you're not playing as well you don't put as
much pressure on yourself. But if you putt well and you know the
course, that's the whole secret.''
</P>
<P>
   The reference being, he is a good putter and does know the
course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not exactly where I'd like to be,'' said O'Meara, who
finished tied for 31st in his title defense a year ago. ``You want
to go there hitting that high draw, and that's what I have to keep
working on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have something to prove? Yeah, I have something to prove
to myself _ that I can still play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1032EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
