<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8665 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-SHOP-BOS &LR;      04-06 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-SHOP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIND YOUR E-BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They look like boutiques, with their tasteful decor and
luxurious offerings. But what's behind those Internet storefronts
may surprise you.
</P>
<P>
   At CSAJewelry.com, a Web store so well designed that it looks
like it's operated by a jewelry chain, the owner is packing orders
herself in Longwood, Fla. At an online tobacco shop, an annoyed
woman picked up the phone and muttered, ``No one's here.''
</P>
<P>
   In this booming economy any entrepreneur with a computer can
seem like a legitimate business. While there are some online
bandits, in general, there's nothing sinister about most of the
virtual stores dotting cyberspace, including CSAJewelry.com. The
problem for many small and inexperienced sellers is that they may
not have the staffs or inventory systems needed to deliver goods
during peak periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we tell people is, `Don't judge the product
you're buying based on a nice-looking Web site,' '' said Tara
Finck, a spokeswoman for the National Consumers League. ``Just
because they have all of the bells and whistles doesn't mean they
are an up-and-up company.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the experts can't always tell who's who. Finck, for
instance, assumed that the humidor she bought online came from a
large, established retailer. But the humidor was slow to arrive,
and when she called the retailer about the delay, a company
representative greeted her with an informal ``hello.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `OK, this is a really small operation,' '' Finck
said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't too long ago that Internet retailers were boasting
that they could handily steal sales and shoppers from Old World
merchants. But it turns out that selling on the Web is the simple
part. Filling orders, on the other hand, requires strong
distribution facilities and a small army of employees to answer
e-mails and pack products.
</P>
<P>
   Internet retailers that flocked to the Web before the holiday
shopping season may have built pretty sites, but they couldn't
always handle the crowds. Swamped with orders, several online
beauty shops did not ship merchandise in a timely fashion. Even
large merchants, like Toys R Us Inc., disappointed Web shoppers by
failing to deliver before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   After the winter holidays, about a quarter of Internet stores
surveyed by the research firm Jupiter Communications confessed that
they had problems filling orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more expensive to do it well than people realized,
said Jeff Wiles, a senior vice president with Fingerhut Companies
Inc., a large catalog retailer that also fills orders for Internet
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that many online retailers have not
developed systems that allow them to quickly update inventories,
Wiles said. That means a customer who places an order for Barbie
may be informed two days later that the doll was not in stock.
These are costly mistakes for online retailers, because most
consumers cancel their orders after receiving such notices, Wiles
said.
</P>
<P>
   More worrisome to consumer advocates are the rapidly rising
number of Internet fraud complaints. Customers reported 10,660
incidents of fraud last year, up from just 690 in 1996, according
to the National Consumers League. Online fraud cost shoppers about
$3.2 million, with the average customer losing $580.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the complaints emerging are about the Wild West of the
electronic marketplace: auction sites. The list of gripes includes
bogus bids, mysterious merchants and criminals who never intended
to ship goods.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Merring, a law firm librarian in Newport Beach, Calif.,
said a seller at eBay, the Web's biggest bazaar, cashed her check
and promised to ship her a $20 purse. ``I didn't get it before
Christmas and at the end of January, I said, `Wait a minute,''' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   When she tried to contact the seller, all she got was ``a song
and dance.'' Last month, she was trying to work with the seller to
get her money returned.
</P>
<P>
   Although wary online shoppers can scan reviews of sellers
written by previous customers, some say the ratings aren't
reliable. One problem: disreputable merchants create different user
identities at eBay and then give themselves rave reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, shoppers also have to wonder who's doing the
complaining: Is it a truly burned customer or someone who's angry
about losing in the bidding process? The brawls between buyers and
sellers provide entertaining reading, but they aren't likely to
help users make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to one of your satisfied customers today,'' a user
wrote in the feedback section for an online jewelry seller at eBay.
``He says you sell fake Rolexes!''
</P>
<P>
   ``This person is a total liar (and) holds two screen names,''
the merchant responded in a subsequent message.
</P>
<P>
   Several high-profile hoaxes have embarrassed auction officials.
A New Jersey teenager, using his parents' credit card, bid $900,000
on an antique bed. eBay itself was offered on another auction site.
</P>
<P>
   In response, eBay, which had more than 10 million users last
year, has been trying to clamp down on online marauders. All
comments on the seller feedback rating must now be related to
transactions _ or users risk being suspended or expelled from the
site. In September, the auction site required new sellers to give
eBay their credit card numbers. To protect merchants, eBay plans to
begin asking bidders to hand over their credit card numbers on
offers above $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we have been a pioneer in this area,'' said Kevin
Pursglove, a spokesman for San Jose, Calif.-based eBay.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they're doing what they think is appropriate,''
said Finck of the National Consumers League. ``We wish they would
do a lot more.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0067 </DOCNO>
