<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8666 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-REPORTERS-BOS &LR;      04-06 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-REPORTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYS ON THE BUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If a presidential candidate gave a speech and no one was there
to capture it on a mini digital voice recorder, would anyone hear
it?
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely the candidates of Campaign 2000 will find out.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time _ way back in the 1970s _ reporters routinely
used paper notebooks. They dragged 10-pound manual typewriters on
the road. They fought over the sole pay phone. They made tapping
sounds as they wrote, then handed a piece of paper to a ``Western
Union man,'' who trancribed it and sent it, via Telex, to a central
newsroom. And as recently as five years ago, photographers shot
their pictures on film _ film! _ and sent it by courier back home.
</P>
<P>
   Today, it seems almost quaint.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 years after newspaper reporters first began carrying
portable tape recorders (during, appropriately enough, the 1972
reelection campaign of Richard M. Nixon), the election trail is
awash in electronic devices capable of recording every word of a
candidate's speech, reconfiguring it on a 1.7-pound laptop, and
transmitting it around the world via the Internet. Within minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the world wants that close a view is up for debate. So
is the efficiency of the technology itself. Reporters on the
campaign trail still carry at least 10 pounds of electronic gear _
only now it's phones, computers, and connector cables. They are
still plagued with logistical inconveniences, except they now
appear in the form of dead cell phone zones and dying laptop
batteries. And they still have to get questions answered quickly,
whether it's by calling a candidate's press secretary or by calling
up his Web site via cellular modem while riding on a bus.
</P>
<P>
   And of course they still have to cover the candidates. Who are
still giving the time-honored stump speech _ whether anyone is
listening or not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Judy Keen, political reporter, USA Today:
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1988, when I was covering the Dukakis campaign, we had to
put acoustic couplers over phone handsets to file,'' says Keen,
motioning with both hands to try to demonstrate just what an
acoustic coupler was. ``And look at us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Keen's latest acquisition _ a Sprint PCS Touchpoint cell phone _
is becoming more commonplace on the cellular market. But it verges
on revolutionary in presidential campaign land, where reporters
reconvene only every four years with a set of tools virtually
unrecognizable from the campaign before.
</P>
<P>
   What's so great about the phone? For one thing, it is a direct
link to the Internet, which Keen can use to read headlines off
Yahoo, Amazon.com, and Fox Sports _ on the face of the phone _
while riding a bus. Or read her e-mail as the campaign plane taxis
down the runway. Or file a story for the next day's paper from a
remote field in Iowa, by simply attaching the phone to her IBM
Think Pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be we'd be on a bus in Iowa and have no idea what
the other campaign was doing,'' Keen says. ``Now there's instant
info. There's no excuse for not reporting what the other campaign
is doing. You can't ever relax.''
</P>
<P>
   One method of blocking out work: audio caller ID.
</P>
<P>
   Keen has programmed the phone to ring one way when it's her
editor, another way when it's her husband. Best of all, ``I never
see the bills,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --John Berman, editorial producer, ABC News:
</P>
<P>
   There is one essential piece of techno-fashion in Campaign 2000.
And there is one place to find it: lodged in John Berman's ear.
</P>
<P>
   The toy is a near-invisible headset, which Berman uses to talk
on his cellular phone hands-free for hours each day. It is simply a
wire running from the base of his Nokia 5100 series to his ear _
making him appear, at times, to be talking to himself.
</P>
<P>
   But Berman says it has altered his cellular experience
dramatically, especially on the noisy campaign bus, where the
wire's improved sound quality blocks out nearby conversations and
background sound. At the same time, it keeps him from having to
hold the phone up to his head _ a big deal for a producer who goes
through one or two cell phone batteries a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My ear would start to hurt, and my arm would start to hurt,
with the amount I was holding it up to my head,'' he said. ``It was
more a medical decision than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   His collection of other electronic devices _ including a
Panasonic Shock Wave Metal CD player, a Kodak zoom digital camera,
and a Palm V _ has a slightly different therapeutic effect. Even
Berman admits his Olympus digital audio recorder is ``just plain
cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The slim, palm-sized recorder, which holds up to two hours and
42 minutes of sound, tracks what time each recording was made. On
the campaign trail, that means Berman can keep a perfect record of
each sound-bite. Which in turn means he can explain the gadget to
his bosses as a ``very crucial television device.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Mike Roselli, political producer, CNN:
</P>
<P>
   You'd think the backbreaking luggage would have disappeared from
the campaign trail with the advent of miniature electronic gadgets
_ especially the latest generation of featherweight laptops.
</P>
<P>
   But as Roselli has discovered this year, the ever-shrinking
computer has simply made room for more technical supplies. Even
though his Toshiba Portegelaptop is half the weight of the one he
carried during the Dole campaign in 1996, Roselli's gear bag is
nearly twice as heavy this time around.
</P>
<P>
   The reason? Four Nokia phone batteries. A Motorola text pager. A
lithium battery. A Palm Pilot. Double A Batteries. A Motorola
``talk about'' walkie-talkie transmittor.
</P>
<P>
   By far the biggest drag: Cell phones. Three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Because as technology has improved, expectations have soared.
Now that cell phones are ubiquitous, every reporter demands to be
able to make and receive calls anytime, anywhere. But with cellular
service still wildly unreliable across the country, especially in
the key primary states of New Hampshire and Iowa, a frequent cry on
the campaign bus during rural stops is still: ``You're breaking
up.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Roselli carries three separate phones (Nokia 5100
series, a StarTac Digital, and an Ericsson), with different service
providers (Bell South and Sprint), to increase his chances of
getting a signal.
</P>
<P>
   Or in case any of his five batteries happen to die.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Carl Cameron, senior political correspondent, Fox News:
</P>
<P>
   Of course, computer size does still matter _ to some reporters,
anyway. One of them is Cameron, a former reporter for WMUR in New
Hampshire who got his first laptop when Ronald Reagan was
president.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why he still proudly carries _ sometimes, in the palm
of his hand _ the 1.9-pound Toshiba Libretto 70 he bought two years
ago. Despite its 5-inch monitor, the computer has many features of
a regular laptop, allowing Cameron to write TV scripts on it,
compose e-mail, and send faxes. It also has a 56K cellular modem,
allowing him to log on from anywhere. And in the moments _ rare, of
course _ when he isn't working, Cameron attaches a tiny camera to
the computer and connects with his computer at home for a
teleconference with his young kids.
</P>
<P>
   Not that he would ever use his computer for pure fun. ``Gadgets
are key to hard-hitting, ethical journalism,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anne E. Kornblut, a political reporter in the Globe's Washington
bureau, covered George W. Bush during the 2000 presidential
primary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1035EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8667 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-GAMES-BOS &LR;      04-06 1709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-GAMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING IN THE GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Life wasn't easy for Gary Willoughby those first few days in
Europa. Despite his skills as a Web page designer, the only job he
could find was as a woodcutter. After a week of exhausting labor,
he'd finally chopped enough timber to earn a bit of money. He
trudged back into town with his burden, only to find himself
face-to-face with a homicidal maniac lusting for his blood.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most fun Willoughby had in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time you face a human opponent in a fight is quite
frankly one of the most nerve wracking experiences I have ever
had,'' he recalls in an e-mail message. ``It is so funny and scary,
and downright fun!''
</P>
<P>
   And besides, if he'd been killed, Willoughby would only have to
log off his computer and retire to bed in his London home. His
ghost would patiently haunt Europa, awaiting his return.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody really dies in Europa, a land where reincarnation happens
all the time. But while life is eternal, everything else changes.
Residents come and go, houses are built and enlarged as their
owners grow wealthy, murderers slay and are slain, and both
monsters and heroes stride across the land.
</P>
<P>
   It's a magical place, not quite real of course, but real enough
to hold the attention of 175,000 people around the world. Europa is
one of several worlds that these people regularly visit via the
Internet, as participants in a vast electronic society called
Ultima Online.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ultima is a computer game, but in the same sense that
``Star Trek'' is a TV show. ``Star Trek'' transcended the tube to
become a culture all its own. In similar fashion, Ultima began as a
crude desktop amusement, and has spawned a global fantasy culture.
It's a digital realm inhabited round the clock by characters
dreamed up by the players, characters whose lives go on for months
and years, characters who can change and grow, turn good or evil,
become rich or poor, all depending on the whims of their creators
and the luck of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Ultima characters needn't be knights in shining armor; many
choose to be laborers, tradesmen, or sages. Some become PKs _
player killers _ and seek to bump each other off. Others have no
interest in harming a soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swore off fighting and revenge,'' says Karen Lofstrom, a
52-year-old mother and student in Honolulu. ``I slipped once but
otherwise I've been a good online Buddhist.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that ability to choose the artificial life you desire that
appeals to Michael Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game is what you make of it, says Miller, a 35-year-old
civilian network administrator for the Air Force in Colorado
Springs, Colo. ``If you are looking for adventure and to see new
places you can. If you want to get a job and make a nice life for
yourself you can. If you want to isolate yourself and drop out of
society you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Serious players often meet in the real world to chat about their
characters and adventures. Lasting friendships have sprung up among
players, even a few marriages. And because an Ultima Online player
can own and develop land and property in the game world, some
passionate gamers will pay real money for properties, tools, and
weapons to be used in the game. The online auction site eBay
features hundreds of auctions where Ultima Online players buy and
sell items from each other. Once money changes hands in the real
world, the players log on and complete the bargain in the Ultima
universe.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about the basic concept behind Ultima. Its
creator, renowned game designer Richard Garriott, is an old player
of the tabletop fantasy game Dungeons and Dragons, where he earned
the nickname he uses to this day _ Lord British.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, the teenage Garriott created one of the first graphic
games for the old Apple II computer. Akalabeth: World of Doom was
laughably crude by modern standards _ ``Graphics in those days were
quite primitive,'' says Garriott, now 38 _ but it did a good job of
creating a simple fantasy universe where a hero could smash into
fortresses, seize treasures, and slaughter monsters.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred on by the success of Akalabeth, Garriott launched a
series of games titled Ultima, featuring ever-more-demanding and
sophisticated adventures, as computers got more and more powerful.
The trouble was that these games still lacked one of the chief
attractions of tabletop fantasy games _ the ability for multiple
players to easily join the adventure.
</P>
<P>
   It took the development of the Internet to solve the problem.
Garriott realized that it would now be possible to turn Ultima into
a new kind of computer entertainment _ what's known in the industry
as a ``massively multiplayer game,'' in which players from around
the world would compete over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Such games have been around even before the Internet became
popular. The software company Kesmai Corp. began sponsoring games
on the CompuServe online service in 1982. These were text-based
adventure games; the crude personal computers of the era would not
alllow for pretty graphics. Instead, the players would type in
simple commands, like ``turn left,'' and the game would describe
the result _ for instance, ``You come face to face with a hideous
demon!''
</P>
<P>
   By 1987, the Apple Macintosh computer had brought major
improvements in computer graphics. Kesmai responded with Air
Warrior, a graphic-based World War II air combat game hosted on the
now-defunct Genie online service. Military buffs found the game
irresistible. Thousands signed on to play, even though online
services charged by the hour in those days. Faithful players might
run up hundreds of dollars in online bills every month, but kept
coming back for more.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are many such online games, where a player can log
in on the spur of the moment and fight furious land, sea, or air
battles. Many popular games are designed so that the players can
hook up with rivals over the Internet. Most of these services are
provided at no charge, as an extra incentive to buy the game
software. For instance, owners of Microsoft Corp.'s Combat Flight
Simulator who want to slug it out in the skies over Europe during
World War II can log onto the Microsoft Gaming Zone and play all
day for free.
</P>
<P>
   But this sort of game is over as soon as the players log off.
There's no continuity, no sense of being a permanent character
rooted in a permanent world.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Ultima Online is different. Garriott and the team
at his software firm, Austin, Texas-based Origin Systems, wanted to
add something new to the mix-something that game designers call
``persistence.'' They wanted a gaming universe built around an
established society, in which the absence or presence of any one
member would be of little significance. When a player entered this
new world, he'd be like a visitor to a strange country, surrounded
by other players going on about their lives. When he left, the rest
of the world would go on without him. And when the player returned,
everything in his world might have changed, because of the
activities of all the other players.
</P>
<P>
   By 1998, Origin had finished their first version of such a game,
Ultima Online. ``We thought the total marketplace for this game
would be (5,000) or 10,000 copies,'' said Garriott. At first, he
planned to give away the software disks, and charge only a monthly
subscription fee to play.
</P>
<P>
   But when it was time to test the software, Garriott didn't want
to give away thousands of free test copies. A certain number of
people would try the game, then quit. But that could overload the
crude early server computers of the Ultima network. So Garriott
decided to filter out the unserious gamers by charging for the test
software.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work; 50,000 people asked to buy the unfinished
software. Says Garriott: ``That's when we suddenly realized we had
a real good problem.'' Today, there are 175,000 registered Ultima
Online players, each paying around $20 for the software and $9.95 a
month to live in the Ultima universe.
</P>
<P>
   Garriott last week announced that he was leaving Origin Systems
to pursue other interests. But his fantasy world will survive his
passing, just as it's survived a number of upstart competitors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Microsoft Corp. signed a contract with Turbine
Entertainment Software Corporation of Westwood to have Turbine
create such a game, titled Asheron's Call. It took the company more
than three years to pull it off. Asheron's Call came to market late
last year. Microsoft has not yet revealed the number of players
who've signed up. But on a typical night, it's easy to find 10,000
players signed on at one time.
</P>
<P>
   Ultima settled for an attractive, but relatively simple
two-dimensional game, while Turbine insisted on creating a game
with the kind of three-dimensional graphics players had grown
accustomed to seeing on popular games like Quake. As a result,
Asheron's Call offers a far richer visual experience than Ultima
Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone else is going to be playing catch-up to the
technology we've already developed for the next generation of
games,'' says Toby Ragaini, lead designer of Asheron's Call.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sony Computer Entertainment Inc. has done well enough
with its multiplayer adventure game EverQuest to draw the attention
of ``Star Wars'' creator George Lucas. He's chosen the EverQuest
team to create an online game that will allow people to play out
ongoing stories in the ``Star Wars'' universe. That game is set for
release sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   There's virtually no limit to the kinds of worlds that can be
simulated this way. Eventually, we could see games set in
Washington or the Kremlin during the Cold War, or in Chicago during
the era of Al Capone.
</P>
<P>
   But for players like Gary Willoughby, there's a special appeal
to life in a never-never-land of medieval fantasy. After much toil
and terror, he's found himself a home in Ultima.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have chopped many trees, made many bows, and been killed and
looted a lot, but now I'm much stronger and a better fighter,'' he
writes. ``I find murderers now run away from me. . . . Not to
mention I have met a rather lovely young lady in there too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
