<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-SLAM-BOS &LR;      04-06 1552
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-SLAM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN TIGER HIT THE GRAND SLAM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Reality commands your attention, but you can
barely focus as you gaze down the tree-lined fairways of Augusta
National. Surely, the shadows from majestic pines that soar
hundreds of feet toward the heavens block your view.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it something else? The blazing sun that is at work drying
the morning dew? No, something else interferes with your senses.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hits you _ the shadows that block your vision are not
from the trees that are so overwhelming; they belong, instead, to
the spirit of a man who was larger than life and they stretch from
the first tee, around Amen Corner, over Rae's Creek, all the way to
the 18th green of America's most hallowed golf course.
</P>
<P>
   You cannot escape the presence of Robert Tyre Jones Jr. as you
walk upon the pine needles and rich soil of this onetime fruit
nursery. He has been dead nearly 29 years, but he is here and all
that he represented can be felt. The shadows are his, and on the
eve of the 64th Masters, only one living soul has the chance to
step outside them.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   What defined the life of Jones was what the legendary
sportswriter Grantland Rice called ``the impregnable
quadrilateral.'' Poetic license for what is commonly referred to as
the ``Grand Slam.''
</P>
<P>
   It was September 1930 and Jones, already a national sports hero,
embarked upon 36 holes of golf that would forever solidify his
unquestioned stature as legend. At Merion Golf Club outside of
Philadelphia, Jones defeated Gene Homans, 8 and 7, to win his fifth
US Amateur title and prove that the impossible was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Jones had won the US Open, the British Open, the British
Amateur, and the US Amateur in the same calender year. The world
did not quite stand still, but it stopped long enough for Jones to
take stock of all he had accomplished. There was nothing more he
could do, he concluded, and so that US Amateur _ his 13th major
championship _ was his final encore.
</P>
<P>
   At 28, he left the spotlight to others, but for 70 years, no one
has been quite able to command it as he did. Better golfers have
come and gone, both professional and amateur, but it has always
been accepted as impossible that anyone else could win the
``impregnable quadrilateral'' as Jones did in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods makes us stop and think. Can he, too, prove that the
impossible is possible?
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't place it out of the realm of possibility,'' said
Ben Crenshaw. As a passionate historian, it took a lot to get
Crenshaw to acknowledge even this much. The mere sequence of words
made him shake his head. Never, he said, did he imagine himself
saying such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Woods will not strike his first shot in the season's first major
championship until 10:38 this morning. The mere thought of him
winning all four majors in 2000 before he has won this is beyond
ludicrous. Isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you put yourself in there enough times,'' said Woods, ``you
never know. I won, what, eight times last year? If I won the right
four of those, I'd be doing all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price pondered the question and stared the stare that pro
golfers stare when the situation is critical. There was a moment of
silence, but he didn't laugh you away. ``That's a tall order. Even
for him.'' In 1994, Price won half a slam (British Open, PGA
Championship), so certainly he would tell you you were thinking the
unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I would love to see it done, just like everyone else.
I'd like to see it done in my lifetime. He certainly is the person
who could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The mere speculation seemed to arouse Price's enthusiasm. The
venues, he thought aloud. Just think about where they are playing
this year's four major championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Masters? ``He has won at Augusta.''
</P>
<P>
   The US Open? ``He has won at Pebble Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   The British Open. ``St. Andrews is perfect for him. He's a long
hitter. It's a bomber's and a putter's course, so that's perfect
for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship? ``Valhalla?'' and Price scratched his
head. Not much is known about this relatively new course in
Louisville, Ky., except that Mark Brooks captured the PGA there in
1996. ``He's not that long, so who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``But I tell you, it would be a great thing for golf. And he
could do it. There's no doubt about it. I guarantee you this: In
his life, in his career, he'll come very close to doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jones's grand slam is not Woods's grand slam. Different era.
Entirely different circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was an amateur, thus ineligible for the PGA Championship.
No matter, for in 1920s, the pro golfer took a back seat to the
gentleman amateur. Jones was treated to ticker-tape parades and
Hollywood stardom because of what he accomplished in amateur golf _
his four US Opens and three British Opens a proof that he was
better than his colleagues who played the game for money.
</P>
<P>
   The grand slam that remains the ultimate goal for today's
professional golfer is a relatively young experience. It was born
out of Arnold Palmer's quest to challenge himself to the fullest.
Having won the Masters and his only US Open in 1960, Palmer thought
it would make sense to play the British Open. He had never done so
_ very few American golfers did in those days _ and this was
unsettling to Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   The British Open is golf's oldest championship, dating back to
Willie Park's victory in 1860. To win that, reasoned Palmer,
irregardless of the puny purse, was a mandatory entry on any great
golfer's resume. Money be damned, he said. This was about honor,
tradition, and accepting the ultimate test.
</P>
<P>
   So, in 1960 Palmer ventured to no more appropriate a place than
St. Andrews to set in motion golf folklore. He shot 279 and lost by
one shot to Kel Nagle. His quest for the slam was stopped, but not
before he had framed the route his predecessors would have to
travel.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer remains just one of four players to win the Masters and
the US Open in the same year, though none have ever done the
impossible and won the other half. Ben Hogan came close in 1953,
but this was long before media hype, before the words ``Grand
Slam'' were part of our sports jargon. His only appearance in the
British Open (and a successful one, at that) prohibited Hogan from
playing in the PGA Championship because the events overlapped.
There would be no grand slam for Hogan not out of failure, but out
of effort.
</P>
<P>
   It just wasn't part of the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   But after Palmer threw down the gauntlet in 1960, it was. But
since then, only Jack Nicklaus has won the Masters and US Open. It
was 1972, but Nicklaus, like Palmer, fell short in the British, by
one shot to Lee Trevino at Muirfield. Eerily, the score was the
same as 1960: 278-279.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, there have been others who have won two majors in a
season, but the Masters-US Open quinela hasn't been seen since
Nicklaus 28 years ago. And, as the saying goes, on early evening of
the Masters' final round, only one person has a chance to win that
year's grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That golfer, in 2000, will be Woods. Or so it is assumed. There
are a number of reasons why he is favored, not the least of which
is his course record 270 here three years ago that ignited what has
become known as ``Tigermania.''
</P>
<P>
   Things he has done since then have not diminished its strength.
At 24, he is the world's most dominant sports personality, not just
his sport's best player. He has teed it up in 77 PGA Tour events
and won 18 of them. In his last 17 starts, 10 times he has taken
home the winner's check.
</P>
<P>
   His second major title came at the PGA Championship last August
and helped set off this most incredible roll he's been on, one that
has his left his peers in awe. ``The thing you have to really be
amazed at is that every time he tees it up, everyone expects him to
win,'' said Mark O'Meara. ``But if anyone could win the grand slam,
certainly Tiger Woods has the ability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's phenomenal,'' said Price, one of those who was left to
pick up Woods's divots at the PGA Championship last summer. ``The
guy hits the ball a long way. He hits it straight. He is a wizard
around the greens. I mean, you put all those things together and
throw in the fact he's motivated. He's got big-time fire in his
belly . . . and I think that's great.''
</P>
<P>
   Bookmakers in England aren't so sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Tiger manages to win all four (majors), it will mean the
biggest golf betting payout ever for William Hill of up to $10
million,'' said Graham Sharpe, a spokesman for the bookmaker. ``And
the whole industry could be hit for over $50 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Is winning the grand slam an impossible task? Consider the
numbers out of England, where betting is legal and very much a part
of the sporting culture. Three major bookmakers _ Coral, Ladbrokes,
and William Hill _ have lowered the price to 2-1 to win the
Masters, the shortest price ever.
</P>
<P>
   But more strikingly, they have taken huge bets on Woods winning
all four majors this year. At the start of the year, their odds
were 250-1 (1,000-1 for everyone else), but that has since fallen
to 33-1. 33-1!
</P>
<P>
   It is a ratio that narrow even further if Woods rises to the
occasion this weekend.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
