</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-ROOKIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRASH COURSE FOR BEGINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ His Gallic flair for words did not disappoint.
Jean Van de Velde stood on the knoll above the 18th green at
Augusta National Golf Club, looked out at American golf's holiest
grass, the Frenchman saying, ``For all my life to be here was a
dream; now it's a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   The Scot, Paul Lawrie, was a bit more understated with his
words, the British Open champion saying of his first look at
Augusta National, ``Very hilly . . . the second . . . never saw
that hole much on TV . . . the fairway is steep. You know, I've
watched in years gone by on television, you can't understand how
hilly it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments earlier, the Spaniard and defending Masters champion,
Jose Maria Olazabal had said Augusta National ``is a true piece of
art. You know, when you have a great painting or whatever, you
don't try to change much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Precisely.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers the world over know Augusta National by images flashed
on TV screens for years and years, but this year, rules changes
have allowed more first-timers than usual to come to the Masters.
And the course they see in real life is virtually identical _
except for a few tweaks and subtle changes here and there _ to the
Augusta National they have seen for years on television.
</P>
<P>
   But the course also is so different. So, so different.
Television, as usual, can mislead.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of the course, said Van de Velde, is as advertised.
``It's magical, the landscape is beautiful, the trees are
spectacular and, from that point of view, it is what you have seen
(on TV).'' And Van de Velde is determined to enjoy it all, from
having his 8-year-old daughter be his caddy (with a cut-down bag)
in Wednesday's par-3 tournament to soaking in all of Augusta's
charm.
</P>
<P>
   But, the Frenchman was quick to add, ``What you don't see on TV
is the elevation. How much hilly it is . . . because the TV
flattens out everything it sees. And what you see from the 11th
(tee) on TV, it looks so very, very narrow, but, actually it is
very, very wide. And like the 18th green . . . on TV, it looks very
huge, but actually it's very small.''
</P>
<P>
   The 18th green may not be as small as Van de Velde believes it
is after first glance, but any wayward perceptions are an
indication of what the tournament's first-timers are going through.
Their minds are spinning with the undulations of the greens and how
all shots to the greens must be studied and analyzed and plotted
with an engineer's precision.
</P>
<P>
   Hamlet himself could stand on the tee of the tiny 12th hole and
not be torn as much as Lawrie was after his first look down the 155
yards across Rae's Creek to the green. Lawrie had seen on TV Fred
Couples, Greg Norman, Nick Faldo, Olazabal, and golfers one and all
stand on that tee and look up at the trees behind them, peer over
to the trees to their left behind the adjacent 11th green, gaze
even at that temptress of a flag on No. 12, or even glance over to
the trees beyond the 13th tee, just to the right of the 12th green,
hoping to find a clue as to which direction the wind is blowing.
</P>
<P>
   As he stood on that 12th tee for the first time, Lawrie finally
understood the doubts, confusion, and endless reaching into the bag
for another club he had seen time and again on television. Fellow
Scot Colin Montgomerie was his guide, and Montgomerie gave him
various clues to solving the puzzle of wind direction but finally
said, according to Lawrie, ``He said the wind was into us and also
down at 12 . . . it was just incredible. Obviously, it's going to
be great fun there trying to get the wind right.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Van de Velde put it after two practice rounds, ``This is
as tough as it gets in golf. There is no harder than the 12th. You
need to select a shot, know exactly where you want to go. For me, I
decided there are not going to be too many chances (taken) on the
12th. For me, it's going to be over the middle bunker and (into)
the middle of the green. I will let the pin be where it wants to
be. I will go safe. I will select a club, I will pull the trigger,
and I will accept what comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers, one and all, intuitively realized after one go around
Augusta National that all their years of watching telecasts or tape
replays of the Masters golf meant little. They all needed savvy,
wily and wise guides to uncover the nuances.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Monday, that's why I played with Seve (Balesteros) and Jose
(Olazabal),'' said Van de Velde. ``And (Tuesday) I played with
Bernhard Langer. And I ask them all questions, big-time. I'm not
going to go around here and try to invent anything. I'm just trying
to go out there and learn pretty quickly. It's good to learn from
these guys; I've never played here before and they know . . . I
mean, look how many times they have won here.''
</P>
<P>
   An example or two, Jean, of what you asked Ballesteros, Olazabal
and Langer?
</P>
<P>
   ``From the 12th standing on the tee, I wonder which direction
the wind is blowing and do I look at the 11th flag, the 12th flag,
or what is the trick? So they debate, and one says one (thing) and
one says the other. And so I ask, do you play conservatively or
what? But they gave me good tips, particularly Jose.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Geiberger also is a Masters rookie, but Geiberger is no
stranger to Augusta National, having trailed after his father, Al,
several times when the senior Geiberger was a Masters player ``when
I was 10 or 12 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Geiberger gave his son a few tips before Brent headed to
Augusta, but, tips and all, the younger Geiberger soon found after
arriving here that there was a great deal more to learn.
</P>
<P>
   Geiberger played a practice round with Lee Janzen ``and when
we'd get around the greens, we'd talk about pin placements. Lee
really helped me out there, because that's the hardest part of
being a rookie here,'' said Brent. Putting is first and foremost
the toughest thing out here _ it's just so tough _ and this is a
course you've got to play backwards. First, you've got to think
(during an approach shot) where you want to be putting from. You
never want to be above the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   For Padraig Harrington, Ireland's rookie in the Masters, ``the
last 2 1/2 days have been a cram session. There is so much to
learn. I played a practice round with Bernhard (Langer), and he was
out there on the course taking notes. And he's been coming here 18
years. And I'm trying to learn all I can in 2 1/2 days.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest shock for Harrington, from the Augusta he has seen
on TV and the Augusta he played this week was the 11th hole. For
years and years, Harrington explained, he could not understand what
he was seeing on TV, that the best golfers in the world almost
always aimed their approach shots to the right edge of the green to
avoid the pond, even if the pin was located on the left part of the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golfers always see holes protected by water and they're not
afriad to go for the pin,'' said Harrington. ``But now that I am
here, I understand why they would go to the right and not dare the
pin. It's a very difficult shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian amateur Aaron Baddeley also was surprised by the real
Augusta, even though he has played tapes of past Masters
tournaments over and over, ``the first in memory is when Langer
holed that eagle putt in '93 and Jose (Olazabal) in '94. I just
watched the tape until it's nearly worn out.''
</P>
<P>
   But, his first real-life view of the course surprised him, said
Baddeley. After driving up Magnolia Lane, ``you see the trees
overhanging, and you can see the flowers with the Georgia shape and
you're thinking, `I'm at Augusta.' (But) I thought the first hole
was going away from the clubhouse instead of running with it. You
know, you sort of imagine things because you've never seen it
before and you've heard stories. You sort of get a picture in your
head, but it's sort of different.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, even with Baddeley getting tips from fellow Australian
Norman, and even with Lawrie helped by Montgomerie, even with Van
de Velde helped by Ballesteros, Olazabal, and Langer, all will
learn the most important trait of playing Augusta only through
experience, said Spaniard Miguel Angel Jimenez, playing in his
third Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And that one trait?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is patience . . . only now do I know that patience is all
important here.''
</P>
<P>
   And not until Saturday and Sunday will all of the tournament's
rookies understand the magnitude of Augusta National's great
equalizer, its fast, undulating greens. ``Have you ever played in
Australia?'' asked the Van de Velde, saying he is no stranger to
fast greens. ``Greens there are so hard and fast. Like concrete. So
quick. Frightening. So I imagine they are like that here.''
</P>
<P>
   Patience, as Jimenez said. Time. And time will tell these
rookies that no greens are like Augusta's. None.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
