<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 10:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECHNO-WIRELESS-2ND &LR;  &UR;      04-06 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECHNO-WIRELESS-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... available. here.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you're thinking that these wireless telephones that can get
information from the Internet sound pretty interesting _ but not
necessarily so interesting that you want to shell out an extra $10
a month plus burning up airtime to read stock quotes and news
headlines.
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, a Seattle company called Xypoint.com last
month began offering a cheap way to get wireless data on your phone
that makes an end-run around the Net portals set up by Bell
Atlantic Mobile, Sprint PCS, and others.
</P>
<P>
   For just the $4 a month or so you would generally spend to get
text messaging capability on your digital cell phone, you can use
the Xypoint system to access much of the information you would pay
more to obtain through a wireless Web browser.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Once you have made sure your digital phone
can get text messages (basically setting up and paying for an
e-mail account for the phone), you use your computer to visit
webwirelessnow.com. There, you set up a list of information sources
you want to get on your phone, which requires divulging your name
and e-mail address among other personal data.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the offerings include up to five stock quotes at a
pop, airline flight information, a weather forecast by ZIP code,
lottery results for Powerball and the Big Game, ski conditions, and
a horoscope (for now, you can only get traffic conditions in
Seattle).
</P>
<P>
   Xypoint then corresponds each data source to a phone number,
which currently would be a 206 Seattle number. But you only get
billed for one initial call; the rest of the time it's free. The
trick Xypoint has perfected is that when you speed-dial the number
corresponding to, for example, your stock quotes, you only let the
phone ring once and disconnect.
</P>
<P>
   Without answering and making you pay for the call, Xypoint uses
caller ID technology to register that it is your phone calling this
specific number, which means you are asking for a portfolio update.
It then shoots back to your phone a digital text message containing
the current price of your five stocks, or the ski report for your
favorite mountain.
</P>
<P>
   While you have to wait for the system to respond, Ken Arneson,
president of Xypoint, said, ``I guarantee it will be two times as
fast as any Wireless Application Protocol phone. It's just two
buttons you have to push'' instead of having to toggle through a
browser on the phone screen to get to what you want.
</P>
<P>
   And, Arneson adds, ``Who wants to pay the 25 or 30 cents a
minute while you have the browser on?'' when for a little upfront
effort you can get the information you want free.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Xypoint is a national leader in providing
services to complete 911 calls for several major carriers,
including GTE Wireless, Vodafone AirTouch, and US Cellular. It is
working to get more sites added to the Net content delivery
service, which would generate new revenues.
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like the kind of service cell companies spending
millions on wireless Net access would want to kill in the crib. But
Rick Pearl, a spokesman for Sprint PCS's New England operations,
said of Xypoint: ``We don't fear them, and we don't hate them.''
</P>
<P>
   From Sprint's perspective, Xypoint could drive new business for
digital text messaging, enticing people to spend a little more who
otherwise might balk at spending at least $50 a month for a calling
plan that includes wireless Web access, then pay $10 a month more
plus airtime for Web surfing. (Sprint does frequently have
six-months-free promotions for the wireless Web service).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to hate anybody who uses this
service because, obviously, they're using the phone, and that's a
good thing,'' Pearl said. ``If people just want access to a few
limited things, that's fine,'' and could get them hooked and
willing to pay for the full Sprint wireless Web package.
</P>
<P>
   Arneson said he is optimistic other wireless carriers around the
country will see things the same way. ``They can have a little bit
of a huge market with us,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
