<P>
   GAYS-VIOLENCE (San Francisco) _ While the number of anti-gay
hate crimes and harassment incidents dropped slightly in the United
States and the Bay Area in 1999, the number of violent and deadly
attacks increased, a new study shows. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SNACKS (Undated) _ Snack food is everywhere. Even if you avoid
keeping it in the house because you're apt to indulge too often,
you'll be bombarded with it at the office. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DREAM-WEDDING (Albany, N.Y.) _ Valentine's Day on a little
Caribbean island. The ring sparkled. The steel-drum band played.
The engagement got off to a hip start. The biggest decision was SPF
10 or 15. A year and a half in the distance, the wedding seemed
like a vague, groovy daydream. I imagined a salsa band, a black
cocktail dress. The bride, margarita in hand, working the room.
Feasting on sushi and spring rolls. Everybody dancing. A foolish
sun-baked dream. By JESSICA BARBARO.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS-NOTEBOOK (Augusta, Ga.) _ First, we have
www.tigerwoodsisgod.com. Now, Gary Player has nominated the golfing
superstar for president. Player, addressing a crowd of about 450 on
hand for the annual golf writers' dinner Wednesday night, got up to
introduce Lee Elder and ended up making a rambling political
statement that touched on everything from apartheid in his native
South Africa to golf etiquette to, yes, Tiger for president. By
SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MINORITIES (Augusta, Ga. _ It's been 25 years since Lee
Elder integrated the Masters, palms sweating as he made his way up
Magnolia Lane for the first time to enter a club that he had always
considered to be racist. When he rolled in to commemorate the
anniversary with an honor-filled weekend at Augusta National, it
occurred to him that the more things change, the more they stay the
same. By SUSAN FORNOFF.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-TIGER (Undated) _ Tiger Woods has a deep, dark secret that
could ruin everything. There. Now that we have your undivided
attention, let us turn to more mundane matters. Woods has
accomplished a lot of things. He became a millionaire more than 50
times over before he took his first professional swing. Lapped the
Masters by 12 shots at age 21. Won six tournaments in row from the
end of 1999 to the beginning of 2000. More amazingly, Woods made
golf cool to the masses. Ponder the magnitude of that. By STEVE
CAMPBELL.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-HIPPENSTEEL (Stanford, Calif.) _ When a ruptured spleen
brought on by a severe case of mononucleosis sidelined Stanford
tennis ace K.J. Hippensteel in January, doctors told him he would
have to ``kiss the season goodbye.'' Hippensteel was having none of
that. By CHRISTOPHER ARGYRIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Dom DiMaggio is a famously nice
guy, as outgoing as his late brother Joe was private. But you don't
want to get this former Red Sox center fielder angry. Morris
Engelberg has gotten Dom DiMaggio very angry. On Wednesday, Dom was
boiling that Engelberg, the executor of Joe's estate, is
threatening to sue San Francisco in the name of the DiMaggio family
if the city renames the North Beach Playground in honor of Joe,
instead of renaming something big like the Bay Bridge, the airport
or a gift horse's mouth. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   WONG-COLUMN (Piedmont, Calif.) _ The epic Elian Gonzalez drama
being played out in south Florida has lessons for all Americans in
an era of heightened multiculturalism. By WILLIAM WONG.
</P>
