<HEADER>
A8680 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-PINS-BOS &LR;      04-06 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-PINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENS HAVE PLAYERS ON PINS AND NEEDLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ A brilliant late afternoon sun was no brighter
than the story Gary Player was telling two acquaintances from Japan
Wednesday on the front lawn of the clubhouse of the Augusta
National Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Then, just as Player was saying goodbye to them in Japanese, one
piped up, in English, ``The Ginza . . . the putter?''
</P>
<P>
   Player's eyes lit up and he said, ``Yes, yes, yes. The putter I
bought on the Ginza. I just picked it out of a barrel, in 1965. I
just liked the feel of it. I kept that putter for many years. You
know how much I paid for it? Sixty-five dollars. I won the (career)
Grand Slam with it. In 1965, I remember. I won 100 tournaments with
that putter. And I only paid $65 for it. Yes, I remember the
Ginza.''
</P>
<P>
   The tale was so fitting for these hours before the Masters,
because it is a putter _ no one knows whose _ that probably will
decide the 2000 Masters. Some so-called rough (turf no more fierce
than a good New England fairwway) has been added to Augusta
National, changing the look of the course. But it will be the
greens, not rough, that will decide things this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be the pin placements _ many of them diabolical _
that may determine whose putting will rise to the occasion. Augusta
National is not an unusually difficult golf course, but its greens
_ and those pin placements _ are devilish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single pin placement on this golf course is tough,''
said Player. ``But I think the (par-4) 14th, with the pin on the
back right, is very difficult. And 16 (a par 3), when they put the
pin on the back right. Aw, gee, how do you get to that pin on 16?''
</P>
<P>
   So it went, Player naming the 14th, which has a green that
slopes sharply left and the pin placed atop the slope. Player was
alone in naming the 14th, and he scoffed at the notion that
Sunday's traditional pin placement on 16 _ on the left edge of the
green below a plateau and near a pond _ is tougher.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the easiest (pin placement) on 16,'' he said. ``You
can just roll the ball in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernhard Langer has won two Masters titles and, like Player,
said, ``all the pin placements are tough.'' And, like Player,
Langer said the Sunday pin placement on 16 ``is not that hard,
because you can work the ball in there with the grain.''
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike Player, Langer said ``(the par-3) fourth is always a
difficult one, and (the par-4) third is very tough. There's not
much green to work with either of those.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the third and fourth holes are seldom seen on
television, and while the third (par-4, 350 yards) seems
beguilingly easy, its pin placement on Sundays is diabolical, very
close to the front of a very short green that slopes sharply.
Seemingly perfectly hit balls to the pin often roll back off the
front, while shots struck long leave golfers with nasty downhill
putts.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the fourth, a par-3 with a seemingly easy saucer of a
green, is deceptive. On Sundays, the pin is placed on the very
front of the green, just above a bunker, ``and you just cannot go
for that pin,'' said Langer. ``You are happy to leave that hole
with a 3.''
</P>
<P>
   As Langer put it, ``I've had so many things happen to me over
the (18) years with those pin placements. I've had all things
happen to me, good and bad, on all those holes. But if I were to
say one pin placement is most difficult, I'd say, the third hole.''
</P>
<P>
   To others, the ninth hole seems devilishly diabolical on
Sundays, the pin placed near the front center on a thin plateau of
a sharply sloping green. To land pin-high is an artistic feat of
golf, the margin of error is so thin. A shot that lands above the
hole leaves the player with an extremely delicate snake of a putt.
</P>
<P>
   And Greg Norman could quote chapter and verse of what happens
when a seemingly perfect shot to the ninth lands a fraction short.
Norman's six-shot lead beginning the final round in 1996 was
already beginning to dissipate, but his approach to that ninth
green appeared to be perfect, with the pin placed in the front
center. However, Norman's shot was a tad short and his ball rolled
back yards off the green. Norman's bogey led to a collapse of his
body English and his game. By the 11th hole, Nick Faldo had the
lead and, soon later, the title.
</P>
<P>
   Fuzzy Zoeller needed less than a blink to respond ``the 15th''
when asked about his most challenging pin placement. ``Sure, when
they put it on the left side there . . . it's so hard to hit in to
that little neck (of the green) over there.''
</P>
<P>
   After that, Zoeller went on, ``probably the 12th, when they put
it in the back right there. They put the pin there, you just get
your par and get the hell out of there fast. No more than a 4, then
get out fast.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, it is the 12th hole,'' Seve Ballesteros said. ``On
Sundays, it is to the right on a small green, and it is not safe to
go for that pin. It is just not safe.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12th is the middle hole in Amen Corner, a tempting par-3 of
a mere 155 yards, but the green is placed just above Rae's Creek,
and the right part of the green slopes back down to the creek. Gene
Sarazen's double-eagle on the 15th hole in 1935 still may be the
Masters' most memorable shot, but Fred Couples's tee shot toward
that right pin placement on the 12th hole in 1992 is still regarded
as the most otherworldly shot.
</P>
<P>
   When Couples's shot toward the pin fell short, the ball rolling
back to the creek, it seemed certain to follow the path of several
others that day that rolled smartly down into the water. But
Couples's ball somehow stopped inches short of the water, and from
that moment on, destiny ordained Couples for that '92 title.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not much green to work with there on 12 when the pin
is to the right,'' said Langer, as did golfer after golfer. But
Mark O'Meara, who won the tournament two years ago, said it would
be unfair to pick out any one of innumerable difficut pin
placements.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pin placements are challenging, right from the
get-go,'' said O'Meara. ``From the first hole, when the pin is on
the back left, it is very demanding. There're just no easy pin
placements, to be honest with you. They're all difficult. You can
pick (No.) 3, with the pin up front, or (No.) 4, right behind the
bunker, or (No.) 12 _ there're just so many of them that are
hard.''
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Watson, ``the most challenging pin placement I had was
when I won in '81 and it was on the 17th hole.'' Johnny Miller and
Jack Nicklaus were on Watson's heels on the next-to-last hole, and
the pin on the par-4 hole was on the back right. As Bobby Jones
himself once wrote, ``When the pin is placed to the right, there is
no other option (except to run up the ball) because of a bunker in
the face of the green.'' Watson hit a perfect shot and contends,
``I still say that is the most challenging pin placement I've seen
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Player was asked if it was fair, the Devil himself planting the
pins at Augusta, especially on Sundays?
</P>
<P>
   ``Fair?'' Player replied. ``Golf isn't supposed to be fair.''
</P>
</TEXT>
