<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for  &UR; FRIDAY,
April 7,  &LR; of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `i' news category)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Pakistan's former prime
minister, Nawaz Sharif, who was overthrown by a military coup six
months ago, was sentenced Thursday to life in prison on charges of
terrorism and hijacking. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story, by Christopher S. Wren, will
move by 1 p.m. EST.)
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED-BLOOD (United Nations) _ More than two-thirds of the
world's nations fail to provide safe blood supplies, contributing
significantly to the spread of AIDS and other diseases, the World
Health Organization will announce on Friday. The sea of tainted
blood covers 4.8 billion people, about 80 percent of the world's
population. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEIZMAN (Jerusalem) _ In their report to the attorney
general, Israeli police do not recommend the indictment of
President Ezer Weizman but they hardly exonerate him of shady
dealings. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SPY (Washington) _ Developments in case of a U.S. citizen
who was arrested on charges of spying in Moscow Wednesday.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BOURGUIBA (Undated) _ Habib Bourguiba, who was president of
Tunisia from 1957 to 1987 after leading the country to independence
from France, died Thursday. He was 96 years old and lived in
Monastir in eastern Tunisia. Bourguiba, a spectacularly durable
Arab leader, was relatively moderate and pro-Western and did much
to enhance women's rights in Tunisia. By Eric Pace.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move in `a' news category.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-FOLK-RELIGIONS (Xialing, China) _ Although China's leaders
have spent much of the last year denouncing cults and superstition,
in part to justify their ban on the Falun Gong spiritual movement,
they have mostly turned a blind eye toward the abundance of folk
religions that have re-emerged as a focus of rural life. By
Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   (This story is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) _ World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _  &UR; General &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Developing: The father of Elian
Gonzalez arrived in Washington Thursday and said he and his son
will return to Cuba: talks continue with relatives in Miami. By
Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   (An early version of this story, by Edward Wong, will move by 2
p.m. EST.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-POLITICS (Washington) _ On the debate and discussion
deep in the Clinton administration about how to go forward on the
Elian issue. By John M. Broder. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTISM (Washington) _ A congressional hearing on autism,
scheduled for Thursday, will discuss whether autism is on the
increase and whether there is any evidence that vaccines cause it.
By Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   NY-ACTIVISM-REVIVAL (New York) _ After years of seeing their
activism arouse little passion and even less attention, members of
a divergent cross section of the city's radical organizations _
groups like the Workers World Party, the Spartacist League and the
tiny Workers and Oppressed Unite _ find themselves re-energized in
familiar roles as protesters, if not instigators, at the stream of
demonstrations against police brutality. By Juan Forero.
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG (Columbia, S.C.) _ As marchers protesting the
Confederate battle flag arrive at the state Capitol, it looks as if
a deal to remove the flag may be scuttled for another year. By
David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-RACISM (Undated) _ The bishops of Illinois issue
guidelines on how not to be racist. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   (This story was scheduled yesterday but later eliminated.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES  &LR; _ Washington
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `w' news category)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-HEALTH (Washington) _ House and Senate negotiators work
on legislation to define patients' rights and may agree on an
appeals process for patients denied care by managed care
organizations. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `f' news category)
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-BANKS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Developments in the wake of
the collapse of the Deutsche Bank-Dresdner Bank deal. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `e' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   FEMALE-BODYBUILDERS (New York) _ ``Picturing the Modern Amazon''
at the New Museum of Contemporary Art examines a relatively
invisible, obsessive contemporary sub-culture: female
body-building. It ushers the visitor into a world of
high-definition muscles, low-definition sex-linked characteristics
and gender-bending ambiguity. By Roberta Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CYPRIOT-ART-MET (New York) _ In the new Cypriot galleries at the
Metropolitan Museum, the 600 objects range from colossal sculptures
to poppy-size juglets. And everywhere there are traces of the
various superpowers _ Egypt, Greece, Assyria, Rome _ that
established a presence and contributed to the sweetly unglamorous
carnival of styles known as Cypriot art. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   RAMEAU-BAROQUE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Is there a Baroque beyond Bach?
Yes, though you might be hard put to find it this year, which
commemorates the 250th anniversary of the master's death. Still,
there are outcroppings of Vivaldi here, of Handel there. Now comes
the turn of the fascinating figure of Jean-Philippe Rameau. Some
favorite Rameau recordings of the classical-music critics of The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   EMIGRE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ After World War II the Soviet
government undertook a propaganda campaign to entice Russian
emigres in the West to return home.The beginning of ``East-West,''
Regis Wargnier's sumptuous, moving new film, captures both the hope
of the returning Russians and their brutal betrayal. (In French and
Russian) Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
