<HEADER>
A8716 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GLASS-COLUMN07-COX     04-06 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: CASTRO AND THE CHILD SAVIOUR
 &HT;    Eds: This column, normally for Sunday release, may be used
immediately.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Neither Fidel Castro nor Janet Reno were actors in
the most striking spectacle yet to occur in Elian Gonzalez drama.
</P>
<P>
   That scene was played out when Augustin Roman, Miami's auxiliary
Catholic Bishop and a Cuban exile, led a street mass at a city
intersection to create a giant human cross. The bishop read from
the Holy Scriptures, citing the story of Herod to compare Elian,
then splashing away in a backyard pool, to the Christ child.
</P>
<P>
   God knows politics plays a robust role in this struggle _ one
that by all rights should focus on family values. But a potent brew
of religious mysticism is also at work here, wafting even through
the quiet Washington suburb where the father of the Cuban castaway
went to be reunited with his 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, where Elian's Cuban immigrant relatives have fought a
rear-guard custody battle to keep the boy from ever being hugged by
Castro, those religious factors must be weighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pray for Elian,'' read the signs under a giant mural depicting
the boy as the new Messiah, bearing the prophesy of Castro's
impending doom.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the open hands of God, the protective gaze of the Virgin
Mary and splashing dolphins, Elian rides happily in a rubber tube,
hands outstretched to the Promised Land, represented by the Statue
of Liberty. In the twin scales of justice sit the busts of
President Clinton and Pope John II, who looks away from they boy's
serene visage.
</P>
<P>
   On both sides of the Florida Straits, the pope has been assailed
for keeping his silence. But a satiric essay in the counter-culture
Miami New Times, which argues that the Cuban exile community would
rather see Elian dead than red, reflects the real passions
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives fostered the notion of a child Saviour,
rescued on Thanksgiving Day. (The boy believes dolphins circled him
to keep him safe after his mother, her boyfriend and nine others
drowned.)
</P>
<P>
   These hero-caretakers to the nearly 1 million Miami Cubans
exiled from Castro's domain cite the apparition of the Virgin, who
they say came to their modest home to offer comfort in the form of
a smudge on a mirror in Elian's bedroom window.
</P>
<P>
   Some Cuban-Americans see Elian as possessing supernatural
qualities, a lad saved from the sea by divine intervention. It was
a miracle, they say, that he was found unharmed and suffering no
sunburn, although he had been floating in shark-infested waters
under a blistering sun for 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Others liken the rescue to the tale of the three drowning
fishermen saved by La Ermita de la Caridad, Our Lady of Charity,
and the patron saint of Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Followers of Santeria, an Afro-Cuban mix of Catholicism and
pagan ritual, see Elian as Eleggua, the messenger of the gods, who
escaped the heavens in a rebellion against the old order. The chief
of the gods, Obbatala (i.e. Castro), must now bring him back under
his control to retain his power.
</P>
<P>
   It's no small matter that Castro, an atheist who last year
warmly welcomed a papal visit, remains acutely aware of the power
of a child Saviour on his impoverished island. That's one key
reason why he wants him back.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
