<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8721 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV14-NY     04-06 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRJOY-COLUMN-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 FAMILY IS THE BREEDING GROUND FOR MORALS  
 FOR USE FRIDAY, APRIL 14, OR ANYTIME THEREAFTER
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DRJOY-COLUMN clients. Nonsubscribers can
use this article only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call (888)-269-8796. 
 By DR. JOY BROWNE 
 c.2000 Dr. Joy Browne. 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: Where do people who are not religious in any way
get their morals? Where should people get their morals? Do morals
change with time or are they written in stone? _ D.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I think most of us _ even before we were aware of being
religious or not _ got our sense of right and wrong from our
parents. They are our first source of moral behavior and moral
limits. A parent tells us that a behavior is acceptable or
unacceptable. This may be why some people are lamenting a perceived
lack of morals in our society, which they attribute to families not
spending enough time together to transmit this type of information.
</P>
<P>
   A strong religious belief can be a traditional source for morals
_ although some horrible acts have been committed in the name of
religion. For many people, however, a moral sense starts much
earlier and closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: This is the situation my friends are in: Steve,
41, and Patty, 36, are married. They have a mutual friend named
Scott, who is 22. My wife, Steve, Patty and Scott all work
together. Patty and Scott work beside each other, often go for
lunch together and spend a lot of time together on weekends. Scott
will often go over to Steve and Patty's house.
</P>
<P>
   Steve recently confronted Scott and asked him to lay off. Scott
then told Patty about the conversation. Patty seems to feel that as
long nothing is going on that the relationship is fine, and she
gets upset at Steve. Steve called my wife in confidence to talk
about it.
</P>
<P>
   We both feel that nothing is going on between Patty and Scott,
but I can see that the situation is very stressful for Steve. I
don't think we can do anything, but what should Steve do? _ F.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: I think you're probably right. Nothing is going on
between Patty and Scott, but it sounds as if Steve is feeling like
the odd-man out.
</P>
<P>
   Patty is being flattered by a young man's attention. I would
quietly suggest to Patty that most of her emotional eggs are in
Steve's (not Scott's) basket, so she should spend more time making
her husband feel like he's special. She should ask herself how she
would feel if the roles were reversed and some cutie from work were
spending a lot of time with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   I don't think anything is going on but it's time for Patty to
make her husband feel more important. You're right, the guy should
cool it for a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. JOY: I have been married for six years, and my husband
and I dated for two years prior to marriage. We are best friends.
He is the most dependable person that I know. Problem: lack of
passion in our relationship.
</P>
<P>
   We enjoy sex, but it is always the same way _ no variety or
passion. I am experiencing some unspoken sexual tension with a
co-worker. Nothing untoward has happened, but I am thinking about
it constantly. Any suggestions? I want to be dedicated to my
husband but worry for my future happiness. _ L.
</P>
<P>
   DR. JOY: The ice that you're skating on is so thin that I can
hear it breaking up at this very moment. You stay away from that
co-worker!
</P>
<P>
   If your sex life isn't interesting, do something about making it
more interesting. Go get a book, take a course, but don't you dare
start using up your sexual energy on a co-worker.
</P>
<P>
   You're telling me that this is a great guy, someone you really
trust and love. Don't even think about jeopardizing that
relationship. The same things that make you attracted to this guy
may be part of the problem. You may feel very comfortable with your
husband and not put as much sexual energy into your marriage as you
should.
</P>
<P>
   Go to a store and buy ``The Joy of Sex'' or anything else that
you think might jazz up your sex life at home. Take responsibility.
Stay away from that co-worker and get a lot closer to your husband.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   Questions may be sent to Dr. Joy Browne, c/o The New York Times
Syndication Sales Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168, or
to drjoy &LR; nytsyn.com. Questions of general interest will be answered
in this weekly column. Dr. Joy regrets that unpublished letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
