<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8738 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-06 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WONG-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CULTURAL LESSON FROM THE ELIAN DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By WILLIAM WONG  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ Elian Gonzalez drama being played out in
south Florida has lessons for all Americans in an era of heightened
multiculturalism.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban exiles who want young Elian kept in Miami in defiance of
the U.S. government are showing their true loyalties. Even though
some have lived in the United States for 40 years, they still
consider themselves Cubans, not Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Bragg, a reporter for the New York Times, wrote, ``The
truth is, said many Cuban-Americans, they do not mind if they are
seen as a separate country. Not only do they not want to be part of
middle America, they do not care very much what middle America
thinks of them.''
</P>
<P>
   These exiles are obsessed with hatred of Fidel Castro, the
communist leader whose revolution in the late 1950s precipitated
the exodus of thousands of Cubans to south Florida. Many have
become American citizens and have exercised their right to vote.
Most are Republicans. The GOP is perceived to be more
anti-communist than the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   In their hearts, however, they are Cuban to the core. Older
Cuban exiles especially await the day when Castro is cast aside so
they can return to their homeland, presumably to reinstall their
brand of exploitative capitalism that was wiped out by the Castro
revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban exile community of south Florida isn't a singular
American phenomenon. Other American ethnic groups harbor similar
feelings about their homelands.
</P>
<P>
   Some Vietnamese-Americans, for instance, become apoplectic at
the very sight of communist revolutionary leader Ho Chi Minh on a
poster or in artwork. Mirroring the Cuban exiles, rabidly
anti-communist Vietnamese-Americans are absolutely intolerant of
political views that do not square with their own.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of the diverse Chinese-American community are more driven
by homeland politics and issues than by concerns rooted in America.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans may view these exile enclaves as examples of
multiculturalism run amok in a society that once looked on itself
as one big happy family, reflecting western European political,
economic, cultural and religious values. This despite the fact that
it had a significant African-American minority and a smaller
amalgam of other minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last third of the 20th century, a revolution of sorts
has been taking place in America. Oppressed minority groups have
begun to assert themselves, demanding equal opportunities and equal
access to power. They have used both legal and extra-legal means to
achieve their social-justice goals.
</P>
<P>
   This quasi-American revolution has shaken up Americans who were
content with the 1950s-style status quo. These Americans have
lamented the ``loss'' of a common culture and voiced their
displeasure in many different ways at the increasing colorization
of America, with ethnic groups everywhere demanding this or that.
</P>
<P>
   Even some minority-group Americans, benefiting from civil rights
gains, have joined in the backlash against the idea of a kinder,
gentler multicultural America.
</P>
<P>
   The Elian case certainly can reinforce the paranoia felt by some
Americans about an impending divisive Balkanization of what was
once thought to be a pristine commonweal stitched together by
democratic principles, free-enterprise economics and
Judeo-Christian values.
</P>
<P>
   That danger exists. But there are distinctions to be made. By
definition, exiles harbor emotional feelings about their root
countries that for many tend to supersede all other considerations.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the burgeoning multiculturalism America is
experiencing comes from either homegrown sources
(African-Americans, American Indians) or from immigrants who have
chosen to become part of the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently some Cuban exiles have not. Other immigrants are
better representatives of those newcomers who want to add their
values to making this society, not their homelands, stronger and
better.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (William Wong is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic mail address
is wongink(at)earthlink.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
