<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NOTEBOOK-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A FUTURE PRESIDENT WHO CAN REALLY PLAY GOLF? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Masters Notebook   (For use by New York Times News Service
clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ First, we have www.tigerwoodsisgod.com. Now, Gary
Player has nominated the golfing superstar for president.
</P>
<P>
   Player, addressing a crowd of about 450 on hand for the annual
golf writers' dinner Wednesday night, got up to introduce Lee Elder
and ended up making a rambling political statement that touched on
everything from apartheid in his native South Africa to golf
etiquette to, yes, Tiger for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had Ronald Reagan, an actor, and I think this man could be
president someday if he wants to be,'' Player said, figuring Woods
has the popularity, money and Stanford education. ``And it's a lot
easier than playing golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, who had already been to the podium to accept his player
of the year award, neither accepted nor declined the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   He did join in the standing ovations for Elder.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Garcia was a budding amateur only a year ago, and already
he's a struggling pro. He missed the cut at the Players
Championship and Phoenix Open and wasn't in contention in his three
other PGA Tour events this year; he hasn't won in Europe either.
</P>
<P>
   What's a young man to do? Change caddies, of course. Fanny
Sunesson, who left Nick Faldo because he wasn't supporting her well
enough in recent years, is gone and South African Glenn Murray,
formerly Retief Goosen's porter, is in her place.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 20, was diplomatic about the change on Wednesday, saying
that he and Sunesson were having problems matching clubs to
yardages. Just after the Ryder Cup, he fired caddie Jerry
Higginbotham, who in turn had replaced Garcia's Spanish caddie a
few months earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia says he hopes Murray is the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great caddie, but he's also very funny and he makes me
laugh a lot,'' Garcia said. ``I don't usually pick caddies for one
week.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Notah Begay III is here hoping to make a cut for the first time
since his week in jail on drunken driving charges. He is looking
much more svelte than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't weigh myself, so I'm not sure how much I lost, but I
go by how my fat pants fit,'' he said. ``It's when I have to lay on
the bed to put my pants on that I know I'm in trouble. These are my
normal pants, and they have a lot more room than they used to.''
</P>
<P>
   Begay played a practice round with green jacket holders Woods
and Mark O'Meara and thought he might be able to make a splashy
debut.
</P>
<P>
   Not splashy as in Rae's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to play well,'' he said. ``I like the
course, I'm hitting the ball pretty well, so we'll just see what
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Chris Perry defeated Jay Haas, Jerry Pate and Hunter Haas on the
first playoff hole to win the 41st Par 3 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Perry rolled in a birdie putt for the victory after the four
golfers finished at 4-under 23 in the nine-hole event, played on
the eve of the Masters' opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Begay had the only hole-in-one of the day, sinking his shot at
No. 9. There have been 41 holes-in-one since the Par 3 tournament
began in 1960 on a picturesque course adjacent to the 18-hole
layout.
</P>
</TEXT>
