A8748 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-N     04-06 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS TO BE LEARNED FROM COUNTRY MUSIC  
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you like to listen to loud music in your car, you may want to
avoid the town of Alexandria, La.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you like country music. I mean, really like it.
</P>
<P>
   According to an Associated Press story, Henry Nelson, 20, and
Jon Driggers, 26, pleaded guilty to violating Rapides Parish's
ordinance prohibiting ``loud and offensive noise'' after cranking
up the volume too high on their car stereo.
</P>
<P>
   They were fined, given a suspended jail sentence and probation,
and ordered to attend a ``music appreciation'' session where they
would spend three hours listening to their least-favorite kind of
music _ country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if they had to listen to stuff they hate, it would
teach them to respect other people's rights,'' state District Judge
Tom Yeager said.
</P>
<P>
   Having a 14-year-old in the house, I know something about loud
and offensive noises. I think the dulcet strains of Dysfunction and
Anthrax wafting from his bedroom window could explain why I can't
get any grass to grow in that part of the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I am not sure that making him listen to three hours of
country songs like ``I Don't Know Whether to Kill Myself or Go
Bowling'' or ``You Broke My Denture Slap in Two'' would do anything
to improve his taste in music, let alone the condition of my lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the judge's thinking is that the two young men will
emerge from their music appreciation session so broken and
despondent that they will never want to listen to any music ever
again, let alone groups like Korn and Anti-Flag, which, if played
at a high enough volume, may cause cancer in laboratory rats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, this is supposed to be a civilized country, which makes
me wonder if it might not be cruel and unusual punishment to force
these young men to listen to ``Does The Spearmint Lose its Flavor
on the Bed Post Overnight?,'' ``A Woman Is Just a Woman but a Cigar
Is a Good Smoke'' and ``How Can I Miss You if You Won't Go Away?''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the judge is of the opinion that there are lessons in
morality in country songs, raising the possibility that the young
men will listen to ``I'm My Own Grandpa,'' ``She Feels Like a New
Man Tonight'' and the classic, ``My Uncle Used to Love Me but She
Died.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also possible that the judge is not so much concerned with
the volume of modern music as its satanic undertones. In that case,
he may choose country songs with a more spiritual side to them like
``Would Jesus Wear a Rolex on His Television Show?,'' ``Thank God
and Greyhound She's Gone'' and ``I've Been Roped and Throwed by
Jesus in The Holy Ghost Corral.''
</P>
<P>
   Family values are big these days, and country songs contain
plenty of them, such as ``You're The Reason Our Kids Are So Ugly''
or ``Baby's Got a Mustache.''
</P>
<P>
   Young people always need to be reminded of the dangers of
substance abuse, which is why the judge may have chosen such
country hits as ``You Won't Be Back But George and Jack Will Help
Me Make It Through The Night,'' ``She's Actin' Single, I'm Drinkin'
Doubles'' and the unforgettable ``The Pint of No Return.''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt that young men will be very angry after enduring their
three-hour ``music appreciation'' session.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, Judge Yeager may want to play one last song
for them as they head out of town:
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's A Quarter, Call Someone Who Cares.''
</P>
<P>
   (David Grimes is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. The Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 13:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8750 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-TIGER-HNS &LR;      04-06 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIGER'S LASTING GIFT TO GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEVE CAMPBELL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger Woods has a deep, dark secret that could ruin everything.
</P>
<P>
   There.
</P>
<P>
   Now that we have your undivided attention, let us turn to more
mundane matters.
</P>
<P>
   Woods has accomplished a lot of things. He became a millionaire
more than 50 times over before he took his first professional
swing. Lapped the Masters by 12 shots at age 21. Won six
tournaments in row from the end of 1999 to the beginning of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   More amazingly, Woods made golf cool to the masses. Ponder the
magnitude of that.
</P>
<P>
   Before Woods came along, the general sporting public considered
golfers about as manly as Richard Simmons, quiche and knowing all
the numbers in ``Cats'' by heart. Though the PGA Tour had the good
sense to outlaw too-short shorts, some of the polyester pastel
ensembles that made the rounds weren't much of an improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in golf is so high these days, PGA Tour events
regularly clobber the NBA in the television ratings. People of all
ages, races, sexes and faiths are discovering the wonders of a good
walk spoiled. Don't believe what you may have heard about stuffy
country clubs. Golf is the most inclusive of sports. Sooner than
later, it brings everybody who plays to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about this boom in interest is all the new fans.
They bring energy and enthusiasm to a sport steeped in tradition
and decorum.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing about this boom in interest is all the new fans.
They bring energy and enthusiasm and a glaring lack of knowledge
and appreciation of the sport's tradition and decorum.
</P>
<P>
   The only gentlemanly thing to do is embrace these newcomers.
Well, not actually embrace them, because that would make everybody
either uncomfortable or too comfortable, but give them a nice firm
handshake. Make them feel welcome. Patiently teach them about some
of the finer points of golf.
</P>
<P>
   One of the secrets to a happy golfing existence is finding the
right place to play. There are so many courses out there, public
and private alike. Well, what's a new golfing consumer to do? How's
he supposed to know if he's in a suitable environment to fully
enjoy the golfing experience? Here are some tell-tale signs that
the course you're frequenting does not promote the splendor of
golf:
</P>
<P>
   _ There are metal detectors on every hole.
</P>
<P>
   _ The driving range is located between the barn and the
outhouse.
</P>
<P>
   _ The signature hole is the 19th hole.
</P>
<P>
   _ The beverage-cart girl has a five o'clock shadow and a bulging
Adam's apple.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your backswing constantly gets interrupted by mooing.
</P>
<P>
   _ The foursome on the first tee is wearing blue jeans.
</P>
<P>
   _ The foursome on deck on the first tee is wearing tank tops and
tattoos.
</P>
<P>
   _ The foursome on the 18th green is wearing no pants.
</P>
<P>
   _ The sand traps come equipped with anti-venom kits instead of
rakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The layout has so many doglegs, the snack bar serves
Vietnamese cuisine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Greens fees are double on days when the greens are actually
green.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tournaments with shotgun starts inevitably result in standoffs
that require police intervention.
</P>
<P>
   _ The water hazards double as restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we're getting ahead of ourselves a little bit. Before
a novice gets caught up in shopping for the right course to play,
it's crucial to get the proper instruction. The golf swing is about
as natural as hopping on one foot while yodeling the words to
``Stairway to Heaven.'' Jack Nicklaus likes to start every year
with a lesson to tune up his swing. If Nicklaus needs lessons, then
you need lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But where do you go? Whom do you trust? The wrong instructor can
do more damage than a 1-iron on a water hole. Take heed of these
signs that your swing doctor is a quack:
</P>
<P>
   _ The instructor's nickname is Mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you ask about his/her greatest success story as an
instructor, he/she brags about all the work with Jack Lemmon.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you ask for a suggestion of a helpful instructional
video, he/she tells you to rent ``Caddyshack.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When you ask for a suggestion of a helpful instructional book,
he/she tells you to buy ``The Joy of Sex.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The first time you take a practice swing in his/her presence,
he/she begins laughing uncontrollably.
</P>
<P>
   _ When you ask for a helpful swing thought, he/she suggests the
Tarzan yell.
</P>
<P>
   Once you've found an instructor and a place to play, you need to
know how to act. This goes for spectators as well as players. The
golf establishment frowns on rainbow wigs and shouts of ``It's in
the hole!'' the instant the ball leaves the clubface on the tee
shot of a par-5. Golf is a civilized sport _ so aboveboard, players
are expected to call infractions on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Think about that. Imagine Kurt Warner insisting the officials
take away a touchdown because he knows for a fact that one of his
linemen was holding. Imagine Patrick Ewing instructing the refs
blow the whistle on his game-winning shot because he got open with
a travel move. On the PGA Tour, players regularly penalize or
disqualify themselves for the most seemingly harmless
transgressions.
</P>
<P>
   So please, be considerate of the players around you.
</P>
<P>
   Never, ever cough in the middle of someone's backswing _ unless
you're in America, and it's the Ryder Cup, and one of the Europeans
is hitting an approach shot.
</P>
<P>
   Never, ever make flatulent noises while somebody is standing
over a putt _ unless you have money at stake, and you're trailing
in the match.
</P>
<P>
   Never, ever walk in somebody's putting line _ unless that
somebody made flatulent noises when you stood over your last putt.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Tiger, a lot more people have begun to appreciate the
wonders of golf. As a show of appreciation, any deep, dark secrets
will remain secrets. Still, there are times _ sometimes 100 or more
in one round _ golf truly feels like a good walk spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   Take heart. Take heed: A bad day at most golf courses is still
better than a good day at the office. Just beware of courses with
metal detectors. Steer clear of places where shotgun starts have
been known to lead to shotgun finishes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
