r a BC-DALLAS-WATER-TEX     04-06 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DALLAS-WATER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALLAS FACES DEEPENING WATER CRISIS BECAUSE OF CONTAMINATION OF
LAKE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARY DOCLAR 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ City officials, facing the worst water crisis in 50
years, are preparing to impose tougher use restrictions, build two
pipelines and possibly take legal action in response to a gasoline
spill that contaminated a major source of water.
</P>
<P>
   Those actions come despite assurances from Explorer Pipeline Co.
of Tulsa, Okla., the company that owns the ruptured pipeline, and
the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission that the water
from Lake Tawakoni can be used safely.
</P>
<P>
   Gas from a 500,000-gallon spill near Greenville on March 9 was
carried downstream to Lake Tawakoni, prompting city officials to
stop using the lake, which provides nearly a third of Dallas'
water. Dallas, in turn, sells water to 21 customers, including
Grand Prairie and Irving.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to stop using the lake came after laboratory tests
found that the water contained the gasoline additive known as MTBE,
or methyl tertiary-butyl ether, which is used to reduce air
pollution but is also believed to be a carcinogen that can cause
kidney and liver damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very serious situation,'' Water Utilities Director
Terrace Stewart told the City Council during a briefing on
Wednesday. ``Our effort and hope is to continue to provide
high-quality drinking water to the citizens of Dallas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Explorer officials said the city is overreacting. Scott Van
Dyke, the company's president and chief executive officer, said the
MTBE levels in the lake meet safety standards set by the Texas
Natural Resource Conservation Commission, or TNRCC.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MTBE levels are well below the standard set by the TNRCC,
so we're confused by Dallas water utilities' recommendation because
other communities over there are using that water,'' Van Dyke said.
``We don't understand why Dallas seems to be setting a different
standard than the TNRCC.''
</P>
<P>
   TNRCC toxicologist Michael Honeycutt said that the most recent
sample from Lake Tawakoni shows MTBE levels of 2 parts per billion.
The TNRCC said that any level below 240 parts per billion is safe
but that the agency advocates a level of 15 parts per billion
because higher concentrations cause taste and odor problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water's fine,'' Honeycutt said. ``I can't tell you what's
going to happen if it rains next week. I don't think anybody can.
It's just a real sticky situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart said that any MTBE level above .67 parts per
billion, the level at which the additive is detectable, is
unacceptable. He said that he could taste the turpentine-like
additive at 5 parts per billion. He also said that he is concerned
that high levels of MTBE in adjacent soil could leak into the lake
when it rains.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the same quality water we had before,'' Stewart said.
``Until we get there, I'm sorry, but I'm not using the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Because it's not known when the water can be used again, Stewart
recommended that the council approve tougher water restrictions.
For residential users, that means limiting landscape watering to
once every five days, prohibiting runoff from landscapes and
banning hosing of paved areas. The restrictions, which will be
voted on at Wednesday's council meeting, go into effect May 1 and
carry a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Those restrictions will extend to cities that buy water from
Dallas, including Grand Prairie, which gets 90 percent of its water
from Dallas and a third from Lake Tawakoni. At Tuesday's City
Council meeting in Grand Prairie, members were briefed on the
restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart also proposed that the city begin design and
construction of a $12 million pipeline that would bring additional
water from Lake Ray Hubbard to supplement the city's supply. A
second recommendation is to expedite construction of a previously
planned $180 million pipeline that would provide water from the
Lake Fork reservoir, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lake Ray Hubbard line could be built by July 1, Stewart
said. However, he said that lake could be depleted in 18 to 24
months if Lake Tawakoni remains out of use and drought conditions
continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really in a pretty critical position here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Several council members expressed frustration with the
situation, demanding that Explorer Pipeline pay for all of the
city's costs related to the spill. In addition to the upcoming
pipeline costs, the city has spent $410,000 on environmental and
contamination consultants, Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Laura Miller, who criticized Explorer's response as
``inadequate,'' said she is ready to file a lawsuit if the company
balks at paying for costs related to the gas spill.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which is owned by a consortium of oil companies
including Conoco, Chevron, Citco and Texaco, should have plenty of
funds to pay what is expected to be an expensive bill, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I for one am publicly wanting to sue them quickly if they
don't pay for this,'' Miller said. ``Why should we have the
taxpayers paying for industry's egregious mistake?''
</P>
<P>
   City Manager Ted Benavides said the city has told the company
that it expects to be compensated for all costs related to the
spill.
</P>
<P>
   But Van Dyke said his company has no intention of paying for
pipelines that it believes are unnecessary, even if the city files
a lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's their prerogative,'' he said, adding that some cities
affected by the spill have commended his company's effort to
rectify the problem. ``We're getting high praise for what we're
trying to do over there. I can't stop a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
