<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-CRAIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US LEGAL VETERAN BECOMES A KEY TO CUBAN BOY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He is cast alternately as an unfit father and as
the other helpless victim, as he is shown, eyes swelling with
tears, on Cuban television considering the long separation from his
six-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   But if Juan Miguel Gonzalez wins the battle over Elian, it may
have less to do with his image or emotions than with his powerful
Washington lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory B. Craig, known here as the ``quarterback'' for
President Clinton's impeachment legal team and a longtime adviser
to Senator Edward M. Kennedy, has taken on the father's case. And
the effects of his $400- to $500-an-hour talent are being felt.
</P>
<P>
   Craig's associates say his involvement has nothing to do with
his close ties to the Clinton White House, which has advocated
reuniting Elian with his father. Craig has said he is involved
because he has a six-year-old son of his own. But his entry onto
the scene underscores how tightly intertwined politics, law and
personal diplomacy have become _ even by Washington standards _ in
this highly unusual case.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, 55, for example, was once director of policy planning at
the State Department, the agency that issued a visa to Gonzalez. He
spent time as a foreign policy adviser on Capitol Hill, where
legislators are considering a bill to let Gonzalez stay.
</P>
<P>
   He seeems to have the skills of a Washington insider. He
attended Yale Law School with Bill and Hillary Clinton, and
cultivated strong ties with Kennedy. (All advocate returning Elian
to Cuba).
</P>
<P>
   And he is no stranger to controversy; long before representing
Clinton in the US Senate trial, Craig helped to defend John
Hinckley, the attempted Reagan assassin, and guided Kennedy through
his nephew's Palm Beach rape trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to have someone who had access to the courts and was
well-connected,'' said Rev. Dr. Joan Brown Campbell, formerly of
the National Council of Churches, who travelled to Cuba to
introduce Craig to Gonzalez last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``The father's wishes were taken much more seriously when he
came on board,'' Campbell said of Craig. ``He can speak to lawyers
at INS and at Justice. These are not conversations we were able to
have before. He's had direct access which no one ever had before.''
</P>
<P>
   In part, the change has been in simply gaining respect for
Gonzalez _ and access to the Miami relatives of Elian, who had kept
the boy's Cuban family at arm's length, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, at a news conference outside his office last week,
blasted Elian's Miami guardians for giving the media wide-ranging
access to the boy. He said they had decided to ``parade Elian in
front of demonstrators,'' and added that one point was not
negotiable: ``Elian's best interests lie with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, Craig is, in fact, a negotiator. At once
charming and self-deprecating, he is noted for trying to keep his
opponent talking: In this case, Kendall Coffey, the lawyer for the
sometimes-hostile Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   And while participants declined to specify details, they said
Craig, in general, has brought the Cuban father's perspective more
fully into the national spotlight since coming on board.
</P>
<P>
   As a Harvard senior in 1967, while other students protested in
the streets, Craig chaired a meeting between more moderate college
Vietnam war protesters and US Secretary of State Dean Rusk. It was
an off-the-record gathering, but afterward, Craig went public with
his disappointment, writing an editorial in the Harvard Alumni
Bulletin that described the students' reactions to Rusk's opinions
thus: ``quite literally stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 30 years later, when he was brought in to head
Clinton's impeachment team, Craig found himself once again a voice
of moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with two sets of Clinton advisers, the lawyers who wanted
to keep revelations under wraps, and the political strategists who
saw the value of releasing damaging information fully and fast,
Craig pressed for a certain degree of information to be released in
the interest of public relations.
</P>
<P>
   But ``he really understood that there were different interests
that had to be reconciled,'' said the former White House press
secretary, Michael D. McCurry. Craig wasn't just concerned with
legal issues, he said. ``I always felt he was someone I could talk
to who wouldn't take a real hard line and say, `We can't do X, Y
and Z in the public arena,' '' McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Barney Frank, the Massachusetts Democrat, who has
been friends with Craig since his Harvard days, agreed: ``He pulled
the administration's position into a clear, strategic approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Craig, reporters ``didn't write any stories about how
they were going off in different ways, or about differences among
his advisers, which was really unusual,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the realm of foreign policy, Craig's dealings have not always
won such unmitigated praise. As a foreign policy adviser to Kennedy
in the 1980s, he pressed for sanctions against apartheid-controlled
South Africa _ and did, Kennedy now says, a ``brilliant job.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in private practice, however, Craig represented a Haitian
family with close ties to coup leaders in Haiti. In fighting to
lift sanctions on their behalf, Craig prompted criticism from some
former allies who believed he was tarnishing his idealistic image.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department aide said in his defense: ``Lawyers defend a
lot of people and have a lot of clients.'' But the official added
that in the case of Elian, ``it is natural for him to be on this
side _ more so than representing members of the Haitian elite
class.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, of course, being paid to help Gonzalez. Although Craig
has reduced his fees, the group that is paying them, the General
Board of Church and Society of the United Methodist Church, says it
is raising up to $100,000 for Craig's services. Neither the Cuban
government nor Gonzalez himself is helping foot the bill, said the
group's general secretary, Thom Whitewolf Fassett.
</P>
<P>
   Craig has a fellow Democrat to thank for having landed the case:
Senator Patrick J. Leahy of Vermont, who called Campbell to suggest
she hire Craig to help Gonzalez. Craig has deep family roots in
Vermont, where his father attended college and ran for governor as
a Republican in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   But Campbell believes that what drew Craig to the case was much
more personal. A father of five, Craig talked more than anything
about his own children during his visit with Gonzalez in Havana
last month, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't come to this intellectually. He comes to this as
the father of a six-year-old, and he said quite clearly, `I don't
know how I would function if someone took him away from me,' '' she
said. ``He knows a lot of people. He's very well-connected in a lot
of agencies. But he makes no bones about the fact that he thinks
the father is a good father. That's what his representation is
about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
