<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STUART-BENNETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BENNETT, STUART CASE STILL HURTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A decade after he was cleared as a suspect in one of
Boston's most notorious crimes, William Bennett is still very
angry.
</P>
<P>
   In autumn of 1989, the ex-convict was named a suspect in the
killing of Carol DiMaiti Stuart, a pregnant, suburban white woman
shot, allegedly by a black man, in what looked like a random street
robbery. Bennett's arrest seemed to solve a high-profile murder
case, quieting an outraged city whose leaders promised swift
justice.
</P>
<P>
   But when suspicion shifted to the husband, Charles Stuart,
Bennett went from cold-blooded murder suspect to a symbol of police
abuse and Boston's lingering racial divide.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, in a rare interview, Bennett told The Boston Globe
the case still haunts him. He blames it for his mother's premature
death and frayed family ties. And he refuses to hide his
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't trust anybody. I barely trust myself,'' said Bennett,
now 50. ``The police falsely pinned a crime on me once and they can
do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no faith in the law enforcement and I don't like
cops,'' said Bennett, who does kitchen work for a food service
company. ``Nothing has changed. You still have those same racist
cops on the police force.''
</P>
<P>
   On the night of Oct. 23, Carol Stuart was driving with her
husband from a childbirth class at Brigham and Women's Hospital
when she was shot at close range. She was killed and the couple's
unborn child was fatally injured.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Stuart, who was shot once in the stomach, told police
that a black gunman with a raspy voice forced his way into their
car at a stoplight, ordered them to drive to Mission Hill, robbed
them, then opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   Crack cocaine and gang violence had become epidemics in the
city's Roxbury and Dorchester neighborhoods, but the murder of a
pregnant white woman, allegedly by a black man, was shocking,
front-page news. To police and outsiders, the murder exemplified
the evils of a growing drug problem in a poor, lawless
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Charles Stuart's description, police made a crude
composite of the gunman. Over the objections of community leaders,
patrolmen and detectives stopped black men at random in
predominantly black neighborhoods, in an intense search for the
killer.
</P>
<P>
   And Bennett, who had a long rap sheet dating to the early 1970s,
quickly became a prime suspect.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-year-old drifter whose family lived in Mission Hill, he was
suddenly dragged before the national spotlight, a reluctant
character in an infamous crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when he was pulled out of my home'' in suburban
Burlington, recalled Brenda Nelson, his longtime companion. Bennett
had spent the night with her; she was pregnant at the time with
their daughter, Ebony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the bed and he was in the shower. My own mother was
in the bed,'' Nelson said. ``The police were surrounding the home.
It was all so crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrested on a separate armed-robbery warrant, Bennett was never
directly charged with Carol Stuart's murder. Still, the case was
considered solved _ until detectives began to suspect Charles
Stuart was the real killer. As the investigation closed in, Stuart,
in an apparent suicide, jumped to his death from the Tobin Bridge
in January 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett, however, was convicted and served nearly 10 years in
prison for the 1989 armed robbery of a Brookline video store. To
this day, he maintains he is innocent and believes that conviction
was payback for the Stuart case.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all lies,'' said Bennett. ``I felt they always wanted
to get me for something.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Bennett and Nelson live quietly in a rented house in
Worcester with their family: daughters Ebony, now 10, Aisha, 11,
Whitney, 10, and son Nathaniel, 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to be left alone,'' said Nelson. ``Sometimes
people recognize him and ask if he is Willie Bennett and we say
`no' and walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   But the 10-year anniversary of Carol Stuart's murder _ and her
husband's plunge into the Mystic River _ prompted a number of
forums examining the case and its impact on race relations in the
city. Bennett had stayed in the background until recently.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, he surfaced in the audience of a televised panel
discussion sponsored by WGBH. Bennett rose from the crowd and told
the gathering that the case directly led to the death of his
mother, Pauline Bennett, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Moderator Charles Ogletree of Harvard University was stunned. So
was Boston Police Commissioner Paul Evans, who was a panelist. The
audience gasped and then broke out in applause.
</P>
<P>
   Though the racially charged case divided the city, there have
been efforts to make amends to the African-American community:
Carol Stuart's foundation has sponsored 160 college scholarships
for Mission Hill children, and Bennett's family received a $12,000
settlement in a civil lawsuit against the city.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, former police commissioner Francis ``Mickey'' Roache
told The Boston Globe he believed at the time that Bennett should
never have been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But none of these developments are enough for Bennett. He said
he can't be repaid for the time he missed with his family: his
children's first steps, his mother's last breaths, and the funerals
of his father and two siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``So what _ they are giving scholarships. They haven't done
anything for me,'' he said. ``I really don't give a damn about this
Stuart case anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother is not here today because of this mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Nelson brought the children to the prison to
make sure they knew their father, and it paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids love their father; you can't tell them nothing wrong
about their father,'' she said. ``And they know enough about the
(Stuart) case'' to realize he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Since his release from prison last year, Bennett said, he has
become a recluse and struggles to reclaim his life, but his past
keeps getting in the way. Most employers, he said, are reluctant to
hire him because of his criminal background.
</P>
<P>
   He refuses to watch or read anything about the Stuart case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am just trying to keep a low profile,'' said Bennett. ``Some
people don't know who I am and I don't want them to ever know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
