<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8763 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WEB-MIXUP-BOS &LR;      04-06 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-MIXUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO WEB SITES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all began with a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   McSweeneys.net is an offbeat New York literary journal edited by
acclaimed author David Eggers, while McSweeneys.com is a family Web
site created by the McSweeney clan of Stoneham, Mass. The magazine,
officially called McSweeney's Internet Tendency, publishes such
articles as ``Election 2000, as Seen From Chile'' and ``Fragments
from `Elian! The Musical.' '' The family site is all about, well,
the McSweeneys _ Gerry and Wendy and their four young children, who
enjoy such activities as swimming and skiing.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, people were confused.
</P>
<P>
   When the McSweeney family began receiving unfamily-like e-mail
intended for the magazine, they weren't amused. ``It wasn't
particularly nice,'' says Wendy McSweeney. ``We got some raunchy
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   This sort of mix-up is becoming increasingly common. Internet
domain-level designations were originally meant to define a Web
site's purpose: dot-com stood for commerce; dot-net designated an
Internet company; and dot-org indicated a nonprofit organization.
But now the three designations are virtually indistinguishable, a
fact that is exploited by cyber-squatters eager to reap a profit by
selling variations of desirable Internet addresses.
</P>
<P>
   But neither the dot-com nor the dot-net McSweeneys had any
interest in domain-name bartering. The Stoneham clan simply wanted
to put an end to the unwelcome e-mail. In February, the family
contacted the editors in New York. ``They were peeved at first,''
says associate editor Todd Pruzan. After they all got to know each
other, however, an unlikely friendship was forged. ``We thought it
was neat,'' Wendy McSweeney says.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens, though, that McSweeney's (the magazine) was
experiencing growing pains around the time McSweeneys (the family)
called. Traffic to the site soared early this year after the
publication of Eggers's celebrated memoir, ``A Heartbreaking Work
of Staggering Genius,'' and operating costs skyrocketed. At the
same time, the magazine's Web master decided to pursue a real job
(as in one that pays money). The editors were considering folding
the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   When the McSweeney clan heard this heartbreaking tale, they came
up with an offer of staggering generosity. They would pay the
operating costs for both sites, and computer expert Brendan
McSweeney, 12, would step in as Web master (running the technical,
not content parts) of the magazine. In turn, the editors
volunteered to keep the content of future articles fit for a family
publication; in a note posted on the site this week, the editors
vowed to stay away from ``sexual, scatological, or otherwise
profane writing.'' And that goes for reader mail, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had any 6-year-old readers until now,'' says
Pruzan. Molly McSweeney, the youngest of the Stoneham clan, just
turned 6. ``It seemed like we're all grownups now, and we know what
it means to be responsible in front of children. But this affects
almost none of our content, since we don't have a lot of profane or
sexual content anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement, needless to say, is highly unusual, especially
in an age when anyone and everyone is trying to milk a profit out
of the Internet. Cyber-squatters routinely buy up Internet
addresses and try to resell them for huge profits. Last year, a
Jamaica Plain man bought 65 domain names incorporating the words
Harvard and Radcliffe and tried to sell them for more than
$300,000. Also last year, a Los Angeles company paid a record $7.5
million for the name business.com.
</P>
<P>
   But the McSweeney arrangement isn't about the money or even
about the rights to the name. Both sides refuse to disclose how
much cash is involved, although Pruzan hints that it isn't cheap.
``I can only say that they're very generous,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   And the family members don't seem to be in the deal for their
literary edification, either. These days, Wendy McSweeney's reading
taste doesn't go much beyond books about raising children, and her
favorite magazine is Life. Her husband, who is in real estate,
works long hours and has little free time. Neither one has has
gotten around to reading Eggers's memoir, an astonishing tale about
how he raised his younger brother after their parents both died of
cancer within the same month.
</P>
<P>
   So why become publishers? ``We thought it would be neat for the
kids,'' Wendy McSweeney says. The family's only requirement is that
the two sites be linked together, an odd pairing of wholesome
family photographs with outre articles. What's in a name, indeed?
</P>
<P>
   The young editors are discovering that it is possible to rely on
the kindness of strangers, albeit strangers who share your name.
Oddly enough, the magazine draws its name from a bizarre family
connection. Eggers's mother's maiden name was McSweeney, and
decades ago, she received dozens of letters from a mysterious
Timothy McSweeney desperately begging for money. ``He became this
apocryphal figure for Dave,'' says Pruzan. ``He's probably dead by
now, but it's certainly a strange story.''
</P>
<P>
   This strange story has a happier ending: The Stoneham clan took
over as publisher April 3. As for Wendy McSweeney, she doesn't plan
to contribute any interviews with lunch truck drivers or
meditations on school lunches (two pieces that actually ran in the
magazine). ``No, I won't be doing anything like that,'' she says.
``But it's very interesting stuff.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
