r a BC-TORNADO-DEBRIS-TEX     04-06 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORNADO-DEBRIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TONS OF DEBRIS DOING DAMAGE TO BUDGETS AS COST OF STORM CLEANUP
CLIMBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS VAUGHN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Hour after hour, day after day, the dump
trucks and tractor-trailers have rumbled west on Interstate 30 to a
privately run landfill on the rolling prairie near the
Tarrant-Parker county line.
</P>
<P>
   Overflowing with reminders of the March 28 storms, the trucks
have disgorged tons of glass, roofing shingles, old-growth trees,
and bent and broken remnants of homes. It's enough rubbish, so far,
to cover a football field, end zone to end zone, more than 20 feet
deep.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the sheer amount of debris staggering, but the cost
is on the way up as well. The city of Fort Worth is expecting tens
of thousands of dollars in expenses for the cleanup and is prepared
to ask the federal government to help pay for part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a major expense,'' said Pat Svacina, a spokesman for
the city. ``We've had crews working overtime, on Saturday and
Sunday. We've had wear and tear on equipment. We budget every year
to cover the normal things, but this is extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Mayor Kenneth Barr said Wednesday that Tarrant
County's request for a presidential disaster declaration was to go
to the governor's office Thursday and from there to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``An enormous amount of work has gone into documenting the
damage; the numbers indicate the damage is more significant than we
originally thought,'' Barr said after meeting with federal and
state emergency assessment officials. ``Hopefully, they will sign
off on it in Austin and send it to the president'' today.
</P>
<P>
   City trucks, drawn from several departments, have picked up an
estimated 33,500 cubic yards of debris from downtown and the
Linwood neighborhood north of West Seventh Street. Waste
Management, the city's primary garbage collector, has collected
another estimated 10,000 cubic yards in 450 loads from the
Monticello neighborhood near Osteopathic Medical Center of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Waste Management had to bring in trucks, tractor-trailer rigs
and workers from Dallas, and that still wasn't enough to clean
Monticello. The company also had to call in subcontractors to help,
because Waste Management crews had to continue regular trash pickup
around the rest of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the start, too,'' said Stephen Kellar, marketing
manager with Waste Management. ``Right now, we're just picking up
what's on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the city is counting another 5,000 cubic yards of debris
to be picked up, and that doesn't include the anticipated razing of
several buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup started in the wee hours March 30 and moved quickly
enough, at least in most areas, that tornado researchers wished it
were slower.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Letchford, a professor in the wind engineering program at
Texas Tech University, said some of the rubble was removed from the
streets before it could be studied. The team from Lubbock
considered Fort Worth's storm important because it offered a rare
chance to study a tornado that hit an urban area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more debris we can study, the better,'' Letchford said.
``It gives us the chance to see where it traveled and how it
impacted the buildings around it. I know there's some we didn't get
to see. It was gone before we could get there.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Wendy Davis, who represents downtown and the
Linwood neighborhood, said she is ``incredibly pleased'' with the
cleanup in Linwood, a working-class neighborhood heavily damaged in
the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going way above and beyond anything we're required to
do to help people in that area,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   City officials and Waste Management representatives said they
incurred significant expenses from overtime, equipment use, fuel,
damage to equipment and use of the landfill. But they still have
not arrived at an amount that they can pass on to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal procedures, the Federal Emergency Management
Agency will offer residents and businesses a package of grants,
loans and benefits if the president declares a disaster in the
area.
</P>
<P>
   But the disaster designation is far from automatic.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, such a request must come from the governor's office,
and counties must meet certain criteria.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agencies will help only if the amount of uninsured
damage far exceeds the resources of city and county governments,
officials said. Unexpected city expenses, including employee
overtime, are included in the estimate.
</P>
<P>
   The storms caused an estimated $400 million to $450 million in
damage in River Oaks, Fort Worth, Arlington and Grand Prairie,
according to the Southwestern Insurance Information Service.
</P>
<P>
   However, city and county officials have not announced how much
of that damage is not covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of landfill space consumed in the past week is
significant, city officials said, but ``it's not going to make
landfill space critical in the next two years,'' Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the amount of glass, wood, cardboard and other
traditionally recyclable items left by the tornado, every scrap of
debris has gone to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is usefulness and part is convenience,
officials said. Much of the glass downtown either was rendered
useless even for recycling or it was not the right kind of glass,
Russ said.
</P>
<P>
   But work crews also haven't taken the time to separate debris,
Svacina said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just being swept off the street and taken straight to the
landfill,'' he said. ``It's a mess. You've got paper, shingles,
trees, glass all mixed together and that would be difficult to
separate. We don't have time to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
