<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8766 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WEB-HAGGLERS-ART-BOS &LR;      04-06 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-HAGGLERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 NET FUELING RISE OF AMERICAN BARGAIN HUNTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH DALEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It used to be you paid a fixed price for frozen fish sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Americans hated haggling. And supermarket clerks certainly
couldn't offer 20 cents off at the checkout counter.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, America _ long the landscape of fixed prices _
is turning negotiable.
</P>
<P>
   Name your price online, and you could pay less for the fish than
on triple-coupon day. The same goes for paper towels, cars, and
mortgage rates _ and it's not just on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   Dial your long-distance carrier and get a deal on calls to Japan
by playing a little hardball. If you walk into a chain electronics
store and appear undecided over a video camera, it may suddenly get
less expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Once limited to flea markets and car dealerships, bargaining for
everyday items such as toothpaste and televisions is slowly going
mainstream, specialists say. The popular Priceline.com is even
entertaining bids to fill up your gas tank this spring.
</P>
<P>
   US consumers, long believed to suffer from shyness, guilt, or
just plain awkwardness when engaged in face-to-face dickering,
don't seem to mind it at all when it's anonymous. Or when it's with
huge conglomerates that increasingly sell everything from blue
jeans to compact discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new way of bargaining, we don't usually have to look
someone in the eye and say, `I don't want to pay this price.' It's
the anonymity of the Web and the anonymity of these large, faceless
corporations we deal with that makes it easier,'' said Mary Lou
Roberts, a professor of pricing and e-commerce at University of
Massachusetts at Boston. ``It's an impersonal setting. It makes all
the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The distaste for face-to-face haggling is never more apparent
than when buying a car, at the very least making some uncomfortable
while striking fear in others.
</P>
<P>
   To counter those experiences, car makers including Saturn have
begun offering fixed-priced cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the interaction with (car) salesmen. I don't feel
like I get a good deal. I wouldn't trust them,'' said Denise
Mowles, a mother who in the past has successfully bargained with
big retail outfits for a cheaper TV and video camera. Now, she bids
and shops online for everything from Beanie Babies to Disney
clothes for her children.
</P>
<P>
   The new, online bargaining, however, is a strange, slower-paced
back and forth compared to the bargain banter that defines Turkish
bazaars. Shoppers often submit isolated bids for products and must
wait to hear back. Sometimes they don't get a second chance. Other
sites actually play let's make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't always that way. Once, the American marketplace
pulsated with the same one-on-one negotiating that was the hallmark
of souks, or markets, in the Middle East, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The American general store changed that in the 1800s.
Manufacturers wanted to make sure they got full price for their
goods _ even if someone else was selling them. Selling became
standardized. The supermarket was born.
</P>
<P>
   While Americans have always been price-conscious, they often
saved bargaining for high-ticket items such as houses and cars, and
clipped coupons and shopped on discount days for other items. Even
now, in a flush economy, consumers always want the best deal. In
supermarkets and chain drug stores, consumers can get what they
want _ exactly when they want it. No dickering over cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average American citizen likes to get things quickly. We
want instant gratification,'' said Bruce Weinberg, assistant
professor of marketing and e-commerce at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   While make-a-deal, bidding, auction, and electronic negotiating
sites have helped fuel it, the bargaining craze started pre-Web,
marketing specialists say.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this competitive intensity now,'' said Kathleen
Seiders, marketing professor at Babson College. Many industry
monopolies have been dismantled, and competition for customers has
become fierce. And there are many places to get the same products.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, while the bargaining has yet to hit places like
Filene's or Parade of Shoes, it is happening in chain stores or
companies selling highly competitive items such as electronics or
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   So while the sale of the century may not be listed in the shop
window, employees are more free to offer a discount to customers
who need a little push to buy.
</P>
<P>
   And besides, what do you have to lose when you bargain against a
listed price?
</P>
<P>
   ``The worse thing that can happen is you pay the fixed price,''
Seiders said.
</P>
<P>
   All that means, bargainers and specialists say, is that
consumers are realizing the power of their pocketbook. And for
some, doing it anonymously gives them even more confidence. They
can walk away. They can be the tough customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you went to a mom-and-pop store, they would care if you
came back. You'd treat them a little differently because they
really need you,'' Mowles said.
</P>
<P>
   In big stores and online ``it's not personal,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
