<HEADLINE>
READERS DRIVEN TO WRITE IN ABOUT SUVS, ABS, AND EPA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sorting through reader mail, which flows here not only in great
volume but also in remarkable diversity of tone, from praise to
outright rancor with some interesting technical questions tossed
in:
</P>
<P>
   I remain amazed at the blind rage with which some folks look at
SUVs. When I claimed while reviewing a Chevrolet Suburban that
carried seven people on a ski trip that I had the high
environmental ground over four smaller cars that whizzed by me
carrying, in total, seven people, it set the anti-SUVers into full
attack mode. A sampling:
</P>
<P>
   --``I was so saddened to see your incredibly stupid comment
about having the environmental high ground because you had seven
people in your Suburban.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What about the other 99 percent of the time you drive this
thing and occupy the environmental sub-basement?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Face the fact . . . that 95 percent of the time these cars are
driven by unemployed wealthy suburban dwellers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times do you see a big SUV with more than one or two
people in it?''
</P>
<P>
   Seven people in a Suburban is the way the vehicle should be
used. Far too often I see them driven by a lone commuter or a
driver and one passenger. In past columns, I have called people who
commute alone in SUVs ``jerks.''
</P>
<P>
   My feeling is that if you can afford a big SUV and the gas to
run it, you can also afford an additional, smaller commuter car and
you should buy one and drive it most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   --``In your review of the 2000 Volvo Cross Country, you did not
mention the problem with Volvo headlights, which are burning out
after only 100 hours of driving time. Why not?''
</P>
<P>
   The problem does not occur in the 2000 model year. It is a
problem that cropped up in the V70 and S70 models in 1999. Volvo
says the 4-year, 50,000-mile warranty covers the lights in these
models and dealers should replace them. There is a shortage of the
long-life bulbs they want to install (1,000-hour bulbs), but that
should end in about a month. Meanwhile, if you have to replace your
bulbs with what they have on hand, those, too, will be replaced by
the 1,000-hour bulbs as they become available.
</P>
<P>
   --``I read your column on driving with ABS brakes. Did I have a
(gaseous cranial event) or isn't this the same as anti-skid
systems?''
</P>
<P>
   Anti-lock brakes and anti-skid or stability systems are not the
same. Anti-lock brakes work when a central monitor senses wheel
lockup and briefly eases the brake at the wheel that is about to
lock up. ABS can, however, be a part of an overall anti-skid
system. The latter uses not only brakes, but can also monitor the
position of the front wheels to tell where the driver is trying to
go, as well as the steering wheel, brake pedal pressure, gas pedal
pressure, the clutch and transmission. It can send torque to
nonslipping wheels, cut engine torque, and use the ABS system at
the same time, all aimed at helping you regain control.
</P>
<P>
   --``You completely missed the point about using EPA estimated
gas figures. Your rambling nonsense . . . will never take the place
of objective testing such as that done by the EPA.''
</P>
<P>
   Next time you are at an auto dealership, look at the price
sticker. Look at the fuel economy section. You will find two
numbers are presented in large print: CITY MPG and HIGHWAY MPG. I
just did it with a Mercedes C-Class and the City/Highway figures
were 21 and 27. Now read the fine print: ``Actual mileage will vary
with options, driving conditions, driving habits and vehicle's
condition.'' Now, note this line: ``Results reported to EPA (my
emphasis) indicate that the majority of vehicles with these
estimates will achieve (again, I am quoting the Mercedes sticker
here) between 17 and 25 mpg in the city and between 22 and 32 mpg
on the highway.''
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency gets its numbers not from
its own testing of every vehicle, but from the manufacturers. They
run the cars on dynomometers and simulate 20 minutes of city
driving and 20 minutes of highway driving. They measure carbon
emitted at the tailpipe. This gives them the mileage figures. The
EPA does spot checks to make sure nobody's cheating.
</P>
<P>
   I drive each car I test 800-1,000 miles. I try to drive the way
most people would drive, mixing city, back roads, highways, short
trips, long trips, hauling lots of kids, hauling one kid, going to
the landfill, commuting in and out of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Is it perfect science? Of course not. Does it give me a good
feel for what kind of mileage an auto will get? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   --``Without sounding or feeling stupid, how do I tell if I have
ABS brakes?''
</P>
<P>
   Check your owner's manual. If that's not clear, return to your
dealer and ask. If you want to find out on your own, drive the car
on a deserted stretch of road at about 30 m.p.h. Stamp the brakes
and hold them on. If you have ABS, you'll get a noticeable chatter
in the brake pedal.
</P>
<P>
   --``On a column about the growth of high-tech tracking and
navigation equipment in cars: Is it a good thing to make it
possible for a $9-per-hour computer operator to track upscale
people in their cars? We look for our writers to think, not take
the easy way out.''
</P>
<P>
   Let me think about that.
</P>
<P>
   Yes.
</P>
<P>
   If I am in a car that hits a tree at night on a desolate stretch
of road, I'd love to have an electronic device alert an operator
that my air bag has deployed. If my car is stolen, I'd love to be
able to remotely lock the doors and set off the horn, making life
miserable for the thieves. If I lock myself out of my car, I'd find
it wonderful to be able to call that operator and, after giving the
proper code word, have the car unlocked from afar. Telematics is a
good thing, and it won't always be for the rich. Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   --``I've read columns that describe understeer and oversteer.
Can you explain?''
</P>
<P>
   Understeer, or ``plowing,'' is when you turn your wheels, but
the car tries to keep going straight. Oversteer, or
``fishtailing,'' causes the rear of the car to try to break away to
the outside of the turn and pass the front of the car.
</P>
<P>
   (Royal Ford's e-mail address is ford(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
