<HEADLINE>
FORMER CNN JOURNALIST SEEKS EXONERATION FOR `TAILWIND' ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, D.C. _ Not long after being fired for her role in
producing CNN's ill-fated 1998 telecast about ``Operation
Tailwind,'' April Oliver was struggling to hang on in TV,
freelancing for a tabloid show not known for its high editorial
standards. One day, when she learned that her stint with the show
might make the newspaper, she alerted her bosses. ``We can't be in
the paper next to you,'' she was told.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the dingier corners of the news business, Oliver's name
was poison. ``I cried all night,'' she recalls. ``And I decided I
needed to figure out something new.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, as a tangle of Operation Tailwind lawsuits enters
court-ordered mediation, Oliver _ who is both a plaintiff and a
defendant _ is still crusading for her story, her reputation, and
what she sees as the larger cause of investigative journalism.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's career was not the only casualty of the June 7, 1998
CNN report, with its explosive allegation that the United States
used nerve gas during a 1970 mission to kill American defectors in
Laos. Senior executive producer Pamela Hill resigned and senior
producer Jack Smith was fired. A year later, star correspondent
Peter Arnett _ who narrated the segment as part of CNN's new
collaboration with Time magazine _ was also gone. CNN, which
retracted the story, endured a public relations disaster.
Journalism suffered another credibility crisis. Angry veterans and
military brass claimed the story viciously libeled the nation's
armed services.
</P>
<P>
   Almost two years later, the verdict of public opinion has
hardened: Tailwind _ a segment originally called ``Valley of
Death'' _ was a bad story. Rarely is there a dissenting voice.
</P>
<P>
   Except for April Oliver's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still to this day think we put an accurate story on the air
that is supportable,'' asserts Oliver, who spent the last decade of
her career at PBS and then CNN. ``Whether or not the public has any
interest left I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the defrocked journalist, who is suing both CNN and
retired Army Major General John K. Singlaub over the story, seems
hellbent on vindication. On the other, the 38-year-old mother of
two young kids, who is now studying law at George Mason University,
says ``I'm moving on with my life. I don't want to live my life
bitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Few outside observers can pass definitive judgment on the
veracity of ``Valley of Death.'' But Hodding Carter III, president
of the Knight Foundation and a former boss of Oliver's at PBS, says
that ``she was probably as enthusiastically committed to what I
understand to be the best instincts and principles of journalism''
as anyone. ``If she is convinced that the story is right on the
merits, (she should) fight to the last barricade. I'm a believer in
nothing's over till it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Even First Amendment attorney Floyd Abrams, who helped seal
Oliver's fate by co-authoring the Tailwind post-mortem that advised
CNN to ``retract the story and apologize,'' thinks she has suffered
unduly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am . . . sorry that the effect of this was to keep her from
working elsewhere,'' he says. Other news outlets are ``making a
mistake in not making use of her talents. It's a sad result that
because of this effort, she's out of journalism altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver was driven out of journalism by a tidal wave of
condemnation. The report that Abrams authored at CNN's behest found
the story ``insupportable.'' Both CNN and sister company Time
magazine, which ran a companion Tailwind article, apologized and
retracted. CNN military adviser Perry Smith, a retired Air Force
major general, resigned to protest the telecast, for which he was
not consulted. And ``Valley of Death'' was exhaustively dissected
by the American Journalism Review (``An Ill Tailwind'') and the
Columbia Journalism Review (``Ten Mistakes That Led to the Great
CNN-Time Fiasco.'')
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Oliver found herself with few defenders. ``When push
came to shove, I didn't have that network,'' she says. ``I was
deeply hurt by the lack of support within the journalism community.
. . . It's just a much easier script to buy that I'm the renegade
producer who went astray.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, CNN and parent company Time Warner declined comment
on all matters related to Tailwind. Arnett, who initially responded
to the furor by saying he had played only a minor role as the
program's narrator, could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Singlaub has sued CNN, Time Inc., Time Warner
Inc., Arnett, and Oliver for defamation and intentional infliction
of emotional distress for being ``falsely quoted'' and ``falsely
portrayed as a participant in Tailwind.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's looking to try his best to polish up his tarnished
reputation. He feels that they branded him as a war criminal,
wrongfully,'' says Singlaub attorney Keith Mitnik, adding ``that if
we go trial'' he will be seeking damages in the ``significant seven
figures.''
</P>
<P>
   Singlaub himself says that he ``was initially suspicious'' that
Oliver's vehement defense of the story was designed to ``reduce
(CNN's) liability in a lawsuit.'' Now, he says the ``very anti-CNN
remarks she's made in her public utterances clearly indicate she's
not interested in helping CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver's attitude toward her former employer is manifest in her
cross-claim against CNN: She is seeking damages for, among other
things, ``defamation,'' ``intentional infliction of emotional
distress,'' and ``invasion of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``CNN's decision to publicly retract the report, apologize to
the military, and terminate the employment of Oliver and Smith was
based primarily on business and public relations concerns,'' her
suit states. ``CNN decided to destroy Oliver's career for its own
gain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oliver has also filed a counterclaim against Singlaub,
asserting that in interviews she did while working on the Tailwind
story, he ``expressly confirmed'' the allegations in the story that
he then denounced as erroneous after the program aired.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran journalist Smith, who has slipped from public view, will
begin teaching a course on politics and the press at DePaul and
Loyola of Chicago universities this fall. He is still angry about
what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a young reporter who had her throat cut by a no-guts
management early in her career and she's not gonna' take it,'' he
says, of Oliver. ``I think the whole matter of investigating secret
operations by the US military _ that's what's at stake here.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, mediator Jonathan Marks will attempt to nudge the
parties in this dispute to some kind of settlement. That'll be no
mean feat. Like Mitnik, Oliver's attorney, Roger Simmons, talks
about the price of redemption.
</P>
<P>
   ``April's attitude is that she simply wants to have her good
name back,'' he says. ``The number we've thrown out is the $5
million number.''
</P>
<P>
   If mediation fails, Oliver says, she has ``a short list of
people I want to put on the hot seat'' by deposing CNN founder Ted
Turner, Time Warner boss Gerald Levin, former Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger, and former CIA director Richard Helms.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard not to seem like a zealot when you're in Oliver's
position, poring over documents and depositions for nuggets and
nuance. She produces a 1970 New York Times newsclip quoting a
former Army officer saying he'd seen lethal nerve gas stored in
South Vietnam, and a report of complaints that US planes had
sprayed ``toxic'' and fatal chemicals over Laotian towns during the
war. She and Simmons are heartened because they believe that
Admiral Thomas Moorer _ who was used as a confirming source in the
Tailwind program, but later backed off _ confirmed the accuracy of
Oliver's interview notes in a recent deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took me six months to really believe in her story,'' says
attorney Simmons. ``People have forgotten what the Vietnam War was
about and how the coverups happen. . . . I represent a lot of
investigative journalists. They take a lot of risks and get their
heads kicked in.''
</P>
<P>
   Oliver is still immersed in Tailwind litigation and writing a
book about what she calls the ``the double coverup'' _ the one in
Laos in 1970 and the one ``inside the CNN executive suite.'' But
she also talks about change, about moving away from Washington. She
recalls how in one brief span during her decade-long residence
here, she ran into ``a bunch of fallen celebrities'' _ former Gary
Hart paramour Donna Rice; former Defense Secretary Robert McNamara,
who has apologized for his role in the Vietnam War; and former
Redskins football star Dexter Manley, whose career was punctuated
by drug problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That should have been a cautionary lesson about how this town
can eat you alive,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver also thinks a lot about a new career in law. ``This was a
huge earthquake and it changes a person,'' she says. ``I don't know
how hireable I'll be. Maybe the law is an area where a little bit
of hubris is appreciated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1332EDT &QL; 
