<SLUG> BC-WALKER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MIAMI ICON BECOMES A TARGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADRIAN WALKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Just as it appeared that the Elian crazies had no more
barricades to conquer, they found a new focus for their anger.
Unlike attorney Gregory Craig or Bill Clinton, this foe is one many
of them know well: Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   These are tough times for Janet, a personality so well-known in
this community that thousands of people who've never met her talk
about her as if she were an old acquaintance. She long ago attained
first-name status, joining such local legends as Edna (Buchanan),
Dan (Marino) and Fidel.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have taken to demonstrating outside her small house
at the edge of the Everglades, and the Secret Service has been busy
checking death threats phoned in to Spanish-language radio
stations. Even given the high tensions of the moment, this
animosity is very startling, and no less sad.
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up here, worked here as a reporter, and watched her
career unfold, I feel safe saying this: No one, absolutely no one,
loves Miami more than Janet Reno does. For the mayor of Metro-Dade
County, a fool named Alex Penelas, to stand up as he did last week
and declare that she would be ``held accountable'' if the riot that
he tried to incite comes about is just a measure of how unglued
parts of this community have become.
</P>
<P>
   Reno has a long acquaintance with criticism, here and elsewhere.
Less than two years after becoming state attorney for the county in
1980, her office was defeated at the trial of seven police officers
accused of the beating death of a black motorcyclist. She was
pilloried, especially in the black community, and ``Reno! Reno!''
was one of the signature chants of the riot that followed the
verdict, a bloodbath that left 17 dead and the black neighborhood
of Liberty City in enduring chaos.
</P>
<P>
   She spent much of the next year talking to any black group that
would have her, explaining how her office tried the case, why it
lost, what she would have done differently. I saw some of those
sessions, and still remember how well she handled herself. She
listened as much as she talked, and many people who expected to
hate her were surprised to come away not only liking but respecting
her.
</P>
<P>
   Given her history, Reno is a link between old Miami and the new
city that has emerged. She suceeded Richard Gerstein, an
old-fashioned liberal who was a relic of Miami's almost-forgotten
days as Democratic turf. Reno easily won five elections running as
a Democrat in a city in which they were vanishing _ evidence of,
among other things, her strong standing with the Cuban-American
community gaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Reno's popularity was not always easy to fathom. She famously
does not suffer fools; people still talk about the time she
declared a group of juvenile court judges ``dunderheads'' and
walked out of the conference they were holding. She is not
especially warm. Even old friends laugh about their icy encounters
with her over the years. Her record, especially on public
corruption, remains a matter of some dispute. But she cared deeply
and projected great integrity, and got through on respect rather
than charisma.
</P>
<P>
   Until the day she moved to Washington, she lived in a monument
to eccentricity, a little stone house her mother built with her own
hands in South Dade. Both her parents were reporters. Her father,
Henry, covered the cops for 40 years at the Miami Herald. Her
mother, Jane Wood Reno, was one of the great colorful characters of
local journalism, a star at the late and much lamented Miami News.
Except for college and law school and her time in Washington, Reno
has lived in Miami every day of her life, most of it in the house
now under heavy police guard.
</P>
<P>
   After a distiguished, if tumultuous, tenure as Attorney General
she plans to move back home. No outcome in this case would be
likely to change that. Wednesday, I asked Seymour Gelber, her
friend of more than 30 years and a former mayor of Miami Beach, if
he thought she would still return to Miami, given the animosity
here.
</P>
<P>
   Gelber laughed a long time. ``I don't see that she could or
would go anywhere else,'' he said. ``She wants to go back to that
gray shack and that canoe. Janet's not going to be run out of
town.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Adrian Walker's e-mail address is walker(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
