<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RUMBLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEPTIC TANKS. `PRO' WRESTLING. NEED WE SAY MORE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The unusual credit ``based on World Championship Wrestling
characters'' will be enough to keep some folks away from ``Ready to
Rumble''; the discovery that the wrestling scenes are among the
movie's most highbrow will probably seal the deal. Yet this
slovenly comedy appeals to certain base instincts, such as wanting
to see David Arquette take some sort of punishment after all those
blasted, annoying (800) CALL-ATT commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Arquette and Scott Caan play Gordie and Sean, Wyoming
septic-tank cleaners with an unbalanced obsession for wrestling and
especially for their hero, Jimmy King (Oliver Platt, making like
he's auditioning to play Fat Elvis). Gordie and Sean are more
enamored of ``The King'' than they are of the women at the local
fast-food joint, and get a rare chance to see him live when the WCW
comes to Cheyenne.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, they also get to see their idol mercilessly pummeled
during a career-ending ``massacre'' engineered by backstabbing WCW
honcho Titus Sinclair (Joe Pantoliano). With King at rock bottom
and their own lives just as low, Gordie and Sean decide that
there's only one thing to do: Help their fallen fave make a
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   The recent wrestling documentary ``Beyond the Mat'' informed us
that wrestlers have their flawed human sides, a none-too-startling
revelation that led the World Wrestling Federation to withdraw
support for the film. Rival WCW has no such problem with ``Ready to
Rumble,'' lending many of its real-life stars to a story that
portrays King as a drunken bum who's also a bad son, husband and
father. But Gordie and Sean whip him into shape with the help of a
still-spry wrestling legend (Martin Landau, showing just what being
an Oscar winner means in a brief but lively role) and a Nitro girl
(Rose McGowan) whose seduction of Gordie isn't all that it seems.
</P>
<P>
   It's all even more diagrammed and predictable than real pro
wrestling, but the ring scenes are undeniably exciting if you're up
for this sort of stuff. They're certainly better than the movie's
opening 20 minutes or so, a nonstop barrage of scatalogical humor
and standbys such as the swearing, lecherous old lady (''The
Wedding Singer's'' Ellen Albertini Dow, who should patent this
role). Richard Lineback enlivens things somewhat as Gordie's
father, a trigger-happy state trooper.
</P>
<P>
   A final word of warning to the unsuspecting: ``Ready to Rumble''
is quite possibly the most violent PG-13 movie ever, replete with
so many crotch kicks (including a final-credit montage) that it's
sure to hold the record for this gag unless someone makes a movie
called ``Groin Injury.'' But it's nothing to criticize the ratings
board for. After all, it's all fake.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Ready to Rumble''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Brian Robbins
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: David Arquette, Scott Caan, Oliver Platt
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13 _ wrestling violence, strong language, sexual
situations and toilet humor
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
