A8788 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-RETURNTOME-TEX     04-06 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RETURNTOME-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENIAL CHARACTERS HELP `RETURN TO ME' OVERCOME FLAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every now and then, a movie comes along that breaks down
resistance, that shares flaws with similar films but overcomes them
through some mystical bit of creative alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hunt's ``Return to Me'' is that kind of movie; it commits
a certain number of storytelling sins, such as centering its plot
on an enormous coincidence and a secret that a character must keep
because, if it were divulged, there'd be no more movie. And when it
needs an easy laugh, it leans a little too much on the cuteness of
animals, children and old men.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, it succeeds, thanks to appealing characters, sharp
dialogue and an atmosphere that varies from boisterous to
melancholy without losing its balance. In her directorial debut,
Hunt _ who also co-wrote and appears in a supporting role _ shows a
talent for putting what she's got to its best use. That shows most
in the performance of David Duchovny, who brings his laconic
everyguy charm to a relaxed and varied turn as Bob Rueland, a
Chicago architect whose lovingly cute relationship with his
zoologist wife Elizabeth (Joely Richardson) ends in tragedy when
she dies in a car accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bob spends a lot of time in mournful moping, letting his home
and his appearance go to seed and finding little solace in his
Great Dane, who still stares at the door waiting for Elizabeth to
come home months after her death. Encouraged by an upbeat friend
(David Alan Grier), Bob picks himself up long enough to go on a
blind date with a woman who turns out to be an obnoxious loudmouth
lawyer (Hunt's longtime crony Holly Wortell, in a brief but
scene-stealing role). But it's the waitress Bob clicks with: She's
Grace (Minnie Driver), a heart-transplant recipient trying to get
over her self-consciousness about her scars and join the dating
game. Which she does, reluctantly, with the affable and persistent
Bob in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt filmed the movie in her hometown of Chicago, even going
back to her old neighborhood for some scenes, and she drenches the
city with so much Windy City ambience that you can practically
smell the sausage links. Well, the pasta sauce, anyway _ Grace
works at an Italian-Irish restaurant owned by her Irish grandfather
(Carroll O'Connor, trying out an Irish brogue) and inhabited by her
Italian uncle (Robert Loggia) and a multiethnic crew of other aging
widowers. Without forcing the matter, Hunt does a better job of
portraying a melting pot than James Toback does with his much more
serious-intentioned multiracial ``Black and White.''
</P>
<P>
   Even better, she does it without resorting to too many obnoxious
characters, aside from Wortell's date from hell and a similarly
disastrous blind date for Grace (played amusingly by
co-screenwriter Don Lake). Even James Belushi has a slovenly appeal
as the husband of Grace's best friend, played by Hunt with her
typical supportive warmth. The likable characters, and Duchovny and
Driver's surprising chemistry, help ``Return to Me'' transcend its
problems and turn it into an affectionate winner.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Return to Me''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bonnie Hunt
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: David Duchovny, Minnie Driver
</P>
<P>
   Length: 116 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG _ strong language and adult themes
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
