<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8790 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT     04-06 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-440&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF CUBAN CHILD ARRIVES WITH HOPES OF A SWIFT REUNION 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the hour after sunrise, the jet carrying the father of Elian
Gonzalez touched down Thursday at an airport near Washington, D.C.,
and Juan Miguel Gonzalez set foot on U.S. soil, vowing to take his
son back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am truly impatient to have him returned to me as soon as
possible and go back to Cuba together immediately,'' Juan Miguel
Gonzalez said in Spanish at a news conference at Dulles
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   After more than four months of separation, he said he wanted to
embrace his 6-year-old son. Elian is being cared for by his
great-uncle in Miami, and the relatives there resumed negotiations
with federal officials Thursday morning as Juan Miguel Gonzalez,
his wife and their infant son were whisked off to a Cuban
diplomat's suburban home, where they will stay.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, is appealing in a U.S.
district court in Atlanta to compel the Immigration and
Naturalization Service to grant the boy an asylum hearing. Like
many Cuban-Americans who oppose President Fidel Castro's communist
regime, the great-uncle is reluctant to see Elian returned to Cuba.
He has said he will talk with Elian's father about the boy's future
if the father comes to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Craig, the lawyer for the father, said he traveled to
Cuba on Tuesday and put Juan Miguel Gonzalez's trip into motion
because the INS had said it was negotiating for a transfer of
custody to the father.
</P>
<P>
   Elian was discovered by fishermen floating in an inner-tube off
the Florida coast in November, one of three survivors of a capsized
refugee boat. His mother, who was divorced from the his father, and
10 other Cubans drowned. The INS gave Elian temporary residency
status and placed him in the care of his great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the news conference of his son's ordeal, Juan Miguel
Gonzalez said, ``As if his mother's disappearance before his eyes
and the miracle of his arrival have not inflicted enough damage, he
has had to spend time under the temporary custody of some distant
relatives who had never seen him before.''
</P>
<P>
   Defying the shouts of anti-Castro protesters gathered at the
airport, he further criticized the boy's exposure to the hostile
politics that have characterized relations between Cuba and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an agonizing experience to see my son submitted to
cruel psychological pressures aimed at influencing his personality
already weakened by the terrible trauma,'' Juan Miguel Gonzalez
said. ``Worse still, Elian has been paraded and exhibited in public
rallies and by the media with a clear intent to obtain political
advantage from this tragedy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   While Juan Miguel Gonzalez's arrival gives Justice Department
and INS officials more leverage in negotiating for Elian's
handover, it was not clear Thursday morning exactly what role the
father would play in the process. Juan Miguel Gonzalez and his
family are staying at the home of Fernando Remirez, head of the
Cuban diplomatic mission, in Bethesda, Maryland. Remirez said the
diplomatic immunity status of his residence was being dropped
during Juan Miguel Gonzalez's stay. That would put the home under
the jurisdiction of the U.S. government rather than the Cuban
government.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials said they might meet with the
father as early as Thursday, but have made no plans for him to go
to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe reuniting Elian with his father is not only a matter
of federal law, not only a matter of immigration law, it is simply
the right thing to do,'' Eric Holder, deputy attorney general, said
at a news conference Thursday morning in Washington. ``The father
and his son need to be together, and in the coming days we will do
all that we can to ensure that that happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said no law prevents Gonzalez from leaving the country
immediately if he is given custody of his son, but he said he
believes the father is willing to stay through the legal appeals
process. The U.S. 11th Circuit Court of Appeals in Atlanta has said
it will hear oral arguments starting the week of May 8.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami Thursday, outside the yard where Elian played on a
slide and fired toy guns Thursday morning, about 70 Cuban-American
protesters prepared for what they believe may be a bitter fight.
For days, they have practiced forming a human chain to block
federal officials if they come to retrieve Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Castro said Elian's father could come to the United
States alone if he could bring his son back to Cuba immediately.
But if he would have to wait in the United States through the
appeals process, Castro said Juan Miguel Gonzalez would have to be
accompanied by an entourage of 27 other people including Elian's
classmates, teachers and relatives, as well as child psychiatrists,
doctors and nurses.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, Gonzalez said President Castro ``has been like a
brother, giving me advice and support through our long days of pain
and uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the State Department granted six visas, but three
recipients _ Elian's kindergarten teacher, a close cousin and a
pediatrician _ did not accompany the father. Juan Miguel Gonzalez
urged the U.S. government to allow the rest of the entourage to
come, saying that it would be in the best interests of the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will also need the counseling of specialists and a
propitious environment with his classmates and teachers to help him
back to his old routine of family life, schooling and playing with
his friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As Juan Miguel Gonzalez prepared on Wednesday for his trip,
Castro spoke in Havana before hundreds of university students from
across Latin America and the Caribbean who had gathered for a
regional congress. Castro predicted that Elian and his father would
be reunited soon. ``It is inevitable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (js)
</P>
</TEXT>
