<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8793 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-FLORA-LEWIS-APRIL6-NY     04-06 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORA-LEWIS-APRIL6-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MONOPOLY IS A GLOBAL CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the FLORA-LEWIS column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By FLORA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Flora Lewis 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ There is no more compelling symbol of globalization than
the one evoked by Microsoft. Its reach seems unlimited and its
ambitions are universal. And it represents more than porous borders
that let athletic shoes and hamburgers come from anywhere and go
anywhere, offering hungry peasants the opportunity to become sweat
shop workers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the result of the technological conquest of time
and distance, but the technology itself, evolving so fast that its
creators can scarcely imagine what will come next. But they are
convinced that they must hurry up or they will be left behind in
the new race for the power that ``intelligence technology,''
computing and communicating can bring.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have a passport and its boss is not elected, not even
chosen by stockholders because he owns so much of the stock
himself. He is so rich that he can give away a hundred million
dollars without feeling a dent.
</P>
<P>
   So an American court's decision that this colossus is breaking
the law and must be forced to atone for its transgressions imposes
a startling change in perspective. The U.S. government didn't ask
anybody else about regulating Microsoft, or what the consequences
may be for other countries if the company is broken up or
remodeled. It is a matter of purely national antitrust law, and no
international agreements or obligations are involved.
</P>
<P>
   There was an effort to negotiate a settlement between Microsoft
and the government that would have avoided a judicial decision, but
it broke down. No doubt there will be an appeal, and the case is
likely to drag on for a long time and at great expense. There will
be all kinds of efforts at lobbying, overt and not so
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   But the point has already been made. The United States, by
itself, can overrule Microsoft and nobody else can have any say
about it. That is superpower, and for all the talks and disputes
and pretense of sovereign equality, it is a reminder that the
United States can dominate.
</P>
<P>
   The bewildered behavior of stock markets at the news was another
reminder of how intricately interdependent the world's economy has
become. In the years right after World War II _ when the dollar was
the only reliable currency (except for the Swiss franc) and
everybody's recovery and reconstruction depended on American help _
they used to say, ``When the U.S. sneezes, the world catches
pneumonia.''
</P>
<P>
   Today there is a nervous sense that there would scarcely be time
to take your temperature. The extraordinary gains of the stock
markets in recent years, especially in high tech companies, have
come with the full realization that there is an enormous gap
between value projected from future earnings and value reflected
from goods and services produced. It could be called the
psycho-economy. Everything depends on confidence.
</P>
<P>
   So there is very good reason for the rest of the world to watch
closely the dispute between Microsoft and the U.S. government.
Careful attention must also be paid to how those tribulations may
be interpreted by investors and speculators.
</P>
<P>
   When the Asian financial crises broke a few years ago, followed
by Brazil and Russia, there was a quick sense of the global
economy's common stakes in palliating breakdowns. The international
response was sensitive and realistic. Instead of the kind of panic
and beggar-thy-neighbor responses that turned 1929 bank and credit
failures in Europe into a long and devastating global recession,
there were rescue missions and firebreaks.
</P>
<P>
   For lack of foresight, however, they weren't as good as they
might have been. There was much talk at the time of developing
better international surveillance of financial movements so that
governments need not be overwhelmed by the integration of THE
market.
</P>
<P>
   But the pressure of necessity ebbed, as did political will.
Nothing much was done to show recognition that new economic
circumstances require new political decisions, now quite
necessarily on an international level.
</P>
<P>
   In a perverse way, the Microsoft case renews the sense of need
to strike a balance between the dynamics of totally unrestrained
markets and governments' itch to intervene.
</P>
<P>
   The American antitrust laws were passed at the beginning of the
century in reaction to the terrible excesses of robber-baron
capitalism. It was seen that free markets require that the
government take steps to protect the chance for fair competition.
Microsoft, dealt with as a purely U.S. concern, shows that this is
now true on a global level and should have global coordination.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Flora Lewis is the former foreign-affairs columnist for The
New York Times. She is the author of five books, including
``Europe: Road To Unity'' and ``Europe: A Tapestry of Nations.''
Her articles have appeared in the International Herald Tribune, The
New York Times Magazine, The Atlantic, The Economist, France-Soir,
Life, The London Observer, The New Yorker and many other
periodicals. Last year she won the Overseas Press Club's Award for
Lifetime Achievement.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the FLORA
LEWIS column and other features. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives: &LR;
</P>
