<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8794 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-TEN-HIPPENSTEEL-HNS &LR;      04-06 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-HIPPENSTEEL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STANFORD PLAYER OVERCOMES AILMENTS TO RETURN TO COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CHRISTOPHER ARGYRIS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _ When a ruptured spleen brought on by a severe
case of mononucleosis sidelined Stanford tennis ace K.J.
Hippensteel in January, doctors told him he would have to ``kiss
the season goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel was having none of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked too hard this summer to have a season just lost like
that,'' said Hippensteel, who was coming off an NCAA singles title.
``This was going to be a big year for me.''
</P>
<P>
   So the top-ranked collegiate singles player worked his way back
into form in time for the stretch run at another team title and
individual honors.
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel's return to singles will come Friday when
third-ranked Stanford hosts UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty tough to go down like that, when I was playing
at the top of my game, but it feels good to be back,'' said
Hippensteel, who did not know he had mono at the time of his
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``K.J. is a great team leader,'' Stanford coach Dick Gould said.
``His return is a tremendous boost to the whole team. I've never
seen a bigger smile on a guy than the day when K.J. was cleared to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould said his players were sorry to see Hippensteel go down but
were quick to pick up the slack.
</P>
<P>
   ``no one loves to compete more than K.J., so it was
disheartening for us to lose him when he was playing so well,''
Gould said. ``But I was really impressed with how they played
without him, how we were able to stay undefeated. It's quite
remarkable really, and a testament to this team's strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Gould praised Alex Kim and Geoff Abrams, who have split time at
No. 1 singles since Hippensteel went down. He has not played a
singles match since Jan. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel will be eased back into the lineup, Gould said. The
coach isn't worried about what slot Hippensteel will fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more concerned about getting my guys healthy and doing
well in the team championships,'' Gould said. ``Whom I play at what
spot will take care of itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel said he respects Gould's decision, wherever he puts
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Gould knows what's best for the team, where to put his
guys in the lineup,'' he said. ``I just need to focus playing my
best and getting my singles confidence back.''
</P>
<P>
   As an unseeded entrant in the Intercollegiate Tennis Association
All-American Championships in Austin, Texas, in October,
Hippensteel beat six of the nation's top 40 players en route to the
No. 1 ranking in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel entered the winter season as the top-ranked player
in Division I, and was the top seed at the National Collegiate
Tennis Classic. But he suffered his injury in his first match at
that event, and was sidelined until his return to doubles action
March 28.
</P>
<P>
   He won the NCAA doubles championship last year with Ryan
Wolters.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal (15-0) in Friday's rematch with UCLA (16-2) seek to
remain the only undefeated team in Division I. On Feb. 27 in
Louisville, the then-No. 2 Cardinal beat the No. 7 Bruins, 4-3, in
the finals of the National Team Indoor Championships.
</P>
<P>
   Hippensteel admits returning to singles against the top team in
the land is not exactly easing his way back, but he is aching to
get thrown back into the fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be quite a challenge for me, physically as well as
psychologically, but I'm ready to go. And UCLA will be out to get
back at us after our win in Louisville, for sure,'' he said. ``I
just can't wait to get back on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what you get up in the morning to practice for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
