<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ The House has just pulled one of
those transparent political stunts that underestimates the
intelligence of the voters. For the third time in recent years,
conservatives have approved an abortion-procedure ban they know is
going nowhere because President Clinton will veto it. And once
again they put preserving a fetus ahead of protecting the health of
the mother. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON-PROTESTS (Washington) _ Four months after paralyzing
Seattle's meeting of the World Trade Organization, dozens of
protest groups will soon arrive here to make life miserable for two
other multinational financial institutions: the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund. The protesters want them to forgive
many nations' debts, pay more attention to the environment and
provide loans that directly help people rather than corporations.
The April 16 and 17 meetings will bring together financial
officials from 182 nations. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ Lawmakers may change the way the
federal government distributes $1.6 billion for AIDS care and
prevention. Instead of giving the money just to those with AIDS
cases, they are considering a plan to give part of it also to
people with HIV, the virus that causes AIDS. By JUDY HOLLAND.
</P>
