<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8797 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-CELEB-CAUSES-C     04-06 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-CELEB-CAUSES-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRITIES AND THEIR CAUSES: A POLITICAL REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Thursday, April 6, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You have to love celebrities and their causes.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Campbell appearing nearly nude in ads with the tagline,
``I'd rather go naked than wear fur.''
</P>
<P>
   Madonna literally wrapping herself in the American flag for MTV
and cooing, ``If you don't vote, you're going to get a spanky!''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Danson explaining why he's already forgotten more about the
environment than you'll ever learn.
</P>
<P>
   Alec Baldwin and Kim Basinger striving valiantly to save those
Manhattan horses from their carriage-pulling enslavement.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Goldie Hawn. Actress, singer, dancer, committed
girlfriend to Kurt Russell, devoted mother. Plus she cares! Just
last month, Goldie wrote a letter of concern to legislators in
Maryland, her home state if you can believe it.
</P>
<P>
   The topic: Circus elephants. There's a bill before the Maryland
General Assembly that would ban the use of elephants for
entertainment of any kind, and Goldie's all for it.
</P>
<P>
   As she put it in her open letter to the Maryland Judiciary
Committee: ``Circus elephants are denied almost everything
important to them, including family relationships, privacy, mental
stimulation, physical exercise and emotional outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   She's talking about privacy for elephants. How can you not love
that?
</P>
<P>
   As entertaining and informative as it is when celebs are
arrested in the name of their pet causes, it's even more inspiring
when Hollywood stars make the pilgrimage to Washington, D.C., to
testify about issues like starvation (they're almost always against
it) and literacy (they're almost always for it).
</P>
<P>
   Last month Michael Bolton appeared before Congress to deliver
more than 40,000 signatures supporting an extension of the Violence
Against Women Act, which provides funds for programs and shelters
for women who have been abused. There ain't a damn thing funny
about violence against women _ but do we need the man who has
sullied ``When a Man Loves a Woman'' to run point on this issue?
How about an amendment prohibiting Michael Bolton from remaking
golden oldies?
</P>
<P>
   Even better was the all-star panel that met with lawmakers on
March 30 to voice support of the Shambala Wild Protection Act,
which would impose further regulations on the breeding and sale of
large exotic animals. The roster of stars included Melanie
Griffith, her mom, Tippi Hedren, and Bo Derek _ all of whom have
been mauled by lions, if you can believe it. Only Hedren has ever
been mauled by birds, but that wasn't in real life, that was in
``The Birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on hand (so to speak) was Kermit the Frog, who is a hand
puppet. Imagine being the guy who had to crouch under the desk and
manipulate Kermy as he testified to bigwig lawmakers. Quite a life
moment!
</P>
<P>
   Some passionate celebrities and the causes, illnesses or
injustices they've talked about on Capitol Hill:
</P>
<P>
   Mary Tyler Moore, juvenile diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Fox, Parkinson's disease.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi Judd, hepatitis C.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Douglas, nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   Meryl Streep, chemicals in apples.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Cash, copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   Isaac Hayes, Scientology.
</P>
<P>
   Don Henley, copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Seymour, alternative medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Lasorda, flag-desecration amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Oprah Winfrey, children's rights.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Allen, colorization of classic films.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these appearances have been more compelling than others.
How can anyone be unmoved by Christopher Reeve, speaking from
tragic firsthand experience, about the need for more funding to
find a way to repair spinal cord damage? Then again, how can anyone
but a handful of very famous people care when Paul Reiser speaks
about the need for more legislation protecting the privacy of
celebrities? Not exactly an issue of deep concern to the average
working-class family.
</P>
<P>
   There's something refreshing about good old-fashioned hedonists
like Jack Nicholson, who seem to be interested only in doing
movies, golfing and having a helluva good time. I can't imagine
Jack appearing before a judiciary committee to ask for more funding
to combat rickets or something.
</P>
<P>
   One thing, though. No matter what the motives of the celebrity
who vamps for Congress or gets arrested while the cameras click
away, the publicity stunt invariably accomplishes its mission.
Hearings about juvenile diabetes or the plight of Tibetans won't
get a paragraph in most newspapers _ unless somebody famous shows
up to talk about it. Those comments from stars who say things like
``I'm using my celebrity to increase awareness of this terrible
situation'' _ they happen to be accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Pretentious to the brink of being insufferable, but accurate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
