<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8800 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-LIST-$ADV09-COX     04-06 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LIST-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE STORIES BEHIND THE STORIES ABOUT GORE
 &HT;    With GORE-HYPE. Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories for release Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In several cases, stories about Vice President Al
Gore's tendency to exaggerate his accomplishments or personal
history have been distorted themselves:
</P>
<P>
   MYTH:
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore discovered the Love Canal toxic waste dump.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE:
</P>
<P>
   Misquotes by The New York Times and The Washington Post of
remarks Gore made Nov. 30, 1999, in a campaign visit to Concord
High School in Concord, N.H. The papers quoted him as saying, ``I
was the one that started it all.''
</P>
<P>
   REALITY:
</P>
<P>
   In exhorting the students to reject cynicism about politics and
government, Gore cited a letter he received as a congressman from a
high school girl in Tennessee about toxic waste in her hometown of
Toone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called for a congressional investigation and a hearing,''
Gore said. ``I looked around the country for other sites like that.
I found a little place in upstate New York called Love Canal. Had
the first hearing on that issue, and Toone, Tennessee _ that was
the one that you didn't hear of. But that was the one that started
it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post ran a correction on Dec. 7, 1999. The New
York Times ran a correction on Dec. 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   MYTH:
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore claimed he ``invented'' the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE:
</P>
<P>
   A March 9, 1999, interview with CNN's Wolf Blitzer in which Gore
said, ``During my service in the United States Congress, I took the
initiative in creating the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   REALITY:
</P>
<P>
   Gore was the leader in Congress on the connections between data
transmission and computing power. This information technology
helped transform the tiny ARPANET, created in 1969 by the Defense
Department and used largely by academicians, into what is known as
the Internet today.
</P>
<P>
   MYTH:
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore claimed he and his wife, Tipper, were the prototypes for
the Ryan O'Neal and Ali McGraw characters in the movie ``Love
Story,'' which was based on Erich Segal's novel by the same name.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE:
</P>
<P>
   A Time magazine profile of Gore written by Karen Tumulty that
was based, in part, on a two-hour conversation the vice president
had with reporters on a late-night flight of Air Force Two.
</P>
<P>
   REALITY:
</P>
<P>
   Segal modeled the Ryan O'Neal character on two people: Gore and
one of his Harvard roommate, actor Tommy Lee Jones, who had a small
part in the movie as O'Neal's roommate. The Ali McGraw character
was not based on Tipper Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore based his comments to Tumulty and others on erroneous news
accounts of ``Love Story'' in the Nashville Tennessean newspaper
following the 1970 release of the hit movie. ``All I know'' is what
Segal had told reporters in Tennessee, Gore said. Segal confirmed
that the Tennessean ``exaggerated a bit'' in its coverage of the
movie.
</P>
<P>
   MYTH:
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore dishonestly portrayed his boyhood summers on the Gore
family farm in Tennessee by fabricating stories of strenuous
chores.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE:
</P>
<P>
   A March 24, 1999, column in the Washington Post by Michael Kelly
under the headline ``Farmer Al.'' Kelly took fanciful issue with
Gore's description of his relationship with his father during an
interview published March 16, 1999, by the Des Moines Register:
``He taught me how to clean out hog waste with a shovel and a hose.
He taught me how to clear land with a double-bladed ax. He taught
me how to plow a steep hillside with a team of mules. He taught me
how to take up hay all day long in the hot sun.''
</P>
<P>
   REALITY:
</P>
<P>
   Gore's summers in Tennessee were more like character-building
boot camps, according to two critical biographers, Bob Zelnick and
Bill Turque. His chores, which included baling hay, feeding
livestock and shoveling manure, often stretched from sunup to
sundown. His late father once acknowledged that he was ``a little
severe'' the summer regimen he set for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly himself, in a 1987 Gore profile he wrote for the Baltimore
Sun, noted that ``life was different'' for Gore, the son of a
senator, during his chore-filled summers in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
