<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v BC-PRISONS-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      04-06 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, April 6, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To save on the huge cost of prison construction, New York has
become one of the first states to segregate two inmates together in
maximum-security cells that prisoners derisively call The Box.
</P>
<P>
   The unorthodox move _ which prison officials call double-bunking
_ changes the definition of solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel Peace Prize-winning Amnesty International says such
imprisonment meets the definition of torture under international
law.
</P>
<P>
   But state and federal court decisions so far have upheld New
York's prison policies regarding disciplinary confinement. State
officials say the prisoners have brought the punishment on
themselves by bad behavior behind bars, and need to be segregated
in special cells.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, nearly 5,700 prisoners are confined to 23-hour
disciplinary lockdown. That amounts to roughly 8 percent of the
state's 72,000 inmates, four times the national average of about 2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the following stories and sidebars, Paul Grondahl of the
Albany Times Union takes a look at the increase in maximum-security
confinement and the potential effects on the prison population.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions, please contact Tim Spence at the Hearst
News Service, 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will move in the NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category).
Here is the story lineup:
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-THE-BOX (Albany, N.Y.) _ Prisoners call it The Box, a
kind of hermetically sealed netherworld, devoid of outside contact.
Nowhere in the world is The Box _ super maximum-security
confinement _ used more than in the United States. Nowhere in
America is it used more than in New York state. Human rights groups
say such imprisonment meets the definition of torture under
international law, and that it violates constitutional prohibitions
against cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic: PRISONS-UN
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-PRIEST (Coxsackie, N.Y.) _ For a few hours each day at
New York state's Greene Correctional Facility, the Rev. Joe Ramona
pushed a cart with rosaries, books and spiritual reading material.
What Romano witnessed among these young men, many of them between
the ages of 16 and 19, caused the cleric deep despair. Ultimately,
he said, it hastened his retirement last November after 15 years of
prison work.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-JUDGE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Sol Wachtler wrote court
decisions on solitary confinement as the one-time chief judge of
the state of New York. He also spent a month himself in what he
calls ``the hole'' while serving a federal prison sentence. That
gives him a unique position to assess this form of incarceration in
his book, ``After The Madness: A Judge's Own Prison Memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-PSYCHIATRIST (Undated) _ Dr. Stuart Grassian never set
out to become the country's leading specialist on the psychological
effects of long-term solitary confinement on prisoners. ``I was
shocked to find out that the prison psychiatrists who were supposed
to be doing this job weren't, so I got involved,'' the Harvard
Medical School professor says.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-ARIZONA (Undated) _ After 21 years on death row in the
Arizona state prison system, 14 of them in a solitary confinement,
Paris Carriger was left with a mind and a body eroded by the
ordeal. Carriger, now 55 and living in Oklahoma, was released in
January 1999 after a review of his case and a re-trial that found
him innocent and set him free. Today he cannot find work and
survives on Social Security disability.
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-HISTORY (Undated) _ Charles Dickens visited Eastern
Penitentiary in Philadelphia in 1842 and wrote that solitary
confinement is ``immeasurably worse than any torture of the body
... a secret punishment which slumbering humanity is not roused up
to stay.'' Dickens' report and other negative reviews roused public
opinion against this form of punishment, yet solitary confinement
has never disappeared from the prison landscape.
</P>
<P>
   With: PRISONS-PUNISHMENT
</P>
<P>
   PRISONS-BOX-LIFE (Undated) _ Your fellow inmates call it The
Box, the small maximum-security cells where two convicts are
housed. There are few liberties, and those must be earned through a
system of merits. But if you don't follow the rules, your actions
are punishable by additional time in The Box.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1421EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8803 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GORE-HYPE-$ADV09-COX     04-06 2365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-HYPE-$ADV09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE MORE VICTIMIZED THAN GUILTY OF FALSEHOODS, PRESS CRITICS
SAY
 &HT;    1720&AMP;add. With GORE-LIST. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories for release Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Politicians embellish, and Vice President Al Gore
is no exception. But press critics, led by Bob Somerby, Gore's
college roommate, say that media coverage of Gore's exaggerations
have themselves been exaggerated to the point of recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   The critics say Gore has been unfairly portrayed as a delusional
``Zelig''-like figure and an untrustworthy political ``Pinocchio.''
</P>
<P>
   They say the portrait is partly rooted in exaggerated or
inaccurate accounts of Gore claiming he uncovered the Love Canal
toxic waste scandal, ``invented'' the Internet, inspired the novel
``Love Story,'' and spent summers doing back-breaking chores on the
family farm in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   These accounts continue to appear in news stories and opinion
columns, and have become a theme of attacks by Gore's political
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Some have become so deeply embedded in the coverage of the
presidential campaign that Gore himself has simply apologized for
misimpressions, apparently in order to avoid further controversy.
</P>
<P>
   The front-line reporters and biographers who know Gore best say
the vice president himself is responsible for the atmosphere of
skepticism that permeates their coverage. His tendency to embellish
his accomplishments and rewrite his biography are well documented,
they note.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the coverage of Gore's campaign has triggered a backlash
from media critics and ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't understand the venom that the press directs at Al
Gore,'' said Joanne McGlynn, a New Hampshire high school teacher
whose students have been waging their own campaign to correct the
record about a visit Gore made to their school last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Somerby, in a recent interview, said, ``The image of the
Washington press corps from `All The President's Men' is a couple
of young guys pounding the pavement, trying to get it right, trying
to beat the other guy. But that's just not the way it works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, instead of being entrepreneurial, they seem to be
desperate to stay on script. There's this tremendous uniformity of
expression. And there is clearly a code of silence _ a tacit
agreement that you never, never criticize another journalist in the
club.''
</P>
<P>
   Somerby, a native of Boston, delights in boxing the ears of
media stars inside the Washington Beltway from his home in nearby
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Somerby's targets dismiss him and his Web site, The
Daily Howler (www.dailyhowler.com), as an unofficial arm of the
Gore presidential campaign. Somerby shared a dorm room at Harvard
University with Gore and actor Tommy Lee Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Somerby remains a friend of the vice president, but denies that
the Gore campaign has any involvement in his efforts. In fact,
Somerby is now beginning to take aim at what he believes is unfair
press coverage of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, Gore's likely
opponent in the White House general election this fall.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a recent New York Times interview with Bush in which
the paper reported that Bush had said he had not ``learned''
anything from his tough Republican primary contest with Sen. John
McCain of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word 'learn' _ it's like Gore 'inspired' 'Love Story,'
'invented' the Internet, 'discovered' Love Canal,'' said Somerby.
``Those verbs were never uttered by either man.''
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized a recent U.S. News and World Report article
which called both Bush and Gore ``dim bulbs.'' ``I don't know
Governor Bush, but I would suggest you can't run a state as big as
Texas if you are a dim bulb,'' he said. ``But it's another case of
the media elite asserting their superiority over politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a recent interview with Cox Newspapers, declined to
address the issue of his ``exaggerations.'' But he referred the
interviewer to Somerby's Web site. ``You'll get a kick out of it,''
the vice president said.
</P>
<P>
   Somerby taught the fifth grade in Baltimore public schools for
13 years before becoming a stand-up comedian in 1981. He also began
writing free-lance commentaries for the Baltimore Sun, occasionally
in defense of his old Harvard roommate.
</P>
<P>
   Somerby launched the Daily Howler in early 1998 after the Sun
rejected a commentary criticizing media coverage of President
Clinton's political supporters staying overnight in the Lincoln
Bedroom at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized, `Ohhh, articles on the national press corps don't
get published,' '' he said, slapping his forehead in mock surprise.
``Articles criticizing Clinton will. Articles criticizing (former
House Speaker Newt) Gingrich will. Articles criticizing The
Washington Post and The New York Times won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Two magazine articles highly critical of the Post and the Times
coverage of Gore have been published recently by The Washington
Monthly and Brill's Content. Both articles focused on how difficult
it has been to stop the reverberation of a small reporting error by
the Post and Times about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Love Canal'' incident provides a textbook example of how
the candidate, the press and the public have come to view the
veracity of candidates and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The reporting error grew out of Gore's Nov. 30 visit to Concord
High School in Concord, N.H. In response to a student's question,
Gore cautioned against cynicism about the political process. He
illustrated his point with a story about how he had received a
letter from a high school girl in Tennessee when he was in
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which complained about toxic waste in Toone, Tenn.,
eventually led to Gore holding the first congressional hearings on
Love Canal, an upstate New York neighborhood contaminated by
chemical waste during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called for a congressional investigation and a hearing,''
Gore said in the course of a seven-minute response. ``I looked
around the country for other sites like that. I found a little
place in upstate New York called Love Canal. Had the first hearing
on that issue, and Toone, Tennessee _ that was the one you didn't
hear of _ but that's was the one that started it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The Post's Ceci Connolly and the Times's Katharine Seelye quoted
Gore as having said, ``I was the one that started it all.''
</P>
<P>
   The misquote was widely cited as evidence of Gore's tendency to
exaggerate or falsify his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's George Stephanopoulos said it was an example of Gore's
``Pinocchio problem.'' MSNBC's Chris Matthews, host of the program
``Hardball,'' talked about Gore's ``Zelig'' condition, a reference
to the Woody Allen character who appeared in a procession of
historical events.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's the guy who said he was the main character in `Love
Story,' `I invented the Internet, I invented Love Canal,' chortled
Matthews. ``Isn't it getting to be delusionary?''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews continued in this line even though he had played a tape
of Gore's remarks to correct the Post and Times accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The day after his remarks at Concord High, Gore issued a
statement apologizing for any misimpression he may have created
with his comments.
</P>
<P>
   The Post printed a correction seven days after the event, and
the Times printed one after 10 days. In the meantime, both
newspapers ran additional stories exploring Gore's exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   Seelye, in an interview last week, repeated her earlier
contention that the controversy was ``overblown.'' She also noted
that another statement by Gore about Love Canal provided the
context for the misquote. ``The vice president clearly said, 'I
found a little town in upstate New York called Love Canal','' she
said. ``And the vice president has never disputed that quote.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly, reluctantly agreeing to discuss the matter last week _
``I don't generally want to be a part of a story,'' she explained _
insisted that ``the one word did not change the context that the
vice president had claimed to have found Love Canal.''
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed out that Gore had apologized for causing a
misunderstanding, ``a rare occurrence with the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pride, editor of the Concord Monitor, which helped
publicize the reporting error, said last week that ``in an age in
which this morning's newspaper account is tonight's talk-show
ridicule, the premium on accuracy is higher than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Gore's appearance at Concord High, late-night
comedian David Letterman issued his ``Top Ten Other Achievements
Claimed By Al Gore'' _ ``No. 1, Gave Mankind Fire.''
</P>
<P>
   The coverage of Gore's visit prompted the students in Joanne
McGlynn's English class at Concord High to issue their own press
release under the heading: ``Top 10 Reasons Why Many Concord High
Students Feel Betrayed by Some of the Media Coverage of Al Gore's
Visit to Their School.''
</P>
<P>
   Her students are ``still charged up about how things are
covered'' by the media, McGlynn said in a telephone interview from
her school last week. ``They're concerned, but they aren't cynical
... yet.''
</P>
<P>
   McGlynn said that while Gore had intended to caution her
students about cynicism, ``It was troubling to see that message get
lost because the press is so cynical about politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They hear him telling that story totally as self-aggrandizing
because that's the story they are ready to hear about Al Gore,''
she said. ``They've got a pre-existing script about Al Gore, and so
that story fit their script.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Turque, a Newsweek correspondent and author of a new
biography, ``Inventing Al Gore,'' which includes the inaccurate
``Love Canal'' account, acknowledged that some reporters are ``on a
kind of hair trigger'' with Gore because of earlier exaggerations.
</P>
<P>
   He cited as ``falsehoods'' Gore's claims that his marijuana
smoking in the 1960s and 1970s was infrequent, that his work as a
newspaper reporter in Tennessee led to the imprisonment of two
Nashville city councilmen, that he took direct enemy fire as an
information specialist in Vietnam, and that he made very few
fund-raising telephone calls from the White House during the 1996
Clinton-Gore re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like on `Love Canal' there probably was a rush to
judgment based on some garbled quotes,'' Turque said in an
interview last week. ``But I don't think we're being unfair. What
happens is when you establish a reputation like that, all the
little stuff sticks to you that you might have gotten a pass on if
all this other stuff hadn't happened.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Somerby claims that Gore is subjected to a different standard
than the other presidential candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Somerby cites the example of McCain, heralded for his honesty
with reporters riding his ``Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus.
</P>
<P>
   ``McCain was lying straight to their faces that he didn't know
about the Catholic Voter Alert,'' Somerby said, referring to the
McCain-financed organization that was calling Republican voters
with allegations of anti-Catholic bias against Bush during the GOP
primary. ``Meanwhile, they're sifting through 25-year-old letters
Gore wrote to see if they can find some comma out of place, because
the theme on Gore is, Gore makes up things, but McCain is a
straight shooter.''
</P>
<P>
   Somerby said he does not object to criticism of Gore, even from
the Republican National Committee (RNC), which sends faxes to
newsrooms around the country repeating some of the inaccuracies
about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In the `Love Canal' case, the RNC actually changed the Gore
misquote to make it grammatically correct. The RNC fax quoted Gore
as saying, ``I was the one who started it all,'' along with an
analysis from RNC Chairman Jim Nicholson: ``It's a pattern of
phoniness _ and it would be funny if it weren't also a little
scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Yu, an RNC spokesman, defended the RNC's action. ``We
worked off what was reported and we stand by our statement,'' Yu
said last week. ``Al Gore got caught trying to rewrite history. He
did not find a place in upstate New York called Love Canal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is it not news that factually inaccurate press releases
are coming out every day and are being written up in major
papers?'' Somerby asked. ``Isn't it the normal process of the press
to sift through everything for accuracy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be,'' said Bob Parry, editor of the investigative
magazine American Dispatches and author of a recent Washington
Monthly cover article, ``He's No Pinocchio: How the Press Has
Exaggerated Al Gore's Exaggerations.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But Journalism 101, especially in political coverage, has been
replaced by journalism that values entertainment above all else,''
Parry said in an interview last week. Parry is and editor of a Web
site, www.consortiumnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lyons, an Arkansas columnist and author of the book ``Fools
For Scandal,'' a scathing critique of the Washington press coverage
of the Clinton presidency, is just as critical of the Gore
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reporting the news is not enough,'' Lyons said from Little
Rock in a telephone interview last week. ``You've got to be seen to
be witty. You've got to say things cleverly. And you've got to
assert your superiority to the politicians.''
</P>
<P>
   He also suggested that celebrity journalists ``achieve a
unanimity'' of views because ``they don't have time to do their own
work any more, they're so busy running from one TV station to the
next.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Somerby plans the next edition of The Daily Howler
with no illusions that anything in Washington is going to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Washington press corps is where comedy was, say, 12 years
ago _ it's cool to be negative and dark,'' he said. ``But the
comedy world almost killed itself 12 years ago with all that Andrew
Dice Clay negativity. And that's why people are tuning politics
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   (For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
