<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8804 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISONS-THE-BOX-2NDTA     04-06 1236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-THE-BOX-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALBANY, N.Y.: xxx numbing sameness. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A prisoner is allowed to leave the main box for one hour each
morning for ``recreation'' in an empty 9-by-7-foot caged balcony
attached to the back of The Box. There are no programs, educational
or otherwise. If SHU prisoners complain or don't follow the rules,
they may get additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   SHU prisoners say they are being treated like animals.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, some animals kept in laboratories for scientific
research have more room. A pig, for instance, must be provided at
least 36 square feet of living space under Food and Drug
Administration regulations.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to research swine, New York's SHU prisoners share
about 60 square feet of usable open floor space in The Box. That is
30 square feet per man _ about 16 percent less floor space than
federal regulations require for pigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general impression is that this is the old hole,'' Goord
said. ``This is not the old hole. Our new cells are very large.
They have a window and an outside area.''
</P>
<P>
   New York's SHUs meet the accreditation standards of the American
Correctional Association (ACA), a prison industry group in Maryland
to which all 50 states and several foreign countries belong,
according to Robert Verdeyen, director of standards and
accreditation for the ACA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't find New York's number of SHU beds out of line,''
Verdeyen said. ``Several courts in the U.S. have held that people
placed in solitary confinement in SHUs that are accredited by us
and follow our standards meet the constitutional minimum.''
</P>
<P>
   Human-rights groups are working to reduce the burgeoning number
of prisoners confined to SHUs in New York and other states, which
they claim is unconstitutional and a form of torture in United
Nations declarations that the United States has signed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This amounts to cruel and inhuman punishment, which is
unconstitutional, and it falls under the international standard of
torture,'' said Angela Wright, an Amnesty International official in
London who is the group's leading researcher on the
maximum-security prisons in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Even some correction officials are dubious about over-reliance
on The Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel there are only a small number of individuals for whom
the high security of super-max prisons is necessary for defensible
reasons,'' said Chase Riveland, former secretary of the Department
of Corrections in Washington state. Riveland has run prisons in
three states, written extensively on correction policy and received
numerous state and national awards for his work in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this proliferation of super-max prisons is particularly
disturbing to me because it's so generally accepted by correction
officials,'' Riveland said. ``Admittance is driven by open SHU
beds. If you build them, they shall come.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once they put these young men, who are mostly black and
Hispanic, into solitary, any rehabilitation is hopeless,'' Riveland
said. ``They're locked away so tightly, they have no voice. Out of
sight, out of mind is politically attractive. Invisible prisoners
don't rile the public.''
</P>
<P>
   But Goord and his spokesman, Jim Flateau, defended the sharp
increase of 23-hour disciplinary lockdown under Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Both said the frenzy of SHU bed building was necessary to
relieve pent-up demand among unruly prisoners inadequately
segregated after a decade of soaring inmate populations and a surge
in medium-security prison construction that did not allocate enough
SHU beds.
</P>
<P>
   Goord called SHU cells ``an effective management tool'' that has
helped achieve a decline in prison violence in the past few years.
Inmate-on-staff assaults have dropped 25 percent, from 960 in 1995
to 630 incidents last year. There were similar reported decreases
in inmate-on-inmate assault and in the rate of inmate possession of
weapons, the commissioner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking the bad actors out of the general population and
it's getting results,'' Flateau said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll compare my rate of staff injuries and inmate injuries to
any state or federal prison in the country,'' Goord said. ``I'm the
person responsible for controlling violence and creating a safe
prison environment, and I take that responsibility very
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Among the offenses that can land a prisoner in The Box are
these: testing positive for drugs; assault of a correction officer
or another inmate; possession of a weapon; throwing feces or urine
on prison staff; conspiring to create a prison disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Being sentenced to time in The Box has nothing to do with the
violence of the crime that landed the person in prison in the first
place. Convicted murderers or inmates sentenced to life without
parole are not automatically housed in 23-hour lockdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of SHU is to teach a prisoner that if you act out
and are disruptive, you'll be locked down,'' Flateau said. ``They
knew the rules from day one, and they broke them.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say prisoners are placed in confinement for increasingly
minor infractions. Interviews with more than a dozen SHU prisoners
and their families revealed a pattern of confinement for what
inmates claimed were minor incidents ranging from arguments with
correction officers to the lockdown of a group allegedly involved
in a ``Y2K protest'' leading up to New Year's Day. The protest
involved eating in silence in the mess hall and wearing prison
greens in place of civilian clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into nonsensical claims from inmates,''
Flateau said. ``There's no such thing as a nonviolent demonstration
in prison. The smallest thing could turn it violent.''
</P>
<P>
   Some critics disagree with that argument. ``Our studies show
that many super-max prisoners are not dangerous. They're perceived
as a threat, so they're locked down,'' said James Austin,
co-director of the Institute on Crime, Justice and Corrections at
George Washington University in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Austin criticized New York and other states that lack a clearly
defined criteria for why prisoners are placed in disciplinary
lockdown and a uniform standard for how much time each infraction
gets in The Box. Furthermore, Austin said, states typically have
only internal review for SHU cases, with no outside scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But Goord said he was comfortable with the review and appeal
process for SHU inmates. The policies of New York's SHUs, bolstered
by case law, also appear to be supported by the correction staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``SHUs have kept the rest of the system safe,'' said Art
Leonardo, a retired prison superintendent at three New York
correctional facilities who spent 32 years working in the state's
prisons. ``I think New York's SHU system is as fair and as humane
as it can be.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless somebody comes up with a better solution to solve the
problem of a violent person who's a threat to the staff or other
inmates, I think the SHU beds should continue to grow,'' said Ted
Flegel, a retired officer at the Coxsackie Correctional Facility.
Flegel spent 25 of his 38 years at Coxsackie assigned to the SHU
there.
</P>
<P>
   Flegel described being knocked unconscious in an inmate melee,
being spit upon by inmates and being hit with excrement hurled at
him by prisoners. ``We need the SHU to control those kinds of guys.
It's a deterrent to keep them straight,'' Flegel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
