<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8805 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISONS-THE-BOX-2TAKE     04-06 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-THE-BOX-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK REDEFINES SOLITARY CONFINEMENT WITH GROWING USE OF
`THE BOX' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: With: PRISONS-BOX-LIFE and PRISONS-UN)  
 &HT;     (ATTN: N.Y., Wash.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Prisoners call it The Box.
</P>
<P>
   It is a kind of hermetically sealed netherworld, devoid of
outside contact. In New York and elsewhere across the country,
thousands of inmates languish in cells isolated from the general
prison population, locked down for 23 hours a day for months or
even years.
</P>
<P>
   There is no thought of rehabilitation. This is segregation and
removal from human society for prisoners the authorities say need
discipline that ordinary imprisonment does not provide.
</P>
<P>
   The prefabricated, high-tech cellblocks, operated from a central
console station, are eerily efficient. It amounts to incarceration
by remote control.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the world is The Box used more than in the United
States. Nowhere in America is it used more than in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups, including the Nobel Peace Prize-winning
Amnesty International, say such imprisonment meets the definition
of torture under international law. Prison watchdog organizations
claim it violates the 8th Amendment of the U.S. Constitution, which
prohibits cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In New York _ the state that introduced solitary confinement to
North America in the early 1800s _ nearly 5,700 prisoners are
confined to 23-hour disciplinary lockdown in what prison officials
often call special housing units, or SHUs. That amounts to roughly
8 percent of the state's 72,000 inmates, a reliance on The Box that
is four times the national average of about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The number of prisoners confined to specially designed SHU cells
has more than doubled in the five years since George Pataki, a
Republican, became governor.
</P>
<P>
   But the public knows little about this forgotten population.
Many of these prisoners are isolated in distant reaches of the
state. Access by the press and other prison watchdog groups is
generally blocked.
</P>
<P>
   For some of New York's inmates, lockdown has become a way of
life.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are deemed to pose an ongoing threat of violence to
the prison staff or other inmates, about 150 prisoners have been
confined to 23-hour lockdown for more than five years. A handful of
inmates have spent more than 15 years in these disciplinary cells.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, to save on the huge cost of prison
construction, New York has become one of the first states to
segregate two inmates together in The Box. The unorthodox move _
which prison officials call double-bunking _ changes the definition
of solitary confinement. In the aftermath of the recent choking
death of an inmate after a fight with his cellmate in The Box and
another fatality following the forcible removal of an inmate, new
concerns about the policy are being voiced.
</P>
<P>
   But state and federal court decisions so far have upheld New
York's prison policies regarding disciplinary lockdown. State
officials say the prisoners have brought the punishment on
themselves by bad behavior behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was their action that put them in prison and it was their
action that made me take them out of the prison community itself,''
said Glenn S. Goord, commissioner of the New York state Department
of Correctional Services (DOCS).
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to protect staff and other inmates. That's what I
want to be known for,'' Goord said. ``I don't feel our use of SHUs
is excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   But the recent SHU building spree, in New York and elsewhere,
has energized critics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Super-max confinement is an abomination,'' said Hans Toch,
professor of criminal justice at the State University of New York
at Albany. ``Emotionally disturbed prisoners are over-represented
in super-max. The proliferation of these prisons is happening all
over the country, and it's not a development of which we can be
very proud.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 40 super maximum-security prisons have been built in
the United States in the last decade. They now hold more than
23,000 prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki plans to continue the growth trend in New York. A $180
million, 750-cell maximum-security prison with all the SHU
high-tech hardware, now being built in Seneca County, southeast of
Rochester, could easily be converted into an SHU facility for 1,500
prisoners. In his current budget proposal, Pataki has asked for
another $180 million to build a similar prison.
</P>
<P>
   That could allow the number of prisoners in The Box to grow by
another 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to other states that have only solitary cells _ that
is, holding one prisoner _ New York's recent policy of
double-bunking inmates in The Box is unusual. But double-bunking
lowers construction costs by packing twice as many prisoners into
half the space.
</P>
<P>
   Two recent deaths among SHU inmates have not caused the
correction commissioner to re-evaluate the double-bunking issue.
``Of course I have concerns,'' Goord said. ``Those were unfortunate
deaths. I'm in a risk business. Is there a risk with two people in
a cell? Yes. But thousands of inmates have gone through double
cells successfully.''
</P>
<P>
   Goord said he believed that the rate of violence such as assault
in double-bunked SHU cells is no higher than in single-bed SHU
cells.
</P>
<P>
   In New York The Box measures about 14 feet by 8 feet. It
contains two beds, a desk, a shower, a sink and toilet. Prisoners
sleep, eat, defecate and shower in The Box. And little else. There
is no variation from day to day. Prisoners who have been there say
the months blur into a grinding, numbing sameness.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
