<SLUG> BC-EAST-WEST-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST-WEST ROAD LEADS TO NOWHERE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
 
 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``East-West'' is a movie that many predicted would win the Oscar
for best foreign film last month. It didn't, losing to Pedro
Almodovar's ``All About My Mother,'' and voters can take comfort in
having done the right thing. ``East-West'' certainly has good
intentions, and it's easy to see why it was nominated. That doesn't
mean it's a good movie, however. It is the type of foreign film
that the academy inexplicably likes to honor _ sweeping, stolid,
somber and, most of all, somnolent.
</P>
<P>
   The movie follows a group of people who could charitably be
called idealists, although it's hard to avoid being constantly
reminded of their naivete. In June 1946, Stalin offered Russian
emigrants amnesty and invited them back to the motherland to help
rebuild the Soviet Union. That was the offer, anyway. But _
surprise, surprise _ Stalin lied. Most of the emigrants who
returned were sent to forced labor camps. Some were shot on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei (Oleg Menchikov), a doctor, along with his French wife,
Marie (Sandrine Bonnaire), and their young son escape the fate of
the gulags. But life isn't exactly beautiful. Alexei is assigned to
an infirmary of a textile factory in Kiev, and he and his family
live in a rat-infested communal apartment along with five other
families.
</P>
<P>
   Marie hates her new life and determines that they must return to
France.
</P>
<P>
   Alexei agrees in an intellectual way, but he's not a man blessed
with much backbone or boldness. Marie realizes she must take
matters into her own hands, and when a French theater group comes
to town, she daringly contacts an actress (Catherine Deneuve),
hoping to alert French authorities to her family's plight.
</P>
<P>
   ``East-West'' continues on, with assorted melodramatic subplots
and a story that takes decades to play out (and it almost feels
like real time, as you're sitting there, half-awake, in the
theater). Director and co-writer Regis Wargnier is obviously trying
to create a serious saga in the vein of his Oscar-winning
``Indochine,'' but this film lacks the story, the pretty pictures
and the strong central performance that made ``Indochine'' at least
watchable.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnaire does her best as the sympathetic heroine, but the
supporting characters are mostly caricatures, particularly the
Soviet officials, who seem to have stepped out of a Cold War comic
book. This is hardly the stuff of moving drama, much less of a film
that somehow found itself nominated for an Oscar.________ &QL; 
The film: ``East-West'' (PG-13; violence, brief sensuality.) &QL; 
The stars: Sandrine Bonnaire, Oleg Menchikov, Serguei Bodrov Jr.,
Catherine Deneuve. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Regis Wargnier. Screenplay by
Wargnier, Roustam Ibraguimbekov, Serguei Bodrov, Louis Gardel.
Released by Sony Pictures Classics. &QL; 
Running time: Two hours, one minute &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
