<HEADLINE>
&HT;     INNOCENT MAN REMAINS ENTRAPPED BY EXPERIENCE BEHIND BARS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Ariz., Okla.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 21 years on death row in the Arizona state prison system,
14 of them in a solitary confinement cell measuring 6 feet by 7
feet, Paris Carriger was left with a mind and a body eroded by the
ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   His muscle tone gone from neglect, Carriger left prison in a
wheelchair. He suffers from paranoid delusions, unable to focus
beyond an animallike instinct to survive that particular day. He
can't hold a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ex-death row is distinctly unemployable,'' Carriger said in a
telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Carriger, now 55 and living in Oklahoma, was released in January
1999 after a review of his case and a re-trial that found him
innocent and set him free.
</P>
<P>
   Free to what?
</P>
<P>
   ``My attorneys couldn't understand why I didn't rejoice when I
won,'' Carriger said. ``I had no emotional connection to it. My
emotions had atrophied along with my ability to walk after 14 years
in solitary.''
</P>
<P>
   During those many years, Carriger was allowed out of his cell
for one hour three times per week during which, in shackles and
under guard, he could shower and exercise in a ``dog pen'' at the
end of his cellblock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gradually lost my ability to manufacture hope,'' Carriger
said.
</P>
<P>
   Several times, Carriger came within an eyelash of being put to
death before his attorneys managed to secure a stay of execution.
Thoughts of suicide frequently floated through his consciousness,
but he lacked the equipment or the will to act upon them.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my head, I was preparing to be executed. It seemed like a
good idea, because the pain would be over,'' Carriger said. ``Each
time they backed away, I had to go on antidepressants to try to
reorient my thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Carriger said the only ``humanizing effect'' during his time on
death row arrived in the form of letters from four women, whose
devotion to Carriger and attention to his case was described in an
April 19, 1999, article in The New Yorker magazine.
</P>
<P>
   He shunned visits. ``I didn't want my people to see me the way I
was,'' Carriger said.
</P>
<P>
   Carriger wrote his own account, ``Requiem for Justice,''
published recently in Contemporary Justice Review. The quarterly,
which focuses on restorative justice, is edited by Dennis Sullivan
of Voorheesville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Carriger wrote: ``In the course of 21 years, I have been stabbed
half a dozen times, burned once, punched more than I can remember.
I once sat in the dark in my cell waiting for a man who had already
stabbed me to come back and try to finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past year of freedom, Carriger has remained on the move.
``I don't stay inside any more than I have to,'' he said. ``The
best thing is being able to open the door when I want.''
</P>
<P>
   Carriger exists on disability benefits from Social Security, and
asked that the name of the town where he lives in Oklahoma not be
published. ``I buy and sell in yard sales to pay for gas,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Carriger avoids tightly enclosed spaces. ``I find myself
huddling close to the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in solitary teaches you to be wary, that the rest of the
world is unsafe, Carriger said. ``I wasn't physically touched for
21 years unless someone was attacking me or putting on or taking
off handcuffs,'' he said. ``I ended up losing my human instinct for
touch. I became this cocoon being, totally shut down and
isolated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
