<HEADER>
A8811 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISONS-HISTORY-HNS &LR;      04-06 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-HISTORY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     SOLITARY CONFINEMENT IN U.S. DATES TO EARLY 1800s  
 &HT;     (EDS: With PRISONS-PUNISHMENT)  
 &HT;     (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Solitary confinement in the New York state prison system dates
to the early 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   In 1816, state officials built a new prison complex in Auburn,
Cayuga County, where harsh and experimental correctional tactics
were tested. The state Legislature enacted more punitive prison
legislation in 1819, allowing Auburn's prison officials to place
inmates in solitary confinement with a diet of bread and water, to
use irons or stocks and to whip any male inmate who violated prison
rules with as many as 39 lashes.
</P>
<P>
   (Auburn's female inmates, while subjected to solitary
confinement in some cases, were supposed to be protected from
floggings, although documented abuses occurred.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1821, a new solitary confinement wing was opened at Auburn.
Each cell held a single prisoner and measured 7 feet long and 3{
feet wide, with 7-foot ceilings. On Christmas Day that year, 80
convicts were moved to the new wing. These were the most
``hardened'' prisoners under Auburn's classification system.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Christianson chronicled these developments at the Auburn
prison in his 1998 book, ``With Liberty For Some: 500 Years of
Imprisonment in America.'' Christianson, who lives in Rensselaer
County, wrote: ``Held in complete isolation, monitored day and
night to keep them from communicating with anyone except the
chaplain, they remained idle and alone in their dark cells and were
even prevented from lying down in daytime, presumably to prevent
muscular atrophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The first 80 inmates were placed in isolation cells at Auburn on
Christmas Day 1821. By New Year's Day, 1823, out of Auburn's 80
solitary confinement inmates, at least five had died of consumption
and 41 were seriously ill, according to Christianson.
</P>
<P>
   Others went insane. When one convict's cell was opened, he
sprang out and leaped from the fourth floor to his death. Another
bashed his head against the cell wall until he destroyed one of his
eyes. Another slashed his veins with a piece of tin and bled to
death.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Gov. Joseph C. Yates visited Auburn prison, was
said to be horrified by the conditions, and pardoned some survivors
of the solitary confinement experiment on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown on Auburn's prisoners thus halted by Yates wasn't
America's first foray into isolation cells.
</P>
<P>
   Solitary was used during the early 1800s in Pennsylvania
penitentiaries as part of a prison reform movement led by the
Quakers, who believed that forced isolation would allow
contemplation and, ultimately, repentance and rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dickens visited Eastern Penitentiary in Philadelphia in
1842 and wrote: ``The system here is rigid, strict, and hopeless
solitary confinement. I believe it, in its effects, to be cruel and
wrong. ... I am persuaded that those who devised this system of
Prison Discipline, and those benevolent gentlemen who carry it into
execution, do not know what it is that they are doing. ... I hold
this slow and daily tampering with the mysteries of the brain, to
be immeasurably worse than any torture of the body ... a secret
punishment which slumbering humanity is not roused up to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickens' report and other negative reviews roused public opinion
against this form of punishment. Solitary confinement never
entirely disappeared from the prison landscape, although its use in
New York for the next century and a half was limited to a small
number of ``problem inmates'' who assaulted or killed other
prisoners or correction staff.
</P>
<P>
   This long period of stasis regarding the use of solitary
confinement was radically altered in the past three years, when
Gov. George Pataki approved the construction of more than 3,000 new
23-hour lockdown disciplinary beds _ doubling the previous
capacity. Pataki, a Republican, also curbed construction costs by
allowing double-bunking (two inmates per isolation cell), an
unorthodox form of lockdown that New York was the first to try.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
