<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-JUDGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     EX-JUDGE LEARNS ABOUT `THE HOLE' FROM HIS OWN PRISON TERM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Sol Wachtler wrote court decisions on solitary
confinement. He also spent a month himself in what he calls ``the
hole.'' That gives him a unique position to assess this form of
incarceration.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1997 book, ``After The Madness: A Judge's Own Prison
Memoir,'' the former chief judge of the state of New York _ who was
convicted in federal court for harassing his ex-mistress _ quoted
from a diary he kept while confined to an isolation cell in a
medium-security federal prison in Butner, N.C., for what he was
told was mental health observation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I write this entry from the hole. Soon the light will go out,
and I will hear the banging on the doors and the cries for help.
Because the dog man is still here, the barking has already begun.
... Days have a way of running together when you're in solitary
confinement. ... I seem to spend most of my time staring at the
ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler, now 69, conceded a ``breathless fear of being sealed
alive in a coffin, unable to breathe.'' He also wrote: ``There is
no chair or table in my cell, so I eat sitting on the steel shelf
which I will use for a bed, using my lap for a table. I feel
aboriginal.''
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler was placed in solitary for observation and
administrative segregation.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview from his home on Long Island,
where Wachtler teaches at the Jacob D. Fuchsberg Law Center of
Touro College, the ex-convict and ex-chief judge of the New York
Court of Appeals reflected on solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler recalled writing a Court of Appeals opinion in the
mid-1980s in the case Wilkinson vs. Skinner, in which an inmate
sued a county sheriff for a five-day solitary confinement the
inmate claimed constituted ``cruel and unusual punishment,'' thus
prohibited by the Eighth Amendment to the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler wrote for the court: ``Merely confining an inmate in a
segregated cell does not constitute cruel and unusual punishment.
There are, of course, some cells that are so subhuman as to
constitute such punishment even for a very brief confinement. One
day in some cells might be constitutionally intolerable.''
Wachtler's opinion prevailed, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know how prophetic that opinion was,'' Wachtler said.
</P>
<P>
   His weeks in solitary only solidified that position. ``What
happens to you in the hole defies description,'' Wachtler said.
``You have to have been there to understand.''
</P>
<P>
   Based upon his own experiences and those related to him by other
inmates, Wachtler said solitary confinement _ a tool correction
officials contend helps them maintain discipline among inmates
difficult to control _ is frequently abused.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw guys put in the hole for making fun of a guard, for
having a radio with somebody else's initials in their locker and a
lot of minor infractions,'' Wachtler said. ``It's a system of
discipline administered peremptorily and without appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   He witnessed harassment and abuse by guards, but inmates were
afraid of reporting it for fear of retribution. ``If you're in the
hole and complain, they'll double your time in the hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler, who is writing a book on prison reform, said the
method of assigning solitary confinement needs an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   He advocates a system that would allow inmates to appeal
solitary confinement sentences and file complaints of abuse to an
objective oversight committee that would ensure inmate
confidentiality.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler also would like to see more care for mentally ill
inmates in solitary. ``Many inmates had trouble coping with reality
when they were in the real world. Imagine how much more
dysfunctional solitary makes them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachtler advocates these changes to solitary confinement policy:
</P>
<P>
   _ Physical inspection without notice by prison watchdog groups.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inspectors allowed to deliver sealed, confidential reviews of
their findings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restrictions on the use and duration of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Immediate moratorium on placing two inmates in a single cell
in isolation, as New York does, which Wachtler labels ``totally
inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   The long isolation confinements in New York, some lasting a few
years, ``constitute cruel and inhuman punishment'' and should be
ruled unconstitutional, according to Wachtler.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a long period in isolation, these people come out 10
times worse than when they went in,'' the former judge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
