<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GOD'S MISSION LEADS TO BURNOUT IN PRISON `BOX' 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COXSACKIE, N.Y. _ The Rev. Joe Romano could detect it first in
the eyes of inmates.
</P>
<P>
   It might take a few weeks or a few months, but there was a
defining moment when the mostly youthful prisoners in isolation
units regressed into something less than human.
</P>
<P>
   ``The light went out in their eyes,'' said Romano, a retired
Roman Catholic prison chaplain. ``They became like zombies. I'd
talk to them through the food slot, and all I got back was a blank
stare.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours each day at New York state's Greene Correctional
Facility, Romano pushed a cart with rosaries, books and spiritual
reading material. He would go from cell to cell in the special
housing unit (SHU), where 200 inmates are confined two per cell.
The SHU, what inmates call The Box, was added to the prison in the
spring of 1998, replacing a 15-cell isolation unit.
</P>
<P>
   What Romano witnessed among these young men _ more than half of
the 1,700 inmates at Greene, a medium-security prison in Coxsackie
in Greene County, are between the ages of 16 and 19 _ caused the
cleric deep despair. Ultimately, he said, it hastened his
retirement last November after 15 years of prison work.
</P>
<P>
   On rare occasions, Romano grimly watched the prison's response
team storm the SHU in ``uniforms like Darth Vader,'' led by
correction officers who ``got their jollies by beating guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The drill was known as ``breaking a cell.'' It was used on
prisoners who _ in protest or by reason of loss of mental reasoning
_ refused to come out of their cell at the end of their SHU
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, Romano was successful in talking an inmate into
coming out voluntarily just before the response team prepared to
swarm the tight confines in riot gear while lobbing tear gas into
the cell.
</P>
<P>
   More commonly, Romano's were the broad shoulders these young
felons cried upon. ``Please tell my family where I am,'' was a
typical tearful plea, Romano said. Since they were denied access to
a phone, computer or other instant communications (letters are
permitted), it often fell to Romano to break the news of deaths or
family emergencies to the inmates in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent a lot of time trying to console scared kids who cried
and cried,'' Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Romano sometimes tried to intervene and demand reassignments for
young prisoners who complained to the priest of being sexually
abused by ``booty bandits'' _ bigger, older men who acted as sexual
predators against weaker cellmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday experience in the SHU was pretty awful for these
kids,'' Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things he saw:
</P>
<P>
   _ Attempted suicides.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sexual assaults.
</P>
<P>
   _ Nude inmates lolling on the floor, openly masturbating.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inmate self-mutilation with names, swastikas and other symbols
carved into their bodies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Smearing and throwing of feces and urine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inmates unresponsive and catatonic.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inmates in psychotic rages, ranting obscenities and banging
heads on walls.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inmates sleeping naked on cement floors to combat sweltering
summer heat without air-conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation in these young lives inside was startling.
Romano described an angry, loud vitality in the general inmate
population at Greene. After a few weeks in The Box, though, that
life force seeped out from the inmates as inevitably as air from a
punctured balloon.
</P>
<P>
   And with it, Romano's own passion for attempting to reform young
criminals evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a priest, and we're in the forgiveness business,'' said
Romano, 60, who now is assistant pastor of Saint Catherine of Siena
Church in Albany. ``The SHU is only about punishment and breaking
down these guys. There's nothing about forgiveness or
rehabilitation.''
</P>
<P>
   Romano's affable personality and knowledge of the ways of the
streets seemed to help earn him the respect of inmates. ``I never
felt I was a savior,'' Romano said. ``If I helped one of these guys
a little, I thought I'd done OK. That's what saved my sanity
working on the SHU.''
</P>
<P>
   The inmates weren't the only tortured souls on the SHUs. ``Being
a C.O. is a horribly stressful and difficult job,'' Romano said,
using an abbreviation for correction officer. He counseled officers
about problems that plagued them disproportionately, including
alcoholism, depression and domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   In his 15 years at Greene Correctional Facility, Romano talked
drunk and despondent correction officers out of committing suicide
_ twice literally removing loaded guns from the hands of officers
preparing to take their own lives. Six officers finished the
suicide attempts and killed themselves during his tenure there,
Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Romano blames much of the human wreckage he observed on The Box.
The priest did what he could to alleviate the despair by delivering
communion wafers through the cells' food slots, distributing books
donated by parishioners and starting a Bible studies program.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 100-cell SHU was monitored by audio and video
equipment and inmates were loathe to participate in the Catholic
sacrament of confession, Romano lobbied for and won the right to
hear confession through two-way field phones that maintained some
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These guys were starved for anything that gave them hope,''
Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, old divisions conspired against Romano's ministry.
Greene's inmate population is about 60 percent black, 30 percent
Hispanic and 10 percent white. Allegiances to street gangs don't
end at the prison walls.
</P>
<P>
   Romano, who speaks Spanish, was accepted by Hispanic inmates,
particularly the Latin Kings gang, a powerful force in the prison.
The Latin Kings and other Hispanic gangs openly warred with rival
black gangs, The Bloods and The Crips.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Romano had to offer two Masses on Saturday nights _ one
on the north side of prison and the other on the south side _ to
keep feuding gangs physically separated. When they clashed, the
result was ``cuttings,'' prison slang for disfiguring and sometimes
serious slashings with homemade shanks.
</P>
<P>
   One Saturday night last summer, after a sermon on forgiveness
based on the Scripture readings for the Mass, the futility of his
prison ministry was driven home to Romano.
</P>
<P>
   An inmate was at Greene for killing a young man on the streets
of the Bronx. The murdered man's brother was sent to Greene for a
different crime. The convicted killer attended Romano's Mass and,
unknowingly, sat next to the brother of his victim. The two even
exchanged the handshake of peace, Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   After Mass, the victim's brother sidled up to his brother's
murderer and, according to witnesses, muttered a sentiment of
forgiveness in cynical reference to Romano's sermon. Then he
slashed the fellow inmate's throat, face and chest.
</P>
<P>
   The recipient of the cutting narrowly escaped bleeding to death
on the spot. After 119 stitches and surgery, the prisoner
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That did it for me. I couldn't take any more,'' Romano said.
``I was burned out, and it was time to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
