<HEADER>
A8814 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISONS-PSYCHIATRIST-     04-06 0555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-PSYCHIATRIST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HARVARD PSYCHIATRIST DEPLORES LIFE IN SOLITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dr. Stuart Grassian never set out to become the country's
leading expert on the psychological effects of long-term solitary
confinement on prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The Harvard Medical School professor, who practices psychiatry
in the Boston area, came to dominate the literature on the topic by
default. ``I was shocked to find out that the prison psychiatrists
who were supposed to be doing this job weren't, so I got
involved,'' Grassian said.
</P>
<P>
   Grassian's 1979 study of prisoners confined to 23-hour lockdown
in special housing units (SHUs) coined the term ``SHU syndrome''
and its attendant symptoms of mental illness: depression, increased
paranoia, agitation, manic activity, delusions, florid psychotic
illness and suicide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a psychological toxicity among solitary confinement
in super-max prisons,'' Grassian said by phone from Boston. ``These
places are breeding grounds for mental illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Super maximum-security refers to the punitive 23-hour
disciplinary lockdowns where prisoners have few or no privileges.
</P>
<P>
   Grassian discussed New York state's early 19th-century
experiments with solitary confinement at Auburn prison as
``undertaken with the best of intentions and open to public
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1830s, however, Auburn's experiment was dropped because
of ``a high rate of catastrophic incidents of psychiatric illness
and death,'' according to Grassian. Soon, solitary confinement fell
out of favor in New York and across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past 20 years _ despite extensive federal research on
the psychologically harmful effects of solitary confinement on
prisoners of war _ state prison systems around the country have
built at a furious pace prisons dedicated to isolating and
punishing inmates in 23-hour disciplinary lockdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a horrendous development,'' Grassian said. Moreover,
prison officials in New York and elsewhere are ``systematically
denying the psychiatric problems'' and refuse press access or
public scrutiny of SHU conditions.
</P>
<P>
   To save on the huge cost of prison construction, New York has
become one of the first states to segregate two inmates together in
super maximum-security cells that prisoners derisively call The
Box.
</P>
<P>
   During two decades, Grassian has evaluated hundreds of SHU
prisoners in a dozen states.
</P>
<P>
   Grassian wrote an extensive follow-up report on the Attica,
N.Y., SHU last fall in which he concluded: ``The psychiatric
evaluation and periodic monitoring of mentally ill Attica SHU
inmates are grossly inadequate; seriously mentally ill inmates
continue to be housed in SHU, and often psychiatrically deteriorate
as a result of the stringent conditions of confinement prevailing
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Grassian said prisoners who act out or can't comply with rules
in the general prison population likely suffer from mild forms of
mental illness to begin with. Those psychiatric problems deepen and
become profoundly dangerous during long months, even years, in the
isolation of SHUs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're taking sick people and making them sicker,'' Grassian
said. ``Mentally ill people need treatment, not disciplinary
punishment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
