<HEADER>
A8816 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-PRISONS-BOX-LIFE-2NDT     04-06 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-BOX-LIFE-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; COXSACKIE, N.Y.: other SHU cellblocks. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Your inmate handbook details SHU rules. Cells must be kept neat
and clean at all times. Any markings in the cell or affixing any
articles to the walls is punishable by additional time in The Box.
Wet towels may not be hung from the bunks; they may be hung to dry
only from the second rung of the bunk bed ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates will be issued one paper drinking cup. The cup will only
be exchanged if necessary during morning rounds. Possession of
cups, trays and utensils after food tray pickup will be considered
contraband. That is punishable by additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   Lights are turned on at 6 a.m. and turned off at 11 p.m. daily
in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   You are not allowed to make telephone calls. To contact the
outside world, you may write some letters. You slide outgoing
letters under the cell door before lights out at night. If you have
no money in your inmate account, you must wait 30 days until you
are issued postage. You will be given one 33-cent stamp each month
if you have no money in your account. If you attempt to wash off
canceled stamp marks or illegally reuse stamps, you may be punished
by additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after 6 a.m., two COs on rounds will gather the mail
from the cellblock corridor and slide back under the cell door a
corresponding amount of paper and envelopes. There is no mail
delivery on Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   You are not permitted to wear a watch. You will learn to mark
time by the rhythms of your SHU day. Shifts change at 7 a.m. and
new COs come on duty. A CO escorts a nurse who makes rounds
beginning at 7 a.m. to check on inmates who filled out a sick call
request slip the night before.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m., you will hear other inmates rousing, washing up,
getting dressed and waiting at their cell door for breakfast. COs
bring around the food trays between 7 and 8 a.m. If you oversleep
and are not waiting at the food tray slot to receive your food, the
CO will pass by your cell and you will not eat.
</P>
<P>
   You will learn to eat quickly. The COs come back around in about
15 minutes to collect the empty trays, milk cartons and plastic
``sporks'' _ a single utensil combining a spoon and the tines of a
fork. Failure to return immediately any of these items will
constitute contraband, punishable by additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   At 8:30 a.m., the console officer will make an announcement over
loudspeakers that it is recreation time. You will go to the back
door and be ready to open it when the console officer
electronically unlocks all doors leading to the caged balcony. The
doors will remain unlocked for one hour, until 9:30 a.m. In the
case of double-bunked cells, inmates alternate one-hour shifts in
the caged balcony and the doors are locked down at 10:30 a.m. The
console officer will watch you on video monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Any attempt to prop open the door beyond the one-hour allowable
recreation time will be detected by electronic surveillance and is
punishable by additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   You go back inside your cell until lunch. Line up at your cell
door. The food trays arrive between 11:30 a.m. and noon. They are
collected shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Another shift change comes at 3 p.m., signaling the arrival of a
new CO, who delivers incoming mail.
</P>
<P>
   Line up at your cell door for dinner. The food trays arrive
about 4:30 p.m. Eat quickly. Return the tray and the spork on
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Until lights out at 11 p.m., you may read or listen to the radio
with earphones on one of three stations selected by the console
officer.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you'll learn to pass the empty hours in conversation
with your bunky. Or, you may remain wary of this stranger, vigilant
to fend off his advances.
</P>
<P>
   Try not to doze or sleep too much during the day or you'll lie
awake at night, listening to the moans, rantings and pounding of
agitated inmates. There are six cells for psychiatric observation
in the medical wing adjacent to the SHU.
</P>
<P>
   You will look forward to your three shower days each week. In
the morning, during recreation time, the console officer will make
an announcement when the showers will be turned on. You and your
bunky will alternate in the shower. The water will run for about
five minutes. There is no curtain. You will need to mop up water on
the cell floor with your towels. You may request a disposable razor
during the shower period three days each week. The razor must be
immediately returned. If it is not, or if it has been tampered
with, the infraction is punishable with additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates are allowed one haircut per month on scheduled days, if
requested. Inmates will be placed in a waist chain and handcuffs
during the haircut. Inmates will not be allowed to bring a comb or
brush.
</P>
<P>
   Each inmate will be required to clean his cell three times each
week. Inmates will be issued a sponge, toilet brush, mini-broom,
cleaning cloth and mop. Failure to return these items is punishable
by additional time in The Box.
</P>
<P>
   One day each week, inmates will receive linen exchange. Inmates
must separate greens in one net bag and whites in the other.
Clothing to be washed will be picked up at 8 p.m. on your scheduled
day and returned the following day. At that time, you will exchange
your two sheets and one pillow case for clean linen.
</P>
<P>
   Visits are allowed one day per week, either Saturday or Sunday.
Inmates are led by COs in waist chains and handcuffs to the
visiting area, where inmates are confined in caged areas and
separated from visitors by wire mesh. An inmate can bring into the
visiting area only a wedding band, religious medal and a pair of
prescription eyeglasses. No exchange of items with visitors is
allowed. Attempts are punishable by additional time in The Box.
Visitors may stay for up to five hours.
</P>
<P>
   Your time in SHU will be defined by the Progressive Inmate
Movement system (PIMs). Inmates begin at Level I, the most
restrictive, and can progress to Level II and Level III after 30
days in each level _ given proper behavior and no disciplinary
reports.
</P>
<P>
   On Level I, you are not allowed earphones or commissary
privileges. You will remain in waist chain and handcuff restraints
at all times while out of the cell, including visits.
</P>
<P>
   On Level II, your waist chain and restraints will be removed in
the visiting area. If approved, you also can enroll in a cell study
program. That means you will be able to pick two books and one
periodical from a library cart. Materials are rotated every 60
days. Swapping with your bunky doubles your reading options. You
may request up to two books or journals from the law library and
borrow them for up to 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   On Level III, you will be allowed one pair of personal sneakers
and one pair of personal shorts. You will graduate from three to
four showers per week. You will be granted an additional 30 minutes
of daily exercise in your cell's caged balcony.
</P>
<P>
   Even with a good record of behavior on Level III, however, your
parole board will take note of your lack of program involvement
during your SHU time. There are no programs offered to prisoners in
The Box. Being sent to The Box in the first place wipes out any
time off a sentence you may have accumulated for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   If your frustration over being denied parole results in breaking
any prison rules, your actions are punishable by additional time in
The Box.
</P>
</TEXT>
