<SLUG> BC-PRISONS-PUNISHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     A BATH AND A FLOG 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   These forms of punishment were used in 19th-century isolation
cells in New York state prisons, according the book ``With Liberty
for Some,'' by Scott Christianson:
</P>
<P>
   _ Arriving prisoners dumped in vats of hot, soapy water and
scrubbed with brushes to remove filth and vermin from county jail.
</P>
<P>
   _ Prison officials shaved face and heads of inmates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Inmates herded in lockstep human chain by guards with rifles
and bayonets.
</P>
<P>
   _ Discipline included floggings with bullwhips and
cat-o'-nine-tails.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cells were kept dark and inmates prevented from lying down in
daytime.
</P>
<P>
   _ No mail could be sent or received by prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   _ No family visits except in extraordinary circumstances
</P>
<P>
   _ Hard labor in prison factories, with no talking permitted.
</P>
</TEXT>
