<P>
   &UR; CUBAN BOY &LR;  (``a'' code, regardless of dateline)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Developments: Elian Gonzalez's father
arrives in Washington, pleads for his son and says they will return
together to Cuba. Officials continue talks with the Miami
relatives. By Neil A. Lewis. With photo, NYT4.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-POLITICS (Washington) _ On the debate and discussion
deep in the administration about how to go forward on the Elian
issue: hawks, doves, and those in the middle. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI (Miami) _ The scene at the house. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-ENVOY (Washington) _ On the senior Cuban diplomat, at
whose home Elian's father is staying, and the Cuban Interest
Section in Washington. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE (Washington) _ Developments on the harassment
case. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-PATIENT-RIGHTS (Washington) _ House and Senate
negotiators work on legislation to define patients' rights; they
may agree on an appeals process for patients denied care by HMO's.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS (Washington) _ Concern is rising about the lagging return
rate of the census long forms with business groups, economists
government officials saying the short fall could call into question
accuracy of government economic data like the consumer price index
and the unemployment statistics that are derived from it. By Steven
A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ George W. Bush begins a two
day swing in Calif. He seems to be hoping to do in the Golden State
what Al Gore is trying to do to him in the Sunshine State. By Frank
Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to kum) _ Gore's day. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBS-CONVENTION (Philadelphia) _ The Pennsylvania ACLU and a
coalition of civic groups are filing a lawsuit complaining that
Philadelphia's tight public assembly rules for the Republican
presidential convention violate free speech rights of protest
groups. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-POLL (New York) _ Results of the latest NYT-CBS poll
on the New York Senate race between Rudy Giuliani and Hillary
Rodham Clinton. By Adam Clymer and Marjorie Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Notes from the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG (Columbia, S.C.) _ As marchers protesting the flying of
the Confederate battle flag arrive at the state Capitol, it looks
as if a deal to remove the flag may be scuttled for another year.
Hard-core flag supporters in the legislature are digging in their
heals, to the dismay of tourist officials, the business community,
fellow Republicans and, of course, flag opponents. By David
Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   BISHOPS-RACISM (Undated) _ The bishops of Illinois issue
guidelines on how not to be racist. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ The main contenders in the race to
sequence the human genome appear before a congressional panel. By
Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-AUTISM (Washington) _ A congressional hearing is held on
autism and the issue of whether it is on the increase a debate over
whether there is any evidence that childhood vaccines cause it. By
Philip J. Hilts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Karachi) _ Ousted Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif
escaped the death penalty Thursday but was sentenced to life in
prison for refusing to allow a passenger plane carrying the army
chief to land in Pakistan, a confrontation that occurred as the
army toppled Sharif's government in October. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-WEIZMAN (Jerusalem) _ In their report to attorney
general, Israeli police do not recommend indictment of President
Ezer Weizman, but hardly exonerate him of shady dealings. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TERROR (Dateline to kum) _ Developments in the case
against terror suspect in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED-BLOOD (United Nations) _ More than two-thirds of the
world's nations fail to provide safe blood supplies, contributing
significantly to the spread of AIDS and other diseases, the World
Health Organization is to announce. The sea of tainted blood covers
4.8 billion people, about 80 percent of the world's population. By
Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SPY (Washington) _ Developments in case of an
American arrested in Moscow on spying charges. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BOURGUIBA (Undated) _ Habib Bourguiba, who was president of
Tunisia from 1957 to 1987 after leading the country to independence
from France, died Thursday. He was 96 years old and lived in
Monastir in eastern Tunisia. Bourguiba, a spectacularly durable
Arab leader, was relatively moderate and pro-Western and did much
to enhance women's rights in Tunisia. By Eric Pace.
</P>
<P>
   (This story will move in `a' news category.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Developments in the Microsoft
antitrust case. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-STRATEGY (Undated) _ Looking at what comes next in
Microsoft's strategy for the future. The company is betting on a
loosely articulated vision intended to shift its business away from
the personal computer and onto the Internet. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARGINS (Chicago) _ Looking at margin calls and their
impact on the market. Trying to get voices of small investors who
have received margin calls and how they are reacting. Developing.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were higher in mid-afternoon. The Dow
Jones industrial average was up 126 points, the S&AMP;P 500 was up 19
points and the Nasdaq composite index was up 144 points.
Biotechnology shares were extending their Wednesday gains,
bolstered by the announcement by Celera that it had decoded 99
percent of human DNA. Internet stocks like eBay, DoubleClick and
Commerce One were also up smartly. European markets were higher:
London, resuming normal trading, was up 1.25 percent and Frankfurt
up 2 percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed down 1.17 percent, while
the Hang Seng ended up 1.06 percent.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   GASOLINE-OUTLOOK (Dallas) _ A revised forecast by the Energy
Department says gasoline prices should peak later this month and
decline to an average of $1.46 a gallon for the summer. While the
average would be 25 percent higher than a year ago, it is still
lower than the average of $1.80 a gallon forecast a month ago. By
Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-GAS-ELECTRIC (Detroit) _ Ford will build a
gasoline-electric sport utility vehicle in 2003, which will get
almost 40 miles per gallon. This is the first formal announcement
of such a vehicle, although others are in the works. By Keith
Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-BANKS (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Developments in the wake of
the collapse of the Deutsche Bank-Dresdner Bank deal. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
