<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RETURN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART OF OLD-FASHIONED LOVE STORY BEATS IN CHARMING `RETURN TO
ME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whatever happened to good old-fashioned, uncomplicated romance
in the cinema? In a world of movies rife with sex, foul language
and the confusion of lust for love, ``Return to Me'' is a welcome
return to the courtship, cuddling and sweet nothings of yesteryear.
</P>
<P>
   Gifted funnywoman Bonnie Hunt's directorial debut is a flyweight
heartwarmer brimming with winning characters, but it's built around
a story so slight and predictable it's a foregone conclusion from
the first act.
</P>
<P>
   David Duchovny, the deadpan star of ``The X-Files,'' is all
smiles and charm as Bob, a successful contractor with a storybook
marriage to zoologist Elizabeth (Joely Fisher). ``I promise you
we'll see Italy,'' she pledges, dooming her in the world of
romantic tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Minnie Driver, who could charm the world in her sleep, is Grace,
a sickly girl raised by an overprotective grandpa awaiting the
heart transplant needed to save her life.
</P>
<P>
   In the most plot-stuffed opening in recent years, Bob loses his
wife in a car wreck (delicately portrayed in a restrained but
emotionally devastating sequence), Grace is the lucky recipient of
her heart, and after a year of near misses while they're absorbed
in mournful solitude and shy retreat, the strangers meet with an
instant simpatico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do we know each other?'' is no pick-up line but the
unnecessary nudging of a script reminding us that these two hearts
are fated for true love. They court like shy, sincere school kids,
nervous and giddy.
</P>
<P>
   If we didn't already know where this is going, Hunt's
sledgehammer reminders lay the destiny on thick, making more of the
heart-crossed complication than it deserves. She has little
delicacy with the architecture of plot and every meaningful moment
is spelled out in capital letters, but she saves herself with
marvelous comic instincts and a light touch with actors.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny is a Hollywood dream man: kind, sweet, funny, confident
and (as he shows in a heart-tugging breakdown of soulful sobbing in
the first act) achingly vulnerable. Driver unleashes that slow grin
that takes over her face like a sunrise but has frustratingly
little else to do: It's hard to imagine casting such a vibrant
actress as a naive wallflower, but she brings Grace to life with a
glow.
</P>
<P>
   Hunt, who also co-stars as Grace's understanding best friend,
surrounds these two star turns with a marvelous ensemble that
lazily banters and bickers like old friends and extended family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Me'' carries no surprises but floats nicely on the
simple charm of innocent romance and the good company of endearing
characters. It's not quite magic, but it'll do until the real thing
comes along.
</P>
<P>
   Return to Me. Directed by Bonnie Hunt. Screenplay by Hunt and
Don Lake. Cast: David Duchovny, Minnie Driver, Carroll O'Conner,
Robert Loggia, Bonnie Hunt, Joely Richardson, James Belushi. MGM.
116 minutes. Rated PG for mild language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B (romantics add a +, cynics a -)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
