<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-DARK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIONS OF DARKNESS, DESPAIR AND HOPE IN A SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
FALLING DARK 
By Tim Tharp 
Milkweed Editions, 271 pp., $39.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tim Tharp's ``Falling Dark'' is a version and a vision of the
pastoral. It is not an idealized pastoral of the past, even the
recent past, though a young boy in a small Oklahoma town dreams of
visiting a farm, and a friend of his, a young African-American boy,
does go to visit relatives who live on a farm.
</P>
<P>
   The town has a past you can glimpse beyond the blacktop and the
neon detritus of ``civilization.'' Once, 20 years ago, there was a
commune where the Sunshine People expected to find themselves in
nature and nature in themselves. It didn't work out that way; only
an old geodesic dome still stands, down by the pond on Sam Casey's
place.
</P>
<P>
   Life is rough and limited in this part of the world. The
Git-N-Go sign shines on, and there's a Dairy Queen, a gas station,
some sagging rent houses, a bar, and a lot of broken dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Bless works checkout at the grocery store. Since her
husband was gunned down by some crazy teenagers, she's been trying
to hold things together for her two sons, Wesley and Nelson, boys
who haven't been spoiled yet by the world they're in. It's an
uphill battle: Donna has a generous heart, but she also has a
problem. Despite her best intentions, she drinks way more than a
little bit too much. A friend says, coaxingly, ``One little beer
never did anybody any harm.'' `` `I don't know,' Donna said. But
she did know. She knew all about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The friend's efforts to fix Donna up with a new man end up in an
attempted rape. She is rescued by Roy Dale, who is not exactly a
knight in shining armor; he moves into her life, and she accepts
him there because she's lonely, but the situation is no good, and
she knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Roy is a drifter and a liar, and, it turns out, a smalltime drug
dealer. There's a sizable marijuana crop growing out there at
Sam's, and Roy isn't above stealing some of the stash and taking it
in his pickup to Tulsa to do some business.
</P>
<P>
   Other characters who come into the story include Sam's daughter
Melinda and Melinda's friend Jennifer, who is a wild one, out of
control, and it turns out she has plenty of reason to be. `` `You
know, it's like I said,' Melinda observes, `she's the oldest friend
I have and my father always told me you have your regular family
and then you have the one you find along the way and that's how it
is with Jennifer and me. She might not always act like I think she
should, and I'll let her know it too, but I'm still going to try to
be the same kind of friend I'd want for myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Melinda is a good person in an environment that doesn't seem to
care one way or the other about anything good. Wesley and Nelson
are good; and in different ways, Sam and Donna, who have seen a lot
more of life, are still trying to be good. It's a struggle, as even
the pure of heart learn. Ragel, the black boy, tells a kid on a
minibike who wants to beat him up, ``You know what's the matter
with you. . . . People treat you like trash, and so you have to go
around treating other people like trash. My daddy told me about
that, he told me all about what makes people like you.'' Even
little Nelson has a bedtime epiphany. ``Nelson lay his head back on
the pillow then and that was something he never knew. He never knew
how you could grow up to understand the world less than you did
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Tharp understands the world and this particular place very well.
He grew up in Henryetta, Okla., and (according to a brief biography
printed at the end of the book) explored the United States by thumb
and pickup truck before experimenting with a variety of jobs. Now
he teaches at Oklahoma State University in Okmulgee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falling Dark'' won Milkweed Press's national fiction prize,
and it deserves to. Tharp is an economical writer, uncannily
sensitive to the poetry of ordinary speech, but never soft at the
center. Donna ``pictured Sam Casey again, the way she had done
since seeing him on her front porch that night, standing there
half-turned, like a door that was just opening in front of her.''
That kind of precise language recalls some of the miracles in the
early work of Larry Woiwode, a writer of a different region.
</P>
<P>
   When, finally, Tharp writes about hope, as pastoral writers
always do, you have to believe him, because he knows all there is
to know about despair.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1458EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2TAKES-     04-06 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARDEN TOURS ABROAD LURE PLANT-OBSESSED AMERICANS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most people visit a few parks or gardens while vacationing
abroad. It's part of seeing the sights. But 10 years ago, it was
difficult to find tour roups headed abroad specifically to look at
gardens.
</P>
<P>
   No more. Gardengoers now make up almost 16 percent of American
specialty tours to Europe, according to Bob Titsley of the British
Tourist Authority. Bonafide plant nuts whose idea of bliss is to
visit two gardens a day for 10 days are making garden tourism a
growing niche in the travel business.
</P>
<P>
   But garden hopping especially lends itself to organized tours
because, unlike, say, world-famous opera houses, great gardens are
usually not near a subway stop. In fact, notable gardens are often
notably hard to reach, being retreats from the world literally as
well as figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   If you go solo, you have to rent a car and find your way to 12
Horsenuts Lane in Clydesdale County, and when you get there you
often find you've arrived on the day it's closed or a week when the
famous laburnum walk is bare of petals.
</P>
<P>
   A well-organized tour eliminates these tragedies and often costs
little more than doing it on your own. It also provides reasonable
pacing, entry by special arrangement to private gardens that are
often better than the public ones, and, best of all, the company of
other gardening maniacs so you don't have to drag your civilian
friends and family members along. (My patient husband often sits in
the car reading a newspaper while I explore yet another garden.)
</P>
<P>
   Even gardeners can find themselves prematurely sated. The same
variety of antique rose that looked sublime in the first garden on
the first day can look ho-hum by the 12th garden on the sixth day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a deep interest in gardens if it's that kind
of a trip,'' warns Lois Rosenfeld, author of the popular annual
guide ``The Garden Tourist.'' ``Otherwise, you're better off taking
a tour that mixes gardens and architecture or other historic
sights. Some of them I've noticed have theater or sightseeing
thrown in so you don't completely zone out on gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   The thriftiest way to visit gardens abroad, suggests Rosenfeld,
is often to ``check if there are any local one-day garden tours out
of major cities you might be staying in.'' For instance, I took in
Monet's waterlily garden at Giverny in an inexpensive half-day bus
tour available to anyone staying in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Arm yourself with comfortable shoes ``and four times as much
film as you think you'll need, because you'll use it,'' advises Nan
Sinton, who directs Horticulture magazine's excellent tour program.
There seems to be some direct neural connection between garden
gazing and photo snapping. ``People on garden tours use cameras
today the way they used sketchbooks 100 years ago. Still
photographs work better than camcorders for this. But don't take a
tripod, which usually aren't allowed because they block traffic and
they introduce a discordant element.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Leading destinations &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   England and Canada are still the leading foreign destinations
for garden visitors from the United States. The Chelsea Flower
Show, in London, May 23-26, is such a mainstream tourist event that
you can shop for special packages through the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, as of last week Virgin Atlantic Airlines was
offering an unbeatable deal: Roundtrip tickets on an overnight
flight leaving New York May 22 and returning May 29, downtown
London hotel with breakfast for six nights, a fFlower sShow ticket,
and tours of several gardens including Sissinghurst, starting at
$1,269. Call 1-800-937-8474 or check their websiteWeb site at
www.Virgin-Atlantic.com.cq
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the best way to get tickets to this preeminent event,
which always sells out far in advance, is to join the British Royal
Horticulture Society and go on one of their two members' days. As a
bonus you get their excellent magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Canada offers ``the most comfort and ease if you're traveling on
your own,'' says Rosenfeld. It also offers the biggest bang for the
buck _ or loonie _ and is almost as garden-fixated as England,
despite (or perhaps because of) its northern latitude. Whenever I
drove through the tunnel from the vacant lots of downtown Detroit
to the civic gardens of downtown Windsor, Ontario, I felt like
Dorothy entering the Technicolor kingdom of Oz.
</P>
<P>
   French-speaking Canada loves flowers just as much, and Quebec is
close enough for a weekend getaway. The Montreal Botanical Garden
has 10 exhibition greenhouses and 30 outdoor gardens on 180 acres.
Montreal is also the setting for an unprecedented summerlong
multi-million-dollar international competition in ``mosaiculture''
_ sculptures and pictures pieced together from plant materials.
Quebec exhibited a sensual example at the New England Spring Flower
Show last month. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Summer gardens in winter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ring of garden travel seems to be widening. England's
gardens no longer seem so exotic, so today's trendy destinations
include Tuscany, Provence,Portugal, and Japan, where the Zen
gardens of Kyoto are a big draw.
</P>
<P>
   In the English-speaking world, New Zealand (with a much lusher
climate than Australia) is becoming popular despite the
knee-crunching 12-hour plane trip (from Los Angeles) because you
can enjoy gardens from October through February, thanks to the
equatorial inversion of seasons. The Taranaki Rhododendron
Festival, Oct. 28-Nov. 6, is justly famous. Once you get there, New
Zealand rivals Canada for ease of travel, thanks to the disarmingly
helpful inhabitants who to a soul seem thrilled to have visitors.
When I lost my wallet there on a visit, it was quickly returned,
cash intact.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is another south-of-the-equator destination that
has grown in popularity as a midwinter garden spot. Its unique
indigenous flora and thriving horticulture industry provide much
for flower lovers to see, as do the game preserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``My South African tours are always billed as wildflower and
wildlife tours. The wildflowers are good for most of the year, but
I always go in September, which is spring there, because the grass
is not very high and you see the animals much more easily, and you
often see babies,'' says the Brooklyn Botanic Garden's South
African-born director emeritus, Elizabeth Scholtz, who led some of
the first garden tours to that country.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of garden tour directors, Scholtz has led 79 excursions
to 42 countries since the program began in 1964. ``For a long time
we were the only kids on the block because when we would announce a
tour it would fill up overnight. Now everyone seems to be running
garden tours,'' she says. Based on long experience, her favorite
garden destinations include Japan, New Zealand, the Greek Isles,
and Madeira and elsewhere in Portugal, as well as South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Ireland is also making a strong bid for garden tourism. The
European Regional Redevelopment Fund has made matching grants
available to privately owned Irish gardens that open their gates to
the public year-round, prompting a great increase in sites to
visit.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Irish Department of Tourism, more than 600,000
foreigners visit Irish gardens each year, about three times the
number of tourists who come to swing a golf club. But very good
Irish gardens such as Creagh in County Cork and Derreen in County
Kerry still log only about 9,000 annual visitors in contrast with
60,000 or more to comparable British gardens, according to Olda
FitzGerald, whose own estate garden at Glin Castle in County
Limerick is open to the public. That sounds heavenly to garden
travelers who have waited in line to get into Sissinghurst. &QL; 
 &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
