<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-2ND </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... Sissinghurst.  Irish Gardens of Eden 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Irish gardens are wilder than their English counterparts,
according to FitzGerald, wife of the well-known architectural
preservationist Desmond FitzGerald, the 29th knight of Glin. She
has just written ``Irish Gardens'' ($40, Hearst), to raise the
profile of 20 great Irish gardens open to visitors. ``Ireland does
have its clipped hedges and parterres, but if you leave it for one
minute, it grows twice as fast as England,'' says FitzGerald.
</P>
<P>
   This is because the Irish climate is generally wetter and milder
than even England's, making it hospitable to palm trees and other
semitropical plants, as well as rampant vines. Mixing exotics with
native plants for a Garden of Eden effect was a dictum of the
influential turn-of-the-century Irish garden writer and designer
William Robinson, and remains a trademark of the Irish garden
style.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently Ireland's great estate gardens were barely
surviving, however. ``Things were quite gloomy from 1939 on. The
gardens were running down badly because there was less money to
keep them up, fewer workers to do so, and a general lack of
interest. Gardening was seen as a property of the middle-class
Protestant spinster ladies. And there was always (the feeling)
about the big homes and their walled gardens that (they
represented) a colonial elite. But now everybody's interested in
the gardens and dreaming of a good tourist trade,'' says
FitzGerald.
</P>
<P>
   Two of her favorites are Helen Dillon's garden in Dublin and
designer Jim Reynolds's Butterstream in County Meath. Reynolds is
chairman of the Great Gardens of Ireland Restoration Programme,
which since 1994 has helped save a number of old estate gardens
``just before they disappeared into the jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   If you decide to tackle the byways to find Ireland's gardens,
FitzGerald warned, ``Ireland is a small country, but you need to
have a map. There's a lot of untouched countryside. And you need to
keep very calm. Because a cow in the road could easily happen.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tours and organizers &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A sampler of garden tours:
</P>
