<SLUG> BC-RETURN-TO-ME-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILLED WITH PLEASANT SURPRISES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Return to Me'' is a movie that has no business working, but it
does. The premise alone should be required to carry some sort of
warning: Widower falls in love with transplant patient who carries
his late wife's heart.
</P>
<P>
   If you just groaned, then find another movie. This one is so
full of whimsy that the set decorators probably had to sweep the
fairy dust away at the end of each day. But for anyone who misses
Doris Day, believes that love conquers all and that it's possible
to get good corned beef and cabbage at an Italian restaurant named
O'Reilly's, ``Return to Me'' is a romantic throwback that will warm
your heart and give your handkerchief a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnie Hunt, !ital!the gal pal of the romantic fantasy genre
(``Jerry Maguire,'' ``Only You,'' etc., etc.) co-wrote and directed
``Return to Me,'' !ital!and cast herself as the movie's gal pal.
It's a hit-and-miss effort. Too often Hunt settles for the
trite-and-true with twinkly old-timers, non-existent character arcs
and a shameless (not to mention stupid and strained) subplot
involving a lonesome gorilla.
</P>
<P>
   And yet just when you feel an overpowering urge to run to the
exit (this is especially pressing in the film's first 20 minutes),
Hunt reins the film in and creates such an appealing atmosphere of
sweetness and innocence that you can't help but follow the words of
an old Dean Martin hit and ``smile, smile, smile.''
</P>
<P>
   Dino, of course, sings the film's title song, and he and Sinatra
and Jackie Gleason's syrupy orchestra provide the mood music for
the movie. David Duchovny shrugs off his dour ``X-Files'' persona
to play the widower, Bob, who's devastated after losing his beloved
wife in an automobile accident. Minnie Driver, returning to the
kind of vulnerable role that won her acclaim in ``Good Will
Hunting,'' is the beneficiary of the wife's misfortune, getting a
new lease on a life that, until now, has been rather sheltered.
</P>
<P>
   Driver's character, Grace, waits tables at the improbable
Italian restaurant, where her grandfather (Carroll O'Connor) and
his chef (Robert Loggia) and their cronies seem to spend more time
playing poker (and Cupid) than they do serving pasta. When Bob
finds himself in O'Reilly's on the blind date from hell, he and
Grace meet and !ital!zing go the strings of their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Only Grace's heart came from Bob's dead wife. Only Grace doesn't
know that, and Bob certainly doesn't, either. And therein lies the
obstacle to their future happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Duchovny and Driver have a natural ease together, giving their
scenes an engaging believability in this most heightened of
fantasies. Hunt and co-writer Don Lake also play favorites, giving
her some enjoyably earthy supporting scenes with Jim Belushi.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Belushi? Enjoyable? Like we said, ``Return to Me'' provides
a number of unlikely pleasures. &QL; 
_______ &QL; 
The film: ``Return to Me'' (PG; some language). &QL; 
!bbox!The stars: David Duchovny, Minnie Driver, Carroll O'Connor,
Robert Loggia, Bonnie Hunt, Jim Belushi. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Bonnie Hunt. Screenplay by Hunt and
Don Lake. Released by MGM Pictures. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 55 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
