<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     DIPLOMATIC DiMAGGIO STRIKES OUT A LAWYER  
 &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ROB MORSE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Dom DiMaggio is a famously nice guy, as outgoing
as his late brother Joe was private.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't want to get this former Red Sox center fielder
angry.
</P>
<P>
   Morris Engelberg has gotten Dom DiMaggio very angry.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Dom was boiling that Engelberg, the executor of
Joe's estate, is threatening to sue San Francisco in the name of
the DiMaggio family if the city renames the North Beach Playground
in honor of Joe, instead of renaming something big like the Bay
Bridge, the airport or a gift horse's mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm outraged. He's intimating that I've been involved in
what's going on,'' said DiMaggio, when I called him at his home in
Florida. ``I have been treated as a complete stranger. As an
individual and a human being, I'm ashamed at what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Engelberg has said he's speaking for the family, but he hasn't
talked to the most famous living DiMaggio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not represent me,'' said Dom, who has let his feelings
be known to city officials. ``I've sat by long enough. I think I'm
affected now.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominic Paul DiMaggio (known as ``The Little Professor'' because
of his glasses and articulate manner of speaking) had an impressive
career batting average of .298 over 11 seasons with the Boston Red
Sox, and played with great grace, like his more famous brother.
</P>
<P>
   He's proud of having learned to play ball with his brothers on
that little playground, and thinks it would be wonderful to name it
after Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all, we lived only a block from there,'' he said. ``We
played there morning, noon and night. We even jumped over the fence
on Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   Dom said he'd like to see future major leaguers learn to play
ball in a playground named for his brother Joe.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, San Francisco could call it ``DiMaggio
Playground'' for Dom. The man has a lot of class.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always had my admiration. He supported us from day one,
but wanted to keep a low profile,'' said city Supervisor Gavin
Newsom, who has led San Francisco's efforts to find a DiMaggio
memorial. ``What I like is his deep love and admiration for the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Engelberg, what can you say?
</P>
<P>
   There are some parts of San Francisco worthy of naming after
him, if we haven't cleaned up all our toxic waste sites.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   Bill Gates' biggest innovation: Use the word ``innovation'' as
many times as possible.
</P>
<P>
   In a public letter printed in newspapers Wednesday after the
antitrust decision against Microsoft, Gates used the word
``innovation'' three times, as well as ``innovate,'' ``innovative''
and ``innovating'' one time each.
</P>
<P>
   I asked a techie friend what technical innovations Microsoft had
ever made and all he could think of was an elegant little operating
system for the old Tandy 100 portable computers. Even Microsoft's
business practices are less than innovative, having been developed
by moguls born 100 years before Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans don't care how innovative Microsoft is. They care
how Microsoft stock is doing, and my bet is that it will continue
to perform better than those ``innovative'' Microsoft products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
