<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOPRANOS: SO MANY PLOTS, SO LITTLE TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHTIE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This was TV Guide's entire teaser for last Sunday's episode of
``The Sopranos'': ``Tony throws a party for Richie and Janice.''
</P>
<P>
   And what a party it was. Such a happy couple. Who would have
guessed that before the hour was out she'd whack him with the gun
he liked to hold to her head when they were in bed?
</P>
<P>
   Janice merely suggested that it was no big deal if Richie's
ballroom-dancing son was gay. Richie responded by smashing her in
the mouth. Bang. Bang. Richie didn't even get to finish his ziti.
Minutes later, Christopher and Furio were stuffing his remains into
a meat grinder at Satriale's butcher shop. I guess this means the
wedding is off.
</P>
<P>
   What do we have to look forward to this Sunday on ``The
Sopranos'' season-ending episode? Here's what TV Guide says: ``Tony
visits the rarely seen Livia to negotiate her future living
arrangements. Meanwhile Meadow's graduation is cause for
celebration, and Carmela gets an extravagant addition to her
wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   No hint of mayhem there. But let's not be discouraged. Look what
happened last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sopranos'' fans have their own ideas about what turns the plot
may take. I have mine, you have yours, and if you log on to HBO.com
there's a message board full of fans' predictions about what could
happen on the season's last show. Most seem to agree on one thing;
Pussy has to go. But who knows?
</P>
<P>
   One of many things that sets this series apart is its
unpredictability. Another is its dead-on depiction of ordinary,
everyday, dysfunctional family life with all the plotting and
scheming, the suspicion, the greed, the lying, the back-stabbing,
the betrayals, the grudges, the yearning for revenge. They may be
Family but they're family, too. No wonder we love them.
</P>
<P>
   Some fans' predictions for the season-ender are a tad
far-fetched even by ``Sopranos'' standards. One rabid viewer
suggests that Richie didn't die, that he was wearing a bullet-proof
vest, and that the shooting was staged by Uncle Junior to give
Richie a chance to kill Tony in the season finale.
</P>
<P>
   Another prediction, almost as loony, has Junior killed, Tony
going to prison, and Janice, or possibly Carmela, taking over the
business.
</P>
<P>
   A number of contributors think Dr. Melfi has the hots for her
most notorious patient and has taken to drinking to avoid
confronting her feelings for Tony. Personally, I think she's
drinking because Peter Bogdanovich is her psychiatrist, but that's
just my opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Here are my final episode predictions, for what they're worth,
ie., not much. Anthony Jr. becomes convinced he's adopted, that
he's really Jewish and has been cheated out of a bar mitzvah.
Meadow reluctantly agrees to go to NYU, then comes out as a lesbian
to annoy her parents. After Carmela has a vision, the Soprano
swimming pool becomes a place of religious pilgrimage. The FDA
shuts down Satriale's when an outbreak of sausage-related E. coli
sweeps New Jersey. Christopher marries Adrianna, who whines
incessantly that Tony killed her Uncle Richie. Adrianna disappears.
Dr. Melfi consults the psychic in Nyack about her drinking problem.
Pussy undergoes sex re-assignment surgery and enters the federal
witness protection program. Uncle Junior gets his hand stuck in the
garbage disposal again. Tony has the mother of all panic attacks
when he wakes up in bed with Livia. Is he dreaming? We'll have to
wait until next season to find out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
