<HEADLINE>
SHOPPING AROUND: SKIING IN THE SOUTHERN HEMISPHERE  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. ONE COLOR SLIDE, AVAILABLE FREE OF CHARGE, CAN BE
SENT TO YOU ELECTRONICALLY. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By EVERETT POTTER  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    Dedicated skiers and snowboarders don't have to put away their
gear just yet. Instead, they should look south for the summer. Both
New Zealand and South America offer challenging mountains and
cultural adventures.
 &HT;    In the Southern Alps of New Zealand, the bowls of the
Remarkables and natural half-pipes of Treble Cone are the backdrop
for the ski town of Queenstown.
 &HT;    At the Chilean resort of Portillo, it's condors, not condos,
that predominate, along with fresh Pacific powder and views of
23,000-foot Cerro Aconcagua, the highest peak in the Americas.
 &HT;    In Argentina, the slopes of Las Lenas and the nightlife of
Bariloche are the draws.
 &HT;    Skiing in New Zealand or South America may be an exotic
adventure, but it doesn't have to break your budget. By taking
advantage of low-season airfares, using air-and-hotel packages and
putting frequent-flier miles to work, it can be the affordable ski
trip of a lifetime. Seven-night deals for less than $2,000 _
including airfare and some meals _ are quite common.
 &HT;    Start in New Zealand, where the Southern Alps offer
above-treeline skiing, a relatively mild winter climate and easy
access to glacier- and heli-skiing. On the North Island, there's
skiing on the slopes of a live volcano, Mt. Ruapehu.
 &HT;    All of New Zealand's resorts could fit into Squaw Valley and
Alpine combined, so don't expect vast amounts of terrain. Instead,
come for the challenge and adventure of skiing down under.
 &HT;    The only drawback for New Zealand-bound skiers is time.
Considering that the direct flight takes about 11 hours from Los
Angeles and 15 from New York, nine days would seem to be the
absolute minimum stay.
 &HT;    To maximize such a skiing vacation, it's best to be based in one
location. Ideally, that's Queenstown, on the Southern Island, which
is about two-and-a-half hours by air from Auckland, via
Christchurch.
 &HT;    Often compared to Lake Tahoe, Queenstown is set on the shores of
Lake Whakatipu. This former gold-rush town is now a lively resort
of 15,000 people. Many skiers take advantage of Queenstown's
year-round bungee jumping, white-water rafting and heli-skiing,
which have earned it the title ``Terror-Tourism Capital of the
World.''
 &HT;    Within 90 minutes of Queenstown are four major resorts. Cardrona
and Coronet Peak are ideal family resorts, with terrain for skiers
of all abilities. The Remarkables appeal to advanced skiers and
snowboarders, while Treble Cone has the most challenging runs
around.
 &HT;    On the North Island, the resorts of Whakapapa and Turoa are on
the slopes of the volcanic Mount Mt. Ruapehu. The best place to
stay is the resort town of Ohakune.
 &HT;    The resorts of Chile and Argentina promise abundant snow,
challenging runs and spectacular scenery. North Americans like
skiing here because a weeklong trip is possible, jet lag is minimal
and it takes them to the heart of two of South America's most
exciting countries. An extra day for sightseeing in Buenos Aires
and Santiago can easily be added on.
 &HT;    In Argentina, Valle de Las Lenas is the first and only choice
for many North American skiers. Its vast area of lift-serviced
terrain exceeds any single North American resort. Totally above
treeline, it boasts extraordinary steeps that are reminiscent of
Verbier and Chamonix and can rattle the most accomplished expert.
There's a vigorous nightlife, including a casino, at this
stand-alone resort.
 &HT;    North Americans also go to San Carlos de Bariloche, the only
town in South America with a traditional ski culture and a jet-set
presence. Lodging is available either in the bustling,
Swiss-inspired town or at Bariloche's main ski mountain, Gran
Catedral, a few miles away.
 &HT;    It's worth making the spectacular two-hour drive north from
Bariloche to ski Chapelco, a mountain known for its advanced runs.
 &HT;    In Chile, many North American skiers head to Portillo, which is
a self-contained resort several hours from Santiago. The resorts of
Valle Nevado, La Parva and El Colorado are closer to the capital
and comprise one of South America's largest lift-connected
complexes.
 &HT;    Valle Nevado has a village that's located on top of the
mountain. The skiing is varied, with plenty of intermediate as well
as expert terrain.
 &HT;    Finally, about 300 miles south of Santiago is Termas de Chillan,
known for its long runs and hot springs.
 &HT;    The ski season south of the border runs from June to October,
with high season from mid-July through mid-August. Spring skiing,
which brings warmer temperatures and lower prices, begins in
mid-September.
 &HT;    A typical trip? Adventures on Skis (815 North Road, Westfield,
Mass. 01085; 800-628-9655; www.advonskis.com) sends skiers to South
America and Las Lenas, Argentina, for $1,555 per person, based on
double occupancy. That includes round-trip airfare from New York to
Buenos Aires; round-trip airfare from Buenos Aires to Malargue;
transfers; seven nights at Hotel Escorpio; daily breakfast; and
dinner.
 &HT;    Or contact Moguls Ski &AMP; Snowboard Tours (4876 Sterling Drive,
Boulder, Colo. 80301; 800-666-4857; www.skimoguls.com); Ski
Vacation Planners (800-UCANSKI; www.skivacationplanners.com); or
Holidaze Ski Tours (810 Belmar Plaza, Belmar N.J. 07719;
800-526-2827; www.holidaze.com). These companies have extensive
programs in both New Zealand and South America.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Everett Potter is a New York City-based free-lance travel
writer.) 
 &HT;    -----
 c.2000 Everett Potter 
