<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8886 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF &LR;      04-06 2652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-FARE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COLORFUL TROVE IN MEXICO CITY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by WAY TO GO! clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement. For purchase information,
see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``t'' travel news and ``l'' lifestyle news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By KATHERINE ASHENBURG  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    At the beginning it seemed pretty straightforward. I was going
to Mexico for the first time, and I didn't know enough about
Mexican history. I planned to learn more about it, and to focus a
week's stay in Mexico City, through clothes. In the costume
collections of the city's museums and, I hoped, in its shops and
markets, I would begin to understand the country's numerous
revolutions, the relationship between the Indians and Spanish
conquerors, even something about the depths of the Mexican soul.
 &HT;    Those ignorant of the seriousness of costume history might
dismiss this as the project of an optimist, even an airhead. Wiser
minds know better. Think of the significance of cotton in
determining the Civil War, of the flapper's dress in signaling a
sexual revolution. Undeniably, clothing is a window onto large
events as well as intangibles like culture.
 &HT;    By and large, my plan was a success. But, as often happens in
unsystematic enterprises, things didn't quite proceed in the
correct order.
 &HT;    My quest began with two books, the name of a shop and the name
of a woman. The books were the Lonely Planet guide to Mexico City
and Chloe Sayer's magisterial history, ``Costumes of Mexico.'' The
shop was Casa Victor, a hideaway selling some of the best of
Mexico's folk arts. The woman's name was Ruth Lechuga. A friend in
Toronto told me that she had a large private collection of folk
arts, which she showed to interested visitors.
 &HT;    But first I wanted to familiarize myself with a few museum
collections. The National Museum of Anthropology would no doubt
have extensive holdings of clothes from Mexico's 50-some Indian
cultures, but it sounded daunting. Looking for a more manageable
start, I scanned Lonely Planet and discovered the Franz Mayer
Museum (Avenida Hidalgo 45, at the north end of the city's downtown
park, the Alameda), a small, choice collection of the applied arts.
Its holdings include antique rebozos (women's rectangular shawls
that double as a carryall) and serapes (the blanket that frequently
includes an opening for the head). I'm off.
 &HT;    It's my first mistake. Which doesn't mean that the Franz Mayer
isn't eminently visitable. The colonial ceramics, silver and
furniture are splendid, its home in a 16th-century hospital has
been sensitively restored, and the cafe in the crisply formal
cloister garden is one of the nicest places to eat in Mexico City.
Its rebozos and serapes are also very fine, but they belong at the
end of the week, not the beginning.
 &HT;    Just inside the Franz Mayer's textile rooms, cases display the
natural dyes, materials and techniques that go into Mexican
clothes. Unfortunately, I don't read Spanish. Using my French, the
tattered remnants of my Latin and the exhibits themselves, I begin
to acquire some essential vocabulary _ lana (wool), lino (linen),
seda (silk) and algodon (cotton). Indigo is easy. Bordado means
embroidery; aplicacion is applique. It's a start, but meanwhile I'm
missing about 90 percent of the information.
 &HT;    Even Spanish signs, I realize when I enter the main textile
room, are better than no signs. This softly lighted gallery has
cases of superb objects, with no indication of their provenance or
age. At least I've read enough Chloe Sayer to recognize a rebozo,
perhaps the quintessential colonial Mexican garment, and one in
particular intrigues me.
 &HT;    Three long panels of beige silk, connected by bands of guilloche
work (a braided effect), are embroidered with houses, fountains,
cornucopias and very European-looking ladies and gentlemen. Judging
by the ladies' and gentlemen's clothes, it dates from the 18th
century and is an extraordinarily delicate example of a style worn
by all social classes.
 &HT;    Less sumptuous but still handsome, nine rebozos _ somberly
striped in blue, brown and red _ occupy a nearby case. At this
point, I don't even know how they are made (on an Indian backstrap
loom, using a complex method of tie-dyeing called ikat).
 &HT;    A group of embroidery samplers charms me; later I learn that
these were the means by which Mexican pupils learned Spanish
stitches during the colonial period (1521-1821).
 &HT;    I leave the Franz Mayer discouraged but unbowed, hoping for a
more user-friendly museum. The Serfin Museum (Avenida Madero 33)
has a collection of more than 5,000 pieces of Indian costumes. One
big workaday room, the museum proper displays perhaps 20 life-size
models dressed in the clothes of a particular region, with other
examples hung on the walls.
 &HT;    At first the Serfin, too, looks like a challenge _ signs only in
Spanish, the current exhibition limited to the dress of the
Zapotecs in Oaxaca.
 &HT;    Don't panic, I tell myself, enjoy the details, the lace, the
almost-African combinations of yellow and red, the bold woolen
flowers blooming on black velvet festival dresses. Along the way
(my Spanish is improving rapidly), I learn something about the
huipil, the indigenous woman's tunic in use for the last 2,000
years. Sleeveless, often but not always sewn up the sides, the
Zapotecs' huipil is typically an immaculate white, minimally
embroidered or decorated with white-on-white woven effects.
 &HT;    Examples of another pre-Hispanic dress, a short-sleeved square
blouse with sash and wraparound skirt, are seen here in brilliant
reds and rich browns. Like the huipil and Indian clothing in
general, they are composed entirely of rectangular pieces, because
that's what the backstrap loom produces.
 &HT;    More familiar to Americans than the huipil is the short-sleeved
white blouse whose yoke and sleeves are embroidered with flowers.
The embroidery here, on blouses from Ocotlan, is far more
painstaking than anything I have seen made for the tourist market.
Minuscule, beautifully worked pink and red flowers, with the
occasional yellow accent, cover the yoke of one blouse.
 &HT;    Just up the street from the Serfin is Casa Victor (Avenida
Madero 10), the shop I had heard about from a Mexican friend in
Toronto. The office building is nondescript, and there is no sign.
 &HT;    Dubious, I climb two heart-thumping flights of stairs to No. 305
(don't smile, until you've done stairs at Mexico City's altitude)
and find a treasure trove of Mexican crafts. Chosen with
discernment and affection from all over the country, they include
silver, tinware and ceramics, but I head for the tables neatly
piled with clothes in the center of the room.
 &HT;    Perhaps because it is a shop, where I can touch the fabrics;
perhaps because I have accepted the haphazard nature of my quest, I
relax. I pore over a Huichol cotton smock, densely embroidered with
geometric motifs, stars and deer that, in their red-and-blue
precision, could be mistaken for Nordic. At $390, calculated at 9
pesos to the dollar, it is not inexpensive, but its verve is so
distinctive I could imagine displaying it on a wall.
 &HT;    Cotton shirts can be had at Casa Victor for as little as $12;
rebozos striped in the traditional flamelike designs cost from $83
to about $133. But what wins my heart is a spectacular fiesta skirt
from Puebla, its red wool thickly strewn with sequined butterflies
and black ``lace.'' (The lace is actually drawn on, then outlined
in sequins.)
 &HT;    The whole outrageously glamorous piece ends in a green satin
border and costs $89. The saleswoman murmurs, ``china poblana''
when she sees me admiring it. That night I learn from ``Costumes of
Mexico'' that a china poblana is a showy 19th-century belle of
mixed European and Indian blood; flashy clothes in that style are
called china poblana by extension. I return to Casa Victor twice
during the week, at least partly to visit that skirt.
 &HT;    By midweek I feel ready to tackle the vast National Museum of
Anthropology in Chapultepec Park, with its 10 second-floor halls
devoted to the Indians of contemporary Mexico. They demand the best
part of the day, and the English signs range from nonexistent to
excellent, but the reward is that the clothes are shown in the
context of a culture.
 &HT;    The Totonacs on the Gulf Coast, for example, are vanilla growers
whose women are noted for their textiles. The short chairs on which
they spin and weave cotton are part of the exhibit, as are displays
of their fishing gear, their home altars, and costumed mannequins
demonstrating their elaborate dances.
 &HT;    A typically gauzy Totonac quechquemitl (the pre-conquest woman's
poncho) on display is decorated twice, with a sure eye for design _
first with fine white thread on the loosely woven cotton, then
over-embroidered with brilliant birds and flowers.
 &HT;    The model of a Totonac wedding couple is particularly
interesting for the groom's attire, since traditional male clothing
has become increasingly rare as men join the modern work force.
This groom wears a bright white pair of the short, loose pants
called calzon; a short flared shirt that barely meets his pants and
two neckerchiefs, one white, one yellow.
 &HT;    In the Maya highlands of Chiapas, Spanish missionaries imposed
variations on the Indians' clothing according to their village, as
a method of keeping tabs on their comings and goings. A market
scene in the Maya hall shows 16 figures, each from a different
village, in the particular, vivid dress peculiar to that village.
 &HT;    No amount of orders from without seems to have diminished the
Indians' graphic sense, as a case of dramatic huipils in the same
hall illustrates. One stunningly designed piece has warm brown
diamond-shaped motifs on the shoulders and breast, lighter ones
below and then, on the white skirt, a single, memorable line of
brown thread running vertically to the hem.
 &HT;    I have reserved my last day to visit Ruth Lechuga, whom I found
in the Mexico City phone book. Yes, she would show me her
collection.
 &HT;    When I ring the bell at her building in the quiet Condesa
quarter, a white head appears on the third floor and tosses me the
key. Although I know that Lechuga, who arrived in Mexico in 1939 as
a teenage Jewish refugee from Vienna, is one of the foremost
authorities on Mexican folk arts and that her apartment is a
private museum (nothing is for sale), I'm unprepared for the wonder
of it.
 &HT;    Eighteen rooms (two old-fashioned, roomy apartments have been
combined) full of smartly displayed, meticulously cataloged masks,
toys, pottery, gourds, paintings, furniture and textiles are
presided over by their diminutive collector. She began driving to
remote parts of Mexico in the 1940s, buying what appealed to her in
the markets. At 80, she is still interested in acquiring an example
of something she doesn't have _ but that doesn't often happen.
 &HT;    After a general tour of the collection, including her
shocking-pink bedroom decorated with Day of the Dead papier-mache
skulls, we sit down together. I have told her I'm interested in
clothes, and she has chosen a representative selection of rebozos,
huipils, serapes, quechquemitls, sashes, wraparound skirts.
 &HT;    For more than an hour, in what amounts to a private tutorial,
she shows me what to look for in a rebozo; what is special about a
particular brocaded yoke on a huipil; why a child's cap comes in
bright colors (to distract the evil eye so it doesn't land on the
child); how the Indians blend synthetic and natural materials, hand
and machine embroidery, modern and traditional motifs; how they use
smocking as a way to tailor their rectangular pieces of cloth; how
they take a secretion from a particular shellfish (without killing
it) to produce a subtle amethyst color.
 &HT;    It strikes me as a heady, rare privilege, but ``this is how I
earn my living,'' she tells me. The cost for a tour is $16.50.
 &HT;    Clearly, I've done everything backward. I should have begun with
Ruth Lechuga, gone on to the Museum of Anthropology, then the
Serfin Museum and ended in that connoisseur's haven, the Franz
Mayer, savoring those silent cases with more appreciation. The only
things I've done ``correctly'' were reading ''Costumes of Mexico''
and visiting Casa Victor three times.
 &HT;    But I don't really regret my herky-jerky progress. I'm
significantly less ignorant about Mexico than I was a week ago.
I've also spent absorbed, delightful hours peering at blouses
crowded with blossoms, hand-knotted fringe and fine weaving. One of
the gnomic sayings I remember from Kurt Vonnegut's ``Cat's Cradle''
is ``Peculiar travel suggestions are dancing lessons from God.'' In
my case, amend that to ``embroidery lessons.''
 &HT;    -----
 SIDEBAR: WHERE TO LOOK, WHERE TO BUY  
 THE MUSEUMS  
 &HT;    The Franz Mayer Museum, (52-5) 518-2271, is open every day
except Monday, from 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. Admission is $1.70.
 &HT;    The Serfin Museum, (52-5) 625-5600, is open, free of charge,
Tuesday through Sunday, 10 a.m. to 5 p.m.
 &HT;    The National Museum of Anthropology, (52-5) 553-6381, is open
Tuesday through Sunday, 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Admission is $2.75, with
no charge on Sundays.
 &HT;    Ruth Lechuga's collection of Mexican clothing and folk art,
including pottery and masks, is shown by appointment only; call or
fax (52-5) 5553-5538; the fee for a visit is $16.50.
 SHOPPING  
 &HT;    There are other shops selling Mexican folk clothes, both new and
old, but none that compare, in my experience, with Casa Victor, at
10 Avenida Madero, (52-5) 5512-1263, open weekdays 12:30 to 7 p.m.
The shop sells everything from 60-cent souvenirs to Huichol
paintings at $225.
 &HT;    Fonart (National Fund for Crafts) is a respected name and there
are occasional pleasant pieces, but I found its selection of
rebozos and serapes unexciting. The main store is at Avenida
Patriotismo 691, (52-5) 598-1666. The market on Balderas at Donde
not far from the Alameda, the Centro de Artesanias La Ciudadela, is
more fun but similarly unrewarding.
 &HT;    In the Bazar Sabado (Saturday Bazaar), held from 10 a.m. to 7
p.m. every Saturday in Plaza San Jacinto in the charming San Angel
neighborhood, it's worth checking out Textiles de Michoacan for
good-quality, but expensive, pieces. Also, the antiques shops in
the Plaza del Angel, between Hamburgo and Londres in the Zona Rosa,
will sometimes turn up pieces of vintage clothing of fine quality.
 BOOKS  
 &HT;    ``Costumes of Mexico'' by Chloe Sayer (University of Texas
Press) is out of print, but may be available in libraries.
 &HT;    The English guide to the National Museum of Anthropology by
Ignacio Bernal is a good investment at $15.
 &HT;    -----
 &HT;    (Katherine Ashenburg is the author of ``Going to Town:
Architectural Walking Tours in Southern Ontario'' (McFarlane,
Walter &AMP; Ross).  
 &HT;    -----
