<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS DECK ISN'T WEATHERING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'd like to get a weathered effect on my deck floorboards.
They are four years old and I have been using a sealer every year.
What else should I do?
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD MAGUE, Marlborough, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If the deck is pressure-treated and the sealer is a clear
sealer, it should have turned to a nice weathered gray by now.
Ditto for a mahogany or cedar deck.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is pressure-treated or mahogany, you can stop
applying the sealer or continue with it; the deck has been through
enough cycles of contraction and expansion not to splinter, spall,
or split.
</P>
<P>
   If it's cedar, it may not weather very attractively, so it might
be best to continue the sealer treatment, even though it's an
annual pain. If it were my deck, I would not treat it at all, and
let it weather.
</P>
<P>
   If you want more of a light-gray weathered look, you can treat
the deck with semitransparent stain of a medium to light gray. This
will last for three to five years, and only one coat is needed each
time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. One of the toilets on the second floor is leaking; the drain
in the basement is wet and dripping. How can I locate the leak?
</P>
<P>
   DESPERATE, and wasting water
</P>
<P>
   A. The leak may be where you see the drain dripping water or it
may be higher up, and is telegraphing down the outside of the pipe
and dripping where it goes from vertical to nearly horizontal on
its way to the main sewer pipe. You could try wiping the pipe and
inspecting it for a possible leak, or more likely, a break in the
drain where it makes a turn. If you find nothing suspicious, you
may have to break into the wall amd make a visual inspection. Have
a helper flush the toilet while you make the inspection; the leak
should manifest itself immediately. And if the drain is leaking,
you really are not wasting water; it just is not going to the right
place.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My 55-year-old house has painted cedar shingles. Recently, I
noticed brown stains at the bottom of some shingles on the north
side of the house, especially just under the eaves. My neighbor has
the same thing on the south side. What is it, and how can I prevent
it?
</P>
<P>
   PAUL ANDERSON, Melrose, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It is the dreaded cedar bleed, which has become a plague in
New England with our red cedar shingles and clapboards, all nicely
painted or stained a light color.
</P>
<P>
   The cause is moisture behind the shingles, which leaches out the
tannins in the red cedar, dissolving them into that brown ooze.
There is little you can do except wash the stains; power washing
will be even more helpful.
</P>
<P>
   But the stains will return if the water is allowed to remain.
So, check for leaks in the wall or roof, or a blocked gutter, which
overflows down the face of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you fix the leaks, the stains may continue, because the
moisture may be behind the shingles. It arrives there as water
vapor that migrated from inside the house, through walls and
insulation, and condensed on the cool sheathing, turning into water
that penetrated the sheathing and resulted in the brown stains.
Ventilating or dehumidifying the house may help some.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I stripped the top of my maple Hitchcock tabletop where
something dripped and took off the stain. I sanded to the bare wood
and planned to stain it, butthe maple will not take stain. How can
I get the original stain color back?
</P>
<P>
   GLENN DEMERS, Danvers, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Maple is a very hard hardwood, and dense, too, making it
difficult to impossible for ordinary oil stains to penetrate. So,
you have to use a different stain. Use a stain made from
water-soluble or alcohol-soluble analine dyes. As a bonus, regular
oil stains can be applied over dried analine dyes to get the
desired color.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
