<HEADER>
A8898 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-FAILSAFE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-06 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FAILSAFE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING A CHANCE ON LIVE TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm a George Clooney fan. Admired him in ``ER.'' Loved ``Out of
Sight'' and ``Three Kings.'' Forgave him for the ``Batman'' thing.
</P>
<P>
   The guy projects star quality onscreen and has a reputation as
one of show business' more likable personalities off camera.
</P>
<P>
   He's no snob about theatrical films versus TV, and he isn't
averse to taking risks. Clooney was the force behind the live
``ER'' episode in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Clooney will leap onto the high wire again.
</P>
<P>
   This time it will be a live, black-and-white production of
``Fail Safe,'' based on the nuclear shocker novel and the 1964 film
that starred Henry Fonda, Walter Matthau, Dan O'Herlihy and Larry
Hagman.
</P>
<P>
   The two-hour production will originate Sunday from Burbank on
CBS. Viewers in the East will see it live. On the West Coast, it'll
be shown tape-delayed, possible screw-ups and all.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the new TV version will have a heftier cast than
the movie. Joining Clooney will be Richard Dreyfuss (in Fonda's
role as the president), James Cromwell, Brian Dennehy, Harvey
Keitel, Sam Elliott, Norman Lloyd, Hank Azaria, Don Cheadle,
William Smitrovich and Noah Wyle. You can even add Walter Cronkite,
who will introduce the program.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Frears (``High Fidelity'') will direct from a
refurbished script by Walter Bernstein, who wrote the 1964 film.
Clooney is co-executive producer and the man who put the project
together. Seems that ``Fail-Safe'' was his favorite movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to screen that movie over at my house all the time and
make people watch it,'' Clooney said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens to be one of my favorite stories of all time. In
fact, my favorite film of all time. We thought it was sort of made
for live television. ... It's a very personal story about several
million people being killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney was only partly joking; the description isn't far off
the mark. The Cold War novel by Harvey Wheeler and Eugene Burdick
is about nuclear-laden bombers mistakenly sent to obliterate
Moscow, and the tense effort by the American president to avert
nuclear holocaust. He offers a frightful quid pro quo solution if
Moscow is nuked.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney will play the U.S. pilot _ Edward Binns had the role in
the old movie _ who is on a seemingly irretrievable course toward
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these characters who are making decisions on a lot
of people's lives and negotiating how many people they'll kill, and
there's a logic to it,'' Clooney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scary thing, and what's great about this story, is it
talks about that and says, `Isn't this insane?' _ that that logic,
somehow, makes sense to us. I think that's what always appealed to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, it's ``Dr. Strangelove'' without the dark humor.
The 1964 film was released only two years after the Cuban missile
crisis, when public dread of the possibility of nuclear
annihilation was still at a peak.
</P>
<P>
   There's no time shifting in the CBS version; it too will be set
in the mid-1960s. And that raises a question about viewer interest,
given the end of the Cold War, the dissolution of the Soviet Union
and subsequent reduction of nuclear tensions. Clooney said the
cautionary story is still worth telling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story itself isn't necessarily about Russia, although we
are using Russia as the vehicle, of course,'' Clooney said. ``But
the question is whether or not machines and our technology get
ahead of us and actually put us in jeopardy of nuclear war. With
China and Korea, I think that's still sort of relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, ``Fail Safe'' seems a decent fit for TV. It was a
stark black-and-white film with few sets, reminiscent of live TV
dramas in the 1950s. Viewers who get the Turner Classic Movies
cable channel can see for themselves; the 1964 ``Fail-Safe'' is
scheduled for 11:30 p.m. Sunday, half an hour after the CBS
production ends.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney said he'd like to see ``Fail Safe'' become the first of
an occasional series of live prime-time shows _ perhaps four a
year. If he wants to know more about the risks, he need look no
further than scriptwriter Bernstein, a veteran of the old live TV
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein still chuckles about an incident involving a 1950s
anthology series called ``Danger,'' on CBS.
</P>
<P>
   In the climactic moment of one story, he said, the villain was
to edge toward the tiger cage at a circus and be fatally clawed by
a tiger. An animal trainer was stationed behind the stage with a
stick to jab the tiger at the right moment, to provoke the animal's
``attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Sidney Lumet (who also directed the ``Fail-Safe''
film), the climax came off convincingly in rehearsal. Then came the
live scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``The villain got close to the cage, the cue came, the trainer
jabbed the tiger, and the tiger just sat there,'' Bernstein said.
``It was like he'd been waiting for that moment. Sidney, of course,
had to cut to the villain, who was staggering back after nothing
had happened, with blood pouring.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Clooney and his colleagues face the high-wire chance of
similar mishaps with ``Fail Safe.'' Yes, he said, he'd asked his
father, longtime television personality Nick Clooney, for advice.
Which was:
</P>
<P>
   `` `Don't do it,' '' George Clooney said. `` `What are you,
stoned?,' I believe, was his exact phrase.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
