<HEADER>
A8904 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-ART-PICASSO-SFCHRON &LR;      04-06 0420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-PICASSO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCUSATIONS FLY IN FIGHT OVER A PICASSO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE HAMLIN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A nasty dispute has flared up between two
prominent San Francisco families _ pitting the children of arts
patron Madeleine Haas Russell against investment brokerage baron
Charles Schwab and his wife, Helen _ over the sale of a $45 million
Picasso painting last fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwabs and the San Francisco Museum of Modern Art are
considering suing the Madeleine Haas Russell Trust for allegedly
breaching a ``binding'' oral contract to sell them Picasso's
masterpiece ``Nu au fauteuil noir.'' The painting, a famously
erotic depiction of Picasso's mistress Marie-Therese Walter, was
sold at a Christie's auction for $45.1 million in November along
with other works from Russell's estate. Russell was a longtime
trustee of SFMOMA, where Helen Schwab is a board member.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement the Schwabs released Wednesday through
San Francisco attorney Charles Cohler, the Schwabs and SFMOMA had
made a deal in September to jointly buy the painting from the
Russell estate, a claim Russell's heirs deny.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwabs say they planned to give the museum the money to buy
40 percent of the painting, and they would pay for 60 percent of
the $44 million purchase. According to their statement, they
planned to make their share of the painting a ``promised gift'' to
the museum upon their deaths. They claim that Haas' three grown
children ``reneged on the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to SFMOMA's board of trustees expressing ``dismay at
the Museum's threats to sue us,'' Russell's heirs _ Alice
Russell-Shapiro, Charles P. Russell and Christine H. Russell _ say
they were ``led to believe that there would be sole use of the
painting by the Museum, and ultimately sole ownership by the
Museum.'' When they learned that the painting would be jointly
owned and used, they say, they decided not to proceed with the
sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have an agreement until both parties sign on the
dotted line,'' said their attorney, Roger Mead of the San Francisco
firm of Folger, Levin &AMP; Kahn. ``We are confident that when the
museum trustees give the matter proper consideration, they will
conclude that it would be reckless to pursue these baseless
claims.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schwabs and SFMOMA may sue. Cohler said, ``Mr. and Mrs.
Schwab wish to see the museum made whole again and do not intend to
seek (personal) damages.''
</P>
<P>
