<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8906 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-RUMBLE-SPI &LR;      04-06 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RUMBLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`READY TO RUMBLE' TAKES A DIVE IN SEWER OF POTTY HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C-  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thick-headed hicks Gordie Boggs (David Arquette) and Sean
Dawkins (Scott Caan) live for wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Septic tank cleaners by day (where the toilet humor runs like an
open sewer), they spend their nights in worship to their hero, WCW
champion Jimmy King (Oliver Platt), unaware he is just a soused
prima donna who's forgotten that his reign is the result of careful
scripting.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as no shock when King loses his crown in a last minute
rewrite by Titus Sinclair (Joe Pantoliano), the man we love to hate
league president (and a fairly transparent swipe at rival WWF
president Vince McMahon). Muscle-bound villain Diamond Dallas Page
takes the crown and Sinclair bans King for life.
</P>
<P>
   But fear not, for Boggs and Dawkins become knights errant to
their tarnished King, now a bitter drunkard hiding from debtors in
trailer park, put him back in touch with his white trash roots, and
challenge Sinclair and Diamond Dallas to a dreaded Death Match: a
pay-per-view exclusive that could leave King dead, or worse,
embarrassed!
</P>
<P>
   With his beer belly and abs of flab, Platt only look slightly
less convincing as a modern day wrestling star than, say, Adam
Sandler (``Memo to Mr. Sandler: I've got your next vehicle right
here!'').
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by real life icons of the WCW like Goldberg, Sting
and Page, all of whom have a better sense of what this about than
the actors, Platt is less wrestling royalty than drawling Elvis
wannabe, a white trash showman trading the karate chop moves of
overweight Vegas showman for body slams and pile-drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Director Brian Robbins (``Varsity Blues'') shows little facility
for comedy. Squirrelly Arquette flops all over the place with
eye-ball rolling goofiness and the usually dependable Platt mugs
shamelessly. The gifted Martin Landau is wasted as a spry old-time
wrestler with more moves up his tights than Fred Astaire and indie
sexpot Rose McGowan becomes mere window dressing: her tight
sweaters and hot pants become the defining elements of her
conniving WCW Nitro dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Brill's flat-footed script begins as an idiot comedy
with the gross-out gags of a Farrelly Bros. film. But when it loses
the anything-for-a-laugh excess, there's little left. Real
professional wrestling has become such a circus of outrageous
stunts and soap opera mythology that this winds up less parody than
pale imitation.
</P>
<P>
   Ready to Rumble. Directed by Brian Robbins. Screenplay by
Stephen Brill. Cast: David Arquette, Oliver Platt, Scott Caan, Rose
McGowan, Martin Landau, Joe Pantoliano. Warner Bros. 100 Minutes.
Rated PG-13 for language, crude humor, sexual content including
brief nudity and wrestling violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8907 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0407-     04-06 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-0407-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RUSSIA FACES SUSPENSION FROM HUMAN RIGHTS BODY FOR CHECHEN WAR
OFFENSES
 &HT;    (400&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine _ Striking a severe blow to Russia's international
prestige, the Council of Europe voted on Thursday to suspend
Russia's membership in the human rights body because of Moscow's
controversial and bloody war in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The move is a slap in the face to Russia's President-elect
Vladimir Putin, who gained popularity at home thanks to the war and
made closer ties to the West part of his election platform.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin's reaction to the vote was indignant. Its
parliamentary delegation walked out of the Strasbourg, France-based
body, founded in 1949 to promote democracy and human rights in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not able to participate in the work of the
parliamentary assembly in the Council of Europe. We regret that
this has happened,'' the head of the Russian delegation, Dmitry
Rogozin, told the assembly seconds after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of Russians support the offensive, despite
growing evidence reported by international journalists and human
rights organizations of summary executions, rape and looting by the
Russian army against civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia has violated some of its most important obligations
under both the European Convention on Human Rights and
international humanitarian law,'' said the text of the motion,
passed in a 78-to-64 vote. It asked governments to report back to
the Assembly in June, saying that they should start suspension
proceedings against Russia ``should substantial, accelerating and
demonstrable progress not be made immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution, however, could only be a symbolic act. The
41-nation organization has little real power. For the vote to take
affect, the governments must also approve of the action. No nation
has been suspended in the body's 51-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said this could be unlikely, given international
governments' past refusal to risk upsetting the world's
second-largest nuclear power on most issues, like corruption,
economics and foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russia's behavior in Chechnya certainly does not correspond to
European standards, and in principle Russia should be sanctioned,''
said Boris Makarenko, deputy director of the Center for Political
Technologies, a Moscow-based think tank.
</P>
<P>
   ``But suspension would provoke (the Russian government) to slam
the door and stop cooperating with the West,'' he added. ``No
Western country wants to shut the door on a nuclear power.''
</P>
<P>
   Russia has denied allegations against its army. Moscow defends
the offensive as a war against terrorism, saying that if abuses by
the army have occurred then they are the exception, rather than the
rule.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   However, uproar over Moscow's offensive has swelled in recent
weeks, with polite diplomatic exchanges being replaced by
out-and-out condemnation. After a weekend trip to the war-torn
region, United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights Mary
Robinson told reporters she was shocked about what she saw and what
she heard from some of the 200,000 refugees who have fled fighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to testimony of summary executions, intimidation,
looting by military personnel, disproportionate use of force,
attacks on civilian convoys, rape and other violations,'' she said.
``These accounts corroborate much of the serious and documented
information available so far, and they require a serious
response.''
</P>
<P>
   After her trip, the Council of Europe's political committee met
Tuesday and recommended the larger body sanction Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has made a few small, conciliatory steps to calm world
opinion. Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov announced Tuesday that Moscow
would allow Council of Europe observers to take part in a
Russian-led investigation into army abuses. The army has also
arrested one colonel, alleging he raped and killed a Chechen girl.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
