<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8912 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-FAIL-SAFE-PREVIEW-LAD     04-06 1503
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIL-SAFE-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOWHERE TO HIDE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Clooney usually comes across as self-assured, but on
Wednesday he was more like a nervous bridegroom. Sure, he loves her
and wants to get married, but can he get through the ceremony
without throwing up?
</P>
<P>
   The cause of his anxiety is Sunday's live broadcast of the Cold
War drama ``Fail Safe'' on CBS. Based on the 1962 best-selling
novel by Harvey Wheeler and Eugene Burdick, ``Fail Safe'' deals
with a B-52 bomber dispatched by computer error to drop a
20-megaton nuclear warhead on Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   It will be the first live broadcast of a dramatic movie on any
network since CBS' ``Playhouse 90,'' which ended its four-year run
in May 1960.
</P>
<P>
   When Clooney, the rest of the cast and all the behind-the-scenes
honchos met with reporters Wednesday during a rehearsal break,
their mood was jovial, but it was clear all were feeling the
deadline creeping up on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in over our heads a little bit right now, we're a little
crazed,'' Clooney said with a chuckle. ``Everybody's here because
we want to be here and because we think it might be fun, and we're
not quite sure if we can pull it off but we're going to give it a
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clooney plays the bomber pilot, Col. Jack Grady, and is
executive producing the project with his Maysville Pictures
partner, Pam Williams, and former Fox 2000 chief Laura Ziskin.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen it before, the TV movie or special with this star or
that one billed as executive producer. ``Yeah, right,'' we say,
dismissing the credit as unbelievable as a pair of Nikes labeled
``made in the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the case, though, with Clooney, who was the catalyst
behind the live episode of ``ER'' in 1997. Although he was
disappointed with some aspects of that show, it whetted his
appetite for more.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week, at the end of another long day of
juggling rehearsals and production details, Clooney sounded as
energized and enthused as if it were the first time someone had
asked him about ``Fail Safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's !ital!insane,'' he said of the mood in the production
office and two massive Warner stages. ``The Omaha war room is
gigantic. It literally takes up all of Stage 15. It's huge. It's
the biggest set I've ever seen. It's just gigantic. It's
ridiculous. We have a 38-foot screen of the (radar) map that's
constantly in motion, the map of the planes going in and out. It's
great.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke in detail about the 22 camera operators (many of whom
will be in Army uniforms so they can move through the background
unnoticed), potential logistics problems, the art of special
effects for live TV and other particulars.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney was a hands-on executive producer from the start, when
he pitched ``Fail Safe'' to CBS Television president Les Moonves,
through the selection of director Stephen Frears (``Dangerous
Liaisons'' and the just-released ``High Fidelity'') and the casting
of Richard Dreyfuss, Hank Azaria, Noah Wyle, Harvey Keitel, Brian
Dennehy, Don Cheadle, Sam Elliott, James Cromwell and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney, 38, has remained grounded amid Hollywood stardom by
staying close with his longtime friends, a philosophy he applied to
this job. Indeed, someday people might sit around at parties
playing Six Degrees of Fail Safe.
</P>
<P>
   Clooney worked with Keitel in ``From Dusk Till Dawn,'' knew
Cheadle from ``Out of Sight'' and, of course, Wyle from ``ER.''
Frears directed Elliott in ``The Hi-Lo Country'' and made ``Hero''
with producer Ziskin. Ziskin, meanwhile, headed the Fox film
division for which Clooney made ``One Fine Day,'' and she produced
``What About Bob?'' starring Dreyfuss. Clooney also brought in Tom
Park, who produced the live ``ER'' episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were the people we went to first because we know them
and we like them,'' Clooney said. ``These guys don't do a lot of
television, if any, but they could do something if you do it live
... and then it's a story they all happen to like very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's getting any money here,'' he added. ``It's a very
expensive project. But it's all up on the screen because I
literally had to call them up and say, `Look, I was paid this
amount of money to do it as an actor and a producer, and I took it
and put it back into the production, because my name's on it and I
can't have my name on something and have it not work. There's no
back end (payoff) on this because it's live. There's nothing to
offer you except six weeks of terror if you want to do it,' and
everyone came on board and said, 'Sure.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's terror of dwelling for hours each day in a make-believe
nuclear crisis, and terror in playing it live before millions of
viewers. Producer Park said there will be no cue cards, despite the
fact that as of Wednesday afternoon some of the actors still were
referring to their scripts. ``No net. That's one of George's
favorite phrases for this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the program runs short because of, say, an adrenaline-rushed
pace or dropped lines, Azaria joked, ``We all have songs
prepared,'' and Norman Lloyd said he will recite Shakespeare's
sonnets.
</P>
<P>
   Azaria compared it to an auto race. ``I'm sure half the people
will be watching to see who's going to mess up.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfuss, Keitel, Dennehy and William Smitrovich talked about
the appeal of ``Fail Safe's'' anti-nuclear-war message and the
importance of getting it across to a young audience.
</P>
<P>
   But Clooney said Wednesday that his choice of this story ``had
nothing to do with its relevance, politically or socially.'' The
1964 feature starring Henry Fonda, Dan O'Herlihy and Walter Matthau
has been his favorite film since he first saw it as a teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Even as he settled on the title, he also resolved to shoot it in
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black and white makes it more cinematic,'' he said. ``Part of
the pitch I had with Les was to make sure it's in black and white
because it's a back-breaker if it's in color. It looks like a porno
film without the sex. It just looks cheaper than hell.''
</P>
<P>
   The live broadcast for the eastern and central time zones will
have the crisp look generated by 16 digital cameras, but on the
West Coast where it will air delayed, the picture will seem
old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to have real hot whites, real high contrast, so it
should look like kinescopes,'' Clooney said. Cinematographer John
Alonzo has framed the shots in a near-letterbox configuration, he
said, with borders at the top and bottom of the TV picture to add
to the cinematic effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been doing the camera tests and we're able to get the
camera literally about six inches from our faces, so we're able to
get these closeups just of eyes,'' Clooney said. ``It's pretty
shocking what we're able to do with very little light because we're
using digital cameras.''
</P>
<P>
   He said one of the most compelling aspects of director Sidney
Lumet's original film was its complete lack of music. He and
screenwriter Walter Bernstein, who also scripted the 1964 movie,
stayed with that concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``The silence and the room tone alone are part of what you sell
the story with,'' Clooney explained. ``I'm a big fan of that whole
MTV look and how we've oversaturated the senses with rapid cuts,
but now with this, what we're trying to do _ which they did really
successfully in the film _ is sort of resensitize people to
stillness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There're going to be great moments where you're just going to
see the president (Dreyfuss) and the translator (Wyle) sitting in
this white room and a single table with a single phone on the
desk,'' he said. ``It's going to be 30 seconds while they wait for
the Soviet premier to get on the line of just pure silence, and
with any luck at all that will be as interesting as all these rapid
cuts have been over the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really, really, really great storytelling,'' he said.
``It takes a lot of patience because television doesn't like to sit
still at all now. But that's part of the fun of this.''
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well with ``Fail Safe'' _ as judged by Clooney's
standards, the ratings, the reviews and the reactions of Moonves
and key sponsors Ford and State Farm _ Clooney would like to do
other live television dramas, although he says there aren't any
projects in the pipeline just yet.
</P>
<P>
   USC professor Barbara Corday, creator of ``Cagney &AMP; Lacey'' and
former head of CBS prime time and Columbia Pictures Television,
loves the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I can't imagine the downside of this,'' Corday said.
``In terms of the future, if someone like George would say, 'Once a
year or every 18 months I'm going to do this and it's going to be
fully sponsored by X and I'm going to get all my movie friends to
be in it, I just can't imagine anyone turning that down.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Clooney is only making plans for what he'll be
doing right after Sunday's broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drinking,'' he said. Several of his co-stars nodded in
agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1518EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
