<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREAT OF NUCLEAR WAR NO FANTASY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VALERIE KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While ``Fail-Safe'' is set in the early 1960s, when computer
technology in defense systems was primative and Cold War tensions
were at their peak, the Global Security Institute maintains the
threat of nuclear war ``is not ancient history.''
</P>
<P>
   The institute, founded by former California Sen. Alan Cranston,
is using Sunday night's telecast as an opportunity to spread its
disarmament message with discussions and screenings at 10 college
campuses nationwide, including UCLA and Loyola Marymount
University.
</P>
<P>
   Both Los Angeles campuses will show the program at 9 p.m.,
preceded by an hourlong talk with defense and disarmament experts.
</P>
<P>
   Former Canadian Prime Minister Kim Campbell, institute vice
president Tad Daley, former UC regent Stanley Sheinbaum and Robert
Scheer of the Los Angeles Times are slated to speak at the UCLA
program at Sproul Hall. Parking is available at the Sunset Village
parking structure for $5.
</P>
<P>
   The Loyola Marymount event, held in the library auditorium, will
feature theology professors Thomas Rausch and Daniel
Smith-Christopher as well as Dr. James Yamazaki of the Nagasaki
Atomic Bomb Casualty Commission and Jonathan Parfrey of Physicians
for Social Responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Similar events have been organized at Stanford (where Cranston
will speak), UC Berkeley, Notre Dame, the University of Michigan,
the University of Maryland, Swarthmore, Columbia and Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Daley said although the constantly flying bombers central to the
``Fail-Safe'' plot have been grounded for nearly a decade,
accidental nuclear war still is possible because of the ``launch on
warning'' strategies in place in the United States and Russia. Both
nations would fire their own missiles 30 minutes after detecting an
attacking missile. In 1995, he noted, Russia was three minutes away
from attacking the United States after mistaking a weather
satellite for an incoming warhead.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Security Institute has designated Monday as a
``Fail-Safe'' national call-in day, urging concerned citizens to
call the White House and the campaigns of presidential candidates
George W. Bush and Al Gore to press for global nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (310) 458-2694 or go to www.prs.org
or www.gsinstitute.org on the Web. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
