<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, April 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CYPRIOT-ART-MET (New York) _ In the new Cypriot galleries at the
Metropolitan Museum, the 600 objects range from colossal sculptures
to poppy-size juglets. And everywhere there are traces of the
various superpowers _ Egypt, Greece, Assyria, Rome _ that
established a presence and contributed to the sweetly unglamorous
carnival of styles known as Cypriot art. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2.
</P>
<P>
   RAMEAU-BAROQUE-MUSIC (Undated) _ Is there a Baroque beyond Bach?
Yes, though you might be hard put to find it this year, which
commemorates the 250th anniversary of the master's death. Still,
there are outcroppings of Vivaldi here, of Handel there. Now comes
the turn of the fascinating figure of Jean-Philippe Rameau. Some
favorite Rameau recordings of the classical-music critics of The
New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-DISTRICT (Pittsburgh) _ Heinz Hall for the
Performing Arts opened in 1971, with its plush three-story-high
domed lobby and an arcade of Corinthian columns with gilded
capitals. This became the turning point and the gold standard for
an imaginative urban renaissance based on Heinz's theory that the
arts lead the way to economic development. Rather than destroying
an old neighborhood to build a congested performing arts center,
Pittsburgh opted to create a performing arts district: many of its
cultural institutions are housed in the restored regal surroundings
of its surviving movie palaces, scattered through a 14-square-block
area that had been a red-light district. It is now called the
Pittsburgh Cultural District and is overseen by the 16-year-old
Pittsburgh Cultural Trust. By Paula Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
