<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-AWACS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASHING ALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was an attention-getter, to say the least. There was
Secretary of Defense William Cohen standing alongside Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak Monday in Jerusalem, chastizing Israel for its
pending delivery of an AWACS-type surveillance plane to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Such official American criticism of Israel is rare, and rarer
still was Cohen's overt airing of differences at a joint press
conference. Coming as it did at a time when Washington is laboring
mightily to mediate Israeli peace agreements with the Palestinians
and Syria _ accords that are expected to entail considerable new
infusions of US aid to Israel _ Cohen's disapproval of the AWACS
sale signified an unusual clash of Israeli and US interests.
</P>
<P>
   The bellicose threats Beijing issued during the runup to
Taiwan's recent presidential election underlined how perilous to
Asian stability an arms race between the island and the mainland
could be. Cohen did not mince words when lamenting Israel's role in
stimulating such an arms race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States does not support the sale of this type of
technology to China because of the potential of changing the
strategic balance in that region, with the tensions running high as
they are between China and Taiwan,'' Cohen said. Left unsaid was
the potential of the Israeli surveillance aircraft to help Beijing
overcome the qualitative edge in military technology enjoyed by
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen could not be expected to demand that Israel cancel its
contracts with China because, when Israel first submitted the sale
to the Pentagon for vetting, it was told that the sale was
permissible since there are no American components in the
surveillance planes and the sale involved no transfer to China of
US technology.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen had to complain about Israel threatening the strategic
balance in Asia because, in the four years it took Israel Aircraft
Industries to roll out the first of four airborne radar systems it
hopes to sell to Beijing, things changed in the geopolitics around
the Taiwan Strait. If Israel now wants to show itself a faithful
ally, it will forgo the sale of the other three AWACS planes China
wanted to buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1522EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
