<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8928 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-ENGAGEMENT-SPI &LR;      04-06 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ENGAGEMENT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S NO DEFENDING THE BEFUDDLED `RULES OF ENGAGEMENT' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: D  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The credits (which include a former secretary of the Navy as
executive producer) and advertising for the military drama ``Rules
of Engagement'' would lead one to expect the most intelligent and
thought-provoking Hollywood court-martial thriller since ``A Few
Good Men.''
</P>
<P>
   And those expectations are heightened when the film opens with
not one but two devastating action sequences _ one set in 1968
Vietnam, the other in contemporary Yemen _ that recall director
William Friedkin's heyday of ``The French Connection'' and ``The
Exorcist.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's downhill from this point on and, by the time the film
plummets to its rock bottom, we find ourselves in a flag-waving
no-brainer of the first order, and one of the most thoroughly
confused morality tales in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of Col. Terry Childers (Samuel L. Jackson), a
highly decorated U.S. Marine officer, who, in the midst of an
operation to rescue the besieged U.S. ambassador to Yemen and his
family, orders his men to fire into a crowd that's attacking the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   When 83 civilians, including women and children, are killed, a
slimy National Security adviser (Bruce Greenwood) decides to
destroy a surveillance tape that proves the crowd was filled with
armed snipers and prosecute Childers for murder _ hoping this will
placate our angry allies in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   To defend him at his court-martial, Childers chooses a fellow
Marine, Col. Hays Hodges (Tommy Lee Jones), an old buddy from the
Vietnam War whose life he saved in the prologue _ a man with his
own demons who is not much of a lawyer and even less of a
detective.
</P>
<P>
   From here, we have to watch Childers as he's ``hung out to dry''
_ spit on by protesters, perjured in the courtroom and made to look
like an out-of-control psychopath, even though we know he's
innocent of the charges and an all-around great American who wants
nothing out of life but the privilege of serving his country.
</P>
<P>
   As a drama, it's all very heavy-handed and plodding: filled with
one-note characters, mindless patriotic sentiment and tiresome
macho bonding rituals. (At one point, the two 50 year-old Marines
duke it out in Childers' quarters, and come up bloody and smiling _
like we're suddenly in a John Wayne movie!).
</P>
<P>
   As a legal thriller, its not just weak, but a Swiss cheese of
story holes and non sequiturs. Childers' whole defense depends on
proving the crowd was armed and yet no one even thinks of calling
to the stand one of the Marines who carried out Childers' orders
and surely would have been in a perfect position to see the crowd.
And that's just one of maybe a dozen points that makes you want to
grab the screenwriter by the throat.
</P>
<P>
   As a morality tale, the film is even more of a disaster. It asks
us, ultimately, to see Childers as a noble warrior and a put-upon
martyr, but we clearly see him commit a war crime in the Vietnam
prologue _ callously executing an unarmed POW _ and he doesn't even
try to disperse the crowd of mostly women and children by shooting
over its head.
</P>
<P>
   But, by far, the biggest failing of ``Rules of Engagement'' is
that it simply can't make us believe its preposterous premise _
that the U.S. government would rather have another William Calley
scandal on its hands than face a few Arab allies with evidence that
its man acted in self-defense. It just doesn't make any sense.
</P>
<P>
   Rules of Engagement. Directed by William Friedkin. Cast: Tommy
Lee Jones, Samuel L. Jackson, Guy Pearce, Bruce Greenwood, Anne
Archer, Ben Kingsley. Paramount. 123 minutes. Rated R for combat
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1527EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8930 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-400&AMP;ADD-NY     04-06 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SAYS IT HAS FINISHED MAP OF HUMAN GENOME 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Celera Corp. said Thursday that it has sequenced the human
genome, in effect discovering the sequence of DNA molecules in
which information on human heredity is inscribed.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, a private company in Rockville, Md., has been racing
government-sponsored researchers to decode the human genome, which
offers a blueprint to life. The company, which was established
barely two years ago, reported that it would now attempt to
assemble the genetic fragments in their proper order.
</P>
<P>
   Celera's announcement Thursday drove the stock up nearly 25
percent, to $143 a share, by noon.
</P>
<P>
   Discovering the sequence is an essential step toward mapping the
entire human genome, though the real challenge will be to put the
sequence together properly. Celera said in a statement issued
Thursday that it expected to complete the task over the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   The progress is significant because assembling the full sequence
could transform the eventual practice of biology and medicine,
providing doctors with a roadmap for confronting diseases at the
genetic level and programming the human organism to combat them.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton announced last month that the United States
and Britain had agreed to cooperate by sharing research data to
break the codes governing human genetics, and invited private
companies to join the effort. But some, like Celera, prefer to
proceed alone.
</P>
<P>
   The length of the human genome involves at least 3 billion bases
of DNA, and calculations suggest that the sequence needs to be
established a half dozen times to ensure that the assembly is
accurate.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty in comprehending the formula has been that
genomes in living creatures contain numerous repeats, which are
copies of stretches of DNA that follow nearly identical sequences,
confusing the assembly process.
</P>
<P>
   Celera's scientists said earlier this year that they had
developed techniques for bridging the repeat stretches to
unscramble at least some of them.
</P>
<P>
   The company's research involved establishing the DNA sequence of
a single anonymous man. The male genome is considered
scientifically more interesting because it contains both the X and
the Y chromosome, while female genomes contain only the X
chromosome.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Venter, Celera's chairman and chief scientific officer,
told Reuters Thursday that ``Now that we have completed the
sequencing of one human being's genome, we will turn our
computational power to the task of ordering the human genome.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The company next plans to assemble the final human genome
sequence from the genes of five anonymous people. This would allow
the researchers to compare the donated genes to detect the minute
changes that make one human being different from another.
</P>
<P>
   The competing public consortium of researchers subsidized by the
government is sequencing a ``mosaic'' genome in which different
segments are taken from about 10 anonymous donors.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, whose operation employs 300 sequencing machines and the
largest known civilian computer, last month reported assembling the
sequencing of the genome of a fruit fly.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the magazine Science, two researchers, Eugene W.
Myers and Edward Winstead, explained that the assembly began with
3.1 million fragments of the genome, which they described as
``random bits of fly DNA that have been converted into characters
that a computer can read.'' The fragments, they said, provided
enough DNA to cover the genome 14 times over.
</P>
<P>
   The task, they said, had been ``to arrange these DNA sequences
into a properly ordered and nearly complete genome,'' by matching
the overlapping sequences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
