<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8947 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX     04-06 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENETIC ALTERATIONS: SOMETHING TO CHEW OVER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, the organic farmer known as Prince sent shock
waves through the world of big agriculture, food processing and
associated businesses by vehemently denouncing genetically modified
foods.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles, presumably the heir to the British throne, said
he bloody well wouldn't eat GM foods, and neither would he serve
the flaming stuff to his family or his guests.
</P>
<P>
   The British government was anything but pleased with the man who
might be king someday for poking his nose into such serious
business. That's not in his royal job description.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of Charles' untimely comments, the real British
government was mounting a campaign to persuade domestic and foreign
corporations that British consumers could be convinced to accept GM
foods as safe to eat.
</P>
<P>
   But the prince came along and rekindled a public debate on GM
foods that until then had subsided into a low simmer. Asserting
that he didn't think it was right to ``tamper with the building
blocks of nature,'' the Prince of Wales, in an interview in ``The
Independent'' later that year, called for ``sustained pressure from
consumers demanding choice in the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   In his earlier interview in The London Daily Mail, the would-be
monarch referred to laboratory tests indicating that pollen from GM
maize in the United States caused damage to the caterpillars of
monarch butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   He also labeled arguments that GM foods offer hope for
eliminating hunger in the world and raising people out of poverty
as ``emotional blackmail.''
</P>
<P>
   The prince's views on GM foods, of course, have to be taken with
several spoons of salt. He is Britain's most renowned exponent and
practitioner of organic farming. At his Highgrove estate in
Gloucestershire, they grow their vegetables without the use of
chemical fertilizers, pesticides or gene splicing.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for organic food has boomed in Britain since the prince
took his public stand. And the waves he made in England about GM
foods have wafted to the shores of this country, Japan and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Just as is the case in the United States, some Australian
experts have challenged the prince's views on the safety of GM
foods. Dr. Geoffrey Annison, scientific and technical director of
the Australian Food and Grocery Council, said the technology has
been built up over 50 years of comprehensive research into the way
that genetic characteristics are transmitted from one organism to
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who suggests that safety work has not been done
doesn't really know what's going on,'' Annison said in The Sydney
Morning Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Then Annison posed this dilemma:
</P>
<P>
   ``If you work out we will need one million tons of soyabean in
2020, and using current technology we can only reach half that,
then we have two choices. We can use more land, or we can increase
yield.''
</P>
<P>
   Therein lies the crux of the issue. GM foods offer the
possibility of using less of the world's land for food production,
which could halt deforestation and soil depletion. At the same
time, biotechnology advances associated with GM food production
offer the prospect of accelerating reforestation and reclamation of
natural habitat.
</P>
<P>
   That is not emotional blackmail. The alternative is to clear
more forest and lay waste to more arable land to feed the world's
growing population.
</P>
<P>
   Prince Charles talks bloody nonsense when he asserts that a lack
of food is not the underlying cause of starvation in some of the
world's poorest places. That's like saying that the primary reason
for a car stalling on the freeway is not that its fuel tank is
empty.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, wars, a lack of infrastructure, and corrupt and inept
governments play major roles in preventing food from getting to
hungry people in some parts of the world. But a lot of people could
starve before those problems are solved.
</P>
<P>
   Even if those obstacles were overcome, the answer to the food
problems of developing nations cannot be organic, land-intensive
farming. For better or for worse, the day of the small farmer is
plowing to an end. The challenge for the developing world is find
other things for most of the people to do for a living besides
subsistence farming.
</P>
<P>
   Still, like the protesters in Boston who demonstrated outside
the recent BIO2000 convention, Prince Charles has raised some
legitimate issues. They may not really know what they are talking
about, but their concerns need to be taken seriously.
Biotechnologists need to do a better job of explaining what is
happening in their field to the uninformed masses.
</P>
<P>
   In this country, it is well that Congress is considering
legislation that would require understandable labeling of foods
that have been genetically altered or contain such ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   There are several grains of truth spliced into the simplistic
statement, ``We are what we eat.'' That being the case, American
consumers need to know as much as possible about what they are
eating.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
