</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-SHANGHAI-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEDALING THEIR WAY TO SHANGHAI'S VIRTUAL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480,
fax 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333, fax
212-499-3382.)
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 By GRACE FAN  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Every day of the week, wiry, 27-year-old Zhang Minyou hoists 40
to 80 water jugs out of his smart, 19th-century-styled pedicart,
trudges through a labyrinth of laundry-lined alleys and groans his
way up dozens of creaky stairs.
</P>
<P>
   After delivering the goods to one customer, Minyou, an Aquarius
water deliveryman, hops back on his tricycle to peddle to his next
customer through Shanghai's byzantine streets.
</P>
<P>
   He is a cheap but crucial link in an idiosyncratic door-to-door
mainland distribution system that fills orders placed with the
click of a 21st-century mouse.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, this ``fulfillment'' can be left to
domestic mail carriers, such as the United States Postal Service
and United Parcel Service, that offer easy, efficient delivery,
making the transition from a virtual to a physical world a seamless
process for new Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   But in China, where the dreams of dot-com wealth soar as high as
the obstacles to e-commerce _ such as snail mail that deserves the
name, a balkanized banking system and a near-absence of consumer
credit cards _ success calls for a kind of ingenuity not taught at
business school.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of credit-card transactions, cash on delivery is the
most common method of e-commerce payment. Instead of relying on
delivery companies, start-ups like MyWeb of San Francisco are
becoming partners with a rare combination of local distributors,
including fleets of taxis and university students on bicycles.
</P>
<P>
   The auction house EachNet, with listings that span nine mainland
cities, links buyers and sellers in any given city. After the
bidding is closed, they arrange to meet each other face to face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just last June, there wasn't a lot being done,'' says Ted
Dean, a partner at the Beijing-based Internet consulting company
BDA. ``Now there are entrepreneurs setting up partnerships,
delivering goods, marketing to customers and dealing with
processing returns. Even if China's still in the early stages of
e-commerce, even if most transactions are still cash on delivery,
the Net companies are actually solving the next set of marketing
and logistical problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In a reversal of conventional Internet wisdom, traditional
brick-and-mortar, state-owned enterprises that boast an established
distribution system and a valuable customer base may have an edge
over brash new Net companies struggling to overcome delivery
problems and increase online traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were virtual before we went online,'' Aquarius sales
manager Yan Boer says.
</P>
<P>
   The company's more than 400,000 customers could already order
through the network's 24-hour, seven-day a week telephone hotline
last year, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was already computerized,'' he says, ``and our
delivery system was already in place. All we needed to do was to
add a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   The site went up on Jan. 1, adding a virtual layer to an
operation that, as Yan boasted, started from the ground up as a
traditional delivery company. Trucks from the Aquarius warehouses
stop daily at more than 100 delivery depots across the city, each
equipped with a computer linked to the headquarters, where 28,000
transactions are processed on the telephone and Web daily.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 pedicart drivers gather at the depots to get
their routes each morning and load their carts. They return twice
during their 12-to-15-hour workday, to get the afternoon and
evening orders and refill their carts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cost-effective and efficient,'' Yan says, adding that
Aquarius, a unit of one of Shanghai's largest food companies, plans
to expand its operations to seven more cities this year.
</P>
<P>
   Unspoken is the fact that a distribution system like this
depends on a cheap migrant work force flooding into the major
cities from poorer provinces, working for as little as 36 cents an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Minyou the pedicart driver says it's better than Anhui,
the province south of Shanghai where he came from.
</P>
<P>
   ``Food costs next to nothing here,'' he says, ``so I can save a
lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   As he hops on his tricycle and prepares to peddle half a mile
through icy winds to his next delivery site, Li Zhongshen, a
35-year-old driver and former rice farmer, says that such work will
always fall to migrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``No Shanghainese could do this anyway,'' he says. ``They
wouldn't be able to stand it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Grace Fan is a Shanghai-based free-lance writer.) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
