<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8950 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f BC-ECOM-NONCOMMERCIAL-SI     04-06 1331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-NONCOMMERCIAL-SITES-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS ANYONE NOT OUT FOR E-BILLIONS? JOSIE TRUE, FOR ONE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ANDREA ADELSON  
 c.2000 The New York Times   
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;  &QL;
<P>
   Josie True, a Chinese-American cartoon girl in an online game,
hunts for her missing teacher by time-traveling. Along the way, she
strikes up conversations with little-known historical heroines like
Bessie Coleman, the first African-American to earn an international
pilot's license.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most Web-based action games, which generally interest
boys, ``The Adventures of Josie True'' is designed to appeal to
girls' interests in characters and narratives. In sly fashion,
Josie also introduces players to role models absent from most
history books, while increasing their computer fluency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a moneymaking scheme,'' said Mary Flanagan, an
assistant professor of media studies at the University of Buffalo,
who is developing the game with a grant of $199,920 from the
National Science Foundation. Her concern is the lack of educational
software aimed at girls, particularly minority girls.
</P>
<P>
   Tapping this overlooked market, Flanagan thought, could help
solve a stubborn gender gap. Girls still take fewer advanced
computer-science classes than boys and are more likely to shy away
from careers like engineering, said a 1998 report by the American
Association of University Women. Part of the reason, the report
said, was that boys play computer games more than girls and enter
classrooms far more comfortable with computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a software developer's dream to do something you're
committed to,'' said Flanagan, who hired graduate students to
finish the online game
(www.buffalo.edu &QC; /scripts/newnews/index.cgi?article &QC; (EQ)theadventu)
by the end of this year. For schools and girls without Web access,
Flanagan intends to produce CD-ROMs. With modest government
assistance and a passion for closing the digital gender gap,
Flanagan is demonstrating how the Internet can be an egalitarian
tool for self-expression. The site, like other noncommercial sites
being developed around the United States, is intended to be an
example of high-minded goals that have not been eclipsed by the
cacophony of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Without millions of dollars of investors' money to buy
mass-market advertising, noncommercial sites, especially ones
catering to untapped or underserved sectors, face an uphill battle
as they try to gather like-minded audiences from the far corners of
cyberspace. But such efforts are far from a lost cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not different from any other medium,'' said Ekaterina
Walsh, a consumer analyst for Forrester Research in Cambridge,
Mass. Compared with slickly packaged Web content for mass
audiences, original and unadorned sites are a breath of fresh air
that gain word-of-mouth (or e-mail) credibility ``in the same way
NPR and PBS stand out on radio and TV,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   And developers of noncommercial sites can salve their dot-com
envy with a patina of respect. Research shows that consumers are
more likely to trust nonprofit sites than commercial ones, Walsh
said.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to penetrate popular culture through radio and television
advertisements, some developers of noncommercial sites have
resorted to grass-roots efforts to build an audience, particularly
among those without Internet connections. This approach can be
successful when the audience itself ends up being the supplier of
low-cost content.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in public libraries in Newark, Harlem and
Melbourne, Australia, youngsters are dabbling at a test site,
www.kahootz.com.au, where they can create and publish animated
stories and inventions online, then ``chat'' about their work.
</P>
<P>
   At a recent tryout of the site in Newark, schoolchildren on two
continents showed off their child-centric creations: a homework
helper and a dirt-to-food machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating a channl for interactive design to stimulate
girls and kids who don't have computers at home, to get them to
start thinking of themselves as designers and inventors,'' said
Dorothy T. Bennett, the project director of the Education
Development Center for Children and Technology, which is developing
the site with the Children's Television Foundation in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Another grass-roots project has already drawn participation from
nearly 1,000 children in 139 countries. Their contributions filled
an online bulletin board devoted to how young people believe
technology can improve the world. The first Web site,
www.jrsummit.net, spawned a second, www.nation1.org. The project
began with professors at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology
Media Lab, who contacted education officials around the world to
attract young people to participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about bringing underrepresented groups online,'' said
Justine Cassell, a Media Lab professor who was one of the program's
organizers and is a co-editor of the book ``From Barbie to Mortal
Kombat: Gender and Computer Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Another approach to reaching such an overlooked audience comes
from Oakland, Calif., the eighth-largest city in the state.
Pummeled by the 1989 earthquake and a catastrophic fire in 1994,
the city is struggling to make an economic comeback, particularly
in East and West Oakland, which are characterized by a mix of
stately but aging Victorian houses, boarded-up storefronts and few
commercial services, like supermarkets and bank branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the underserved communities to move to the served
category,'' the community, not corporations, will have to create
the content, said David Geilhufe, the director of the Eastmont
Computing Center in Oakland, where 350 people receive computer
training financed by the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   This version of urban renewal is aimed at compressing the
digital divide in poorer neighborhoods without typically putting
computers in every classroom. Instead, the city and its
philanthropic partners are counting on the virtual world to provide
banking services that are unavailable to many residents in the
community.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of developing an e-banking service in this market,
about $300,000, with investment payback expected to be slow, is
being shared by four lenders led by Union Bank of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll mobilize and test and pull people into it,'' said Donald
Vial, the chairman of the California Foundation on the Environment
and Economy, a nonprofit group in San Francisco. Starting in May,
about 200 people will use the service, which will be offered at
five community technology centers, among them Eastmont.
</P>
<P>
   Participants will receive training in computers and household
financial management and learn how to navigate an e-banking site
that will be customized for language and culture, said Norman Jayo,
the foundation's senior strategist.
</P>
<P>
   E-banking has the potential to show people that technology can
make a difference in their lives, whether by helping a small
business grow or helping someone on welfare to find a job, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A goal of Oakland's e-banking site is to show lenders and other
Web businesses that demand exists in neighborhoods being bypassed
by e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the application is significant to them, it takes off,''
Jayo said. ``It's using technology as a base for empowerment.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrea Adelson is a New York Times staff writer.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
