<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0205 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8953 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-ECOM-CEO-RECRUITING-N     04-06 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-CEO-RECRUITING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS PITCH: COME ON IN, THE WATER'S LUCRATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By SAUL HANSELL  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Who wants to be a centimillionaire?
</P>
<P>
   That is the question rattling around the most elite country
clubs and the executive washrooms of the biggest corporations, as
the nation's most experienced managers decide whether to jump to
Internet startups with little more than a business plan and a pile
of not-yet-valuable stock options.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, for those who want to take their chances, is that
Silicon Valley needs as many chief executives as Cecil B. DeMille
needed extras. Still, for the open CEO jobs and headless companies,
the mating rituals between start-up and seasoned executive are
complex. No one is likely to know them better than David Beirne, a
top technology headhunter who is now a partner in Benchmark
Capital, a leading Silicon Valley venture capital fund.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, Beirne was a partner at Ramsey/Beirne Associates
of Ossining, N.Y., and recruited top names, including Robert J.
Herbold from Procter &AMP; Gamble to be chief operating officer at
Microsoft and James Barksdale from Federal Express to be chief
executive of the young Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Beirne's switch, in 1997, to Benchmark, notable for its early
investment in eBay, the online auction company, was not as big a
jump as it might have seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do any more recruiting or any less than the other
partners here,'' Beirne said. ``But all of us spend a tremendous
amount of time recruiting for our companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, talent wins.''
</P>
<P>
   Bierne spoke about the challenges of recruiting Internet chief
executives in true Silicon Valley style _ while talking on a cell
phone as he jumped out of a taxi and ran through an airport
security check on his way home from a corporate board meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you look for in a chief executive to run an Internet
company?
</P>
<P>
   A: One size doesn't fit all. Intellect and raw leadership
ability is a given. What you really need is someone who is a magnet
for talent. Since talent is the scarcest resource and getting more
scarce, the key to success is being able to recruit a world-class
team.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is different about recruiting a chief executive for an
Internet company?
</P>
<P>
   A: What's more apparent is the need for speed. Five years ago,
people could take their time making decisions. Today, if someone
doesn't have the ability to adapt to the pace, you have to pass on
them.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you tell if a candidate can keep up with Internet
time?
</P>
<P>
   A: You have to spend a tremendous amount of time with them to
get into their heads. You also look at what culture they come from.
It's one thing to say to yourself you can deal with the pace; it's
another thing to have lived it.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that so many Internet executives were at FedEx
in the early days, like Barksdale, Christos (M. Cotsakos) of
E-Trade Group, and (William J.) Razzouk, who is now running
PlanetRx.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why would someone quit a cushy, well-paid job at the top of a
big company to join a start-up?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't believe there is such a thing as a person who can't
be recruited. You have to find the right opportunity for someone
and sell them the dream.
</P>
<P>
   A person wants to come in and really have an impact on the
world. Instead of running some division of AT&AMP;T, they want to
create something that has huge shareholder value that changes the
way people do what they do. There is a huge psychic reward to doing
that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did somebody say stock options?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most of these guys have made enough money, so it's not about
that anymore. It is about psychic gratification when the day is
done.
</P>
<P>
   There is financial reward _ if it works. There is more financial
upside and higher risk.
</P>
<P>
   Look at Shaun Holliday, who now runs Living.Com (an online
furniture store in which Benchmark has an investment). He was
running Guinness Ireland, and so he was practically running
Ireland. Now he has only $200,000 in cash compensation. But like
all these guys, he can make $100 million or more if it works.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why would you pick someone like George Shaheen, who ran
Andersen Consulting, to be the head of WebVan, an Internet grocery
store?
</P>
<P>
   A: First of all, WebVan isn't just a grocery store, it's the
last mile for the Internet. At the end of the day, it's a systems
company. Hiring a marketing guy from Pepsi wouldn't have been right
for this company. I can get all the marketing people I want to work
under him. Also, Shaheen is a great leader, a magnet for talent,
and people will follow him. And he has built a massive scale
business on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So, with all the billions that have been made by Internet
executives, are you besieged by corner-office executives who want
to run Internet companies?
</P>
<P>
   A: It certainly was different when I recruited Barksdale to
Netscape. That was a seminal event: the first time a world-class
executive ever came to run an Internet company. It was a lot more
difficult before people saw the wealth creation.
</P>
<P>
   There is now a huge number of executives who want to leave their
corporate jobs and join the next dot-com. And with success,
executives can see 10 other people with experience they can relate
to. They see they can have a fun quotient. But I don't think it's
getting any easier to find the talent you really need to have. A
lot of companies are settling just to get a body in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you have been a headhunter so long, can you save money
on fees to search firms?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. There hasn't been a time that I haven't hired a search
firm. It's another set of eyes and ears. And even if I know my
first and second choice, you need a process in place behind you if
you can't get them.
</P>
<P>
   (Saul Hansell is a New York Times staff writer.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
