<SLUG> BC-ECOM-PRICELINE.COM-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND `NAME YOUR OWN PRICE' LIES A MESH OF PARTNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 &HT;    
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ALLEN R. MYERSON  
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. _ Priceline.com does not even look like your
normal dot-com company. Its headquarters are not in Silicon Valley,
but in a suburban office park. Instead of 20-somethings in jeans
and T-shirts with long hair and short resumes, many of its
inhabitants are gray-haired recruits from companies like Citigroup
and AT&AMP;T. Some wear neat, casual clothes, while others wear suits.
</P>
<P>
   Looks are not deceiving. For all its e-commerce, new-economy
credentials, Priceline wants to be a member of the Old World
corporate club. Instead of battling older, more traditional
companies, Jay S. Walker, its 46-year-old founder and largest
shareholder, and his lieutenants have turned them into partners and
allies. If he does well, he says, so will Delta Airlines, American
Airlines, AT&AMP;T, A&AMP;P, D'Agostino's, Pathmark, the National and
Budget car rental companies and the Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't compete against these companies,'' Walker said at his
office. ``We don't seek to own an airline. We don't seek to be a
car dealer. We don't seek to be a grocery store. We don't seek to
be a phone company. We seek to improve the profitability of our
partners rather than cannibalize it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of conducting auctions with rising bids, Priceline
allows a buyer to propose a price that the seller, whether of
airline tickets or orange juice, can choose to accept or reject.
Translated into Pricelinese, this approach comes out as the slogan
``Name Your Own Price.''
</P>
<P>
   For all Priceline's establishment stripes, what Walker has in
mind is more radical than eBay, pushing a strategy that is becoming
more important throughout e-commerce: partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, when customers call up a Web site, they see a
single entrance to a structure made up of many businesses in a
tangle of alliances and subsidies. Entrepreneurs like Walker
concentrate on what they do best, finding partners for everything
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We distribute prices, not products,'' Walker said, his bushy
eyebrows rising and falling for emphasis. Priceline, he said, is
demonstrating how the Web can introduce a new series of
relationships between seller and buyer. ``You can't wheel a grocery
cart down the aisle and have AT&AMP;T say, `You know what? I'll pay for
all the meat in your grocery cart if you'll try our long-distance
service for 7 cents a minute.' The Net allows for far richer, far
more customized, instantaneously creative partnering.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, Priceline's target is not the customer who wants
favorite grocery brands delivered to the door, who wants to fly
direct flights at reasonable hours and stay in favorite hotels. All
those desires are served well by other companies and Web sites.
Priceline targets the bargain hunter.
</P>
<P>
   Stores like Wal-Mart manage to offer low prices partly by using
their size to win special breaks from their suppliers. Walker does
not. He wants sellers to have the flexibility to lower their
prices, then raise them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not use our size to try to extract concessionary
prices,'' he said. ``Sellers like us because they can use us to
balance supply and demand in a constantly changing business.''
</P>
<P>
   But isn't Walker dishing out some unrealistic bargains? Yes, he
said, at least for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model in every business is subsidize first to build
traffic,'' he said. ``Every business spends money to acquire
customers. It's every grand-opening sale that has ever existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts like Henry Blodget, at Merrill Lynch, remain optimistic
about Priceline's prospects, but they also wonder what will happen
when the grand-opening sale ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question is what happens when the discounts narrow and the
consumers won't be getting such a great deal,'' Blodget said.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said that Priceline will be able to sustain attractive
discounts. Bidding and buying through Priceline, he said, can
involve a deal with up to five parties: Priceline, the customer, a
retailer like a grocery store, a manufacturer or a service
provider, and the provider of an unrelated service like
long-distance calling or credit cards or magazine subscriptions.
</P>
<P>
   The issuer of Discover cards, for instance, will add $30 to
Priceline customers' bids for airline tickets if they apply for the
cards. Another $5 from Discover goes to Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   The corporate partners are so important to Walker that he often
identifies them, not his online buyers, as his true market, as when
he said, ``We're not here to compete with our customers.''
</P>
<P>
   His office seems like a shrine to those partners-cum-customers.
Against an incongruous background of bookshelves filled with
leather-bound classics, he displays dozens of packages _ Cheerios,
Dove soap, Joy dishwashing detergent _ and model jets.
</P>
<P>
   So strong is Walker's belief in his strategy's distinctiveness
that he has taken out several patents, recorded on plaques that
line a Priceline.com hallway, to protect his business processes. He
has sued Microsoft, maintaining that it has infringed on Priceline,
a contention Microsoft strongly disputes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this strategy will benefit consumers or investors once
consumers exhaust their specials and Wall Street starts demanding
profits is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Wall Street's passion remains strong. Though Lauren
Cooks Levitan, an analyst at Robertson Stephens, raises questions
about how many industries will be receptive to Walker's approach,
she praises the concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jay stands apart as a real visionary,'' she said. ``He
isn't just trying to shift market share online, but develop a whole
new business model.''
</P>
<P>
   The Priceline strategy has been applied to hotel rooms, rental
cars, mortgages, groceries, new cars, castoff household appliances
and, as announced just last month, gasoline, but it will not work
everywhere. Given the opportunity to offer name-your-own-terms
credit cards, many major issuers have balked, as have some large
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft Foods, a unit of Philip Morris and the nation's largest
maker of packaged foods, has also balked. So for the time being,
shoppers who want Kool-Aid, Jell-O, Post cereals, Maxwell House
coffee, Kraft cheeses or Oscar Mayer hot dogs cannot order through
Priceline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not participating,'' said Moyra Knight, a spokeswoman
for Kraft. ``We just need a better understanding of their
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Airline tickets, the closest thing to a certifiable success for
Priceline, have features that suit the company's strategy, a point
Walker readily confirmed. Airlines have to unload a highly
perishable inventory, seats that would otherwise be empty, at low
prices, without sacrificing revenue from business travelers and
others willing to pay high prices. Priceline allows the airlines to
find travelers willing to accept inconvenient connections and
departure times in return for a bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Just as clothing stores do not usually post signs telling
shoppers about their outlets, airlines do not play up their
Priceline partnerships. American Airlines, for example, refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   But other partners see so many benefits, and so few risks, that
they are happy to voice their praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stores like it and the customers seem to be happy,'' said
Nick D'Agostino III, a vice president at D'Agostino Supermarkets
Inc. of New York. Priceline allows his stores to sell groceries
over the Web at no extra cost to them, he said, because the
manufacturers provide the discounts and the customers pick up the
groceries themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Walker came to his big idea in stages. As a student at Cornell
University, he was sued by Parker Brothers to prevent him from
publishing a guide to winning at Monopoly, and watched the weekly
newspaper he started in Ithaca, N.Y., collapse under competition
from a local daily owned by the Gannett Co. chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you become more experienced in business, you learn that
picking a fight is usually the last thing you want to do,'' he
said. ``War is the ultimate failure of diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Priceline began operating in April 1998, inviting customers
to propose prices for airline tickets, its diplomacy led to the
signing of only two, relatively meek carriers: TWA and America
West. Securing major airlines as partners took money, in the form
of Priceline shares.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, Delta Airlines agreed to sell its tickets on
Priceline's Web site in return for, among other goodies, rights to
buy millions of shares for nearly nothing. Other major airlines
followed, with American and United also receiving Priceline stakes,
although smaller. The total cost to Priceline _ if not in cash, in
the ability to raise it _ is about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way they could have primed the pump without doing
that,'' Blodget said. Walker, saying that such concessions are not
habit forming, said that he has not had to give equity stakes to
any other partners.
</P>
<P>
   And if Priceline initially subsidized the tickets, paying the
airlines more than it was receiving from customers, the company is
paying less now. Marketing expenses, including those television
advertisements with the actor William Shatner, still leave
Priceline with heavy but narrowing losses.
</P>
<P>
   Will the strategy work? The results, so far, are unclear. But it
is a strategy distinct from the backward-looking approaches to
selling over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just catalogs online,'' Walker said. ``That's not
the future of e-commerce.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Allen R. Myerson is a staff writer for The New York Times.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
