r f BC-ECOM-GE-ONLINE-NYTSF &LR;      04-06 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-GE-ONLINE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO PUT GE ONLINE MEANT PUTTING A DOZEN INDUSTRIES ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    Douglas Frantz writes for The New York Times.
 By DOUGLAS FRANTZ 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Early last year, John F. Welch, the chief executive and chairman
of General Electric, set an ambitious goal for the managers of the
huge company's businesses _ establish a strategy for using the
Internet and put it into effect before the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   All 12 of GE's departments, from airplane engines to appliances
to industrial systems, met the goal that the company, long the
leader of the old economy, had set as part of its ferocious battle
to transform itself into a leader of the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   The company's speedy adaptation would not have been so
remarkable if it were another dot-com start-up or a small computer
company. But General Electric is the world's largest non-technology
company, a manufacturing and financial-services giant with $112
billion in revenue last year and 340,000 employees in about 100
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Working in teams and sharing information across the company's
global span, GE developed novel ways to do everything from speeding
up the overhaul of jet engines to buying a staple gun.
</P>
<P>
   Through the Internet, GE industrial engineers on three
continents can meet to discuss new products. Customers can go
online to buy GE mutual funds or analyze the cost and benefits of
upgrading the turbines at a generating plant.
</P>
<P>
   GE was not the first manufacturing company to adapt to the Web,
but the lessons it has been learning are more likely to affect the
rest of the industrial sector and beyond. GE has developed much of
its own Web software, but has also hired other companies to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are being smart because they are going after the Internet
in a hundred different directions,'' said William J. Fiala, an
analyst at the brokerage firm Edward D. Jones &AMP; Co., in St. Louis.
``They are big enough and rich enough to afford to take their
swings, knowing that they are going to hit a few home runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, GE has learned a few things that could apply to
any business interested in the Web. Early on, for instance, the
company determined that simply listing products and services on a
Web site, a technique known as ``brochureware,'' is not very
helpful to customers, said Gary M. Reiner, the senior vice
president who is overseeing the company's Internet strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company has developed interactive Web sites that
allow customers to buy goods and services, track their orders,
compare various products and tap into GE's technical expertise.
</P>
<P>
   The company also learned that an organizational structure based
on geography should not simply be transferred to a Web site. When
the site for GE's plastics business was unveiled last spring, there
were separate sections for the Americas, Europe and Asia. But
customers did not care about those divisions, so the site was
reorganized by products and services.
</P>
<P>
   One technique GE executives say has worked is the creation of
``wizards'' that enable customers to solve complex problems on the
Web. A design engineer at a manufacturing company, for example, can
log on to the GE plastics site and use a specialized engineering
calculator to determine a polycarbonate's strength, adhesion and
color.
</P>
<P>
   When the GE aircraft-engines business wanted to expand its share
of the maintenance and overhaul market, it adapted diagnostic tools
used on GE medical-imaging equipment to a site that company
executives say has sharply cut the time and cost of engine repairs.
</P>
<P>
   One important decision in overhauling such engines is whether to
retain, rebuild or discard a worn part. In pre-Web days, the part
in question was often sent to the customer to be evaluated before
it was installed, or the repairs had to wait until a customer's
representative could inspect it at GE, processes that could take
days or weeks. Today, a clear picture of the part can be
transmitted over the Internet and quickly evaluated by the
customer.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of GE's Internet innovations are aimed at its customers.
The industrial systems business, which supplies equipment to
distribute, operate and control electricity, has developed a
virtual city on the Web where its engineers, who are in 100
countries, can share ideas and information and work on projects
simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   When employees go to the site, known as WebCity, they see
three-dimensional images of the city's buildings, including a
library, where information is stored; a university, where training
classes are available; and a factory, where products are developed.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a City Hall, with its own mayor, Chris Fuselier,
who happens to be the general manager of technology for the
industrial systems business. He and his staff, which includes a
``zoning board,'' set the agenda for WebCity. Fuselier, who has
been at GE for 31 years, says the site acts as a tool for tying
together a worldwide business. Tasks that once required airplane
trips and telephone calls across time zones are now accomplished in
less time and at less cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``The arrangement breaks down barriers of time and location,''
Fuselier said. ``We've gone from a traditional 10-hour workday to
where we are pretty much able to operate 24 hours a day, seven days
a week.''
</P>
<P>
   In developing its Internet strategies, GE is trying to turn the
Web into a profit center as well as a cost cutter.
</P>
<P>
   For example, a procurement employee who needs to buy staple guns
can go to a GE site and search for vendors from whom the company
has agreed to buy such items at a predetermined price. The employee
enters the kind and number of guns wanted, and the order is
processed. If the order is big enough to require approval, an
e-mail message is automatically sent to a supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner says consultants estimated that the cost of placing an
order used to be $50 to $200, but the cost via the Web site is only
about $1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to saving money on its own purchases by using the
Web, GE formed a venture with the Thomas Publishing Co. to sell the
service to other businesses. So far, Reiner said, there are about
10 customers, including Boeing and 3M.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its effort to develop e-businesses as alternatives to
traditional brick-and-mortar operations, the company created two
new companies early in March. One of them, GE Global eXchange
Services, will provide Internet data exchange. The other, GE
Systems Services, will provide the operations infrastructure to
support e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring gains in productivity from using the Internet has
proved elusive, as it has for other e-commerce businesses. Fuselier
thinks he and his team from industrial systems have at least part
of the answer. Based on 600 projects that have been completed
during the first five months of WebCity's operation, Fuselier said,
the time it takes to develop a product has been cut 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
