<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOM-NONPROFITS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHARITIES SEE WEB'S POTENTIAL, BUT FIND IT HARD TO AFFORD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    (This special ``one-shot'' article is culled from E-COMMERCE, a
stand-alone news section from The New York Times of March 29. It
examines how the business of electronic commerce is changing our
lives. For purchase information, contact one of these New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives:
 &HT;    _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
 &HT;    _ Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: This article has been transmitted in the
``a'' general news and ``f'' business news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Reed Abelson writes for The New York Times.
 By REED ABELSON 
 c.2000 The New York Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Businesses have discovered the power of the Internet for
communicating with employees and customers quickly through e-mail
or a Web site. Buying automobile parts, selling books or arranging
vacations can also be done efficiently online. Nonprofit
organizations should find the Internet just as appealing. What
better way to reach like-minded advocates, donors and volunteers or
to coordinate services?
</P>
<P>
   The desire is there, but most nonprofit groups have been slow to
pursue it. There are exceptions, most notably the American Red
Cross, which is planning to develop an online system for its blood
banks; and America's Second Harvest is using the Internet to
distribute food more efficiently. But the vast majority of
charitable organizations, while starting to raise money on their
sites, have been hindered by a lack of money, time, workers and
technological savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the struggles we have had for a long time is that
nonprofits are late adopters in terms of technology,'' said Ken
Goldstein, the director of online community development for
HandsNet, a San Jose, Calif., group that advises human-service
organizations about technology. Goldstein is convinced these groups
need to make more use of the Internet, and argues that being online
is becoming akin to being listed in the telephone directory.
</P>
<P>
   Most nonprofit groups have a long way to go. Catholic Charities
USA, for example, is the largest private network of social service
agencies in the United States. The charity, located in Alexandria,
Va., works with up to 144 major agencies across the country. But
only a third of those agencies have Web sites. ``This is still an
area where we are trying to bring them along,'' said Jo-Ann Leitch,
a spokeswoman for Catholic Charities. ``It's not where they spend a
lot of their money.''
</P>
<P>
   Those furthest behind are the thousands of organizations with
small budgets and limited expertise. ``Most nonprofits are small,
and most small organizations are not networked,'' explained Anthony
Wilhelm, the program director for communications policy for the
Benton Foundation in Washington, D.C., which is active in helping
nonprofit organizations make full use of technology. Many are
unable even to use e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current enthusiasm for the Web to date has focused
on fund-raising. Many charities' sites allow people to make
donations online. The American Red Cross has had significant
success using its site to raise funds.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, in response to the war in Kosovo, the charity raised
$1.2 million from people who logged on to its site. While that
amount was less than 4 percent of the $34 million raised by the Red
Cross during the crisis, it hinted at what many see as the
potential for electronic fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But such fund-raising is in its infancy: a survey by Independent
Sector, a Washington, D.C. organization that promotes charitable
giving and volunteerism, found last year that only 1 percent of the
people who gave to charity said they used the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Relatively few charities are using the Internet to communicate
with their members or to deliver services. There are notable
exceptions. America's Second Harvest, the nation's largest
charitable hunger-relief organization, which has a network of
nearly 200 food banks, has developed an e-service called
ResourceLink with Hewlett-Packard. The service, begun in October,
enables corporations to log on and provide information about
donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be up to date in technology,'' said Deborah Leff,
the president and chief executive of America's Second Harvest,
which is in Chicago. Because so many of its corporate donors use
the Internet to increase efficiency, the charity is exploring how
the medium can help ensure a steady flow of donations and
distribute food more quickly. While some of the agencies the
charity uses do not have access to computers, the hope is that all
the food banks will eventually log on to see if certain available
donations meet their needs.
</P>
<P>
   ResourceLink has made the gathering of information about
donations much simpler. When Nestle donated about 100,000 pounds of
one of its snacks, for example, it provided the necessary details,
including where the donation was located and whom to contact there
online. America's Second Harvest, which was alerted via e-mail to
the donation, placed the donation with six food banks.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plans to adapt the same process to other kinds of
donations, like clothing or building materials, so that the
Internet can serve as a clearinghouse for large gifts, particularly
from corporations.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross is also developing its Internet services.
In addition to maintaining a site about disaster relief,
www.disasterrelief.org, the charity has another site that describes
its charitable work, www.redcross.org, which is considered a very
sophisticated charity site.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Red Cross has such far-flung operations, the
Internet is a perfect medium to communicate national policies and
activities to its roughly 1,500 chapters and local units. The
chapters use the Internet to share information about their
successful activities, according to Tom Woteki, the charity's chief
information officer. The Red Cross is also planning an online
system of blood-supply management and delivery that will help
corporations conduct blood drives and allow doctors to use its
blood supplies better.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more to be done. ``We haven't really scratched the
surface in building a community of volunteers,'' Woteki said.
</P>
<P>
   Developing community via e-mail, chat rooms and private Web
sites is just happening. Many groups, from Amnesty International to
smaller organizations, understand the potential for the Internet as
an advocacy tool. During the height of recent tobacco litigation,
for example, Tobacco Control Advocates ran a private network for
about two years on which several hundred activists could read daily
news bulletins and receive action alerts, allowing quick access to
the news and helping them to coordinate responses.
</P>
<P>
   And the World Wildlife Fund, whose site, www.worldwildlife.org,
is also among the most advanced, uses the Internet for its
Conservation Action Network. About 15,000 of its 1.2 million
members in the United States receive alerts about news in their
areas of interest and ways in which they can try to effect change.
</P>
<P>
   The fund does not plan to offer a more sophisticated site,
though its members coordinate activities, swap information or plan
strategies in the near future, because maintenance would be too
expensive, said Kathleen Nixon, the director of marketing alliances
for the World Wildlife Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have expectations,'' she said. ``We don't have the
resources of Amazon.com.''
</P>
<P>
   Many charities are shocked to discover how expensive the
technology is, because the bulk of the costs are ongoing, said
Michael Gilbert, the director of the Internet Nonprofit Center, an
online resource for charities. ``Nonprofits have just started to
understand the total cost,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many donors, including corporations and foundations, prefer to
see their money go directly to the charity's mission.
``Infrastructure is not the most attractive thing to donors,'' said
Leff, of America's Second Harvest.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Internet may force changes in the philanthropic
world. Unable to afford the technology to raise money, create
change or provide services, charities that have been reluctant to
work together might have to create alliances to pool their
resources. ``To some extent, the Internet is going to force
collaborations,'' said Gilbert, of the Internet Nonprofit Center.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LIFEBEAT
and other features. &QL;
</P>
