<SLUG> BC-TREK-DENNIS-QUAID-IN-FREQUENCY-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AHEAD TO THE PAST: DENNIS QUAID ON `FREQUENCY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Dennis Quaid
in a scene from ``Frequency.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Call him the reluctant sci-fi guy.
 &HT;    ``It's just not something I seek out,'' Dennis Quaid says. ``I
have done some sci-fi, but I am more interested in the human
aspects of a story. That's what really gets me.
 &HT;    ``You can use sci-fi as a means of telling a good story,'' he
says. ``And that's worked for several of my films.''
 &HT;    Among the actor's genre films are the based-on-real-life ``The
Right Stuff,'' ``Innerspace,'' ``Enemy Mine'' and the
sword-and-sorcery epic ``Dragonheart.'' Now add to that list the
time-tripping drama ``Frequency,'' which will open nationwide on
April 28.
 &HT;    Set in 1999, ``Frequency'' finds sullen cop John Sullivan (Jim
Caviezel) suddenly able to communicate with his late father Frank
(Quaid) _ via ham radio during an aurora borealis _ 30 years in the
past, on the day before the firefighter perished in a blaze. John
warns Frank of what's to come, and the next day Frank is still
alive in 1999.
 &HT;    But now his mother (Elizabeth Mitchell) is dead, and John and
Frank _ with Frank in 1969 and John in 1999 _ must race to set
things right.
 &HT;    ``For me, the movie is about playing God with your own
destiny,'' Quaid says over lunch at New York's Regency Hotel. The
actor is tan and rested, and looks lean in blue jeans and a white
T-shirt. ``I liked the aspect of communicating across time with a
loved one _ I found that really fantastic. Then it's got the
father-son bonding, some action and this murder mystery going on.
So the movie has a lot going for it.''
 &HT;    To pull off his role, Quaid relied a great deal on director
Gregory Hoblit's guidance and screenwriter Toby Emmerich's
dialogue. He also tapped into his relationship with his own father
and son.
 &HT;    ``I brought both of those things to the table,'' Quaid says.
``My son was 6 at the time we were shooting, which was the same age
as my son in the 1969 portion of the film. My father is no longer
here, but I talk to him in my head. I think we all do that. There's
a yearning for that.''
 &HT;    As for his earlier genre stints, the actor describes ``Enemy
Mine'' as a particularly tough film to make.
 &HT;    ``Another day, another special effect,'' he says of the film
that paired him with Louis Gossett Jr. as a human and an alien,
hereditary enemies, forced to cooperate on a hostile planet.
 &HT;    He met his future wife, Meg Ryan, and befriended funnyman Martin
Short while filming ``Innerspace,'' a sci-fi comedy he considers
``hugely underrated.''
 &HT;    ``Dragonheart,'' though he considers it a good film, was
difficult because of the challenge of acting opposite an invisible
dragon, who was added later through digital magic.
 &HT;    ``Basically,'' the actor says, ``I remember talking to three
tennis balls the whole time.''
 &HT;    Quaid's career has had more ups and downs than a tennis ball at
the U.S. Open. He's been in hits and flops and, at times, teetered
on the brink of losing his leading-man status. Just as quickly,
however, he has recovered. There's been a ``The Big Easy'' for
every ``Jaws 3-D'' and an ``Any Given Sunday'' for every
``Switchback.''
 &HT;    Along the way, Quaid _ who will next co-star in ``Traffic,''
director Steven Soderbergh's soon-to-shoot ensemble film _ has
developed a reputation as an underrated actor. Which, he says, is
something he tries not to fret about.
 &HT;    ``I try not to live my life that way,'' he says. ``Anybody could
feel that way. That could be an insatiable thirst, to start looking
for approval from other places.
 &HT;    ``I'm pretty secure in the talent I've got,'' he adds. ``I'm
good at what I do. I think I've always kind of believed that.''
 &HT;    So, even if he could go back in time and change the past ...
 &HT;    ``I think we all wonder `What if' about our lives,'' the actor
says. ``What if I'd gotten up an hour earlier today? What if I had
graduated college?
 &HT;    ``In the end,'' Quaid says, ``I don't think I'd change a thing
about my life. If you change something you didn't like about your
life, you also could be changing a lot of what you did like about
it.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Frequency,'' consult the
official Web site at www.frequencymovie.com. And don't forget to
visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
