<HEADER>
A8969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-GLF-MINORITIES-HNS &LR;      04-06 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MINORITIES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MAN WHO INTEGRATED THE MASTERS STILL SEES FEW MINORITY PROS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SUSAN FORNOFF  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ It has been 25 years since Lee Elder integrated
the Masters, palms sweating as he made his way up Magnolia Lane for
the first time to enter a club that he had always considered to be
racist.
</P>
<P>
   By now, he would have figured to be entitled to utter some
cliche like ``We've come a long way, baby'' or ``How sweet it is.''
But when he rolled in from his Florida home to commemorate the
anniversary with an honor-filled weekend at Augusta National, it
occurred to him that the more things change, the more they stay the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around, he saw just two minorities, Tiger Woods and
Notah Begay III, an American Indian, in a field of 95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't see any (more) on the horizon,'' said Elder,
65, who played in the Masters six times after first qualifying with
a victory in the 1974 Monsanto Open. ``I've been to quite a number
of colleges around the country, and I really do not see any. ...
Yes, it is (disappointing). I would have thought that we would have
had more on the tour playing and more that would have won golf
tournaments by now.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, of course, is winning enough golf tournaments to carry
the entire human race. He has three titles in only seven events,
and has won seven of his last 11 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have a lot of other guys that I'm close with, and I've
been pulling for some time,'' Elder said. ``Hal Sutton is one and
so is Davis Love. ... But no doubt about it, I think the man to
beat is Tiger Woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods recognizes the contributions of Elder and even those who
came before him, saying, ``They broke the barriers and knocked the
walls down. From there, it's up to us to keep doing what we're
doing, keep being positive role models and keep aspiring to get
other people who are minorities in the world to play this great
game of golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods certainly does his part, through youth clinics presented
around the country by his foundation. And 18 PGA Tour victories
likely have an impact as well.
</P>
<P>
   The Lee Elder National Youth Program is in 10 cities now, and
the PGA Tour and other governing bodies of golf are still at work
on the First Tee initiative to provide golf lessons in inner
cities.
</P>
<P>
   The going has been slow and so has been the progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we had a nationally recognized junior program, you
would have more country clubs that would open their doors to the
minorities and to the blacks to come play,'' Elder said, ``but we
do not have a recognized program to show that we're trying to help
these youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus, the majority of the kids now get their training through
college, and the majority of our (black) colleges do not have, say,
your top teaching professionals. ... And you can't learn anything
from an instructor when you probably know more about golf than he
does.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most elite and expensive golf clubs still have no
black members. Woods did not come into the game through the country
club's front door; he grew up on the public and military courses of
Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   That is not the road most traveled by a member of the PGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not been able to prepare ourselves to compete on the
good golf courses or the courses we'd be competing on the regular
tour,'' Elder noted. ``We'd have to play in public facilities or
dig a hole out in the field someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Elder had thought about boycotting the Masters in 1975, and
talked to a few friends about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, I felt I would not be accomplishing anything by
running away from it,'' he said Wednesday night. Moments earlier,
he received two standing ovations and a special award from the Golf
Writers Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   It was a significant moment for golf, which never before treated
Elder as its Jackie Robinson. He remembered walking in the rain out
of the clubhouse, under the ancient oak to the first tee that dull,
miserable day in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as soon as I got to the tee, the sun came through,'' he
said. ``And I remember thinking, maybe this is why God put me
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
