A8972 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-RULES-TEX     04-06 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-RULES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RULES' TO LIVE BY: COURT-MARTIAL DRAMA HITS JUST SHY OF ITS MARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Samuel L. Jackson and Tommy Lee Jones should have been
evangelists; each, when riled, has a stentorian tone that could
convert the most recalcitrant sinner. They have the power to
persuade, and they can elevate a movie simply by convincing you
that what you're seeing is better than it really is.
</P>
<P>
   Director William Friedkin and his casting director scored quite
a coup, then, by snagging Jackson and Jones for ``Rules of
Engagement,'' a military court-martial drama with inevitable echoes
of ``Courage Under Fire'' and ``A Few Good Men.'' The movie is
well-meaning and entertaining, but a bit shallow, setting its
targets up a little too obviously in its questioning of how much
violence is too much in a combat situation. But its stars make it
worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is introduced as a hero, Col. Terry Childers, a 30-year
Marine veteran of Vietnam, Beirut and the Persian Gulf War. His
heroism comes into question during a rescue mission at the U.S.
Embassy in Yemen, where the ambassador (Ben Kingsley) and his
family are under siege. After helping the Americans escape,
Childers orders his troops to open fire on a large group of
anti-American protesters, killing more than 80, including children.
The question is, did the protesters shoot first, or was Childers
demonstrating recklessness under fire?
</P>
<P>
   Childers maintains that he acted within the rules of engagement,
which provide guidelines concerning when to fire upon an enemy. But
the government sets him up as a fall guy, and this is where the
movie starts derailing, as Childers starts looking like the victim
of a conspiracy and the movie begins stacking the deck. The
ambassador's family turn its back on him, and a nefarious national
security adviser (Bruce Greenwood at his most skulky) destroys
evidence that could clear his name. The only guy who stands by
Childers is Jones' character, Col. Hays Hodges, whom Childers hires
as his attorney.
</P>
<P>
   It must've fulfilled someone's dream to put Jones and Jackson in
a courtroom situation, where both could give double meaning to
``testifying''! And it's thrilling to watch the two actors in
action, whether Jackson is barking back at someone who's cornered
him or Jones is growling someone into inadvertently admitting a
lie. But the courtroom setting limits the movie, confining it to
trial-drama rules of objections and revelations, which isn't much
of a surprise when you discover that screenwriter Stephen Gaghan
was once a staff writer for TV's ``The Practice.'' ``L.A.
Confidential's'' Guy Pearce, speaking for no accountable reason in
a New Yawk bruiser accent, adds to the familiarity as an ambitious
and intractable prosecuting attorney.
</P>
<P>
   This may be Friedkin's best movie in years _ it's certainly his
most high- profile _ but that's not saying much for a director who
hasn't had a sizable hit since 1973's ``The Exorcist.'' Friedkin's
seldom one for subtlety, and his knack for sledgehammering shows in
``Rules of Engagement,'' when he portrays the massacre scene in all
its bloody agony _ and then repeats it, in detail, in flashback.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin has assembled some top-notch talent for this, including
veteran cinematographer William Fraker, ``Saving Private Ryan''
adviser Dale Dye (who appears in a supporting role) and composer
Mark Isham (who provides the requisite martial snare-drum
soundtrack). But Friedkin's biggest success is with his two stars;
with Jackson and Jones working at full throttle, the rest is just
gravy.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Rules of Engagement''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: William Friedkin
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Samuel L. Jackson, Tommy Lee Jones
</P>
<P>
   Length: 123 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence and strong language
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
