<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-STRATEGY-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDUCE TAX REFUNDS TO SAVE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN HIELSCHER   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Millions of Americans could give themselves a
raise of $140 or more a month through some simple tweaking on their
pay stubs, say tax experts.
</P>
<P>
   Financial advisers say that too many taxpayers withhold too much
for federal income taxes, giving the government free use of their
money for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   As the April 17 filing deadline approaches, and with many early
filers already receiving their tax refunds, accountants say now is
the perfect time to review how much money is withheld from your
paycheck and to make changes to reduce the size of that refund.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, many taxpayers love to get that check from the U.S.
Treasury every year. For some, it's a form of enforced savings,
money put aside that they would probably spend if it were
available.
</P>
<P>
   But that money could be put to better use over the course of the
year, say through interest-earning savings or to pay off debts that
are generating more interest costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why give the government your money interest-free?'' asked
Linda Lindsay, an accountant and enrolled agent with Howard &AMP; Co.
of Sarasota Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three-quarters of the 127 million taxpayers will get
refunds this year, according to the IRS. Through March 17, some
47.3 million taxpayers had received $80.6 billion in refunds, an
average of $1,705 per check.
</P>
<P>
   Even the IRS doesn't understand why so many people prefer to get
their hands on that money later than right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thank you for letting us use your money all year,'' joked
Bob Firman, an IRS spokesman in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   Firman said that most taxpayers can adjust their tax withholding
allowance so they either owe a small tax at year end or receive a
modest refund. Employees can file a new W-4 form with their
employer and increase their allowances to lower the taxes withheld.
On the other hand, if your tax burden is too high, you can file for
fewer allowances so more taxes are taken out of each paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suggest that any employee who got a large refund this
year fill out a new W-4 with their employer and adjust their
withholding exemptions,'' Lindsay said.
</P>
<P>
   The W-4 form contains several worksheets. One projects the
federal income tax liability for the year. A second worksheet
estimates the total withholding and compares it to the projected
tax.
</P>
<P>
   If you are having too little withheld, it is probably because
you work more than one job; have a spouse who works; have income
not subject to withholding, such as capital gains, interest,
dividends or rental income; or owe other taxes such as
self-employment or household employment.
</P>
<P>
   If your employer cannot withhold enough additional tax from your
pay, you may need to make estimated tax payments. The IRS expects
such payments on a quarterly basis, and accountants say taxpayers
can be subject to penalties if they don't pay it on that income.
</P>
<P>
   The W-4 form has a line allowing taxpayers to add an additional
amount taken from each paycheck. Suppose you just estimated your
2000 tax at $5,000, and your withholding will be $4,700. To cover
that $300, the taxpayer can request having $8 more withheld from
each weekly paycheck ($300 divided by the 38 remaining weeks of
this year) so no tax will be owed.
</P>
<P>
   A big refund check this year probably means you are having too
much tax withheld. Your current withholding also may be too high if
your adjustments, deductions or credits will increase significantly
this year, or if you qualify for new tax credits this year.
</P>
<P>
   The child credit, new for the 1998 tax year and increased to
$500 for 1999, bumped up tax refunds for millions of taxpayers, and
most haven't factored that into their regular withholding.
Education credits, mortgage interest deductions for new homeowners,
and child-care credits also are often forgotten when figuring out
proper withholding.
</P>
<P>
   The W-4 form includes a worksheet for figuring how projected
itemized deductions and other adjustments can be factored into your
personal allowances. A separate worksheet for single people who
work more than one job, or for married couples with at least two
jobs between them, can add even more allowances.
</P>
<P>
   Firman said that many employed taxpayers with uncomplicated
returns can adjust their withholding so their tax liability or
refund could be under $100 every year.
</P>
<P>
   (John Hielscher writes for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla.,
which is a member of The New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The New York Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
