<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CENSUS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By ignoring census, we hurt ourselves
 &HT;    (EDs: This is an editorial from Friday's Atlanta Constitution.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Public response to the Census Bureau's nationwide
mailing is well below the agency's ambitious target of 70 percent
of forms returned. That's a big disappointment on two counts.
</P>
<P>
   First, it means the 2000 census will be more expensive than it
needs to be. Beginning next week, the bureau's nose-counters will
be forced to go door-to-door trying to account for those who failed
to mail in their forms. Each 1 percent of U.S. households that
failed to respond to the census inquiries costs taxpayers an
estimated $42 million.
</P>
<P>
   More distressing, it means all too many of our fellow Americans
either don't care about or actually chafe at their obligations as
U.S. citizens to cooperate in this once-in-a-decade,
constitutionally mandated exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Some of that chafing has been expressed in complaints about the
``intrusive'' questions on the census long form, a huffiness
encouraged by politicians posing as anti-Washington populists. Both
the complainers and the pols have short memories. The questions
differ only slightly from previous census queries, and are actually
fewer in number this time around. Members of Congress had ample
opportunity to modify the questions two years ago, and nobody
squawked then.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, every one of the questions was required by an act
of Congress or a court ruling. Why does Uncle Sam want to know if
respondents have indoor plumbing? Because if enough people in a
community don't use a sewage or septic system, that information
could help pinpoint areas of ground water contamination. Why is
Washington asking about people with disabilities? Because the
information is useful in planning appropriate services.
</P>
<P>
   Census participation rates are especially low in the South, in
part perhaps because of lingering suspicions about Washington's
motives and the uses to which it might put the census data. If
people succeed in evading the count, however, they also succeed in
denying themselves and their fellow Southerners a fair share of
federal funding and representation in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't answer, they don't get the money,'' Newsday (N.Y.)
columnist Marie Cocco wrote this week about Southerners' poor
showing on the census. ``That would mean more for everybody else.
And that would be an exquisitely just outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe for her part of the country, but not ours.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
