<HEADER>
A8983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-DREAM-WEDDING-HNS &LR;      04-06 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAM-WEDDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE TRIBULATIONS OF PRE-MARITAL STRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JESSICA BARBARO  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Valentine's Day on a little Caribbean island. The
ring sparkled. The steel-drum band played. The engagement got off
to a hip start. The biggest decision was SPF 10 or 15.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half in the distance, the wedding seemed like a
vague, groovy daydream. I imagined a salsa band, a black cocktail
dress. The bride, margarita in hand, working the room. Feasting on
sushi and spring rolls. Everybody dancing. A foolish sun-baked
dream.
</P>
<P>
   A little background. My wedding nightmare starts like this: The
bride, swaddled in tulle, is a vision that Glinda the Good Witch
threw up on as she sashays down the aisle. She is froofy _ think
Stay-Puff Marshmallow Man. She wears what my mother calls ``one of
those veils that looks like a huge bird landed on your head.''
</P>
<P>
   She sports a bejeweled tiara and has relocated a colony of
oysters around her neck. She clutches four dozen of something
called ``sweetheart'' roses arranged in the shape of a heart.
Baring $3,000 worth of orthodonture at her 400 nearest and dearest,
she makes her way to the altar. Queen for a day, baby.
</P>
<P>
   I never wanted to star in one of these productions. But faster
than an ice cube melting in a rum drink, it snuck up on me.
</P>
<P>
   A month after uttering the word ``yes,'' my little soiree has
morphed into a traditional church ceremony and a reception for 150.
And yes, a white dress. There is talk of a videographer.
</P>
<P>
   I was informed immediately upon our return that unless my
groovemaster reception was to take place in a fire hall, I had
better get moving. Ha! I intended to plan my wedding in a leisurely
fashion. A lazy Sunday drive here and there to look at reception
spots in springtime. Let the nervous nellies get their veils in a
bunch. Not me.
</P>
<P>
   A few casual phone calls later, the dread set in. The summer of
2001 was already heavily booked. A Saturday night in June? Muffled
howls of laughter from the other end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The process of setting a date seemed like it would be a
sentimental process, blithely selecting a meaningful day to do the
deed.
</P>
<P>
   The date actually is chosen from a catering manager's planner.
Then it's a race to find out if the priest is available, how
precariously near the horse racing season you are, and whether
there are any available hotel rooms within a day's drive.
</P>
<P>
   Love is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   The warnings come from friends, acquaintances, colleagues. My
relationship, they caution, is in imminent peril.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our worst wedding fight was over which stamps to put on the
invitations,'' said one friend. ``She wanted the `love' stamps and
I said that was too much of a clichi _ I wanted the fruit stamps. I
simply would not cave in. It was a major issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridal magazines and Web sites devote large amounts of space to
how to deal with wedding, and if you can believe it,
engagement-related stress. ``A complete guide to dealing with the
in-laws.'' Articles on yoga and acupuncture and good nutrition to
help you through these trying times. How peaceful deep breathing
can help you avoid snarling at his parents. How not to kill a
well-meaning groom who thinks it would be cool to match his
cummerbund to the bridesmaids' dresses. Who were these angry
brides? I started waiting to turn into this kind of she-devil
werewolf.
</P>
<P>
   Engagement stress? People have entirely too much free time on
their hands when these are the trials we face. I'm all for going
back to the times when people had real concerns to stress about _
like gathering enough berries to survive the winter.
</P>
<P>
   When a wedding consisted of crowning the bride with some dried
leaves and rustling up some fish from the stream for a feast.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's all about the petite Beef Wellingtons and the rolled
fondant latticework atop the cake.
</P>
<P>
   But even though I'm not one of those women who is ga-ga for a
girly wedding, my betrothed points out that I have my whole life to
wear black. That most of our relatives probably hate sushi. And,
God willing, that we're only gonna make that walk once.
</P>
<P>
   And he tricked me into agreeing to wear a white wonder by saying
he wants to show me off to the world.
</P>
<P>
   I'm toast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
