<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8990 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PHILIPMORRIS-COMMERCI     04-06 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPMORRIS-COMMERCIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICS SAY GOOD-GUY PHILIP MORRIS ADS DON'T FIT THE
CIGARETTE-MAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM MADIGAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In March 1990, the skies above Elba, Ala., opened and 16 inches
of rain fell in a few days. A nearby levee broke during the deluge,
and most of the homes and businesses in the town of 4,500 were
swamped in 12 feet of water. Relief poured in from across the
Southeast. A few hours' drive away, in Albany, Ga., a Miller
Brewing plant stopped bottling beer, and began bottling water to
assist the stricken place.
</P>
<P>
   But then you already knew that, at least if you've gone anywhere
near a television in the last five months. Since the fall, a
ubiquitous national ad campaign sponsored by mammoth
cigarette-maker Philip Morris Co. has trumpeted such altruism. The
spots are slick and heart-rending, reminding the world how the
world's largest cigarette company and its subsidiaries, like Miller
Beer, have helped flooded towns or, in the case of other ads,
victims of domestic violence and the home-bound elderly.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, the campaign seems a cynical attempt to obscure
the fundamental reality of Philip Morris, which a recent article in
Business Week magazine termed ``arguably the most reviled
corporation in America.'' With its huge market share in the
cigarette industry, the article said, the manufacturers of Marlboro
could be blamed for 200,000-smoking related deaths a year. In
recent years, the company has paid billions to various states for
the cost of treating smoking-related illnesses. Multimillion-dollar
court verdicts against Philip Morris and its tobacco brethren are
bound to pile up. That is a lot to obscure.
</P>
<P>
   But where Philip Morris is concerned, there is a competing
reality. There is a compelling basis for the ad campaign. For
decades, Philip Morris has been among the world's most
philanthropic companies, giving away millions to fight hunger,
support the arts, fund scholarships for minorities, and combat
domestic violence, to name just a few of its endeavors. Such
generosity was a corporate benchmark long before its major product
became the source of its current public-relations nightmare,
company observers say.
</P>
<P>
   The industry's many opponents, to be sure, are not fooled by the
Philip Morris philanthropy or the ad campaign that promotes it, an
effort costing the company roughly $100 million a year. While
``good neighbor'' ads fill the airways, Philip Morris continues to
promote cigarettes in ways that appeal to young people, such as
buying ads in glitzy magazines, opponents say. Philip Morris is
also ``flooding the political system with millions of dollars in
campaign contributions and soft money, contributions designed to
get politicians to look the other way,'' says Matthew Myers, of the
Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a small price to pay to continue to make billions of
dollars selling cigarettes to kids,'' Myers says.
</P>
<P>
   But to some observers, cigarette-manufacturing on the one hand,
and a long philanthropic history on the other, is a bewildering
paradox.
</P>
<P>
   For a Business Week piece last November, writer John A. Byrne
was given unprecedented access to Philip Morris executives and
company headquarters in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Byrne saw ashtrays built into granite walls outside elevators on
every floor. (The headquarters has the city's only exemption to a
New York smoking ban.) Wooden boxes filled with cigarettes adorn
conference tables. At the end of each day, Byrne, a nonsmoker,
emerged from the headquarters feeling ill, and smelling like an
ashtray. Yet he also tells this story:
</P>
<P>
   ``The CEO (Geoffrey Bible) is a devout Catholic. One day he's
coming to work and he heard the Harlem Boys Choir was in financial
trouble and might have to disband,'' Byrne says. ``He went in and
insisted Philip Morris give a huge donation, a million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's almost impossible to reconcile,'' Byrne said. ``There's
no simple, clean answer.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the company's research indicated a public
relations problem that transcended its tobacco products. Philip
Morris polls showed that only a small percentage of the public was
aware that the company also owned Miller Brewing and Kraft Foods,
or had long been a corporate leader in charitable giving, or had
programs to combat the use of tobacco and alcohol by minors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had to do something to educate or inform the
general public about who we are,'' says Jim Spector, a Philip
Morris vice president. ``Part of what we are is a tobacco company.
We're not trying to hide that. What we're trying to do is give a
more complete picture about what this corporation is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence the advertising blitz that began last October, a campaign
designed by the Leo Burnett agency of Chicago. Even Spector
concedes the irony of that choice, for in 1954, it was to that same
advertising firm that Philip Morris turned for help during another
watershed moment in the corporation's history.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the company's Malboro brand had been a
premium-priced women's cigarette. The company, lagging well behind
other cigarette makers, wanted to change Malboro's image and
broaden its appeal to all age groups and both sexes, according to
the memoir of a former Philip Morris executive named Joseph
Cullman. After a meeting with Philip Morris executives, it was
Burnett who devised the red top to a flip-up Malboro box. More
importantly, it was Burnett's idea to employ the American cowboy as
Marlboro's new symbol.
</P>
<P>
   More than any single factor, creation of the Marlboro Man
propelled the brand into the bestselling cigarette in the world,
and made Philip Morris the most successful cigarette maker.
Opponents also argue that the Malboro Man has contributed to _ and
continues to bear blame for _ an inestimable number of
smoking-related deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the Malboro campaign, more children smoke the
Malboro brand than all other cigarettes combined,'' says Myers, of
the Campaign for Tobacco-Free Kids. ``That has remained unchanged.
Sixty percent of kids who smoke smoke Marlboro. The western, cowboy
image is the perfect image for the adolescent boy or girl. It's a
virile, strong, independent, good-looking rebellious image. It is
everything that an adolescent isn't and wants to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Spector said using the Burnett firm for the new campaign opened
Philip Morris to further criticism. But he said the agency came
back with the strongest advertising plan and hired a new team to
produce the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not dealing with the tobacco end of the agency's
business,'' Spector said. ``And they shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The result have been spots like those that have made Elba a
tourist destination. The local sheriff seen on TV, and a grizzled
old codger in the courthouse square, are really actors. But a dozen
residents of the town make an appearance in the ad, including a
group of young Elba boys jumping from a dock into water.
</P>
<P>
   ``They helped out greatly,'' Elba Mayor James Grimes says of
Miller, sounding as if he could have had a role in the commercial
himself. ``They brought a truckload of water over here and stacked
it up on the courthouse square. They stopped bottling beer so they
could bottle water.''
</P>
<P>
   Mention of cigarettes, heart disease and lung cancer are absent
from the Elba spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``In short, when you look at their actions, instead of their
ads, it's the same old tobacco industry,'' says Myers, the tobacco
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   But Elba residents testify to a more complicated corporate
reality.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't smoke,'' says Kaye Whitworth, executive director of
the Elba Chamber of Commerce. ``I don't like to be around smoking.
It stinks. If they never made another cigarette, I would not care.
But I don't have to buy them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot say how much we appreciate what they did for us,''
Whitworth says. ``They really came to our rescue. They truly did.
That's the only water we had.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
