<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENERGY DEPARTMENT SAYS GAS WILL BE CHEAPER BY SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Energy Department sharply revised its
predictions about gasoline prices Thursday, saying that the worst
will soon be over and that by the summer vacation season fuel will
be a little cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The nationwide average has been hovering around $1.52 a gallon
for regular unleaded, but it should soon decline to $1.46 and stay
there through the summer, then slide to $1.39 by September, the
department's Energy Information Administration said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   That forecast is starkly different from what the administration
said just four weeks ago, when it predicted a national average of
$1.56 for a gallon of regular unleaded this summer and said prices
would probably not start to go down until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's slightly rosier forecast was attributed to the recent
decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries to
step up production. The Energy Information Administration projected
that the additional supply would pull down the price of imported
crude oil, from the current level of about $27 a barrel to $25 by
June, then to $23.50 by the end of 2000 and $21.50 by the end of
2001.
</P>
<P>
   But all these predictions are based on the assumption that
conditions in the Middle East will remain stable. If there is a war
(as there have been before between OPEC members), or an oil
embargo, or if OPEC decided to turn down the spigot again, gasoline
prices could soar.
</P>
<P>
   Several other caveats must be observed. The nationwide average
for a gallon of regular unleaded is virtually meaningless in
high-cost regions, especially California, which requires
cleaner-burning, and therefore more expensive, gasoline. Prices in
California have been $2 or more a gallon in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   American drivers with good short-term memories may recall that
they were paying an average of 53 cents a gallon more last month
for regular unleaded than they were in March 1999, and that last
summer's average was only $1.17 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   But drivers with good long-term memories may recall that today's
prices are about 40 percent below what they were in March 1981,
after adjusting for inflation. They may recall that the same amount
of gasoline that cost $10 in 1984 cost only $10.19 in July 1999,
when prices were much lower than they are now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1627EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
