<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8994 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MOVIE-ENGAGE07-COX     04-06 0624
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-ENGAGE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Courtroom drama easy to object to
 &HT;    By Hap Erstein
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ On cue at the Palm Beach International
Film Festival, director William Friedkin, producer Richard Zanuck
and stars Tommy Lee Jones and Samuel L. Jackson all said the right
upbeat, bullish things about their imminent military courtroom
drama. After seeing the cliche-riddled, slow-moving ``Rules of
Engagement,'' though, you will wonder whether this is really the
movie they were referring to.
</P>
<P>
   There is promise in the early scenes, starting with a brief
prologue in 1968 Vietnamese swamps, a visceral, blood- and
mud-spattered combat sequence in which Terry Childers (Jackson)
saves the life of a wounded Hayes Hodges (Jones). The movie then
fast-forwards to 1996, to a scene of pomp and camaraderie over
Hodges' retirement from the Marines. He goes fishing, while
Childers returns to duty aboard ship in the Indian Ocean. Once
there, he receives emergency orders to head to Yemen and rescue the
besieged U.S. ambassador (Ben Kingsley), who is contending with an
angry protest against our presence in the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Friedkin draws unmistakable parallels between the chaos of
Vietnam combat and the embassy attack, where a rattled Childers
orders his men to fire into the crowd of demonstrators. The
ambassador gets helicoptered out to safety, but when no weapons are
found on the dead protesters, the government suddenly needs a
scapegoat. So _ let's have a show of hands _ who gets charged with
83 counts of murder? And which rusty lawyer who owes Childers his
life will be called out of retirement to defend him?
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement'' is the sort of movie where the relative
novice Hodges will fly halfway around the globe to Yemen to see the
alleged crime scene and stumble onto evidence that a team of
investigators had overlooked. It is the sort of movie where the
defendant will say things like ``If I'm guilty of this, I'm guilty
of everything I did in combat for the last 30 years.'' It's the
sort of movie where an intelligent, cool-headed guy like Childers
will be easily goaded into incriminating outbursts in court. The
sort of movie where the government will destroy evidence to further
the foreign relations interests of the nation. And on and on.
</P>
<P>
   With the new battle lines clearly drawn, Friedkin settles into
and settles for an all-too-familiar courtroom yarn. We wait
dutifully for the surprise witness, the legal twist, the discovery
of the key evidence that we know has been suppressed. And wait and
wait. Picture ``A Few Good Men'' but without the crackling
histrionics. ``Rules of Engagement'' may be a more realistic
depiction of military justice, but it is far less dramatic. We can
handle the truth, but prefer that it not lull us to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is typically understated as Hodges, through whose eyes we
watch the trial unfold, but it is a role that any stalwart,
craggy-faced actor could handle. Jackson gets a few scenery-chewing
explosions, which he manages well, yet you sense that he too is not
working on all cylinders. Australian Guy Pearce (``L.A.
Confidential'') shows up with a New Yawk accent as the whippet-like
prosecutor, Kingsley has a few good moments as the duplicitous
ambassador, and Philip Baker Hall (``Magnolia'') gets a few minutes
of screen time as Hodges' father, who tries to dissuade him from
taking the case.
</P>
<P>
   If only more cast members had listened to him. ``Rules of
Engagement'' will soon be a minor, forgettable item on their
resumes, and those of us eager to see director Friedkin's career
back on track will have to keep waiting.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
