</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMIGRE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EAST-WEST': WELCOME HOME, IMPERIALIST DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: production notes at end of review)  
 
 By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After World War II the Soviet government undertook a propaganda
campaign to entice Russian emigres in the West to return home.
Thousands accepted the offer of Soviet citizenship and the chance
to help rebuild their devastated motherland. In return for their
devotion, most were summarily executed or imprisoned, victims of
either Stalin's paranoia _ he thought that they must be imperialist
spies _ or of a state that reserved some of its greatest cruelties
for those who trusted and believed in it.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of ``East-West,'' Regis Wargnier's sumptuous,
moving new film, captures both the hope of the returning Russians
and their brutal betrayal. A voyage on an elegant steamship,
complete with vodka toasts and patriotic songs, gives way to the
grim reality of life and death in a police state. As they
disembark, the returnees are separated into two groups, fit and
unfit, in a scene clearly meant to put us in mind of the similar
sortings at the Nazi death camps a few years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei Golovine and his French wife, Marie, the fictional
couple at the center of ``East-West,'' are luckier than most of
their fellow travelers. Because Aleksei (Oleg Menchikov) is a
doctor whose skills might be of use to them, the authorities assign
the Golovines and their young son, Serioja, to a communal apartment
in Kiev, where they share cramped quarters with a motley assortment
of New Socialist snoops, black marketeers and drunkards.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Marie (Sandrine Bonnaire), the old woman charged by
the state with minding everybody's business speaks some French, but
this is a small mercy in a situation whose hellishness is amplified
by the impossibility of escape. On Marie's arrival, her French
passport is destroyed, and her husband, deaf to the intensity of
her misery, decides that behaving like a good Soviet citizen is the
best way to protect his family.
</P>
<P>
   When ``East-West'' was released in France last year, it drew
some criticism for its supposed anti-communism, but its politics
are fairly restrained. Wargnier, who collaborated with two Russian
writers, Roustam Ibraguimbek and Sergei Bodrove, on the screenplay,
shows the essential monstrosity of Stalinism. But he does not
conclude that everyone who lived under it was a monster.
</P>
<P>
   Even the system's most dedicated functionaries _ a military
officer who is kind to Marie, the hospital bureaucrat who rewards
Aleksei's talent and dedication, a tyrannical swimming coach _ are
given redeeming human qualities. Only one character, the vicious
secret-police officer who is convinced that Marie is a spy, is an
unambiguous embodiment of evil. And Marie, a furious, unyielding
martyr, is no saint. To her neighbors and co-workers, next to whom
she is comparatively privileged, she often seems haughty, selfish
and capricious.
</P>
<P>
   For all its moral complexity, ``East-West'' has a decidedly
old-fashioned, big-movie feeling. It's a throwback to the lush,
emotionally emphatic films of the era in which it takes place.
French critics and politicians like to complain about the
destruction of their national cinema by the hegemony of Hollywood,
but Wargnier has clearly learned something from recent American
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Like Steven Spielberg, he is fond of presenting climactic scenes
in counterpoint, cutting back and forth, for instance, between the
bustle and grandeur of a concert hall and the desperate struggle of
a lone swimmer in a dark, choppy sea. He also shares with Spielberg
an unfortunate taste for swelling, high-volume soundtrack music, as
if the only way to prevent the audience from remaining dry-eyed
were to drown it.
</P>
<P>
   But the sumptuous romanticism of the story makes it bearable,
and this may be grounds for criticism. The film may justly be
faulted for dissolving the horrors of history in the catharsis of
melodrama, but it also uses the resources of melodrama to shed
light on forgotten history. ``East-West'' is a historical pageant,
full of grandeur and period detail, but it is also the portrait of
a marriage under extreme pressure, external and internal.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene Marie sits in her room and weeps as she reads the
passage from ``Madame Bovary'' describing the heady bliss of its
heroine's first adultery. And like an unwillingly proletarian Emma
Bovary, Marie finds relief from her stultifying daily life and her
husband's drab conventionality in the arms of a lover, a young
swimmer named Sacha (Sergi Bodrov Jr.), whose parents were executed
as class enemies in the great terror of the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   Aleksei is engaged in an affair of his own, with the nosy,
officious neighbor who replaces Sacha's grandmother as manager of
the communal apartment after the grandmother is taken away by the
police.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of Aleksei's character _ we are kept wondering
about his loyalties and his motives, until the very end _ binds the
movie together, and Menchikov, who looks like a sensitive, Slavic
Gabriel Byrne, is a subtle, generous actor. But this is, in the
best old Hollywood sense, a woman's picture. ``East-West'' was
nominated for this year's Oscar for best foreign film, and like the
film that won, Pedro Almodovar's ``All About My Mother,'' it is in
part a heartfelt tribute to the iconic movie actresses of the past.
</P>
<P>
   Bonnaire burns with moral passion and erotic fervor, as if
inhabited by the spirit of Ingrid Bergman. Catherine Deneuve,
playing a French actress who takes up the cause of Marie's
repatriation, is the living incarnation of everything noble and
beautiful in postwar French cinema. She was playing a bored French
housewife in Luis Bunuel's ``Belle de Jour'' the year Bonnaire was
born. To paraphrase Harold Brodkey: To see them on screen together
is to see Marxism die.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EAST-WEST'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Regis Wargnier; written (in French and Russian, with
English subtitles) by Roustam Ibraguimbek, Sergei Bodrov, Louis
Gardel and Wargnier; director of photography, Laurent Dailland;
edited by Isabelle Proust, Eric Dardill and Herve Schneid; music by
Patrick Doyle; production designers, Vladimir Svetozarov and
Aleksei Levtchenko; produced by Yves Marmion; released by Sony
Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   With: Sandrine Bonnaire (Marie), Oleg Menchikov (Aleksei),
Catherine Deneuve (Gabrielle), Sergei Bodrov Jr. (Sacha), Ruben
Tapiero (Serioja at 7) and Erwan Baynaud (Serioja at 14). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 115 minutes.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``East-West'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned). It
includes sexual situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
