<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOUTHPAW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTHPAW' IS A PUZZLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past few weeks, maverick independent studio The Shooting
Gallery has been running a series of offbeat films in an attempt to
showcase non-mainstream entertainment. The choices, including the
moody black-and-white seriocomedy ``Judy Berlin'' and the dense and
multilayered ``Such a Long Journey,'' have often been intriguing,
if not always artistically successful.
</P>
<P>
   The latest entry, though, is a puzzler. It's ``Southpaw,'' a
documentary about Francis Barrett, a 19-year-old Irish boxer from
Galway. Barrett is also a Traveller, a member of a much-maligned
Gypsylike class of drifters who live in trailer encampments on
Galway's outskirts. The movie chronicles Barrett's successes and
failures as he competes in the 1996 Summer Olympics (where he
carries the Irish flag and becomes a national hero by winning his
first fight) and in the Irish and English championships.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't get much deeper than that; we learn a little about
Barrett's clanlike family, see amusing footage of a mass wedding
(and its aftermath), and watch Barrett fight in scenes that are
truncated until virtually all the boxing excitement is removed. We
don't learn much about why the Travellers are so reviled in Ireland
(the Irish-made film seems to take this for granted), or about what
Barrett's victories mean to his society. Because it's a
documentary, ``Southpaw'' showed signs of being able to rise above
the current crop of boxing movies. But it's just another one that
ends up down for the count.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Southpaw''
</P>
<P>
   Length: 79 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: Not rated
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
