<HEADER>
A9005 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-BROWN09-COX     04-06 1831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-BROWN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Spare prose sketches a gritty reality, born of a self-taught
Mississippi author who wouldn't give up
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, Miss. _ It is an awkward time at the Ajax Diner, that
twilight zone between the last lunch servings of chicken-fried
steak and mashed potatoes and the first beers and burgers of happy
hour.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't bother Larry Brown. Stepping off the oak-shaded
square of William Faulkner's hometown into the darkened bar, the
bearded, wiry firefighter-turned-author greets the waitresses by
name and heads for a red vinyl booth in the ``Closed'' section of
the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Lighting up a Marlboro, he orders a Budweiser and leans back to
talk about how much his life has changed from his days of fighting
fires, cutting pulpwood and writing sex-filled stories about
man-eating bears in Yellowstone National Park.
</P>
<P>
   With two collections of critically acclaimed short stories and
four other books under his belt, Brown has become a nationally
known author and a literary folk hero in a town where Faulkner
ranks second only to God, or maybe John Grisham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've spent so much of my life in bars,'' Brown says. ``That's
where I get a lot of my stories. There's so much material there. I
just watch what goes on and later on I find a place to put that
stuff in my novels. It's fascinating watching somebody come in
sober and then see how they behave when they get intoxicated.''
</P>
<P>
   In Brown's gritty literary world, bars are hangouts for his
blue-collar characters. They are refuges for desperate men and
women who are trying to escape boring, dead-end lives with too many
troubles and too little money. Men like the title character in his
1991 novel ``Joe,'' a divorced ex-con who spends his days poisoning
unwanted trash trees for a timber company and his nights gambling
and drinking. Or women like the teenage girl in his new novel,
``Fay'' (Algonquin, $24.95), a beautiful, resourceful temptress who
runs away from an abusive father and plunges into a world of
murder, violence and sexual exploitation. The character of Fay made
a brief appearance in ``Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All I knew about her when I first started was what I wrote
about her in `Joe,''' Brown says. ``I knew she had been raised in
labor camps and she was naive and didn't know much about the world.
She just walked out of `Joe' and disappeared, and all this time I
wondered what became of her. One day I just sat down and started
writing about her walking down this dirt road that came out of this
ridge over at Tula, right close to where I live.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing a novel from a woman's viewpoint was a challenge, says
Brown, who frequently sought guidance from his wife, Mary Annie,
about such feminine matters as morning sickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted it to be genuine to women who read it,'' Brown says.
``Fay was real naive and she was headstrong, too, to take off
walking like that. Her main thing was that she didn't want to be
alone. She wanted a man to take care of her, and not prey on her.''
</P>
<P>
   In essence, Fay, like many of his other characters, struggles to
survive in a violent, hardscrabble world that Brown knows
intimately. Born in 1951 on a small farm in Potlockney, Miss.,
Brown grew up in a family usually in desperate straits because of
his father's drinking.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran of World War II, Brown's father never recovered fully
from his combat experiences. He dealt with the nightmares by
drinking, often spending the last dollar of grocery money for a
bottle. ``It was like trouble followed us from place to place,''
Brown recalls.
</P>
<P>
   When he was old enough, Brown escaped by joining the Marines.
Two years later, he returned to take a job with the Oxford Fire
Department and get married. He supported his growing family by
painting houses, hauling hay and cleaning carpets.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown turned 30, however, he took stock of himself and
decided he didn't like what he saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a job as a firefighter, but I wondered where I'd be 10
years on down the road. I always had this question about how people
learned to write. I'd always loved to read so much, I just kept
thinking and thinking about it and one day I said I was going to
sit down and write a novel, to see if I could do it. I wondered if
it might be like learning how to build houses, or lay brick, or
even fight fires.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife recalls that he came home from work one day with a
stack of typing paper and announced he was going to write a novel.
</P>
<P>
   From the ground up
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a whim at first,'' she says, ``but when he
kept at it, month after month, I knew he was serious. He was so
determined to make it. The rejection slips would come in, and
they'd be real short sentences saying, `We're sorry we can't
publish this at this time.' Things like that. We got used to doing
things without him around because he was always writing.''
</P>
<P>
   After the novel about man-eating bears was rejected, Brown
tackled the short-story form, churning out a few horrible pieces
that nobody wanted. In addition to his firefighting job, he worked
at a place called Commanche Pottery on his days off, pouring liquid
plaster into molds shaped like Indian heads and animals. When the
place burned down, he lost his moonlighting job but gained more
time to write.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Brown decided he had better go to the library and
find some books on writing and learn more about the craft. He began
his education in earnest, checking out books on writing by the
armload. Later, Oxford bookseller Richard Howorth became his mentor
and provided a reading list of novels and short story collections
by Faulkner and other writers.
</P>
<P>
   For the next eight years, Brown wrote like a man possessed,
accumulating piles of rejection slips (at last count, he had 250),
and turning out more than 100 short stories and five novels. After
he audited Ellen Douglas' writing class at Ole Miss, however, he
began to see things more clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did was point him in the right direction,'' Douglas
says. ``I suggested Flannery O'Connor and Faulkner, of course, but
he had already begun to read Faulkner. I also suggested James
Joyce, Katherine Anne Porter and a number of Southern writers. I
was impressed with his sense of voice. He had a natural talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's big break came in 1987 when Algonquin editor Shannon
Ravenel read one of his stories, ``Facing the Music,'' in the
Mississippi Review.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called me and asked if I had enough stories for a
collection,'' Brown says. ``I told her, `I've got a hundred. How
many would you like to see?'''
</P>
<P>
   When ``Facing the Music'' was published as a collection of short
stories, critics praised the spare, powerful language, particularly
in the title story about a man's reaction to his wife's mastectomy.
They continued to rave when ``Dirty Work'' appeared later, calling
the novel about two hospitalized Vietnam veterans ``the most
unflinching depiction of war and its scars since `Johnny Got His
Gun.'''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the real thing, both personally and professionally,
says his friend, North Carolina novelist Clyde Edgerton. ``I think
he has a deep love of the earth. He loves people and things in a
way that keeps him anchored to his own good sense. His writing
shows that he's in touch with something at a deep level that few
writers ever make it down to.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, says Georgia State University professor Tom McHaney,
Brown is writing about his own little corner of Faulkner's
fictional Yoknapatawpha County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larry made himself into a writer, much as Faulkner did.
Faulkner was also without an education, he'd like to say, but as a
writer he was self-made through reading. That's exactly what Larry
has done. I think Faulkner would have liked `Dirty Work' and pieces
like that because they express a point of view and a voice with
great clarity.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing from the countryside
</P>
<P>
   As dusk settles over the Delta, Brown says goodbye to the crowd
in the Ajax and heads for his truck. Retrieving a cold beer from
the cooler in the back, he pops in a CD titled ``From Senegal to
Senatobia,'' the latest eclectic blues offerings by Otha Turner and
the Afrossippi Allstars, and gets ready for one of his favorite
pastimes _ slow ridin'.
</P>
<P>
   As he bounces along the Mississippi backroads, he points out the
places where he grew up as the son of a sharecropper and the
locations that find their way into his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right here is where Fay walked out onto the highway,'' he
says, slowing down where a dirt road intersects with the highway.
``I write about places I know so I won't have to do much
research.''
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later he turns off the blacktop onto a rutted
wagon road and parks on the piece of land where he's building a
writing cabin. He hikes across the dam of the pond and up the hill
where the unfinished 10-by-12-foot wooden structure sits perched on
concrete blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started building this not quite two years ago,'' he says,
caressing the frame like a proud father. ``I'd like to move my
writing operation over here. It's nice and isolated and I can go
fishing in the pond. I'm going to have electricity but no plumbing.
I don't need no plumbing. I've got an outhouse I'm restoring.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Brown pulls into the driveway of his ranch house, looks
out over the pasture where a coyote has been carrying off his baby
goats, and unlocks a small office on the other side of the
breezeway.
</P>
<P>
   As narrow as a small walk-in closet, the office is crammed with
books, snapshots of writing pals Edgerton, Grisham, Rick Bass and
others, and clippings about his books.
</P>
<P>
   The past 10 years have been overwhelming, Brown says. Writers he
hadn't heard of two decades ago _ legendary authors such as Harry
Crews and Cormac McCarthy and Richard Ford _ now correspond
regularly with him. Colleges frequently ask him to speak at
literary conferences and he is the subject of a forthcoming
documentary film, ``The Rough Life of Larry Brown.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown is on the verge of making big money, as well. Billy Bob
Thornton has bought an option on ``Joe,'' and movie deals are in
the works for ``Father and Son,'' ``Dirty Work'' and ``Big Bad
Love.'' Still, Brown seems unaffected by fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a person, he hasn't changed a bit,'' says Howorth, owner of
Square Books. ``He's still the same gracious, down-to-earth person
he's always been. But as a writer, I think he's grown. He's very
careful about his craft and continues to read other writers with an
eye on story development.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the promise of Hollywood riches doesn't faze him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing pretty much what I want to be doing,'' says Brown.
``What would I do if I got a lot more money? I don't think I'd do
anything much different. I guess I would like to get my little
writing cabin finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
