<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9009 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SECRET-FILM-NYT &LR;      04-06 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-FILM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOE GOULD'S SECRET': CHARISMATIC CURMUDGEON VS. NEW YORKER WRITER
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review; note that a word in
graf 12 could be offensive to some readers.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The great British actor Ian Holm has had many juicy film roles,
but none has placed him so ferociously front and center as the
title character of ``Joe Gould's Secret.'' Ian's ranting,
fiery-eyed performance is the brilliant spark that ignites this
otherwise rather somnolent film, adapted by Stanley Tucci and the
screenwriter Howard A. Rodman from Joseph Mitchell's famous New
Yorker profiles, ``Professor Sea Gull'' and ``Joe Gould's Secret.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been easy for Holm to sentimentalize Gould by
softening this thorny bohemian character who lived off handouts and
made grandiose literary claims into a dreamy-eyed holy man and
tragic misfit. Instead, the 69-year-old actor goes in the opposite
direction. The character is a raving crank, a pathological liar, an
obnoxious drunk, a disheveled, flailing, broken-down genius manque.
He is just the kind of person many would cross the street to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the movie is a rambling, episodic portrait of the
relationship between Mitchell (who died in 1996) and Gould, who
died indigent and senile at Pilgrim State Hospital on Long Island
four decades earlier (in 1957). Although that relationship had its
tender side, it was also mutually exploitative.
</P>
<P>
   The profiles, published more than two decades apart, in 1942 and
1964, significantly burnished Mitchell's journalistic reputation.
The first established Gould as a bohemian icon who held court at
the Minetta Tavern for fans who donated cash to his ever depleted
Joe Gould Fund.
</P>
<P>
   As infuriating as he is, Holm's Gould is also charismatic. A
Harvard graduate with an unstable personality and a major chip on
his shoulder, Gould moved in 1916 to New York City, where he
panhandled for a living while saying he was working on a literary
masterwork, his million-word-plus ``Oral History of Our Time.''
</P>
<P>
   He also claimed to understand and speak the language of sea
gulls and would entertain people in bars and at parties with his
expressive birdlike squawks.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Mitchell caught up with him, Gould's oral history,
an epic anthology of overheard conversations, essays and apercus
hand-written in school composition books, had been more than 25
years in the making. Gould boasted that if the collected notebooks
were stacked they would tower over his head.
</P>
<P>
   Their initial meeting takes place in a diner, where Gould
flamboyantly empties an entire bottle of ketchup into his soup.
Gould hungers for recognition, and it isn't long before he becomes
a pest, dropping in at the New Yorker offices at all hours and
demanding attention and whatever cash Mitchell can scrounge up.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell eventually resorts to having his receptionist cover for
him, and at one point she invents a bogus vacation. The
relationship becomes so uncomfortable that Mitchell guiltily hides
around a corner while Gould is talked out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell repeatedly presses Gould to produce his oral history,
but all Gould will show him are a few essays. The bulk of the work,
which Gould with typical grandiosity describes as mapping the
city's unconscious, is supposedly stored at a poultry farm on Long
Island. Gould's evasions lead Mitchell to doubt its very existence.
</P>
<P>
   The movie does a lovely job of evoking a boozy 1940s Greenwich
Village of poetry readings, cavernous bars and raucous parties.
Compared to today's free-for-all urban climate of sex, drugs,
hip-hop and voracious tourism, however, it all seems poignantly
innocent and genteel.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Sarandon and Patricia Clarkson have vivid cameos as the
legendary painter Alice Neel (whose nude portrait of Gould depicted
him as an exhibitionist with three penises) and Vivian Marquie, an
art gallery owner and close friend who administered Gould's modest
income from an anonymous benefactor.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes in flophouses, soup kitchens and a mental hospital
remind us that New York City's social safety net was a lot more
secure in those days.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its rich period ambience and Ian's fiery acting, the
movie never brings Mitchell's relationship to Gould into clear
enough focus. To play Mitchell (who came from North Carolina),
Tucci adopts a credible Southern accent, but his character remains
a suave, low-key enigma. Even in the scenes of Mitchell at home
with his wife, the photographer Therese Mitchell (Hope Davis), and
their two children, the character comes across as a slightly
wistful, gentlemanly observer of his own life.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking dramatic tension, ``Joe Gould's Secret'' settles for
being an atmospheric scenes-in-the-life biography of someone's most
unforgettable character. It could have been so much more. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `JOE GOULD'S SECRET'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Stanley Tucci; written by Howard A. Rodman, based on
``Professor Sea Gull'' and ``Joe Gould's Secret'' by Joseph
Mitchell; director of photography, Maryse Alberti; edited by Suzy
Elmiger; music by Evan Lurie; production designer, Andrew Jackness;
produced by Elizabeth W. Alexander, Tucci and Charles Weinstock;
released by USA Films/October Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Ian Holm (Joe Gould), Stanley Tucci (Joe Mitchell), Hope
Davis (Therese Mitchell), Sarah Hyland (Elizabeth Mitchell), Hallee
Hirsh (Nora Mitchell), Celia Weston (Sarah), Patrick Tovatt (Harold
Ross), Susan Sarandon (Alice Neel) and Patricia Clarkson (Vivian
Marquie).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 108 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Gould's Secret'' is rated R (under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It has strong language and
a glimpse of a male nude portrait.
</P>
</TEXT>
