<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-WRESTLING-WRESTLEMANI     04-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRESTLING-WRESTLEMANIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WWF reaches another crossroads
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's called the Super Bowl of professional wrestling, and this
year the WWF's WrestleMania pay-per-view had all the hype and TV
saturation as a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A record crowd of pay-per-view subscribers was expected to pay
the $49.95 for Sunday's broadcast, not so much for the live event
as to relive the past 15 WrestleManias through highlight clips and
wrestlers' remembrances of WrestleManias past. That led up to the
16th WrestleMania, live from The Pond in Anaheim, Calif.,
culminating in a noon-to-midnight extravaganza.
</P>
<P>
   The live crowd at The Pond numbered 13,871, who paid more than
$1.2 million to attend, small by WrestleMania standards. But the
pay-per-view crowd is expect to reach record figures. Although
exact numbers are not expected until next week, the show will
undoubtedly have the largest gross of the year for wrestling
programs, considering the high price (normally $29.95) and the
viewers who were drawn to the unprecedented offering of historical
footage.
</P>
<P>
   WrestleMania viewers are rarely disappointed; some of the major
turning points in WWF history have occurred at WrestleMania.
Sunday's event was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   But let's look at the history first. The highlight reels shown
Sunday featured three WWF watershed events.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved the largest crowd ever to watch a live
professional wrestling event in the United States. WrestleMania III
in 1987 was held at the Pontiac Silverdome in Detroit, and although
many in attendance probably couldn't see a thing, 93,179 packed the
stadium to watch a showdown between up-and-coming Hulk Hogan and
aging-but-unbeatable Andre the Giant. Although Hogan was the
champion and an established star, the Giant had been such an icon
in the wrestling world that a victory over him would elevate Hogan
to icon status.
</P>
<P>
   As Hogan would say after the match, ``He's 7-foot-4 and over 500
pounds. If he didn't want to lose, he wasn't going to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Andre did allow Hogan to win and thus began Hogan's reign as
the undisputed king of the wrestling ring and a pop-culture icon.
</P>
<P>
   The next turning point for the WWF was 1990. For years the
Ultimate Warrior had been rampaging through the ring much like
Goldberg when he started his career. And like Goldberg, the
Ultimate Warrior had to meet and beat Hogan to complete his rise to
the top. The main event of WrestleMania VI featured Hogan and
Warrior in a matchup of the top two titleholders in the WWF. In the
end, the Warrior won and Hogan left to pursue an acting career.
</P>
<P>
   The effects on the WWF were not as rosy. A steroid scandal kept
WWF owner Vince McMahon in court and caused a lot of the heavily
muscled wrestlers to ``disappear'' and return much smaller. The WWF
and professional wrestling as a whole was on a downswing.
</P>
<P>
   Until the next turn. In 1997, ``Stone Cold'' Steve Austin was
running his mouth and stunning a WWF audience that had turned a
character who was a classic bad guy into one of the top fan
favorites. He met longtime champion Bret Hart in a match that
cemented Austin's future as the top wrestler in the WWF. Although
he lost the match, Austin won over all the fans by passing out
rather than quitting. The picture of Austin screaming in pain,
blood pouring down his face, made him the poster boy for the new,
raw WWF.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to the present. Sunday's event could also be a
turning point for the WWF, but not in a good way.
</P>
<P>
   The main event between The Rock, Mick Foley, the Big Show and
Triple H was not the best match of the night. In fact it probably
ranked third, behind a three-team ladder match between The Hardy
Boyz, the Dudley Boyz and Edge-Christian and a hardcore battle
royal that saw eight champions come and go in a 15-minute span.
</P>
<P>
   The main event was probably the final match in Foley's career,
and instead of going out with a ``bang-bang,'' he went out with a
whimper, injuring his shoulder early in the match so it was hard to
use his arm, and then completely missing a move on The Rock because
he didn't jump far enough. The ending was then a complete remake of
the Austin-McMahon feud that lasted too long two years ago and is
tired to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   With Eric Bischoff and Vince Russo taking over control of the
WCW and the possibility of WWF being without three of its top stars
(Foley to retirement, Austin to surgery and The Rock to make a
movie) for the next few months, the WWF is at another turning
point. Will it continue to dominate or are is it falling back to
the pack?
</P>
<P>
   With the announcement that the 2001 WrestleMania will be held at
the Astrodome in Houston with the hopes of breaking the 1987
attendance record, it will be important for McMahon to bring some
fresh ideas to the table before the cycle takes a downward spiral
again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
