<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FASHION-DESIGNERS09-C     04-06 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-DESIGNERS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q&AMP;A with two of fashions hottest designers
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Those unfamiliar with Custo of Barcelona's sportswear or Steve
Madden's shoes might look at their designs and wonder, ``What were
they thinking?'' Each Custo piece is a wild collage of fabrics,
prints and colors. And Madden's shoes typically feature
treacherously high heels.
</P>
<P>
   But meeting and chatting with Madden and Custo Dalmau, as we did
recently, makes you aware that there's more method and meaning to
their mad styles than is readily apparent. It's also evident that
both designers' wares have a wider appeal than you might imagine.
</P>
<P>
   When Dalmau paid a visit to Neiman Marcus in Atlanta, dozens of
women lined up to buy the separates he was there to autograph.
Dalmau's tops and bottoms sell in the $55-$150 range, and some of
his fans bought as many as 10 pieces on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   Madden dropped by his Lenox Square mall boutique in Atlanta,
unannounced and went unnoticed as customers scurried around
snatching shoes to try on.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as he sat in the mall courtyard sipping coffee, he
pointed out scores of shoppers shod in his platforms and spike
heels.
</P>
<P>
   Since both designers' styles have a similarly youthful and
flamboyant attitude, we posed the same questions to Madden and
Dalmau to see how their responses would match up.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Are your designs based on how you want women to look, or on
what women say they want to wear?
</P>
<P>
   Custo Dalmau: The second. We imagine the woman as we like her to
look, and design for this woman.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Madden: It's a little bit of both. When you design
something you can't presume that someone will like it. You have to
do it because you like it.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: In terms of the business climate, is this a good time to be
taking design risks or do you have to be careful with what you
offer?
</P>
<P>
   CD: We always take a risk. For the 20 years we've been in this
business we haven't been conservative or traditional at all, and
we've always tried to do something new in fashion.
</P>
<P>
   SM: The easy answer is to say, `Oh, we've gotta take risks.'
You've got to take some risks, but it's also true that we're in the
business of making shoes that make sense and that our constituency
wants to wear. Occasionally we go out on the limb with something.
But usually when we create a shoe it makes sense to us. If we made
a flat, that would be a risk. But if we make a four-inch platform
it's not. Our girls have been wearing platforms for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: How big a challenge would it be for you to start designing
for men?
</P>
<P>
   CD: I think men are getting a little bit bored with what's on
the market. We're starting with 25 tops for men this fall and
they're selling (to stores) incredibly well; much more than what we
expected. I think the stores were starving for something new.
</P>
<P>
   SM: I've always said we may do men's shoes one day, but it's not
something that interests me personally. ...We might do it. We just
think we're good at what we do and want to stay focused.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: Which celebrity, to you, most embodies the spirit of your
designs?
</P>
<P>
   CD: Probably Madonna. She's the prototype of the woman who feels
individualistic, sexy and young. That's the woman we're targeting.
There are women 70 and 80 years old who wear our pieces, but they
have the mindsets of teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   SM: (long pause) Lauryn Hill. I think she'd be a good prototype.
She just seems fast, but not over-the-top. I'm not even a huge fan
of hers. But there's something about her that seems very stylish,
cool and of the times.
</P>
<P>
   AJC: What was the one big break that launched you into the big
time?
</P>
<P>
   CD: When we first started selling in America in 1996. ...The
stylists in Hollywood were all looking for something new to dress
stars in for the movies and TV. And by chance, they chose our
pieces. The first merchandise we shipped to this market wound up on
`Friends' and `Caroline in the City' and other popular shows. It
was a case of being in the right place at the right time.
</P>
<P>
   SM: We've had a lot of breaks, but one of the biggest came in
'93 when we made this one shoe called the Mary Lou. It was a patent
leather Mary Jane style. We made it and I started getting calls
from the mothers of all these kids who wanted it to wear to
parties. That set us off on this direction of being a popular
teenage brand.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
