<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0237 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9014 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SAVANNAH09-COX     04-06 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVANNAH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Savannah embraces elegant newcomer on the river's edge
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By Eileen M. Drennen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAVANNAH, Ga. _ Folks here are so grateful for the luxurious
Westin Savannah Harbor Resort on Hutchinson Island, a sandy spit of
land across the river from the city's historic district, that they
haven't particularly minded that it opened as something of a work
in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The Westin's ballrooms and restaurants have been hopping with
meetings and parties since the December debut of the 16-story
Regency-style hotel with twin turrets and pricey details. Never
mind that the much-hyped Greenbrier Spa is still not finished and
won't be until April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Golfers can play 18 holes on the resort's lush golf course,
designed by the legendary Sam Snead. But forget about grabbing a
cold one at the clubhouse: It's not finished either.
</P>
<P>
   Locals would encourage you not to sweat the small stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Savannahians may love their city's cobblestone streets,
wrought-iron-enclosed gardens and oak-draped squares, but they are
not immune to a Stylish New Thing. Especially when it's as pretty
as the Westin, which sits on the banks of Hutchinson Island like
some younger cousin of St. Petersburg's Don CeSar.
</P>
<P>
   At twilight, the sun drapes the Westin's salmon-colored stucco
in dreamy washes of shell and lemon. Viewed from River Street
against the empty sky of the 18-hole golf course behind it, its
outline seems etched in dark pearl, a beacon for the steady stream
of locals and visitors who cross nightly by water taxi to play
here.
</P>
<P>
   AquaStar, the Westin's twinkly shrine to local seafood, draws
them with Lowcountry favorites and picture-window views of the
water and the lamp-lit city beyond. Meeting rooms are abuzz with
conventioneers and salesmen. And it's often hard to find a seat in
the tiny Midnight Sun bar (named for a song by native son Johnny
Mercer) overlooking river and marsh.
</P>
<P>
   With 403 rooms, the Westin is the biggest hotel this city _ so
rich in fancy B&AMP;Bs _ has ever seen. What's more, its construction
on this undeveloped stretch makes it the island's first real
destination (unless you count the former kaolin plant, boat garages
or racetrack). But it's not its last: The 330,000-square-foot
Savannah International Trade and Convention Center, expected to
inject $150 million yearly into the local economy, has its grand
opening May 5-6. Mixed-use housing and shops are planned as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's exciting about the Westin is that it's an upscale,
self-contained resort,'' says Tony Schopp, president of the
Savannah Convention and Visitors Bureau. ``It's the first we've had
here in Savannah in 20 years.'' (A Sheraton resort opened on
Wilmington Island, about eight miles away, in the '70s and closed
in the '90s).
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bringing Savannah its first championship golf
course, the Westin's proximity to the convention center makes it
the only resort in the country adjacent to a civic building of that
size.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy percent of the city's visitors come to River Street,''
Schopp adds. ``Now when they look across the river, they see growth
_ but we're not compromising the integrity of our historic
district. It's a win-win situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Westin's attention to detail continues inside. Reproduction
antiques, ornate rugs and kaleidoscopic blown-glass sculptures and
lamps fill the front lobby. As you'd expect from someplace so close
to the Savannah College of Art and Design, original art adorns the
walls. Atlantan Virginia Cannon, director of the Soho Myriad Art
Network, curated the SCAD-heavy collection, which includes
sculptures, photos and paintings of waterfront life and Savannah
vistas. Margaret Tolbert's sea-colored tile installation ``North
Florida Springs Mosaic'' arches over the main floor's grand
stairway, and work by Atlanta photographers Rob Brinson and Kathryn
Kolb crops up in hallways and alcoves.
</P>
<P>
   Since it's a resort, guest rooms are plush. The Westin's
10-layer ``Heavenly Bed'' _ piled high with comforter, down
blanket, duvet and three high-thread-count sheets and five pillows,
all in white _ is crisp truth in advertising. (But if your
shoulders are crying for a few hours with a masseuse, you'll have
to look elsewhere until the Greenbrier opens in late April. The
concierge can suggest a couple of substitutes, including the
Rejuvenation Center on Paulsen Street, about 15 minutes away. He'll
also arrange the gratis ride there and back.)
</P>
<P>
   In-room art is not the typical landscapes and florals of most
hotel chains, but the same kind of carefully selected work
displayed downstairs. Ours had chic architectural photos of rusted
hinges and locks, so reflective of this town's lived-in glory.
</P>
<P>
   Being on this side of the river means it's quiet at most hours,
the only sound being the musical traffic of boats. In post-midnight
blackness, we watched an impossibly huge (and barely lit) freighter
slide past our fourth-floor perch almost soundlessly. Yet another
reason to reserve a riverside room.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever you tire of hotel life, twice-hourly water taxis whisk
you to River Street in less than two minutes. Savannah's 2
1/2-square-mile historic district is compact enough to explore by
foot, and when you're ready for a nap, the watercab gets you back
to your room in no time.
</P>
<P>
   On a take-it-easy weekend, your biggest struggle may be deciding
where to eat. Everyone has a suggestion, but we found the lunch
crowd outside The Lady and Son's on West Congress Street on the
right track. Twenty minutes after adding our names to the list, we
were elbowing our way to the best buffet in town. Piled high with
Southern classics (three meats, including light and tender fried
chicken, and nine vegetables, from sweet potatoes to greens), it
also had surprisingly tasty spaghetti and meat sauce. And great
desserts and salad are included in the $9.99 price ($12.99 on
Sundays).
</P>
<P>
   For dinner, the Southwestern-style Tucson Grill on Broughton,
famous for preparing impossibly fresh guacamole right at your
table, hit the mark. Then we ducked back to the hotel for a
nightcap at the Midnight Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back across the water at the soft lights of Savannah's
historic district, we marveled at the city's considerable charms _
both enduring and new.
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Driving from Atlanta, take I-75 south to I-16
and go east to Savannah. Take Exit 38, which leads you onto the
Talmadge Bridge. Take Hutchinson Island exit onto Resort Drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hotel restaurant: AquaStar, open for lunch and dinner.
Appetizers from $3.95 to $21 (recommended: oyster sampler and fried
colossal shrimp) and entrees from $13.75 to $22.95
(almond-Parmesan-
</P>
<P>
   encrusted flounder and cedar-plank-baked salmon were
exceptional).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting around: Water taxis leave the Westin's dock at quarter
past and quarter till the hour; they leave River Street on the hour
and half-hour. Included in hotel fees for Westin guests; $2
round-trip for visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hotel: 1-800-937-8461 or 912-201-2000, www.westinsavannah
</P>
<P>
   .com. Room rates, based on double occupancy: $179, golf view;
$199, river view; $239-$299, club level.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Savannah Convention and Visitors Bureau:
1-877-728-2662. Web site: www.savannahvisit.com
</P>
<P>
   Eileen M. Drennen is the Arts Editor for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
