<HEADER>
A9022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-JOKES07-CO     04-06 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-JOKES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laugh tracks: NASCAR drivers, crews add smiles to the miles
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that NASCAR has gone big-time with a mega-bucks television
deal, stock-car racing probably will get more serious. But
participants in the sport still enjoy laughing at themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing is like dark comedy,'' driver Kyle Petty said. ``You
make fun of all the serious stuff. You make fun of wrecks, just so
you don't have to think about them.''
</P>
<P>
   Race long enough, Petty said, and three things are certain to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to leave the garage area at some point, ride
around, build up speed on the backstretch, and the hood's going to
blow straight up, because they left the hood pins out,'' Petty
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometime during the race, you're going to leave a pit stop,
and your tires are going to run off, because they didn't get the
lug nuts on, because you left too soon. Sometime during your
career, you're going to hit the wall so hard that you don't know
where you're at until the Wednesday or Thursday of that week.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty, of course, is three for three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit the wall early,'' he said. ``I just left the hood pins
out on purpose to get it over with. And you feel like an idiot when
the wheels are falling off. Everybody's done it. It's just
miscommunication. You're thinking you're going to change two tires;
they're thinking you're going to change four. While they're
changing the right side, they're taking the left side lug nuts off.
They drop the jack, you take off.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's a wreck at Indianapolis that makes Petty look
humorously at racing's dark side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I blew a tire going into turn four, and I hit the outside
wall,'' Petty recalled. ``I hit a ton. It knocked me just goofy.
Then I hit again, and I thought I had hit the outside wall and come
back across the race track and hit the inside wall. That's really
all I remember. Then I kind of woke up and they were trying to get
me out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``What had happened was I hit the outside wall, I came back
across the track, and Sterling Marlin hit me in the left front and
drove the wheel up on the motor, and it hung the accelerator wide
open. I went back and hit the outside wall again, then it came
across and hit the inside wall. I don't remember the last two hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in this car, and I wake up, and I'm all slumped over. The
rescue guy's talking to me, and I'm like, `Yeah.' I got my eyes
closed. You ever wake up in the morning and you're in a fog? You
know things are going on, but you're not really sure it's a dream
or whether you're awake. So I'm kind of in a fog and I'm praying.
I'm praying that if I did die that I'm going to heaven. I told 'em
I'd heard Sterling Marlin talking, and I knew I'd died and gone to
hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, he was removed from the car and lifted on a stretcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time they went to pick me up, they said I'd scream. A
blood-curdling scream. And they'd set me back down. They did it
three times. Finally, they realized when the guy went to pick me
up, he was standing on my pony tail. Every time he'd go to pick me
up, it'd stretch my head back. Sterling had to get them off my pony
tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``From that point on, when I get in a car, I always take my pony
tail and double it and put another band around it, so it doesn't
hang out too far.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of NASCAR's humor is grim.
</P>
<P>
   One year during a race at Daytona, crew chief Tony Liberati got
distracted listening to MRN Radio's coverage. ``The radio said,
`The caution's coming out!' `` Liberati said. ``And I went running,
jumping up, throwing my hands up in the air, saying the caution's
coming out.'' Liberati was signaling driver Michael Waltrip to slow
down.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble was, MRN was playing a Daytona flashback of a wreck 15
years earlier between Cale Yarborough and David Pearson.
``Everybody looked at me like I was stupid. Once I realized what
I'd done, I sort of just sat there.''
</P>
<P>
   As a kid, Jeremy Mayfield raced go-karts, which intrigued his
mother, Judy Gordon. She started racing, too, and one night she was
running against her son.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were side by side, and going into the turn she cut across
me a little bit,'' Mayfield said. ``It was just enough to spin her
out. It didn't hurt her or anything, just spun her out. What made
it bad was it wasn't anything intentional at all, but, all of the
sudden there's ol' Jeremy turning his Mom. One guy said once, `You
hear about guys who'd spin their mother out to win a race, but
Jeremy actually did it!'''
</P>
<P>
   Adam Petty remembers when he started racing late models and
thought he was cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed up one night for practice and was horsing around and
talking to people,'' Petty said. ``It got time to put on my uniform
for practice, and I realized I had forgotten to bring it. I ended
up sitting around having to explain to everyone who walked by why I
was sitting there in street clothes, waiting for my Mom to bring my
uniform.''
</P>
<P>
   Things are a little more relaxed in the Winston Cup garage area,
now that Henry Benfield has retired. Benfield, former gas man for
the No. 4 car, was racing's most notorious practical joker.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 25 years, he delighted in serving opposing crew
members brownies baked with Ex-Lax and lemonade mixed with citrate
of magnesia. ``If you see somebody running, you'd better get out of
the way, because he has got to go,'' Benfield said.
</P>
<P>
   He also has sprayed racing gas on the toilet paper in the garage
restroom. ``You can hear those boys splashing water to cool off,''
he said. He teases the mechanics he knows are afraid of snakes by
throwing grass snakes at them. ``They even jump when you throw your
belt or a piece of rope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
