<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9023 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES07-CO     04-06 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    News and notes from the Winston Cup ciruit
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Young and hungry: As exemplified with Tony Stewart last year,
NASCAR thrives when new, young stars arrive and succeed. Dale
Earnhardt Jr. might have be one of the most hyped rookies to enter
the Winston Cup circuit, but he proved he belonged in the big time
with his string of top 10 qualifying efforts this season and,
finally, by driving down victory last week at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Little E'' predicts he won't be the last rookie to win in
2000. Who will be next rookie to roll down Victory Lane: Matt
Kenseth? Scott Pruett? Perhaps we'll find out at Martinsville.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING HEADLINES: Our take on the sport's top stories
</P>
<P>
   Tide driver involved in dirty deal: Scott Pruett was the
feel-good story of Texas for awhile. The rookie suffered the
embarrassment of failing to make the field at Bristol and
Darlington, but rallied back in sensational fashion by qualifying
third in the Lone Star State.
</P>
<P>
   Pruett stunned race fans by taking the lead on the fourth lap,
but was knocked out of contention a dozen laps later after three
consecutive bumps in the rear by Steve Park.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD:
</P>
<P>
   Long-overdue rule to be enforced: The most dangerous place to
work in NASCAR this year has been on pit road, not behind a
steering wheel. Many of the mishaps have occurred because of tires
left outside of the pit box.
</P>
<P>
   The sport's governing body announced that beginning Sunday,
teams will be penalized if right-side tires are left outside of the
pit box. Thankfully, no one was killed or seriously injured before
NASCAR finally took action.
</P>
<P>
   Will a record be broken? The Winston Cup Series has had a
roaring start in 2000 with seven different winners in seven races.
How long will this streak of different winners continue?
</P>
<P>
   Eight different winners in a row to start the season would be a
modern-era record. What's truly amazing is Jeff Gordon and Tony
Stewart, who combined for a total of 10 wins in 1999, have been
blocked from victory lane so far. Three-time Winston Cup champ
Gordon has gone 12 races without a top-five finish _ the worst
drought of his Winston Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   POWER INDEX: FAST TALKERS
</P>
<P>
   These drivers know their way around a microphone
</P>
<P>
   1. Jimmy Spencer _ Last month at Atlanta, moments after Dale
Jarrett openly blasted the press for continuing to harp on ``boring
racing,'' Spencer held court in the infield media center and talked
about how racing really was dull and what could be done to fix it.
This is one driver that shoots straight from the hip.
</P>
<P>
   2. Jeff Gordon _ The true measure of a driver is how they react
when things are not going well. This season has been disastrous for
Gordon _ by his standards. Yet, the Chevy No. 24 driver has refused
to run and hide from the media, unlike many other high-profile
drivers do in the same situation.
</P>
<P>
   3. Kyle Petty _ Ten years ago Petty was still getting questions
about the length of his hair. Today it's more than an afterthought
as he definitely does things his way. Petty is similar to Spencer
in a free-spirit manner of speaking, only he is much more radical
and funny. Son Adam will likely surpass his father down the road as
the best Petty spokeman.
</P>
<P>
   4. Darrell Waltrip _ D.W. revolutionized the way that the media
covers NASCAR. Twenty years ago few drivers realized the potential
of television. Most disappeared when they saw the cameras; not
Waltrip. In fact, he sought out the media and his wit, ability to
speak well, and tremendous on-camera presence was actually a
wake-up call to the rest of the drivers in the garage. He is
considered one of the master's of the one-liners.
</P>
<P>
   5. Rusty Wallace _ The Ford No. 2 crew likely cost Wallace a
shot at winning the Daytona 500 and they were not much better at
Rockingham. Who informed the press of these shortcomings about the
crew? Rusty Wallace. This Missouri native can never be accused of
being muzzled during an interview. Over the years he has been vocal
about other drivers, rule changes and even his current teammate.
</P>
<P>
   These NASCAR pros tell it like it is during interviews
</P>
<P>
   1. Larry McReynolds _ This part-time commentator for TNN
expresses himself well when discussing technical issues. He held
his ground in 1998 when being critical of Dale Earnhardt, the
driver he worked with for 18 months. He said that Earnhardt was not
``focused,'' which may have turned Earnhardt's career around.
</P>
<P>
   2. Todd Parrott _ Like father, like son. Buddy Parrott, team
manager for Jeff Burton, is a no-nonsense talker with a quick wit.
Todd Parrott, who makes the calls for Dale Jarrett, is built in the
same mold, and not afraid to hold his tongue on any issue. At Texas
Parrott chewed out Jarrett for giving teammate Ricky Rudd a lap
when a caution flag was raised. Parrott turned to a reporter and
said, ``That was Rudd's break for the day; they'll have to get the
rest on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   3. Robin Pemberton _ A little more mild-mannered than Rusty
Wallace, his outspoken driver, Pemberton will respond to a question
with a direct answer. Great one-liners, and known to return calls
to reporters while testing in a wind tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   4. Kevin Hamlin _ Faces the pressure of working for one of the
all-time greats, Dale Earnhardt. When ``The Intimidator'' gets
moody and doesn't have time to bother with media, Hamlin steps in.
He is a man of few words, but makes them count with valuable
insight.
</P>
<P>
   5. Andy Petree _ Owner of the No. 33 car and crew chief for
driver Joe Nemechek. Petree is never short on opinions. He
recognizes the importance of the media, and takes the proper time
to explain NASCAR rules or issues at length _ and in laymen's
terms.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, for the second time in his career, John Andretti
enters a Winston Cup race as a defending champion. He recently
spoke with Cox News Service reporter Rick Minter:
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does it feel to drive the No. 43 car, which won 200 races
and seven championships with your car owner, Richard Petty, at the
wheel?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's an ideal situation for me. A lot of driver who have
driven the No. 43 feel like they get caught in the King's shadow. I
like to get caught in the King's shadow. There are a lot of good
things that go with it, but there's also a tremendous amount of
responsibility because this car sort of identifies Winston Cup
racing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does Richard Petty talk to you on the radio during races?
</P>
<P>
   A: Very, very seldom do I ever hear his voice. I know that if I
hear his voice, either I'm in trouble or somebody else is. Usually
I only hear from him if I get in a fight on the race track with the
race cars. He always tells me that if I want to take something out,
don't take it out on my race car.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the fact that you're leaving Pontiac and getting a new
Dodge ready for next year going be a detriment this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Pontiac hasn't changed in a few years, so we're pretty
set with it. We've got a lot of work to do with the new Dodge, but
we should be ready to come out of the gate fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you and your uncle, Mario Andretti, talk a lot about
racing?
</P>
<P>
   A: Every time I do well in a race, I get a call from him. He's
usually the first or second message on my answering machine. That
really makes me feel good. I grew up with him, but I just didn't
realize who he was or how much he's done until I got older. Then I
was sort of intimidated by him, but when you get next to him and
talk to him, he's just like everybody else. But I have a lot of
admiration for everything he's done. It's the same with my
godfather, A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Since you're likely to be compared to racing legends Richard
Petty, Mario Andretti and A.J. Foyt, what kind of career will you
have to have to satisfy yourself?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a lot of ways, you're never going to be satisfied. The
King, Uncle Mario and A.J., they're not satisfied, because they
could have won one more 500 and they should have. I want to be
ultra successful, not so much for the fans, but so my peers _ the
people in the garage area _ will respect what I've done. That will
determine whether I'm satisfied or not.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
