<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, April 7. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Nawaz Sharif, ousted as
Pakistan's prime minister in a military coup last October, was
convicted Thursday of hijacking a commercial airliner, sentenced to
life imprisonment and ordered to forfeit all his personal property.
Standing along with six co-defendants who each were acquitted, the
balding, doughy Sharif barely blinked when the judgment was read. A
shriek from his daughter Maryam broke the silence. ``Have fear of
God!'' she cried out. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED-BLOOD (United Nations) _ More than two-thirds of the
world's nations fail to provide safe blood supplies, contributing
significantly to the spread of AIDS and other diseases, the World
Health Organization will announce on Friday. The sea of tainted
blood covers 4.8 billion people, about 80 percent of the world's
population. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has not seen
his son Elian since the boy and his mother left Cuba on a rickety
raft for a new life in America, set foot on American soil here
Thursday and told a crowd of reporters and television cameras that,
``I hope I will soon be able to embrace my son.'' Justice
Department officials said they would move quickly to transer
custody of the boy to his father. Senior administration officials
made it clear they believed that the arrival of Gonzalez from Cuba
had altered the situation dramatically in favor of their efforts to
transfer custody of the boy from his Miami relative. By Neil A.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CALIF (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Visiting California for the
first time since the March 7 primary, George W. Bush focused
strongly on education and reached out to Latino voters. Those are
two strategies that Bush's advisers and analysts say could be
crucial to any hopes that he might have of winning the state. And
in sticking to them, Bush seemed to signal, at least for now, an
intention to fight that battle. Although the conventionial wisdom
puts California in the Gore column, the March 7 primary results
give Bush some reason for hope. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-POLL (New York) _ Results of the latest NYT-CBS poll
on the New York Senate race between Rudy Giuliani and Hillary
Rodham Clinton. By Adam Clymer and Marjorie Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARGINS (Chicago) _ Looking at margin calls and their
impact on the market. Trying to get voices of small investors who
have received margin calls and how they are reacting. Developing.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ The human genome, the 3 billion
chemical letters that encode the genetic instructions for making
and maintaining a human being, will be decoded within three to six
weeks, Dr. J. Craig Venter, the president of Celera Corp. told a
congressional committee Thursday. Celera, which jumped into a race
with a public funded consortium of academic centers 22 months ago,
now seems likely to achieve a clear victory. Though Venter's claims
have been challenged in the past, his successful completion last
month of a pilot project, the fruitfly genome, has in effect
silenced critics. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-PROTEST-SUIT (New York) _ A U.S. District Court judge struck
down a city law Thursday governing the number of protesters allowed
on the steps of City Hall, ruling that the city could not deny
access to a favored spot for everything from demonstrations to news
conferences. The struggle over access to the City Hall steps has
become one of the symbolic battles of the Giuliani administration,
with the mayor arguing increased security is needed and opponents
claiming they have been barred from the city's quintessential
public space. In his third decision regarding protests in front of
City Hall, Judge Harold Baer focused on city officials' decisions
to allow certain gatherings, such as a Yankees victory celebration,
while denying others. By John Sullivan.
</P>
</TEXT>
