</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE AMERICAN PRESIDENT': A SWEEPING SURVEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
 By WILLIAM McDONALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   One was described by contemporaries as ``a third-rate
nonentity,'' another as ``a total failure _ cowardly, weak, senile
and vacillating.'' Still another saved everyone the trouble when he
volunteered this self-appraisal: ``I am not fit for this office and
should never have been here.''
</P>
<P>
   A sorry lot indeed, and happily for the Republic they're gone
now; they're history. Yet for a time these men _ respectively,
Rutherford B. Hayes, James Buchanan and Warren G. Harding _ held
the highest office in the land.
</P>
<P>
   How could that have happened? Beginning Sunday night on PBS,
``The American President'' _ a sprawling, flawed, but ultimately
worthwhile 10-part documentary in which those withering assessments
are heard _ tries to supply some answers.
</P>
<P>
   It also prompts a disconcerting thought: if we're no smarter
than our forebears (and we're not), and if history repeats itself
(as it probably will), what sort of major American electoral
mistakes might be in store for the 21st century?
</P>
<P>
   The documentary, narrated by Hugh Sidey, Time magazine's veteran
White House correspondent, and enriched by commentary by the
eminent Harvard historian Richard E. Neustadt, shies away from
speculating about the future. But in keeping with its respectful
and celebratory tone, the series does offer a reassuring if
unsurprising moral: that no matter who has occupied the presidency,
and no matter how fit or unfit for the job he has been, a certain
genius has nevertheless presided over the land since the founders
put their experimental apparatus of laws in motion, a genius
planted not in the executive's chair but in the country's very
system of government. And that system of checks and balances, the
series makes clear, has endured, albeit fitfully and
notwithstanding the occasional mediocrity or worse at the helm.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to suggest that ``The American President'' is
weighted toward the misfits. In a manner both grandly comprehensive
and, even in 10 hours over five consecutive nights, necessarily
cursory, the documentary surveys the entire bunch, from George
Washington to Bill Clinton, acting something like the moderator of
a presidential debate as it gives roughly equal time to each.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the project's creators, Philip Kunhardt Jr. and his sons
Philip III and Peter, pride themselves on being the first
documentarians to examine the terms of all 42 presidents.
</P>
<P>
   But that's about as far as their groundbreaking goes. The
Kunhardts have otherwise modeled their series on what has by now
become the industry standard for high-end historical documentaries.
Call it the Ken Burns approach: Find striking archival photographs
and artwork, as Burns did in his ``Civil War'' series; let the
camera pan over or zoom in on the stills to inject movement;
overlay the visuals with evocative period music; interlace with
sage commentary; and hire famous people to speak the words of
distant historical figures.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The American President,'' a star-spangled roster of
political and media figures worthy of Washington's best dinner
parties can be heard as the voices of the chief executives, and
part of the fun of watching is waiting to see who gets to be whom.
Thus we hear, among others, Bob Dole as Herbert Hoover, Andrew
Young as Thomas Jefferson (a touch of irony, given Jefferson's
reputed conduct as a slaveholder), Tim Russert as Millard Fillmore,
Ben Bradlee as Warren G. Harding and, perhaps the most inspired
choice of all, Don Imus as the unsavory Andrew Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, though, the pairings are off: Abraham Lincoln is
said to have spoken at a higher pitch, but his voice here belongs
to that basso profundo Paul Simon, the former senator from
Illinois. And Walter Cronkite (George Washington) will never be
convincing as anyone but Walter Cronkite.
</P>
<P>
   As chroniclers, the Kunhardts have wisely avoided organizing
their series by potentially deadening chronology. Instead they've
taken a thematic approach, linking and juxtaposing a handful of
presidents in each episode by a common characteristic. This makes a
livelier telling of history, and most of the groupings make sense.
One episode rounds up presidents like John Tyler and Chester A.
Arthur, who came to power through the death of a predecessor;
another groups those who made their mark in foreign affairs, like
Woodrow Wilson and George Bush. But some marriages seem strained.
Thomas Jefferson is joined with Calvin Coolidge, for example, as
men of ``executive vision.''
</P>
<P>
   What is lost in this format is the flow of history; a segment on
Ulysses S. Grant and Reconstruction, for instance, is followed by
one on Dwight D. Eisenhower and the nuclear age. Only minor damage
is done here, though; Sidey's pithy narration does well in placing
a presidential profile in context even when lifted out of
historical sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the series doesn't propose to trace an American
timeline as threaded through the executive branch. It's more a
cavalcade of presidential character, a mix-and-match primer on the
men who shaped and were shaped by events, with an emphasis on
personality, idiosyncrasy and illuminating biographical detail.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9034 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-WEEKEND-2NDTAKE-NY     04-06 0388
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: biographical detail.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As such, it offers polished and intelligent television to the
general viewer but probably little news to the serious student of
history. Given so much ground to cover, much of it well-trodden,
the series by necessity sacrifices some depth as it forced to leap
from one salient point to another, leaving gaps in between. At one
point we're told how Harry S. Truman went from the bottom of the
popularity polls to an upset re-election victory over Thomas E.
Dewey. How did he pull it off? The documentary says only that
Truman refused ``to be submerged.''
</P>
<P>
   Also missing here is a range of opinion. Neustadt, whose seminal
book ``Presidential Power'' persuaded John F. Kennedy to seek out
its author for advice, provides much adroit commentary and a
charmingly rumpled professorial presence. And he is so steeped in
White House lore that he recalls each president as if he had known
him. But not only is his the final word on every president, it's
the only word. Other historians' views would have been welcome,
particularly concerning more recent presidents whose importance is
still being argued about. (With the exception of the incapacitated
Ronald Reagan, all the surviving former presidents, as well as
President Clinton, are interviewed for their segments.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, in the case of the impeachment-torn Clinton presidency
and the poisonously partisan environment in which it has
functioned, we're given only one sweeping conclusion to draw, and
as enunciated by Neustadt, it's a debatable _ not to mention
downbeat _ one at that. ``It is now plain,'' he says, ``that every
president, immediately upon election, attracts the serious interest
of political opponents and the professional interests of the media
in tearing him down and pushing him toward resignation.''
</P>
<P>
   If that is true, then we can thank the founders one more time
for those ingenious checks and balances. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE AMERICAN PRESIDENT'
</P>
<P>
   9 p.m. Sunday on PBS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First two hours of a 10-hour documentary series written,
produced and directed by Philip B. Kunhardt Jr., Philip B. Kunhardt
III and Peter W. Kunhardt. A co-production of Kunhardt Productions
and WNET/New York. Peter W. Kunhardt and William R. Grant,
executive producers.
</P>
