<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART NOTES: WERNHER COLLECTION TO BE AUCTIONED; DISPUTE OVER A
PICASSO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Britain, Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Selling a Rubens And Other Gems
</P>
<P>
   Christie's in London seems to be getting some of Europe's
greatest collections to sell. Last summer, in a sale that totaled
$89.9 million, it auctioned Old Master paintings, objects, arms and
armor, as well as one of the world's greatest collections of
scientific instruments, which had been looted by the Nazis and
returned to the Austrian branch of the Rothschild family.
</P>
<P>
   On July 5, it will auction artworks from the Wernher collection
of Old Master paintings, French furniture, silver and Renaissance
sculpture, which was housed for nearly a century at Bath House,
Piccadilly, and at Luton Hoo, Bedfordshire. The sale is expected to
bring more than $16 million.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was formed by Julius Wernher, a diamond merchant
who was a governor of De Beers, the South African diamond
conglomerate, and his friend Wilhelm von Bode, the director of the
Kaiser Friedrich Museum in Berlin. ``With the exception of families
like the Rothschilds, Wernher had a kind of taste that didn't exist
anywhere in England,'' said Lord Hindlip, chairman of Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Wernher died in 1912, and his second son, Harold Wernher, who
lived at Luton Hoo, followed in his father's footsteps as a
collector and philanthropist. He died in 1973. His heirs and the
Wernher Foundation are selling these works to raise money to
preserve the rest of the collection.
</P>
<P>
   While Sotheby's sold some of Luton Hoo's contents in 1995,
Christie's has represented the Wernher family for generations,
negotiating the sales of several paintings to a number of museums.
The most important of these transactions was the sale of ``Christ
Taking Leave of His Mother,'' by Albrecht Altorfer, to the National
Gallery in London in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights of Christie's sale is a Rubens, ``Diana and
Her Nymphs Hunting'' (circa 1636-37), one of the famous series he
painted for Philip IV of Spain to display at Torre de la Parada,
the royal hunting lodge near Madrid. This oil sketch is considered
one of the best examples of Rubens' Baroque period. It is expected
to sell for $960,000 to $1.2 million. The sale also includes
Titian's ``Portrait of Giacomo Doria'' (circa 1531), estimated at
$1.1 million to $1.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   Also for sale is outstanding silver, including two superb
examples of late Gothic figures: St. Sebastian and St. Christopher.
St. Christopher, made in 1493, is an intricate work that shows him
carrying Jesus on his shoulders across a silver river. The figures
are expected to sell for $1.5 million each.
</P>
<P>
   A Picasso Problem
</P>
<P>
   A lawsuit may be looming between the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art and the trust established by one of its longtime
supporters, Madeleine Haas Russell, who died last year at 84.
Russell, one of San Francisco's most important philanthropists as
well as a museum trustee and a great-grandniece of Levi Strauss,
set up the trust in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 2, the trust entered into an oral agreement _ which
Charles B. Cohler, a lawyer for the museum and its trustees Charles
and Helen Schwab, described as legally binding _ to sell Picasso's
``Nude on a Black Armchair,'' a 1932 portrait of his mistress
Marie-Therese Walter. The museum and the Schwabs had agreed to buy
the painting for $44 million and to pay Sotheby's a fee of 5
percent of the purchase price as its commission for negotiating the
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The Schwabs intended to make a donation to the museum to finance
its 40 percent interest in the painting. They were also prepared to
acquire the rest for themselves and to leave their share to the
museum upon their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The museum contends that the trust breached its agreement by
deciding instead to sell the painting in November at Christie's,
where Leslie Wexner, chairman of the Limited, bought it for $45.1
million. (That figure includes the $41 million purchase price plus
Christie's commission, 15 percent of the first $50,000 and 10
percent of the rest.)
</P>
<P>
   Had the trust ended up selling the painting to the museum and
the Schwabs, it would have received $3 million more, and the
painting would have been on public view for at least part of each
year.
</P>
<P>
   According to memos and letters from the museum's lawyers, the
breach of contract cost the institution a prized Picasso, which
would have helped raise its attendance. It is seeking damages in
excess of $18 million, or 40 percent of what experts consider the
fair market value of the painting.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the trust say that they had no enforceable contract,
and that if the museum wanted the painting so badly, it could have
bid at auction, as it had done in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the museum wait six months instead of trying to stop the
November auction? ``On Oct. 18, the museum and the Schwabs invited
the Russell Trust to resolve this question by private arbitration,
and only last week did they reject that proposal,'' Cohler said.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Mead, the lawyer for the trust, said that it had promptly
rejected the October request for arbitration, and that the museum
asked again in March and again was told no.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident that when the museum trustees give the matter
proper consideration, they will conclude that it would be reckless
to pursue these baseless claims,'' said Mead. Cohler said, ``The
museum is considering its legal rights and remedies.''
</P>
<P>
   A Met Retirement
</P>
<P>
   After 30 years at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York,
Dr. Wen C. Fong, its first consultative chairman of the department
of Asian art and its curator of Chinese painting and calligraphy,
will retire on June 30. Fong, 69, played a major role in building
the museum's Asian collection, expanding and renovating its
galleries and organizing dozens of exhibitions. Philippe de
Montebello, director of the Met, said a search for a successor
would begin immediately.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1706EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-06 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTIQUES: A SHOW FIT FOR PANDORA 
</HEADLINE>
   By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Helen Costantino Fioratti, the Manhattan antiques
dealer, bought her first antique when she was 16. ``One day I found
a Gothic case covered in red silk velvet in a cardboard box at an
auction house,'' she recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took it home to mother,'' Fioratti said, referring to Ruth,
Countess Costantino, one of the first female dealers in antiques
and fine art in the United States, ``and she recognized it. She
told me it was very rare and had once belonged to Mrs. Firestone.''
Thus began a passion that continues to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helen has been buying boxes her whole life,'' said James
Montrose Sansum, her partner at L'Antiquaire and the Connoisseur, a
gallery in Manhattan, which opened in 1918.
</P>
<P>
   Fioratti writes in the preface to ``Tempting Pandora,'' a
225-page book of scholarly essays, ``The box is truly a temptation
to have, to hold and, of course, to open, as poor Pandora
discovered.'' The book accompanies a show of 150 European boxes
made from 1200 to 1800, at the gallery through April 21. The show
then moves to the Foster-Gwin Gallery in San Francisco, May 16
through June 1. Prices range from $750 to $235,000.
</P>
<P>
   According to Greek mythology, Pandora, the first woman on earth,
was endowed with every charm. Zeus gave her a box and told her she
must not open it. She couldn't resist and raised its lid, releasing
all the evils that have afflicted humanity ever since. The
sumptuous boxes in this show make one understand Pandora's
weakness.
</P>
<P>
   These are no mere utilitarian containers but works of art. There
are treasure boxes made for sacred relics or jewels. The group
includes reliquaries, missal coffers made for transport, gilded
leather cases for ink containers, sweetmeat boxes, game boxes,
snuff boxes and cosmetics cases. Made of ebony, ivory, metal,
leather, straw, enamel and wood, they are decorated with silver,
mother-of-pearl, tortoise shell, ivory, embroidery and precious
stones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the earliest boxes is an enameled pyx made in Limoges,
France, about 1230. The pyx is a religious object used to hold the
Communion host or holy oil for baptisms or last rites. This one is
cylindrical, with a conical lid that once held a cross finial. It
is covered with scrolls of gilded copper on blue champleve enamel.
A reliquary coffer made in Constantinople around 1270 was once
owned by John Pierpont Morgan. It is decorated with the Tree of
Jesse, the symbolic depiction of the genealogy of Jesus, and
illustrates the line from the prophet Isaiah: ``And there shall
come forth a rod out of the stem of Jesse, and a branch shall grow
out of its roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a red cloak, Jesse is shown sleeping on one side of the
box. Tree branches encircle his son David and other Biblical
ancestors of Jesus. An angel wearing a cuirass and grasping a
scabbard is probably Michael, the archangel warrior. On another
side, a different angel appears in a dream to a figure that is
probably Joseph, warning him to flee Bethlehem and the massacre of
the innocents. The stylized, finely painted faces recall Byzantine
mosaic saints.
</P>
<P>
   Other boxes have no religious significance. In the catalog, the
Baltimore art historian Dr. Martha A. McCrory writes about the
forziere, the painted marriage chest that Italians made in the 14th
and 15th centuries to furnish the camera, or main room, in an
Italian palazzo. The show has several examples of the forziere,
which ``accompanied the bride when she arrived in her new home,
where it served to contain clothing and linens,'' McCrory writes.
``The furniture in the camera was not renewed during the course of
a marriage and was thus an important nuptial acquisition, sometimes
ordered from the most important painters of a city.''
</P>
<P>
   Fioratti added: ``After a wedding such chests were paraded
through the streets to show people how rich and important the
couple was. Only later on, when they were safely inside, did the
husband open it. Often there was a painting of a nude female figure
on the inside of the lid to show the husband what he was getting.''
</P>
<P>
   She has several French strongboxes from the 15th century. They
look like trunks. ``We see the shape as an early Spanish form, but
it was probably influenced by Arab cabinets brought to Spain,''
Sansum said. ``Strongboxes were made by the craftsmen who fashioned
arms and armor.'' The boxes are sheathed with interlocking iron
loops, like chain mail. Some have locks with hidden keyholes. ``You
have to push a secret lever to release the keyhole cover,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the safes is lined in cream-colored linen that is held in
place by bright red leather cross bands secured with golden studs.
The inside is as sumptuous as the outside is forbidding. Other
boxes, originally inspired by Middle Eastern cases designed to hold
the Koran, are inlaid with ivory, ebony, stained bone and precious
woods arranged in geometric motifs. Merchants in the Levantine sold
such inlaid wood boxes to Italy, and the Venetians copied them. The
boxes in the show are Venetian and are decorated in orange, green,
black and white.
</P>
<P>
   One case, which was made to hold an ink container, is covered in
leather. The leather is elaborately tooled with scrolling foliage
patterns. The catalog says the technique of boiling leather to make
cases dates back to Neolithic times and became popular in France
and England only in the 14th century. The leather was softened in
water, molded into a shape, then dried in moderate heat until it
hardened. It was then decorated by incising lines with a pointed
tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leather was used to protect precious things that had to be
constantly transported, like books with miniatures or scribes' ink
wells,'' she said. ``If you were an important person, everything
you carried had to show how important you were. You had to have
beautiful accouterments.''
</P>
<P>
   Antique boxes covered in embroidery, applique or needlework are
rare because the ground material, usually silk, faded or
disintegrated in sunlight. The decoration was usually figural,
floral or geometric. ``Many embroideries resembled plans for
landscape architecture, such as the parterres of Versailles,''
writes Annie Carlano, a former textiles curator at the Museum of
Fine Arts in Boston, in the catalog. ``The great Florentine
needlework traditions were brought to the French court by Catherine
de' Medici, herself an avid embroiderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Who needs a university core curriculum when you can learn all
this from a group of boxes?
</P>
<P>
   Audubon Record
</P>
<P>
   A double elephant, four-volume set of ``Birds of America'' by
John James Audubon has been sold at Christie's New York for $8.8
million, against an estimate of $4 million. Francis Wahlgren, head
of Christie's book department in New York, said the March 10 sale
set a world auction record for a printed book. ``This price,'' he
said, ``smashes Christie's previous record of $7.6 million for
Chaucer's `Canterbury Tales,' sold at Christie's London in July
1998.'' The previous record for a ``Birds of America'' was $4
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
