<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9038 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS09-COX     04-06 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Culture goes from lowbrow to `Nob(registered)ow'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, April 9.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a puzzle for you: Why should Mark Fuhrman, Andrew Morton
and Cynthia Ozick be mentioned in the same breath?
</P>
<P>
   A one-time L.A. cop whose name was made infamous during the O.J.
Simpson trial. A celebrity biographer (Princess Diana, the
Windsors, Monica Lewinsky). A novelist and critic whose work has
appeared in The New York Review of Books and The New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   A mixed bag, to say the least. But the answer is that they are
all, in their rather different ways, authors, and if you can guess
which of the three must plead her case, then you know the culture
we live in.
</P>
<P>
   It comes to John Seabrook as something of a surprise, but better
that he know one of the facts of commerce: The masses like their
schlock and the publishing industry is happy to keep their bellies
full. Seabrook, a writer for The New Yorker, Vanity Fair and
Harper's, tells a story of attending a panel discussion at the New
York Public Library on the future of books. The discussion brought
together writers and readers, booksellers and publishers, with
media columnist Ken Auletta moderating.
</P>
<P>
   These tend to be dull affairs, swollen with platitudes, suffused
with piety for the written word. But halfway through the evening,
Ozick voiced a concern of serious writers: the need to preserve
midlist authors, those writers whose books are not automatic best
sellers, who do not pander to the lowest common denominator, who
instead write with wit and intelligence about literature and
culture, history and current affairs.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts she made her plea with much eloquence, and a
sympathetic audience warmly applauded. Then it was Leonard Riggio's
turn.
</P>
<P>
   A question of the bottom line
</P>
<P>
   Riggio is the president of Barnes &AMP; Noble, and his first words
were: ``Well, Cynthia, I happen to have your sales figures right
here.'' He must have anticipated an appeal on behalf of art because
he had his computer printout handy and it showed that Cynthia Ozick
was not a big seller at Barnes &AMP; Noble. She was, Seabrook leads us
to think, a lesser attraction than the Mark Fuhrmans and the Andrew
Mortons.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, no fan of Cynthia Ozick's will be disappointed at
chains like Barnes &AMP; Noble or Borders. She is hardly obscure, and
her books are reliably in stock. Nonetheless, Riggio made his
point: ``So why should the publishing industry support a midlist
book that readers clearly don't want?''
</P>
<P>
   If you say it's a legitimate business question, you must
acknowledge it's also the question of a philistine. When the bottom
line becomes the only arbiter of value, publishing is no different
from network television.
</P>
<P>
   This is the familiar issue _ art vs. commerce _ from which
Seabrook tries to derive a more general cultural significance. To
say that he has bitten off more than he can chew is putting it
generously, but he drops enough names and fires enough buckshot
that a casual reader is persuaded he is not entirely wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The old lines that once separated the highbrow from the
middlebrow, and both from the lowbrow, have disintegrated, he says,
and what we have in their place is the triumph of marketing. Nobrow
is the democratization of entertainment in all its forms. They are
nothing more than commodities, up one day, down another, their
worth measured by numbers. What fuels their market value is not
intrinsic merit but ``the Buzz'' _ what people are saying about
them, what people are able to get other people to say about them.
Performance is superseded by promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing deeply on personal experience
</P>
<P>
   None of this is news, exactly, but Seabrook touches all the
obvious bases _ the film industry, the magazine business, books,
music _ and creates the superficial impression of having canvassed
pretty much everything. He draws, for example, on the disappointing
sales of his first book, ``Deeper: My Two-Year Odyssey in
Cyberspace,'' to illustrate what in fact is little more than
personal experience:
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the book was about the Net, a
</P>
<P>
   pop-culture subject, the publisher had been persuaded that
`Deeper' would be a popular megastore commodity, maybe even a best
</P>
<P>
   seller, and I had been paid a large advance to write the book.
I, in turn, took the advance as confirmation that I was, in fact,
writing a best sellr. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``the book tanked.'' Publisher's expectations to the
contrary, ``I had produced a book that was neither a high brow
literary work nor low brow guide to the Net, but some unmarketable
combination of categories: the dreaded tweener.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this may be true, but it is only evidence of _ at most _
poor marketing. By implication, that is part of what Seabrook wants
to say. But he is so busy dropping glamorous names and recounting
trivial experiences that the pillars of a real argument are never
planted. It may be, of course, that he takes those pillars to
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
