A9039 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MEAT07-COX     04-06 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEAT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    END URGED TO BAN ON INTERSTATE SHIPMENT OF STATE-INSPECTED MEAT
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    BY ISMAIL TURAY Jr.
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ban on interstate shipment of state-inspected
meat and poultry should be lifted to provide a ``level playing
field'' for the nation's small meat-packing businesses, Congress
was told Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, consisting of government officials and
representatives from various meat processing organizations, urged
the Senate Agriculture Committee to pass the New Markets for
State-Inspected Meat Act.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation will help increase competition in the meat
packing industry, said Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, who along with
Sen. Tom Daschle, D-S.D., co-sponsored the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, only federally inspected meat can be shipped from
state to state. Hatch said, however, that three separate U.S.
Department of Agriculture advisory committees have recommended
lifting the ban on state-inspected products as a way to create more
opportunities for small packers and livestock producers in rural
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's okay to sell state-inspected beef or pork in Utah, but
nowhere else. That make absolutely no sense,'' he said. ``But what
makes less sense is the fact that while those Nevada casinos or
Idaho supermarkets are banned from buying sausage and other
products from Utah, they have no problem whatsoever importing it
from a foreign country.''
</P>
<P>
   Forty-one small plants since 1996 have been forced to shut down
in Ohio alone as a result of the ban, said Fred Dailey, director of
the state's Department of Agriculture. A 1997 Ohio State University
study found that Ohio's economy would increase by more than $56
million annually if the ban were lifted, Dailey added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the question before you,'' he told the committee, ``is
whether it is time to create a level economic playing field and
provide the same opportunities for all meat and poultry processors,
both large and small, or to continue the government-sanctioned
economic advantage for large corporations and foreign competitors
at the expense of small business owners and operators.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents told the committee that the proposed law would mean
that the uniform system for meat inspection will be eliminated,
making it easier for diseases such as salmonella to spread.
</P>
<P>
   However, the American Meat Institute would support the bill if
it required state inspectors to follow the many notices, directives
and other federal requirements that are not regulations, but
constitute the ``nuts and bolts'' of the system under which federal
plants operate, said J. Patrick Boyle, AMI president.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be truly uniform, state plants must meet these same
requirements and the bill should explicitly state this,'' said
Boyle, whose organization represents plants producing more than 70
percent of the country's beef, pork, lamb, veal and turkey
products.
</P>
<P>
   Before state-inspected plants can ship interstate, USDA will
first conduct comprehensive reviews of all state programs and
confirm that all recommendations from the reviews have been
implemented, responded Richard Rominger, the Department of
Agriculture's deputy secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said that under the legislation, all salmonella
performance standards for products eligible for a federal mark of
inspection, whether in a federal or state establishment, will be
collected by the his department and analyzed in its laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will also give consumers confidence in federal oversight
of the system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Turay Jr.'s e-mail address is ismailt(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
