w e BC-IVOR-SANDRA-BULLOCK-I     04-06 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-SANDRA-BULLOCK-IN-28-DAYS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK SIDE: SANDRA BULLOCK FACES HER OWN DEMONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Sandra Bullock
in scenes from ``28 Days.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Believe it or not, Sandra Bullock _ Hollywood's eternally
buoyant Little Mary Sunshine _ says that a recent four-day stay in
a drug-and-alcoholic-rehabilitation clinic changed her life.
 &HT;    No, of course Bullock doesn't have a drug or alcohol problem,
nor has she ever. The actress visited the rehab center Sierra
Tucson to conduct research for her latest movie, ``28 Days,'' which
will open April 14.
 &HT;    In the dark comedy _ think ``MASH'' (1970) _ Bullock plays
successful New York writer Gwen Cummings, a falling-down drunk
whose life is completely out of control after too many
party-hopping nights on the town. When she's arrested after a
particularly disgraceful exhibition at her sister's wedding, she
ends up sentenced to spend 28 days drying out at a clinic.
 &HT;    A YMCA in Asheville, N.C., stood in for the clinic in shooting
the movie, but Bullock went to Tucson, Ariz., to visit a real
clinic to learn more about both alcoholism and rehab itself.
 &HT;    She was there for only four days, she says, but learned more
than 28 days' worth of life lessons.
 &HT;    ``I have friends in the program,'' she explains, ``and when I
hear of some of their behavior I can't believe it, because it seems
so uncharacteristic of the people I know.
 &HT;    ``But I learned that the fault is in the behavior and not the
person,'' Bullock says. ``It's what the drugs or alcohol make the
person do that's bad. I thought I was going to meet a bunch of
celebrities, rock stars, actors and writers, but these were your
next-door neighbors.''
 &HT;    Co-starring with Bullock is the British actor Dominic West as
her boyfriend, and Viggo Mortensen, Azura Skye, Michael O'Malley,
Steve Buscemi, Marianne Jean-Baptiste and Diane Ladd as fellow
patients at the clinic. But in a sense, she says, her real co-stars
were the real-life recovering people she met in Tucson, with whom
she shared tough talking-therapy sessions which required her to
reveal her own personal weaknesses and insecurities.
 &HT;    Many of the patients, she admits, were not happy about the idea
of sharing their secrets with a movie star.
 &HT;    ``I promised them anonymity, of course,'' the actress says,
``but still a lot of them made it clear they didn't want me there.
One person just left.''
 &HT;    Those who stayed learned that even the best-adjusted Hollywood
star can have her share of problems.
 &HT;    ``One of the other women said, `I thought you were one of those
happy, smiling people that nothing bad ever happens to. But now I
see you have as many insecurities as we do,''' Bullock recalls.
 &HT;    It's true, she says. In her own way, she's been as badly off as
her character in ``28 Days.''
 &HT;    ``I've never had drug or drink problems,'' she says, ``but I
will say that, not long ago, my emotional vices were far more
paralyzing. Yes, I'm optimistic and joyful, but I'm also very, very
afraid and insecure.''
 &HT;    That's hard to believe of the woman who inherited Mary
Pickford's nickname ``America's Sweetheart'' after such hit films
as ``Speed'' (l994), ``While You Were Sleeping'' (l995) and ``Hope
Floats'' (1998).
 &HT;    But since coming to Virginia from Germany at age 13 _ her mother
is a German opera singer, her father a voice coach who went to work
for the Pentagon _ Bullock says she has been plagued by
insecurities which, before and even after her success, left her
wracked with self-doubt and low self-esteem.
 &HT;    ``It began in junior high school, when I was 13,'' she recalls.
``I had just come from Germany, and I sounded different and I
dressed differently and I was just reaching puberty. It was a
difficult hormonal time to begin with, but because I was the
outsider the other kids picked on me and humiliated me. I got my
butt kicked a lot of the time, and often came home from school
crying.''
 &HT;    The result, she says, was that it took her a long time to grow
up.
 &HT;    ``I'm beginning to peak now,'' she says, ``while many of my
contemporaries peaked at high school.''
 &HT;    Today, she adds, she's finally got her act together, realizing
that there's more to life than being a $12 million-a-picture movie
star.
 &HT;    ``I've never felt better than I do today,'' Bullock says. ``I
think it's because I like my mind better these days. I feel as if
I've unscrewed my head and washed out my brain. I've also gotten
rid of a lot of my manic behavior _ I don't find it necessary
anymore to be talking and moving all the time. I'm a much quieter
person.''
 &HT;    The turnaround began four years ago, she says, when she left
Hollywood for a home of her own in Texas. She renovated a stone
cottage on a 22-acre site in the woods outside Austin, which now
comes complete with a pool, a lake, a screening room, a gym,
crystal chandeliers from Paris and a huge sleigh bed.
 &HT;    ``I never had a fun childhood,'' the actress says, ``but my new
liberation is giving me the kind of blissfulness and carefreeness I
never experienced before. I find it easier to let go of things I
thought I had to do before.''
 &HT;    For too long, she adds, she was a chronic pleaser, worrying
about other people and neglecting her own interests.
 &HT;    ``I was spending too much time on everybody else's causes and
not enough on mine,'' Bullock says. ``I discovered I needed to stay
home more, to have a home. This place has given me a place of
emotional refuge.''
 &HT;    It has also led to a new boyfriend, Bob Schneider, a musician
based in Texas.
 &HT;    ``I didn't have a life outside of acting,'' she says cheerfully.
``Now I have one.''
 &HT;    In fact, the actress says, she even finds herself thinking of
having children.
 &HT;    ``I know I will have a child,'' she says. ``I will probably have
several. But I won't get pregnant just because I feel my biological
time clock is running out _ I will only have a child with a man I'm
truly in love with.''
 &HT;    Bullock's next film will be ``Miss Congeniality,'' in which she
plays a tough FBI agent assigned to infiltrate a beauty contest to
investigate charges of bribery. Michael Caine plays the senior
agent who teaches her the ropes, including how to walk in a more
feminine fashion.
 &HT;    ``It's an `Educating Rita' type of movie,'' she explains with a
laugh. ``For the film I'm allowing myself not to be a lady, and
it's very liberating.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter and columnist.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``28 Days,'' consult the Sony
Pictures Web site at www.spe.sony.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Hollywood Stars
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
