<HEADER>
A9047 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      04-06 1119
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALONG THE ROAD TO RICHES, OR PERHAPS IT'S A DETOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE ROAD TO EL DORADO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With the voices of Kevin Kline, Kenneth Branagh, Rosie Perez &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Eric Bibo Bergeron and Don Paul &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 89 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Zero surprises lie along a sprightly animated path to riches and
reconciliation in 16th-century Mexico. Winners in a shady game of
craps, two rollicking lads, Tulio and Miguel, come into possession
of an average-looking treasure map pointing toward El Dorado, city
of gold. A chase or two later they are shipboard prisoners of a
typically rapacious conquistador sailing off to plunder the New
World.
</P>
<P>
   After routine sea perils, the boys and a white horse named
Altivo wash up on a jungle-fringed beach. Deep in the forest lie
shimmering pyramidal structures, wheelbarrows full of goblets and
plates and whatever glittering encrustations one might expect in a
place like El Dorado.
</P>
<P>
   Here the two young men make standard figureheads in the
leadership struggle between the high priest Tzekel-Kan, an adherent
of human sacrifice, and the kindly tribal chief.
</P>
<P>
   As interlopers, Tulio and Miguel have a problem often
encountered by movie visitors from the north: the white-god
syndrome or, as Miguel puts it, ``If they say I'm a God, that's
what I am.'' Obliged to prove it by summoning a cataclysmic
happening, he gets help from a volcano in the middle distance.
</P>
<P>
   But Tulio and Miguel have their own conflict to resolve. Tulio
is more inclined to take the goblets and run. The more spiritual
Miguel comes out against human sacrifice, mingles with the people
and takes to his godly duties. So who is going? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: Tzekel-Kan threatens to toss sacrifices off a cliff,
and it is made clear that El Doradoans aren't gentle with those
needing punishment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Tulio has off-screen relations with Chel, a native girl. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-6: The film makes formulaic, good-looking fare for the
littlest ones, though the smallest might dive for cover in mildly
scary situations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 7-10: For messages, there are the folly of greed and the
value of friendship, but age 10 is the outer edge for this film. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SKULLS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Jackson, Paul Walker, Craig T. Nelson, Leslie Bibb, Hill
Harper &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Rob Cohen &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 100 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The halls are vaulted and heavily timbered, the students
graduated at last from the high school movie. Now they attend an
unnamed Ivy League institution (Yale) and are initiates in the
Skulls, Hollywood's idea of a campus secret society (modeled after
Skull and Bones at Yale) that produces presidents, moguls and the
cream of the legal establishment.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the goings-on here, that's a little hard to imagine,
or maybe it isn't. Having bought the society's code of honor when
they were students decades ago, powerful old Skulls preside over
gothic initiation rites administered to this year's elite young
designates.
</P>
<P>
   Running the show is Litten Mandrake (Nelson), on his way to a
Supreme Court appointment and every Skull's model of rectitude.
This year his son, Caleb (Walker), a troubled golden boy, will
enter the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Make that the vise. In return for lifelong wealth and power, the
Skulls demand allegiance above all else. In the beginning that is
acceptable to Luke McNamara (Jackson), a working-class boy who
exudes enough top-drawer potential to earn a bid to join the
society.
</P>
<P>
   After ponderous proclamations at the initiation ceremony,
forearms are branded and huge gold watches passed out to cover the
scars. Later there will be hot convertibles for everybody and an
extra $20,000 popping up in checking accounts.
</P>
<P>
   But soon the Skulls' presumption of infallibility begins to
bother Luke, and it positively nauseates his old friend Will
(Beckford), a student journalist who is investigating the
organization. Suddenly we are in an all-out action film, with hit
men in speeding sport utility vehicles and a couple of killings.
Now a marked man, Luke and his plucky girlfriend (Bibb), an Exeter
girl, are running for their lives. Have they reported this to the
dean's office? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: A student has some help getting his neck broken in a
so-called accident. This being the Ivy League, the goons are in
suits and button-down shirts, but they still shoot and drive to
kill. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: Sexual activities are alluded to but nothing transpires. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Yes, within PG-13 limits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10: Not many parents will regard this as the most
worthwhile movie experience. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-13: Jackson (``Dawson's Creek''), Walker (``Varsity
Blues'') and others will exert a pull, as will the college scene.
Parental guidelines will vary here, but there is no great harm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: Some teen-agers will think it silly. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHATEVER IT TAKES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shane West, Marla Sokoloff, Jodi Lyn O'Keefe, James Franco &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by David Raynr &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 92 minutes &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pygmalion having gotten a good kicking around as underpinning
for the high school movie, it is now time for ``Cyrano de
Bergerac.'' When there's no possibility of a makeover, one goes
with someone else as a spokesman, or so it occurs to Ryan (West)
and Chris (Franco). A gentle accordion player, Ryan needs Chris'
help to snag Ashley (O'Keefe), the school's reigning female
attraction. Chris, a top roue (and Ashley's cousin), will oblige if
the sensitive and expressive Ryan will put the right words in
Chris' mouth to impress the very down-to-earth Maggie (Sokoloff).
</P>
<P>
   Since Ryan and Maggie are next-door neighbors and true soul
mates, it doesn't take an advice columnist to figure out where all
this is headed. Before that eventuality, however, Ryan nimbly darts
around throwing out enough verbal epiphanies to win Maggie for
Chris. That's distressing to Ryan, of course, and there is the
additional problem of what to do with Ashley, who has responded
passionately according to Chris' recommendation: Treat her like
dirt. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE: None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX: A gentle, sensitive person herself, Maggie exhibits a
surprising knowledge of how to lash a guy (Chris) to the bedposts
and oil him down good and proper. But she's only doing this to tell
him off. There is no sex then or at any other time, only some
suggestive talk. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY: Some. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDER AGE 10: Obviously inappropriate from several standpoints. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 11-14: Of all the screen teen-agers around, these are as
purely teen-age as any. Whatever that implies, it makes for
harmless viewing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 14 AND UP: The film is too juvenile for older teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1714EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9048 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER07-COX     04-06 2047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Veep sweepstakes off and running
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore's search for a Democratic running mate will be led by
former Secretary of State Warren Christopher, The Associated Press
reports. Christopher also led the task force that helped
then-Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton select Gore as his 1992 vice
presidential running mate. Christopher also helped Clinton pick his
first Cabinet, which included himself as secretary of state. Gore's
staff planned to announce the move shortly, the AP said. Advisers
to George W. Bush say he'll soon put his search committee in place.
</P>
<P>
   AND HE'S PROBABLY AT THE TOP OF THE LIST
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore was at the Palm Beach, Fla., home of attorney Bob
Montgomery Thursday night for a $10,000-a-person dinner. Today,
Gore travels to to the Broward County home of Rep. Peter Deutsch,
where he will attend a $5,000-a-person lunch with about 85 people.
The more than $1 million expected to be raised from the two events
is going to the Democratic National Committee. That ``soft money''
money will be used to help elect Democratic candidates. One of
those, of course, is Gore.
</P>
<P>
   OPENING THE PLATFORM TO ALL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is expected to talk today about the Democratic Party
platform and a plan to allow people to send suggestions about
changing the party platform over the Internet. The Democratic
National Committee has formed a partnership with SpeakOut.com, a
Web site that helps people find out about issues and contact their
elected officials. The Democrats plan to use SpeakOut.com to allow
people to read the party platform and make comments.
</P>
<P>
   SORRY, PAT, IT'LL BE LONG BEACH
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party leaders overwhelmingly rejected Pat Buchanan's bid
Thursday to move the party's nominating convention from Long Beach,
Calif., to Nashville. The issue arose last month after party
Chairman Pat Choate and the Buchanan camp became concerned that the
Long Beach Convention and Entertainment Center had also booked a
big religious conference the same week. Bay Buchanan, Pat
Buchanan's sister and campaign manager, said last week that the
campaign preferred Nashville for logistical reasons as well as its
``middle America'' image. But California is home to 9 million
registered independents and 11 percent of the party's delegates,
said convention Chairman Gerry Moan.
</P>
<P>
   BIG PUSH IN BIG ENCHILADA
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is popular in California, the state's economy
is golden, and Al Gore is leading in the polls. Should George W.
Bush even bother? Bush, in an interview with the Los Angeles Times,
``insists'' that ``he plans to to compete all-out'' there.
Thursday, Bush started his 12th California trip, the first since
the state's primary, and, according to CNN, the state's Republicans
are thrilled. The Bush campaign says he will continue to go to
California because the state is winnable. Even California Secretary
of State Bill Jones, who had defected from the Bush campaign to
support John McCain, is now back with Bush for a race he thinks is
winnable.
</P>
<P>
   DAY OF THE MEDIA JACKAL
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura has some clear targets in line for
his next book _ primarily ``media jackals'' and spineless
politicians. It will be called ``Do I Stand Alone? Going to the Mat
Against Political Pawns and Media Jackals,'' his publisher said
Thursday. The book is due out in September, Ann Harris, spokeswoman
for the Pocket Books division of Simon &AMP; Schuster, told the Reuters
news agency. The pro wrestler-turned-politician published a
best-selling autobiography last year titled ``I Ain't Got Time to
Bleed.''
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S ALWAYS A BETTER WAY
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Americans are unhappy with the way presidential
nominees are chosen, even though they say they're generally
satisfied with the candidates this year, says a poll released
Thursday. The most popular alternative to the current system would
be a national primary with all states holding their contests on the
same day, preferably in May or June. That option was chosen by 56
percent in the poll by the Vanishing Voter Project, while the
current system was preferred by 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OPEN MINDED OPENING TO HISPANICS
</P>
<P>
   Going after the traditionally Democratic Hispanic vote,
Republicans are airing a Spanish-language TV ad in California that
asks voters to at least consider the GOP. ``This year I plan to
keep an open mind and vote for the best person, and that includes
Republicans,'' a Christina Bustos from Los Angeles says in the ad,
which is also airing in English. The GOP is spending $125,000 to
test the ad in the Fresno, Calif., area and plans to take it
national if it proves effective. The ad will run enough times in
Fresno for the average TV viewer to see it 12 times.
</P>
<P>
   RICKY DON'T LOSE THAT NUMBER
</P>
<P>
   Even though New York Gov. George Pataki wants him out of the
Senate race, Republican Rep. Rick Lazio insisted in an interview
with Hearst News Service that he's the best one to run against
Hillary Rodham Clinton. Lazio said Pataki's disapproval would
``disincline me'' from challenging Rudy Giuliani, but he continued
to insist that the controversial mayor was dragging down the GOP
with him. Lazio said Giuliani's handling of fatal police shootings
in New York City is evidence of a political tin ear that's driving
his poll numbers down.
</P>
<P>
   BUT THAT OTHER 10 PERCENT IS POWERFUL
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore presented himself to Maryland supporters as a candidate
able to reach across party lines, claiming rank-and-file
Republicans agreed with him on ``90 percent of the issues.'' Megan
Jones, deputy press secretary at the Democratic National Committee,
said the money raised at the $25,000-a-couple dinner at a private
home _ an estimated $600,000 _ will go to the party ``for electing
Democrats at all levels.'' Gore's own campaign finance troubles
were on the minds of a few protesters who chanted ``No more Gore''
as the candidate alighted from his helicopter in Annapolis.
</P>
<P>
   AND TO SHOW YOUR LATEST DANCE STEP
</P>
<P>
   Onetime newspaper reporter Al Gore hasn't held a news conference
in more than six weeks, and George W. Bush's campaign is starting
to track the days. They're suggesting Gore is hiding from questions
about fund raising and other controversial matters. The Republican
National Committee _ with the Bush camp's blessing _ launched the
``Al Gore News Conference Watch'' on Wednesday. Opening count: 46
days without one, dating to Feb. 19 in Springfield, Mass. Bush
spokesman Ari Fleischer, while conceding that Gore regularly grants
one-on-ones, said those are easier to control. ``News conferences
are a way to see how fast you are on your feet.''
</P>
<P>
   IN FLORIDA, IT'S ALL ABOUT ELIAN
</P>
<P>
   National Democratic Party chief Joseph Andrew cited a
fund-raising appeal by Florida Republicans to accuse them of using
the custody battle over 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to raise campaign
money. Andrew released an intercepted GOP fund-raising letter in
February that condemned the Clinton administration's handling of
the case. The letter, signed by Cuban-born lawyer Al Cardenas,
appealed for donations to serve as a ``powerful force against the
Democrats and the liberals who act cowardly before the intimidating
tactics, the hysterical speeches and the criminal lies of Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONAL, AT NO EXTRA COST
</P>
<P>
   Pat Buchanan says the reason he's running for president is to
give voters a new option. ``Unless I ran as the Reform Party
candidate, Americans would not have a real choice,'' he said in
Kansas City. Areas where he said he differs with the major
candidates: Free trade, immigration and the World Trade
Organization, which he says the United States should never have
joined. China _ no normal trade status until it ``stops persecuting
Christians'' and drops threats against the United States and
Taiwan. Bosnia and Kosovo _ bring American troops home. ``I think
it's time we defended the borders of our own country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   BAUER SHOULD HAVE A CLEAR FIELD IN '04
</P>
<P>
   After two disastrous White House bids, inheritance-advantaged
Steve Forbes has decided against trying a third time. Appearing at
the Russian Tea Room in Manhattan for the launching of his new
coffee-table book, ``Faberge: the Forbes Collection,'' Forbes said,
``Twice is enough. I'll be lobbing grenades and rolling editorial
bombs from another vantage point on the sidelines. I won't be doing
it again.''
</P>
<P>
   BE MORE LIKE MCCAIN
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is well liked by swing voters who could be decisive
in the battle for control of the House, according to a Republican
survey obtained by The Associated Press. The survey indicates he's
favored _ more than Al Gore and George W. Bush _ by voters who
describe themselves as uncommitted in hypothetical congressional
matchups. The finding emerged from a poll conducted for SAFE, an
organization associated with Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, to help
assure continued GOP control of the House in the fall elections.
House Republicans already were moving eagerly to enlist McCain's
aid in key districts around the country.
</P>
<P>
   THE INCREDIBLE SHRINKING CANDIDATE
</P>
<P>
   Consumer activist Ralph Nader, in Iowa to push his presidential
bid as a Green Party candidate, scoffed at suggestions his campaign
merely drains liberal votes from Democrats. He said that shrinking
either major party is ``exactly what we want.'' He pointed to
studies of the 1996 election when he was on the ballot in
California, and said he drew almost as many Republican voters as
Democrats. ``Our two parties are basically one corporate party
wearing two heads and different makeup,'' Nader said. ``There is a
difference between Tweedledum and Tweedledee, but not that much.''
</P>
<P>
   MARRIED, WITH BALLOTS
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore and George W. Bush are competing heavily for the votes
of white, married mothers, an enormous and critical group that is
emerging as one potential key to the 2000 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaigns and pollsters have targeted these mothers, and
they could deliver a win to either candidate. A new poll (2.9
percent margin of error) released by EMILY's List, an organization
that supports abortion-rights candidates, showed that although Gore
has a slight lead among women overall and has been gaining in
recent months, Bush is ahead among white, married moms by 47
percent to 39 percent. In 1996 and 1992, white married moms voted
for President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   HAMMERING ON EDUCATION
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore stepped up his attacks on George W. Bush's education and
tax policies before an enthusiastic labor union crowd in
Washington. Gore charged that Bush's education proposals would not
lower class sizes or help rebuild schools that are falling apart
and that his planned tax cuts would create spending deficits. He
called Bush's tax plan a ``reckless scheme that (would) devastate
public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY SIDING WITH THE TEACHERS
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton said that plans to sharply cut back
summer school in New York City represented a ``terrible admission
of failure'' on the part of Rudy Giuliani. She attacked the mayor's
push for teacher merit pay, the issue that led to the breakdown in
talks with the United Federation of Teachers, calling it a crude
and ineffective way to improve public education. Giuliani has
argued for individual teacher stipends based on student test scores
as an incentive for teachers to work this summer and as his opening
move in negotiations with the union, whose contract expires in
November.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY FUND-RAISER SIGNING ON WITH GORE
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of his continuing efforts to unite the Democratic
Party, Al Gore plans to announce on Monday the endorsements of a
group of Bill Bradley's Florida supporters. The group will be lead,
according to The New York Times, by Stephen Pajcic, a Jacksonville
lawyer who raised money for Bradley. Pajcic said he also expects to
help raise money for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by Ernie Freda from Cox staff and wire reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
