<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      04-06 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Wild' Is Right: Planning `Party' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Talk about crunch time. With openings just days away, two major
Broadway productions were doing whatever they could to squeeze
extra time into packed schedules and energy out of exhausted
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure was perhaps most intense at the Virginia Theater on
the set of the Public Theater's ``Wild Party,'' where the director
and co-writer, George C. Wolfe, was juggling everything from the
health of his cast to the length of his show. The musical opens on
Thursday; critics are due on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the sniffle front, at least, things seemed to be settling
down after several weeks of uneasiness about the voice of Mandy
Patinkin, who plays the ruffian Burrs. Patinkin, who missed a
stretch of previews in late March because of a vocal inflammation,
has been back in the cast since March 28 but missed last Saturday's
matinee. Toni Collette, the female lead, also missed several
performances this week because of a cold.
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, the show's pace has been a principal concern,
and an area of major improvement. Early previews ran about 2 hours
20 minutes without an intermission, causing some audience members
to gripe. Wolfe has trimmed the running time to less than two
hours, but there is still no intermission, on artistic grounds: the
musical is about a party, after all, and few parties have
intermissions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wolfe was continuing to shape the musical and canceled
Wednesday's matinee to allow for more rehearsal time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wild Party,'' based on a 1928 poem by Joseph Moncure
March, is being watched by Broadway for many reasons, not the least
of which is that it will be the season's last new musical. It is
also bound to be compared to another musical based on that poem
that opened in February at Manhattan Theater Club.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there is Wolfe's own personal mystique, a mix of talent
and ego that is simultaneously admired and reviled by many on
Broadway. A hit with ``The Wild Party'' is likely to be seen as
redemption for Wolfe's most recent Broadway outing, last year's
unsuccessful revival of ``On the Town.'' A pan would be seen as
another costly uptown misfire for him.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe said he was too busy to dwell on such things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always said that doing a musical is like landing at
Normandy,'' he said Thursday, sounding upbeat. ``It's also akin to
childbirth. You don't remember the pain, otherwise you'd never do
it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Another big-time director, Julie Taymor, has been trying to
steal some extra hours, for ``The Green Bird,'' which is to open on
April 18 at the Cort Theater. Wednesday's matinee was canceled
along with the matinee on April 12 to open the way for more
rehearsals for this tech-heavy show. Practice would seem to be
prudent; on Sunday, the actors Reg E. Cathey and Edward Hibbert
were beaned with a piece of scenery during a set change, and the
performance was canceled. Cathey was taken to the emergency room
for precautionary X-rays. He was fine. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `The Dead' Ends &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was, from the beginning, an unorthodox musical: a quiet,
meditative piece taken from the writings of perhaps the headiest
scribe of all, James Joyce. Its existence, let alone survival, on
Broadway seemed miraculous to Disney-weary critics, who almost
unanimously sang its praises.
</P>
<P>
   But with a crush of new shows opening, it seemed increasingly
unlikely to producers that such an unassuming little piece could
survive. So on April 16, ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' starring
Christopher Walken, will close its four-month run at the Belasco.
</P>
<P>
   The show had broken even or better most weeks, but sales have
slipped lately. The prospect of Tony nominations next month in
several categories was apparently not enough to save the show.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Mosher, one of its producers, said the show would
continue in several arenas and a national tour is planned. ``It's
strange to close a thing like this having gotten the amount of
support we did,'' he said. ``But this one's going to have a longer
life.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lavin on Broadway &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's official: Charles Busch's comedy ``The Tale of the
Allergist's Wife,'' playing to full houses at Manhattan Theater
Club's snug Stage 2, will transfer to Broadway in the fall. No
specific dates are set, but Linda Lavin is signed to return to her
role as Majorie Taub, a depressed intellectual dilettante whose
life is upended by the arrival of a long-lost friend played by
Michele Lee, who is also expected to return for the Broadway run.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Roberts is to rejoin the cast as the allergist.
Performances will probably begin in mid-October for a early
November opening. Lynne Meadow directs. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Naked? No! &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First things first: Kathleen Turner has no plans to get naked in
``Tallulah.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she's opposed to the idea, she says; ``it just doesn't
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is of acute importance, of course, because of
Turner's current project, a stage version of ``The Graduate'' that
opened in London on Wednesday night. Therein, Turner disrobes as
Mrs. Robinson, briefly and in dim light, an event that has been
front-page tabloid news on both sides of the Atlantic and has set
off a more-sex-please-we're-British fervor at the box office.
</P>
<P>
   The limited run has sold out faster than you can say,
``Plastics.'' And the reviews? Although the show's notices were
mixed, Turner is said to do quite well, and looks, in the words of
The Daily Telegraph, ``very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   All of which, of course, has given rise to dreams of an American
run. But first, Turner is committed to ``Tallulah,'' a one-woman
play about the salty stage and screen star Tallulah Bankhead, a
woman who, Turner said, ``acts to excess in many ways, both good
and bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The show, in development since 1997, is now scheduled for a
11-city United States tour beginning in October in Minneapolis,
followed by a Broadway landing next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Previous productions of ``Tallulah'' had been criticized for a
weak second act, but Turner says that has been fixed. The play
follows an evening in Bankhead's life in 1947, complete with
remembrance, bons mots and a few visits to the bar.
</P>
<P>
   But no nudity, eh?
</P>
<P>
   ``I try never,'' Turner said with a purr, ``to repeat myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
