<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9058 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CYPRIOT-ART-MET-ART-2     04-06 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYPRIOT-ART-MET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART REVIEW: A CARNIVAL OF STYLES FROM ANCIENT CYPRUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT1 and 2 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The island of Cyprus, off the coast of Asia Minor,
was the Times Square stop on that great mass transit system known
as the ancient Mediterranean world. It was the node where dozens of
cultures, European and Asian, crossed paths in an exchange of
people, goods and ideas before moving on to other destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Some whiff of that hustle and bustle comes across in the new
Cypriot galleries at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The 600
objects range from colossal sculptures to poppy-shaped juglets
(thought to have been used for exporting opium). And everywhere
there are traces of the various superpowers _ Egypt, Greece,
Assyria, Rome _ that established a presence and contributed to the
sweetly unglamorous carnival of styles known as Cypriot art.
</P>
<P>
   The new galleries, which conclude a second phase in the Met's
renovation of its Greek and Roman collection, also embody a
different, more modern history, one related to a notable, even
notorious episode in the early days of the museum itself.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Cypriot holdings were amassed more than a century
ago by Luigi Palma di Cesnola (1832-1904), a wily and ambitious
diplomatic-corps type who emigrated from Italy to America to make a
career. He signed up as a Union cavalryman in the Civil War, spent
10 months in a Confederate prison and talked his way into a job as
U.S. consul to Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Like other foreign self-seekers on the island, he took up
archaeology as an exotic hobby. It wasn't long before he began to
see himself as being in competition with Heinrich Schliemann, who
was then making headlines with his discoveries at Troy and Mycenae.
But where Schliemann at least preserved some small sense of context
in his work, Cesnola unearthed things willy-nilly and shipped them
off.
</P>
<P>
   And worse, in his drive to produce newsworthy ``discoveries,''
he was not above grafting stray sculptural parts, sometimes from
different eras, or massaging the data about where certain pieces
were found. He announced a trove he called the ``Kourion
Treasure,'' which may never have existed as such.
</P>
<P>
   All this behavior was more or less routine in an era when
museums and archaeology alike were in their infancy and
opportunistic deals were going on all around. (In certain ways
things aren't all that different today, though the cushioning
etiquette around such activities has grown subtler.)
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, Cesnola's public relations campaign worked. He
got the attention he was after. His collection was bought by public
subscription for the brand new Metropolitan Museum and provided a
starry-eyed institution with its first claim to international
prominence. No European museum had comparable Cypriot material.
</P>
<P>
   To cap his story, the museum hired Cesnola as its first
director, though his archaeological methods eventually came under
fire, as did the price he had demanded for his collection. After
his death, the Met auctioned off the bulk of his objects, leaving a
core of 6,000 from which the new Cypriot installation has been
culled by the curators Carlos A. Picon, Joan R. Mertens,
Christopher S. Lightfoot, Elizabeth J. Milleker and Sean Hemingway,
all of the Met, and Vassos Karageorghis, former director of
antiquities in Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Cesnola did wrong, he left an amazing legacy. Many of
his choicest acquisitions are now back on view as a group for the
first time in half a century, and they give a panoramic summary
view of ancient Cypriot culture.
</P>
<P>
   Cyprus was famous in the ancient world as a source of copper.
But most of its early art is of humble stuff like terra cotta and
soft, grainy local stone. The opening gallery, in fact, which
begins with Neolithic work from around 7000 B.C., has a
pots-and-pans atmosphere, like a prehistoric housewares department.
</P>
<P>
   Here one finds dozens of clay vessels, some workaday, others
whimsical. One vase imitates the shape of a leather purse; another
takes the form of a mischievous antlered creature about the size of
a Beanie Baby. There is also, in a nice curatorial touch, a chorus
line of goddess figurines with birdlike faces.
</P>
<P>
   They have an unfussed-over, improvised look, as if made for fun
as much as for use. (Cyprus, the Greeks decided, was the birthplace
of Aphrodite.)
</P>
<P>
   By the late Bronze Age (circa 1600-circa 1000 B.C.), many
cultures had converged on the island. Refugees from the devastated
city of Mycenae brought Greek traditions. Phoenician settlers
introduced Egyptian styles. Cypriot artists, particularly potters,
recast these influences into lively designs, as one sees in a
barrel-shaped jug, circa 750 B.C., with the graphically crisp image
of a sea bird, perhaps a cormorant, with stylized lotuses.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
