<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9061 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CYPRIOT-ART-MET-ART-2     04-06 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYPRIOT-ART-MET-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: stylized lotuses.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The outstanding art of the Archaic period (750-480 B.C.) was
figurative stone sculpture. Because Cyprus has no marble, limestone
was the material of choice. And the use of this common, elemental
rock formed from calcified sea shells (marble itself is an
ultrarefined version of it) contributes to the earthy, almost
archetypically provincial charm and variety of much Cypriot art.
</P>
<P>
   A figure of a youth from the sixth century B.C., for example, is
clearly modeled on the Greek kouros. But instead of a ramrod
posture and a buffed nude physique, he has slope-shoulders and
wears unsexy Fruit of the Loom briefs with big rosettes.
</P>
<P>
   His fetchingly nerdy attire is part of a circus of personal
styles. Some figures come with Egyptian kilts and wigs, or curly
Near Eastern beards. Others flash a particularly jolly version of
the V-shaped ``archaic smile'' of Greek sculpture. Finally, one
might locate a real Cypriot ``look'' in a colossal male head
displaying a conical homeboy cap and a large, inelegant, decidedly
un-Grecian nose.
</P>
<P>
   Metalwork also yields transcultural motifs, as in a set of
silver, gold and bronze bowls incised or embossed with narrative
scenes and decorative patterns that draw on sources from Homeric
Greece to Assyria and strings them together with an audacious ``who
cares?'' abandon. These bowls were part of Cesnola's ``Kourion
Treasure,'' and he was right to consider them among his signal
discoveries.
</P>
<P>
   But if one were to choose a single highlight from the
installation, it would almost certainly be a polychrome limestone
sarcophagus carved around 475 B.C. Monumental in scale and
spectacularly well preserved (recent cleaning has brought out the
color), it shows the vivacious Cypriot International style in its
classical phase. Most of the surface is carved in high relief. On
one short end there are figures of the scowling Egyptian deity Bes;
on the other, the Phoenician goddess Astarte appears, nude, on
tiptoe, touching her breasts. The two long sides depict a stately
but leisurely procession. The men are dressed in Cypriot conical
caps; one holds a Persian-style parasol over his chariot mate.
Greek sphinxes crouch, alert as terriers, on the lid.
</P>
<P>
   It is thought that the sarcophagus was carved at a time when
Cyprus was trying to obtain an alliance with Greece against Persia.
And there's no question that the island saw itself as being, in
some essential way, within the Greek cultural sphere.
</P>
<P>
   This is apparent in two fifth-century B.C. full-length figures:
one has a clean-shaven idealized face, the other a beard and a
Danny Kaye profile, but they share a classical poise. (Both are
also suspected of being Cesnola ``restorations.'' The head of the
first figure and the feet of the second may not be original to the
bodies.)
</P>
<P>
   But political jockeying was old news on an island where
overlords came and went. Persian domination ended during the rule
of Alexander the Great. Then the Romans arrived. With typical
strength and resilience, Cyprus managed to absorb these incursions
and keep to its own track, which was always both inside and outside
the greater imperial loops.
</P>
<P>
   In comparison with textbook Mediterranean and Aegean art,
Cypriot work doesn't stack up as a peak, seamless, resolved
achievement. It has neither the abstract ``modernist'' allure of
Cycladic sculpture nor the consolingly idealistic beauty attributed
to sculpture from classical Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in interesting ways the work in the Cesnola collection,
which would be easy to overlook in a greatest-hits museum tour,
makes a perfect fit, both for New York and for the Met. This vast
gathering of provincial material provided the archaeological
foundation for what was, at least at the start, a feisty provincial
institution. And the spirit of the art somehow suits the city
itself.
</P>
<P>
   In place of purity, Cypriot work offers a welter of
style-sampling invention, with results that are by turns madcap and
flat-footed, virtuosic and funky. Its very impurity is what makes
it attractive to us. And in fact, if one were trying to come up
with an Ancient World analogy for art being produced in New York
right now, the Met's Cypriot galleries would be a good place to
start.
</P>
<P>
   The New Cypriot Galleries are on permanent view at the
Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
