<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ About five miles outside the nation's capital,
this normally quiet suburban neighborhood where signs on front
lawns tout ``Vote for Pat Baptiste, Democrat for County Council,''
became an international center of attention Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The buzz of news reporters mixed with the chirping of birds to
form a surreal picture outside the tan brick house where Juan
Miguel Gonzalez arrived Thursday morning to wait out the fate of
his son, 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez emerged from the house, which belongs Cuban
Interests Section head Fernando Remirez, once with a Cuban official
to walk around the front yard. He made no statement.
</P>
<P>
   The houses along the middle of Millwood Road, in Montgomery
County, are like any other, with yellow and blue pansies in flower
boxes and white picket fences.
</P>
<P>
   Nannies push strollers with snoozing infants and toddlers, while
joggers run up and down the block stopping occasionally to take a
rest.
</P>
<P>
   Into that ``American Beauty'' scene Thursday morning, before the
dew lifted from the freshly cut lawns, came the orange and white
barriers, police road blocks and nearly two dozen television
satellite trucks to interrupt the morning's normally tranquil
routine.
</P>
<P>
   While trying to walk his dog Sasha, 25-year resident Marcel
Hodak had to duck under the yellow police tape, and side-step the
TV cable lines that covered the sidewalk outside his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like it, this is something that only
happens on TV,'' Hodak said, mugging for one of the dozens of
camera crews filming the neighborhood. ``Now, I'm on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   Other neighbors, like Alex and Marion Kelly have lived on
Millwood for more than a decade, were more eager to see what was
going on, standing shoulder-to-shoulder with more than 50
television cameras, photographers and reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We routinely walk around the neighborhood, and all this
commotion is just providing some excitement for our walk,'' said
Marion Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a possible magnet for protests _ or so the police
believe. The area cordoned off by police for protestors was empty
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But Catholic University graduate student Camila Ruiz _ among
several Cuban-American students from colleges and universities in
the Washington area that showed up _ stood behind the barriers
telling reporters that she supported Gonzalez in efforts to get his
son back and hoped he was able to express himself free from the
pressures of Cuban President Fidel Castro's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro has made us (Cuban-Americans) out to be some sort of
mafia,'' said Ruiz, a Cuban-American from Santa Clara, Calif. ``We
only want Juan Gonzalez to come out by himself and to be able to
speak his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   In this politically moderate enclave, the sentiment appears to
lean toward the the father being reunited with his son,
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not up to us to pass judgement on where a kid should
live,'' said Aileen Cohen, taking her 16-month-old son, Gabriel,
out for his morning stroll.
</P>
<P>
   Then it hit her. Pointing toward the media horde, Cohen added,
``It never occurred to me that this could go on for weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
