<HEADER>
A9071 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SOUTHPAW-FILM-REVIEW-     04-06 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHPAW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOUTHPAW': AN IRISH BOXER KEEPS HIS CHIN (AND HIS DREAMS) UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By DAVE KEHR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The inspirational Irish documentary ``Southpaw,'' directed by
Liam McGrath, is a profile of Francis Barrett, known as Frankie, a
clean-cut, soft-spoken young man with a winning smile and a mean
left hand. He dreams of becoming an Olympic boxer in the
light-welterweight category, and by the looks of things he has some
talent.
</P>
<P>
   But Barrett also has a disadvantage: he and his family are
Travelers, members of an old and well-defined itinerant caste. Once
Travelers lived in handsome, horse-drawn wagons, spoke their own
language and grandly roamed the countryside. (See Mike Newell's
1992 film on the subject, ``Into the West.'') These days, though,
they more often occupy dingy house trailers anchored in abandoned
lots on the edge of the city, living without utilities or social
respect.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing, of course, has long been a favorite fictional device for
moving characters up the social ladder; it's a sport that takes
what is assumed to be a lower-class talent _ a skill in physical
violence _ and ennobles it with an upper-class income. But Barrett
is no Jim Corbett or Mike Tyson, living out the American dream by
battling his way from poverty to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   His ambitions are modest, and his means appear to be even more
so, as he is shown going about his training in a sadly
underequipped amateur boxing club.
</P>
<P>
   The self-appointed head of the storefront institution, grandly
called the Galway Olympic Club, is Chick Gillen, a middle-aged
barber and expansive local character who doubles as Barrett's
coach. Because Gillen seems to have no actual boxing experience,
his coaching is largely limited to platitudes on the order of
``Keep your chin up.'' His main function in McGrath's film is to
keep the blarney level high enough to please fans of ``Waking Ned
Devine'' and the many other made-for-export Irish comedies that
have lately filled American screens.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise ``Southpaw'' mostly dodges the whimsy and sentiment
that define the Uber-Irish genre, though McGrath can't resist
inserting the occasional reaction shot of a lovable codger pulling
on his pint. (Helpfully, the thickest accents have been subtitled.)
McGrath's filmmaking is plain and straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   What the film resembles more than anything else is one of the
miniature human-interest profiles that the networks have taken to
inserting between the events in their Olympic coverage, little
films designed to increase viewer interest by increasing their
identification with the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sign of the anger that Barrett must have known as a
member of a persecuted minority. Instead, the film portrays him as
all smiles and optimism, boyish and unthreatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southpaw'' begins with Barrett's journey to the Olympic Games
in Atlanta, where his greatest moment comes in being allowed to
carry the Irish flag in the opening ceremonies, and concludes with
him training for the Olympics scheduled for September in Sydney,
Australia. You can only wish him luck.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SOUTHPAW'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Liam McGrath; director of photography, Cian de
Buitlear; edited by James Dalton; music by Dario Marianelli;
produced by Robert Walpole and Paddy Breathnach; released by the
Shooting Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Francis Barrett, Kathleen McDonagh and Chick Gillen.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 77 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   This film is not rated. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
