<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, April 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rapid changes will continue across the eastern half of the
nation Friday as powerful jet stream winds propel storms from the
Plains to the Northeast in less than two days. New England will be
cool and dry with fading sunshine. The Middle Atlantic region
should start dull, but become brighter and warmer, though not as
windy as Thursday. The Southeast will stay warm.
</P>
<P>
   A swath of light to moderate snow will fall from the eastern
Dakotas to Wisconsin as a storm strengthens over Missouri. Showers
and a few thunderstorms will dampen the middle Mississippi and Ohio
valleys. A cold rain is expected near the southern Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Warm air over the southern Plains will yield to advancing cold
from the north. Snow showers will end in the eastern Rockies. High
pressure building into the Northwest will promote dry, milder
weather.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: STRONG WINDS
</P>
<P>
   A fast-moving storm brought wind gusts between 45 mph and 60 mph
from the Middle West to the Northeast on Wednesday and Thursday.
Steady strong winds can be traced to great horizontal pressure
contrasts in the atmosphere. Extreme gusts usually result when
turbulent air motions, akin to eddies in a rushing stream, mix
winds from thousands of feet above the ground toward the earth's
surface. Winds at altitudes of 10,000 to 20,000 feet, unencumbered
by frictional forces, commonly reach 50 to 100 knots providing the
impetus for gusty ground-level winds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
