<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THERE'S MORE TO LIFE THAN EARNING A LIVING, AUTHOR SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you think you don't have time to read this review, maybe you
should make time.
</P>
<P>
   It could change your life.
</P>
<P>
   That's the argument made by Beth Sawi, a top executive of
Charles Schwab &AMP; Co. who recently wrote a book on how time
management shapes lives.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Coming Up For Air: How to Build a Balanced Life in a
Workaholic World'' (Hyperion, 253 pages, $23.95), Sawi makes the
case that individuals need not work endless hours to succeed.
Rather, success is achieved by establishing priorities and
allocating time to attain those objectives, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people spend time thinking about what is important to
them other than their work,'' Sawi writes. ``This is such a great
loss. Identifying your priorities is like paging through a
scrapbook of fondly remembered times. Each image brings a smile of
recognition and a sense of belonging. Once you reacquaint yourself
with your core values, you'll always have your guiding stars, even
during the darkest times.''
</P>
<P>
   Those lifestyle goals are different for each individual.
Although some people remain focused on the monetary and prestige
rewards that come from work, others strive to spend more time with
their family, focus on charity efforts or simply walk the dog.
</P>
<P>
   Success, the author contends, depends on setting and adhering to
time-management priorities rather than trying to live up to others'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Sawi writes, for instance, of the single mother who decided to
curtail socializing at work so that she could get her assignments
done during traditional working hours. She decided that getting
work done and getting home to her family is more important to her
than catching up on the lives of co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of focusing exclusively on accomplishments that others
acclaim, you need to concentrate on what will make you a happier
and more authentic person,'' Sawi writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Focusing on these inner fundamental goals will force you to
reorder your priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's message is akin to many delivered in self-help
books. The difference is that Sawi peppers her writing with
real-life anecdotes and easy-to-understand exercises that simplify
the task of applying time-management lessons in everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   Sawi brings a realistic outlook to time-management issues and
provides helpful suggestions for dealing with workplace issues,
ranging from demanding bosses to peer pressure to work extended
hours.
</P>
<P>
   She offers readers a useful map for navigating the road away
from workaholism and into a more balanced, rewarding life. Although
some individuals may sacrifice career goals to attain such a life,
the pursuit of balance can empower some to embrace a lifestyle that
makes them more effective at work and happier on a personal basis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too often, people assume that adding balance to their lives
will lessen their work contributions,'' Sawi writes. ``But
frequently, respecting all that's important to you rejuvenates your
entire being, generating more energy both for your work life and
your home life.''
</P>
<P>
   Sawi urges readers to establish priorities by imagining what
perspective they will have on life at 80. By analyzing what will be
most important over the long term, people can become more focused
on how to better use the individual moments of each day in reaching
their life goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of your life,'' Sawi writes, ``you won't be
remembered for how you earned your money, but for how you spent
your time.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Jacket blurbs
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``Play Like a Man Win Like a Woman: What Men Know About Success
That Women Need to Learn''
</P>
<P>
   By Gail Evans
</P>
<P>
   Broadway Books, $35.95
</P>
<P>
   Women still feel ``baffled, angry, lost, trapped, stuck and
overwhelmed'' in the workplace _ even executives of large
corporations, says Gail Evans, an executive vice president at CNN.
But Evans says some of the glass ceiling is self-created, and she
offers ideas for climbing the corporate ladder that men have always
known. The book is a refreshing and honest look at the business
world, offering a positive approach to women's careers rather than
a rehashing of how bad the obstacles are.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good News About Careers: How You'll Be Working in the Next
Decade''
</P>
<P>
   By Barbara Moses
</P>
<P>
   Jossey-Bass, $25
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cult of Busyness,'' ``TempWorld'' and ``Laptops at the
Beach'' are some of the chapter topics in this insightful look.
Capitalizing on the good parts of the business world _ flexible,
fulfilling, independent careers _ while sidestepping the bad parts
_ layoffs, cutbacks, longer days, fewer vacations _ is part of what
business guru and speaker Barbara Moses preaches in her latest
book.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``J.K. Lasser's Taxes Made Easy for Your Home-Based Business:
The Ultimate Tax Handbook for Self-Employed Professionals,
Consultants and Freelancers''
</P>
<P>
   By Gary W. Carter
</P>
<P>
   IDG Books, $15.95
</P>
<P>
   Congress changed the tax code to make home-based office
deduction rules less restrictive than at any time since 1976,
writes Gary Carter, who has spent more than 20 years as a revenue
auditor, tax practitioner and faculty member at the University of
Minnesota. Before you finish (or start) your 1999 taxes, it might
be worth perusing this book, which focuses squarely on the home
office and what can and cannot be deducted.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
