<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0284 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9076 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      04-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MIGHT HAVE MISSED IT. MOVING IN THE ``E''
AND ``L'' CATEGORIES) 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule reviews of new books: &QL; 
 &UR; ``THE OPERATOR'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Tom King (Random House, $25.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This biography of producer and record industry mogul David
Geffen is interesting on two levels. First, there is King's
portrayal of Geffen as a man of ratlike cunning, a dealmaker with a
voracious lust for money and power. Even more interesting is
Geffen's involvement with celebrities of the past three decades,
whose professional and personal lives he directed with both
tyrannical self-interest and the concern of a doting den mother. He
was engaged to Cher until she dumped him for Gregg Allman. ``I want
all my presents back!'' Geffen shouted and then went into a deep
depression, which he conquered by attending ``est'' seminars and
facing up to his homosexuality. He was arrested for buying drugs
for David Crosby, and he comforted Yoko Ono at the hospital after
John Lennon died. His friends included Joni Mitchell, Bob Dylan and
Jackson Browne, and he was once rumored to have secretly married
Keanu Reeves. He even counseled the president and first lady after
the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke _ there is no end to his
territory. King is a reporter for the ``Wall Street Journal.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``SEEING MARY PLAIN'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Frances Kiernan (Norton, $35) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There's a word for Mary McCarthy, and it isn't pretty. Today,
more than a decade after her death, she is known for her
controversial meanspiritedness far more than for her fiction or
criticism. As Kiernan says in this honest and oddly affectionate
biography, if she had never written a single word, we would still
want to know about her. She was outspoken, sarcastic, beautiful and
intimidating, a writer who held strong views on many subjects and
did not suffer fools gladly. She is most widely known, perhaps, for
the remark she made about Lillian Hellman in a televised interview
with Dick Cavett in 1980: ``Every word she writes,'' McCarthy said,
`is a lie, including `and' and `the.' '' Hellman sued but McCarthy
refused to back down, even when the lawsuit threatened to bankrupt
her. Kiernan, a former editor at the ``New Yorker,'' conducted
interviews with McCarthy's friends, former lovers, colleagues and
acquaintances, some of whom reveal lingering distaste for a woman
who was capable, as Clifton Fadiman once wrote, ``of dissecting
people and leaving a nasty mess on the table.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``JOAN OF ARC'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Mary Gordon (Viking, $19.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The delight of the ``Penguin Lives'' series of short biographies
is the pairing of author and subject, and the brevity of the
effort. These ``biographies'' rarely reach 200 pages, and because
of it they take on a decidedly personal tone _ we sense the
writer's pleasure in what he or she is writing about, and it
becomes part of our pleasure as well. Past or planned installments
include Larry McMurtry writing on Crazy Horse, Jonathan Spence on
Mao Tse-tung, Edna O'Brien on James Joyce, Bobbie Ann Mason on
Elvis Presley, and Roy Blount Jr. on Robert E. Lee. Now we have
Mary Gordon, whose writing is steeped in her experience of Roman
Catholicism, pondering the shocking and much-manipulated story of
the French girl-soldier who at 17 left her village to lead an army
and two years later died in agony. Joan was not perfect, and Gordon
addresses her sins as well as her sainthood. She is not so much the
patroness of France, writes Gordon, as ``the patroness of the vivid
life, prized not for military victories but for the gift of
passionate action taken against ridiculous odds, for the grace of
holding nothing back.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``CYBILL DISOBEDIENCE'' &QL; 
 &UR; By Cybill Shepherd (HarperCollins, $26) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd has written a memoir about her sex life, and she has
dedicated it to her parents. OK, we exaggerate _ only half of it is
about her sex life (including a romp with Elvis Presley _ you'll
want to read that part). Maybe she's hoping her parents won't
notice. Still, once you get past its unfortunate title and
prologue, this is an engaging book. Shepherd is smart. She says she
reads Henry James and Joseph Conrad and is inspired by Goethe. She
might be making that up, but she uses the word ``flummoxed''
correctly and with a straight face, and we think she means it. She
is funny and self-deprecating in much the same way that Candice
Bergen was in her better-than-average memoir, ``Knock Wood.''
Shepherd talks about her family, career, marriages and lovers,
leading men (Robert De Niro, Bruce Willis), aging and its
ramifications for an actress (``It's OK for Robert Mitchum to get
up early in the morning and look like Robert Mitchum, but it was
not OK for me to wake up in the morning and look like Robert
Mitchum . . .''). She's not Goethe, but there's more to her than
meets the eye.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1756EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0285 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
