<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9079 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-D     04-06 1068
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-DISTRICT-MAP-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTTRESSING AN OLD CITY   WITH NEW ARTISTIC GIRDERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Michigan, South Korea, Japan) (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(An information box appears at end of story.) By PAULA DEITZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Like the fantasy pleasure dome of Xanadu, the term
movie palace conjures up a magical image: a romantic time when the
film world was bursting with technological advances, complemented
by live entertainment. In downtown Pittsburgh alone, there were
once eight such extravaganzas within a few blocks' radius, and in
their heyday, the 1920s and '30s, people flocked to the cinema and
to vaudeville acts in an atmosphere that dripped with gilded
plaster and crystal chandeliers.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward 30 years. Pittsburgh was in a financial slump. But
the Pittsburgh Symphony, thriving nonetheless, required a new home
beyond the Syria Mosque. Gordon Bunshaft of Skidmore, Owings &AMP;
Merrill was hired to design a new home, but, to the city's eventual
good fortune, the effort stalled. Then in 1967 Henry John Heinz II,
who had recently retired as chairman of the H.J. Heinz Co., made a
momentous visit to the once-lavish Loews Penn Theater, accompanied
by the president of the symphony. With a grant from the Howard
Heinz Endowment, the symphony bought the property and the rest is
legend: Heinz Hall for the Performing Arts opened in 1971, with its
plush three-story-high domed lobby and an arcade of Corinthian
columns with gilded capitals.
</P>
<P>
   This became the turning point and the gold standard for an
imaginative urban renaissance based on Heinz's theory that the arts
lead the way to economic development. Rather than destroying an old
neighborhood to build a congested performing arts center,
Pittsburgh opted to create a performing arts district: many of its
cultural institutions are housed in the restored regal surroundings
of its surviving movie palaces, scattered through a 14-square-block
area that had been a red-light district. It is now called the
Pittsburgh Cultural District and is overseen by the 16-year-old
Pittsburgh Cultural Trust.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent rain-slicked Saturday night at curtain time, the
streets were bustling with theatergoers coming from parking lots
dispersed sensibly through the area or from neighborhood
restaurants. The thrill is enhanced by the great marquee of the
Benedum Center for the Performing Arts, the former Stanley Theater,
where the chaser lights are miraculously intact.
</P>
<P>
   On a side facade of the center, flashing lights still announce
``Stanley's Photoplays.'' Inside, the immense barrel-vaulted lobby
and performance hall have been restored to their original palette
of Etruscan colors, with decorative plasterwork burnished with
aluminum-foil gilt. Relighted with chandeliers, the entire space
glows with a festive air that inspires the audience to dress up for
the occasion, on this evening a performance of Massenet's opera
``Werther'' by the Pittsburgh Opera under the artistic direction of
Tito Capobianco.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural district here, which includes new public squares
and parkland on the Allegheny River, reflects a general mood in
Pittsburgh. As the largest inland port in America (the Delta Queen
calls about twice a year), it is a true early gateway to the West.
At the majestic confluence of the Allegheny, Monongahela and Ohio
Rivers, the city encompasses 40 miles of riverfront and more than
2,000 bridges, representing almost every style of engineering.
</P>
<P>
   While this city boasts old, established cultural institutions
like the Carnegie Museums of Art and Natural History and obligatory
skyscrapers like the 1984 neo-Gothic spires in reflective glass for
PPG Place by Philip Johnson and John Burgee, there is a new
vivacity that accompanies the emerging biomedical and computer
science industries spurred by the research units of its major
universities.
</P>
<P>
   NEW LIFE FOR OLD BUILDINGS
</P>
<P>
   One could say that Pittsburgh's fighting spirit in the face of
its loss of the steel industry comes from its namesake, William
Pitt, who as prime minister of Britain in the 1750s gave the
colonists the wherewithal to do proper battle against the French.
After his forces captured Fort Duquesne in 1758, one of Gen. John
Forbes' last acts was to name their conquest after Pitt, whose
spirit had made them, he said, ``masters of the place.'' This story
is inscribed on a plaque outside H.H. Richardson's celebrated
Allegheny County Courthouse and Jail, two massive turreted piles of
rusticated stone linked across a city street by a Bridge of Sighs
providing secure passage for prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   Though Pittsburgh's steel industry died, none of its other
important elements did; the city survived, unlike others caught up
in a similar economic downturn. To prove it, three department
stores thrive downtown. But there is a lot of vacant real estate,
and the trick has been to renovate and incorporate the empty
structures there into the texture of urban life in a ``practical,
affordable, useful and beautiful'' way, said Teresa Heinz, who has
carried on the family's philanthropic interests since the death of
her husband Sen. John Heinz III.
</P>
<P>
   The cultural trust's consortium, for example, includes two other
theaters in addition to Heinz Hall and the Benedum, with at least
1,200 events a year taking place in the district. The opera shares
the Benedum with the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, the Civic Light
Opera, visiting dance companies and touring Broadway shows. Now in
its 61st season, the opera company has been staging four operas a
year. Next year, a fifth, ``Therese Raquin,'' by the American
composer Tobias Picker and commissioned in a joint production with
the Dallas and Montreal Operas, will be staged at the nearby
1,329-seat Byham Theater, a renovated vaudeville hall the size of
smaller European opera houses.
</P>
<P>
   For a site down the street from the Benedum, on the footprint of
a vaudeville house demolished after sustaining damage in a 1936
flood, the cultural trust commissioned Michael Graves to design the
only new theater in the district. The O'Reilly Theater, now the
home of the Pittsburgh Public Theater, has all the charm of Graves'
own drawings of squat classical stone pavilions in rustic
landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9080 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      04-06 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBSITE &AMP; MAGAZNIE REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 (RESENDING. MOVING IN THE ``E'' AND ``L`` CATEGORIES) 
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Muller takes a quick look at some current magazine issues
and a website:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; WEBSITE &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; movie-list.com &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tired of watching those trailers while people are still finding
their seats and rattling their popcorn bags? Then Movie-List is for
you. The site features theatrical trailers for all the hot movies
coming out this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The site offers trailers and so-called teasers (shorter versions
of the trailer) in Quicktime. They are available in high-resolution
or low-resolution formats, depending on the speed of your
connection and how long you want to wait for a download.
</P>
<P>
   Recent additions to the site include trailers for ``The Hollow
Man,''which features Kevin Bacon as a not-so-nice invisible man,
``The Filth and the Fury,'' a documentary about the British punk
band the Sex Pistols, and ``Dinosaur,'' a Disney film about
prehistoric creatures.
</P>
<P>
   There also is ``Battlefield Earth,'' a new John Travolta flick
based on an L. Ron Hubbard book and ``Gone in Sixty Seconds,'' the
remake of the '70s movie of the same name, starring Nicolas Cage
and Angelina Jolie.
</P>
<P>
   So, grab some popcorn and soda, and take a gander. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAGAZINE REVIEWS &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``BOY'S LIFE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Published by the Boy Scouts of America, this magazine is fun for
Scouts and non-Scouts alike, offering easy-to-read articles,
age-appropriate advice, cartoons and puzzles. My favorite how-to
this month is a primer on replacing a bike tire inner tube. Such
knowledge is especially useful in Arizona, land of the angry thorn.
There is also a Q-and-A on camping, which counsels Scouts to pack
out their garbage and avoid scratching their names on trees or
burning down the forest. Keep in mind that the magazine does have
some religious overtones. This issue includes a short story on
Scouts visiting churches, chapels and temples to learn more about
other religions. With baseball season starting, there also is a
reprint of the Thayer poem, ``Casey at the Bat,'' and a short story
on a light-hitting Little Leaguer who saves the day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ESQUIRE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Answers the burning question, ``What's on Heather Graham's
Mind?'' which, after reading the story, we have to conclude is
``not much.'' Still in all, it's an amusing if self-conscious story
about the winsome actress, whose appearance in ``Austin Powers 2:
The Spy Who Shagged Me'' has vaulted her to instant cult status,
especially among the denizens of the Internet. It's funny to learn
that she first appeared in film as a dead junkie in ``Drugstore
Cowboy.'' In that inexplicable ``Esquire''-think, the magazine
lists the 18 most important golf courses in America, and then tops
the list with the Old Course at St. Andrews, SCOTLAND. They're
trying to be cute here, but it just doesn't work. There is also a
piece on golfer John Daly, he of the thunderous swing and alcohol
problem. Again, we have to wade through all the self-serving pap
about the writer palling around with Daly until we get to the real
story: Daly is losing but happy. I wonder if that is his final
answer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``OUTSIDE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the camping issue, but hey, isn't every issue? Worth
picking up for story on the ``Surf Chimp,'' a long-armed surfer
dude named Jeff Hakman who dominated his sport, founded a
multimillion-dollar surfwear company and then lost it all to a
heroin addiction _ twice. Now he's competing on the surfing
equivalent of a senior's tour. Who knew? There also is an
interesting piece on those so-called adventure races where people
scale cliffs and navigate rapids so they break their arms and legs
and are shown weeping on the Discovery Channel. Article wonders
aloud if it's all just becoming too commercial. Surely not. Being
on TV has nothing to do with making money, does it? Also includes a
nicely done piece that suggests leaving behind all your techno
stuff _ phones, pagers, Iridium satellites _ when you head out to
the wilderness, so you can forget about civilization. What was that
again? &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``REASON'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The libertarian magazine goes after _ surprise! _ Bill Clinton
this month, noting that he's survived scandals not because he's
innocent, but because he's an expert at managing the news and
handling internal crises. Interesting piece offers ``a five-step
program for surviving endless scandal,'' noting that Clinton
doesn't feed scandals and uses his office to distract the public,
mostly by having the military blow something up.
</P>
<P>
   There's another piece on agronomist extraordinaire Norman
Borlaug, the father of the so-called Green Revolution and a Nobel
Peace Prize winner, who is still teaching at Texas A&AMP;M at age 86.
Borlaug is widely credited with increasing wheat yields in the late
1960s and saving millions from starvation in Mexico, India and
Pakistan. There also is a good piece noting that this year's
presidential election will be less about issues than any election,
ever. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
