<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-D     04-06 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-DISTRICT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PITTSBURGH: rustic landscapes.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A BRIGHT NIGHT LIFE
</P>
<P>
   There is also a whiff of Alvar Aalto in the side view of red
brick and blue tile walls. The theater's porous semicircular glass
facade is an inviting presence on the streetscape, making it an
easy stop for buying tickets. At night the second-level foyer,
capped by a barrel-vaulted roof, offers lively views of theater
crowds. Behind the foyer's long bar hangs one of Graves' murals of
pavilions in the Italian countryside. Playing at the O'Reilly on a
recent weekend was Conor McPherson's peripatetic play ``The Weir,''
with some Irish cast members who lent authenticity to the mystery.
The O'Reilly's thrust stage, though close to the audience, is
always an island of space unto itself, thus maintaining the
theatrical illusion.
</P>
<P>
   The show does not stop in Pittsburgh when the performances end,
as a walk in the neighborhood proves. At the central intersection
of Penn Avenue and Seventh Street, two squares face each other with
public sculptures that exert an especially powerful force after
dark. In a fresh interpretation of the civic fountain, the artist
Louise Bourgeois fashioned for the Agnes R. Katz Plaza a
25-foot-high spiral mountain of bronze with water rushing down its
troughs, which are illuminated fiber-optically with a bluish light.
</P>
<P>
   Seen against the lights of Pittsburgh's skyline, this glowing
mound has become a strong nocturnal image, particularly in its park
setting of clipped linden trees designed by Dan Kiley. By
collaborating, the sculptor and landscape architect have produced a
winning urban plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, the Russian artist Aleksandr Brodsky
constructed a different sort of mound, a vast pyramid of Beaux-Arts
terra-cotta ornaments from buildings that had been demolished in
the district. Long buried in a ditch, the pieces were retrieved and
inventoried before the artist carefully piled the cornices, columns
and rosettes into a kind of memorial to vanished architecture.
``Palazzo Nudo'' he calls it.
</P>
<P>
   Set behind a chain-link fence and a cage of metal scaffolding
with hanging industrial lights, this elegant scrap pile glistens
with new life on a rainy night. While many buildings were
destroyed, the streets are now lined with others that were once
marred by false fronts but now reveal their original facades
intact.
</P>
<P>
   Night lighting is a major ingredient in animating the cultural
district and is the basis of another ingenious collaboration, this
one between the artist-designer Robert Wilson and the architect
Richard Gluckman. In addition to the main avenues and cross
streets, the district is filled with back alleys and blank walls
next to empty lots where buildings once stood. Lightwalls for
beauty and safety were the answer rather than ugly,
income-producing billboards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Light will be an object and light will be space'' and ``light
will be static and light will be dynamic'' are how the team
describes a phenomenon that it expects will enliven the
neighborhood and in time, no doubt, cities everywhere. While
reviving the movie palaces builds on the past, the lightwalls will
be one of the trust's contributions to the future.
</P>
<P>
   The first one has been installed on a wall next to a parking lot
near the Benedum: an eerie wash of pale light with a horizontal
band of the faintest mauve moving slowly down the side of the
building. It transforms a drab wall into a theater set.
</P>
<P>
   True to form, people are beginning to move into this loft
district (along with one dry cleaner and a florist), and its seven
art galleries are a draw during the day, as are the exhibitions at
the trust's own Wood Street Galleries. The adjoining neighborhood,
called the Strip and home to Pittsburgh's wholesale food markets,
is a lively mecca of shops and restaurants, particularly on
Saturday mornings. Embracing the Rivers
</P>
<P>
   As part of its city planning, the cultural trust has also taken
the lead in opening up the adjacent riverfront area: Pittsburgh,
like many major river cities, had turned its back on its greatest
resource. A 1911 Olmsted Brothers' concept for a narrow collar of
parks along the Allegheny and Monongahela that joined where the two
met the Ohio at Point State Park had lain dormant until it served
as inspiration to another team commissioned by the trust, this time
to design Allegheny Riverfront Park at the edge of the cultural
district.
</P>
<P>
   A match was made between the landscape artist Michael Van
Valkenburgh and the artist Ann Hamilton, who represented the United
States last year at the Venice Biennale. A 4,000-foot-long,
35-foot-wide esplanade runs under the three Sister Bridges; it is
approached from the street by long ramps with an undulating bronze
handrail that connotes thin tree trunks with the smoothness of an
arm. High vine screens for Virginia creeper create a vertical wall
from the street above, where a second phase of the park will
eventually be planted with plane trees.
</P>
<P>
   To border the promenade below Van Valkenburgh has planted a
crush of native flood plain trees and rugged plants, expecting that
they will not all survive the periodic flooding and winter ice
floes, and interspersed among them boulders collected from the area
that give the plantings a Japanese quality and also serve as
convenient seating.
</P>
<P>
   When the cement was poured for the walkway along the water,
Hamilton devised a method to lay dry reeds into the wet cement so
that the promenade has a bulrush pattern that looks like a fossil
from the original shoreline. The rough surface favors walkers over
in-line skaters and skateboarders.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Allegheny on Pittsburgh's North Side, art is also a
catalyst for redevelopment, as is already well known from the
museum dedicated to Pittsburgh's native son Andy Warhol. The story
of the sculptor Barbara Luderowski and the founding of the Mattress
Factory in 1977 as a museum of installation art on Sampsonia Way is
another example of the city's cultural draw.
</P>
<P>
   When Luderowski stopped in Pittsburgh in the early 1970s, on the
way to show her work in New York, she was driven around the narrow
streets of town houses on the North Side and fell in love with the
neighborhood. She never got to New York. Instead she returned to
Michigan, sold her house there and moved to Pittsburgh, where she
eventually purchased the old mattress factory that is an ideal
architectural framework for conveying the imaginary worlds of
installation art. Later she bought a house and a storefront on
adjoining streets to expand the museum.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
