A9088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-D     04-06 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PITTSBURGH-CULTURAL-DISTRICT-3rdTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
 
PITTSBURGH: the museum.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A COMMUNITY OF ARTISTS
</P>
<P>
   The title of the current exhibition, ``Installations by Asian
Artists in Residence,'' also explains the museum's method, devised
by Luderowski as the artistic director and by the curator, Michael
Olijnyk. The artists live at the Mattress Factory as a community
while they build their art.
</P>
<P>
   In constructing his phantom house of cast paraffin wax that
fills an entire gallery, the Japanese artist Goro Hirata based his
design on a traditional Japanese house with shoji screens. Because
the material is translucent, natural light from the windows glows
through the walls and shifts during the day. Sora Kim, from Seoul,
South Korea, filled another gallery with a product called
D-Gravitzer, along with its marketing campaign that proves how
being relieved of gravity allows the user to clean ceilings and
difficult corners.
</P>
<P>
   Two of James Turrell's disquieting room installations dealing
with the perception of light are among the permanent exhibits, as
is Jene Highstein's ``Bed-Sitting Rooms for Artist in Residence,''
in which two beds slide back and forth between slots in the wall,
depending on the number of occupants in a room.
</P>
<P>
   Even the garden, designed by Winifred Lutz, is installation art.
In a brilliant stroke, she created an archaeological site by
excavating the basement of a burned-out factory next door,
uncovering several levels reached by steps with twisted iron
handrails. Planted with grasses and wildflowers, it could be a site
from ancient Rome.
</P>
<P>
   CULTURAL FOOTINGS
</P>
