<SLUG> BC-MYSELF-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ME, MYSELF I': OH, ITS A WONDERFUL LIFE! (IF ONLY SHE'D REALIZE
IT) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Which of us hasn't wondered in a moment of despondency whether
life might have turned out for the better had a former relationship
not been discarded? That big what-if drives ``Me Myself I,'' a
sugarcoated romantic comedy that is just clever enough to make you
wish it were three times as smart and only a third as sweet.
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist of this grown-up fairy tale, Pamela Drury
(Rachel Griffiths), is a lonely single woman approaching 40 who
gets a magical opportunity to sample the life she might have lived
had she married the man she retrospectively believes to have been
her Right. Except for one final plot twist, the movie is a
be-thankful-for-what-you've-got fable that aspires to be the single
person's answer to ``It's a Wonderful Life.'' Despite some witty
sequences, the slickly plotted fantasy has only a small fraction of
the conviction of Frank Capra's weeping-for-joy classic.
</P>
<P>
   The early scenes find Pamela, who writes peppy articles for
women's magazines, moping about her apartment, shuffling through
snapshots of old boyfriends and pining for romance. One afternoon,
while researching an article, she meets a promising new dreamboat,
Ben Monroe (Sandy Winton), a sensitive hunk whose blazing blue eyes
make Pamela's heart go pitter-patter.
</P>
<P>
   Too shy to call him up for a date, Pamela finds his address in
the telephone book and hand-delivers a letter containing some of
her articles to his house in the middle of a roaring thunderstorm.
It turns out that Ben is at home. And in a moment of excruciating
self-torture Pamela, soaked to the skin, huddles under a window
like a bachelorette Stella Dallas to observe him and his
picture-perfect wife and their two children gazing dreamily out at
the rain. Little wonder that when Pamela returns home, she
seriously contemplates dropping her hair dryer into the bubble bath
and electrocuting herself.
</P>
<P>
   But like a fairy godmother, a perfect clone of Pamela
materializes just in time to shepherd her into the life she might
have lived had she married Robert Dickson (David Roberts), the true
love she left 13 years earlier. The spirit or clone, or whatever it
is, then abruptly vanishes, abandoning Pamela to an existence she
believes to be a dream until she bangs her head against a wall and
discovers that it's terribly real.
</P>
<P>
   As the wife of Robert and the mother of three demanding children
_ henna-haired Stacey (Yael Stone), who is just entering puberty;
Douglas (Shaun Loseby), a feisty little skateboarder; and adorable
towheaded Rupert (Trent Sullivan), who still needs help going to
the bathroom _ Pamela copes absurdly well. (Rupert is the only one
in the family who senses a difference between the two Pamelas.)
Although she never liked children, Pamela swiftly adjusts to her
new life of dirty laundry and no spare time. As compensation she
has the good sex she aggressively rekindles in a relationship that
had gone romantically dry.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pamela still turns out hack pieces for a magazine
called Now Woman, her writing career has not progressed as far as
it did when she was single. Pamela also runs into Ben, who is
leading a parallel, alternate life. This time he is single and very
available.
</P>
<P>
   The feature film debut of Pip Karmel, an Australian filmmaker,
``Me Myself I'' is a technically polished piece of work that
maintains a steady and comfortable balance between fantasy and
realism. And Griffiths, as in many of her other roles, conveys
fine, high-strung intelligence beneath a slightly chilly exterior.
Roberts and Winton bring just the right romantic ardor to their
roles. But for its comic warmth, ``Me Myself I'' isn't much more
than a Cosmo girl's daydream, one in which an appreciative
fail-safe Prince Charming is conveniently posted at every junction.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ME MYSELF I'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Pip Karmel; director of photography,
Graeme Lind; edited by Denise Haratzis; music by Charlie Chan;
production designer, Murray Picknett; produced by Fabien Liron;
released by Sony Pictures Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Rachel Griffiths (Pamela), David Roberts (Robert), Sandy
Winton (Ben), Yael Stone (Stacey), Shaun Loseby (Douglas) and Trent
Sullivan (Rupert).
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 104 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me Myself I'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It has nudity and sexual situations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
