<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SPAIN-FAITH-EXHIBIT-A     04-06 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-FAITH-EXHIBIT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FESTIVITY AND FAITH,   SPAIN'S RELIGIOUS IMAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Spain, N.M., Neb.) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In most religions, devotional images are not
inanimate objects; they are responsive presences with feelings and
personalities. They console, reprimand, give directions and, for
believers, carry an emotional charge mingling awe with affection.
</P>
<P>
   This dynamic is the subject of an exhibition titled ``Images in
Procession: Testimonies to Spanish Faith'' at the American Bible
Society in Manhattan. The works include Baroque sculptures,
19th-century paintings from New Mexico and documentary photographs
of religious pageants taken in the 1920s in Spain, where the public
ceremonial display of religious art has a long and fervid history.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all the works on view are from the collection of the
Hispanic Society of America, one of the world's most comprehensive
repositories of Spanish and Latin American culture. They range from
a grief-drenched relief of the dead Christ surrounded by mourners,
carved by an unknown 16th-century Castillian sculptor, to a
sunshiney depiction of the Virgin of Guadalupe done around 1835 by
a New Mexican painter called the Quill Pen Master.
</P>
<P>
   The least familiar entries are the 55 photographs taken by Ruth
Anderson (1893-1983). Anderson was born in Nebraska and studied at
the Clarence White School for Photography in New York. After
receiving her degree, she took a job as photographer _ and later as
curator of costume _ with the Hispanic Society and made several
documentary trips to Spain during the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things that intrigued her, in part because they had
been little studied, were religious festivals and, specifically,
the elaborate street processions and performances involving
large-scale portable sculptures. Based on late medieval traditions,
they offered a vivid blend of Roman Catholic orthodoxy, civic pride
and edifying entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson kept a daily journal when she was in Spain, and
excerpts from it appear throughout the show, which has been
organized by Patrick Lenaghan and Ena Heller. Her words convey a
cool ethnologist's remove from what she was seeing, but also a
sense of engagement and wonder. These attitudes come through in her
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest are of Holy Week activities in northwest Spain. In
the provincial city of Zamora, Anderson photographed processions of
large floats, called pasos, bearing sculptural tableaus of scenes
from the Passion. Winding through the streets on Good Friday, they
were accompanied by penitents, members of local confraternities
dressed in face-concealing robes and high ked caps.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby town of Villalcampo, she recorded a dramatization,
performed on an outdoor stage hung with quilts and blankets, of
Jesus' final days. Local citizens play all the parts. A few years
later, in the village of La Alberca on the Feast of the Assumption,
she saw another pageant, in which the devil made a literally
explosive entry, followed by the Archangel Michael, portrayed by a
young girl wearing a white gown and wings.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson often photographed processions from a high window or
rooftop. This distance can give a sense of choreographic symmetry,
as in her shot of a formation of white-clad penitents with the
trains of their robes spread out behind them as if they were
brides. In many cases, though, it makes specific activity hard to
read and gives little for the eye to fasten on.
</P>
<P>
   She was at her best when she moved in close. Her stage-side
shots of the Villalcampo Passion play feel as direct and unaffected
as the performance itself. Her pictures of costumed children _
miniature pentitents looking shyly into the camera _ are wonderful.
Here, one feels, she connected most comfortably with the intensely
emotional events that were her subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Such intensity is all but impossible to distill in an
exhibition, and this one doesn't capture it. As Lenaghan relates in
his catalog, no Spanish processional figures of the kind seen in
Zamora are to be found in American collections; and the sound and
sights of the festivals themselves can only be experienced on the
spot.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, nothing Anderson depicts is really foreign to
New York, where religiously based processions of all kinds are
still common. One on 14th Street honors the Virgin of Guadalupe.
Another in East Harlem observes the day of the Three Kings with
colorful sculptures and costumes. And far downtown near Wall
Street, hundreds of people wend their way with candles on the night
of Good Friday to the tiny Greek Orthodox church of St. Nicholas,
dwarfed by the towers of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   There are many other such events annually in the city; perhaps
information on them will be available at a free public symposium
that is to take place Friday at the American Bible Society. Titled
``Religious Rituals in Europe and the Americas,'' it will address
the same interaction of faith and festivity that Anderson did in
her pictures, and may well do so with her combination of
objectivity and tenderness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1806EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
