<HEADLINE>
BOND PRICES DOWN AS INVESTORS RETURN TO THE STOCK MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bond prices declined Thursday as some investors took
advantage of rebounding stocks to shift back out of the
fixed-income market.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year bond declined 3/32, to 106 19/32, while
its yield, which moves in the opposite direction from the price,
rose to 5.79 percent from 5.78 percent on Wednesday. The two-year
note, whose yield has plunged recently as investors positioned
themselves away from volatile stocks, fell 5/32, to 100 7/32. Its
yield rose to 6.38 percent from 6.30 percent, still giving the
highest return among various Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   William McDonough, president of the New York Federal Reserve
Bank, said in a speech to the New York State Banker's Association
that inflation was all but dormant in the face of strong economic
growth but that the very prosperity that growth generates could
expose the economy to real risks. Traders said his comments had
little effect ahead of a key employment report due Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The nonfarm payroll data for March is expected to confirm that a
very tight labor market could reignite investor fears that the Fed
could become more aggressive still in raising short-term rates to
keep inflation under control.
</P>
<P>
   Economists polled by Reuters are forecasting that the March
payrolls number grew by 376,000 and that the hourly earnings
increased by 0.3 percent. The tightness in the labor market is
likely to be underscored by a decline in the unemployment rate to 4
percent, from 4.1 percent in February.
</P>
<P>
   Rick MacDonald, an economist with Standard &AMP; Poor's MMS, a
market research and analysis firm in San Francisco, thinks the
focus will be on wages and unemployment because the payroll number
will probably have two distortions for March: a lift from hiring
for government census workers and an extra week because of the leap
year. So the data for five weeks is condensed into a month normally
reporting four weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1808EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0298 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9100 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BLUE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE BLUE BEDSPREAD': FAMILY SECRETS OF A MOST TERRIBLE KIND 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With young writers like Arundhati Roy, Pankaj Mishra and Amit
Chaudhuri appearing on the scene in recent years, Indian fiction
seems assured of a bright present and a brilliant future. That
conviction gains force with ``The Blue Bedspread,'' a first novel
by Raj Kamal Jha, an editor at The Indian Express, India's largest
newspaper. Jha, who is in his mid-30s, has produced a spare,
mysterious and somber tale of erotic violence and illicit love that
stays in the mind long after the last page has been turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blue Bedspread'' begins on a sultry night in Calcutta,
which Jha describes in a way reminiscent of James Joyce's Dublin,
though Jha's Calcutta is viewed through a more lurid and sensualist
lens. It is a city that gives off a kind of luscious odor of decay;
it imparts the feeling of ``an ocean, wet and heavy'' whose every
sound and sight seems magnified. A man who does not give his name
(``It doesn't matter in this city of 12 million names'') receives a
call from the police telling him that his sister has died in
childbirth and that he must take care of her daughter for one
night, until she can be placed with the couple that will adopt her.
</P>
<P>
   The man, who is the principal narrator of ``The Blue
Bedspread,'' brings the infant home and settles her to sleep. He
then spends the night writing out the stories that he feels she
needs to know if she is ever to understand exactly who she is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I shall retell some stories,'' he tells her, ``the ones your
mother told me, even those that she told not in words, but in
gestures and glances. Like that of the black-and-yellow Boroline
Cream banners catching the wind on Durga Puja day; the dead pigeon,
its stain carried all across the city; the albino cockroach
hanging, upside down, from the bathroom drain.''
</P>
<P>
   Jha's tale takes form out of the jagged landscape of his
narrator's mind, each element of the larger story associated with a
different talisman, like the black and yellow advertising banner
for an antiseptic cream, Boroline, that he associates with an event
from his sister's terrible marriage. Slowly, the reader understands
the deeper purpose of this midnight chronicle. The man intends to
reveal the long-kept secrets of a Calcutta family that, with the
death of his sister, have become his exclusive possession.
</P>
<P>
   They are terrible, disquieting secrets. Jha's storyteller,
seated in his bare study, listening to a drip of water falling on
the red tiles of his bathroom, tells them as if he were pulling
open the heavy door of a crypt, allowing them to emerge _ one by
one, single file, shaking off the heavy dust of the past _ into the
light. As he does so, a picture of childhood affliction takes
shape. The boy stutters; he describes the way words ``grow and grow
until they fill up my lungs and refuse to come out''; he remembers
his sister beaten for an offense that he committed.
</P>
<P>
   At times, when the memories are too sharp, he imagines that he
is telling a story about somebody else, a boy who lies secretly on
the outside of a window and sees his mother beaten senseless by his
father. He tells of the same boy, now explicitly himself,
blackmailed by his father to force him to submit without
complaining to perverted desire. But the biggest secret has to do
with the blue bedspread on which his sister's baby is even now
sleeping in the other room. It is an object from his childhood full
of totemic power, the rectangular terrain on which he and the
baby's mother, seeking a place of safety and solace, played out a
``daily theater of pleasure and fear ... that carried us as if on a
wave from one night to the next.''
</P>
<P>
   As Jha's narrator explicates both the pleasure and the fear, he
imposes no artificial order on his memory but replicates it in its
disjointed reality, allowing it to perform its own juxtaposition of
thoughts, objects, sounds and smells. The boy, at the moment of his
worst terror, hears ``the sound of cars splashing the water in the
potholes outside'' and the ``minibus conductors shout their
destinations: Dum Dum, Howrah, Entally, Roxy Cinema.'' His
nocturnal storyteller notices the imprint of sweat that a woman's
elbow makes when she leans on a glass counter. He sees that two
dead cockroaches are trapped in the frame that holds his mother's
picture. He remembers the way his sister's tears fell onto her
mother-in-law's silk sari, and then disappeared as she ironed it.
</P>
<P>
   He captures in a few images his sister's horrible realization
that she hates her husband, and those images open into a terse
premonition of imprisonment: ``She watched his bare haunches, his
arms, his broad shoulders, the rise and fall of his chest. She kept
staring at the fan, trying to count the blades on her first night,
the beginning of a lifetime in a two-room flat where the sky
squeezes itself into narrow lanes to keep the buildings from
touching each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Jha's world is a cruel one in which all normal yearnings for
happiness are thwarted by poverty, or the dead hand of custom, or
the untrustworthiness of others. But what is really a dismal horror
story is told with a kind of Shubertian loveliness that transforms
it into an elegant, melancholy meditation on love and courage.
</P>
<P>
   Jha exhibits a remarkable honesty as a writer, and he is in
impressive command of a technique that creates a powerful
psychological realism out of a near phantasmagoric collage. His
final paragraphs manage artfully to recapitulate almost all of what
has preceded them, and to suggest the elements of a moral
redemption at the same time. In short, ``The Blue Bedspread'' is a
brilliant beginning for a writer whose voice already shows a
maturity well beyond his years.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `THE BLUE BEDSPREAD'
</P>
<P>
   By Raj Kamal Jha
</P>
<P>
   212 pages. Random House. $21.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
