<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9102 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RAMEAU-BAROQUE-MUSIC-     04-06 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMEAU-BAROQUE-MUSIC-4TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAYING COURT TO A WRY MASTER OF THE FRENCH BAROQUE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a Baroque beyond Bach? Yes, though you may be hard put
to find it this year, with performers and record companies tripping
over one another to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the
master's death.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are outcroppings of Vivaldi here, Handel there. Now
comes the turn of the fascinating figure Jean-Philippe Rameau
(1683-1764), the French composer and theorist who died 14 years
after Bach. (What wonders of Rameau revival might thus await
listeners in 2014, given what has emerged over the last two
decades?)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bach, Handel and Vivaldi, however much they may have
benefited from the modern early-music movement, Rameau was one of
the composers who needed it, or something like it, to make his way.
His music, unsurpassed in elegance and wit, can survive perhaps
anything but the ponderous weight to which it was long subjected.
When, that is, it was noticed at all.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Rameau will be represented modestly on Saturday
evening with one of his ``Pieces de Clavecin en Concerts'' in a
program by the Four Nations Ensemble and Music From China,
``Entertainment for Kings,'' at the 92nd Street Y. Then, on
Tuesday, he takes center stage with a new production of his opera
``Platee,'' directed by Mark Morris and presented by the New York
City Opera at the New York State Theater.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Performances of Rameau remain rare, and most listeners today
still know Rameau best through recordings. So the classical music
critics of The New York Times are listing their own favorite
recordings in hopes of encouraging listeners to wade farther into
this fascinating repertory.
</P>
<P>
   Be assured, however, that you will probably not go far wrong
exploring even beyond those choices, for most of the performers
involved with Rameau these days are committed, knowledgeable and
highly musical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES R. OESTREICH
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RAMEAU DISCOGRAPHY: TIMES CRITICS' PICKS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are some favorite Rameau recordings of the classical music
critics of The New York Times. CDs range in price from $5.97 to
$18.97 for one CD to $21.97 for a two-CD set and $36.97 for a
three-CD set.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BERNARD HOLLAND &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PIECES DE CLAVECIN,'' Books 1 and 2. Frederick Haas,
harpsichordist (Calliope CAL 9278). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PIECES DE CLAVECIN EN CONCERTS.'' Gustav Leonhardt,
harpsichordist; Frans Bruggen, flutist; Sigiswald Kuijken,
violinist; and Wieland Kuijken, violist da gamba (Teldec
9031-77618-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Philippe Rameau was 50 before he wrote his first opera, but
``Hippolyte et Aricie'' was, in 1733, a natural progression from
the remarkable harpsichord pieces of the 1720s and a natural
prelude to the ``Pieces de Clavecin en Concerts,'' which arrived
eight years later. Rameau's harpsichord music bristles with
provocative movement and illustrative titles. Here, the hen is
elevated to high art (``La Poule''); New World savages dance
violently (``Les Sauvages''); birds sing (``Le Rappel des
Oiseaux'').
</P>
<P>
   Rameau the man could be imperious and forbidding. (His final act
of music criticism was to cite a priest for singing off key at his
deathbed.) But this is music intended for theatrical display, even
when no theater is in sight. Its forwardness establishes the
fundamental equipoise of the French Baroque: Rameau, brilliant and
imposing; Couperin, wistful, private, tender, heartbreaking.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners interested in completeness may still be able to find
Trevor Pinnock's old CRD recordings in specialty shops. Novices
might prefer to dabble in a variety of performances, and there are
several places in which their fingers might profitably be dipped.
The shallowest waters are the first book of ``Pieces de Clavecin''
from 1706. The second book of ``Pieces de Clavecin'' in 1724 and
the ``Nouvelles Suites de Pieces de Clavecin'' four years later
represent a composer of solo music at his most inventive.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Pieces de Clavecin en Concerts,'' written during a
five-year interlude in Rameau's opera career, expand into chamber
music, with a flute and two strings as foils to the harpsichord.
Rameau claimed that with an emendation here and there, these five
three- and four-movement ``concerts'' could be reduced for keyboard
alone, but their value is as ensemble music.
</P>
<P>
   Frederick Haas plays the first two books on Calliope. The first
has all the energy and bright self-advertisement of a composer in
his early 20s. The disc also includes the 1724 Suites in E and D.
Although Pinnock's playing had a joy and precision that made his
offerings near irresistible, Haas is very good indeed.
</P>
<P>
   For the ``Pieces de Clavecin en Concerts,'' try the quartet of
Gustav Leonhardt, Frans Bruggen and Sigiswald and Wieland Kuijken.
Rameau's sense of high drama and high spirits survive in this
subtler and more involved format, and the playing of these four has
a style and dignity appropriate to an 18th-century home
entertainment of great originality.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTHONY TOMMASINI &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``LES BOREADES.'' Monteverdi Choir and English Baroque
Soloists, conducted by John Eliot Gardiner (Erato Musifrance
2292-45572-2; three CDs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ MOTETS. La Chapelle Royale, conducted by Philippe Herreweghe
(Harmonia Mundi France HMA 1901078). Le Concert Spirituel,
conducted by Herve Niquet (Virgin Veritas 5 61526 2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PLATEE'' AND ``DARDANUS'' SUITES. Philharmonia Baroque
Orchestra, conducted by Nicholas McGegan (Conifer 75605 51313). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``CASTOR ET POLLUX.'' Les Arts Florissants, conducted by
William Christie (Harmonia Mundi France HMA 901435; three CDs).
</P>
<P>
   The conductor William Christie, the director of the estimable
ensemble Les Arts Florissants, has won deserved praise for his
historically informed and scrupulously rendered performances of
Baroque operas and choral works, especially Rameau's. Still, I seem
to be among the minority who find his work, however impressive,
self-consciously authoritative.
</P>
<P>
   Other fine conductors have performed Rameau with, to my mind,
more spontaneity and grace: Sir John Eliot Gardiner, for one. In
1982 at the Festival of Aix-en-Provence in France, this superb
English conductor presented what was apparently the first complete
performance of ``Les Boreades,'' a tragedie lyrique. Sir John
worked from an edition he had prepared. His beguiling recording
with the Monteverdi Choir and the English Baroque Soloists was
released in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Rameau wrote his last opera, ``Les Boreades,'' incredibly, at
81. Rehearsals for the work's premiere at the Paris Opera had begun
when Rameau died; the production was inexplicably canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Far from approaching this work with the trepidation of old age,
Rameau seems to have felt that he could finally write an opera the
way he wanted to, not as the current style dictated. The
semi-mythological story concerns Queen Alphisa of ancient Bactria,
who is permitted to marry only a descendant of Boreas the terrible
god of the north wind, but who, alas, loves a mortal. Though the
plot is explained in detail in the program book, no libretto is
provided (evidently because of legal hassles over rights). In
truth, closely following Rameau's librettos is not exactly crucial
to appreciating his operas, for the composer, famously tolerant of
weak texts, was never a skilled dramatist like his exacting
predecessor Lully.
</P>
<P>
   But the score is wondrous, a mosaic of infectious dances,
glorious arias, ebullient choruses, elegant recitative and vivid
pictorial music that evokes nature, thunder and icy winds. More
effectively than in his other operas, Rameau weaves these separate
pieces into a continuous musical and dramatic structure. Indeed,
the overture, with its hunting music, segues directly into the
opening aria, an innovation that Gluck mirrored 10 years later in
``Iphigenie en Aulide.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem: the recording is technically unavailable in the
United States. But Tower Records carries it as a special import.
Gardiner's lithe, humane and vibrant performance is worth searching
out.
</P>
<P>
   Try also two recent recordings of the great motets. Many critics
consider these sacred works lesser Rameau. Either of the recordings
_ one by the excellent conductor Philippe Herreweghe with La
Chapelle Royale, the other by Herve Niquet and Le Concert Spirituel
_ should convince you otherwise. Whereas so many settings of these
Latin texts are thick with contrapuntal writing and expressively
severe, Rameau's have a refreshing lucidity and lightness, the
essence of French refinement.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas McGegan's recording of suites from ``Dardanus'' and the
astonishing comic opera-ballet ``Platee'' with the Philharmonia
Baroque Orchestra is also wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, to give credit where credit is due, Christie's account
of the seminal opera ``Castor et Pollux'' is inarguably fine.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALLAN KOZINN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PLATEE'' AND ``DARDANUS'' SUITES. Philharmonia Baroque
Orchestra, conducted by Nicholas McGegan (Conifer 75605 51313). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``LA NAISSANCE D'OSIRIS'' AND ``LES BOREADES'' SUITES. Capella
Savaria, conducted by Mary Terey-Smith (Naxos 8.553388). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``ANACREON'' AND ``DAPHNIS ET EGLE'' SUITES. Capella Savaria,
conducted by Terey-Smith (Naxos 8.553746). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ CANTATAS. New Chamber Opera Ensemble, conducted by Gary Cooper
(ASV GAX 234; two CDs).
</P>
<P>
   Because dance was such an essential component of French Baroque
opera, Rameau's stage works yield colorful, rhythmically vital
orchestral suites. It would be an overstatement to say that these
suites offer distillations of the dramas from which they are drawn.
But they tell us a great deal about the fertility of Rameau's
imagination. Faced with standard dance movements that more
typically interrupt the drama than further it, Rameau composed
music of great variety and energy.
</P>
<P>
   There is always, of course, the nagging feeling that one ought
to be listening to the complete opera, that the suite is like a
digest version of a great book. But Nicholas McGegan and
Philharmonia Baroque, a period-instrument group based in San
Francisco, make a superb case for the practice on a disc of suites
from ``Platee'' and ``Dardanus.'' The orchestra's string and wind
textures have an appealing bite as well as complete transparency.
And the playing over all has a kind of electricity that suggests
the drama of the works from which the dances are drawn.
</P>
<P>
   Two discs by the Capella Savaria accomplish much the same
effect, in performances of a very different kind. In suites from
``La Naissance d'Osiris'' and ``Les Boreades'' in Volume 1, and
``Anacreon'' and ``Daphnis et Egle'' in Volume 2, this Hungarian
period-instrument group produces a rounded timbre, closer to that
of modern instruments. In addition, the group's director, Mary
Terey-Smith, also favors relaxed tempos, but this preference exacts
no cost in vibrancy or _ in movements like the Contredanse en
Rondeau from the ``Boreades'' Suite _ sheer rambunctiousness.
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to opera fairly late in life, Rameau tried his
hand at dramatic writing in a series of magnificent cantatas,
mostly on mythological or allegorical subjects, and mostly
ruminations on the tribulations of love. They are refreshing works.
``Orphee,'' for instance, zooms in on the moment when Orpheus lost
Eurydice by looking back at her as they departed Hades, and Rameau
dispenses with the happy ending found in the Monteverdi opera;
instead, lovers are advised to master their impetuous desires. In
another, ``Les Amants Trahis,'' a dialogue between a naive lover
and a cynic, the cynic prevails.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of these works survive, and the New Chamber Opera
Ensemble, directed by Gary Cooper, has recorded them all, along
with the extant variants. The vocal soloists _ Rachel Elliott,
soprano; James Gilchrist, tenor; Roderick Williams, baritone; and
Thomas Guthrie, bass _ bring attractive timbres, stylish
ornamentation and a necessary depth of feeling to the music, and
one could not want livelier or more beautiful playing from the
instrumental ensemble.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PAUL GRIFFITHS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``ACANTE ET CEPHISE'' AND ``LES FETES D'HEBE'' SUITES.
Orchestra of the 18th Century, conducted by Frans Bruggen (Glossa
GCD 921103). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``NAIS'' AND ``LE TEMPLE DE LA GLOIRE'' SUITES. Philharmonia
Baroque Orchestra, conducted by Nicholas McGegan (Harmonia Mundi
France HMU 907121). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``HIPPOLYTE ET ARICIE.'' Les Arts Florissants, conducted by
William Christie (Erato 0630-15517-2). Les Musiciens du Louvre,
conducted by Marc Minkowski (Deutsche Grammophon Archiv 445
853-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``PIGMALION.'' Le Concert Spirituel, conducted by Herve Niquet
(Virgin Veritas 5 61539 2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``CASTOR ET POLLUX.'' Les Arts Florissants, conducted by
Christie (Harmonia Mundi France HM 901435, three CDs; highlights on
Harmonia Mundi France HM 1901501). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rameau lets us hear Voltaire's smile. His music is often
touchingly expressive, often magical, often joyous, and it
perfectly suits the graceful characters _ too vulnerable to be
quite heroic _ who dance through so many lyric tragedies,
opera-ballets and other classical and exotic entertainments. But
his contemplation of human and musical follies is also, much of the
time, amused. He was in full middle age before he scored his first
big success. He observed his characters' bold declarations and love
affairs, and their constant dancing, with wry wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no recording captures all the qualities of Rameau's gaze
_ the merriment and the fondness, the regret and the elation _
better than Frans Bruggen's of suites from ``Acante et Cephise''
and ``Les Fetes d'Hebe.'' The playing of the Orchestra of the 18th
Century is full of athletic energy and color, and the musicians
bring out the music's huge range of character in the way they toss
off its often irregular or oddly emphasized gestures.
</P>
<P>
   One understands why the Rameau revival had to await the
re-emergence of period-style instruments, with their particular
timbres and ways of speaking. ``Acante'' includes some spectacular
fireworks music in its overture, and is even more than usually full
of choice instrumental combinations and bizarre, vivid strokes. But
charm, delight and fun abound in both suites in these superb and
graphic performances.
</P>
<P>
   Also outstanding _ if not quite matching the delicacy and
earthiness Bruggen finds in such music, often simultaneously _ is
another collection of overtures and dances from two stage works,
this time ``Nais'' and ``Le Temple de la Gloire,'' with Nicholas
McGegan conducting the Philharmonia Baroque Orchestra. The two
overtures, with trumpets and drums, are sheer excitement: that to
``Nais'' has thrilling syncopations, and ``Le Temple de la Gloire''
opens by piling magnificence on magnificence as trumpets cap horns
and are themselves capped by piccolos, all trilling away.
Brilliance appears, too, in some of the dances, which are again
picturequely scored and picturesquely played.
</P>
<P>
   But wonderful though suites are, one needs to hear at least some
of the stage works in full. Both recent recordings of the earliest,
``Hippolyte et Aricie,'' have their points, including the singing
of Lorraine Hunt Lieberson as Phaedra with Les Arts Florissants and
William Christie, and that of Jean-Paul Fouchecourt as Hippolytus
with Les Musiciens du Louvre and Marc Minkowski. You could settle
happily for the Arts Florissants version and hear Fouchecourt's
lively, unusual and stylish high tenor instead in the one-act
``Pigmalion,'' with fit support from Herve Niquet and Le Concert
Spirituel.
</P>
<P>
   Before either ``Hippolyte,'' though, take ``Castor et Pollux''
as also recorded by Christie and his Arts Florissants. ``Castor''
is the stronger piece, as was recognized while Rameau was alive,
and this recording conveys all its sadness and its gaiety, which
are so often mixed in pearly emotional shades. The highlights disc,
including powerful choruses, brilliant dances and one of the most
gorgeous arias in the history of music (``Tristes apprets''), is
the great Rameau bargain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JAMES R. OESTREICH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ OVERTURES. Les Talens Lyriques, conducted by Christophe
Rousset (L'Oiseau-Lyre 455 293-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``HIPPOLYTE ET ARICIE.'' Les Arts Florissants, conducted by
William Christie (Erato 0630-15517-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PLATEE.'' Ensemble Vocal Francoise Herr and Les Musiciens du
Louvre, conducted by Marc Minkowski (Erato Musifrance
2292-45028-2). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``PIECES DE CLAVECIN.'' Christie, harpsichordist (Harmonia
Mundi France HMA 1901120/2; two CDs). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ ``LES INDES GALANTES.'' Olivier Baumont, harpsichordist (Adda
581150). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All too predictably, given the moribund state of the classical
record business today, several favorite Rameau recordings are out
of print, including one of the best: Frans Bruggen's 1987 disc of
suites from ``Les Boreades'' and ``Dardanus'' with the Orchestra of
the 18th Century, on Philips. Happily, good recordings of these
suites and many others abound.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Rameau's operas are well represented even in complete
recordings _ if not in the catalog, then in special imports at
Tower Records, as with ``Platee.'' A rudimentary sense of the
spectacular range of styles in the various stage works can be
gleaned in another Tower import, a lively compilation of 17
overtures, with Christophe Rousset leading the period band Les
Talens Lyriques. The rustic mingles freely with the grand, the
sprightly with the stately in the music, and the performers'
affection is by no means limited to the group's delightful
namesake, ``Les Fetes d'Hebe, ou Les Talens Lyriques.''
</P>
<P>
   My first actual sighting of a Rameau opera came in 1983, with
``Hippolyte et Aricie'' at the Festival of Aix-en-Provence in
France. At a time when early-music attractions often still relied
on big-name mainstream performers to draw crowds, the production
placed Jessye Norman, as Phaedra, awkwardly in the middle of a
cohesive period-style troupe, conducted by Sir John Eliot Gardiner.
</P>
<P>
   It is a joy to return to that opera and find a singer at least
as expressive and infinitely more congenial to her surroundings,
the superb Lorraine Hunt Lieberson, in the role in a typically fine
recording from William Christie and Les Arts Florissants. Hunt
Lieberson is also to be heard next week in the New York City Opera
production of ``Platee.''
</P>
<P>
   The available recording of that work, despite a superior vocal
ensemble, including Gilles Ragon, Guy de Mey, Guillemette Laurens
and Veronique Gens, boasts no such single asset. Still, it is in
excellent hands, with Marc Minkowski, who has plied this repertory
almost as assiduously as Christie, leading Les Musiciens du Louvre.
</P>
<P>
   As large as the operas of Rameau's last three decades loom, the
earlier harpsichord suites are by no means negigible. In fact, they
are sheer delights in their lively depictions of nature and the
supernatural, their kaleidoscopic colors and their quirky humor. As
remarkable as it is to analyze and appreciate Rameau's various
musical gifts _ for melody, harmony, rhythm, sonority _ they are
hard to isolate in the listening, so compelling and unified is the
whole.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the case, at least, in Christie's splendid compilation
of the four suites of 1724 and 1728. If Christie occasionally errs
toward stiffness, his upright manner seems on the whole only to
reinforce the archness of Rameau's humor.
</P>
<P>
   Olivier Baumont, on Adda, is a bit freer in approach, and his
recordings provide an alternative hardly less fine. Or try him
instead in Rameau's harpsichord arrangement of his exotic
opera-ballet ``Les Indes Galantes.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is yet another way into those operas. And into them you
will surely want to plunge if you spend any time at all with this
composer.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLOWS IN 4th TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   RAMEAU REVIVED ONSTAGE
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Four Nations Ensemble and Music From China are
presenting a program called ``Entertainment for Kings'' at the 92nd
Street Y (at Lexington Avenue) tomorrow that includes the first of
Rameau's ``Pieces de Clavecin en Concerts.'' The program also
includes music by Corbetta, Couperin and Marais, and works from the
Qing, Han, Tang, Jin and Ming Dynasties. The concert starts at 8
p.m.; tickets are $25. Information: (212) 996-1100.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Opera production of Rameau's ``Platee'' will
be performed at the New York State Theater on Tuesday at 7:30 p.m.,
April 14 at 8 p.m., April 16 at 1:30 p.m., April 18 and 20 at 7:30
p.m. and April 22 at 8 p.m. The director and choreographer of the
opera, which is sung in French with English supertitles, is Mark
Morris.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $22 to $95.
</P>
<P>
   Information: (212) 870-5570.
</P>
</TEXT>
