<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PRESIDENTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU ELECT TO WATCH, PBS'S `AMERICAN PRESIDENT' IS A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: A-  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone who has tried to memorize the presidents of the United
States in chronological order will be frustrated by PBS's ``The
American President.''
</P>
<P>
   The 10-hour documentary series, running two hours each night
from Sunday through Thursday, takes a thematic approach in its
profiles of our 41 chief executives, not a linear one. But, while
obviously contrived to force four men (five, in one case) neatly
into each theme, it's a mostly pleasant departure from the
numerical, ``name-the-16th-president'' style we may remember from
grade school.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Sunday's first installment passes up George
Washington, John Adams, Thomas Jefferson and James Madison in favor
of John Quincy Adams, Benjamin Harrison, Franklin D. Roosevelt and
John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely foursome, it would seem, unless one considers the
title of Episode 1: ``Family Ties.'' All were members of political
clans, which more or less considered the presidency a natural
component of the family business. Presidential scholar Richard
Neustadt, the only talking-head expert who appears in the series,
even suggests that FDR, who was a cousin of Theodore Roosevelt and
who married Teddy's favorite niece, Eleanor (his own fifth cousin),
``saw the presidency as almost family property and thought of the
country as his patrimony.''
</P>
<P>
   Neustadt doesn't view this as necessarily bad. Even in a
democracy, he says, power often resides in families that pass the
baton from one generation to the next. The beauty of democracy is
that voters eventually tire of such autocratic succession and do
something about it, or fate steps in and takes care of things. Two
of the four presidents in ``Family Ties,'' Roosevelt and Kennedy,
died in office, leaving power in the hands of men who weren't quite
expecting it.
</P>
<P>
   Nine such individuals have risen to the presidency accidentally,
but ``Happenstance,'' the second episode airing Sunday night,
focuses only on five: John Tyler (who succeeded William Henry
Harrison), Millard Fillmore (Zachary Taylor), Andrew Johnson
(Abraham Lincoln), Chester Arthur (James Garfield) and Harry Truman
(FDR). The other accidental presidents are themed thusly: Lyndon
Johnson in ``The Professional Politician,'' airing Mon-
</P>
<P>
   day; Calvin Coolidge in ``The American Way'' Tuesday; Gerald
Ford in ``Compromise Choices'' Wednesday, and Theodore Roosevelt in
``Expanding Power'' Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   This arbitrary, though not unthoughtful, construction allows
armchair historians to quibble all the way to next Election Day.
Why aren't Andrew Jackson, Taylor and Theodore Roosevelt included
in ``The Heroic Posture'' with other military men? (Well, for one
thing, only 12 presidents have had no military experience, so it
also overlooks James Monroe, Rutherford B. Hayes, James Garfield,
Kennedy, George Bush and several others who served with
distinction.) Or how can Bush be part of ``The World Stage'' _ a
grouping of presidents known for their accomplishments in foreign
policy _ and Richard Nixon not be? (Because Nixon happens to be a
good fit in ``Expanding Power,'' a look at four presidents who did
just that.)
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the placement doesn't much matter. ``The American
President'' is a precious, well-written resource from the
father-and-sons team of Philip Kunhardt Jr., Philip Kunhardt III
and Peter Kunhardt, all veteran writer/
</P>
<P>
   producers of historical books and TV documentaries. (A companion
volume by the Kunhardts, published by Riverhead Books, is available
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   for $50.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The American President'' may periodically confuse the
chronologically minded as it leaps about from pillar to Polk. But
whether one is seeking great trivia _ Zachary Taylor was Jefferson
Davis' father-in-law _ or great quotes _ James Madison said: ``The
great truth is that governments do better without kings'' _ or
great insight _ Neustadt on apolitical presidents: ``The American
public from time to time wishes to see the trustee who looks
neither right nor left but only up to the heavens and down to the
work before him, a man of independence; it is not, however, a good
formula for doing what presidents have to do'' _ ``The American
President'' does what good TV always does. While informing and even
entertaining viewers, it challenges them to look at things in a
different way, to think, to question, to analyze.
</P>
<P>
   If only we could all be so engaged before electing the next
president ...
</P>
<P>
   The American President. Ten-hour documentary series on the 41
presidents of the United States, narrated by Hugh Sidey. Sunday
through Thursday on PBS. Parental guideline rating: TV-G.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
