<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BEST PICK FOR BEATING TIGER WOODS IS HIMSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRUCE MEADOWS   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa, Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To say Tiger Woods has a great chance of winning this year's
Masters golf tournament at Augusta National is sort of like saying
the Los Angeles Lakers have a great chance of winning the NBA
championship this season.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that in men's professional golf today, there
are two kinds of stories: Tiger Woods and whoever happens to beat
Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Will somebody knock off Woods this week at Augusta and, for at
least a brief moment, become that other story?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't seem likely, although in golf, unlike most sports,
with so many quality players in the field, anyone can find the
magic and beat Woods, especially if Woods helps a little and beats
himself, something he has done at times.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger has won 18 PGA tournaments since turning pro in late 1996,
including the 1997 Masters. By comparison, 45-year-old Greg Norman
has also won 18 times and has never won a Masters, even though he
has come agonizingly close recently with a third-place finish last
year and in 1995, and second place in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to remember when one player has commanded as much
attention, even if you go back to the glory days of Jack Nicklaus,
Tom Watson or Arnold Palmer. It's tough to recall a player being
such an overwhelming favorite in a field full of such talented
golfers.
</P>
<P>
   But the bottom line is that like so many other events, as far as
the 24-year-old Woods is concerned, this year's Masters is probably
his to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he is ready to play and firing on all cylinders and you
get him on the type of golf course that suits him, he is very, very
difficult to beat,'' said Nick Price this week.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Augusta is his type of course _ even though it has been
tweaked to make it ``Tiger proof'' _ is not a question. His
18-under-par winning score of 270 in 1997 beat Tom Kite by 12
shots.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lowest 72-hole score since Augusta opened in 1934 and
the largest margin of victory in a major championship since young
Tom Morris won the British Open by 13 shots ... in 1870!
</P>
<P>
   Woods has won three times already in 2000 _ the Mercedes
Championship, the AT&AMP;T Pebble Beach Pro-Am and most recently, the
Bay Hill Invitational March 19 in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The frightening thing _ well, at least frightening to other
players _ is Woods seems to be getting better. His short game and
putting has improved, he's matured as a person and a golfer, using
better judgment on shots and not relying strictly on his length.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been targeting my game ... it's been getting better week
by week,'' he said Monday at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   As far as course changes _ more rough, narrower fairways and
more pitch to several greens _ Woods only smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to play a little differently,'' he said this week.
``It's such a great course ... I don't see the need for these
little changes every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, the people at Augusta do. They don't want this kid carving
18 shots off par again this week.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are he won't. But chances are he'll play well enough to
win, and if he's close on Sunday ... well we've all seen what
happens when he senses the kill. Just ask young Matt Gogel about
Pebble Beach this past February.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all very new ... the complete dominance by one
player,'' said Scotsman Colin Montgomerie. ``Tiger seems to have
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes one green jacket, but he wants more. At least six,
which is what the legendary Jack Nicklaus owns. Nicklaus, in fact,
has 18 victories in major tournaments, which is perhaps Tiger's
most coveted goal.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there will be challengers in this first major of the
new millennium. I like Jim Furyk _ he's a grinder and somebody who
can perhaps hang with Woods at crunch time.
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the usual suspects like Phil Mickelson,
chasing his first major, David Duval, Davis Love III, Tom Lehman
and Ernie Els, among others. Who knows who else might emerge from
the pack to make things interesting.
</P>
<P>
   But regardless, who doesn't think Woods will be in the hunt on
the back nine Sunday afternoon?
</P>
<P>
   I think he'll win because majors are what golf is all about for
Tiger Woods. God knows it's not the money, given his incredible
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   I just hope it's close and dramatic _ no 12-shot victories _ and
perhaps even comes down to the final few holes.
</P>
<P>
   If it does, wagering against Tiger Woods may be a sucker bet.
</P>
<P>
   (Bruce Meadows writes for The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa,
Calif. The Press Democrat is part of the New York Times Regional
Newspaper Group.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
