</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEO NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER M. NICHOLS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   `Three Kings' In Hindsight
</P>
<P>
   As filmmakers' commentaries proliferate on DVD, so do
perspectives on how movies are made. In two separate commentaries
for ``Three Kings,'' to be released on disc and videocassette by
Warner on Tuesday, the director, David Russell, and two of its
producers, Charles Roven and Edward McDonnell, talk all movie long
about a film that succeeded in the end but had particular troubles,
from the time it was shot in the deserts of Mexico and Arizona to
its release in theaters last October.
</P>
<P>
   In the film, the American-led offensive against Iraq has just
ended, and four American soldiers (George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg,
Ice Cube and Spike Jonze) plan to abscond with $23 million worth of
gold bullion plundered from Kuwait by the Iraqis and hidden in the
desert. Instead, against their mercenary instincts, they become
personally involved with Iraqis resisting President Saddam Hussein
and help them escape into Iran.
</P>
<P>
   As with most disc commentaries, the fun is in the details.
Makeup people needed two hours a day to cover Wahlberg's body
tattoos, but there was no way Warner would allow the film to be
made without his taking his shirt off. Clooney's problem was time.
On loan from the television series ``E.R.,'' he could give the
production only three days a week during the 78 days it took to
make the film.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily a television actor, he had to concentrate on looking
at people when speaking to them, a departure from talking on the
run in an emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the White House, which, Russell says, has
second-rate movie-watching facilities. After the film was screened
for President Clinton, the director adds, he and Clinton talked
about the issues involved until the wee hours. The presidential
entourage wasn't sure whether to laugh or cringe at the treatment
of the enemy by excited American soldiers who dash about with no
clear idea of what they're supposed to do with terrified Iraqis who
are suddenly surrendering by the thousands.
</P>
<P>
   From there the commentaries get down to larger questions about
the nature and purpose of the film. Originally it was intended as a
straight action film, then as a kind of ``Treasure of the Sierra
Madre'' about tensions among four characters seeking antiquities in
the desert.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the more politically motivated Russell took aim at the
cultural stew that spilled American consumer goods all over the
desert while everybody tried to determine the point of the war. To
him the point of the movie was a failure by the United States to
support large segments of the Iraqi population who thought the
American military operation was intended to free them from Hussein.
The producers, on the other hand, echo the U.S. position: the
object was to liberate Kuwait and avoid further complications in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, their movie was different, which cost it somewhat
at the box office. The producers talk about the challenge of
marketing a film with action for young male audiences, attractive
men for young female audiences, narrative substance for older men,
heart for older women and a little comedy for everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted this to be a genre-busting movie,'' Roven says.
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   The Insider
</P>
<P>
   With knowledge that cigarette company executives lied about the
effect of nicotine in their product, the chemist Jeffrey Wigand
(Russell Crowe) cautiously gives the story to Lowell Bergman (Al
Pacino), a producer of the CBS program ``60 Minutes,'' who in turn
interests the newsman Mike Wallace (Christopher Plummer). In the
trouble ahead, however, Wigand finds his confidentiality
compromised, his wife walks out and just when the ``60 Minutes''
report is to be shown, CBS gets cold feet. Pacino's scenery-chewing
can be distracting, but Michael Mann directs his film, Janet Maslin
wrote in The New York Times, with ``a pulse-quickening panache that
heightens the tensions within its story.''
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Touchstone. $107.37; DVD, $29.99. 157 minutes. Closed
captioned. R. Release date: April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Tumbleweeds
</P>
<P>
   Fleeing another abusive relationship, the lusty Mary Jo Walker
(Janet McTeer) packs up her 12-year-old daughter, Ava (Kimberly J.
Brown), and drives off toward no place in particular. Attracting
men is what Mary Jo does best, and mother and daughter set up
housekeeping with Jack (Gavin O'Connor), a truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   A sweet, long-suffering child strongly attached to her mother,
Ava blossoms in new surroundings. Jack doesn't work out, of course,
but McTeer melts into the role so deeply that ``what is on the
screen is not a performance at all but a kind of spontaneous
alchemy'' (Stephen Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. New Line. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 104 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Three To Tango
</P>
<P>
   Needing a ``safe'' male to watch his girlfriend, Amy (Neve
Campbell), when he's not around, a crass developer named Charles
(Dylan McDermott) enlists Oscar (Matthew Perry), an architect who
the developer assumes is gay. Competing to design a $90 million
project controlled by Charles, Oscar goes along, but being avowedly
heterosexual he naturally has a hard time controlling his impulses
toward Amy.
</P>
<P>
   That sets up a self-conscious and uncomfortable time with
homosexuality in an allegedly liberated comedy with ``some nasty
undercurrents that lend it a slightly sour taste'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Warner. $107.37; DVD, $24.98. 98 minutes. Closed
captioned. Release date: April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Happy, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A couple of crooks (Jeremy Northam and Steve Zahn) duck the law
in small-town Texas by posing as a gay couple who produce
children's beauty pageants. In the town of Happy, they are hailed
as miracle workers who can pump a little life into the Little
Squeezed Pageant. With no alternative, the pair struggles to oblige
in a nonsensical comedy that ``is giddy and cuddlesome with a
gosh-oh-gee enthusiasm that is at first engaging, but quickly
becomes a sign of a desperation to be liked'' (Holden).
</P>
<P>
   _1999. Miramax. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 96 minutes. Closed
captioned. PG-13. Release date: April 11.
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in
earlier editions.
</P>
<P>
   JEAN COCTEAU'S ORPHIC CYCLE. Three films by the novelist, poet,
painter, playwright, screenwriter, director and much else include
his first film, ``The Blood of a Poet'' (1930, 55 minutes), a
highly personalized expression (with Cocteau as commentator) of
fears and obsessions about life and death; ``Orpheus'' (1950, 86
minutes), part Greek myth and part Cocteau's personal experience,
starring Jean Marais as a poet whiling away his talent until he
meets Princess Death; and ``The Testament of Orpheus'' (1960, 79
minutes), with a cast including Picasso and Yul Brynner, about a
poet who travels a mysterious wasteland on his way to death and
resurrection. Home Vision. VHS, $29.95 each; DVD, a three-disc box
set from the Criterion Collection, $79.95. French with English
subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   CABARET BALKAN. The leering master of ceremonies in a Belgrade
nightclub before the NATO bombing last year introduces a series of
not-so-nice vignettes aimed at venting a few hatreds and
frustrations. Illustrating what might be called a Pandora's box
theory of social order, Goran Paskaljevic's garishly
expressionistic portrait of life, from murder in the shower to a
mob stoning of a man trying to escape over a fence, lets everybody
lash out. 1999. Paramount. 102 minutes. R. Release date: April 11.
</P>
<P>
   P.T. BARNUM. In an A&AMP;E production, Beau Bridges and his son
Jordan star as the circus impresario and showman who once allowed
that ``without printer's ink, I should be no bigger than Tom
Thumb.'' 1999. Artisan. $19.98. 138 minutes. Closed captioned.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
