<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, April 7 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-POLL (New York) _ Results of the latest NYT-CBS poll
on the New York Senate race between Rudy Giuliani and Hillary
Rodham Clinton. By Adam Clymer and Marjorie Connelly.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has not seen
his son Elian since the boy and his mother left Cuba on a rickety
raft for a new life in America, set foot on American soil here
Thursday and told a crowd of reporters and television cameras that,
``I hope I will soon be able to embrace my son.'' Justice
Department officials said they would move quickly to transfer
custody of the boy to his father. Senior administration officials
made it clear they believed that the arrival of Gonzalez from Cuba
had altered the situation dramatically in favor of their efforts to
transfer custody of the boy from his Miami relative. By Neil A.
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT4
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-CORRUPTION (New York) _ More details are emerging on the
accusations that Christie's and Sotheby's, the giant auction
houses, colluded to fix prices. (Editors: This story is exclusive
and competitive. We plan to move it at 9:45 p.m.) By Douglas
Frantz, Ralph Blumenthal and Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Nawaz Sharif, ousted as
Pakistan's prime minister in a military coup last October, was
convicted Thursday of hijacking a commercial airliner, sentenced to
life imprisonment and ordered to forfeit all his personal property.
Standing along with six co-defendants who each were acquitted, the
balding, doughy Sharif barely blinked when the judgment was read. A
shriek from his daughter Maryam broke the silence. ``Have fear of
God!'' she cried out. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   (1stLd has MOVED)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RIGHTS (Jerusalem) _ Over the years, Israel has earned a
regular place on the blacklists of many human and civil rights
organizations by invoking national security to explain practices
that were considered exclusionary, discriminatory and coercive
toward Israeli Arabs and Palestinians. But since the right-wing
government was replaced last summer by a broad coalition including
several leftists and human rights advocates, key policy changes
have been made that together with a spate of High Court decisions
point toward a sea change. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-POORER-TEAMS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ For baseball fans, hope is
supposed to spring eternal at this time each year. The breeze
blowing through the empty stadium is almost expected to whisper the
universal mantra of fans everywhere: Maybe this year will be the
year. But here in Kansas City, as in Pittsburgh, Montreal,
Minneapolis and many smaller cities with major league teams, that
perennial optimism has withered over the last decade in the face of
a growing gap between rich and poor franchises. There is a growing
consensus among owners, fans and experts on the game that the
disparity between high-revenue teams and those in small markets
threatens the sport's future popularity. Last year, the eight teams
that made it to the playoffs were all among the top ten payrolls in
the game. Some owners are asking how baseball can sustain the
interest of fans and attract new devotees if only a handful of
lucrative teams have a realistic chance of making the playoffs each
year. By James C. McKinley Jr.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET-MARGINS (Chicago) _ Looking at margin calls and their
impact on the market. Trying to get voices of small investors who
have received margin calls and how they are reacting. Developing.
By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
