<SLUG> BC-PANIC-INVESTORS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICING IS OFF E-COMMERCE AND INTERNET SECTORS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This timely 725-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE
INDEPENDENT newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As ever, there was some hoopla on Wall Street
Wednesday as two new companies came to the New York Stock Exchange
offering shares in themselves in the hope of raising lots of money.
A blue and white blimp bobbed beneath the clouds overhead and
everyone seemed to be breakfasting on doughnuts.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what, though? There was not a dot.com company in sight.
</P>
<P>
   These were two decidedly old-economy companies celebrating their
new listings _ Metropolitan Life Insurance, owners of the airship,
and Krispy Kreme, a doughnut firm that has a cult following because
of its retro branding.
</P>
<P>
   The icing is decidedly off the e-commerce and Internet sectors.
Cyber-companies, also known as Netcos, that had been planning
initial public offerings have been advised by the banks to
postpone. With the tech-heavy Nasdaq in bungee mode this week, that
would seem like wise counsel.
</P>
<P>
   There is a new fear in the air for Internet-related concerns,
where, until just a few weeks ago, there was only optimism.
</P>
<P>
   It is scary for investors. But what about those legions of
cyber-executives, who may have left good, established employers, to
join the cyberspace gold rush? For them it is terrifying.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Darby Williams, for example, who, at 46, left Microsoft to
launch Cook Express, an outfit that allowed consumers to order
gastronomic dishes online for delivery to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, his became the first e-commerce company to
file for bankruptcy in Silicon Valley. When he needed money to
cover debts accumulated during his start-up, suddenly the venture
capitalists told him no.
</P>
<P>
   Or Bill Malloy, who recently resigned as chief executive of
Peapod.com, a site for those who would prefer to shop for food
online rather than visit the supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   When Peapod began to come face to face with reality _ started to
run out of cash _ he resigned because of ``physical and mental
exhaustion.''
</P>
<P>
   It was news last week about the plight of several high-profile
Net pioneers, including Peabod.com, that first began to tilt the
Nasdaq into the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   Warnings were issued about the ability of Peapod and Drkoop.com,
a health-care site, to stay in business. They followed an
announcement last Thursday from CDNow Inc. that it too faced a
rapid loss of cash and possible closure.
</P>
<P>
   The shakeout that seemed to be looming last week now seems
almost inevitable. The desperate plunge in the Nasdaq on Tuesday,
which was later largely recovered, will probably have profound
consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Now _ and, arguably, not before time _ investors will be looking
for real signs of profit in the Internet enterprises before they
offer the new money.
</P>
<P>
   Many players will find themselves denied funds. The only
alternative to death will be mergers and partnerships with stronger
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you need money because you are trying to pay for a branding
strategy, the it will be hard,'' commented David Golden of Chase
H&AMP;Q. ``Unless companies are on the cusp of profitability, it will
be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the giants of the sector happened to be in New York for
a media conference on Tuesday, as the Nasdaq executed its
acrobatics. Like Jeff Bezos, founder of Amazon.com and George Bell
of Excite &LR; Home. They said they liked what they were seeing.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end the focus will be on sustainable business models,
which will be good for the whole industry,'' Bell insisted.
``Investors are coming to grips with how much time they want to
give these customers to demonstrate themselves,'' Bezos added.
``And I think that is great for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite for everyone, of course. Morale in cyberland is
suddenly crashing. Not only are many companies facing some harsh
realities, but their employees are being hurt because many are
remunerated through stocks and options.
</P>
<P>
   When the value of those packages collapse, as so many will have
done this week, the motivation to work will vanish.
</P>
<P>
   Some CEO's are urging employees to keep their eyes on their
jobs, not on the value of the shares and options.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Slatt of Watchguard Technologies, an Internet security
company, sent this e-mail to his staff during Tuesday: ``With these
fluctuations, you'll literally drive looking every day'' at your
personal worth. (And, of course, they may also be driven out of the
door to alternative employment.) &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 725-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
