<HEADER>
A9128 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DEFIANT-GATES-INDEPEN     04-06 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFIANT-GATES-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. MICROSOFT REMAINS DEFIANT: `COMMON SENSE STANDS ON OUR SIDE'  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By DAVID USBORNE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Gates remained defiant Tuesday in the face of a
dramatic court ruling on Monday that his software behemoth,
Microsoft, blatantly violated free competition laws to squash its
Silicon Valley rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling triggered a dramatic meltdown in technology stocks as
investors ran scared, triggering a massive sell-off across Wall
Street Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the stock of his company _ and therefore the paper value
of his own fortune _ continued to plunge, Gates brushed aside
suggestions that his company may be broken up by the courts as
punishment for its transgressions. He also reiterated his promise
to fight the findings in the appeal courts.
</P>
<P>
   The next stage in the battle will be hearings by the same judge
who issued Monday's verdict, Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, to
determine just what the punishment should be.
</P>
<P>
   They could last four months with the judge therefore reaching
his conclusion in the late summer. That, however, is when the
appeals process is likely to begin.
</P>
<P>
   It will pass through the Washington, D.C. appellate system first
before it goes thereafter, almost inevitably, to the U.S. Supreme
Court. Most experts consider that the entire process will not be
exhausted until the summer of 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Because the road ahead is so long, any real pain for Microsoft
is likely to be delayed or blunted. And while the wheels of U.S.
justice continue to turn at their near-glacial pace, innovation in
the marketplace continues to accelerate. In two years time, any
final outcome for Microsoft may be moot.
</P>
<P>
   Options for Judge Penfield Jackson in the penalty phase range
from breaking up Microsoft into several new companies, perhaps as
many as five, to something far less draconian like demanding that
the existing Microsoft simply adopt more competition-friendly
business practices.
</P>
<P>
   There were calls on the court Tuesday to take the harshest steps
possible against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge has laid the foundation for the breakup of
Microsoft,'' consumer advocate Ralph Nader commented. ``Anything
less than that will be like a thundering elephant emitting the
squeak of a mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gates, in an interview with the BBC, seemed sure that would
not happen. ``I don't think any extreme remedy such as a breakup is
at all consistent with what the court put forward,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that Microsoft would prevail on appeal, he added:
``Common sense stands on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   So does time. While the U.S. government may seek to have parts
of whatever remedy Judge Penfield Jackson comes out with applied
immediately, it is likely that any serious sort of sanctions,
certainly including a call for a breakup, would be frozen by the
courts pending Microsoft's appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile history shows that Microsoft does better with appeals
judges than in the lower courts.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the politics of the fight. It remains unclear
whether even the Clinton administration would really have the
stomach to splinter Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gates may be hoping for a change of party colors at
the White House. He will be hoping for a victory in November for
George Bush, Jr., who is thought to have a slightly more relaxed
view on enforcement of U.S. monopoly laws.
</P>
<P>
   That there are several factors still on Gates' side was
reflected by investor alerts issues by several leading Wall Street
banks Tuesday, all urging clients to buy Microsoft shares rather
than to dump them.
</P>
<P>
   As well as pointing to the likely length of an appeals effort,
analysts noted that a settlement between the company and the
government remains a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the case moves forward from here, the government may find
it increasingly difficult to count on the outcome,'' Credit Suisse
First Boston said in its alert. ``This could in turn increase the
potential for a settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that investors themselves were listening Tuesday as a
continuing sell-off on the Nasdaq exchange in New York pushed it
into what is formally termed a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft itself continued to suffer a brutal battering, sinking
by midday an additional 2 5/8 to 88. That in turn meant further
devastation of the fortune of Gates himself, who saw its value, in
paper terms, eroded by $12.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrating the historic ruling, meanwhile, are most of
Microsoft's Silicon Valley rivals, some of whom were instrumental
in triggering the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been vindicated,'' remarked James Barksdale, the founder
of Netscape. ``The ruling is great for consumers and for people who
use technology.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1828EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
