<SLUG> BC-OBUCHI-`DISAPPEARED'-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY, SECRECY SURROUND OBUCHI'S STROKE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 775-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 By RICHARD LLOYD PARRY  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Keizo Obuchi, the outgoing Japanese prime minister,
disappeared for four hours after suffering a stroke on Sunday and
was out of contact with his government as aides tried desperately
to cover up his critical condition, the Independent has learned.
</P>
<P>
   The revelation came Wednesday as his successor, Yoshiro Mori,
was sworn in as prime minister, three days after Obuchi's sudden
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary sequence of midnight events, which further
raise questions about the Japanese government's capacity to handle
emergencies, the ailing prime minister travelled to hospital in an
unarmored minivan driven by his personal doctor, without his
complement of bodyguards and without the knowledge of any members
of the government.
</P>
<P>
   According to Mikio Aoki, the cabinet secretary who took over as
interim acting prime minister, it was early on Sunday morning when
he was informed of Obuchi's condition, more than four hours after
he was first taken ill.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, the 62-year old prime minister was accompanied
only by his wife and a junior secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were some reasons to travel to the hospital
without security,'' Akitaka Saiki, Obuchi's deputy press secretary
said Wednesday, who confirmed that during that four-hour period no
one in the government knew where the prime minister was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the prime minister's health condition immediately
impacts on the political situation. I think that's the main reason
his aides wanted to have a minimum amount of information
provided.''
</P>
<P>
   The government has already been criticized for waiting more than
22 hours before announcing Obuchi's illness _ indeed on Sunday, as
he was lying in Tokyo's Juntendo Hospital, an aide told reporters
that the prime minister was working at home.
</P>
<P>
   Aoki has insisted that he was waiting for the results of tests
before making a definitive announcement about his leader's
condition; but there is suspicion that he was buying time for
consultation among officials of Obuchi's ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP).
</P>
<P>
   However the latest revelations suggest an even more alarming
scenario: that Obuchi's personal security was compromised in order
to conceal the fact of his hospitalization.
</P>
<P>
   A Japanese prime minister is normally guarded by a dozen armed
members of the Japanese Special Police.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, the prime minister's office and the Tokyo
Metropolitan Police were unable to say whether any bodyguards had
accompanied him to hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The prime minister first complained of illness in the first few
minutes of last Sunday, and his personal doctor, Hidehiko Hisaoka
of Juntendo Hospital, was called to his official residence.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi was conscious at the time and, instead of taking an
ambulance or an official car with security escorts, Dr. Hisaoka
drove there in his minivan, arriving at around 1 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery surrounds the rest of the day. Doctors at the hospital
have refused to make any statement on Obuchi or his treatment, and
the only source of information is Aoki, who claims that he saw the
prime minister at 7 p.m. and was asked by him to take over as
acting prime minster, which he did the following day.
</P>
<P>
   By the official account, Obuchi's condition worsened half an
hour later, and within two hours he had fallen into a coma from
which he has not emerged.
</P>
<P>
   But the only witness to this exchange was Obuchi's wife, who has
not spoken to reporters since her husband's illness.
</P>
<P>
   From the account of Saiki, who worked alongside the prime
minister in his office, it is clear that Obuchi was under intense
physical and mental strain at the time of his stroke.
</P>
<P>
   According to his deputy spokesman, Saiki, Obuchi was working
from 6 a.m. until 11 a.m. and frequently woke up in the middle of
the night to review papers at his desk.
</P>
<P>
   He has not had any time off since last August, and took only
three days of vacation during his entire 20 months in office.
</P>
<P>
   His condition was described Wednesday as ``stable but still
critical'' but, by Wednesday night, Obuchi had already been
consigned to political history.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshiro Mori, his 62-year old university friend, was comfortably
elected as the new prime minister by the LDP-dominated coalition
which has a majority in both houses of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In emergency after emergency _ from the Kobe earthquake to the
nerve gas attack on the Tokyo subway _ Japan has been let down by
its crisis control measures, and Obuchi's illness is just the
latest example.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has never happened before,'' said Saiki. ``We don't have
the so-called manuals to cope with this situation. But on the basis
of this case I am sure some manuals will be developed.'' &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 775-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
London, it must be purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's
sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at
732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is weyded(at)nytimes.com. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
