A9150 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-(TRIMS     04-06 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-WEIZMAN-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI POLICE RECOMMEND THAT PRESIDENT NOT BE CHARGED FOR
ACCEPTING FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ At 75, President Ezer Weizman, having endured
military and political battles that span his country's lifetime,
was not about to cap his career by submitting to public pressure to
resign just because he was being investigated by the police.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, his proud obstinacy paid off. The police closed a
three-month investigation of Weizman with the recommendation that
he not be prosecuted for accepting substantial payments from a
French investor.
</P>
<P>
   But the police did not exactly exonerate Weizman, a founding
father of the 52-year-old state who embodies the bluntness and
swagger of the true sabra, or native-born Israeli. And he is likely
to pay a price, at the least by having his biography tainted by
what many political analysts Thursday deemed unsavory conduct that
made him unfit for office.
</P>
<P>
   ``True, there is a recommendation to close the file on the legal
level,'' said Moshe Negbi, a legal commentator for Israel Radio and
the Maariv newspaper. ``But there is no doubt that in the framework
of norms and principles there is a very strong conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Weizman told a television reporter that he felt
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good?'' the reporter asked. ``Yes,'' Weizman said. ``I feel
good that the case has been closed. What do you want from me? There
are things here and there in the report that I will take to
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have to review the recommendation. But it is highly
unlikely that they will disagree with the conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation immediately moved into high gear about the leading
candidates to succeed Weizman in the ceremonial post, among them
former Prime Minister Shimon Peres, Foreign Minister David Levy and
Moshe Katzav, a Likud Party lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Weizman still has three years left in his second term. But many
people believe that the elderly, sometimes ailing, president will
step down, as he was supposedly planning to do before the scandal
erupted in January.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, there were many calls, some judgmental and some
compassionate, for him to do so swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would urge him to find an elegant way of leaving his post
and retreating to Caesarea,'' the coastal town where he maintains a
second house, said Tommy Lapid, a legislator.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A summary of the 120-page investigative report indicates that
the police suspected that Weizman was indeed involved in a
bribe-taking relationship. They said there was insufficient
evidence for a successful prosecution ``beyond a reasonable
doubt,'' but they did not cite ``lack of guilt,'' as they did with
another charge.
</P>
<P>
   The police said they had found enough evidence to sustain
charges of breach of trust and fraud for Weizman's failure to
report the payments as income. But the statute of limitations on
those charges had expired.
</P>
<P>
   The police documented an eight-year financial relationship
between Weizman and the French businessman, Edouard Seroussi, a
Sudanese-born Jew who has a house in a suburb of Tel Aviv. The
relationship existed from 1985 to 1993, mostly when Weizman was a
member of Parliament and Cabinet minister. He became president in
May 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The police said Seroussi paid Weizman $400,000 in that period,
most of it deposited monthly into a trust. Seroussi also gave
Weizman a car.
</P>
<P>
   The police described a business relationship that evolved into
``a strong friendship between the two that made Seroussi want to
help Weizman in his daily troubles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence shows that the beginning of the relationship
between Weizman and Seroussi was based on business and financial
interests,'' the report said. ``Seroussi identified the business
potential in the name Weizman as a name that could cross borders,
and he was willing to invest a lot of money for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The evidence indicates, as a fact, that over the course of the
year a close friendship did, indeed, develop. At the same time, the
existence of the friendship, which is not doubted, does not negate
the other dimensions of the relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Weizman, who did not live the high life, said he
had spent much of the money caring for his son Shaul, who was
wounded in the Suez Canal in 1970 and died in a car accident in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   Seroussi also paid off the $800,000 in debts for a political
party that Weizman tried to create in 1988, the police said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The police mentioned only two instances in which Weizman seemed
to use his position to give Seroussi something in return. But
neither amounted to anything.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, Weizman vouched for his friend when he sought to
buy shares in a holding company that controls the First
International Bank. The deal never went through. In the other case,
Weizman tried to help him start an English-language newspaper here,
but the venture never started.
</P>
</TEXT>
