<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COSMETICS-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU SEEKS TO BAN COSMETICS TESTING ON LIVE ANIMALS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 350-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``a''
general news file.)  
  
 By STEPHEN CASTLE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS _ Brussels Wednesday proposed a total ban on testing of
cosmetics on live animals in the EU, but provoked complaints that
the plans will water down existing controls and export cruel
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission announced that it wants to amend
existing legislation due to come into force on July 1, under which
European member states were committed to a ban on the sale of
cosmetics containing ingredients tested on animals after July 1,
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Brussels gets its way, that will now be put on ice in favor
of a full-scale ban on animal testing in the production of
cosmetics inside the EU. Imported goods will not, however, be
covered.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ideas will be discussed on May 5 and, if agreed, the
directive will be suspended until moves to amend it have been
through all their legislative stages.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday's plan has lead to accusations that the new
proposal will delay and weaken controls that were first agreed in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Britain's Mark Watts, Labour's spokesman on animal welfare in
the European Parliament, said the new measures were ``totally
inadequate'' adding: ``This ban has been on the table for year and
has been subject to endless delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There can be no justification for painful skin tests on
rabbits or testing burning eye drops on mice for luxury products
which can be tested in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Brussels says that it efforts to take imports out of the scope
of the directive has been prompted by fears that new restrictions
on goods made abroad could fall foul of the World Trade
Organization, the arbiter of global trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
   The European Commission said in a statement: ``In order to avoid
any difficulties with our trade partners which would risk putting
into question the EU legislation regarding animal testing, the
Commission proposes to modify the ban to ensure
WTO-compatibility''.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated that 0.3 percent of the animals involved in the
EU each year in experimentation are used for tests on ingredients
which make up cosmetic products. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
 &UR; (To publish this 350-word article from THE INDEPENDENT newspaper in
