<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HITECH-SHAKEOUT-INDEPENDENT-825&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HI-TECH SHAKEOUT, RATTLE AND TOLL  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (ATTN. EDITORS: FOR THOSE DESIRING A SHORTER VERSION, THIS
INSIGHTFUL ARTICLE OFFERS A 175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM AT 825. TOTAL
UNCUT IS 1,050.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``k''
commentary news, ``f'' financial news and ``a'' domestic/general
news files.)  
  
 By HAMISH MCRAE  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Wednesday morning, while walking the dog around the
local park, I bumped into an old friend also walking her dog. ``I
must ask you,'' she said, ``what you think about Bill Gates and the
market. What is going to happen?''
</P>
<P>
   She is not a tech-head, nor does she have a background in
finance, but it transpired that she was renovating an apartment and
was concerned about London property prices.
</P>
<P>
   Intuitively she could spot the links between the Microsoft case,
the price of U.S. hi-tech stocks, the possibility of a global
slowdown and the impact that might have on the price of a London
apartment.
</P>
<P>
   I mumbled an extremely inadequate answer and promised a more
thought-through one in the paper. Here goes.
</P>
<P>
   There are really two questions. What is happening now? And what
will happen next?
</P>
<P>
   When markets jump about as much as they have in the last few
days, they are groping for something that they cannot understand.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they were far too slow in appreciating that the new
communications technologies would change utterly the face of the
business world, they then overestimated the money that might be
made out of these technologies.
</P>
<P>
   The result was always going to be a sharp break in the markets,
and it looks as though that is happening now.
</P>
<P>
   If it is, then there is a nice parallel with the share crash of
October 1987, which occurred immediately after the great storm. For
the storm, read the collapse of share trading on the London market
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, no connection between the two. But the
collapse of our share trading technology Wednesday highlights the
vulnerability of companies selling intangibles rather than real
items.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us now spend more on phone calls than we do on lunch,
but you cannot eat a virtual sandwich. People were sooner or later
going to cotton onto the fact that most of the thousands of
entrepreneurial companies spawned by the communications revolution
would end up losers.
</P>
<P>
   While the few winners would transform the whole business world,
figuring out who they would be was like finding Ford out of the
2,000 car makers in the U.S. in the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
   So we are seeing, in all probability, the first stages of the
hi-tech shakeout.
</P>
<P>
   What happens next? Typically, when markets pull back from a
burst of over-enthusiasm, there are several months of indecision.
Things don't happen in a straight-line, orderly way.
</P>
<P>
   Actually that period of indecision started about three months
ago, though initially it was indecision about the impact of the new
technologies on the old economy, and only in the last couple of
weeks has it spread.
</P>
<P>
   As many people have pointed out, were it not for the hi-tech
sector, we would be already clearly in a bear market.
</P>
<P>
   So expect another six to 18 months of uncertainty; expect that
to be most evident in the United States, where valuations have been
pushed to extreme levels, but expect it also to show itself in the
U.K. and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That will lead eventually to a period of much slower growth. The
U.S. is particularly vulnerable because of the extent to which the
dollar has been supported by foreign money flowing into the new
industries, but we should not kid ourselves that if the U.S. slows
we will not slow too. We will. And eventually so too will
continental Europe.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to questions about the timing of the slowdown and its
likely severity. On timing, things always seem to take longer than
you think.
</P>
<P>
   Given the momentum behind the U.S. economy at the moment, with
an extraordinary burst of growth at the turn of the year of about 7
percent, it is hard to see that coming off quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Those of us who thought there would be a post-millennial flop
have been proved wrong. My guess now is that the slowdown will not
start seriously until 2001 or maybe even 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Expect the pattern of the last downturn to be repeated, with the
U.S. and U.K. slowing first and continental Europe following.
Expect too that the U.S. and U.K. will emerge more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   On severity, as far as the U.S. is concerned, expect something
between, on the optimistic side, a couple of years of very slow
growth and, on the pessimistic side, a recession akin to that of
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The U.K. underwent a worse experience in the early 1990s than
the U.S., but this time it should have a less serious one because
the imbalances are less serious.
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the year 2002 will be one of very slow growth.
For continental Europe the bad year will be 2003. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (175-WORD OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS HERE AT 825) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if that old, familiar beast called the business cycle is
about to stir, woken by the turmoil on the U.S. share market, do
not expect the first decade of this century to be similar in other
ways to the last two decades of the previous one.
</P>
<P>
   We have all become accustomed to the idea that the cyclical
forces are the most important. Here in Britain the impact of the
business cycle has seared itself into our daily lives though its
impact on house prices.
</P>
<P>
   There are still people who bought homes in 1988 and have only
just emerged from negative equity on them. There are many people
who have fared even worse, losing their homes altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Other people found that they made more out of buying and selling
homes at the right time than they made out of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Like my dog-walking friend, we are all very sensitive to the
possibility of a share-price crash leading to a property price
one. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CONTINUES TO 1,050) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the next 10, maybe 20, years structural change is going to
be more important than cyclical change. We will still live in the
same sort of houses and drive similar cars. But in other ways _ in
particular in the ways we communicate and work _ our lives will
change utterly.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just that new companies that have not yet even been
formed will dominate the corporate league tables. Those league
tables may not matter much, as more and more people will work for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the railway boom. Successive waves of massive
investment during the 19th century created the railways, and
successive waves of investors either made fortunes or went bust.
</P>
<P>
   What we are seeing now is equivalent to the end of the first
railway boom. But the railways still got built, and that changed
the lives of humankind. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
