<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      04-06 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ANOTHER CHAPTER IN ABORTION POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sad but true: Politicians think the voters are so
dumb that they will be taken in by cheap stunts useful for campaign
sound bites but empty of real meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The latest example of this fakery is the House approval this
week of a ban on a controversial form of late-term abortion that
members know President Clinton will veto. He has already done so
twice.
</P>
<P>
   This was the third time in five years that Congress has tried to
get around the Supreme Court's limited protection of abortion
rights by focusing on a rarely used procedure that is frequently
described as gruesome.
</P>
<P>
   If advocates of the ban were really serious, they would have
approved a proposed exception to the ban if the pregnant woman's
health were endangered. That would not only have been the humane
course but it would have met the president's objections and
eliminated his veto threat.
</P>
<P>
   But no, the anti-abortion grandstanders weren't serious. They
wanted the world to hear that they were putting the preservation of
an unborn fetus ahead of protecting the well-being of the living
adult who is the potential mother. She might, they feared, merely
suffer depression or other mental illness, problems they had no
sympathy with. This cold-hearted attitude, they think, is good
politics. As a national policy, it is nuts.
</P>
<P>
   House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde, R-Ill, opposed
the exception because, he said, ``This is a debate about human
dignity.'' Whose dignity? Not that of the pregnant woman, who the
legislators insist should not have any say in the matter of her own
health.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-abortion forces call the procedure in question
``partial birth abortion,'' the better to make it sound horrible
and politically difficult to tolerate. Medically, it is known as
intact dilation and extraction, during which the skull is punctured
to allow a fetus that cannot yet live outside the womb to pass
though the cervix. Calling this a birth is a medical and legal
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   The current bill, similar to laws in 30 states, describes the
procedure so vaguely that the ban could technically apply to many
forms of abortion, even those in the first and second trimesters,
the most protected periods under the Constitution. Congress, in
fact, seems eager to provide an excuse to scare doctors away from
performing any legal abortion at all. The Senate has passed similar
legislation by a 63-34 vote, which fell short of the two-thirds
majority needed to override a presidential veto.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the issues before the nation, this does not deserve the
priority Congress gives it. The poohbahs on Capitol Hill find time
to invade the privacy of pregnant women but not to vote on the
important subjects the country really cares about, like Social
Security and education.
</P>
<P>
   The political purpose here is to posture before anti-abortion
activists in hopes of energizing them to cough up campaign cash and
turn out to vote. Only eight Republicans voted against the ban,
along with 132 Democrats and one independent; 209 Republicans voted
for it as well as 77 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt, D-Mo., to his shame,
voted for the ban. He is usually pro-choice, but he didn't have the
courage to test Missouri's anti-abortion mood these days.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the Supreme Court may be about to trump Congress on
the subject. On April 25 it will hear a Nebraska doctor's challenge
to that state's ban as unconstitutionally vague. Federal and state
courts around the country have reached contradictory rulings on the
legality of criminalizing the procedure, and the high bench will
now have the final say.
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that the court will rule such laws
invalid as a backdoor method of reversing Roe v. Wade, the 1973
decision that legalized abortion. When the court granted review of
the Nebraska case, it indicated that it would not revisit the basic
question of the constitutional status of abortion, meaning Roe v.
Wade is still the operating precedent.
</P>
<P>
   A Supreme Court ruling that so-called ``partial birth''
abortions are constitutionally protected would make congressional
action look silly _ like the recent failed legislative attempt to
reverse the court's insistence that flag burning is constitutional
free speech. Congress moved to get on the record before that could
happen. This latest abortion stunt is another pitiful indication
that political posturing, not serious legislating, is what such
votes are all about.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
