<HEADER>
A9164 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-NYT &LR;      04-06 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-ISRAEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARAB WORLD TRIES TO PREPARE FOR ISRAELI WITHDRAWAL FROM SOUTHERN
LEBANON 
</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon _ In a new sign of Arab unease, officials here
warned Thursday that they could not, and would not, prevent
Palestinian militants from using Lebanese territory to mount
attacks on Israel once its army withdraws unilaterally from
southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Emile Lahoud, the Lebanese president, said ``daily miniwars''
could break out along the border with Israel unless the United
Nations disarmed the Palestinian refugees living in miserable camps
scattered across Lebanon _ and unless it actively prevented Israeli
retaliation against any Palestinian operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether this disarming takes place or not,'' Lahoud said,
``what are the United Nations' guarantees that Israel will not
violate Lebanon's territorial and naval borders and its airspace or
carry out short-term attacks on the south and inside Lebanon?''
</P>
<P>
   The warning came in a rambling letter given to a U.N. envoy,
Terje Larsen, who met with Lahoud and other Lebanese officials
Thursday. Larsen is to go to the Syrian capital of Damascus on
Friday for more discussions about the planned Israeli withdrawal
and the possible role of U.N. forces in south Lebanon in connection
with the evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   Syria, which holds ultimate political and military power in
Lebanon, has maintained a stony silence in the weeks since Israel's
Cabinet endorsed the plan of Prime Minister Ehud Barak to end
Israel's 15-year occupation of a nine-mile-deep strip of southern
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   But Lebanese politicians, who generally take their cue from
Damascus, have reacted with a series of increasingly agitated
statements. This week, Defense Minister Ghazi Zueiter said Lebanon
might ask Syria to station its soldiers and missiles along the
border after a withdrawal. Syria immediately dismissed his
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Other officials have said an Israeli withdrawal would not meet
Lebanese demands unless one of three conditions was met: all
Palestinian refugees' being allowed to return to their homes;
Jerusalem's becoming the capital of a Palestinian state, or
Israel's abandoning Zionism. Those conditions were not part of the
Israeli-Syrian peace negotiations, which broke down in mid-January
and have yet to be resumed.
</P>
<P>
   In adding a condition that Palestinian refugees in Lebanon be
disarmed, Lahoud brought up a particularly touchy subject for his
small country, which suffered through a long and bitter civil war
that began as a backlash against Palestinian militants operating
from Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Over more than 15 years, Lebanese fought Lebanese and
Palestinians, Israel invaded and occupied parts of the country in a
drive to expel the Palestinians, and Syria moved its army into
Lebanon to battle Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Palestine Liberation Organization was eventually
forced out, some 400,000 Palestinian refugees remain in Lebanon.
They are not permitted to live outside their shabby camps, and all
of Lebanon's various political and religious factions vehemently
oppose giving them the privileges of permanent residents.
</P>
<P>
   The Lebanese army, with its many Christian and Muslim veterans
of the serial battles against Palestinians, does not even enter the
Palestinian camps. Syria, which has 35,000 soldiers in Lebanon, has
a few checkpoints outside of some camps, but it does not police
them either.
</P>
<P>
   The camps house a number of Palestinian factions that officially
reject the peace negotiations between the PLO leader, Yasser
Arafat, and Israel. But the leadership of those factions is based
in Damascus and relies on Syria, which for the past few years has
largely frozen subsidies and other support.
</P>
<P>
   In Damascus Thursday, the Syrian vice president, Abdel-Halim
Khaddam, summoned the leader of one of the rejectionist factions,
George Habash, for a brief meeting. But many Lebanese do not
believe that Syria would unleash its Palestinian clients to provoke
a new conflict after an Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Syria has no influence except over a very small number of
groups,'' said Hussein Husseini, a former Lebanese Parliament
speaker and Shiite Muslim leader. Palestinians in the refugee camps
do have weapons, he added, but disrupting the status quo by taking
them away would only end up destabilizing Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   The military rulers of south Lebanon _ the Hezbollah militia _
also expressed ambivalence. Nawaf Mousawi, a senior member of the
Hezbollah political bureau, said Lebanon had a right to demand U.N.
help in controlling the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is Lebanon going to assign a policeman for every person so
they don't move?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mousawi also indicated that Hezbollah _ supported by Syria
and hugely popular in the Arab world since it began to present
itself as a national resistance to Israel's occupation _ would not
actively aid in attacks on Israel once all of southern Lebanon was
in Lebanese hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's tension in the region, it could lead to an
explosion,'' he said, ``and it does not need Hezbollah
cooperation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
