<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9165 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-AIDS-FUNDING-$ADV09-H     04-06 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIDS-FUNDING-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CONGRESS TO WEIGH NEW RULE FOR RYAN WHITE AIDS MONEY  
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By JUDY HOLLAND   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress will be asked this week to change the way
the federal government spends $1.6 billion for AIDS care and
prevention, switching from a system that doles out dollars based on
full-blown AIDS cases toward one based on infection with the HIV
virus that leads to the disease.
</P>
<P>
   Public health officials argue that it doesn't make sense to
continue distributing federal money to states, cities, U.S.
territories and health service organizations based on tallies of
AIDS cases because new medical breakthroughs have greatly prolonged
the HIV stage of the disease. The result is that federal funding
goes primarily to places where the disease first emerged, leaving
areas with newer outbreaks with less funding.
</P>
<P>
   One effect of such a switch would be to cut the amount of money
going to areas with longer histories of the AIDS epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   About 300,000 people in the United States have AIDS, while
500,000 to 600,000 others are infected with the HIV virus but don't
yet have the usually fatal AIDS disease, according to estimates by
the federal Centers for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., an obstetrician who is introducing
legislation this week to authorize the switch, wants HIV _ not AIDS
_ to be the basis for federal funding by the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea is to emphasize prevention and make sure the
dollars go where the disease is,'' Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn says states and cities with relatively new outbreaks _
especially rural areas _ are not getting needed government
financial support because it may take 10 or more years for someone
infected with HIV to develop AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn says places like San Francisco, where the epidemic hit
nearly two decades ago, ``get a disproportionate amount of money''
because they have a higher percentage of AIDS cases compared with
cases of HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   Coburn's legislation would amend the Ryan White Care Act which
empowers the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services to pay
for care and medications for people who aren't poor or sick enough
to receive Medicaid, but who don't have private insurance. The Ryan
White program is named after the hemophiliac teenager from Kokomo,
Ind., who contracted the disease through tainted blood and died in
1990 at age 19. The program serves about a half million people each
year and, since 1991, has distributed $6.4 billion to states and
local governments on the basis of a federal formula that counts
AIDS cases but not cases of HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system that we built that provided the answers 10 years
ago, isn't providing the answers we need now,'' said Dr. Patricia
Fleming, chief of the HIV/AIDS Surveillance branch within CDC.
``The epidemic has changed and the surveillance system needs to
change too.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said scientists know from clinical trials that people
with HIV are surviving longer and that both the incidence of AIDS
and the death rate have declined. However, the states don't know
how many HIV cases are not progressing to AIDS, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming said she expects every state will have adopted an HIV
reporting system by the end of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires states to collect AIDS statistics from
healthcare providers. Any program that tracks HIV cases raises
concerns that the privacy of people with HIV could be placed in
jeopardy, harming their ability to remain productive and part of
the community.
</P>
<P>
   The Centers for Disease Control recommended last December that
state health officials report HIV cases as they now do with AIDS
cases. Currently, state health officials contact laboratories,
physicians and clinics to get reports of AIDS cases.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two states and the Virgin Islands now record HIV cases by
patient name. New York announced last week that it will begin
reporting HIV cases by name in June. Illinois, Maryland,
Massachusetts, Vermont and Puerto Rico use ``unique identifier''
codes to report HIV cases. Pennsylvania, California and Oregon have
yet to develop systems for tracking HIV cases.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McClain, a public health consultant who chairs the Care
Coalition, a group that represents cities and clinics seeking more
federal money for care and treatment of people with HIV, said using
HIV data would provide a more accurate measure of the rate of
infection. AIDS data tends to be out of date and ``always talking
about the past,'' McClain said.
</P>
<P>
   But McClain said accurate data wouldn't be available until
states have developed HIV counting methods that would guarantee
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   McClain said many people with HIV are afraid that their health
status could be ``outed'' accidentally to employers or family
members if it is federally recorded. ``It's a legitimate fear,'' he
said. ``Many people with HIV fear losing their jobs and health
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain said people with HIV fear being ``ostracized, isolated,
rejected and disowned, all at a time when you've just discovered
that you have HIV or AIDS We all recognize that using HIV (counts)
nationally would be the best thing, but socially, politically and
technically it's just not there.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Kelly, deputy director of the National Alliance of States
and Territorial AIDS directors, said the ``current system for
distributing federal AIDS dollars is inadequate in reflecting the
breadth of the epidemic, but the catch is, we're just not there in
terms of having HIV reporting everywhere in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get there soon, but we need to know that these
numbers are accurate and that we have confidence in our data
collection systems,'' Kelly said. ``When that happens, many of us
believe we should move to use HIV and AIDS as a basis for
distributing these Ryan White Care funds.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be reached at 202-298-6920 or by e-mail at
Judy(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
