<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9166 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0407-COX     04-06 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-ELIAN-0407-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ELIAN'S FATHER INTENT ON RECLAIMING SON, BUT WHEN REMAINS
UNCERTAIN
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With ELIAN-FAMILY-0407; ELIAN-SCENE-0407.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Forcing a legal and political showdown over the
fate of 6-year-old Cuban rafter Elian Gonzalez, his father arrived
here Thursday to reclaim his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am truly impatient to have (Elian) returned to me as soon as
possible and go back to Cuba together, immediately,'' Juan Miguel
Gonzalez said after his arrival at Dulles International Airport,
outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Miami, talks broke down between U.S. immigration
officials and attorneys for the Miami relatives who have cared for
Elian since he was found floating on an inner-tube off the Fort
Lauderdale coast on Thanksgiving Day. His mother, who was divorced
from Juan Miguel, drowned along with 10 others after fleeing Cuba
for the United States in a 16-foot motor boat.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the Miami family emerged after several hours of
negotiations Thursday expressing frustration and anger at federal
government insistence that Elian's custody be transferred from his
great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, to the father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government rejected the standard of the best interest of
the child as the guiding principle,'' Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, an
attorney for the family, said. ``The government will not guarantee
that it will not take Elian away, or try to take Elian away, in the
middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not had his day in court,'' he added. ``This is a very,
very sad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez is expected to meet Friday with Attorney General Janet
Reno, Immigration and Naturalization Service Commissioner Doris
Meissner and other officials.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Elian seemed unaware of the new phase in the struggle
over his future. He played on a slide outside his great-uncle's
home and fired a toy gun as the usual horde of reporters and
photographers took note.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives said he learned of his father's trip only hours before
it took place.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan Miguel said in a ``message to the American people''
after he arrived Thursday morning with his wife and 6-month-old son
_ Elian's half-brother _ that he was traveling with Elian's ``true
family.''
</P>
<P>
   He accused the Miami relatives of exploiting his son and
demanded a halt to the ``endless confusing legal procedures'' that
have separated them.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Gonzalez said he hoped to ``soon be able to embrace my
son'' after 137 days of what he described as cruel separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that the U.S. authorities will not allow my
child to continue to be hurt,'' Gonzalez said, adding that he still
hoped Elian's classmates, teachers and Cuban psychologists would be
allowed to come to this country to give him support while they wait
_ possibly months _ for a final federal appeals court decision.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokeswoman said Thursday no decision had
been reached on the request for 22 additional visas.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez' arrival in the United States increases the pressure on
the Clinton administration to resolve the thorny humanitarian,
legal and political issue that has drawn worldwide attention, and
caused the most recent conflict between the United States and the
Cuban regime of President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the administration
believes ``this is a positive step towards ultimately reuniting a
father with his son. That's what the courts have ruled. The father
coming here is a constructive way to facilitate that process.''
</P>
<P>
   The INS, declared early this year that Juan Miguel Gonzalez is
the only person legally authorized to speak for Elian on the
question of whether the child should remain in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives last month lost a federal suit to
overturn the INS ruling and grant them authority to seek asylum on
the child's behalf. That decision has been appealed the 11th
Circuit Court in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the Justice Department has allowed the Miami relatives
to retain custody of Elian, but Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder
told a Washington news conference Thursday that he expects the boy
to be reunited with his father ``in a relatively short period of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The father and the son need to be together and, in the coming
days, we will do everything we can to see that that happens,'' said
Holder, the father of a 6-year-old girl. ``I believe reuniting
Elian with his father is not only a matter of federal law . . . it
is simply the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday the delicate choreography over custody of the boy
remained jumbled, however.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's Miami relatives invited Juan Miguel to come to their
home to visit his son, but not take him away. Juan Miguel has
refused to go to Miami and instead insists that his son be brought
to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives also sought assurances that if Elian is
turned over to Juan Miguel, they will not to leave the country
until the appeal is resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel has indicated, through his attorney, Gregory B.
Craig that he would remain in the United States until the appeals
court rules. But Garcia-Pedrosa noted that federal officials would
not guarantee that Juan Miguel would remain.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel's family is staying at the residence of Fernando
Remirez, head of the Cuban Interests Section in nearby Bethesda,
Md. Remirez temporarily moved out of his home and waived its
diplomatic immunity, allegedly to lessen the appearance that the
father is under the control of communist Cuban authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, there was no movement on bills to grant Elian
either permanent residency status or U.S. citizenship. Both bills
would have the effect of removing the case from INS control and
putting it before a state family court. Vice President Al Gore
recently split with the Clinton administration in supporting the
permanent residency bill.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Republican from Miami, said she did
not anticipate any congressional action on the bills until the
appeals process has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Ros-Lehtinen who spoke by telephone with Lazaro Gonzalez _ and
with Elian _ Thursday morning, described the Miami family as
``pretty dug in'' over their insistence that Juan Miguel come to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami relatives also want Elian to be examined by three
psychologists to determine whether removing him _ particularly from
his cousin, 21-year-old Marisleysis Gonzalez who has been his
primary caretaker in the United States _ would be psychologically
harmful.
</P>
<P>
   But Juan Miguel Gonzalez said his son ``has had to spend time
under the temporary custody of some distant relatives who had never
seen him before.'' He said the Miami relatives harassed Elian when
the father would call him from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an agonizing experience to see my son submitted to
cruel psychological pressures aimed at influencing his
personality,'' Juan Miguel said, speaking through an interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel also charged that ``Elian has been paraded and
exhibited in public rallies and by the media with a clear intent to
obtain political advantage from this tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Cox Newspapers correspondents Sue Schultz, and Eunice Moscoso
contributed to this story from Washington. Caribbean/Latin America
correspondent Mike Williams contributed from Miami.)
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
