<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9181 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-SC-FLAG07-COX     04-06 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    400 flag protesters arrive in South Carolina capital
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ A five-day march that started 120 miles away in
Charleston to protest the Confederate battle flag flying over the
Statehouse dome culminated Thursday in a contest of sloganeering
and posturing.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Charleston Mayor Joe Riley, who organized the Get
in Step with the People of South Carolina March, displayed bumper
stickers demanding ``Take It Down.'' Riley and an estimated 400
marchers arrived about noon on the south side of the Capitol, where
they were greeted by Gov. Jim Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   On the north side of the Capitol, hundreds of Confederate battle
flags _ with the distinctive blue X and white stars criss-crossing
over a bright red background _ flew in opposition to Riley and
Hodges. A small plane towed a banner: Keep the Flag. Dump Riley and
Hodges.
</P>
<P>
   Joining those opposed to flying the flag over the Statehouse was
former Gov. David Beasley, who stood on the Capitol steps with
Riley. A Republican, Beasley lost to Hodges in 1998, partly because
he urged legislators to move the battle emblem to historic grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must, as South Carolinians, move forward and get this issue
resolved, and we must move the flag from the dome,'' Hodges told
the crowd. ``I don't know about you, but frankly I'm tired of the
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the march, neither chamber in the state Legislature had
made progress on bills before them that would remove the
controversial Civil War emblem from flying over the Statehouse
dome.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, though, the state Senate took a small step and
agreed to set a flag bill on priority status for floor debate,
possibly on April 12.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview after the march Thursday, Senate Majority Leader
John Land, a Democrat from Manning, said he's optimistic a
compromise will be worked out before the June 1 adjournment and
that it will include die-hard flag supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will end quicker than you think,'' Land said. ``I think
the march must have had some effect. Here's a man who walked 120
miles. That had to have an impact. David Beasley was up there. You
talk about healing. That's very symbolic.''
</P>
<P>
   Land said he's certain the compromise will be supported by
Republican Glenn McConnell, a Charleston senator and one of the
staunchest flag backers. If McConnell does come on board with a
compromise, ``It'll be over,'' Land said.
</P>
<P>
   The state House has vowed to debate nothing until the Senate
sends it a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is beginning to become a major factor,'' said House
Speaker David Wilkins. The Greenville Republican has been pressured
to move the flag by Michelin and BMW, two of the top businesses in
his district. ``I'm still hopeful we can work something out. But I
also know the clock is ticking.''
</P>
<P>
   On New Year's Day, the national NAACP formally launched a
tourism boycott of South Carolina. The NAACP said the boycott,
which was begun by the state chapter last summer, has cost the
state at least $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Convention and visitor bureaus in the state have reported losses
of nearly $10 million in canceled meetings, though tourism
officials say exact numbers on the boycott's impact are impossible
to calculate.
</P>
<P>
   Among those demonstrating Thursday in support of flying the flag
was Pamela Ridings, a 47-year-old secretary from Columbia, who held
up a homemade sign: God Save the South. She complained that outside
groups, namely the NAACP, are unduly pressuring South Carolina
lawmakers to bow to their wishes. Further, she said retirees from
up North are trying to change the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not from up there,'' Ridings said. ``Don't take over our
rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridings, whose face turned pink in the bright noon sun, said few
of the South Carolinians who fought in the Civil War actually owned
slaves and were just ``working stiffs like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the other counterprotesters gathered Thursday, 37-year-old
James Boland said the flag is part of the South's heritage. He
dressed in a $300 wool replica of the cadet blue uniform worn by
Confederate generals and waved a battle flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both sides were American,'' said Boland, who took a day off
from his job of making fishing line for a local manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the Capitol, Riley told the crowd that the
heritage of the flag comes from a time long, long ago that is no
longer part of South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said he received an unsigned letter that promised to put
him in a gunsight. Another protester, the mayor said, displayed a
bumper sticker that read ``John Rocker for President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not heritage, that is hate,'' Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   Winston McCuen, 38, drove from Greenville in support of the
flag. A private school in Greenville fired him from his job as an
American history professor because he refused to remove a small
battle flag from his desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina has a history of resisting tyranny,'' said
McCuen, now a welder. He carried a $10 rebel flag with the logo ``I
ain't coming down.'' McCuen hung his flag from a flagstaff made of
metal wiring conduit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tired of being put down by our overlords in Washington
and here in Columbia,'' McCuen said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
