<SLUG> BC-VAIN-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSULTANT BAIN IN E-COMMERCE VENTURE CAPITAL PARTNERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The consulting firm Bain &AMP; Co. has formed a partnership
with venture capital giants Kleiner Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers to
help large non-US companies expand into e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, called eVolution Global Partners, will be based in
London. James Allen, former director of Bain's London office, will
be CEO of the new group.
</P>
<P>
   Bain and Silicon Valley's Kleiner Perkins will invest equally in
the new company, along with some partners of Texas Pacific Group, a
Fort Worth-based private equity investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   John Donahoe, worldwide managing director of Bain, said there's
huge demand from consulting clients for strategies on getting onto
the Web. The firm aims to help multinational companies take
advantage of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Bain side, we have been hearing from our clients for a
year on how to best leverage their assets . . . to use the power of
the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kleiner Perkins, the renowned venture capital shop, this is
a first foray overseas. Brook Byers, a partner at the firm, said
the joint venture is the best way for Kleiner Perkins to take
advantage of opportunities in Europe, Asia, and Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   David Barry, senior editor of the Private Equity Analyst in
Wellesley, said the Silicon Valley cowboys are attempting to take
their business to Europe now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to do Europe right, you'd better have an
office there _ and have people who know how things work there,''
Barry said. While Kleiner brings its know-how in start-up
businesses and technology to this new venture, he said, it's also
``a way for Kleiner to get a foot in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Pacific is experienced in leveraged buyouts and
large-scale transactions, Barry said. The firm also has experience
overseas, as does Bain, which consults to companies around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership is unusual in that it melds consulting and
investment interests. Consultants have increasingly been jumping
into the venture business on their own. Andersen Consulting and
Deloitte &AMP; Touche have both launched large venture funds. Bain
itself has an incubator for start-ups, bainlab.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1913EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0363 </DOCNO>
