<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9184 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RETAL-SALES-BOS &LR;      04-06 0549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAL-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE EASTER TRIMS MARCH RETAIL GAINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because of this year's late Easter US retailers eked out one of
their smallest monthly gains since 1996, but most analysts said
they found little hard evidence in March retail sales that
consumers have reined in their free-spending ways.
</P>
<P>
   That could change in April. Higher gas prices, higher interest
rates, and a gyrating stock market could persuade consumers to
delay some purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But at the moment, ``there's not one scintilla of evidence that
consumer spending is slowing down,'' said Kurt Barnard, president
of Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   At Talbots Inc., known for classic women's apparel, March sales
at stores open at least a year were up a whopping 17.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Talbots said Thursday it expects its first-quarter
earnings to exceed Wall Street's estimates. Now some analysts think
Talbots could beat last year's first-quarter earnings by 40
percent. On the New York Stock Exchange, Talbots shares rose
$2.3125 to close at $60.1875.
</P>
<P>
   Talbots customers remain ``enthusiastic about our spring line,''
said president and chief executive Arnold B. Zetcher.
</P>
<P>
   Not all that long ago, Talbots was routinely disappointing
investors; now Talbots is exceeding Wall Street's expectations on a
regular basis, said Charles L. Hill, director of research at First
Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman Marcus Group, a luxury retailer, also had a big month.
Sales at stores open at least a year were up 16.3 percent in March.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Easter, a big shopping event, fell three weeks
earlier, and that meant strong sales in March.
</P>
<P>
   With Easter coming on April 23 this year, most Easter shopping
is expected to occur this month. To get a true picture of spring
retail sales, the two months of March and April need to be looked
at together and compared with the same two-month period last year,
said PaineWebber analyst Richard E. Jaffe.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, this year's March sales looked somewhat anemic
in comparison to March 1999, but analysts warned against jumping to
conclusions until April numbers are available.
</P>
<P>
   In gauging consumer spending, retail analysts look to a measure
called same-store sales _ that is, sales at stores open at least a
year.
</P>
<P>
   At BJ's Wholesale Club Inc., March same-store sales rose 4.4
percent, boosted by brisk demand for spring seasonal merchandise,
jewelry, housewares, computer equipment, and health and beauty
aids, said president and chief executive Jack Nugent.
</P>
<P>
   The TJX Cos., which operate T.J. Maxx and Marshalls, saw
same-store sales rise 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the late Easter, TJX chairman and chief executive Bernard
Cammarata said, ``We look forward to a very strong first quarter
and remain very confident in our ability to deliver on our
objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradlees Inc., the discount department store chain, said March
same-store sales fell 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the Easter shift, Bradlees expected sales to be lower
this March, said Peter Thorner, Bradlees chairman and chief
executive. ``When taken together, we believe that March and April
sales results will reflect the continued growth and strength of our
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1915EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0364 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9187 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BLEDSOE-WEB-BOS &LR;      04-06 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLEDSOE-WEB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE FIELDS INTERNET SERVICE PROVIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (s and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ He does not own a car dealership or a
restaurant. Drew Bledsoe's outside activity is the Drew Bledsoe
Foundation, a nonprofit education organization that focuses on good
parenting.
</P>
<P>
   Its offices are now in Rodman Park, about one mile south of
Foxboro Stadium, where Thursday Bledsoe became the first big-name
professional athlete to begin an Internet service provider
(Bledsoenet.com), with most of the proceeds going to fund the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   While Bledsoe also commented on issues such as the Patriots' new
uniforms, the new offense, the team, and his contract, the day was
really to launch his business venture. There's an ironic twist to
the venture. Bledsoe was burned by the very medium that he is now a
part of _ the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Late last season, an Internet rumor concerning his personal life
was picked up by local radio stations, which caused the quarterback
considerable anguish and led him to wonder how a rumor could
suddenly be legitimized in the mainstream media.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience with the Internet was a bit uncomfortable to say
the least,'' said Bledsoe. ``You can't control what is out there
and what your children have access to. That's a major reason we
started Bledsoenet.com, so that parents of young kids can have a
certain level of comfort knowing what they have access to is
filtered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, you can't control everything that comes across. We
will specifically filter out pornography, bomb-making recipes,
hate-crime type of things. They'll be filtered out through our
filtering service. The second reason is to fund our foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe, flanked by foundation CEO Don Berube, said the filtered
service would cost $19.95 per month while unfiltered service would
cost $17.95. Start up will be explained on the Bledsoenet.com Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   Berube said the service would soon provide DSL service.
</P>
<P>
   ``As my kids grow up, I'd like to have some certainty and
comfort that Stu (Bledsoe's oldest son) can't just pull up porno
sites and bomb-making recipes,'' said Bledsoe. ``There are many
other ways he'll get into trouble without having easy access to
anything he wants to get to. The filtering service is done through
a third party which is updated hourly, and they're constantly
filtering out sites that are not appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a proactive reaction to what happened to me. If
somebody is going to send out an e-mail starting rumors about
somebody, we're obviously not going to be able to control that. But
what happened to me last year was eye-opening in that while the
Internet is a great resource, and while it is the wave of the
future, there are downsides to it in that everybody can put
anything out there. This was important to me as a parent.''
</P>
<P>
   After the rumor surfaced, Bledsoe threatened to sue those who
broadcast it, but now says that's less likely.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe considered himself a ``computer nerd'' when he was in
college, but he said he got away from it until his wife, Maura,
bought him a laptop for Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's currently trying to enroll some of his teammates,
and has already taken much ribbing. He said right guard Todd Rucci
now writes ``ToddRucci(at)Bledsoenet.com'' on his e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Concerning his full-time job, Bledsoe said he likes the new
uniforms (darker blue) and added there's even a ``Monday Night
Football'' uniform that would include the navy blue jersey and navy
blue pants.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe said there was nothing new with his contract extension
and said, ``The contract I signed I'm perfectly happy to play that
out. There are no monetary reasons to redo it, but if it gives us
more leeway to signing free agents, I would do it.''
</P>
<P>
   His preliminary meeting with new offensive coordinator Charlie
Weis has also given him reason for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have more formations, spread the field out more
on early downs, and what that does is spread the defense out,''
Bledsoe said. ``That will allow me to determine what the defense is
trying to do to me right away. When you're in a base formation, the
defenses can give you all of their exotic coverages and all their
disguises. When you spread the field, they have to declare what
they're going to do. Hopefully it'll help our running game a little
bit.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9188 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CENSUS-RESPONSE-HNS &LR;      04-06 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-RESPONSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CENSUS OFFICIALS OPTIMISTIC ABOUT MAIL-IN RESPONSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By AUSTIN ZALKIN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Census Bureau officials said Thursday they will
meet and possibly exceed their goal of a 61 percent mail-in
response to the forms they sent to 120 million households last
month.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, the response stood at 58 percent. The bureau has
set a minimum goal of 61 percent and a maximum target of 70 percent
before Census officials begin making house calls to non-respondents
on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Despite public debate about privacy and the personal nature of
some questions, the response was higher than at the comparable time
in 1990, when 49 percent of the public had responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are expecting, hoping that by the weekend we will cross the
61 percent mark,'' Census Bureau director Kenneth Prewitt told a
House Appropriations subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautiously optimistic that we will get better than 65
percent,'' Edison Gore, the bureau's assistant division chief for
field programs, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   However, criticism of the 53-item questionnaire that was mailed
to 20 million households may have lowered the return rate for those
forms.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks several Republican leaders have objected to
census questions that some of their constituents had complained
about, particularly those on the long form.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the presumptive GOP presidential
nominee, said last week he might not answer all of the questions on
the long form if it were mailed to him. And Senate Majority Leader
Trent Lott, R-Miss., encouraged people to leave blank any questions
they felt invaded their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   As of Wednesday, 60 percent of the recipients of the
six-question short form had responded while 48 percent had returned
the long form. In 1990, the last census, 66 percent answered the
short form and 60 percent returned the long form.
</P>
<P>
   Mail-in responses have declined dramatically from 1970, when 80
percent responded. The bureau chose the 61 percent response target
for this year based on an expectation of further declining rates,
Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Census officials privately expressed concern in March that they
might not meet the minimum target, but are now heartened by the
response so far.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the bureau projected a lower response than in 1990,
it challenged cities and states to encourage residents to
participate in the census. The census is used as a basis for
apportioning federal aid and in congressional districting.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990 census forms were mailed on March 23 and officials began
door-to-door visits for non-respondents on April 26. This year
mailings began March 13 and officials will begin to canvass homes
on April 27.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, 21 days remained until census workers begin
their visits. In 1990, with the same number of days remaining
before the home visits, the response rate was 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   (Austin Zalkin can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
dart(at)hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
