<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9194 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l BC-RAVE4JESUS-AZR &LR;      04-06 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAVE4JESUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHRISTIAN DEEJAYS TRY CONVERTING THROUGH TECHNO MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Gilbert randomly bleaches the spiky ends of his dark hair
before dyeing them a reddish color. He wears old jeans, a T-shirt
and skater shoes. He fits on Mill Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Which is where he was hanging out when he heard street preachers
ranting at two punk rockers: Judgment Day's coming. Look at how
you're dressed. You must be sinners. You're going to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the street preacher started ripping into him.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, a deejay who spins electronic and house music, believes
in Jesus. He wants the punk rockers to believe, too, but this isn't
the way. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Late on a Friday night, a crowd gathers at The Icehouse in
downtown Phoenix. Two girls with butterfly wings, blue body paint
and not much else stand on the sidewalk waiting for the doors to
open for the rave. They are joined by other teenagers and young
adults. The scent of clove cigarettes fills the air.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Cottier passes out bottles of water with labels that read
``Without love there is nothing,'' and include the Urban Ministry
of Sound's e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, is that free water? Can I have one?'' asks a guy with a
stud just below his lip. They stop and talk. Cottier gives the guy,
who just moved from Seattle, a bottle of water and his phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   For Cottier and the rest of the Valley techno musicians and
deejays who make up the Urban Ministry of Sound, this is the way to
Jesus. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, Cottier and the others go where most
wear-a-tie-to-church people would be uncomfortable _ bars, skate
parks and raves _ to play their music, pass out water and make
friends.
</P>
<P>
   They all have day jobs but their music is good _ mixes by
Cottier and Gilbert have hit the top spots on secular and Christian
dance charts here and in Europe, and the songs have been featured
on CD compilations.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Harold and Geoff Wilcoxin, who perform original electronic
keyboard music as mint, are working on a contract with a secular
recording company. NSoul Records will be producing and distributing
an album of dance music from all the members of Urban Ministry of
Sound through such outlets as Target and Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath their rhythms is a desire to build real friendships
with the teens and young adults, and let them know this: Jesus
loves you no matter what you look like or what kind of music you
like.
</P>
<P>
   The group spent more than a year finding its niche. Dance
parties were held at some Valley churches, but church officials
didn't appreciate the drinking and smoking in the parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are in several venues, mostly secular. None of the
music is ``Christian,'' but it is positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all got the idea that God wanted us to go to the people
instead of coaxing them to come to us,'' Cottier says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's idea of a Christian is Channel 21,'' he says,
referring to the Christian TV station.
</P>
<P>
   These guys are anything but Channel 21. Outside the rave Cottier
gives out water while inside Wilcoxin and Harold play.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Routh, 19, of Mesa likes mint and says it doesn't matter
if the group is Christian.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they feel good about their music and as long as
they are into the grooves and everyone else can feel it, that's all
it takes,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Urban Ministry of Sound's ideas of love and acceptance play well
with the scene, where the crowd is used to insults _ like the punk
rockers on Mill Avenue _ from the established church.
</P>
<P>
   Some pastors are beginning to see the value in this kind of
ministry, says Scott Blackwell, a deejay/mixer/producer who founded
NSoul Records and is president of MYX, a Christian dance label. He
lives in LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are starting to realize the gap between the church and
youth culture is so wide that they need to rethink
evangelization,'' he says. ``The real ministry comes with the
lifestyles.''
</P>
<P>
   Groups like Urban Ministry of Sound are popping up all over the
country, the second generation of musicians who first pioneered
dance music in the Christian community over protests the music was
the devil's beat, Blackwell says.
</P>
<P>
   The going is slow, but Urban Ministry of Sound has seen some
results, as in this e-mail from a Goth kid in New Mexico: ``You
said that Jesus's love is the only thing that mattered. You were so
right and you knew that if I accepted him then the other garbage
would fall away. I have even begun to use my real name again.
Talked to my parents last weekend, first time in four months.''
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth Sunday of the month, the Urban Ministry of Sound
hosts an X-treme Worship Service at Lifeline Community Church in
Phoenix. Except for the lyrics and the absence of cigarette smoke,
the beat and the lighting invoke the atmosphere of a dance party.
</P>
<P>
   It's a different experience for those who didn't think church
could be hip.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the music at the skate park, some boys from a
group home have attended services there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are cool with them. They don't have to be us. They don't
have to act like us,'' says Dorie Anderson, Lifeline's associate
pastor for youth, college and career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traditionally, these are the kids who need the help the most,
and there's nobody who will relate to them and touch their lives.
They are too shook up about the paraphernalia and the piercings.
That has nothing to do with the person.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the hope of Urban Ministry of Sound: More churchgoers
will be accepting and more people who have given up on their
parents' God will find a God.
</P>
<P>
   In Heaven, says Cottier, ``I could see this totally
purple-haired, body-pierced guy saying, `Man, you don't know me but
. . .'' &QL; 
Reach the reporter at Kelly.Ettenborough(at)ArizonaRepublic.com or
at (602) 444-7728. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
