<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday April 7. If you have
any questions, please call The Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
PHONES (Undated) - In one of the hottest housing markets in the
country, there's no guarantee your new home will come with a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Phoenix area, growth is outpacing the telephone
infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   In outlying high growth areas such as Gold Canyon and Queen
Creek, new homeowners are being told by US West they may have to
wait months for telephone service. Residents of new subdivisions in
the west Valley, Chandler, north Scottsdale and north Phoenix are
hearing the same story, the Arizona Corporation Commission reports.
By MAX JARMAN. Story will move in the `A` category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RAVE4JESUS (Phoenix) - Late on a Friday night, a crowd gathers at
The Icehouse in downtown Phoenix. Two girls with butterfly wings,
blue body paint and not much else stand on the sidewalk waiting for
the doors to open for the rave. They are joined by other teenagers
and young adults. The scent of clove cigarettes fills the air.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Cottier passes out bottles of water with labels that read
``Without love there is nothing,'' and include the Urban Ministry
of Sound's e-mail address.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, is that free water? Can I have one?'' asks a guy with a
stud just below his lip. They stop and talk. Cottier gives the guy,
who just moved from Seattle, a bottle of water and his phone
number.
</P>
<P>
   For Cottier and the rest of the Valley techno musicians and
deejays who make up the Urban Ministry of Sound, this is the way to
Jesus. By KELLY ETTENBOROUGH. Story moved in the `L` category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
