<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9214 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CARTER-0407-COX     04-06 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTER-0407-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON HOSTS CARTERS DURING NOSTALGIC WHITE HOUSE EVENING
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One leader's trip down memory lane was another's
glimpse into the not-too-distant future Wednesday night when
President Clinton hosted former President Jimmy Carter for a
private dinner and a personal tour at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by his wife Rosalynn and their daughter Amy, Carter
dropped in with half a dozen of the couple's 13 grandchildren in
tow to take them on a long-promised walk-through of the Georgians'
former digs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was so taken by the assemblage that he spent nearly two
hours with the Carter clan _ deferring a flight to his new private
residence in Chappaqua, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton overnighted in Chappaqua with First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton, who is spending most of her time in New York campaigning
for a U.S. Senate seat, before returning to the White House on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   President and Mrs. Carter, meanwhile, slept at the White House
in what must have been a nostalgic visit to the place they lived in
from 1977 until 1981.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he finally lifted off of the White House lawn aboard
Marine One, the presidential helicopter, Clinton received a unique
send-off: the Carter entourage waving from the balcony above the
portico overlooking the South Lawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Carter had promised his grandchildren a tour of the
residence and the White House, and the president, I think, hung
around a little bit later than expected last night to make sure
that he could lead it
</P>
<P>
   personally,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed by reporters _ some of whom stood by looking at their
watches the previous night before Clinton's long-delayed departure
_ Lockhart shrugged, ``Yeah, well, it's a big building.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, dressed in a blue check shirt, dark blazer and gray
slacks, and Mrs. Carter, in a tan trench coat, had plenty of time
to amble about their former quarters.
</P>
<P>
   No official notetakers were on hand, but it's hard to imagine
that the subject of life after the presidency wasn't on both men's
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Carter has distinguished himself in his presidential afterlife
with global missions centered on peacekeeping, democratization and
ridding the developing world of disease and hunger. He's provided
an ambitious template for Clinton, who has yet to crystallize his
own plans for life after he leaves office in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has said he's started to appreciate the role
ex-presidents play in American culture,'' one White House official
said, conceding that the subject was a likely topic of conversation
between the two men.
</P>
<P>
   It's probable also that the group lingered over rooms and
furnishings that connect the two administrations, perhaps none more
so than the 19th Century walnut conference table used by both men
for signings of historic Mideast peace agreements.
</P>
<P>
   Carter had the table _ commissioned by President Ulysses S.
Grant _ hauled out to the front lawn bordering Pennsylvania Ave.
for the inking of the Israeli-Egyptian Camp David accords in 1979.
Clinton placed it on the South Lawn for the signing of
Israeli-Palestinian agreements in 1993, and again the next year for
an Israeli-Jordanian peace accord.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton treated the Carters to an impromptu dinner in the White
House solarium, a room on the private third-floor of the
presidential living quarters. Favored by Mrs. Clinton for reading
and study, the airy room was dubbed the ``sky parlor'' early last
century by former First Lady Grace Anna Goodhue Coolidge.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Carter's own marks can still be seen. An active advocate of
the American arts, she was instrumental in securing the private
donations of some two dozen paintings still hanging in the White
House. On her watch, also, workers began carefully chipping away at
42 coats of paint that had begun to obscure hand carvings in much
of the stone work there.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Clinton and Carter _ the only two Democrats to
occupy the White House over the past three decades _ have been
strained at times.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, a devout Christian who still teaches Sunday school in
his tiny hometown of Plains, Ga., has a personal image somewhat
different from that of Clinton, whose relationship with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky threw the institution into 15
months of turmoil and impeachment proceedings that ended with his
acquittal last year.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans can be reached by e-mail at: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
