<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-STUDENTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CITY RELEASES DETAINEES AFTER DEADLY CLASH AT COLLEGE CAMPUS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ALISON GREGOR  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MATAMOROS, Mexico _ Fifteen college students, teachers and
administrators were released from jail here late Thursday after a
clash with police that left one officer dead and several other
people wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, hundreds of students at the Matamoros Institute of
Technology were rallying on the campus in preparation for a march
on City Hall to demand the release of their colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Matamoros officials meeting at City Hall had given little
indication they would release the detainees. They said they turned
the investigation of Wednesday's confrontation over to the state
attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city government demands strict application of the law, and
it will support totally any decision by the state,'' Matamoros
Mayor Homar Zamorano Ayala said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the attorney general's office could not be
reached for comment. Zamorano said he regretted the events of
Wednesday evening, when, he alleged, a large group of police
officers was attacked by students on the campus resulting what the
authorities said was the beating death of the policeman, identified
as Manuel Davila Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor was not available reached for comment after students
were released.
</P>
<P>
   Students at the technical college, which has an enrollment of
1,500, told a different story than that given by city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Engineering student Daniel Flores said a minor traffic accident
between a college student and the son of a police commander
triggered the confrontation. The police were unfairly and
inaccurately blaming the college student for the mishap, Flores
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the fault of the police officer's son,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police, a group of students came to the police
station looking for justice Wednesday afternoon, and ended up
commandeering a patrol car. They drove it back to the campus where
it was set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Students also set at least one other vehicle on fire, the police
said. Students admitted burning the patrol car, which has been done
as a sign of protest in the past. But they said they did not
provoke the confrontation that ensued.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Manuel Garcia Reyna, the head of one of the college's
engineering divisions, said about 150 police and transit officers
showed up at the campus gate Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Unprovoked, they entered and began beating the 30 or so students
and bystanders present with clubs and pelting them with stones,
Garcia said. The officers broke car windows, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no call for this kind of force,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   The violence continued unchecked until the 15 individuals,
including the college's director, Nicolas Baca Cisneros, were
arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said about 10 people were treated for injuries, including
a teacher who was severely beaten on the head. Engineering
professor Claudio Alcala de Salinas showed up for a news conference
Thursday with bruises and cuts to his face and lacerations in his
scalp, saying he was the one who was beaten by the police.
</P>
<P>
   The police attacked people indiscriminately, Garcia said,
including a student who was five months pregnant. She fled.
</P>
<P>
   It was near the end of the police attack that Davila clutched
his chest and fell to the ground, apparently suffering a heart
attack, according to one student witness.
</P>
<P>
   However, a photograph of Davila in Thursday's edition of El
Bravo showed a body with lacerations and contusions on the face.
</P>
<P>
   One administrator at the college, who did not identify himself,
said Davila was not injured, nor did he die on the college campus.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said that eight months ago the police also showed up at
the campus, but they resolved their problems in talks with
administrators that time.
</P>
<P>
   Flores said there is a long history of hostility between the
students and local police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very different,'' he said. ``Some of them can't read,
and they can't write.''
</P>
</TEXT>
