<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEN-DAVISCUP07-COX     04-06 0465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McEnroe's drive leading U.S. team
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The late Harry Hopman was the life's blood
of Australia's 16 championship teams in the 1950s and '60s. No
other Davis Cup captain had assumed the same stature as his
superstar players.
</P>
<P>
   Then came John McEnroe.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1995, Andre Agassi and Pete Sampras
will be Davis Cup teammates, when the U.S. meets the Czech Republic
in a quarterfinal that begins today.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, the rookie captain who brought together these reluctant
patriots, is no less vital for what has become at least a mild U.S.
resurgence in Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   His first asset is star quality, and his second gift is the
respect of his players. Not to say that he can't bruise an ego.
After Sampras withrdrew injured from the U.S. team in the first
round, McEnroe said he thought that Sampras did not want to go to
Zimbabwe in the first place. They've since made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to bring Davis Cup to the forefront and make people
think about Davis Cup,'' McEnroe said. ``And it's critical that the
best players play.''
</P>
<P>
   For Sampras, McEnroe actually needed little persuasion, although
Sampras hasn't played Davis Cup singles in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't be remembered when my career was done (for) how often
I was No. 1,'' Sampras said. ``It's time to find the motivation to
do some other things. Davis Cup fits right in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, on the other hand, didn't come so easily. He has been a
Davis Cup warrior over the years, once winning a U.S.-record 16
matches in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he bolted the team last year with harsh words for
then-president of the USTA Harry Marmion. Agassi accused Marmion of
ignoring the players' feelings in site selection and in the firing
of the team doctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like it really wasn't much of a team anymore,'' Agassi
said. ``I want to be able to make decisions with the team that are
important to the team, and that starts with our captain.''
</P>
<P>
   When new USTA President Judy Levering's tenure began Jan. 1, she
immediately asked what the players wanted.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe was in, replacing Tom Gullikson. Even though Gullikson
had been a well-liked captain, he couldn't secure top U.S. players
for the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's sudden emergence as a USTA authority figure is not
without irony. As a player in 1985, McEnroe essentially was banned
from the team by then-USTA President Randy Gregson for his churlish
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Levering said she has not given McEnroe's history a second
thought since hiring him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been very impressed with John's passion,''
Levering said. ``That's something you can't buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
