<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9224 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-RUMBLE-FILM-REVIEW-NY     04-06 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUMBLE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`READY TO RUMBLE': WALLOWING IN THE WORLD OF WRESTLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Ready to Rumble'' is a courageous, devastating expose of the
brutality, misogyny and homophobia that pervade the so-called sport
of professional wrestling. The film goes to shocking lengths to
show how this wildly popular form of entertainment transforms its
young male fans into uncouth, slack-jawed dolts who think that
punching women in the face is an acceptable mode of foreplay, and
who are entirely unable to distinguish fantasy from reality. The
movie also explores, with candor and sensitivity, the undercurrent
of sado-masochistic homoeroticism that has made wrestling a
big-money attraction for the whole family.
</P>
<P>
   Just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Brian Robbins' ``Ready to Rumble'' is not a satire of
the idiocy of professional wrestling, but a long, self-satisfied
wallow in it. The film was made with the cooperation of World
Championship Wrestling, an organization whose logo is much in
evidence and several of whose real-life stars (if that's the right
phrase) turn up to break chairs over other people's heads. Compared
to WCW, the better-known World Wrestling Federation looks downright
highbrow; after all, the WWF has recently been the subject of a
documentary, a word few of the characters in ``Ready to Rumble''
are probably able to spell.
</P>
<P>
   You may say I'm missing the point. Everyone knows pro wrestling
is fake, everyone knows it's stupid, and that's part of the fun.
Well, far be it from me to stand against the atrophy of human
intelligence, but ``Ready to Rumble'' is not much fun at all.
</P>
<P>
   It stars David Arquette and Scott Caan as Gordie and Sean, a
pair of portable-toilet maintenance workers dumbed down from the
``Bill and Ted'' movies of an earlier, more sophisticated age.
Gordie and Sean's line of work provides the film's first half with
its big laughs, including a high-concept highway accident involving
their sewage-filled tanker truck and an 18-wheeler carrying a big
load of toilet paper. It's downhill from there. Soon Sean and
Gordie have embarked on a crusade to save the career of their hero,
a bulky WCW figurehead named Jimmy King (Oliver Platt). To call
their plans (or the script) harebrained is to insult the cognitive
ability of rabbits. Suffice it to say that the plot calls for
smackdowns aplenty, and a climactic triple-cage death match at the
MGM Grand in Las Vegas. If you don't know what these terms mean,
consider yourself lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Adding insult to a great many injuries (some of which look as if
they really hurt) is the spectacle of Platt, always a good sport,
singing Run DMC's ``King of Rock'' wearing a studded black leather
body suit and a gimcrack crown. And then there is the Oscar winner
Martin Landau delivering whippings to anyone who crosses his path.
These men are good actors, as is Joe Pantoliano, who plays a
villainous WCW impresario. Let's hope that they got their money up
front, and that the winsome Rose McGowan, playing a ``Nitro Girl''
exotic dancer who is briefly Gordy's love interest, manages to
forget she was ever mixed up in a movie in which the only thing
women are called upon to do is strip down to their underwear.
</P>
<P>
   As the credits roll, ``Ready to Rumble'' runs the now-obligatory
blooper reel, which is indistinguishable from what has come before
and leaves the disturbing impression that Arquette may not have
been acting at all. At the end we are treated to a montage of kicks
to various groins, a perfect expression of the film's idea of humor
and its opinion of its audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think a loser would have tickets to the championship?''
Gordie taunts a stuck-up french fry slinger named Brittany, played
by Jill Ritchie, early in the action. Brittany's incisive response
is ``yes.'' It's the smartest line in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `READY TO RUMBLE'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brian Robbins; written by Steven Brill, based on
World Championship Wrestling characters; director of photography,
Clark Mathis; edited by Ned Bastille; music by George S. Clinton;
production designer, Jaymes Hinkle; produced by Bobby Newmyer and
Jeffrey Silver; released by Warner Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: David Arquette (Gordie Boggs), Oliver Platt (Jimmy King),
Scott Caan (Sean Dawkins), Bill Goldberg (Goldberg), Rose McGowan
(Sasha), Diamond Dallas Page (himself), Joe Pantoliano (Titus
Sinclair), Martin Landau (Sal) and Jill Ritchie (Brittany). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 107 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ready to Rumble'' is rated PG-13 (Parents strongly cautioned).
It has nonstop mayhem, profanities uttered both in affection and in
anger, and a sense of humor that might be politely described as
excremental.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 1944EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
