<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GENOME-SEQUENCE-BOS &LR;      04-06 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENOME-SEQUENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US-FUNDED LAB DISPUTES CLAIM THAT HUMAN GENE IS DECIPHERED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Another dispute over deciphering the human genetic blueprint
broke out Thursday, with Celera Genomics Inc. telling Congress it
had identified all the DNA ``letters'' in a single human blueprint
and a government scientist calling the claim a ``nonstory.''
</P>
<P>
   The claim was made by J. Craig Venter, founder of the Rockville,
Md., company that is racing to decipher the human DNA blueprint _
and give the information preferentially to paying subscribers _
against the government's Human Genome Project, which routinely
gives its data free to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Venter, testifying before a subcommittee of the U.S. House
Committee on Science, said his scientists had deciphered all the
chemical units making up all the genes of one individual. But
Celera has only determined the order of all the ``bases,'' or
chemical units in thousands of small pieces of the blueprint: it
still has to assemble them in the proper order, a process they say
can be completed in weeks using powerful computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the key milestone,'' Venter said. He added that the
gene blueprint was that of a single human being. ``By the end of
next week, we will have finished the gene sequence for a female.''
</P>
<P>
   Completing the finished blueprint of the human genome is
expected to lead to revolutionary new and safer drugs and leapfrog
treatment in diseases such as cancer and Alzheimer's.
</P>
<P>
   Because people have individual differences in about 1 of every
1,000 bases along the chromosomes that carry the DNA, a number of
peoples' genomes (the set of all genes) will have to be sequenced.
</P>
<P>
   But Eric Lander, a leading genetic scientist who heads the
federally funded Center for Genome Research at the Whitehead
Institute in Cambridge, Mass., disputed Celera's claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``A naive listener might get the mistaken impression that Celera
was announcing that it had just sequenced the human genome,''
Lander said. ``In fact, it has produced only a small fraction of
the data required _ and actually less data than has been produced
by the international public sequencing consortium.''
</P>
<P>
   Celera and government scientists have previously argued about
the company's claims and about Celera's strategy of withholding its
sequence data until it has finished the job.
</P>
<P>
   But even what finishing the job means is a matter of contention.
All the DNA in the nucleus of human cells amounts is made up of an
estimated 3.2 million bases _ the individual letters that, in long
sequences of genetic code spell out the instructions in the genes,
of which there are an estimated 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sequencing'' the genome means discovering the exact order of
all 3.2 million bases, so that their message can be read. As
gargantuan a task as this is, it isn't done when all the bases have
been read through one time. Inevitable errors will creep in, so the
task has to be done several times over to ensure accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   Lander said that Celera has only read the order of bases three
times, ``and you cannot assemble the vast majority of sequence''
accurately without many more repetitions of the task. He noted that
Celera, which recently announced it had sequenced the entire genome
of the fruit fly, covered the genome 13 times.
</P>
<P>
   But Lander said it is ``a mistake to think in terms of
milestones'' in the sequencing effort. There is no finish line, he
said, because scientists have been using the public sequence data
as it pours into the GenBank database the U.S. government operates.
And there will be no neat conclusion to the sequencing effort
either, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long run,'' said Lander, ``in three or four years, no
one's going to care'' who ``won'' the race. ``All of this hoopla is
just a footnote'' to the sequencing project, ``which is a tribute
to 20 years of molecular biology.''
</P>
<P>
   But investors picked a winner Thursday, pushing Celera's stock
up nearly 22 percent. Shares of PE Corp., Celera's parent company,
rose $25 to $140 in trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
