<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9230 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DELL07-COX     04-06 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell: Internet growth could double revenue in next few years
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Michael Dell told Wall Street analysts Thursday that
the explosive growth of the Internet in both hardware and services
could lead his $25 billion company to double in revenue in the next
few years.
</P>
<P>
   But that means winning the battle for the hearts, minds and
wallets of companies that buy servers, the machines that power
computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time you type www, you're accessing a server
somewhere,'' Dell told analysts at The Pierre, a Four Seasons Hotel
across Fifth Avenue from Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Looking past Houston-based Compaq Computer Corp., the world's
largest personal computer maker ahead of Dell, the Round Rock,
Texas, company's boss threw down the gauntlet at the feet of Sun
Microsystems, which saw revenue hit almost $12 billion in its last
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said there already are signs in some market segments of
passing Compaq as the leading seller of Intel-based servers in the
United States, where Compaq holds about 40 percent of the market
vs. Dell's 25 percent share.
</P>
<P>
   Dell is banking on continued growth of less expensive
Intel-based server systems as an alternative to Sun and its
proprietary, high-powered Unix-based servers that enjoyed a large
part of the early market for Internet servers. Dell's servers are
made in Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Ground Zero for Dell,'' Dell said. ``Sun is the
relevant competitor here in server share and growth.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Dell unveiled a much-expected line of low-cost,
efficient servers called Internet appliance servers designed to do
specific individual tasks, such as store Web pages, handle e-mail
or manage Web site traffic. Traditional full-service servers are
more expensive and generally designed to handle multiple tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we're seeing in the market is that you don't need
a Sun E-10,000 to run these complex (Web) sites,'' Dell said.
``Obviously, we're going to pour kerosene on that fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Walter Winnitzki of Chase Hambrect &AMP; Quist, however,
predicted a long battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to happen overnight,'' he said. ``Sun's well
entrenched.''
</P>
<P>
   Servers are just one part of Dell's efforts to capitalize on the
opportunity created by the Internet. The company on Wednesday
unveiled a service program aimed at Internet service providers and
application service providers using Dell equipment. Dell said it
will partner with consulting firms Arthur Andersen and Gen3
Partners to offer its e-commerce expertise to companies.
</P>
<P>
   Dell also is stepping up its efforts to provide Internet access,
from dial-up service to broadband and wireless offerings, as well
as Web-site hosting. The moves are part of Dell's continuing effort
to move beyond simply making desktop computers and hardware,
tapping into what it believes is a huge potential market for
closely related services driven by expansion of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Financial Officer James Schneider told analysts that when
services, access, consulting and Web-hosting are added to the mix,
the potential worldwide market in 2003 nearly triples to $1
trillion from a $351 billion market for hardware alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine just having 10 percent of this extended market, what
kind of company would it look like?'' said Schneider, who succeeded
Tom Meredith as Dell's chief financial officer a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   However, Schneider and the rest of Dell's executive team were
extremely cautious not to raise analysts' financial expectations
after spending most of last year telling Wall Street to expect the
company's growth to slow to about 30 percent annually from the 50
percent range it enjoyed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're really out to keep expectations low because
they've got burned in the past,'' said Daniel Kunstler, an analyst
with J.P. Morgan in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Dell missed analysts' earnings expectations in the third and
fourth quarters last year because of supply problems and a
Y2K-induced slump in corporate computer purchases. Its stock was
hammered as a result and has only recently climbed back above $50
per share. The stock closed at $51.56, down $2.36 a share, Thursday
in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   The company isn't abandoning the personal computer segment, a
business that's still growing at about 25 percent a year, even
though margins have been declining, executives assured analysts. On
Thursday, Fort Worth-based American Airlines said it chose Dell to
provide computers to its 100,000 employees, who will pay no more
than $12 a month, including Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Dell spokesman Andy North estimated the contract to be worth at
least $15 million over three years. American is the latestcompany
to offer subsidized computers to its employees, following the lead
of Ford Motor Co. and Delta Airlines. But it's the first of these
new contracts Dell has won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to do business in something where we won't make
a profit,'' Schneider told analysts before the American
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
