<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9232 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-WORLD-BANK-PROTESTS-$     04-06 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BANK-PROTESTS-$ADV09-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WASHINGTON BRACES FOR SEATTLE PROTESTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, April 9)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ They're baaack.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after paralyzing the World Trade Organization
meeting in Seattle, the same groups of protesters have begun
arriving in Washington, D.C., to make life difficult for the World
Bank and International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters are hoping to disrupt the two groups' annual
spring joint meeting April 16 and 17, which is scheduled to bring
together finance ministers, central bank governors and other
officials from 182 nations.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers around the country have told their members to
employ some of the tactics used in late last November and early
December in Seattle _ including hanging banners, blockading streets
near the meeting site and civil disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   While disavowing violence, Carol Welch, spokeswoman for Friends
of the Earth, a Washington-based environmental group helping to
coordinate the protests, says her organization and others ``want to
make our voice heard and to wake up the world to what the (IMF and
World Bank) do.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank provides long-term loans for economic development
projects in poor countries while the IMF arranges short-term loans
directly to countries in sudden economic crisis _ often imposing
severe austerity measures on them in return for the aid.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters charge that the two lenders' policies result in harsh
conditions on poor countries and favor western creditors and large
multinational corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The institutions push poor countries to structure their
economies and start projects that give all the power to large
corporations, which could care less about the local people or
environment,'' Welch says.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters are calling on the international organizations to
push for greater environmental protection, minimum wage standards
and better distribution of wealth, especially through debt
forgiveness for poor nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Corporations should not be allowed to dictate how the world
should live just to increase their profits,'' says Welch, who
expects several thousand demonstrators to descend on the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers have urged dozens of groups _ from the Forum of
Indian Leftists to the Progressive Librarians Guild _ to send their
members here for a week of marches, teach-ins and musical
performances. The protesters have set up their own Web site,
www.a16.org, to promote their cause.
</P>
<P>
   A Jubilee 2000/USA will be held Sunday to call for the
cancellation of the debts of African, Latin American, Asia-Pacific,
and Caribbean countries. Later in the week, lectures and rallies
will focus on the global economy. The demonstrators, using giant
puppets and outlandish costumes, will stage their main protest next
Sunday and Monday at the World Bank and IMF joint meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But with the violence in Seattle still fresh in their memory,
protest group leaders are urging demonstrators to be
peaceful.``When fights break out between protesters and police, the
media tend to forget the message of the rally and focus on the
fights, which is not what we want,'' Welch says.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that some ``rogue protesters'' among the 35,000
demonstrators in Seattle caused great property damage to downtown
businesses, Welch said her group has been working with other
organizations on nonviolent techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such assurances, the March of Dimes last month canceled
its annual fund-raising walk set for April 15 in the nation's
capital to avoid potential street violence.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle the protestors shut down the opening ceremonies of
the World Trade Organization's annual meeting. The demonstrations,
televised worldwide, quickly turned tumultuous. Police sprayed tear
gas and fired rubber pellets at many peaceful protesters but failed
to stop the window-smashing and looting by a relatively small group
of vandals less than a block away. Damage was estimated at several
million dollars, and 600 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police Chief Norm Stamper, criticized for his handling
of the protests, resigned.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid a similar scene, Washington's Metropolitan Police
Department has been preparing for the IMF/World Banks protests for
months. Nearly 1,500 officers took a special daylong course to
train for the demonstrations. They watched videos of how Seattle
police lost control and practiced scenarios such as how to handle
5,000 protesters trying to block a major street. Hundreds of
officers from federal and other local law enforcement agencies also
will be standing by in case they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't foresee any real problems,'' says Metropolitan Police
Executive Assistant Chief Terrance Gainer. ``We're sure we can both
let the protesters get out their message and keep the city running
smoothly.''
</P>
<P>
   Gainer says that unlike the Seattle police, D.C. police have ``a
good deal'' of experience dealing with demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   But just to be sure, the police here purchased $1 million worth
of riot gear for the event, including helmets with neck protectors
and arm, chest and shin guards. In addition to service weapons,
officers will carry gas masks, and some will bear arms that can
shoot rubber bullets or deliver tear gas. However, officers are
forbidden from launching any tear gas without orders from Gainer or
Metropolitan Police Chief Charles Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   IMF and World Bank officials insist that no meetings will be
canceled because of demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't expect any changes in our schedule,'' World Bank
spokeswoman Merrell Tuck says. She adds that her organization has
worked hard to reach out to protest groups and address their
concerns. She pointed to items on the spring meeting's agenda aimed
at bettering the condition of all people, such as a poverty
re-education strategy paper and a dialogue about HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope that these groups will also come to listen to what the
bank is doing to fight poverty,'' Tuck says. ``On a lot of issues
we're on the same side.''But Welch disagrees, insisting that while
the IMF and World Bank often talk about helping the poor, their
policies are geared toward enriching corporations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were doing everything they say they do, we wouldn't be
here,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
