<HEADER>
A9235 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      04-06 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERN SAYS HE REFUSED TO RECREATE KEY LEWIS MEDICAL RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SACHA PFEIFFER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Less than a day after Reggie Lewis died of heart
failure while shooting baskets at a Brandeis University gym,
Brigham and Women's Hospital officials called a former medical
intern who had been involved in the Celtics star's care and asked
him to recreate a key document missing in Lewis's medical record.
</P>
<P>
   The intern, William Maisel, testifying Thursday for the first
time in the retrial of the medical malpractice lawsuit stemming
from Lewis's July 1993 death, said he refused the request because
``I didn't feel that it was appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Maisel testified that he had dictated the information before
Lewis left the hospital in May 1993 and left it to be transcribed.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of the document, a discharge summary that would have
outlined Lewis's diagnosis and treatment plan, has been a
particularly contentious issue in the case.
</P>
<P>
   During the first trial, which ended in a hung jury last year, a
lawyer for Lewis's widow, Donna Harris-Lewis -- who sued Lewis's
chief cardiologist, Gilbert H. Mudge Jr., for negligence after her
husband died -- claimed that the record had been purposely lost or
destroyed. Hospital officials testified that the omission was due
to sloppy record-keeping.
</P>
<P>
   The document is important because Mudge has testified that
although he announced publicly that Lewis had a benign fainting
condition that would not end his basketball career, he also
believed Lewis might have a potentially life-threatening heart
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge has also testified that he, the Lewises, hospital
officials, and Celtics representatives agreed to conceal the
second, more worrisome, diagnosis from the public. Harris-Lewis has
testified that Mudge never told her or her husband that he could
have a potentially fatal disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Harris-Lewis's lawyers contend that the missing discharge
summary would provide conclusive proof of Mudge's diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second time in recent weeks that the Brigham's
record-keeping has been called into question. Last month, in an
unrelated case, a judge awarded the family of a brain damaged child
$6.5 million -- removing the statutory cap of $20,000 on damages
against charitable organizations such as hospitals -- because the
Brigham had lost a key medical record in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Maisel, who was not called to the stand during the first trial,
testified that he dictated a discharge summary of roughly one to
one-and-a-half typed pages in length upon Lewis's departure from
the Brigham. But he said he did not know if the dictation was ever
transcribed, and he conceded that the document is not in Lewis's
medical record.
</P>
<P>
   He was not asked what he had dicated and he did not volunteer
the information.
</P>
<P>
   Maisel, who now practices at the Brigham, also testified that
Mudge did -- as he claims -- have a second, unpublicized diagnosis
for Lewis that pointed to a serious heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Maisel was pressed repeatedly on that point by Neil Rossman,
Harris-Lewis's lawyer, who has established that nowhere in Lewis's
medical record was there any indication that Mudge believed Lewis
had a deadly heart ailment.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to a brief ``discharge note'' Maisel wrote for Lewis,
Rossman asked Maisel to indicate where there was a reference to a
deadly disorder. In reply, Maisel said the phrase ``exercise
monitoring,'' which was written in the note, was meant to indicate
that a second diagnosis was also being considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Mudge felt that Mr. Lewis's (problem) could be due to
neurocardiogenic syncope'' -- the benign fainting disorder -- ``but
he had not completely excluded an arrhythmia'' -- the
life-threatening heart condition -- ``and that is why he didn't
want Mr. Lewis to exercise without being monitored,'' Maisel said.
</P>
<P>
   Mudge's attorney, William J. Dailey Jr., contends that Lewis
contributed to his own death by continuing to play basketball
against Mudge's orders.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by Rossman if he was surprised that Mudge mentioned only a
benign fainting disorder when he publicly announced Lewis's
diagnosis, Maisel replied that was.
</P>
<P>
   Rossman also questioned why Maisel, who was ten months out of
medical school when he assisted with Lewis's care, had been given
the authority to draft discharge documents. Maisel replied that at
the time he was a licensed physician who had treated ``hundreds of
patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Also testifying Thursday was former Celtics general manager Jan
Volk, who -- as he testified last year -- said that during a
meeting in which Mudge briefed him on Lewis's medical condition,
Mudge made no mention of a life-threatening heart disorder.
</P>
<P>
   But noting that Volk said Mudge also told him further testing
would be done on Lewis, Dailey attempted to show that Mudge was
merely in the process of evaluating Lewis's medical condition, and
had not yet reached a conclusive diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Dailey also questioned why Volk -- from the time he met with
Mudge till Lewis's death -- never contacted Mudge to inquire about
Lewis's health and ask when he would be able to play professionally
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our very best player,'' Volk said. ``We were going to
give him all the space we could.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a spot for Reggie whenever he was ready,'' he added.
``He was irreplaceable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
