<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9236 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-NEWBORN-SURGERY-BOS &LR;      04-06 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWBORN-SURGERY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS PERFORM UNIQUE SURGERY ON NEWBORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Little Sarah Savage entered the world abruptly two
weeks ago, when Boston doctors, in a rare and daring maneuver,
pulled her halfway out of her mother's womb _ still attached to the
placenta _ to treat a lung blockage that would likely kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Now she is set to go home. But this extraordinary venture in
fetal surgery, carried out March 22 at Children's Hospital, would
take another twist before Sarah could breathe on her own.
</P>
<P>
   The crowded team of obstetrical and surgical experts from
Children's and Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center intended to
perform the delicate operation and return the baby to the mother's
womb. But they soon feared that removing the cyst blocking her
airway would take too long, that the placenta would quickly stop
functioning, and the lungs would become totally obstructed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to buy more time,'' said Dr. Benjamin Sachs,
chairman of obstetrics and gynecology at Beth Israel.
</P>
<P>
   So in another rare move, Sarah was fully delivered, though six
weeks premature, and hooked to a mechanical heart-lung bypass
device. The decision gave the surgeons several hours to perform the
operation and repair her tiny windpipe.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah is now fully normal, and weighing about six pounds, and
the dozens of medical specialists at Beth Israel and Children's who
joined forces to save her are basking in the knowledge that it all
finally worked. ``A tremendous amount of work and coordination
behind the scenes made this all possible,'' said Sachs. The
preparations even included getting permission for Beth Israel
Deaconess obstetricians to deliver Sarah at Children's, which has
no maternity service.
</P>
<P>
   The baby's parents, John and Lucie Savage of Pembroke, said they
were confident throughout the ordeal. It helped that Lucie is a
nurse in the neonatal intensive care unit at Beth Israel. ``People
asked me if that made me more nervous, but it was actually the
opposite,'' said Lucie Savage Thursday. ``It reassured me; I knew I
was in good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   But earlier, when a happy outcome was not assured, the plan
seemed fraught with ethical concerns, because the mother would be
risking her own health to save the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case was fascinating for lots of reasons,'' said Dr.
Russell Jennings, the surgeon who heads the fetal treatment program
at Children's, and who has brought to conservative Boston a long
experience in operating on infants while still in the womb _ a
medical frontier that was opened in San Francisco, where Jennings
trained.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the half-Cesarian birth procedure, known as EXIT,
has been done many times elsewhere, ``but in Boston, everyone's
very nervous about it'' because it is so rare, said Jennings,
adding that it actually poses relatively little risk to the mother.
The major concern is that by opening the womb with a surgical
incision and leaving it open while treating the infant, there's a
risk of major bleeding, requiring transfusions or even a
hysterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   The situation created a potential collision of interests: the
mother's and the fetus's. Yet in cases like this, ``the mom is
always committed to her fetus, so she can't be the best advocate
for herself,'' said Jennings. But John Savage, 36, said the doctors
did a good job ``of making us understand that we could risking
Lucie's life for the sake of this unborn child. That was one of the
hardest parts.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs, the obstetrics chief, took it on himself to be Lucie
Savage's advocate in the operating room, in case doctors focused on
trying to save the baby began to put the mother at increased risk.
Fortunately, Lucie Savage fared very well during the surgery; her
health wasn't compromised by the efforts to save Sarah.
</P>
<P>
   Savage, who also has a 19-month-old, had a normal pregnancy
under the care of Beth Israel doctors until a routine ultrasound in
the 15th week of gestation revealed a growth in the fetus'
breathing passages. Savage was referred to Dr. Deborah Levine, a
radiologist, and Dr. Geoffrey Wong, an obstetrician who manages
high-risk cases, and also to Jennings at Children's.
</P>
<P>
   For many weeks, and through a number of different medical
imaging sessions, the doctors were unsure whether the growth was a
major problem or not. But by her 31st week of gestation, Lucie had
developed excessive fluid in the womb caused by the cysts' growth,
which was putting pressure on the lungs and heart.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing danger forced the combined medical teams to move
ahead faster than they had planned toward the rare operation. At 34
weeks, Lucie Savage was moved from Beth Israel to Children's
Hospital where the delicate procedure began at around noon. After
Sarah was delivered, Jennings and his colleagues worked for several
more hours to remove the cysts, which they believe occurred as an
accident during development, and to repair the breathing passages
to which it was attached.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
