<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9248 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MIAMI-SCENE-0407-COX     04-06 0387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-SCENE-0407-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EXILE PROTESTERS SUPPORT ELIAN'S FATHER, BUT NOT TAKING HIS SON
 &HT;    With Photo from The Palm Beach Post.
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0407.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BILL DOUTHAT 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Crowds tossed long-stemmed carnations over police
barricades Thursday to show that Cuban exiles are prepared to
warmly receive the father of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way we will greet Juan Miguel Gonzalez if he
decides to come here to see his son,'' said Ramon Saul Sanchez, a
protest organizer who last week led the crowds in exercises to form
a human chain around the home where 6-year-old Elian has stayed
since being rescued from the
</P>
<P>
   ocean Thanksgiving Day.
</P>
<P>
   But protestors made it clear that the father, who arrived in the
United States Thursday morning to reclaim his son, could quickly
wear out his welcome if he came only to take Elian back to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Papa, stay here,'' read a freshly painted poster hanging on
the chain link fence in front of the Little Havana home of Lazaro
Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he gets into the house, I'm sure he will ask for
political asylum,'' said Jose Cruz, 21, of West Palm Beach, Fla.,
one of about 200 Cuban-Americans protesting outside the home
Thursday. Cruz said the father was not speaking his heart when said
he wanted to return immediately to Cuba after taking custody of his
son.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who thinks he's speaking freely is naive,'' said
Michael Reyes, 23, of Miami Beach. ``His mother and father are
still in Cuba and he could have been threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, saying he'd welcome the defection of
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, criticized the Clinton administration for
permitting the Cuban government to keep him and his family in the
residence of a Cuban diplomat outside of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``He will be surrounded 24 hours a day and be under the fear and
terror of Cuban security agents,'' Carollo said. ``Why isn't he
staying in a hotel?''
</P>
<P>
   Carollo said he's convinced the father would defect if allowed
to freely visit his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he breathes the air of freedom, I'm sure he'll stay
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
