<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Friday, April 7. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: 888-346-9867 or 212-556-1927;
e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE-POLL (New York) _ Results of the latest New York
Times/CBS poll on the New York Senate race between Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Hillary Rodham Clinton. The mayor's response to the
Patrick Dorismond shooting has resulted in his lowest job-approval
ratings in seven years in office, jolting his campaign for the
Senate while catapulting Hillary Rodham Clinton into the lead for
the first time in a year. By Adam Clymer and Marjorie Connelly. (We
plan to move the story by 9 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo and graphic.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who has not seen
his son Elian since the third week of November when the boy and his
mother departed Cuba on a small and rickety boat for a new life in
the United States, sets foot on American soil. As he stepped off a
small chartered plane, he announced somberly that he had come with
his new wife and 6-month-old son to bring Elian back to Cuba.
Justice Department officials said they would move quickly to
transfer physical custody of the boy to his father, but they
acknowledged that it could take several days to accomplish that. By
Neil A. Lewis. (Eds.: an early version of this story has moved; the
1stLd-Writethru is scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``a'' news
file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column photo, NYT4
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   AUCTION-CORRUPTION (New York) _ More details are emerging on the
accusations that Christie's and Sotheby's, the giant auction
houses, colluded to fix prices. Editors: This story is exclusive
and competitive. By Douglas Frantz, Ralph Blumenthal and Carol
Vogel. (Scheduled to move by 9:45 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   !
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN-SHARIF (Karachi, Pakistan) _ Nawaz Sharif, ousted as
Pakistan's prime minister in a military coup in October, was
convicted today of hijacking a commercial airliner, sentenced to
life imprisonment rather than death and ordered to forfeit all his
personal property. By Barry Bearak. (Eds: 1stLd-Writethru has moved
in ``i'' news file.) 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-RIGHTS (Jerusalem) _ Over the years, Israel has earned a
regular place on the blacklists of many human and civil rights
organizations by invoking national security to explain practices
that were considered exclusionary, discriminatory and coercive
toward Israeli Arabs and Palestinians. But since the right-wing
government was replaced last summer by a broad coalition including
several leftists and human rights advocates, key policy changes
have been made that together with a spate of high court decisions
point toward a sea change. By Deborah Sontag. (The story has moved
in ``i'' news file.) 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   BBO-POORER-TEAMS (Kansas City, Mo.) _ For baseball fans, hope is
supposed to spring eternal at this time each year: Maybe this year
will be the year. But here in Kansas City, as in Pittsburgh,
Montreal, Minneapolis and many smaller cities with major league
teams, that perennial optimism has withered over the last decade in
the face of a growing gap between rich and poor franchises. There
is a growing consensus among owners, fans and experts on the game
that the disparity between high-revenue teams and those in small
markets threatens the sport's future popularity. By James C.
McKinley Jr. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``s'' news
file.) 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   TAINTED-BLOOD (United Nations) _ More than two-thirds of the
world's nations are failing to supply safe blood supplies to their
populations, according to the World Health Organization. Their
failure adds significantly to the spread of the virus that causes
AIDS, as well as potentially deadly forms of hepatitis and other
disease. The countries where people are most at risk are the
poorest and often are those where diseases are spreading fastest,
the group found in a survey. These countries contain 80 percent of
the world's population, or about 4.8 billion people. By Barbara
Crossette. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
900 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME (Washington) _ Craig Venter tells a congressional
committee that his company, Celera Corp., has finished analyzing
all necessary pieces of human DNA and will assemble the whole human
genome within three to six weeks. By Nicholas Wade. (The story has
moved in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NEW-PLANET (Undated) _ What some astronomers believed to be
the only planet ever directly observed outside the solar system has
turned out to be an ordinary dim star, NASA announces. By James
Glanz. (Scheduled to move by 8:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
