<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9254 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE07-COX     04-06 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore's angers party loyalists with stand on Elian
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A few days after he learned that Al Gore planned to
support legislation granting Elian Gonzalez and his family
residency status in the United States, Rep. Charles Rangel (D-N.Y.)
met with the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The gravel-throated congressman from Harlem considered venting
his anger over the vice president's sudden move, which appeared to
many on Capitol Hill as a clumsy attempt to curry votes among Cuban
Americans in Miami. But Rangel, who has endorsed Gore, bit his
tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't think it was my place to be cussing out the vice
president, even though it was my understanding that some members
did,'' said Rangel, one of the House's most senior Democrats. ``It
was a stupid thing that he did. I can't for the life of me think
that he was dumb enough to think that he picks up any political
points in Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the controversy over 6-year-old Elian, such blunt
criticism of Gore was rare. For the most part, Gore and
congressional Democrats have been reading from the same play book,
promoting issues that they believe will help Democrats win back the
Congress and keep the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But the Elian controversy, which angered many members of his own
party, demonstrates the pitfalls Gore faces as he attempts to
appeal to diverse constituencies around the country, while still
maintaining his support among Democrats on Capitol Hill. Another
potential point of friction between Gore and congressional
Democrats looms. House Republicans on Wednesday scheduled a vote
for the week of May 22 on granting China normal trade status on a
permanent basis, a requirement for China's entry into the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, hotly opposed by organized labor, deeply divides
Democrats on Capitol Hill. Gore supports the legislation, which
President Clinton has made one of his top priorities for his last
year in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the most dicey issues for Vice President Gore
because the key component of his constituency, organized labor, is
opposed to the administration's position,'' said Marshall Wittmann,
a congressional analyst with the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative think tank. ``This is a hot-button issue that divides
the new Democrats from the old Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   House Republicans, most of whom support the China trade bill,
are demanding that Clinton produce as many as 100 Democrats in
support of it, putting pressure on the administration to wage an
aggressive campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore has said he will help pass the legislation, it
remains to be seen how active he will be. Minority leader Richard
Gephardt (D-Mo.) said Thursday that he was not yet aware of any
effort on Gore's part to lobby for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``He obviously has every right in the world to talk to people,''
Gephardt said. ``That's up to him. I don't pretend to tell him one
way or the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Several key Hill Democrats and observers said they believe that
Gore will wage only a token effort, effectively getting a bye on
the issue, because of organized labor's strong opposition to the
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a presidential priority,'' said Will Marshall,
president of the Progressive Policy Institute, a centrist
Democratic organization closely allied to Gore. ``I don't think
anyone expects the vice president to be up there bending arms on
this vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Taylor, legislative director for the AFL-CIO, which plans
to bus over 10,000 union members to Capitol Hill April 12 to lobby
against the China trade bill, said the union ``would much have
preferred not to have this fight in an election year.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said it remained an open question how much Gore's support
of the China legislation would dampen enthusiasm for his
presidential campaign among union members.
</P>
<P>
   But Taylor also said that the union leadership felt comfortable
with Gore on other issues important to union workers, such as the
right to organize.
</P>
<P>
   Kathleen Begala, Gore's campaign spokeswoman, downplayed any
potential fallout from the upcoming China vote, noting that the
vice president's free trade positions are widely known both on
Capitol Hill and among union members.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always going to be differences between Democrats,''
Begala said. ``But when it comes to the issues that drive this
election _ health care, education, continuing the economic
prosperity, we agree. Overall, we are clearly a united party.''
</P>
<P>
   While congressional Democrats also largely subscribe to this
view, several indicated that Gore cannot afford too many
controversies such as the one generated by his support of residency
for Elian and his family.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I know more than they do about (Latino) issues, that
campaign is in deep trouble,'' said Rep. Jose Serrano (D-N.Y.), who
fired off an angry letter to Gore.
</P>
<P>
   If the residency bill comes to the House floor, Serrano said he
would consider offering an amendment that would grant residency
status to the 7 million other undocumented aliens living in the
United States. And then he would expect Gore to support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the morally correct thing to do,'' said Serrano, who is
still seething over Gore's decision to support congressional
legislation that singled out just one family.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Gore has sought to mollify his critics by clarifying
his position. He asserted that giving Elian and his family
residence would permit the family courts in Florida the freedom to
resolve the dispute, something Gore has argued all along. Serrano
said he was unmoved.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you tell me this is something you had to do for political
reasons, I can live with that,'' Serrano said. ``But don't insult
my intelligence by telling me this is something you really believe
in.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Rangel is willing to let the matter drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever problems I have with the vice president, I just take
a good hard look at George W. Bush and the warts disappear,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
