<HEADLINE>
RUDDER PROBLEM MAY DELAY SHUTTLE LAUNCH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ NASA on Thursday evaluated a rudder problem on the
shuttle Atlantis that could delay the spacecraft's planned April 24
launch to the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   A launch pad test of the shuttle's tail rudder revealed
hydraulic pressure readings three times higher than specified, said
Joel Wells, a spokesman for NASA's Kennedy Space Center in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The rudder is used to steer the shuttle as it descends to a
landing and to brake the ship as it speeds down the runway.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers were expected to take at least a couple of days to
determine whether a hydraulic system component in the shuttle's
tail compartment was responsible for the high pressure and whether
it can be replaced with Atlantis on the launch pad.
</P>
<P>
   If a launch pad repair is feasible, the shuttle and its
seven-member crew could lift off as scheduled. However, if Atlantis
must be transported to its large processing hangar for the work,
the mission could be delayed, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis crew plans to make several repairs to the
uninhabited first components of the new station and prepare it for
the arrival of Russia's crew module in July.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
