<HEADER>
A9266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSP     04-06 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPSTER IS STIRRING PIRACY CONTROVERSY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shawn Fanning doesn't look, talk, or walk like a revolutionary.
The 19-year-old from Harwich hardly seems like an incendiary
capable of fueling the wrath of the establishment. But that's
exactly what happened after he began tinkering with a computer as a
freshman at Northeastern University last year. He wrote one little
program, and now the lawyers are sharpening their claws, the
students are circulating petitions, and the pundits are predicting
the beginning of a brave new world.
</P>
<P>
   The program is called Napster, which allows computer users to
share digital music files (called MP3s) almost instantly over the
Internet. Faster and more reliable than other MP3 search engines,
Napster is wildly popular among college and high-school students,
who use it to trade both legal and pirated music. Some folks,
however, are not enthralled. The Recording Industry Association of
America has filed suit, and scores of colleges have banned the
program on their campus computer networks.
</P>
<P>
   So why did the guy who started the whole brouhaha write the
program in the first place? ``I was bored,'' Fanning says. ``I had
some free time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fanning has barely had a minute since he dropped out of
college to found Napster, Inc., a startup in San Mateo, Calif.
Fanning himself isn't in the direct firing line; the company
recruited a CEO to handle the business while he puts in long hours
as a software engineer (with stock options, of course). As such,
he's not allowed to talk about the legal issues and seems frazzled
by the controversy. ``I knew Napster had potential,'' he says
during a frequently interrupted phone interview. ``But I didn't
think it would gain this kind of popularity. I didn't think it
would be . . . ''
</P>
<P>
   Contentious? Litigious? He finishes the thought this way.
``Handing over the business stuff was not difficult at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the company is now embroiled in a lawsuit that could
determine the future of the music industry, which is struggling to
redefine itself in the digital age. Napster (the Mac version is
Rapster) enables each user to post his entire MP3 collection online
for others to download, making it simple for anyone to obtain
high-quality music illegally. For instance, tracks from the new 'N
Sync album, ``No Strings Attached,'' were available for downloading
through Napster on Wednesday, the day after the record hit the
stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Recording Industry Association filed its lawsuit late last
year, contending that Napster facilitates piracy. Artists and their
agents contend that such programs are robbing them of their
royalties. Sean ``Puffy'' Combs says the program is a form of
``abuse,'' while Scott Stapp, lead singer for Creed, has said that
Napster is ``robbing me blind.''
</P>
<P>
   But Napster CEO Eileen Richardson begs to differ. ``We want to
create a place where new artists can keep in touch with their
fans,'' she says. Digital distribution, she argues, makes it
possible for unsigned bands to bypass the insular record industry
and market their music directly to millions of potential fans.
Plus, Richardson says, Napster isn't doing anything illegal itself;
the site (www.napster.com) includes a disclaimer warning users to
obey the copyright laws.
</P>
<P>
   Disclaimer or not, the primary use of Napster is to download
pirated music. And the program uses a ton of bandwidth, causing a
different kind of fury at scores of colleges. Indiana University,
for one, banned the program in February. Sophomore Chad Paulson
started www.savenapster.com, a grassroots drive to convince college
administrators to restore access to the program. To date, he has
gathered more than 13,000 signatures on a petition, and this week,
the university announced it was restoring an updated version of
Napster on a trial basis.
</P>
<P>
   The ban at Indiana never had anything to do with the copyright
issues, says Mark Bruhn, the school's information technology policy
officer. The program was eating up more than 60 percent of the
university's network capacity. ``This isn't a legal issue,'' Bruhn
says. ``A screwdriver isn't illegal unless you use it to break into
a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all college officials agree. Robert Weir, vice president of
information services at Northeastern, banned Napster primarily
because of piracy issues. ``A condition of using our systems is
that you don't do anything illegal, and copyright infringement is
illegal,'' he says, allowing that former Northeastern student
Fanning ``wrote a cool piece of code.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Paulson, who fought to reinstate Napster at Indiana,
doesn't argue that most folks use the program to promote legal
MP3s. ``Piracy is wrong,'' Paulson says, claiming that he only
downloaded one song illegally on Napster and immediately deleted
it. That sounds like the musical equivalent of ``I didn't inhale.''
But Paulson also champions independent bands and legal MP3s on his
Web site and says the Internet will bring democracy to the
oligarchic music business.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, both sides are right, and both sides are wrong.
And it's unclear who is going to win the latest round of the music
wars. But neither outcome is particularly attractive. The music
industry is trying to protect its turf and curtail progress; at the
same time, artists deserve to be paid. ``If the recording industry
wins, we lose the huge social advantages,'' says Harvard Law School
professor William Fisher. ``But if the recording industry loses,
artists' rights are eroded.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisher envisions an alternative outcome in the battle, a sort of
new model for the music industry that he whimsically calls ``Doing
Well by Doing Good.'' Under his scenario, artists would release
their music files online in an unprotected format, offering certain
services (such as advance concert tickets) to honest fans who pay
as they play. David Bowie has mastered the concept at
www.davidbowie.com, which offers users everything from Internet
service to CDs (as in compact disc and certificates of deposit).
</P>
<P>
   Fisher's vision is eminently reasonable, since it offers a
compromise that encourages artistic freedom for the masses but
doesn't require artists to work for free. However, the recording
industry isn't going to give in without a fight that could go all
the way to the Supreme Court. And entrepreneurs are not going to
stop coming up with new programs. Just last week, engineers at
Nullsoft, Inc., introduced Gnutella, an open-source program that is
similar to Napster. The only problem was, Nullsoft is owned by
America Online, which recently merged with Time-Warner, which
happens to be a member of the Recording Industry Association.
Gnutella was taken down within hours of its release, but copies are
available all over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, it's Napster, tomorrow it's Gnutella, and the next day,
it's something else,'' says Northeastern's Weir. And who knows?
Maybe Shawn Fanning will start another revolution some day. ``I
have other ideas I'd like to address,'' he says, ``but right now,
I'd like to get some rest.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-03-30-00 1549EST &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
