<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BANK-PROTESTS (Washington) _ Four months after paralyzing
Seattle's meeting of the World Trade Organization, dozens of
protest groups will soon arrive here to make life miserable for two
other multinational financial institutions: the World Bank and
International Monetary Fund. The protesters want them to forgive
many nations' debts, pay more attention to the environment and
provide loans that directly help people rather than corporations.
The April 16 and 17 meetings will bring together financial
officials from 182 nations. By MARK HELM. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-FUNDING (Washington) _ Congress will be asked to change the
way the federal government spends $1.6 billion for AIDS care and
prevention, switching from a system that doles out dollars based on
full-blown AIDS cases to one based on infection with the virus that
leads to the disease. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
