<SLUG> BC-TAINTED-BLOOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH OF WORLD'S BLOOD SUPPLY IS UNSAFE, SAYS U.N. AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ More than two-thirds of the world's nations are
failing to supply safe blood supplies to their populations,
according to the World Health Organization. Their failure adds
significantly to the spread of the virus that causes AIDS, as well
as potentially deadly forms of hepatitis and other disease.
</P>
<P>
   The countries where people are most at risk are the poorest and
often are those where diseases are spreading fastest, WHO found in
a survey. These countries contain 80 percent of the world's
population, or about 4.8 billion people.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, WHO, in cooperation with the International Federation
of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies, will begin a campaign to
improve the safety of blood around the world. Friday is World
Health Day, which WHO is marking this year with the safe-blood
theme.
</P>
<P>
   Poor countries face obvious cost problems in making the blood
supply safe. But that is not the only cause of the failure, experts
say.
</P>
<P>
   Poor social policies with a low priority on public health
programs contribute to the problem, as does inadequate testing.
Hospital equipment may be contaminated, sometimes reused, and blood
may be stored improperly.
</P>
<P>
   Most important may be the ubiquitous Third World practice of
buying blood. ``Paid donors, it has been demonstrated many, many
times, are at much higher risk of being infected,'' said Dr. David
Brandling-Bennett, deputy director of the Pan American Health
Organization in Washington. ``That, of course, means that even if
you do good testing, you have a higher risk of missing somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Brandling-Bennett said in an interview that travelers who visit
developing countries on business usually do not need to fear blood
contamination if they avoid risky behavior and, in emergencies, go
only to hospitals approved by U.S. embassies or consulates. In the
United States, immigrant populations need to have explained to them
the importance of full disclosure when people give blood, he said.
Blood is no longer bought in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Western Hemisphere, said Dr. Jose Ramiro Cruz, the Pan
American Health Organization's adviser on laboratory and blood
safety, is the world's safest in the handling of blood. ``Data
collected in the last five years from every single country in Latin
America and the Caribbean shows that the position has improved
dramatically,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Other regions are not so lucky, said WHO. It estimates that tens
of thousands of people pick up the virus that causes AIDS and
millions are infected annually with hepatitis B and C, which can
lead to liver failure or liver cancer. South Asia, particularly
India, and Africa are special concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kevin Cahill, an expert on tropical diseases in New York,
and the president of the independent Center for International
Health and Cooperation, said that economics and attitudes both play
a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you deal with many countries where the total health
expenditure per capita is in the range of $15 a year, as in some
African countries, the thought that you can spend that amount
typing and cross-matching blood _ it's a fantasy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just blood-banking is a low priority; health is a low
priority in most developing countries,'' Cahill said. ``Health and
humanitarian issues should be central in foreign policies, not
peripheral issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Women of childbearing age are among the most vulnerable people
in the developing world, experts say. Corinne Whitaker, senior
program officer for Africa at the International Women's Health
Coalition in New York, said this is especially true in societies
where women bear children young and often. They are frequently
anemic and their small size makes them prone to injuries in
childbirth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting access to any blood is a challenge in much of
Africa,'' Whitaker said in an interview. ``That's further
complicated by the issue of screening for safe blood.'' She said
that women go to hospitals with ``walking blood banks'' in the form
of relatives to guarantee the availability of blood that is safe.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with the blood supply have not been limited to
developing nations. Over the last decade court cases have
demonstrated to what extent early warnings about the virus that
causes AIDS were ignored in the United States, France, Germany,
Switzerland and other countries, with the result that thousands of
hemophiliacs and others in need of blood may have been infected.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pan American Health Organization, Brandling-Bennett and
Cruz say that now the problem is a decrease in donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say that countries should be targeting to have about 5
percent of their populations regularly donating blood,''
Brandling-Bennett said. ``The U.S. is at about 4 and a half
percent; Canada is a little over 3 percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
