<HEADLINE>
CUBAN NEIGHBORS TAKE CALMER LOOK AT ELIAN'S PLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARDENAS, Cuba _ There was no human chain around 170 Cosio
Street Thursday. No angry, fist-waving protesters. No wall of
spotlights, cameras and microphones.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the small, black-and-white sketches of the
cherubic boy that dot a blue wall of this modest stucco dwelling,
it would be hard to know that this was where Elian Gonzalez used to
live.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 6-year-old boy's other home, the one in Cuba, the
country he left with his mother back in November and the one that
desperately wants him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't need protests here or anything like the circus you
see in Miami,'' said neighbor Carlos Navarro, sitting on a homemade
wooden bench. ``We don't need all that publicity because we don't
tell lies. We want Elian back and we don't want any politics.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone here is certain that Juan Miguel will come back
with Elian. Some whisper that the father might give in to the
pressure and cajoling of his American relatives to stay in the
United States, while others worry that Elian, having grown
accustomed to his comfortable American lifestyle, might fight
coming back to poor, provincial Cardenas.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's home here _ and two nearby houses of relatives _ were
locked Thursday, the family still traveling in Havana, the
neighbors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think he'd really want to come back here?'' one
neighbor said, covering her mouth as if to keep from being heard by
too many people. ``This would be another big change for him. It
will be hard for him to go from having so many things given to
coming back here. He would have to bring his toys.''
</P>
<P>
   As Juan Miguel Gonzalez, Elian's father, went to the United
State Thursday in hopes of taking back his child, friends, family
and neighbors in this city of 100,000 about 80 miles east of Havana
offered their prayers and support in quiet fortitude. That stood in
sharp contrast to the naked emotions that have been seen and heard
in front of Elian's current residence, his great-uncle's home, in
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a matter of family, not an issue for politics,'' said
Elsa Diaz, 59, another of the Gonzalez's neighbors. ``The son
should be with his only surviving parent. We believe and know that,
and we don't have to have protests or violence to prove we're
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Diaz's eyes grow wide and her expression goes blank as she
recalls memories of Elian in the neighborhood: there's Elian
playing with toy guns with the boy next door; there he is again,
darting back and forth across the street, callling out for his
mother, Elizabet, who perished on the trip in November across the
Florida Straits; and then there's Elian joining other boys while
bathing in the flooded streets during the summer rainy season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Elian hovers over this street and this town like a friendly
ghost.
</P>
<P>
   In Cardenas, as in Havana and other Cuban towns, there are signs
all over urging for Elian's return. On the front door of Elian's
grandmother's apartment, which sits above a pharmacy, a sign reads,
``You'll return to the heart of your family, town and country,
symbolic boy, heroic boy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the freedom of little Elian,'' reads a billboard on the
main road that leads into this small city, where most people work
either in surrounding fields or in the hotels of the nearby resort
city of Varadero.
</P>
<P>
   At the Marcelo Salado Primary School, Elian's likeness is
painted in the school's uniform: red pants, crisp white shirt and
red neckerchief. His old desk has been converted into a shrine, and
there's a book containing good wishes and signatures from his
classmates, teachers and even from Cuban President Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss him and we wish he would come back,'' said one student
named Jose. ``But we don't really understand all of the other
things about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most other Cubans, the neighbors along Cosio Street got the
news that Juan Miguel would be leaving directly from Castro, who
made the announcement in a nationally televised speech just hours
before his departure.
</P>
<P>
   At 4 a.m. Wednesday, Castro joined several members of the
Gonzalez family, which had been brought to Havana from Cardenas
earlier in the week, at the Jose Marti International Airport to say
goodbye to Jose Miguel, his wife and their 6-month-old infant. All
three of them boarded a private jet for Dulles International
Airport outside Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the lucky few residents who have access to pirated
satellite television signals from the United States or to the
Internet, most of the country's 12 million residents have been
given daily updates on the situation _ filtered through
government-friendly broadcasters _ in a ``roundtable'' transmitted
at 5 p.m. on state-run television and radio.
</P>
<P>
   Many Cubans believe it was inevitable that Juan Miguel Gonzalez
would have to travel to the United States to be reunited with
Elian.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your child is in danger, then it's your duty as a father to
go get him,'' Victor Matas, 25, said as he sat in a Cardenas
barbershop watching his own 8-year-old son, Victor Jr., get a
haircut.
</P>
<P>
   Before the custody controversy began last fall, the Gonzalezes
were like many Cuban families: a core of relatives on the island
with another close branch of the family in Florida, New Jersey or
elsewhere in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But its clear from friends in the neighborhood _ where this kind
of news travels quickly _ that the battle over Elian has sharply
divided the two families, and the family members that spent
holidays together just a year ago, has stopped talking to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad to see how politics can tear families apart,''
Diaz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
