<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY-FESTIVAL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Blue Ridge, Ga. _ The third annual Blue Ridge Mountain
Adventure Race on Saturday involves 65 coed teams of three running
the Benton McKaye Trail, paddling Funyaks in the Toccoa River Canoe
Trail and mountain-biking the Aska Trails System. Teams will finish
downtown, where Race Days 2000 will be under way, with music, art,
children's activities, antique autos and food from noon to 7 p.m.
Also, rides on the Blue Ridge Scenic Railway, which launches its
season Saturday (reservations required, 1-800-934-1989 or
www.brscenic.com). 1-800-899-6867.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Lanier Islands, Ga. _ The Dogwood Regatta takes place
Saturday and Sunday at Presentation Point, with sailboat races
featuring top Southeastern sailors and rides on spectator boats, a
charity golf tournament, dinner with dancing and entertainment
Saturday night and a silent auction. 770-952-3891.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pine Mountain, Ga. _ Spring Celebration through April 16
features a spectacular display of azaleas in the Overlook Garden,
and the new Callaway Brothers Azalea Bowl serves as the backdrop to
festivities including entertainment, exhibits and special
activities on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-225-5292 or www
</P>
<P>
   .callawaygardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island, Ga. _ Civil War re-enactors portraying the 1st
Regiment State Line Infantry will encamp Friday through Sunday near
the historic Horton House to engage in military drills and other
aspects of camp life. 1-877-453-5955.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Ga. _ The Columbus Museum presents ``Janet Fish:
Recent Paintings'' through June 18. Fish will discuss her work and
career as a still-life painter at 6:30 p.m. May 4. Also showing:
``Selection of Quilts From the Permanent Collection,'' through
April. 706-649-0713.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Dahlonega, Ga. _ The fourth annual Bear on the Square Mountain
Festival April 14-16 offers Appalachian music, workshops, a jam
sesssion, children's events and a street dance. Special guest is
singer-songwriter Hazel Dickens and the Lynn Morris Band. Also,
quilters, weavers, spinners and other authentic mountain
craftspeople will demonstrate and sell their works. 1-800-231-5543
or www
</P>
<P>
   .dahlonega.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cartersville, Ga. _ The 35th running of the Atlanta
Steeplechase at Kingston Downs is April 15. It features five
thoroughbred races over brush jumps for a purse of $200,000.
Pre-race festivities include pig races, Jack Russell terrier races,
pony rides, sky divers and the Parade of the Shamrock Hounds. Also,
barbecue by the Rib Ranch. Picnics welcomed. Racing member tickets
$23; parking passes $20 per car. 770-387-1357.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Perry, Ga. _ The Mossy Creek Barnyard Festival takes place
April 15-16, featuring three entertainment stages, old-time skills
such as hand-building wooden canoes, fine arts and crafts from 26
states, storytelling, wagon and hayrides, children's activities and
country cooking. 912-922-8265.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga _ The Tennessee Valley Railroad's steam-powered
Spring Blossom Special rolls Saturday, departing from Grand
Junction Station for an 85-mile trip in northwest Georgia, through
Rossville, Chickamauga, Rock Spring, LaFayette and Trion. Coach
fare is $67. Reservations: 1-800-397-5544.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eufaula, Ala. _ The 35th annual Eufaula Pilgrimage and Antique
Show is Friday through Sunday, presenting grand antebellum and
Victorian mansions, ``Tales From the Tomb,'' a needlework show, an
art show, afternoon tea and a Sunset Social at the Shorter Mansion.
1-888-383-2852.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Berea, Ky. _ The Spring Showcase of Artists is Saturday and
Sunday, featuring 25 open studios and galleries in the ``folk arts
and crafts capital of Kentucky.'' Tater Knob Pottery and Farm hosts
a Spring Show, where visitors can watch potters and even try their
hand at throwing a pot. 606-986-2167.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Charleston, S.C. _ The 53rd Festival of Houses and Gardens
continues through April 15, offering daily afternoon and
candlelight walking tours and Lowcountry oyster roasts at Drayton
Hall plantation. To order tickets ($40), call 843-722-3405; for
information, www.historiccharleston.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
