<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-RULES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE ANTI-TOBACCO RULES ON THE LINE IN FEDERAL COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The national battle over tobacco control hits a
critical crossroads in a federal courthouse Friday where
Massachusetts is defending its crackdown _ the toughest in the
nation _ on children's exposure to cigarette advertising and
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Thomas F. Reilly's top legal aides will
stand before three members of the US Court of Appeals for the First
Circuit to argue that a lower court ruling in January upholding the
state's right to sharply curb tobacco ads, promotions, and
storefront displays should stand.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the legal struggle over the state
regulations and the ultimate outcome of these hearings is far
reaching, and will have national implications, experts in tobacco
control say.
</P>
<P>
   The courtroom arguments mark the first confrontation between
regulators and the tobacco industry since the US Supreme Court
ruled last month that the US Food and Drug Administration has no
authority to regulate tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for the major cigarette manufacturers will argue that
the attorney general's unilateral regulations _ issued under the
state's consumer protection act _ violate free speech under the
First Amendment, and that federal law preempts state regulations on
advertising and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision, which forced the FDA to shut down
its campaign to keep cigarettes out of the hands of children and to
back off plans to limit harmful chemicals in tobacco products, was
a major victory for the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   Howard K. Koh, the state public health commissioner whose agency
operates one of the country's most comprehensive and heavily funded
tobacco control programs, said the recent high court ruling has
dramatically elevated the significance of the battle over Reilly's
regulations, which closely mirror the now inoperative FDA rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an absolutely critical decision,'' Koh said. ``And the
timing is critically important because now the FDA can't regulate
and Congress continues to study the issue, so the states must act.
This is an opportunity for Massachusetts to once again take the
lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kline, an attorney with the Tobacco Control Resource
Center at Northeastern University School of Law, said the arguments
and the court decision will focus on one of the most important
debates on tobacco control: the power of states to regulate the
promotion of the product.
</P>
<P>
   Kline noted that, unlike other states, which have implemented
less sweeping rules, the Massachusetts regulations were put in
place by the attorney general a year ago, using the state's
consumer protection laws, not by the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This can lead other attorney generals to take the same
approach,'' Kline said. ``State houses around the country are often
confounded by the tobacco industry and their allies. This is a
completely different approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers representing the tobacco companies have declined to
comment until the court hearing is completed. Reilly aides said the
attorney general and his staff would not comment while the case is
pending before the appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts regulations would ban, within 1,000 feet of
schools and playgrounds, all tobacco advertising on billboards, ads
in stores and in their windows, and other promotions for
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area encompassed by the ban covers virtually the entire
populated area of Massachusetts,'' laywers for the industry argue
in their brief. They also argue that the ban eliminates much of the
ability of cigarette makers, distributors, and retailers to provide
consumers with ``truthful brand and pricing information.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulations would also ban the marketing of clothing such as
hats and shirts that carry tobacco logos and prohibit tobacco
sponsored cultural or sporting events.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the US Supreme Court ruling, the national
antismoking effort is realizing that the decision is in fact a
victory for regulation because states could take even more
aggressive control measures than what the FDA was doing.
</P>
<P>
   But the case also is a gamble. The Massachusetts case _ along
with a handful of other cases around the country _ is certain to
land in the Supreme Court, where the industry could prevail with a
ruling that essentially preempts states from regulating tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if the states prevail in the courts, the
aggressive lead by Massachusetts and other jurisdictions may very
likely force Congress to adopt strong national regulations.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments will center on the regulations issued by then
Attorney General Scott Harshbarger shortly before he left office
last year. Using the state's consumer protection laws, the attorney
general argued that the tobacco ads and promotions were ``unfair or
deceptive acts or practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The regulations also placed the cigar industry under the same
advertising restrictions and ordered that its packages for the
first time carry warning labels.
</P>
<P>
   Judge William G. Young, chief jurist in the Boston federal
district, issued a ruling in January that strongly backed Reilly's
arguments and rebuffed the industry's position. He described
cigarette advertising as ``functional pornography'' in the context
of the First Amendment and argument over free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both cigarette advertising and pornography are protected forms
of speech, reaching out to offer messages or products desired by
and legal for adults,'' Young wrote in his opinion. ``At the same
time we leave it to our government to seek to shield our children
form both the forms of speech, believing them to be either
inherently corrupting (pornography) or an inducement (cigarette
advertising) to engage in an activity unlawful for minors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
