<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9286 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LEWIS-SHOTS07-COX     04-06 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-SHOTS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bystander admits shots at Lewis car
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A man on Thursday admitted he was the person who
opened fire on Ray Lewis' stretch limousine as it sped away from an
Atlanta intersection where two men lay dying of stab wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Marlin Burros, 33, said he was a friend of Richard Lollar, 24,
and Jacinth Baker, 21, both of Decatur, Ga., who were stabbed to
death during a fight after a night of post-Super Bowl partying.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the All-Pro linebacker with the Baltimore Ravens, and two
associates, Reginald Oakley of Baltimore and Joseph Sweeting of
Miami, have been charged with murder in the stabbing deaths. They
go to trial May 15.
</P>
<P>
   The question of who fired the six shots at Lewis' limo has
lingered since the incident. No one was harmed by the shooting, but
one of the limo's tires was flattened. Emergency medical
technicians have told police that shell casings from the bullets
were found on top of and close to Baker's body.
</P>
<P>
   Burros has not been charged with firing the shots. Asked if he
expected to be prosecuted, he replied: ``I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Burros said he was walking far behind
his friends, who had just left the Cobalt, a lounge in Atlanta's
enterainment district. Burros said as he walked further up the
street, he saw Baker and Lollar lying on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement given to law enforcement authorities March 16,
Burros said he ran back to his 1999 GMC Yukon to retrieve his
.45-caliber semiautomatic handgun. Burros told authorities he
bought the gun three or four years ago in Ohio from a man he could
not identify.
</P>
<P>
   Burros said his Yukon was about 50 feet away from the
intersection. He told authorities he was in a state of shock and
fired because he wanted the people inside the limo to ``pay'' for
what they did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if they were dead,'' Burros said in the
telephone interview. ``But I knew they were badly hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Autopsy reports show that Baker and Lollar died of stab wounds
to the heart and chest.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, Oakley and Sweeting strongly deny the murder charges, and
some witnesses have said that Lollar and Baker instigated the
deadly fracas. In court motions, Sweeting's attorneys have said
Lollar may have been carrying a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Lollar and Baker have strongly denied that theory,
saying the deceased were not looking for a fight and were victims.
</P>
<P>
   Burros said he did not witness the fight that led to the
stabbings.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and three other friends drove away from the scene
before police and an ambulance arrived, leaving Baker and Lollar
lying on the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he drove away, Burros said: ``What do you
think?'' When pressed, he answered that he left the scene because
``I'd fired the weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
