<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-440-TRIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTIN BACKS AWAY FROM REGIONAL POLITICAL CONFRONTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ As President-elect Vladimir Putin flew
north beyond the Arctic circle this week to ride a nuclear powered
submarine and burnish his image as commander-in-chief, the event
that was making political waves was the scuttling of his
hand-picked candidate for governor of his home region here.
</P>
<P>
   In a humbling concession by Putin to the political strength and
popularity of the incumbent governor, Vladimir Yakolev, the new
Russian president on Tuesday recalled Valentina Matviyenko, his
first deputy prime minister, from her vacation and, according to
Matviyenko, asked her to pull out of the race she had entered with
the Kremlin's blessing less than a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   The decision, while viewed as politically pragmatic by political
observers here and in Moscow, was nonetheless seen as a galling
retreat for Putin, who has long reviled Yakolev as a ``Judas'' for
allegedly betraying his political loyalty to the late Anatoly
Sobchak, who died on Feb. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Sobchak, as mayor of St. Petersburg in the early 1990s, was
among the first generation of charismatic pro-democracy reformers
after the collapse of the Soviet Union. He recruited both Putin and
Yakolev as deputy mayors only to be ousted by Yakolev's insurgency
in the 1996 elections. Yakolev's victory put Putin out of a job
and, as Putin recently revealed in a series of interviews, ``I came
to the conclusion that working with Yakolev was impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Matviyenko announced she would bow to Putin's
request. She closed her campaign headquarters here at No. 1
Revolution St., saying, ``I am quitting the list of candidates, but
not the city.'' She will return to Moscow, she said, to help Putin
form a new government for his swearing in as president on May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, in remarks from Murmansk, as he prepared to take a dive
to 1,300 feet in a Delta-class ballistic missile submarine and then
observe a series of missile firings, offered a somewhat different
account by saying that it was Matviyenko's decision to withdraw
from the race and that when he asked her to return to Moscow, ``I
didn't mean that she should stop her election campaign. After all,
I conducted my campaign while carrying on working.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president-elect added that ``we were coming to a
critical moment in forming the government, and she is one of the
most successful social ministers. I needed her to join our work.''
</P>
<P>
   Reiterating her own account, Matviyenko told campaign workers
the same day, ``I was sure about my victory until Vladimir Putin
convinced me to change my decision.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Political analysts here and in Moscow, said the decision to end
the Kremlin-backed campaign against Yakolev reflects Putin's
recognition not only that his deputy was likely to lose in the May
14 balloting here, but also that the Kremlin could not afford an
antagonistic battle with a regional boss like Yakolev at a time
when Moscow is preparing to undertake a much anticipated economic
reform program in the wake of last month's presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision shows that Putin's priority is to put together a
strong team on the federal level, and this is much more important
to him than fighting a war with Yakolev,'' said Grigory Tomchin, a
liberal member of the national parliament, or Duma, from St.
Petersburg. ``And from the beginning, it was also clear that
Matviyenko was not the best candidate to defeat Yakolev.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Sergei Fetishev, a seasoned political journalist who
covers city hall here, `` Putin had to face the reality of local
power, and therefore it is definitely something of a blow to his
image.''
</P>
<P>
   The worst outcome would have been for Putin to back a loser, as
he did in December when he supported an insurgent candidate against
the powerful mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov, said Sergei Markov, the
director of the Institute of Political Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``To lose in another important region would not look good for
his image,'' Markov said, ``and that is why he decided to join a
winner,'' however personally distasteful that might have been.
``It's a signal that he puts political interests higher than
personal relations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts also saw the hand of Russia's most prominent
oligarch, Boris Berezovsky, shoring up Yakolev's candidacy in an
effort to sway the Kremlin to do the same. ``We need to ensure the
continuity of power, especially in the regions,'' Berezovsky was
quoted today as saying in the Moscow Times. He added, ``Yakolev has
made many mistakes, but the alternative candidate was just not
strong enough to control the problems plaguing the city.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the serious problems here are the organized crime
syndicates who frequently stage contract killings in broad daylight
along the canals and tree-lined esplanades of the city. In the most
recent, on Wednesday, Gennadi Ivanov, 35, the general director of a
textile conglomerate that employs 4,000 people, was fatally shot by
a man who walked up to his blue Volvo 950 when it stopped at a
pedestrian crosswalk near his home.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious assassination here of a liberal
parliamentarian, Galina Starovoitova, who was gunned down in her
stairwell in November 1998, remains unsolved _ like hundreds of
others.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Putin was vaulted into the prime minister's post and
then the presidency, Yakolev's position has been seen as vulnerable
to challenge by a strong Kremlin-backed candidate. Matviyenko's
entry into the race, at first appeared as a settling of accounts
until opinion polls revealed that she was not making headway
against Yakolev's popularity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yakolev may be an alcoholic or even a crook, but he has done a
lot for the city,'' said Sergei Kilmenko, 33, a former army captain
who was on the streets today looking for a job. ``Matviyenko is
seen as a wooden, Communist youth type of person, and the mafia
structure here would have squashed her in no time.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Like Peter the Great, who founded this city of Venetian canals
and palaces on the banks of the Neva River, Yakolev is also known
as a builder who keeps the roads repaired, pays the pensioners on
time and manages to find restoration funds to keep the city's
baroque palaces and monuments from crumbling into the canals. In
his plodding and unflashy manner, Yakolev has forged a broad-based
local political machine that for now seems as unassailable as the
Peter and Paul fortress that secured this swampy territory as
Russia's capital for two centuries.
</P>
<P>
   With one serious rival out of the way, Yakolev Thursday plunged
confidently into another day of campaigning among workers at a
pasta factory in the suburbs, visiting workers' dormitories and
avoiding questions about his own mysterious trips to Moscow last
week and again on Monday, the day before Matviyenko's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   As St. Petersburg prepares to host the world ice hockey
championships on April 29, Yakolev is taking most of the credit for
having secured the venue. The governor is also giving away tens of
thousands of free tickets to citizens who help clean up the city
this month, an offer that some critics see as a blatant form of
vote buying just weeks before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked under Sobchak and he understands the rules of the
game,'' Klimenko said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
