<SLUG> BC-CUBA-BOY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN FATHER DECRIES TREATMENT OF REFUGEE SON IN US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT AND LYNDA GOROV  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Standing on common soil with his 6-year-old son
for the first time in more than four months, Juan Miguel Gonzalez
unleashed a torrent of angry words against Elian's guardians in
Miami Thursday, even as US officials indicated as much confidence
as ever that the boy would soon be returned to his father's care.
</P>
<P>
   Saying Elian had been subjected to ``cruel psychological
pressures'' by ``some distant relatives who had never seen him
before,'' Gonzalez, 31, vowed to reclaim custody of the boy as soon
as possible. He delivered the heated remarks at a dramatic airport
news conference shortly after dawn, then retreated, with his wife
and infant child, to the suburban Washington home of a Cuban
official for the rest of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   His appearance in the nation's capital did little to deter
public attacks from the Miami relatives of Elian, who have cared
for the child since his ill-fated sea journey from Cuba last
Thanksgiving, and who have resisted every entreaty to send the boy
back home. Late Thursday, as talks between the Miami relatives and
federal attorneys broke down, a family spokesman said the
Immigration and Naturalization Service had announced it would carry
out its longstanding threat: to revoke Elian's parole and transfer
custody to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, an attorney for the Miami relatives, said
that despite 40 hours of negotiation the US officials refused to
make a single concession. That resistance remained strong with
Thursday's arrival of Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government will not guarantee that it will not take Elian
away or try to take Elian away in the middle of the night,''
Pedrosa said at a news conference outside the Miami federal
courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton viewed Gonzalez's arrival as a ``positive step
toward ultimately reuniting a father with his son,'' White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart said. INS spokeswoman Maria Cardona said
Gonzalez's presence ``adds an immediacy'' to the agency's goal of
resolving the case, which has resurrected four-decade-old tensions
between Cuba and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe his being in the United States will help us,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by late afternoon, officials could not report any
progress in resolving the greatest public relations puzzle: exactly
how Elian might be turned over to his father's care.
</P>
<P>
   The family expects to be told where to deliver Elian to Gonzalez
or US representatives as early as Monday. But protesters, many of
them Cubans who fled the regime of Fidel Castro years ago, are
conducting a near-round-the-clock vigil outside the Miami home
where Elian is currently housed, making it virtually impossible for
US officials to retrieve the boy against the relatives' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, protesters suggested they would block even Gonzalez
from taking his son away _ although Gregory B. Craig, the attorney
for the father, indicated he was unlikely to show up in such a
hostile environment anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Gonzalez's arrival and attempt to communicate
through the media did not convince the Miami protesters of his
sincerity in wanting the best for his son. After watching his
speech, broadcast live on national TV, many dismissed Gonzalez's
words as too impersonal, too controlled, to have been written by
anyone but Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Cancio, 27, and the mother of a boy around Elian's age,
said she remained convinced the boy is better off with distant
relatives in Miami than with his father in Havana. She said she
believes that ``deep down'' Gonzalez knows it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just reading a speech today,'' she said. ``Those were
written words and they aren't his words.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rita Oliva, a 32-year-old college student and mother of a
13-year-old son, put it: ``I think Fidel Castro should win the
Oscar for best director. And did you see that suit they had made
for him? He looked like a puppet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez arrived from Havana wearing a tailored, dark blue suit
and a lighter blue shirt and tie. After flying in by private jet,
he greeted a throng of reporters at the airport, with his wife,
Nersy, holding their 6-month-old, Hianny.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke through a translator, appearing quietly angry but
controlled. At one point, a handful of anti-Castro protesters
shouted so loudly that Gonzalez could hardly be heard. Later,
critics said it was a mistake for him to appear in Washington at
all.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a sad day,'' Ninoska Perez, a spokeswoman for the
Cuban American National Foundation, said. ``We have said from the
beginning that we welcome Juan Miguel in the United States. It's
just sad he took the plane to Washington and not to Miami to come
and embrace his son.''
</P>
<P>
   If Gonzalez does regain custody of Elian, he will be free to
leave for Cuba immediately, an INS official said.
</P>
<P>
   But as part of the ongoing negotiations, Gonzalez has agreed to
stay in the United States until all the custody proceedings are
resolved. The INS ruled in early January that the Miami relatives
should return Elian to his father, and it has been widely assumed
ever since that the 6-year-old will eventually go home. But his
Miami relatives have appealed to a federal court in Atlanta, where
the case is scheduled to be heard May 11. If that fails, the
relatives' only remaining course would be an appeal to the US
Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   An INS official said the agency expected Elian to be returned to
his father long before the May 11 court date.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Miami relatives had demanded that
government psychologists examine Elian and accept their
recommendations concerning the boy's future. Thursday, lawyers for
the relatives said the government had balked. Attorney Roger
Bernstein said: ``The government is still unwilling to speak to
Elian and understand what he is feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kornblut reported from Maryland and Washington; Gorov reported from
Miami.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
