<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCENROE, SAMPRAS LEAD US INTO DAVIS CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pete and Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it Mac and Pete?
</P>
<P>
   Which one gets top billing _ rookie captain John McEnroe or
newly enlisted Pete Sampras _ is a tough decision as the Davis Cup
marquee is hoisted Friday in the City of Angels, and their team,
the United States, goes against the Czech Republic in a
best-of-five quarterfinal series. And don't forget Andre, of the
Las Vegas Agassis, who is No. 1 in the diversion called
professional tennis.
</P>
<P>
   But it's pious Pete and non-angelic Mac, back together again
after eight years, who make you wonder. Is this the start of a
beautiful friendship? Or just a
let's-get-along-for-appearance-sake, a symbiotic relationship that
could bust a US drought in the Davis Cup dating back to the 1995
victory over Russia, 3-2, crafted virtually by Sampras?
</P>
<P>
   ``John questioned my integrity,'' said Pete Thursday. ``That
made me very uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   His brown eyes were grave as he stood in a corner of the Forum,
the arena where he'll lead off against top Czech, No. 39 Jiri
Novak, this afternoon. Agassi follows against Slava Dosedel, No.
48, with the order flip-flopped Sunday. Doubles (Alex O'Brien and
Jared Palmer against Novak and David Rikl) is the middle match
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very uncomfortable week for me, sitting home
watching it on TV, thinking over what John said.'' recalled Pete,
of the February US win over Zimbabwe, 3-2, that he missed because
of a hip injury incurred while losing an Aussie Open semifinal to
Agassi the previous week. When Pete, who had committed to play,
withdrew from the team, McEnroe commented in a ghosted column under
his name in an Australian newspaper that he never believed Sampras
would show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, nobody wanted to go to Africa right after the
Australian. It was tough on Andre,'' said Pete. ``But I intended to
go. My dad had bought a plane ticket to go to Zimbabwe to watch me.
I've never gone back on my commitments, and John's opinion hurt a
lot. He questioned my integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some phone conversations, and worked it out. He
apologized, so here I am. You know, I don't think there has to be a
lot of talking (between captain and player). That's not my way. I
think it's going to go OK with John. We've got a team that won't be
beat if we play our games.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe is smart enough to say, ``Am I going to tell Pete, or
Andre, how to win? They've been here before. Since I played on some
pretty good teams (five Cups between 1978 and 1992), I'm just going
to say, when some people say, `this is the greatest team the US has
ever had,' that Pete and Andre are two of the greatest ever to pick
up a racket. And Alex and Jared are a very fine doubles team.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper we shouldn't lose a match here. But the good thing
about sports _ and strange things can happen in Davis Cup _ is it's
not scripted.''
</P>
<P>
   Frequently reluctant Pete hasn't started for the US since 1997,
when he suffered a leg injury against Magnus Larsson in the final
at Sweden, a 5-0 defeat, on the first day. During his last
meaningful Cup performance, five years ago on clay in Moscow, he
won both singles (over Andrei Chesnokov and Yevgeny Kafelnikov) and
the doubles, with Todd Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Pete's pouty regret was that the White House didn't summon him
for a Presidential audience. ``Where I'm at now in my career,''
said Sampras, ``I want to get more into Davis Cup. I didn't think I
could do both, stay No. 1 (a pro record six straight years,
1993-98), and give myself wholeheartedly to Davis Cup. Now I want
to.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras says this isn't a reaction to McEnroe's very public
campaign to shame him into re-enlisting, asserting often, ``It's
time for Pete to do his duty.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing John did,'' said Sampras. ``I just wanted to be
part of it'' _ and almost wasn't when Mac got a little too
personal.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago Sampras said he would never play for
McEnroe if Mac got the captaincy. They had last teamed in the 1992
final, victorious doubles accomplices in a wild five-set comeback
over Jakob Hlasek and Mark Rosset as the US barely defeated
Switzerland. Pete, the antithesis of Mac on court, didn't
appreciate his partner's vitriolic tongue in spewing foul insults
at the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe, 40, claims his parental role as father of six has
tempered his famously tempestuous deportment. ``I'm going to try to
just not be in the way. I think we've found a comfort level as a
team where this should be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief comfort-leveler has been US Tennis Association president
Julia Levering, largely responsible for the Pete and Mac and Andre
mosaic.
</P>
<P>
   She chose McEnroe after consulting the players. (``First time
the team has been part of the decision-making,'' said Agassi.) She
retrieved Agassi, who had quit in a huff last year when team
physician and close friend George Fareed was fired, one of those
bureaucratic goofs for which the USTA is justly celebrated. She
``was impressive when she talked to me about playing again,'' said
Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically Petes's curious behavior last July in Boston probably
landed the job for Mac. Rejoining the team for a doubles cameo in
the quarterfinal loss to Australia, he declined to play singles, an
activity at which he is the planetary best. Had Sampras led a very
possible victory, the US might well have gone on to win the Cup
(seized by Australia), and surely his pal, Tom Gullikson, would
have remained in charge.
</P>
<P>
   Fareed, by the way, says Agassi's sprained right ankle that may
have cost him the Ericsson Open semifinal last week against Guga
Kuerten, is ``fully recovered. But it will be taped.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Agassi breakdown would encourage the Czechs, victors
over Britain in the opening round. ``We don't have nothing to lose.
There's no pressure on us,'' said Jiri Novak, correctly. It looks
4-1, US, from here, and a trip to either Spain or Russia for a July
semifinal, most likely on dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Although Andre and Pete are ranked Nos. 1 and 2 and
O'Brien-Palmer are world No. 1 in their precinct, Mac is in no
hurry to annoint them as incomparables. He recalls the last such
glittering lineup, considerably before his minions' time: 1984.
Then Mac himself and Jimmy Connors were 1-2, and Mac and Peter
Fleming No. 1. That ``greatest team of all-time'' reached the
final. But the inconsiderate hosts staged it not on paper but on
messier clay in Goteborg, and the Americans were upstaged, 4-1, by
Sweden.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
