<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-NETWATCH0404-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Record companies should make digital downloads play to their
tune
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Even bad publicity is good publicity,'' the saying
goes. When it comes to digital downloads that's especially true.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Napster.com (www.napster.com). Napster offers
free downloads of a program that searches the Web for MP3 digital
music files and lets users download, share them and play them back
with Napster software.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is so easy to use that it became a favorite with college
students around the country. In fact, as you read this, they are
downloading and playing digital music files over the high-speed
Internet connections most colleges and universities provide.
</P>
<P>
   Before anyone goes running off to download Napster with the
notion of hopping on the digital music bandwagon, it's important to
note that most online digital music files are bootlegs that are not
authorized by the artist or the recording company. If you download
the latest from the Smashing Pumpkins, Moby or Santana, it won't
cost you anything, but the artists don't make a dime _ not one red
cent. Many artists are more than a little upset about this, and the
Recording Industry Association of America is extremely upset.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the RIAA sued Napster, charging that its software
makes illegal music distribution easier. RIAA is asking for
$100,000 for each illegally distributed song.
</P>
<P>
   Also being sued for copyright infringement is MP3.com, the first
digital download ``portal'' that helps music lovers locate recorded
music available over the Internet. MP3.com has always defended its
business, saying that if the music industry would just stop
worrying and learn to love the Internet, there would be a way for
everybody to make money.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com founder Michael Robertson believes the music industry
should have taken the lead in providing a distribution method for
selling its wares online. Robertson said that way, there wouldn't
be so many ordinary people sifting through CD collections and
uploading digital copies of their favorite songs.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com has recently added a new section to its Web site called
``Lawsuit Central'' where users can read up on the latest salvos in
its ongoing battle with the music business.
(www.mp3.com/news/546.html).
</P>
<P>
   Although MP3.com is one of the most popular sites on the Web,
it's busy, complicated and hard to use. In an odd way, this has
worked to the record companies' advantage. If the average user
can't figure out how to download music files, then the industry
didn't have much to worry about. But then Napster came along and
changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   Napster is so easy to use, all users have to do is type in the
name of their favorite musicians and _ poof _ thousands of songs
pop up on the screen. Click on the one you want to download and in
a matter of minutes or hours (depending on your modem speed) you
have CD quality music on your PC.
</P>
<P>
   This is not good for the record industry, which now finds itself
looking at an easy-to-use program designed to download digital
music that they could have come up with themselves if they had
taken a long, analytical look at the Web a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications analyst Aram Sinnreich says Napster is a
very low-tech program that is very easy to replicate. He sees
Napster, not as something music companies should try to stomp out
or buy, but one that they should adapt to suit their own needs.
``It's all about more flexible product formats,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The RIAA suit is a vain attempt to make Napster and MP3.com
simply go away. But ironically, every stand the record industry
takes against online downloads seems to fan the flames and the
demand for online digital music.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is all the publicity. The very existence of Napster
first became known to mainstream music lovers because of the
lawsuit and efforts by Indiana University and Oregon State
University to block students from using the software. The colleges
said the high volume of students downloading music was taking up
too much bandwidth. This in turn, set off a storm of protest from
students. There is a ``Save Napster'' Web site
(www.savenapster.com) which calls the ban a form of censorship.
There are online blueprints outlining ways to circumvent the
university computer network. It also sparked a huge and continuing
debate over copyright and censorship laws on the World Wide Web
Artists Consortium (WWWAC) e-mail list of Silicon Alley insiders.
All of the interest has raised the profile of Napster, which has in
turn raised interest in digital downloads. Good for Napster, bad
for the RIAA.
</P>
<P>
   All the fussing and shouting is increasing interest and demand.
Maybe it will finally move the record companies to do what
Jupiter's Sinnreich suggests: Finally develop their own Web
business mode similar to Napster but incorporating some way to make
money from it. While the lawyers work on copyright protection,
maybe a few designers should be working on their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-03-00 1038EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
