 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Best search engine results come from knowing right techniques
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ By now you are probably a veteran of the Web, with
dozens of bookmarks that help you return to the sites that fit into
your work and personal life. As long as you are searching for the
kind of information that falls within your usual routine, you
probably navigate your way along the Web efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   But the real problems come when you need to get outside that
normal box. If you spend most of your time comfortably learning
about epoxy chemicals and suddenly need to find information on
beekeeping, you may have to spend some time searching unfamiliar
areas to find what you need.
</P>
<P>
   That's where a search engine comes in. Because all use slightly
different techniques, it's a good idea to check the help section to
find out the best way to structure your search. To give an example
of how you can use good technique to make a search easier, we'll
start our search of search engines with AltaVista, at
www.altavista.com.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is to avoid getting off-topic hits. So if you're
looking for information about your old friend Bill Husted on
AltaVista, you don't want to type that name in the keyword area. If
you do it that way, you'd get all the Bills of the Web and all the
Husteds. One way to narrow a search on AltaVista is to use the +
symbol before a word. If you search that way, and use this search
(+Bill +Husted) you'll get pages that must contain both names.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the best way. What you really want is a page with
the exact name. To get that, you need to put the name in quotes
like this: ``Bill Husted''. And that same technique works, of
course, if you want pages that contain the exact phrase ``for whom
the bell tolls'' ... you'd put the phrase in quotes.
</P>
<P>
   Now let's move over to Yahoo, at www.yahoo.com, one of the
oldest of the general purpose search engines on the Web. It's handy
to know that the use of quote marks in a search term works exactly
the same way here. But there's a characteristic of Yahoo _ based on
the way it searches _ that can be of great help.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first choices you'll see, if you do a Yahoo search,
is the fact that almost any search will return _ besides specific
Web pages that contain your search term _ a broader Yahoo category
that relates to your search. Here's an example that will help you
understand how that works. Let's say that you are searching for
garden seeds for spring planting. You'll get a list of companies
offering garden seeds that way, but you'll also get a list of
categories _ for instance, ``Business and Economy-Companies-Home
and Garden-Lawn and Garden-Seeds''
</P>
<P>
   (click on them and you'll be taken to a list of companies and
sites that fall within that category). That's a handy way to let
Yahoo do a lot of the searching work for you.
</P>
<P>
   A newer search engine that is really developing a big following
of fans is Google at www.google.com. If you know how to use
AltaVista, you already know how to use search terms on Google for
the most part. You can use the + symbol to require that a word be
included in the search and the - sign to require that a term not be
included.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at the use of the - sign in a search. Let's say that
you want to find out about the American eagle but that you're
interested in the bird, not an airline with that same name. So you
could frame a search this way (''American eagle'' -airline) and be
sure that you won't get hits from pages that discuss the airline or
flight schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-03-00 1038EDT &QL;
</P>
