<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9300 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RECRUITING-PROBE-BOS &LR;      04-06 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECRUITING-PROBE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROWN UNIVERSITY PROBED FOR TEAM RECRUITING VIOLATONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ABEL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least five sports teams at Brown University are being
investigated for allegedly violating Ivy League recruiting
regulations, university and Ivy league officials confirmed
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Brown officials are expected to file a report as early as Friday
detailing the results of its own investigation, university
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of improper recruiting of athletes for the
incoming 2000 class prompted Brown in early February to launch a
review of its policy of awarding ``supplemental financial awards''
to attractive athletic prospects, said Laura Freid, a Brown
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are technicalities that I can't get into that might have
been only available to athletes,'' she said. ``But there may have
been unintended consequences to changes in our policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring the moves of other Ivy League schools, Brown in
February of 1999 amended its financial aid policies to allow
students to use non-university or supplemental scholarships to
defray tuition costs.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, students, including star athletes, had to rely on
grants, loans and other forms of aid provided by the university.
Grants gained from other sources (such as neighborhood rotary clubs
or companies) would offset the amount of aid the university gave.
</P>
<P>
   The change, however, has opened up the university to charges of
luring athletes with financial aid packages unavailable to other
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the specific sports that are really the issue,'' said
Carolyn Campbell-McGovern, senior associate director of the Ivy
League athletic conference office based in Princeton, N.J. ``It's
the way the athletes were recruited.''
</P>
<P>
   Freid, Campbell-McGovern, and NCAA officials all said they were
reluctant to discuss the specifics of the allegations, which
include how Brown's basketball team recruited its players. But they
said the investigation should be concluded and any penalties
against Brown made public by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Such penalties could parallel the punishment of the University
of Pennsylvania in 1997, which was forced to forfeit several
football victories after an investigation disclosed the team had
used ineligible players.
</P>
<P>
   There are no other investigations of similar alleged violations
at other Ivy League schools, Campbell-McGovern said. The Ivy League
is the only NCAA Division I conference that doesn't award athletic
scholarships. Athletes, like star students, lured to such schools
receive an array of grants, cushy campus jobs and low-interest
loans.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its relatively limited financial resources, Brown,
unlike Yale, Harvard, and Princeton, has traditionally had to rely
more on loans than grants, which don't have to be paid back. And,
Freid said, that has often rankled Brown's coaches, who have lost
many promising prospects to other Ivy League schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The change in our policy was meant to encourage all students
in finding outside scholarships,'' she said. ``We're now looking
into any complications in that process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
