<SLUG> BC-SCI-NEW-PLANET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PLANET IS A MERE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Hawaii)   By JAMES GLANZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What some astronomers believed to be the only planet ever
directly observed outside the solar system has turned out to be an
ordinary dim star, NASA announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent discovery, announced in May, 1998, will also be
retracted in a forthcoming paper whose lead author is Dr. Susan
Terebey, the astronomer at Extrasolar Research Corp. in Pasadena,
Calif., who led the team that made the original observations.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the original announcement, NASA was strongly
criticized in an editorial in the journal Nature for announcing the
results at a news conference before they had been critiqued by the
scientific community. ``One does not need to read between lines to
perceive a deep need within NASA for publicity,'' the editorial
said.
</P>
<P>
   Terebey and her colleagues made the original observations using
the Hubble Space Telescope. The observations seemed to reveal a dim
``rogue planet'' moving away from a double star system in the
constellation Taurus. Seemingly connecting the object to the star
system was a streamer of reflective dust.
</P>
<P>
   Follow-up observations with the Keck Telescope in Hawaii have
revealed that the object is far too hot to be a planet. According
to a NASA news release issued Thursday, the object is more likely
to be a dim star, perhaps partly obscured by dust, that happens to
lie almost directly behind the double star system. The news release
did not say what the apparent streamer might be.
</P>
<P>
   Terebey's paper, which is scheduled to appear in the May issue
of Astronomical Journal, does not cast doubt on the approximately
30 extrasolar planets that have been detected indirectly. The
existence of those planets was inferred by observing a wobble in
their parent stars.
</P>
<P>
   Tereby was traveling abroad Thursday and could not be reached
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past few months the skepticism has been growing about
this,'' said Dr. Robert W. Noyes, an astrophysicist at the
Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics. ``I guess a formal
retraction was expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Donald Savage, the public affairs officer for space science at
NASA headquarters, rejected the criticism directed at the agency by
Nature. ``Their premise was that we should only do press
conferences on peer reviewed material,'' he said. ``That is no
guarantee that things are true or valid or factual. We felt it was
in the public interest to put it out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alan Boss, an astrophysicist at the Carnegie Institution of
Washington who was involved in the original news conference, said,
``at the time of the press conference, the weight of the evidence
was that it was a planet.'' He added that while the evidence now
favors a background star, planet discoveries are ``a fast-breaking
field'' in which announcements often occur before a final
confirmation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
