<HEADER>
A9305 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-PATENTS-595&AMP;ADD-N     04-06 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-PATENTS-595&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATENTS: E-COMMERCE SPURS CHANGES AT PATENT OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By SABRA CHARTRAND   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a couple of minor changes, officials at the federal agency
responsible for patents and trademarks last week began what they
say is a program to make the organization more efficient and
responsive to inventors, patent holders and intellectual-property
lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The real import of the changes, however, appears to lie not in
the patent office's efforts to streamline operations, but in
revised procedures for handling the increasing number of
applications for Internet-related patents, like those in business
method software and electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, many of the changes appear cosmetic. The
agency once known as the Patent and Trademark Office renamed itself
the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office last Wednesday. It also
changed its leader's title from commissioner to director.
</P>
<P>
   But other changes are more substantive. In return for meeting
specific goals in customer service and performance, the agency is
released from government protocols on hiring, procurement and
budget-handling. Other reforms include eliminating employee sign-in
sheets, offering flexible working hours and developing new
procedures for buying computers.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are intended to inaugurate the agency's new role as
a so-called performance-based organization, an element of Vice
President Al Gore's program to reinvent government. Only one other
agency has metamorphosed this way, the Office of Student Financial
Assistance in the Education Department.
</P>
<P>
   But while promoting its makeover last week, the patent and
trademark agency also took the opportunity to address a heated
controversy over the way it handles business method software
patents, a category that includes patents on ways of doing business
on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to complaints that the agency's examiners are too
quick to patent basic methods of doing business, Q. Todd Dickinson,
the office's director, announced plans for increased training,
supervision and review of examiners, as well as a program to reach
out to the software and computer industries for help in
understanding technology and business trends.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a good job of examining business methods patents now,''
Dickinson insisted. ``We keep up very well. But this area is as
cutting-edge as can be; it's emerging so fast that we've got to
ensure the public's level of confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dickinson said the new procedures were part of the
agency's long-planned transformation, they came after months of
mounting reproach from outsiders over the agency's awarding of
patents for simple online business methods like ``one-click''
shopping, reverse auctions, customer profiling and electronic
payment systems.
</P>
<P>
   The explosion in e-commerce has been followed by a boom in
business method software patents, as more entrepreneurs and
investors realize the value of owning a way to do business on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997 the agency created a separate department for processing
those patents. At the time, 12 examiners were assigned to evaluate
920 applications. The next year the number of applications
increased to 1,300, and they doubled in 1999 to 2,600. By then, 40
examiners were working on them.
</P>
<P>
   Each application takes an average 26 months to process, compared
with 18 months for general patents. In 1999, 583 business method
software patents were issued.
</P>
<P>
   The agency issued 161,000 patents overall in 1999, so the number
of business method software patents was still a small fraction of
the total. Still, they are a crucial component of the
high-technology economy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Critics have said the agency approves such patents too readily
because its examiners do not understand current technology and
Internet practices well enough. They have charged the agency with
hampering competition and innovation by allowing commonplace
business practices to be rendered private property, and with
restricting innovation by entrepreneurs wary of infringement
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``That argument has been made many times and has never proved to
be the case,'' Dickinson countered. ``On the contrary, patents spur
innovation.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited the dispute over a patent for ``one-click'' shopping
that was awarded to Jeffrey Bezos, the chief executive of
Amazon.com. The patent is one of the most contested, and is at the
center of a long court battle. But Dickinson believed it resulted
from a process that is intended to encourage innovation and reward
it through patent protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that Barnes &AMP; Noble has now invented a new system,''
he added. ``I understand they created something better. That's how
innovation works.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the patent office seems to have concluded that
some of these patents might deserve greater scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   The new procedures sound remarkably similar to those begun in
1994, after a crisis over patents for software-related inventions.
At the time, the agency was denounced for awarding undeserved
patents because its examiners were not trained software engineers,
were unaware of the latest innovations in software and lacked
comprehensive research materials.
</P>
<P>
   The patent office countered with plans to face the future by
hiring new examiners and training them for two years, and by
expanding its meager software library. Yet the future has arrived,
bringing software for Internet business practices with it, along
with renewed charges from critics that the agency is still
unprepared and continues to award patents for universal practices.
</P>
<P>
   Dickinson made it clear that even though his agency might be
redoubling its hiring and training to process this new type of
software patent application, there will be no re-evaluation of the
merit of business method patents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inventors who worked at a workbench or in a garage are now
online,'' he said. ``But they're still creating inventions they
deserve to have protected, so people can't come along and rip them
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Patents may be viewed on the Web at www.uspto.gov or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office, Washington, DC 20231.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-04-02-00 1811EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
