<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECHNO-SCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-FLIERS SHARE THE WEALTH WITH THEIR OLD SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALEX PHAM   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOODSIDE, Calif. _ In this enclave of fabulous wealth sits a
public school that works hard to blend in with its unassuming
surroundings, lest it betray its high-profile benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   The school, which runs from kindergarten through eighth grade,
counts among its friends Larry Ellison, chief executive of Oracle
Corp. and unofficial Silicon Valley playboy; L. John Doerr, the
uber-venture capitalist who has funded Amazon.com and Netscape;
and, Scott Cook, cofounder of Intuit Inc.
</P>
<P>
   All like to give generously to the school's multimillion-dollar
foundation through an annual auction that has come to symbolize the
power of new money. At last year's auction, described in caustic
and hilarious detail in David Kaplan's recently published book
``The Silicon Boys,'' Ellison offered a week in the French Riviera
on his 192-foot yacht, complete with an 11-person crew. The outing
went for $125,000, thrusting the total amount raised to $439,000
(of which $99,000 went to pay for the auction itself).
</P>
<P>
   The winning bid was lobbed by Bruce Thompson, superintendent of
the Woodside School District. Thompson, it turns out, was bidding
on behalf of a Woodside resident rumored to be J. Taylor Crandall,
financial adviser to the Bass family.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson discreetly declined to confirm the rumor but gracefully
agreed to give a tour of his 580-student school. The tour begins in
a kindergarten classroom decked out in tiny blue chairs and red
Play-Doh. Thompson explained that the school gets about $4,400 in
state funding for each pupil, but the Woodside School Foundation
kicks in another $3,000 per student.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would be very ordinary if it weren't for our parents,''
said Thompson, a slender mustachioed man whom students greet as
``Mr. T.''
</P>
<P>
   He points out the various extras afforded by the foundation.
There are two full-time reading specialists, a full-time librarian,
a dedicated art teacher, and a half-time math specialist who,
Thompson carefully notes, has a doctorate in mathematics. Their
salaries are paid primarily from earmarked foundation dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``These poor teachers. I don't know how they can continue to
live here,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 40 teachers at Woodside live in the town,
where the average home sale price was $1,592,625 in February,
according to the San Mateo County Association of Realtors. Teacher
salaries average only $32,000, Thompson noted. He does not explain
how teachers feel about a seventh-grade math assignment in which
students are asked to spend $1 million imaginary dollars and
display the results on a spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   The tour continues to the school's science center, a building
that came about entirely from two $500,000 donations. The
classrooms have views of a idyllic green lawn surrounded by tall
native oak trees.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation is occasionally interrupted by the din of
construction crews working on a $12 million project that will add a
gym and six new classrooms. About half of the bill will be footed
by the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to make his school appear as normal as possible,
Thompson mentions that many public schools in California now have
foundations, including those in neighboring Portola Valley,
Hillsborough, Atherton, and Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, public school foundations are ubiquitous in California,
said Michael Kirst, professor of education at Stanford University.
But the average amount of voluntary contributions is about $100 per
student, making Woodside's foundation a statistical ``outlier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Woodside is a very unusual community,'' Kirst said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't exist on state dollars,'' Thompson said. He
explained that Proposition 13, the state's 1978 initiative that
limited property taxes to 1 percent of the property's value, put a
severe crimp on the amount of money spent on public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley's insta-wealth has changed this horsey, old-money
community, said Thompson, who has been at Woodside School for 15
years and is retiring later this year to teach at Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mentality of Silicon Valley is that everything has to be
done yesterday,'' said Thompson, who has taken to reading Fortune
and Business Week magazines to better understand his student's
parents. ``That does come into the school. The kids are so highly
programmed that they practically need a Palm Pilot to figure out
where they need to go next. More is better. And the parents are
always negotiating with you.''
</P>
<P>
   The school tries to tone down the Valley's hypercompetitive
culture by requiring that each student perform at least 30 hours of
community service between their sixth and eighth grades.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to teach them to give from the heart,'' Thompson said.
``Many of them will be our future philantropists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can be
reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
