u k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN06-COX-     04-06 0839
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN06-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST Update
 &HT;    EDs: Clarifies Texas' coverage of contraceptives in 11th graf.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Crusading for women, and against Bush
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ How ironic: Two early stalwarts of Planned
Parenthood were George W. Bush's paternal grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   Now the national president of the Planned Parenthood Federation
of America is trying to make sure women around the country know
that the grandson _ the Texas governor and Republican presidential
nominee _opposes a woman's right to an abortion except in cases of
rape or incest or to protect the mother's life.
</P>
<P>
   Texan Gloria Feldt, who was born in Temple, graduated from high
school in Stamford in West Texas and started her career with
Planned Parenthood in Odessa, is the driving force behind the new
pro-active stance of the longtime family planning organization.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt, 57, who has three kids and four grandkids, is traveling
the country, focusing on college campuses. She's warning younger
women that reproductive rights they take for granted may be at
stake in this year's
</P>
<P>
   election.
</P>
<P>
   She's very aware of some male-female ironies. For instance, the
birth control pill celebrates its 40th birthday this month _ but
most insurance plans still don't cover its use, Feldt said. Yet
``when Viagra came out, insurance plans instantly covered it _
instantly!'' Feldt said. ``So male sexual performance was obviously
more important than women's reproductive health.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's a big issue. It's one of those little injustices
that people tended not to know about, and we're making sure that
they know about them.''
</P>
<P>
   The newly aggressive Planned Parenthood organization set up an
independent political arm and a political action committee in 1998
so it could endorse candidates and let voters know its stands on
reproductive
</P>
<P>
   rights issues, Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   The committee pushed issues to ``hold legislators feet to the
fire,'' such as forcing insurance plans to cover contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It surprises most people to know that only about a third of
insurance plans cover contraception routinely, and very few plans
cover all medically approved methods,'' Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   The group pushed that issue in Congress and before state
legislatures, and now federal employees' contraceptive items are
covered, and nine state legislatures have required insurance plans
covering prescription drugs to include contraceptives, Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, through a Texas Department of Insurance regulation, since
1978 has required coverage of oral contraceptives by insurance
plans that cover prescription drugs. But coverage of other forms of
contraception, like patches and injections, is not mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Feldt's target this year is Bush. While Planned Parenthood ``is
a quintessentially nonpartisan organization,'' Feldt said ``that
doesn't stop us from doing voter education.''
</P>
<P>
   And in election year 2000, her organization, which an aide says
has more than 5 million women visiting its 900-plus service
delivery centers annually, plans to make sure Americans know about
Bush's stands on
</P>
<P>
   reproductive health and rights issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has generally soft-pedaled his pro-life stance during
elections in Texas. But in competing for his party's presidential
nomination this year, he became more outspoken. For instance, he
said the Roe decision ``was a reach (and) overstepped the
constitutional bounds.''
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush has already announced himself to be the most
anti-abortion governor in the country,'' Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made the arrogant statement that Americans hearts
aren't right; that's why he can't outlaw abortion altogether just
yet,'' she said. ``But I suppose he thinks he's going to put our
hearts right. I find that about as insulting as anything I've ever
heard _ as if our hearts are not up to his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, several polls show Bush ``has been very good at
obfuscating his position, and in making it sound as though he's not
an extremist, and so therefore he won't make it a big issue,''
Feldt said. But, she reminded, in the U.S. Supreme Court, ``Roe vs.
Wade hangs by a one-vote thread right now _ one vote.'' The next
president will probably have several appointments to the court,
Feldt said.
</P>
<P>
   If history is a guide, as the November general election nears,
Bush and Democratic nominee Al Gore will move toward the center on
issues such as education and health care to appeal to the broadest
number of voters,
</P>
<P>
   Feldt predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) there will be clear-cut differences between these two
candidates on reproductive health and rights issues,'' she said.
``So what could easily happen is that reproductive rights could
become one of the _ if
</P>
<P>
   not the _ most explicitly defining issues of the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes about politics for The Austin
American-Statesman. You
</P>
<P>
   may contact him at dmcneely(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
