u a BC-TX-EMPLOYERS07-COX     04-06 0345
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-EMPLOYERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas employers may fire workers at will
 &HT;    By Bruce Hight
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Employers do not have a legal duty to act with
``good faith and fair dealing'' in their relations with workers,
the Texas Supreme Court said Thursday in one of several rulings
involving employers and workers.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was the first time the court ruled specifically on
the issue, its conclusion conformed with the state's ``at-will''
employment doctrine, under which employers can fire and employees
can quit ``for any reason or no reason at all,'' as the court put
it.
</P>
<P>
   In the case, brought by five current and former Midland police
officers, the court compared an insurer's legal obligation to act
in good faith and provide fair dealing to policyholders with an
employer's relationship with employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``If an insured suffers a loss, he cannot simply contract with
another insurance company to cover that loss,'' said the unanimous
ruling written by Justice Priscilla Owen. ``By contrast, an
employee who has been demoted, transferred or discharged may seek
alternative employment.''
</P>
<P>
   The court also said it saw no difference between government and
private employers on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Levy, legal director for the Texas AFL-CIO, said he was
struck by the fact that the court ruled unanimously. ``On such a
critical issue it shows the court is marching pretty much in
lockstep with the agenda of employers and isn't finely attuned to
the needs of working people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Texas Association of Business and Chambers
of Commerce, a group that often speaks to employer concerns, could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The officers, who had been transferred or lost their status as
peace officers, had sued, alleging retaliation and discrimination.
They lost on most of their claims, but two of them will get a new
hearing on another issue at the trial court level on their claims
for reinstatement.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
