<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9318 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-ENVOY-ART-N     04-06 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ENVOY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARRIVAL OF ELIAN'S FATHER SHEDS LIGHT ON CUBAN INTERESTS SECTION
</HEADLINE>
   (With CUBAN-BOY, CUBAN-BOY-MIAMI) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Streets were blocked off around the suburban
Washington house that is the residence of Cuba's senior diplomat in
the United States _ and as of Thursday, the temporary home of the
father of Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat, Fernando Remirez de Estenoz, runs the Cuban
Interests Section in Washington, the de facto embassy for a
government that has not had full diplomatic relations with the
United States since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymity that Remirez seemed to enjoy in an affluent
neighborhood in Bethesda, Md., disappeared Thursday with the
arrival of Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, from Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomat's two-story brick home, on a street with trees
abloom with cherry blossoms, was surrounded by television satellite
vans, police cruisers and crowds of neighbors interested in the
commotion in what is otherwise a quiet corner of suburbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban government announced Thursday that while Gonzalez
remains in the house, it will not be considered a diplomatic
residence, putting the home under the jurisdiction of American law.
The announcement was apparently an effort to answer Cuban-American
critics who say it would be wrong to unite father and son on Cuban
soil.
</P>
<P>
   Until this week, many of Remirez's neighbors probably did not
know what he did for a living. Even fewer may have known that the
government of Fidel Castro maintains a relatively large diplomatic
presence in Washington despite the decades of hostility between
Cuba and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The interests section, which is formally affiliated with the
Swiss Embassy although it maintains separate offices in a
nondescript building in downtown Washington, is larger than many
embassies here.
</P>
<P>
   It has a staff of about 20 diplomats and other officials whose
activities are supposed to be tightly monitored by the State and
Justice departments out of concern that some of the Cubans are
spies for the Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   In February, a diplomat assigned to the interests section was
ordered expelled from the United States on espionage charges. He
was accused of having maintained contacts with a U.S. immigration
official in Florida who has also been accused of spying for the
Castro government.
</P>
<P>
   Espionage charges are leveled even more often by the Cuban
government against U.S. diplomats assigned to the U.S. interests
section in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. interests section, which is in the seafront,
seven-story building that once served as the U.S. Embassy in
Havana, is regularly denounced as a ``den of spies'' by Cuban news
organizations and is under intense surveillance by Cuban
intelligence agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuban office here and the U.S. interests section in Havana
were established in 1977, during the Carter administration, in what
was seen at the time as an effort to improve relations between the
United States and Cuba. Like their Cuban counterparts here, the
Americans in Havana operate under the auspices of the Swiss.
</P>
<P>
   The work of both offices is much like that of an embassy. Both
issue visas. The U.S. mission in Havana has issued more than
100,000 visas and other travel documents over the last five years.
The Cuban interests section here issued 1,300 visas last year for
reporters, editors and photographers seeking to cover Pope John
Paul II's visit to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The principal restriction on the activities of the diplomats is
one of travel. Cuban diplomats assigned to the interests section
here cannot travel more than 25 miles out of the capital without
the State Department's permission. U.S. diplomats in Havana cannot
pass beyond the city limits without similar permission from the
Cuban Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our main goal is to try to open a new relationship with the
United States and to try to create the best environment with the
Cuban-American community,'' said Luis M. Fernandez, the spokesman
for the interests section. ``We want to try to get rid of the
embargo.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the long-standing hostility between the U.S. and Cuban
governments, he said Cuban diplomats assigned here generally
enjoyed living in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of work, but really, it's a pleasure,'' Fernandez
said. ``It's exciting. We realize that we are doing something very
important for our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the emotions generated by the case of Elian Gonzalez,
the spokesman said, the interests section does not anticipate any
trouble at Remirez's home in Maryland if Gonzalez and his son take
up residence _ at least, no special trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been living for more than 40 years in a crazy
situation, so it's very difficult to say this will be different,''
Fernandez said.
</P>
<P>
   Although they work in Washington, Fernandez and many of the
Cuban diplomats assigned here choose to live in neighboring
Maryland for a reason that many parents in the Washington area
understand: the public schools in Maryland are considered superior.
``The schools are much better than in Washington,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2034EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0453 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BOUNTY07-COX     04-06 1867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOUNTY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BOUNTY HUNTERS: LONG ARMS OF THE LAW
 &HT;    Relentless pursuit of quarry has few rules for the chase
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Dana Tofig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Martin Johnson sits in his business systems class
Tuesday night and has no idea he is being hunted.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't know that two bounty hunters, Garrett Hester and Bob
Fitzgerald, are talking to his brother-in-law, his wife and even
one of his utility companies, trying to find him. And he has no
idea when he pulls into his suburban apartment complex that Hester
and Fitzgerald are waiting.
</P>
<P>
   As Johnson parks his car, the two hunters pounce. They pull
their black Jeep, brights glaring, nose to back bumper against
Johnson's Altima. They jump out on either side of the car.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin, let me see your hands! Let me see your hands!''
Fitzgerald screams. ``Do not move! Do not move!''
</P>
<P>
   Hester gets Johnson out of the car, handcuffs him behind his
back and explains that Johnson missed a court date on a simple
battery charge.
</P>
<P>
   Hester and Fitzgerald work for the company that had posted his
bail.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, their quarry is in the back of the Jeep being carted to
the Dekalb County lockup. After a few moments, Johnson breaks the
silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``So,'' he says with a half-smile, ``this is what you guys do?''
</P>
<P>
   For 14 to 16 hours a day, this is what Hester, Fitzgerald and
the other bail recovery agents at U.S. Fugitive Task Force Inc. do:
Work the phones, their sources and the street looking for people
who have jumped bail.
</P>
<P>
   They have a deep bag of tricks and they are not afraid to use
all of them. They will go anywhere, including funerals and
weddings, and talk to anyone who knows their target.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got a girlfriend who hates you, I'll find you,''
says Buck Buchanan, co-founder of U.S. Fugitive. ``If you've got a
mother who loves you, I'll find you.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Buchanan was coordinating a plan to capture Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin during a March 17 prayer service for the homeless
he was to lead. Al-Amin, the 1960s black militant formerly known as
H. Rap Brown, had failed to appear in court on several charges and
would have cost a bondsman $12,000.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and other agents were going to pose as homeless people
at the prayer service and grab Al-Amin. But the night before
Buchanan was to enact the plan two sheriff's deputies who tried to
serve Al-Amin a warrant were gunned down, one dying hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's prey quickly became the subject of a massive
interstate manhunt by federal, state and local law enforcement
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan says the shooting demonstrates the danger bounty
hunters run across sometimes. But, he adds, he doesn't teach his
agents to be cops or cowboys. Bounty hunters are private citizens
with the power to arrest, and he tries to instill in his agents a
mantra for their craft:
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get dead. Don't get sued. Try to make a living.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30 a.m. Tuesday, Buck Buchanan is in the company's
headquarters, located in the basement of co-founder Dan Sipes'
Gillsville, Ga., home. Buchanan is puffing a big cigar, drinking a
diet Mountain Dew and waxing philosophical about his job. He
realizes that many consider his line of work _ hunting human beings
for profit _ reprehensible. To those people, he is just a ``scumbag
bounty hunter.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old ex-Marine with the receding crew cut sees it
differently.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there are some who give the bounty hunting industry a bad
name. But Buchanan said his firm follows all the rules and he sees
his job as a public service: getting lawbreakers off the street
without having the taxpayers foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you're really doing something good,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Fugitive agents, like most bounty hunters, get hired and
paid by the companies that bail people out of jail and are in
danger of losing hundreds or thousands of dollars because the
defendant didn't show up for court. The pay for the bounty hunter
is usually 10 percent to 15 percent of the bond amount.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters _ or bail recovery agents, in more modern
parlance _ have wide latitude in how they can pursue their prey. By
signing an agreement with a bail bondsmen, defendants have given up
some of their rights if they miss court dates and a judge orders
them rearrested.
</P>
<P>
   The bounty hunters' powers go relatively unchecked and
unsupervised. That lack of supervision has at times caused
problems, with unscrupulous bounty hunters thinking they are above
the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are like extrajudicial. They are not ruled by police.
Nothing applies to them,'' said Don Geary, a metro Atlanta
prosecutor, who has prosecuted three bounty hunters. ``They could
take someone, throw them in the trunk and drive with them 200 miles
in the trunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Charges that bounty hunters have recklessly fired their guns in
the street or broken down the door of a wrong home have led to
changes across the country, in efforts to rein in the ``cowboys.''
</P>
<P>
   Some bounty hunters want to find a ``skip'' quickly so they can
get paid and move on to the next suspect. But it can take days to
track down somebody. U.S. Fugitive agents have traveled across the
country looking for ``skips.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan believes in the ``low and slow'' approach _ staying
invisible and waiting for the fugitive to reveal himself. Maybe
he'll use a credit card. Maybe he'll try to buy a car or rent an
apartment. Or maybe he'll call his mom or order a pizza.
</P>
<P>
   These days, with mailing lists being sold and the frequent
requirement of Social Security numbers, phone numbers and driver's
licenses for identification, it's nearly impossible to hide for
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privacy just doesn't exist,'' Buchanan said. ``If you're
breathing, there's no way to stay private.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan once placed an obituary in a newspaper announcing the
death of a bail jumper's mother. When the man called home to find
out of if it were true, Buchanan traced the phone call.
</P>
<P>
   He has posed as a radio disc jockey handing out free tickets to
an Eagles concert and even passed himself off as a lawyer trying to
organize a class-action lawsuit against bounty hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Once a suspect is captured, Buchanan said, he will treat him
with respect. He may even stop and buy him a six-pack of beer or
give him a couple of smokes during a long car ride. But if they
give him trouble, ``they can ride in the trunk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, Buchanan will never apologize for snatching people
off the street and putting them back in jail. ``He made a deal
(with the bail bondsman), and he broke it.''
</P>
<P>
   After a quick meeting with Buchanan and Sipes at a Waffle House
near Atlanta, Hester and Fitzgerald are ready to make some grabs.
Each has a gun strapped to his side and a badge that reads ``bail
recovery agent.''
</P>
<P>
   Hester said he doesn't like to pull his gun, but sometimes he
will. So far, he hasn't had to fire his weapon in his year as a
bounty hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun speaks for itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Tuesday night would be spent knocking on doors and
gathering small pieces of information about some bail jumpers. The
only pickup they'll make is Martin Johnson, but it won't be easy to
find him.
</P>
<P>
   The first place they head is the home of Johnson's sister, who
co-signed the bail bond agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Hester heads to the front door and Fitzgerald runs around back,
where he is met by Johnson's brother-in-law. They walk into the
house, a small, tidy home with religious trinkets, a drum set and
comfortable sofas. A young girl walks around and stares warily at
the strangers. Hester waves; the girl waves back.
</P>
<P>
   The brother-in-law says Johnson does not live there; he just got
an apartment, but his relative does not know exactly where.
</P>
<P>
   Hester says he is just trying to help Johnson work out his legal
problems. He explains that since Johnson's sister co-signed the
bond, she will be responsible for the $2,800 bond if her brother
isn't found. Hester stresses this many times.
</P>
<P>
   The sister's husband seems very concerned: They don't have that
kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't be arrested, will he?'' the man asks. Hester lies and
says ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Hester says he feels bad sometimes when he has to lie,
``but I think in God's eyes I'll be forgiven for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald adds: ``That's not a rich man back there. We're
fixing on saving him $2,800.''
</P>
<P>
   They find Johnson's apartment complex and start winding through
the many buildings and parking lots looking for his cars: a red
sport-utility vehicle and a green Altima.
</P>
<P>
   After several minutes, Fitzgerald grabs his cellular phone and
dials up a utility company. He identifies himself as Martin
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't received my bill and I want to make sure you have
the right address,'' he says into the phone. The operator asks for
his Social Security number for verification: Fitzgerald has
Johnson's number. She asks for Johnson's phone number: Fitzgerald
has it. She verifies the address and apartment number.
</P>
<P>
   At the apartment, Fitzgerald and Hester encounter Johnson's
wife, who says there must be a mistake. Hester goes through the
same routine: He's here to work this out. He never mentions an
arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The woman says her husband will be home around 9 p.m. They leave
a phone number and say good night. They back their truck into a
nearby space and wait for Johnson to come home.
</P>
<P>
   The simple battery charge is cause for concern. ``This guy, he's
a fighter,'' Hester said. They decide to grab him in his car
instead of letting him get to the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   They don't want to be in the position of having to get rough or
bust down a door. When they do have to force a door open, they make
sure a police officer is there as a witness. But still, they don't
like doing it. Lots of people have guns these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just never know what's behind the closed door,'' Hester
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next half-hour cars pull in and Hester and Fitzgerald
scope out each one carefully. The red SUV is in the lot, so they
are looking for the green Altima.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald smokes a couple of cigarettes. Hester chews tobacco
and spits into an empty bottle.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one has potential,'' Fitzgerald says, watching a car make
its way through the complex. It's a green Altima.
</P>
<P>
   Hester starts the ignition on the Jeep, turns on the brights and
pulls forward. Johnson will later tell his captors that he recently
saw a television show about bounty hunters on a cable channel. They
all share a good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to consider this interactive TV,'' Fitzgerald says.
</P>
<P>
   About 12:30 a.m., Buchanan is back in the office. He's going
through some new files a bail bondsman gave them earlier. U.S.
Fugitive closed out several files Tuesday. Some they picked up;
others were already in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Sipes says, U.S. Fugitive found more than 700 bail
jumpers. This year, it already has more than 450 files.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan freely admits he doesn't have many talents: He's not a
gifted athlete or a great dancer, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even tell particularly good jokes,'' he adds. ``But
I'll find you and put you in jail. That's what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
