<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9321 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-BBO-POORER-TEAMS-ART-     04-06 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-POORER-TEAMS-ART-840-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE HOPE FOR THE POOR BOYS OF SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For baseball fans, hope is supposed to spring
eternal each year as the groundskeepers groom the outfield grass
and comb the base paths for the home opener. But here in Kansas
City, as in Pittsburgh, Montreal, Minneapolis and many other
smaller cities with major-league teams, that perennial optimism has
withered over the last decade in the face of a growing gap between
rich and poor franchises.
</P>
<P>
   As Kansas City prepares for its first home game on Friday, no
longer do most fans here even dream that the once-mighty Royals
will make it to the World Series. Expectations have sunk so low
that even diehard optimists say they would be happy if the Royals
win as many games as they lose this season. Last year the team lost
97 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way we can be competitive,'' complained Joe
O'Keefe, 34, a lifelong Royals' fan, who was watching the season
opener on television at Tanners Sports Bar in a Kansas City suburb
earlier this week. ``They are more of a circus act than a baseball
team. You go out there for the carnival atmosphere. You don't go
out there to watch competitive baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The cynicism of fans like O'Keefe does not bode well for
baseball. There is a growing consensus among team owners, fans and
experts on the game that the disparity between high-revenue teams
and those in small markets threatens the sport's future popularity.
Last year, all eight teams that made the playoffs ranked among the
top 10 payrolls in the game. Some owners are asking how baseball
can sustain the interest of fans and attract new devotees if only a
handful of lucrative teams have a realistic chance to make the
playoffs each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``For teams like Kansas City, we need to change the economic
landscape of the game,'' said Bud Selig, the commissioner of
baseball, who once owned another small-market team, the Milwaukee
Brewers. ``The evidence is very clear that we do have a disparity
problem. We are going to crack it, because it's essential to the
growth of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   In January, the owners voted unanimously to give Selig broader
powers to redistribute the leagues' wealth to less affluent teams;
he has appointed a panel to explore ways to do that, but so far he
has not offered concrete proposals. Baseball officials say the
limited revenue-sharing schemes, including a luxury tax on
high-payroll teams, put in place in 1995 have so far failed to
provide enough extra money to make low-revenue teams more
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   There have always been haves and have-nots in baseball. Teams in
big cities have always had a natural advantage, because they have a
greater population from which to draw people to games and because
their local television and radio broadcasting rights are more
valuable. In recent years, some medium-sized cities, like Cleveland
and Baltimore, have built new ballparks with luxury amenities that
have given their teams an economic advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But the gap between rich and poor franchises has grown
significantly since the strike of 1994 as players' salaries have
skyrocketed, and it has become harder for small-market teams to
hold on to their stars, baseball experts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is no one really knows what level of inequality is
acceptable,'' Andrew Zimbalist, a Smith College economics professor
who writes about sports, said. ``You do want the Yankees and the
Dodgers to win a little more. But you have to have a threshold of
happiness all around. You don't want to have year after year
domination by high-revenue teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The root of the problem is that baseball teams do not share
local broadcast revenues, which vary widely from town to town. In
1998, for instance, the New York Yankees, with a market of more
than 6.8 million households with televisions, received more than
$53 million for local broadcast rights. There are about 802,000
households with televisions in the Kansas City metropolitan area,
and the Royals received only $7 million in broadcast revenues in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, ballplayers' salaries have risen dramatically.
In 1990, the average team payroll was $17 million, and the highest
payroll was about three times larger than the smallest. Last year,
the average payroll had increased to $48 million, and the highest
payroll was six times the size of the smallest. The Yankees spent
$88 million on players' salaries last year, or more than five times
the $16 million the Royals spent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two players on the Yankees are the whole Royals' payroll,''
Mark J. Davis, a season-ticket holder, said. ``What does that tell
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Standing in line outside Kauffman Stadium Thursday to buy
advance tickets, several fans said they still come to the ballpark
for the sunshine or to teach their children about the game. But the
idea of a winning a pennant seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here just to show my son what baseball is like, for
something to do, to learn the game and to see the other team's
stars,'' said Jason Stahl, a 29-year-old salesman.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some in Kansas City say the team's problems flow from bad trades
and poor management. The Royals have not had an owner since Ewing
Kauffman died in 1993, and some critics say the charitable trust
Kauffman set up to oversee the team and search for a new owner has
been rudderless.
</P>
<P>
   But most Royals fans blame the changing economics of baseball.
``We come out of spring training, we know that we are not going to
be there in the end,'' said Charles Graham, a 30-year-old fan. ``We
don't have the money and the players to be there in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   That frustration boiled up in a protest last May, when more than
5,200 fans, organized by Kevin Kietzman, a sports talk show host,
walked out of a Royals-Yankees game in a noisy protest. They wore
T-shirts saying ``Share the Wealth'' and Yankees caps with dollar
bills pasted to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming plain to everyone in Kansas City that the
economics have changed,'' David Judy, a season ticket holder, said.
``Now someone would have to be able to lose $50 million a year to
be a competitive team.''
</P>
<P>
   The stark reality is that teams like Kansas City, which will
spend about $25 million on players this year, can only afford top
athletes early in their careers, before their salaries go out of
reach. Players are now eligible to go to an arbitrator in salary
disputes after three years in the majors, and they become free
agents after six. Since arbitrators peg salaries to those of the
highest paid players, big-market teams set the price for top
players. After three years, the salaries of talented young players
often jump dramatically, and after six they are usually snapped up
by the richer teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest challenge in Kansas City, quite candidly, is to
keep the players we have now, because their salaries just mushroom,
they explode,'' the Royals' general manager, Herk Robinson, said.
</P>
<P>
   The best chance a low-revenue team has of winning a pennant is
to somehow cobble together a group of immensely talented rookies
and make it to the playoffs before they become too expensive. John
Schuerholz, a former Royals' general manager who now holds the same
position with the Atlanta Braves, said even that trick is nearly
impossible under the current salary system.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might get one year where they can compete and even get
the division or a wild-card spot, but to sustain that is
impossible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while lightning does strike for small-market teams; in
recent years, the San Diego Padres and the Florida Marlins reached
the World Series. But in each case, the teams' owners sold off many
of their high-priced players the following year because they were
unwilling to sustain the huge losses necessary to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   All this has had a demoralizing effect on fans. Though the
Royals have a core of good young hitters like Johnny Damon,
Jermaine Dye and Carlos Beltran, it is unclear how long the team
can retain them. Last year, only four Royals made more than $1
million. This year, eight players will cross that threshold. With
total revenues of about $50 million, the Royals would have to
consider letting some of the young stars go if there was another
jump in salaries, team officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much everyone in Kansas City is saying that as soon as
these young kids get a little experience, they will be gone, they
won't be here,'' said Steve Brentano, a fan and the owner of a
string of sports bars. ``This is like a training camp.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gabe Duff, a 23-year-old sheet-metal worker, said the revolving
door of players wears on fan loyalty. ``We have a lot of good
talent come through here,'' Duff said. ``I got tired of players
coming in and going off to the big-time teams, and you would hear
about them in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Royals' fans are more excited this year than they have
been in a while. Many people are hopeful that David Glass, a former
Walmart chief executive who is on the verge of acquiring the
Royals, will be able to lead a charge among low revenue teams to
somehow level the playing field. Glass' $96 million bid for the
Royals has been accepted by the team's board and is expected to be
ratified by the owners later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Glass is no stranger to the team, having served as the chairman
of the board that has managed the Royals since Kauffman's death.
Glass has been a strong proponent of sharing revenues among
major-league teams, and Royals' fans believe he has a powerful ally
in Selig.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Glass said he is confident Selig will do something
to redistribute the wealth. ``Baseball in general has recognized
that the competitive balance has been eroded over the last few
years, and I think there is a consensus among the owners that it
needs to be restored,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Without more revenue sharing, Glass said, teams like the Royals
risk becoming permanent losers, little more than sparring partners
for big-market juggernauts. ``If nothing changes, we will have a
caste system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Royals' second-class status is a bitter pill for older fans
who remember the team's glory days in the late 1970s and early
1980s. Those Royals, lead by George Brett, the Hall-of-Fame third
baseman, were annual contenders, and they often fought the Yankees
down to the last out. The Royals won the American League pennant in
1980 and the World Series in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   But Kauffman, a billionaire drug manufacturer who looked on the
team as a civic duty, was willing in those days to absorb a loss to
win a pennant. ``We will never have an owner like Kauffman,'' said
Lee Bussinger, a longtime fan and member of Royal Lancers, a
booster group. ``His pockets were deep enough to bring the players
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Kauffman were alive, however, it is doubtful he would be
able to contribute the large sums necessary to make the Royals
competitive in today's baseball economy. ``In the days when
Kauffman was alive, he could chip in $2 or $3 million and put our
payroll on a par with the best,'' Robinson, the general manager,
said. ``When you have clubs with payrolls at $80 million or $90
million, it doesn't make a bit of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Royals' fans point to the National Football League and ask
why baseball cannot adopt a similar revenue-sharing strategy. In
the NFL, the network television contract is huge, worth more than
$2.2 billion a year, with each team getting an equal amount: $59
million a year. Since the league also has a salary cap, even small
markets like Green Bay, Nashville, and Jacksonville can field
successful franchises.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Kansas City Chiefs have been playoff contenders for
a decades. They led the NFL in attendance last year at Arrowhead
Stadium, a few hundred yards from Kauffman Stadium, where the
beleaguered Royals struggled to attract 1.5 million fans last year.
In the 1980s, the team regularly attracted at least 2.2 million
fans a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disparity in the league is outrageous and the owners have
to come along and realize they have to go to something like the NFL
has,'' Jim Bayliff, a 25-year-old watchmaker, said as he watched
the Blue Jays trounce the Royals on television earlier this week.
``I believe the small market teams are going to be butchered up and
gone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
