<HEADER>
A9325 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      04-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: ARMY BASE BOMBED
</P>
<P>
   A bomb exploded inside a British army base near Londonderry,
demolishing a guardhouse wall but causing no casualties. It was the
third attack on security forces in two months, all attributed to
republican groups at odds with the Irish Republic Army. Mitchel
McLaughlin, chairman of the IRA's political wing, Sinn Fein, and a
member of the Assembly suspended in February, said, ``There is a
very clear correlation between political failure and the activities
of these groups because they sustain themselves by that failure.''
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: EUROPEAN WARNING
</P>
<P>
   The Council of Europe in Strasbourg, France, has voted to start
suspension proceedings against Russia unless it calls a cease-fire
or starts talks with rebel leaders in Chechnya by May. No country
has ever been suspended from the 41-nation consultative body, and
the Russian delegation walked out after the vote. Officials said in
private it was unlikely member countries would take up the
recommendation. But the vote was intended to put pressure on
President-elect Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: APOLOGY OVER EX-NAZIS
</P>
<P>
   The Social Democrats, in opposition after decades in power,
apologized for providing a political haven to former Nazis after
World War II. The party's new leader, Alfred Gusenbauer, said it
must be ``deeply ashamed'' of the way it welcomed ex-Nazis to its
ranks. Several served in the cabinets of the former Social
Democatic chancellor, Bruno Kreisky; others joined the rightist
Freedom Party now led by Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: RACISM CHARGE
</P>
<P>
   The campaign slogan of a leading Christian Democrat, Juergen
Ruettgers, has been criticized as racist by a European Union
watchdog committee. Ruettgers has been campaigning in North
Rhine-Westphalia with the slogan ``Children not Indians'' _ a
derisive reference to a proposal that skilled Indians should be
allowed to fill jobs in Internet-related industries. ``German
politicians should have learned more than others from history,''
the European Monitoring Center on Racism said.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE: LOOKING TO BRITAIN
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved an amendment to the Constitution requiring
Britain, the former colonial power, to compensate white landowners
for any property seized by the government. The vote was rejected by
Britain, which said one state could not impose constitutional
obligations on another. The clause, which was included in a draft
charter rejected by voters in February, allows the government to
take white-owned land without paying for it.
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA: CULT LEADER WARRANTS
</P>
<P>
   The police issued warrants for the arrest of six leaders of a
doomsday cult that the authorities say killed at least 924 of its
members. It is not known if any of them are still alive after a
church fire in Kanungu, southwest Uganda, on March 17, in which as
many as 530 members died. Among those wanted are Joseph Kibwetere,
leader of the Movement for the Restoration of the Ten Commandments,
and Credonia Mwerinde, who claimed to have had visions of the
Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE: CYCLONE ALERT
</P>
<P>
   A cyclone closed in on Mozambique, drenching its northern region
and setting off a scramble to prepare for a possible new natural
disaster, just weeks after hundreds died in floods. The United
States sent in disaster aid teams to deal with possible damage.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: REFUGEE BILL
</P>
<P>
   The government introduced a bill in Parliament intended to speed
the processing of refugee claims, to better screen claimants for
criminal records, to streamline deportation procedures and to
impose fines of up to $700,000 and life in prison for anyone
convicted of smuggling illegal immigrants. The bill comes after
boatloads of illegal Chinese arrived in Vancouver last year.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: CASTE LEADER HELD
</P>
<P>
   Laloo Prasad Yadav, the charismatic peasant caste leader in the
state of Bihar, was placed in judicial custody for two weeks after
being charged with having more assets than can be explained by his
income. His wife, Rabri Devi, Bihar's chief minister, was given
bail, though she faces the same charges. The judge said, ``She like
any Indian housewife was under pressure of her husband, so she
committed abetment.''
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SETTLERS EVACUATED
</P>
<P>
   Soldiers evacuated an encampment of Jewish settlers, including
leaders of the movement, from a hilltop in the West Bank. The
settlers were protesting a High Court decision to allow Palestinian
cave dwellers to return to their neighboring homes as part of what
they said would be an increase in protest activities against the
policies of Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: CLARIFICATION ON JEWS
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the judiciary said that not all of the 13 Jews
charged with spying for Israel face death or life imprisonment.
Hossain Sadeqi said Iranian law provided for lesser punishments in
some spying cases. The 13 Jews, and six Muslims arrested with them,
are due to face trial on April 13, but court officials have hinted
at a possible delay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
