A9327 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BKC-GTECH-HEWITT07-CO     04-06 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GTECH-HEWITT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hewitt outlines his philosophy for Georgia Tech
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ New Georgia Tech basketball coach Paul Hewitt wasted
little time getting his program going. The former Siena College
coach, introduced to the media Thursday afternoon, immediately hit
the road recruiting.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, who in three seasons at Siena resurrected the program at
the small Franciscan school in upstate New York, is setting his
sights high at Tech. He is expected to make a strong run at Darius
Rice, the Jackson, Miss., forward who is the nation's top unsigned
senior.
</P>
<P>
   Although NCAA rules forbid coaches from commenting on specific
recruits before they sign, Hewitt said he is seeking impact
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can find someone who can come in and help the program,
we'll go after them,'' said Hewitt, who was 66-27 at Siena. ``And
you can find quality players for Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior-college players might be considered, as long as they have
strong academic backgrounds. ``That'll be a bonus if I do find
one,'' Hewitt said. ``They're out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The period allowed for contact with recruits ends Sunday, and
the monthlong signing period begins Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next step is getting in front of people,'' said Hewitt,
who replaces Bobby Cremins, Tech's coach for 19 seasons. ``I hope
to do that tonight. If I can get into somebody's house ... this is
a great product _ Georgia Tech, the city of Atlanta, the
opportunity to play in the ACC.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only goal for players is that they are going to end up with
an option on how to live their lives, a degree and basketball, if
that's what they want to do. I'm not going to shy away from kids
whose goal is to play basketball for a living.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt received a five-year contract worth $400,000 annually,
with an additional $100,000 yearly from camps, speaking engagements
and shoe and apparel contracts. He will meet with current players
individually, including point guard Tony Akins, who has considered
transferring, and center Alvin Jones, who might enter the NBA
Draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to stay,'' Hewitt said. ``But I don't think it's
healthy to convince them to stay. You enjoy the most success when
kids want to be where they are. If they do stay, they'll be better
off for it. If they want to leave, I'll help them the best that I
can.''
</P>
<P>
   Akins said his initial impressions are positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy seems like the type of coach I'd like to play for,''
Akins said. ``His style is up-tempo, shoot a lot of threes. Right
now, I want to meet with him first.''
</P>
<P>
   Other players are looking forward to Hewitt's system.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants everybody to be able to shoot when open,'' guard
Shaun Fein said. ``I'm excited to get things going.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hewitt cautioned that playing a running, pressing
defense is not all fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my goals is to get them into the best shape of their
lives to play this style,'' he said. ``The system is important, but
the thing that has made us successful is our efforts in the area of
player development. If you play the style we play, you've got to
teach people how to play the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Final Four, I had a chance to hear (former coach) Pete
Newell speak. He said he thinks the game today is overcoached and
undertaught. I think if you watch us play you will see a team that
is not overcoached but is very well taught.''
</P>
<P>
   While the pressing, running style with multiple substitutions is
in vogue now, it has been around for decades. Hewitt said he played
in such a system in high school on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hewitt will bring along one member of his Siena staff
and also consider current Tech assistants. Mark Price has continued
to work with players since the season ended, and Willie Reese kept
the recruiting fires burning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it,'' said Reese, who, like Price, played for
Cremins. ``Because I grew up three miles from here, I've never left
Atlanta, and Georgia Tech is in my heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Cremins, who announced Feb. 18 that he would not return for
another season, could not be reached for comment. But longtime Tech
basketball supporters said Cremins would embrace Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who fell in love with Georgia Tech basketball did so
because they fell in love with Bobby Cremins,'' supporter Bill
Gannon said. ``Paul Hewitt is the kind of man Bobby Cremins would
want to follow in his footsteps.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech President Dr. Wayne Clough said the athletics board
approved Hewitt's hiring unanimously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have a winner, and we look for that in our coaching
staff,'' Clough said. ``But at the same time, we look for someone
who appreciates the challenging academic culture at Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletics director Dave Braine said he was made aware of Hewitt
through a mutual friend who is an NBA coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bringing in a good guy here,'' Braine said. ``In a
couple of years, (people) will realize we made an excellent
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
