<SLUG> BC-NOVARTIS-GENERIC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOVARTIS SEEKS CURB ON SALE OF GENERIC CYCLOSPORINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Novartis Pharmaceuticals Inc., facing competition for
cyclosporine, its largest selling drug, has asked health officials
in several states to limit the sale of generic versions claiming
they are not interchangeable.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclosporine is the leading medication for organ transplant
recipients with estimated U.S. sales last year of $550 million.
Novartis' patents on the drug have expired and two small companies
have developed less expensive generic versions.
</P>
<P>
   One firm, Eon Labs Manufacturing Inc. of Laurelton, NY, recieved
US Food and Drug Administration approval earlier this year and
plans to begin marketing its drug later this month. The FDA
maintains Eon's generic version is bioequivalent and could be used
as a replacement for the Novartis drug.
</P>
<P>
   A second company, Sangstat Medical Corp. of Fremont Calif. is
expected to receive a similar FDA endorsement in the next few
months and has teamed up with Abbott Laboratories to market it.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Novartis asked the state's Department of Public
Health to put its brand name drug, called Neoral, on the
``Exemption List'' of interchangeable drugs _ a move that would
require pharmacists throughout Massachausetts to only sell Neoral
unless physicians wrote prescriptions that specified the generic
versions.
</P>
<P>
   If the generics prevail over Novartis, transplant patients would
automatically receive the lower priced versions of cyclosporine,
which would reduce Neoral's revenues and profits.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, generics take 25 to 40 percent of a brand name's
drug's revenue in the first two years of competition.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis insists there are scientific differences between its
drug and the generics. It cites Eon's FDA data over how their
medication with food results in a slightly different interaction
compared to patients using Neoral.
</P>
<P>
   Eon and Sangstat officials maintain Novartis' concerns have less
to do with medical issues and more with competitive fears and loss
of market share for a very profitable drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Novartis is looking to protect its cyclosporine franchise
which means charging patients close $5,000 a year for their drug,
while we plan to charge at least 20 percent less,'' said Frank J.
Della Fera, Eon's vice president of sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But some physicans and pharmacists maintain there could be
differences between the two drugs, noting that a slight variation
in dosage could negatively impact transplant recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stakes are very high to switch patients who have taken
Neoral for many years to a generic, that we don't know much
about,'' said Dr. Fred Gordon, medical director of liver
transplantation at Leahy Clinic in Burlington, Mass. ``Having a
mandatory substitution without physicans knowing how well the
generic is absorbed in the patient's system could prove difficult.
Maybe over time that will change.''
</P>
<P>
   Currently there are no drugs on the Massachusetts ``Exemption
List,'' said Grant Carrow, director of the drug control program of
the Massachusetts Department of Health. He said a discussion and
possible decision on Novartis request, with input from the generic
firms, is scheduled for May 9th by the Drug Formulary Commission,
an eight-person independent group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure that the generic and brand name drugs are
therapeutically the same and they do not pose any potential risk to
the patient's health,'' explained Carrow.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis, which has made similar appeals in Texas, Virginia and
North Carolina, is following in the footsteps of duPont
Pharmaceuticals Inc. which tried unsuccessfully to halt the sales
of a generic equivalent to its drug Coumadin in Massachusetts
nearly five years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
