<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9333 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MARKET-MARGINS-ART-2T     04-06 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-MARGINS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW BREED OF MARGIN TRADER CAREFULLY RIDES MARKET'S UPS AND DOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year ago, Aaron Talsky was doing so well in the stock market
that he gave up his Beverly Hills law practice to spend his days
buying and selling stocks of the new economy from his home near
Laguna Beach, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   When the frenzy for Internet and biotechnology stocks continued
into this year, Talsky, 35, worked out a strategy for even fatter
profits. He bought shares on margin, borrowing against the stock he
already owned to purchase even more in what seemed to him a one-way
street to bull-market riches.
</P>
<P>
   But the enormous technology selloff that culminated Tuesday
brought the first blush of fear to the young investor. Faced with
the prospect of having to put up more money in his brokerage
accounts to meet margin calls _ a brokerage firm requirement when
the value of stocks falls too far _ Talsky sold shares into the
market downturn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw my money just dripping away,'' Talsky said in a
telephone interview Wednesday, noting that it was the first time he
had suffered huge losses. ``I saw balances moving in the wrong
direction, and the speed with which it was happening was
staggering.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's selloff, in which the Nasdaq composite plummeted
nearly 14 percent in just hours, has served as an unwelcome
reminder of the perils of such borrowing, particularly when
brokerage firms tell investors to come up with additional cash.
Talsky, at least, is now vowing to ease up on credit.
</P>
<P>
   But many market observers point to the rise in such borrowing
and worry that Americans have gone to troubling lengths to reap
bigger and bigger rewards in a bull market that seems to have an
infinite number of legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at history, leverage is often a toppler of robust
markets; it magnifies the upside and the downside,'' said Steven
Galbraith, an analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co. ``That's why
the investment community is very concerned about this.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the stock market has climbed in recent years, so has
margin debt, to a record $265 billion in February, from about $152
billion at the end of 1998, according to the New York Stock
Exchange. Margin debt now accounts for more than 1.5 percent of the
Big Board's total market value, also a record.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, borrowing was a high-risk practice left to
professional money managers. Much of the borrowing now, though, is
being done by a new breed of investors who are addicted to the
market and who have learned to manage their own money and trade
online through the likes of Etrade and Charles Schwab &AMP; Co.,
according to industry professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a significant increase in customers using margin,
and we think it's indicative of the entire market,'' said Heather
Fondo, a spokeswoman at Etrade, one of the largest online brokerage
firms.
</P>
<P>
   Schwab said that margin calls on Tuesday ran to three times
their usual level. Datek Online, another online firm, said Tuesday
was one of the five heaviest days there for margin calls. The
well-established Wall Street firms, meanwhile, said they did not
see a significant increase.
</P>
<P>
   Many brokerage firms have tightened their lending policies.
Though the Federal Reserve sets margin requirements _ initially an
investor can borrow no more than 50 percent of a stock's purchase
price _ the firms may set more stringent rules, even creating lists
of technology stocks for higher requirements. The New York Stock
Exchange, which also sets rules for its members, has asked
securities firms for more information about their lending.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., has pushed for an increase in the
initial amount required of investors for margin buying. Though he
has expressed reluctance to raise the requirement, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan has said he would consider it.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy J. Siegel, a professor of finance at the Wharton School
of the University of Pennsylvania, said that although margin calls
were a factor in Tuesday's rout, they were probably not the primary
cause, because institutions were heavy sellers. But he said the
explosion of online investing and the decline in commissions had
exacerbated market swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest factor is the collapse of trading costs,'' he
said. ``That's why people are in and out, in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors find buying on margin so irresistible because the
stock market has been a clear path to riches in the last decade.
And in the last year or two, a craving for technology stocks has
created multibillion-dollar companies almost overnight, giving rise
to the the dot.com mania.
</P>
<P>
   The technological revolution that is minting billionaires in
their 30s is entwined with a frenzied stock market that is turning
former insurance salesmen into self-styled stock experts.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics are lacking, but anecdotal evidence suggests that a
growing number of people are devoting more time to playing the
stock market. Everyone seems to have a story about a friend,
neighbor, cousin or former colleague who is trading stocks from his
or her bedroom, retired at 48, glued to the Web, researching stocks
and talking about price-to-earnings ratios.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's become incredibly prevalent,'' said Charles Pradilla, the
chief investment strategist at SG Cowen in New York. ``I live in
Brooklyn Heights, and my butcher is playing the stock market. He
stopped cutting veal chops and started day trading.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In a market of such high expectations and unprecedented returns,
it is only natural that people would begin borrowing to buy into
the frenzy. Though this week's action was unnerving, it is too
early to conclude that such borrowing will fade.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Silverman, a 74-year-old retired stereo salesman in Boca
Raton, Fla., said his portfolio value jumped early this year and
then crashed early this week, nearly forcing him into a margin call
on the $300,000 he has borrowed to buy stock. But the market picked
up, averting the dreaded request for additional money in his
account.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got very nervous,'' said Silverman. ``I got to the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he began actively trading a year ago, he said, ``If I'm
not on the golf course, I'm playing the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of his activity is with what he calls his fun money. ``I'm
not that worried,'' he said, ``because I've got a lot of income
coming from commercial real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   Having noticed that every selloff in the last few years has been
followed by a stunningly fast bounce back, investors may see little
reason to step aside. Michael Stummer, a day trader in suburban
Chicago, said he was watching intently when the market turned down
_ ``for the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Nasdaq composite had dropped 574 points and had begun
to recover Tuesday afternoon, Stummer said he jumped into the
market. ``I bought a stock at $71 and sold it at $87 an hour
later,'' he said. ``I was screaming and yelling.''
</P>
<P>
   Stummer said he made $50,000 in just hours, his best day ever,
although he said his partners did not fare as well, largely because
they had money tied up in losing stocks and could not muster cash
to jump in on the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders often borrow to buy stocks, but most of them close
out their positions daily. The real leaders in the long-term
borrowing game appear to be active online investors _ people like
Aaron Talsky.
</P>
<P>
   After 10 years as a lawyer, Talsky, who also taught corporate
finance at the University of California at Irvine, was drawn to the
Wall Street boom and the high-tech revolution. He had heard stories
about people trading their own accounts full time, and was reading
daily about Silicon Valley entrepreneurs. He decided he simply had
to be a part of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will probably never be a time when things are this
good,'' he said. ``Not only is there a historic opportunity that
wasn't available five years ago, but I can sit on the beach, I can
sit in my bedroom and have the same access as the investment
banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has no boss, all is not easy. ``I probably work three
times as hard now,'' he said. ``There's always more information
than you can handle. I get up at 6 a.m. and read market briefing,
commentaries, look at upgrades, downgrades, and then turn on
CNBC.''
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming serious about trading, he has bought
biotechnology stocks like Maxigen and Protein Design Labs along
with Internet stocks like Ariba. He watched them climb and climb
and climb until about two weeks ago, when his portfolio faltered.
He recalls sitting in an Indian restaurant in Mission Viejo after
the market closed one day and sensing an impending disaster. Still,
he didn't sell. But in the next few days, the market buckled.
</P>
<P>
   Talsky said he is still doing extremely well after huge runups
last year, but the psychological impact of seeing giant gains
disappear in an instant is jarring. One stock fell to $70 from $300
a share, he said. ``But how can you complain when the stock was at
$20 three months ago?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says he will temper his borrowing, but not give up on
the market game. This week's selloff is just a reminder of what he
has known all along: the more risk you take, the crueler the market
can become.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this market,'' he said, ``if you're going to run with the
bulls, you're going to get trampled every once in a while.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2050EDT &QL; 
