u a BC-SC-FLAG-NYT &LR;      04-06 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG MARCH ENDS IN SOUTH CAROLINA,   BUT LITTLE TIME LEFT TO REMOVE
FLAG 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ By his own estimate, Mayor Joseph P. Riley Jr.
of Charleston had walked nearly 275,000 steps when he turned the
corner onto Main Street Thursday morning and finally saw the
Confederate battle flag that he and hundreds of others had been
marching since Sunday to remove.
</P>
<P>
   Since setting out from Charleston, 120 miles away, he had
endured death threats, roadside obscenities, wet clothes and
blisters so painful that they needed medical attention. For all
that, there was only a slim hope that the state Legislature would
vote to remove the flag from atop the Statehouse dome before the
end of the year's session.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor seemed energized by the sight of the object of his
derision, and there was a new force in his steps as he finished the
last few blocks of his protest march and stood under the dome to
speak to a crowd that had grown to nearly 2,000, about two-thirds
of it white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every religious denomination, every business organization,
every civil rights organization, college boards of trustees and
presidents and athletic directors, and average citizens, rank and
file, have said, remove the Confederate battle flag,'' Riley told
the crowd. ``And our Legislature, with only a few more days left in
the legislative session, hasn't even begun to debate the bill. They
are out of step with the people of South Carolina.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley, a Democrat, chose the long march, with its evocation of
civil rights struggle and Gandhian protest, to demonstrate the
widespread frustration with the presence of the flag in a position
of sovereignty. The mayor, a South Carolina institution who has
been popular since taking office in 1975, had hoped to draw
attention by marching with civic leaders and well-known football
coaches. He attracted nearly 600 marchers on the first day and
close to 1,000 on the last leg Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulty faced by his cause seemed to be illustrated
by the 300 or so counter-demonstrators who waved large Confederate
banners on the north steps of the Capitol while Riley, Gov. Jim
Hodges, and others spoke on the south steps. Some of the pro-flag
speakers called their opponents ``scalawags'' and urged them to
leave the state. The legislative supporters of the flag have
blocked most efforts at a compromise, like moving it to a statue of
a Confederate general near the rear of the Capitol, or putting it
in a glass case on the Statehouse grounds.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the deadline for new legislation will pass at the
end of this month without even a vote on moving the flag. The
Legislature raised the banner in 1962 during the centennial of the
Civil War and kept it up as a gesture of defiance to the civil
rights movement; now only the Legislature can remove it. But
several strongly pro-flag legislators have used every parliamentary
procedure at their disposal to block the compromise bills, and now
there are only nine working days left in this year's session to get
a bill onto the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate did make some progress on the issue Thursday, voting
to put a compromise bill at the top of the agenda, meaning it could
be debated and voted upon next week, then sent to the House. But
legislators said they did not know if there were enough votes to
stop a filibuster, should one of the opponents of compromise begin
one.
</P>
<P>
   If the issue is not resolved this session, the statewide tourism
boycott imposed by the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People in January could continue for another year, with
potentially serious economic consequences. Tourism officials told
the governor on Wednesday that the state was losing hundreds of
conventions and countless vacation trips because of the NAACP
boycott and the growing image of the state as intolerant. Business
leaders, who have been in the forefront of the anti-flag effort,
have said another year of the boycott could be ruinous. Even the
Columbia police chief, Charles Austin, said Thursday that he hoped
a compromise would be reached soon, because he was worried about
public safety in the city if the marches continued.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges, a Democrat who favors a compromise, has not said whether
he would call a special session if the Legislature does not act.
But he accepted the palmetto-tree state flag that Riley carried
with him from Charleston, and said he hoped that the passionate
feelings demonstrated by the march would change a few votes inside.
``Anytime a legislator looks out the window and sees this kind of
crowd, it has the potential to change their mind,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Thursday, before he took off his cracked sneakers
and prepared for a rest, Riley, 57, listed what he said were the
hateful uses of the Confederate battle flag over the years, like
its use as a symbol of the Dixiecrat Party that split from the
Democrats in 1948 over civil rights. (A statue of the Dixiecrat
leader, Sen. Strom Thurmond, stood near the Capitol with its back
toward the rally.)
</P>
<P>
   But the matter was more immediate to Gail Jones, a black woman
who walked every step of the march alongside the mayor. As the
manager of a Circle K convenience store a few blocks from the
Statehouse on Main Street, she has to see the Confederate battle
flag every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of having to lower my eyes every time I go to
work,'' she said. ``I just don't want to see it anymore, and that's
why I marched.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
