<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9343 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-ART-(T     04-06 1201
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-ART-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR GIULIANI IN SENATE RACE DROPS SHARPLY, LATEST POLL
FINDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (With METHOD-BOX) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make
one-time purchases by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM NAGOUREY with MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's response to the shooting
last month of an unarmed black man by a New York City police
officerh has resulted in his lowest job approval ratings in seven
years in office, jolting his campaign for the U.S. Senate while
catapulting Hillary Rodham Clinton into the lead for the first time
in a year, according to the latest New York Times/CBS News Poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, which was completed on Wednesday night, found that
Giuliani's attempt to discredit the dead man, Patrick M. Dorismond,
has raised concerns about the mayor's temperament and
qualifications, while voters' perceptions of Clinton have improved.
The first lady now enjoys a 49-to-41 percent lead over Giuliani;
when undecided voters were pressed to state their leaning, Clinton
moves a full 10 points ahead of Giuliani, 52 to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, Giuliani is now tied with Clinton upstate, where he
is drawing just 44 percent of the vote, significantly less than
what a successful Republican statewide candidate customarily draws
north of New York City's suburbs. Clinton has been campaigning
regularly there, while Giuliani has been criticized by Republicans
for spending little time north of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   He still commands a lead in the immediate suburbs. But in New
York City, where Giuliani's popularity was seen as a serious threat
to Clinton's Democratic base, Clinton is now defeating Giuliani by
nearly three-to-one, the Times/CBS News Poll found.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, whose record as a crime-fighter has lifted him to two
victories in New York City and positioned him as a formidable
Republican challenger to Clinton statewide, has even suffered a
steep decline in the way voters, statewide and in New York City,
judge his actions on his signature issue: Crime reduction.
</P>
<P>
   The number of New York City residents who disapprove of his
handling of crime has jumped almost 30 points since fall, to 50
percent in this latest poll, and a majority believe that Giuliani's
law-enforcement policies have contributed to an increase in police
brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Misgivings among voters have spilled over from the mayor to the
New York City Police Department as well. New York City residents
believe that the police are more likely to use deadly force against
black suspects than white, and that brutality against minorities is
widespread. Nearly two-thirds of people in New York City said the
Police Department was doing only a fair or poor job, with the level
of dismay particularly high among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Tension over police-community relations in the city has
heightened in the last six weeks, since the acquittals of four
officers in the police shooting of Amadou Diallo and then the
shooting of Dorismond, an unarmed man killed by an undercover
officer, last month. In the case of Dorismond, more than half of
voters statewide said the shooting would not affect their vote, but
one-third _ including 15 percent of the Republicans _ said they
were less inclined to vote for Giuliani because of how he handled
the case.
</P>
<P>
   The Times/CBS News Poll was conducted Saturday through
Wednesday, with 1,573 respondents statewide. The margin of sampling
error for all registered voters statewide is 3 percentage points;
for New York City resident, is plus or minus 4 points.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the poll results Thursday night on WCBS-radio,
Giuliani said: ``My reaction is the same to all polls. That is,
they are momentary things.'' Then, alluding to the Dorismond
shooting, Giuliani said the polls ``are things that reflect
sometimes coverage of a particular situation. I think when all the
facts or known and everything is out there, things will return to a
much different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's pollster, Mark Penn, attributed Clinton's gains in the
poll to her efforts to distinguish herself from Giuliani on issues,
though he acknowledged that Giuliani's difficulties in recent weeks
had undercut his campaign. ``The spotlight has been on his lack of
leadership in New York City,'' Penn said, ``and in fact now I think
the fundamental rationale for his campaign is evaporating because
if the people in New York City don't think he's done a good job as
mayor, how is he going to run as that as the major reason for being
the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The election is seven months and dozens of polls away, as the
mayor's aides noted on Thursday, and Giuliani enjoys a large
fund-raising edge over Clinton. The advantage of that money became
clear on Thursday morning, as Giuliani began a statewide series of
television advertisements. It was an early start for an advertising
campaign which suggests both the prosperity and the level of
concern in Giuliani's camp.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even given the buffers of time and money, the Times/CBS
News Poll included a number of reasons for worry on the part of
Giuliani's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   By large numbers, voters believed that Giuliani inflamed the
situation over the Dorismond shooting and strongly disapproved of
Giuliani's decision to release Dorismond's confidential police
record. New York City residents have a decidedly negative view of
Giuliani's handling of race relations, and more than three-quarters
of the respondents in New York City described the shooting as
unjustified, Giuliani's arguments notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the immediate moment of the Dorismond shooting, events
over the past few weeks have appeared to reinforce the arguments
Clinton has offered against the mayor's candidacy. That is the kind
of shift political analysts look for in polls, since it suggests a
change in voters' attitudes that tend to be more consequential than
the back-and-forth of the weekly horserace.
</P>
<P>
   An increasing number of voters do not believe that Giuliani
cares about the ``needs and problems of people like yourself,'' a
measure on which Clinton continues to score highly. About 35
percent of respondents said that Giuliani was trying to divide
people, as Clinton has repeatedly charged, compared to 40 percent
who said that the mayor was seeking to bring people together.
Two-thirds of the voters said Clinton was trying to bring people
together.
</P>
<P>
   By an overwhelming margin, respondents said compromise was a key
attribute for a senator, and Clinton was seen as the more adept
compromiser of the two.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Giuliani's standing with black voters, which has
never been strong, is weaker than ever; the number of New York City
black voters who said they approved of Giuliani's job rating was so
low as to be virtually unmeasurable. That could prove to be a
meaningful finding, particularly if it turns out, as some Democrats
now believe is possible, that Giuliani's presence on the ballot
might encourage the kind of sizable turn-out in black neighborhoods
that has rarely been seen in New York elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
