<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS MAINTAIN THEIR FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ The Mighty Ducks were all but blown out of
the Western Conference playoff race in the Windy City on Wednesday
night when they lost 5-2 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But early Thursday afternoon they dutifully went through their
practice paces at the Gaylord Entertainment Center and then
insisted their playoff hopes aren't dead _ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have hope, no matter how slim it is,'' said Ducks
goalie Guy Hebert. ``We win (tonight versus Nashville) and then
hope something good happens. It would be a great situation to go
into the last game against L.A. (at The Pond on Sunday) with a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been fighting for 80 games and sometimes they say it
takes 82 to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   For that to be the case, the Ducks first need to complete a
four- game season sweep of the Predators and have Vancouver defeat
Edmonton later in the evening. If that happens, Anaheim would then
need Calgary to beat the Oilers on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   That would extend hope, or prolong the agony, into Sunday, when
the Ducks must beat the Kings and then have the Sharks defeat or
tie the Canucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly need some help, but we have to take the approach
(to tonight's game), that nothing but our best effort is
acceptable,'' said Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg. ``There is no
sense moping around now, there is no sense moping around anytime in
this league.''
</P>
<P>
   __ In retrospect: Hebert wasn't moping, but the Anaheim goalie,
who refused to talk to the media after Wednesday's game, openly
admitted Thursday that his evening in Chicago was hardly his finest
hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an excuse, but I had a hard time picking up three
shots,'' he said referring to the three long shots that Chicago
scored on, including a floater by Jean-Yves Leroux that put Chicago
ahead 3-2 just 38 seconds after Paul Kariya had scored on a
breakaway to tie the game at 9:40.
</P>
<P>
   ``That killed us,'' said Hebert. ``Nobody felt worse than I did
at that moment.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Vote of confidence: While Hartsburg made no effort to defend
Hebert on Wednesday, the Anaheim coach gave his No. 1 goalie a vote
of confidence on Thursday when asked if he considered starting
backup Dominic Roussel against Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guy is going to play,'' Hartsburg said without hesitation.
``He has to get the job done. Guy is capable of winning a game for
us. I'm sure he would like to have a couple of those (Wednesday's
goals) back, but it's over and done and he has to rebound for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
