u p BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-METHOD     04-06 0340
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-SENATE-POLL) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll of New York state is
based on telephone interviews conducted April 1 to 5 with 1,573
adults throughout the state. Of those, 1,207 said they were
registered to vote. Interviews were conducted in either English or
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of telephone exchanges called was selected by a
computer from a complete list of exchanges across the state. For
each exchange, the telephone numbers were formed by random digits,
thus permitting access to both listed and unlisted numbers. Within
each household one adult was designated by a random procedure to be
the respondent for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to take account of household size
and number of telephone lines into the residence, and to adjust for
variations in the sample relating to geographic region of the
state, race, Hispanic origin, sex, age and education.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, questions about voting preferences and other
aspects of the 2000 election for U.S. senator are based on the
responses of 1,032 ``usual voters.'' Usual voters are those who say
they are registered and voted in 1998 or 1996, further weighted so
that those who reside in New York City make up 31 percent of the
entire state, which is the city's typical share of total ballots
cast on Election Day.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, in 19 cases out of 20 the results based on such
samples will differ by no more than three percentage points in
either direction from what would have been obtained by seeking out
all adult residents of New York state. For smaller subgroups the
potential sampling error is larger. As an example, for residents of
New York City it is plus or minus four percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to sampling error, the practical difficulties of
conducting any survey of public opinion may introduce other sources
of error. Differences in the wording and order of questions, for
instance, can lead to somewhat varying results.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0472 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-CALIF-730(2TAKES     04-06 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CALIF-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH GOING AFTER CALIFORNIA VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ On his first trip to California since the
Republican primary almost a month ago, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
could not have made his priorities clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the de facto Republican presidential nominee, headed
straight from the airport here to a nearby elementary school, where
he chatted extensively with local educators about the importance of
their mission. He could not dawdle too long, however, because he
was due at another school later on.
</P>
<P>
   At the first stop, Bush placed Jaime Escalante, the Latino
teacher whose work with poor children in southern California
inspired the movie ``Stand and Deliver,'' in the seat beside his
own. And he looked ahead to a speech on Friday morning before the
National Hispanic Women's Conference in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   By simultaneously reaching out to Latinos and emphasizing an
issue, education, that casts him in a relatively moderate light,
Bush was pursuing the two courses of action that many political
analysts say are most vital to any hope he nurtures of winning
California in November.
</P>
<P>
   And he was signaling, at least for now, that his bid for the
nation's richest electoral prize, a state that President Clinton
won handily in both of his races and that Democrats have
increasingly begun to dominate, was earnest and genuine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there's a rumor moving around the press in California
that, somehow, I wasn't going to compete,'' Bush told reporters
shortly before he left the Charles E. Mack Elementary School here,
alluding to news reports that his campaign had been prepared to
close its political office here, then reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just wishful thinking on the part of Al Gore,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Any Republican, at this early stage of a presidential contest,
would say likewise. But Bush and his advisers insist that
California's 54 electoral votes are within their grasp. They point
to the fact that in the March 7 primary, Bush trailed Vice
President Gore by a modest six percentage points, 34 percent to 28
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And they note that the two leading Republicans in that contest,
Bush and Sen. John McCain of Arizona, had a combined total of more
than 50 percent of the popular vote, while Gore and his Democratic
opponent, Bill Bradley, together netted under 45 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good indication that I've got a chance to win
this state,'' Bush said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But many political analysts disagreed, saying that Gore is as
likely to siphon off McCain's support as Bush is, and they placed
long odds on a Bush victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unlikely,'' said Jack Pitney, a professor of government
and politics at Claremont McKenna College in Southern California,
noting that the vast majority of people now holding statewide
office in California are Democrats. ``But it's possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, California is for Bush what Florida is for Gore: a
long shot worth a commitment of time and money if only to compel
the opposition to invest a hefty portion of its own finite
resources in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and his advisers said they were doing more than making
a noble show in the state. Bush noted that his two-day trip to
California is not connected to any fund-raising events and is a
purely political endeavor. One of his senior advisers added that
Bush would be back twice in May and twice in June.
</P>
<P>
   The state's special allure is explained by many political
analysts' electoral arithmetic, which figures that while Bush does
not need to carry California to win the general election, a victory
by him here would almost certainly doom Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with Bush and in subsequent conversations with
his advisers, several aspects of his campaign's strategy for making
that possible became clear. Bush hopes that his sustained focus on
education will appeal to the state's independent voters and others
in the center of the political spectrum; that the inclusive
language in his oratory will draw Latinos to his side; that his
support for free trade will please both agricultural workers and
technology concerns, and that his call for legislation to curtail
lawsuits will draw support in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But several political analysts said there are just as many
losing cards in Bush's deck: notably, his positions and record on
gun control, the environment and abortion, issues on which
Californians tend to be more liberal than Bush.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed a Texas law that allows people with proper training
and certification to carry concealed handguns. He leads a state
that is, by some measures, the most polluted in the country. And he
supports a constitutional amendment to outlaw abortion in most
cases.
</P>
<P>
   Polls of voters after they cast ballots in the California
primary showed that 65 percent of them believed that abortion
should be mostly or always legal. Asked about abortion here
Thursday, Bush suggested that he might actually be better
positioned than Gore and might challenge the vice president as too
extreme on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll sign a ban on partial-birth abortion and my opponent will
not,'' Bush said. ``I look forward to hearing why, and I think a
lot of people in California will look forward to hearing why.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said that Bush's ability to soften his
conservative edges could be decisive, and Bush seems to have taken
that into account.
</P>
<P>
   He gave his first education address, in which he unveiled
proposals that he said were designed to help the neediest students,
at the meeting of a Hispanic business association in Los Angeles in
September.
</P>
<P>
   For a speech last month on the need for people of different
races and religions to respect one another, Bush appeared at the
Simon Wiesenthal Center and Museum of Tolerance in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent that he finds his voice in compassionate
conservatism and has a message of tolerance and inclusion, which is
no different from the way he's governed Texas, he can put together
a winning campaign,'' said Steven Merksamer, a Republican
strategist here.
</P>
<P>
   The specific challenge within that overarching one, political
analysts said, was to grab more than 30 percent of the growing
Latino vote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush won re-election in Texas in 1998 with nearly half of the
Latino vote. But outrage among many Latinos in California over the
harsh language with which Republicans promoted Proposition 187,
which was designed to deny public services to illegal immigrants,
could hurt Bush, political analysts said. He acknowledged that
Thursday, showing in manner and language how badly he wanted to
heal the rift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Republican,'' Bush said at a news conference here.
``There are those who say, `No tiene corazon.' He doesn't have a
heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's what a campaign's about,'' he added, meaning the
changing of inaccurate perceptions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
