<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9353 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-GERMANY-BANKS-525&AMP;ADD     04-06 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BANKS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRESDNER AND DEUTSCHE BANK SEEN VULNERABLE AFTER COLLAPSE OF DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The turmoil in German banking intensified
Thursday, as the chairman of Dresdner Bank resigned because of the
failed merger deal with Deutsche Bank AG.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation of the Dresdner executive, Bernhard Walter, came
a day after he canceled plans for a $29 billion merger with
Deutsche Bank, Germany's largest, which would have created the
biggest banking combination in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   But far from ensuring Dresdner's independence, Walter's moves
seemed to strengthen a conviction among industry executives that
Dresdner, the No. 3 bank in Germany, had become a takeover target
for rivals across Europe and possibly even the United States. ``I
think it's open season,'' said a German investment banker. ``It is
painfully obvious that the bank cannot stay independent.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just Dresdner Bank that now looks vulnerable. Deutsche
Bank, the larger of the would-be partners, has come under withering
criticism from analysts, the German media and some political
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Boersen Zeitung, Germany's stock market newspaper, skewered the
failed merger as a ``Disaster Among Equals.'' The tabloid Bild
carried the headline: ``Megaslap in the Face for Money Bosses.
Whole World Laughs.'' And Germany's chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder,
chimed in, observing that ``I've seen more mature performances in
the corporate sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, German attitudes toward mergers and hostile takeovers
seemed to have crossed a boundary. Suddenly, anything seems
possible and the only consensus view is that things will not stay
the same.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of Deutsche Bank, Rolf-Ernst Breuer, acknowledged
at a news conference in Frankfurt on Thursday that his own company
was not immune from hostile takeover attempts. ``It's something
that naturally runs through your mind,'' Breuer remarked, though he
added that a hostile takeover would not be practical.
</P>
<P>
   Yet beyond bungling a deal it had heralded a month ago, Deutsche
Bank is again burdened with a retail branch network that barely
makes money. The combination with Dresdner was supposed to solve
that problem in two ways. First, Deutsche and Dresdner would have
merged their branches and eliminated overlapping ones. Second, they
would have spun off the combined system into a company controlled
by the German insurer Allianz AG.
</P>
<P>
   But the deal imploded Wednesday, when Walter and Dresdner
refused demands by Deutsche Bank to shut down most of the
investment banking arm, Dresdner Kleinwort Benson.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his resignation, Walter again blamed Deutsche for
the merger's collapse and said an extraordinary opportunity had
been wasted.
</P>
<P>
   And although Dresdner Bank said that its board had unanimously
decided to break off merger talks, Walter seemed to be a target of
wrath within the bank and possibly at Allianz, Dresdner's biggest
shareholder. Allianz executives, though publicly quiet, have let it
be known that they would welcome new takeover bids for Dresdner.
Among the banking companies rumored to have an interest are
Citigroup and Chase Manhattan of the United States, ABN Amro and
ING of the Netherlands, Banque Nationale de Paris and the
British-based HSBC.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Had the intended merger succeeded, the combined assets of
Deutsche Bank and Dresdner Bank would have totaled $1.2 trillion,
second in size to the Mizuho Financial Group _ the announced merger
of Fuji Bank, the Industrial Bank of Japan and Dai-Ichi Kangyo
Bank, with $1.3 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   There were sporadic calls Thursday for Breuer to quit at
Deutsche Bank. But Breuer, looking disappointed but still
unruffled, said he saw ``no reason to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   But the merger fiasco was an acute embarrassment for Breuer, who
has sought to push Deutsche Bank into the elite ranks of global
powerhouses. In failing to anticipate the problems in his own
merger, Breuer raised questions about Deutsche's credibility as an
adviser on other mergers and acquisitions, one of the lucrative
areas of investment banking.
</P>
<P>
   Breuer's image was not helped by his contradictory assertions
immediately after announcing the merger March 9. He insisted then
that Dresdner's investment banking business was ``a jewel'' that
would neither be sold nor shut down. But a few days later, Breuer
reversed himself and said that all options were open. As it
happened, Deutsche Bank pushed hard for an outright sale of
Dresdner Kleinwort Benson and then, as a fallback position, argued
for a ``partial integration'' that would have shut down most of it.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, Breuer said he had not known
what would be necessary because he could not see the details of
Dresdner's structure until after the two banks had announced formal
merger talks.
</P>
<P>
   But he also shed light on a potentially fatal flaw in the way he
approached the issues. Preoccupied about preserving secrecy, Breuer
said he refused to ask for advice from many people within his own
company who knew something about Dresdner Bank's inner workings.
``Once you start asking questions, there are suspicions and that is
when the rumor mill gets started,'' Breuer said. ``We wanted to
limit this to a very small circle of people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
