<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick Map Seen for Human Genome
</P>
<P>
   Dr. J. Craig Venter of Celera Genomics told a congressional
panel that his company would assemble the whole human genome within
three to six weeks, far earlier than previously thought. The
genome's 3 billion letters of DNA are expected to provide the basis
for a new generation of medical treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Arista Future Is Cloudy for Davis
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of an intensifying spat in the music world and his
likely departure from the Arista label, Clive Davis, its longtime
president, is not planning to participate in a meeting next week of
executives of BMG, which owns Arista. Relations between Davis and
BMG have been awkward since reports emerged last year that BMG
wanted to anoint a younger successor to Davis, 66.
</P>
<P>
   Solid Retail Sales Help Lift Stocks
</P>
<P>
   Stocks rose, buoyed in part by news that March store sales at
some retailers were on the high end of expectations. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained 80.35 points, or 0.73 percent, to
11,114.27, while the Nasdaq composite index jumped 98.34 points, or
2.36 percent, to 4,267.56. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index
rose 13.97 points, to 1,501.34.
</P>
<P>
   Ford to Sell Gas-Electric Vehicle
</P>
<P>
   Ford announced that it would begin selling a small sport utility
vehicle in 2003 using both gasoline and electric propulsion for
better gas mileage. General Motors and DaimlerChrysler are working
on similar vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Optimistic Analyst Lifts QXL.com
</P>
<P>
   Shares of QXL.com, a British Internet company, soared 75 percent
after an analyst for one of the brokerage firms that underwrote
QXL's offering six months ago forecast that the shares would rise
more than tenfold. QXL.com leaped $29.65625, to $51.984375. The
timing of the opinion could not have been better for some of the
insiders at QXL.com. The lock-up period, during which insiders were
barred from selling shares, ends today.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Begins TV Ad Campaign
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft began a television advertising campaign featuring Bill
Gates, its chairman, pointing to Microsoft's record of innovation
and determination to carry on. The 30-second ad makes no direct
mention of the ruling this week in which a federal judge found the
company to have violated antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   Gas Prices Expected to Fall
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department said that gasoline will cost a good deal
less this summer than what was predicted just one month ago. Prices
should peak this month at $1.52 a gallon, before falling to $1.39
by September.
</P>
<P>
   SingTel Looks Toward Malaysia
</P>
<P>
   A month after losing a bid to buy Hong Kong's leading telephone
operator, Singapore Telecommunications has turned its attention to
neighboring Malaysia, where it is in talks to buy a stake in Time
Engineering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0478 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FORD-GAS-ELECTRIC-NYT     04-06 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-GAS-ELECTRIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TO SELL GASOLINE-ELECTRIC VEHICLE IN 2003 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo.)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. announced Thursday that it would begin
selling a small sport utility vehicle in 2003 using both gasoline
and electric propulsion for better gas mileage. General Motors and
DaimlerChrysler are working on similar sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Escape, which is a little smaller than a Ford Explorer
and a little larger than a Honda CR-V, will go on sale this autumn
with only gasoline engines available. The optional hybrid engine
will be offered on Escapes built three years later at a slightly
higher price, Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Escape has a carlike underbody, instead of the
heavy, pickup-truck-like underbody of Ford's other sport utilities,
it gets 23 miles to the gallon in the city and 28 miles to the
gallon on the highway with a four-cylinder gasoline engine. Ford
said that equipping the vehicle with the hybrid engine would
increase its fuel efficiency to almost 40 miles a gallon in the
city and on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   In the hybrid models, the gasoline engine and the vehicle's own
braking will charge the electric motor, which will not require
separate charging. In the Escape and other hybrid automobiles, the
gasoline engine shuts off when the vehicle stops; once the driver
touches the accelerator, an electric motor powered by batteries
gets the vehicle moving again while the gasoline engine turns back
on.
</P>
<P>
   Honda has just started selling the Honda Insight, a tiny coupe
with a gasoline-electric engine that gets up to 70 miles per gallon
on the highway. This summer Toyota will start selling its Prius, a
hybrid that is similar to a Toyota Corolla but which gets about 50
miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials said that they had been working on hybrid
technology for years and that their timetable had not been affected
by the Japanese offerings or the recent rise in gasoline prices.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler introduced a prototype of a hybrid Dodge Durango
last autumn that would, the company said, get an average of 18.6
miles per gallon in city and highway driving, compared with 15.5
miles per gallon for the current model with a gasoline-only engine.
GM has been collaborating with Toyota to develop a car-based sport
utility vehicle the size of a Subaru Forester that would also carry
a hybrid engine. GM and DaimlerChrysler have not yet announced
plans for mass production.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives from GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler joined Vice
President Al Gore at a news conference in Washington last week on
improving fuel economy. William Powers, Ford's vice president for
research, said in an interview that the company did not mention its
plans in Washington because ``we had agreed months ago with our
partners we wouldn't upstage each other.'' A Gore aide said that
was true.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has long sought tighter fuel-economy regulations. The
industry supports President Clinton's recent proposal for a $3,000
tax credit for electric and hybrid propulsion automobiles, which
would roughly offset for consumers the extra cost of the hybrid
engine.
</P>
<P>
   The hybrid Ford Escape will be built on the same assembly line
in Claycomo, Mo., that will build the regular Ford Escape, Ford
said. The hybrid will use many components from Visteon Automotive
Systems, a giant auto parts subsidiary that Ford's board is
expected to spin off at its board meeting next Thursday, probably
by ordering that Visteon shares be distributed to Ford
shareholders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0479 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9362 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-ATMs-ART-$ADV09-N     04-06 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ATMs-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.M.)  
 GETTING YOUR CASH WITHOUT PAYING  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo was sent as NYT28 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Just about everyone but the banking industry seems to be
irritated by ATM fees. Especially infuriating to many consumers is
the double whammy: paying a fee to both your bank and another bank
when you use the second bank's automated teller machine.
</P>
<P>
   The fees _ $1.50 to $3 or more a transaction _ may not seem like
much individually, but they can add up to hundreds of dollars a
year, depending on where and how often ATMs are used.
</P>
<P>
   If you are irked enough, though, and don't want the
inconvenience of limiting yourself to your bank's ATMs, there are
some new ways to avoid the fees.
</P>
<P>
   One alternative is Internet banking. Many cyberbanks _ like
X.com, First Internet Bank and CompuBank _ will refund a limited
amount of other banks' ATM charges, usually about $6 a month.
</P>
<P>
   While there is no question that Web banking can often mean lower
fees and higher interest rates, it can also be ragged around the
edges. Some of the Web sites are cluttered and difficult to
navigate. Procedures can be confusing, and it can take longer,
sometimes much longer, to open an account than at a regular bank.
The elderly, especially, may not be comfortable with the online
approach.
</P>
<P>
   And many Web-only banks, of course, have no ATM networks. That
means that their customers must use the fee-charging cash machines
of regular banks _ so that $6 allowance can vanish quickly. If
consumers do their online banking with a traditional bank, they
have access to its ATM network but are unlikely to get the low fees
and high interest rates available at many Internet-only banks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another way to avoid ATM fees is to replace a checking account
with a particular type of asset management account at a brokerage
firm. Merrill Lynch and Charles Schwab, for instance, give holders
of such accounts unlimited refunds on all ATM charges, whatever the
source. The catch at Merrill Lynch is that the account requires a
$250,000 balance; Schwab's requires $100,000, or 12
commission-generating stock trades a year. In both cases, the
balances can be maintained with any blend of assets, including
stocks, bonds and cash.
</P>
<P>
   A few conventional banks also reimburse ATM fees, though there
can be sizable trade-offs. One you might consider is USAA Federal
Savings Bank of San Antonio. The bank, a subsidiary of USAA, the
big insurer that caters to military personnel, welcomes all
consumers and credits an account with up to $1.50 each time another
bank charges for using an ATM, up to $15 a month.
</P>
<P>
   USAA, whose military background makes it accustomed to dealing
with far-flung clients, also offers checking accounts with no fees
and no minimum balances. It also offers overdraft protection, loans
and credit cards (800 531-2265).
</P>
<P>
   Of course, making deposits by mail with a distant institution
takes time. But if your paycheck or retirement check is deposited
electronically, it can go into an out-of-state bank account as
quickly as it goes into one at a local bank.
</P>
<P>
   Some people may worry that local merchants won't accept checks
from an out-of-state bank. But several supermarket managers at
chains in northern New Jersey said this was not a problem if
customers had check-cashing cards issued by the store. Merrill
Lynch and Charles Schwab use banks in Pennsylvania and Ohio,
respectively, for their asset management accounts; representatives
of both firms said check acceptance had not been an issue with
their customers.
</P>
<P>
   And if a merchant won't take such a check, a customer can always
get the cash from an ATM or use a debit or credit card.
</P>
<P>
   Although USAA has been offering its program for five years, the
notion of ATM refunds is not exactly catching fire among
conventional banks. So it pays to shop around.
</P>
<P>
   Hilltop Community Bank in Summit, N.J., which has only one
office and one ATM, will refund from $1.50 to $10 a month of ATM
fees, depending on the account balance. To get the full $10,
customers must maintain a balance of at least $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is credit unions, if you have access to one.
But be careful: some are following banks to the ATM jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, maybe you've decided that using only ATMs operated
by your bank and carrying extra cash isn't such a bad idea after
all.
</P>
<P>
   David A. Remley, 68, a writer and historian who lives in Silver
City, N.M., does just that. He banks at Ambank, a small, locally
owned bank that has only two ATMs, both in Silver City. When he
travels, which he says is not often, he uses his Visa card for
purchases or takes along enough cash to avoid charges for tapping
another bank's machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I would hate those ATM fees,'' he said, ``if I
actually ever paid any.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
