<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9363 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SMITHFIELD-HAM-ART-2T     04-06 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHFIELD-HAM-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISE OF SMITHFIELD FOODS, THE GOLIATH OF THE HOG WORLD, WORRIES
REGULATORS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Colo., N.Y., Va., Iowa, Ill., Mo., Canada, France and
Poland) (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAR HEEL, N.C. _ In the coastal plains here, where tobacco once
ruled, sit hundreds of corporate hog farms, punctuated by giant
lagoons filled with manure. Just off Route 87, not far from the
Cape Fear River, is the world's largest meatpacking plant, a
structure so colossal that its waste-water treatment plant could
serve a midsize city.
</P>
<P>
   The farms and the plant, which can kill 7 million hogs a year,
belong to Smithfield Foods, the world's largest hog producer and
pork processor _ and the company at the center of a fierce debate
over the rise of big agriculture.
</P>
<P>
   By aggressively acquiring its larger rivals over the last two
years and using precision genetics, huge hog farms and giant
meatpacking plants to control every stage of production, Smithfield
has ballooned into a $5 billion company that accounts for nearly a
quarter of the nation's pork.
</P>
<P>
   But in doing so, it has come under intense scrutiny from
regulators who say that agricultural giants may wield too much
control over the food supply.
</P>
<P>
   After Smithfield announced in September that it would acquire
Murphy Family Farms, the nation's largest hog producer, the
Agriculture Department called the company ``absurdly big,'' and
asked the Justice Department's antitrust division to review the
deal. More recently, the attorney general in Iowa, a big pork
producer, challenged the merger in state court, arguing that
Smithfield is trying to skirt a state law that forbids a
meatpacking company from operating hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   There are also growing concerns that the company's hog waste
could pose dangers to local water supplies, and that giant hog
operations could cripple small farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden we have this 800-pound gorilla in the pork
industry,'' said Betsy Freese, the livestock editor at Successful
Farming magazine in Des Moines, Iowa. ``The troubling part for a
lot of farmers is if the packer owns production, where are you
going to sell your pigs?''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, Smithfield executives say the company has been
unfairly maligned and has been a pioneer in developing a more
systematic approach and healthier meat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did in the pork industry is what Perdue and Tyson did
in the poultry business,'' said Joseph W. Luter III, chairman and
chief executive of Smithfield, which is based in Smithfield, Va.
``Vertical integration gives you high quality, consistent products
with consistent genetics. And the only way to do that is to control
the process from the farm to the packing plant.''
</P>
<P>
   Luter says the company is responding to market forces. As
supermarket chains, food-service companies and fast-food outlets
sell more pork, they demand more consistency and higher quality.
</P>
<P>
   Smithfield is also adapting to a trend that began in the
Southeast _ creating factory-size hog farms by using contract
farmers, who put up the capital to build special barns and provide
the labor to raise pigs to company specifications.
</P>
<P>
   No longer is the market dominated by small Midwestern farmers,
who raise hogs and sell them to meatpackers. Four companies now
account for nearly 30 percent of the nation's hog supply, and four
big meatpackers slaughter about 60 percent of the nation's pork.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture, some experts say, is merely mimicking the larger
economy. ``This is what has evolved out of the marketplace,'' said
John Lawrence, an agricultural economist at Iowa State University
in Ames.
</P>
<P>
   In Smithfield's ``birth to bacon'' approach, everything is
calculated: genetics, artificial insemination, barns with automated
feeding systems and computers that monitor temperature and
ventilation. A special feed, executives say, creates pork as lean
as chicken in a brand the company is taking national: Smithfield's
Lean Generation Pork.
</P>
<P>
   Smithfield has one of the world's largest meatpacking plants, a
973,000-square-foot facility here in Tar Heel, about 20 miles east
of Fayetteville. The plant relies on a ``disassembly line,'' which
has its roots in the 19th century, but the system is aided by new
technologies, like laser-equipped cutting machines.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Tar Heel plant _ which can process up to
32,000 hogs a day _ is an efficient killing machine. Squealing hogs
funnel into an area where they are electrocuted, stabbed in the
jugular, then tied, lifted and carried on a winding journey through
the plant. They are dunked in scalding water, their hair is
removed, they are run through a fiery furnace (to burn off residual
hair), then disemboweled and sliced by an army of young, often
immigrant, laborers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the plant, which is chilled, teams of
workers cut hog meat into smaller pieces. Wearing frocks, rubber
boots and ear plugs, they stand shoulder to shoulder, dipping
knives in hot water and then making quick cuts in meat passing
rapidly on a conveyor belt.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Smithfield's five plants can handle up to 19 million
hogs a year, turning out more than 5 billion pounds of pork.
</P>
<P>
   Luter, a tart-tongued 60-year-old Virginian who runs the company
from his Park Avenue apartment in New York City and his home in
Aspen, Colo., took over a small meatpacking company his father
founded in 1936 and made it into one of the world's largest food
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Believing that the fat profits were in raising and processing
hogs, Smithfield joined forces with three North Carolina producers
to form Circle Four Farms. The four companies, which pioneered the
use of giant confinement barns that can hold up to 5,000 pigs,
agreed to use similar genetics and feed and send all hogs to
Smithfield packing plants.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance has moved into Western states but has had less
impact in the Midwest because of anti-corporate farming laws. As a
result, hog production has boomed in the South and West but is in
sharp decline in the Midwest. Chicago is no longer ``hog butcher to
the world.'' Iowa, despite its plentiful grain, is about to lose to
North Carolina its title as the biggest hog state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our farmers are doing pigs because they were looking
for an alternative to tobacco,'' said Walter Cherry, executive
director of the North Carolina Pork Council, in Raleigh.
``Twenty-five years ago, we just didn't have pigs. Now, we're doing
$2 billion in pigs.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Smithfield has acquired most of its Circle Four
partners, including the nation's two largest hog producers,
Carroll's Foods and Murphy Family Farms. It also bought Schneider,
Canada's largest processor, and North Side Foods, maker of
McDonald's breakfast sausages. Smithfield just said it would
acquire a big Iowa processing plant from Farmland Industries, a
huge cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Ranked as the nation's No. 7 pork producer in 1997, Smithfield
is now No. 1; a year ago, it also became the biggest hog processor
and even sells a large array of branded products like Gwaltney's.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though Smithfield's share price has fallen recently, Luter says
the company, which made a profit of $94 million on its $3.7 billion
in sales last year, will produce stronger and less volatile growth.
Smithfield's stock closed unchanged on Thursday, at $22.75, up from
its 52-week low of $14.875 in February, but well below its 52-week
high of $34.0625 last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts agree that the outlook for Smithfield is
bright. ``I'm a big believer,'' said David C. Nelson at Credit
Suisse First Boston, who insists the shares are undervalued. ``They
generated the best return of any food company in the last decade.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's drive, however, could be upset by a thicket of
legal and political challenges. Regulators are considering new
measures to cover corporate hog farms. Battles have broken out in
Colorado, Missouri and Iowa. In North Carolina, there is a
moratorium on building new corporate hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   Putrid smells and contaminated waste water have led to federal
fines and a public relations fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh won a Pulitzer Prize for
a series detailing hog waste problems tied to Murphy Family Farms.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, the Environmental Protection Agency fined
Smithfield $12.6 million after its processing plants violated the
Clean Water Act by discharging pollutants into the Pagan River. The
pollutants eventually reached the Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at his Park Avenue apartment, Luter acknowledged
some lapses, but blamed politicians and environmentalists for
distorting the company's environmental record and ignoring the
benefits of big agriculture. He said the company was spending
millions of dollars on food safety and the environment.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA unjustly fined the company, Luter said, and ignored its
efforts to comply with state laws. ``I'm still outraged,'' he said
of the fines. ``Much of it came from agricultural runoff. Did it
have any major impact on the river? No.''
</P>
<P>
   Luter also scoffs at the idea of dangerous industry
concentration. The poultry and beef industries are much more
concentrated, he said, pointing to a different culprit in recent
low hog prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not concentration; it's too many hogs,'' he said. ``It
was just too profitable for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   With low prices pinching farmers in the Midwest, Congress has
responded by trying to put limits on big mergers and restraints on
companies like Smithfield.
</P>
<P>
   One idea is to give the Agriculture Department the power to
enforce anti-competitive laws, particularly in meatpacking; members
of Congress also plan to introduce legislation to prevent packers
from owning the hogs they slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Charles Grassley, R-Iowa, said he was outraged when Luter
issued a press release saying Smithfield would keep consolidating.
``There's always been some consolidation,'' Grassley said in an
interview. ``But the aggressive pursuit of mega-corporate
agriculture that Smithfield is making will ruin the family farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department is also concerned that consolidation
could give meatpackers too much power over prices. ``Farmers don't
like the fact that they're selling to so few buyers,'' said Keith
Collins, the agency's chief economist.
</P>
<P>
   In Iowa, Attorney General Thomas J. Miller filed suit against
Smithfield in January, trying to block its merger with Murphy.
Because Smithfield has a meatpacking plant in Sioux City, Miller
said the acquisition of Murphy, which produces hogs in Iowa, would
violate the state's corporate farming laws, which forbid a company
to control farm production and processing.
</P>
<P>
   The state also accused Smithfield of engaging in a sham
transaction after it agreed to sell Murphy's hog farms to Randall
D. Stoecker, a Murphy employee, for $79 million. Stoecker borrowed
the $79 million from Murphy and created Stoecker Farms, and the
state says Smithfield still controls the hog production.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a state judge appointed a special investigator to
study the case. Luter said he expected a settlement soon.
</P>
<P>
   With domestic opposition growing, Smithfield has acquired big
companies in Canada, France and Poland. ``The current hostility
from interest groups in this country has made other parts of the
world look good to us,'' Luter said.
</P>
<P>
   At home, many small farmers are fighting back against the
perceived Goliath by joining cooperatives. Many are offering
fatter, better-tasting meat that appeals to fine restaurants and
other niche markets. They are raising hogs that are free of
antibiotics and selling organic pork, at a premium. And legislators
are standing behind them. But Luter insists American agriculture is
forever changed, and global markets, not legislators, are charting
the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is the small farmers have been disappearing
for 100 years,'' Luter said. ``If you want to protect the small
farmer, you are going to do it on the back of the American
consumer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
