<HEADER>
A9365 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-ART     04-06 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-CONVENTION-ART-535&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUPS SUE PHILADELPHIA OVER LIMITS ON PROTESTS AT REPUBLICAN
CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT33 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ A coalition of more than 50 protest groups filed
suit in federal court on Thursday charging that this city's new
restrictions on public assembly during the Republican presidential
convention this summer will stifle dissent and violate the free
speech rights of all but the conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has created a system under which the Republican
National Committee stands astride every public forum in
Philadelphia,'' the coalition, which includes the NAACP and the
National Organization for Women, contended in a complaint filed in
Federal District Court by the American Civil Liberties Union.
</P>
<P>
   The city has passed an ``Omnibus Special Events Permit'' law
that in effect gives Republican officials priority to monopolize
prime public gathering places for convention parties and
gatherings. In addition, city officials have rejected the protest
coalition's permit request for a march and rally through the heart
of the city on July 30, the eve of the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the planned rally, known as Unity 2000, said they had
sought a legal, peaceful demonstration and did not want to be
driven to the civil disobedience that some other groups were
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to go away and we are not going to remain
silent,'' declared Michael Morrill, director of Unity 2000, who
estimated that tens of thousands of demonstrators were planning to
come here during the four-day convention.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the court upholds the right of the protesters to march,
Morrill said, ``I really fear what could happen during the
convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the special law passed for the convention, the city would
restrict protesters to demonstrating in a 40-by-190-foot zone
several hundred feet from the convention center, within sight,
police promise, of delegates arriving by bus at a neighboring
parking area. Fifty minutes would be allotted to each group of up
to 1,500 people chosen under a lottery system. Beyond that zone,
Republican officials would have priority in using the city's major
public areas, including Dilworth Plaza, Love Park and a half dozen
other outdoor venues.
</P>
<P>
   ``No city has ever tried to deed over to one political party the
totality of its expressive places,'' Stefan Presser, legal director
of the ACLU, said at a news conference. In his filing, Presser
cited earlier protest litigation in 1987, during the bicentennial
celebration of the Constitution, when city officials were enjoined
by a federal judge against excessive interference with rightful
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   In preparing for the convention, city officials have been
mindful of the street protests against the World Trade Organization
that veered into vandalism last November in downtown Seattle. But
they say that the squares and parks here might be opened to protest
groups should Republican officials exercise their refusal rights by
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, coalition officials insisted that the refusal was
unlikely and that any decision close to the convention opening
would effectively scuttle their plans for mass protest. The member
groups' causes include labor, the environment, human rights, AIDS,
global economics and women's rights.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the city's current mix of pride and caution about the
convention and all the attention it will bring, The Philadelphia
Inquirer has editorialized that the plan for the ``locked-down look
of Center City'' may seem ``a bit like Chicago'' in 1968 when
anti-war protesters and police clashed violently in the streets.
``The city that is liberty's birthplace ought to be as open to
protest as possible,'' the newspaper advised.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John F. Street, a Democrat, has vowed to accommodate all
visitors fairly and peaceably. While police have been closely
studying the lessons of Seattle and preparing large-scale crowd
control measures, Kenneth Trujillo, the city solicitor, has
emphasized that protest permits are decided on the basis of traffic
and safety considerations, not on the politics of the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city does not have any intention of infringing on
anybody's constitutional rights,'' Trujillo declared.
</P>
<P>
   But the suit contends that the city is intent on avoiding
controversy and polishing its image by limiting mass protest and
has ``in effect authorized a single, preferred ideology'' in behalf
of the Republican conventioneers. The 1996 Republican convention
also had a restricted protest zone in San Diego, where
demonstrators sued to have it placed closer to the convention hall.
Presser argued that Philadelphia had gone beyond this precedent in
controlling prime gathering places beyond the convention to
``prevent all demonstrations.'' Plans for the Democratic convention
in Los Angeles also include a restricted protest zone near the
convention headquarters. But party officials said that so far there
had been no constitutional challenge and that other major city
venues were available for groups seeking to rally.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
