NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR FRIDAY, APRIL 7
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Friday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-NY-FASHION-HELP-NYT (moved on Wednesday, April 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, April
5, about the trend toward casual dress in the workplace misstated
part of the name of a New York law firm that will adopt casual
dress this summer. It is Simpson Thacher &AMP; Bartlett, not Thatcher.
</P>
<P>
   BC-BLACK-WRITERS-CONFERENCE-NYT (moved on Sunday, April 2)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, April 2,
about the Fifth National Black Writers Conference referred
incorrectly to a comment by the writer Ishmael Reed. He said the
Internet enabled black writers to produce and review their own art
independent of critics and publishers. He did not refer
specifically to white critics and publishers.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MILITARY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT (moved on Thursday, March 23)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, March
23, about ``The Kinder, Gentler Military'' by Stephanie Gutmann
misstated the book's description of the Army's grenade throwing
requirement for women in combat training. The book says both men
and women are required to run a course with a grenade and to hit
targets from a variety of distances; women are not allowed merely
to drop a live grenade over a wall.
</P>
