<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9368 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-BIZ-WORLD-IKEA-ART-2T     04-06 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-WORLD-IKEA-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 MOSCOW GIVES IKEA A FROSTY WELCOME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos has been sent as NYT21, 22 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Serice   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Agreed. It wasn't such a good idea for Ikea, the
Swedish furniture retailer, to try to open its advertising campaign
in the Moscow Metro for its first Russian store with a picture of a
bed and the slogan, ``Every 10th European was made in one of our
beds.''
</P>
<P>
   Johannes Stenberg, the Ikea marketing manager for Russia,
acknowledged the error. ``The sensitivities of Russians are higher
than we are used to,'' he said. The Metro management declared the
slogan in bad taste and, Stenberg added, ``said we couldn't prove
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities killed the ad campaign. But now Ikea has a more
serious problem: the City of Moscow is blocking construction of an
overpass the company was building to ease the flow of traffic into
its new store.
</P>
<P>
   The Moscow roadblock is a reminder of the worst aspects of doing
business in Russia, where laws and bureaucrats can be arbitrary,
rules can change quickly and corruption is always a problem. And
the city's refusal to relent is a negative signal for other foreign
investors, especially given Ikea's painstaking two and a half year
effort to bring its low-cost yet stylish furniture and housewares
to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea seemed to have gotten most everything right. It even
managed to convince the Russian government to change the way custom
duties were calculated on furniture, switching from weight to the
value of the furniture itself. The weight method would have made
duties on Ikea furniture so high that it would be impossible to
sell at the company's low prices.
</P>
<P>
   The 300,000-square-foot store just outside Moscow's city limits
in Khimki opened to a crowd of more than 37,000 on March 22.
Stenberg said that about 30 percent of the 265,000 people who
visited the store in its first two weeks made purchases. And he
said that they were not the Russian rich, but average consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were looking out at the parking lot we were seeing
many more Ladas and Zhigulis'' _ workhorses of Russia's automotive
fleet _ ``than Mercedes and BMWs,'' he said. And only about 3
percent of all the purchases were made with credit cards, another
sign, he said, that the store was attracting average consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea is a welcome relief for such Russians. They usually
encounter only top-of-the-line prices in the new, dazzling shopping
malls that have popped up in Moscow to offer foreign-made products.
And those malls have mostly been empty since the financial crisis
that followed the devaluation of the ruble and the government's
default on its debt in August of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the Ikea store and the general plight of the
average Russian consumer have made it hard for the company to
understand why the City of Moscow is refusing to let it complete
the overpass. The traffic jam caused by cars turning off the main
highway on opening day backed up traffic for three miles by noon
and continues to be a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The city stopped Ikea from finishing its $4.5 million overpass
when it was two pillars short of completion, although the overpass
is outside Moscow city limits. The third and fourth pillar must go
on the Leningradskoye Shosse _ the main highway to the airport _
and the city has some control over construction there. Moscow says
that Ikea needs the city's approval before constructing anything
there that would block the view of a famous World War II monument.
</P>
<P>
   However, Moscow's objections to the overpass have been portrayed
in some of the city's newspapers as revenge for Ikea's decision to
locate its store three miles outside of the city limits, depriving
the city of substantial revenues. City officials could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Stenberg, who said ``It's very sad if it is revenge,'' added
that Ikea's choice reflected the company's dedication to keeping
its costs down.
</P>
<P>
   A long-term lease on land in Moscow, he said, would have been
too expensive. Ikea even offered to clean up an old industrial area
in the city in exchange for a cheaper lease, Stenberg said, but
``Moscow showed no flexibility at all.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The prices for a lease in the Moscow region outside of the city
``were much lower and continue to be much lower,'' he said, though
Ikea, which is a private company, would not provide specific
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Ikea, based in Copenhagen for tax reasons, has 153 stores and is
adding 10 to 15 a year. As it expands its global reach, it is has
run into problems in various spots around the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has, for instance, created a small firestorm in Westchester
County, N.Y., with its effort to build a store in New Rochelle, a
project that would require the demolition of homes. In response to
the threat of increased traffic coming through neighboring towns,
the Town Council of Mamaroneck is set to vote this week on a
proposal to require Mamaroneck's approval for large-scale stores
and malls in nearby towns. A resident of Larchmont has founded
Wrain, Westchester Residents Against Ikea Now.
</P>
<P>
   But the Moscow problem is the kind that could be a more chilling
signal to foreign investors, especially given the general
difficulties even successful companies have had locating in Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian economy is recovering. The country's gross national
product rose 3 percent last year and is poised to gain as much or
more this year. That means Russian consumers could have more to
spend.
</P>
<P>
   But the laws, regulations and consistency needed to make doing
business easier is still absent, and it will be some time before it
is clear how much Russia's new president, Vladimir V. Putin, will
change the system.
</P>
<P>
   So a glitch like Ikea's problem with Moscow could deter some
foreign companies from expanding in Russia. Yet this is the kind of
investment that is needed to give the Russian economy a long-term
chance.
</P>
<P>
   The extent of Moscow's unhappiness with Ikea was detailed in an
article in the newspaper Kommersant, a business daily, which said
it had obtained minutes of a March meeting of city hall officials.
The minutes, according to a translation of the article, say that
Mayor Yuri Luzhkov's press secretary was assigned to organize the
publication of relevant critical material concerning ``illegal
activity of Ikea'' in city newspapers. Though the article did not
specify what the alleged illegal activity refers to, Ikea assumes
it is the building of the overpass without Moscow's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question here is what is the law?,'' Stenberg said. ``We
have a document from the region, telling us to build, and we are
getting a decree from the city not to build. However we turn, we
are illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that Ikea's only negotiating point is to say _ as it
has _ that it still wants to build a store in the City of Moscow,
at the right price. But it has already leased a second site, of 131
acres, southwest of Moscow. Stenberg said that although Ikea had
approached the city ``in various ways'' about the overpass, it had
not yet been able to arrange a meeting with Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   If the overpass remains unfinished it would stand, Stenberg
said, ``as another monument to a failure to come to terms with a
major foreign investment in Russia.''
</P>
<P>
   The monument whose view Moscow says it is protecting is the spot
at which the German advance on Moscow was stopped in 1941. In
English, it is called the Tank Trap. Perhaps the unfinished
overpass could be called the Business Trap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
