<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9372 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-ART-     04-06 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-OVERVIEW-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY AN INDEX ISN'T A MIRROR OF THE MARKET  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many investors may think that they are protected from stormy
markets by investing in a large-stock index fund. They couldn't be
more wrong.
</P>
<P>
   With the major market indexes lurching to the precipice and
back, it is more important than ever that investors understand the
limitations of index investing today. Although index funds provide
an inexpensive way for investors to mirror the performance of broad
market indexes like the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the strategy has
become increasingly risky in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the way these funds are put together, they are much
less diversified than they used to be, making it important for
investors to take a more active role in broadening their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   ``By dint of their popularity, we can't ignore indexes,'' said
Anthony Maramarco, portfolio manager at the Babson Value fund in
Cambridge, Mass. ``But we also should realize that the widely
publicized indexes haven't for some time delivered on their claim
of being a truly representative measure of stock market
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of soaring performance, investing on auto pilot has
gone into a stall. Funds that try to reproduce the action of the
S&AMP;P 500, by far the most popular of the index funds, were up only
2.13 percent, on average, in the first quarter. That is a far cry
from the gains of 20 percent and more that investors in these funds
have grown accustomed to seeing in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   With returns on index funds so low, it is not that surprising
that the flood of money into them has slowed significantly. Lipper
Inc. estimates that $2.6 billion went into S&AMP;P 500 index funds in
January, less than half the $6 billion during the corresponding
month of 1999. And February saw an even greater falloff in cash
flows: just $300 million, compared with $4.4 billion in the month a
year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Still, these mutual funds remain home to a huge chunk of
investor assets. More than $228 billion was in S&AMP;P 500 index funds
as of the end of February, Lipper said. Although investors are
putting fresh money elsewhere _ mostly into technology stock funds
_ they still have plenty of their eggs in the index fund basket.
</P>
<P>
   As gains in the major indexes have slowed, or reversed, many
money managers have been finding the S&AMP;P 500 an easy benchmark to
beat. According to Morningstar Inc., nearly two-thirds of
diversified mutual funds investing in United States stocks are
outperforming S&AMP;P 500 index funds this year. That is quite a
turnabout. Three years ago, only 11 percent of mutual fund managers
beat the index.
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes it a very good time to reassess the index fund
phenomenon. Index funds have much going for them, but they have
downsides as well.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest problem is the idea that an investment in an
S&AMP;P 500 index fund is an investment in the broadly diversified
overall market. Because of the way most stock indexes are
constructed, funds that mimic them have heavier weightings in some
sectors than in others. This makes them much riskier than a more
diversified portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to what some investors still seem to think, the S&AMP;P 500
does not comprise equally weighted holdings of America's 500
largest stocks. It is weighted according to the stocks' market
capitalizations. So, as stocks rise in price, their impact on the
index's behavior rises as well. Similarly, as a stock falls on hard
times, its contribution to the S&AMP;P 500's performance dwindles, too.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P 500 index funds are less diversified today than ever. Last
year, only 31 stocks accounted for all the S&AMP;P 500's 21 percent
gain. By contrast, in 1995, 341 stocks were responsible for the
index's 37.6 percent climb. Put in a slightly different way, as of
March 1, the 10 largest holdings represented 25 percent of the
total market value of the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks have become a much larger part of the index.
They account for roughly one-third of its value, up from 9 percent
just 10 years ago. That big leap owes to the fact that the S&AMP;P 500,
as an index weighted by market capitalization, can become dominated
by stocks that have seen big jumps in their values.
</P>
<P>
   High-priced technology stocks are now the tail wagging the index
fund dog. Sure, the S&AMP;P 500 index remained quite stable during the
technology rout early last week. But that was in large part because
big value stocks rose sharply during the technology sell-off.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that making a big bet on technology may not be what
many index funds investors had in mind when they poured their
retirement dollars into funds that are supposed to mirror the
market. These, after all, are among the most volatile stocks
trading today.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 is not the only index in which relatively few issues
hold sway. Many investors have been turning to total stock market
index funds, which reflect the action in the Wilshire 5000 index,
for greater diversification. But, it turns out, these funds do not
necessarily provide it. According to statisticians at the Dow
Theory Forecasts newsletter, the 10 largest holdings in the
Vanguard Total Stock Market Index fund represent 19 percent of its
assets. And in any case, the Wilshire 5000's correlation to the S&AMP;P
500 is remarkably close.
</P>
<P>
   As particular stocks rise in price and constitute a larger
portion of an index, there is another problem for investors who add
to their fund holdings. They are essentially buying greater
proportions of companies that have already risen significantly and
reducing their exposure to stocks that have declined. In other
words, they are buying high and selling low.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, that has meant paying outlandish prices for
stocks that were among the most beloved. According to Maramarco of
Babson Value, investors who bought an S&AMP;P 500 index fund in March
were paying a median trailing price-to-earnings ratio of 42 for the
top 20 stocks in the index, compared with a median of 29 for the
overall index.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at the Leuthold Group, a market research firm in
Minneapolis, have studied some of the most popular stock indexes
and found some surprising discrepancies between what the indexes
are and what they are assumed to be.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the S&AMP;P Mid-Cap 400 index, which purports to be
representative of companies in the middle tier of stock market
capitalization, has a sizable proportion _ 16 percent _ of its
value in what many people consider to be large-cap stocks, those
with capitalizations of about $8 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, about one-tenth of the companies in the index
qualify as small companies, with market caps of less than $1.2
billion and more than $550 million. As a result, only
three-quarters of the index is made up of midsize companies.
</P>
<P>
   Another oddity is the S&AMP;P Small-Cap 600 index, in which 15
percent of the companies are in fact mid-tier. Almost one-third of
the index is made up of stocks with market values of $250 million
or less _ microcap companies by most measures. That means that just
77 percent of the companies in the small-cap index are truly small
companies.
</P>
<P>
   And because the Russell 2000, the most popular proxy for
small-stock performance, is reconstituted only once a year, it can
contain large numbers of stocks that have increased in price, and
therefore, no longer qualify as small.
</P>
<P>
   A result of all this is that fans of index funds who want a
truly diversified portfolio must do a lot more work today to
achieve it. No longer is it enough to buy a fund that mimics the
S&AMP;P 500 and forget about it. Such an investment puts most investors
too squarely in the growth and large-company sectors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, the only way to balance out is to find a value manager
and a small-cap manager,'' said Mike Schurmann, an analyst at the
Leuthold Group. ``Microsoft has a huge weighting on any
capitalization-weighted index it is in, as do the likes of Cisco
and Oracle. It's not just the fact that they're large-cap
companies; it's the fact that they've grown so quickly into being
the largest caps.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other kinds of index funds, of course. Alternatives
for investors looking to diversify include funds that mirror the
performance of the Russell 1000, an index of the country's 1,000
largest companies. While it has historically tracked the S&AMP;P
closely, so far this year it is greatly outperforming. Charles
Schwab's Small Cap Index fund is a low-cost offering that tracks a
proprietary index that includes the second-largest 1,000 companies.
</P>
<P>
   Investors looking for value stocks can choose from small- or
large-company index funds. The Vanguard Value Index fund tracks the
roughly 400 relatively cheap issues in the S&AMP;P/Barra Value index,
while the Vanguard Small Capitalization Value index fund tracks the
S&AMP;P Small-Cap 600/Barra Value index. All these funds have low
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Dimensional Fund Advisors of Santa Monica, Calif., runs a
variety of passively managed funds that are rigorously based on
market capitalizations and value and growth styles, rather than the
often subjective opinions of experts who create indexes. They are,
however, aimed at institutions and financial advisers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2133EDT &QL; 
