</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BISHOPS-RACISM-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLINOIS' CATHOLIC BISHOPS URGE PARISHIONERS TO OPPOSE RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Subs 3rd from last graf to change `those' to `church members') 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic bishops of Illinois have issued a pastoral
letter calling on the 3.7 million parishioners in their state to
oppose all forms of racist behavior, including the use of bigoted
language and racist jokes.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, focused on bias against African-Americans, was
posted on the Archdiocese of Chicago's Internet site
(www.archdiocese-chgo.org) on Tuesday, the 32nd anniversary of the
assassination of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., and is being
mailed this week to parishes in the state's six dioceses.
</P>
<P>
   The letter _ asking Catholics to pray for an end to racism,
avoid investing in companies with racist policies and back public
officials committed to racial healing _ is not the first time that
American bishops have spoken out on the issue. In 1979, the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops issued a statement
describing racism as a sin.
</P>
<P>
   The Illinois bishops said that although ``some progress'' had
been made since then, no one should be lulled into believing racism
is no longer an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not the case,'' the bishops wrote in the letter,
titled ``Moving Beyond Racism: Learning to see with the Eyes of
Christ.'' They added, ``Events continue to remind us that racism
thrives.''
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, they cited hate speech on the Internet; the 1998
murder of James Byrd Jr., a black man chained to a pickup truck and
dragged to death in Texas, and the torture of Abner Louima, a
Haitian immigrant, in a New York police station in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this is so blatantly racist,'' the bishops wrote, ``that
it can shock and therefore move us to ask again how to confront
more effectively the sin of racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Anita Baird, executive assistant to Cardinal Francis
George, the archbishop of Chicago, said in a telephone interview
that the letter originated in a 1994 request by church members
working with black Catholic parishioners in the Illinois dioceses
that the bishops as a group speak out against racism and economic
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   She said the process was interrupted by the death of Cardinal
Joseph Bernardin, George's predecessor as archbishop, in November
1996. Later, the bishops decided to release the letter in 2000,
which the church has proclaimed a Jubilee Year, a period that
emphasizes themes of conversion and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping every member of the parishes will have the
opportunity to read it and have the opportunity to discuss it,''
Sister Baird said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0490 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BMG-ARISTA-DAVIS-NYT &LR;      04-06 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BMG-ARISTA-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERTELSMANN RECORD UNIT AND KEY LABEL PRESIDENT ARE AT ODDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOREEN CARVAJAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For virtually the last decade, the music industry titan Clive
Davis has been a regular on the circuit of international gatherings
of music executives organized by BMG Entertainment, the parent
company of his record label, Arista Records.
</P>
<P>
   But in a sign of an intensifying corporate dispute and the
likely departure of Davis, Arista's longtime president, he is not
planning to participate in a two-day meeting next week of BMG
executives from around the world. The meeting was organized to
coincide with the taping of a prime-time concert Monday celebrating
Arista's 25-year anniversary. The concert is to feature
performances by the label's artists, including Aretha Franklin,
Whitney Houston and Carlos Santana.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Davis and BMG have been extraordinarily
awkward since news articles first leaked out late last year that
BMG, a unit of the German media conglomerate Bertelsmann, wanted to
anoint a younger successor to the 66-year-old Davis as his contract
neared its expiration date at the end of June.
</P>
<P>
   A Harvard-trained lawyer, Davis has made a long and storied
career of nurturing and guiding artists from Janis Joplin and Barry
Manilow to Sarah McLachlan. Earlier this year he won a Grammy award
for producing Santana's No. 1 album, ``Supernatural,'' which has
shipped 16 million copies. And the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame
recently paid tribute to Davis' producing skills, inducting him
into the nonperformer category.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' spokesman, Howard J. Rubenstein, said that Davis is still
involved in serious, continuing discussions with BMG. Strauss
Zelnick, the president of BMG, declined to comment on the
discussions about Davis' future with the company.
</P>
<P>
   A record executive with long ties to Arista said, however, that
those discussions were undermined earlier this week because BMG
started preparing to announce the appointment of a successor to
Davis, Antonio Reid of LaFace Records, which is the home of
recording artists like Toni Braxton, TLC and Usher.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move now would have allowed BMG to introduce Reid at the
big gathering of its recording executives next week. They are
convening in Beverly Hills for a series of presentations, dinners
and performances of new artists in the BMG fold. Over the years
BMG's worldwide music meetings _ as they call them _ have been held
in a variety of countries, but this year the event was arranged for
Los Angeles to accommodate dozens of executives who plan to attend
the Arista concert.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executive close to the developments this week,
Davis was outraged that the announcement of his successor could
have been scheduled so close to the anniversary celebration,
prompting BMG to delay the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, Arista, independently of BMG, issued a news release
promoting its recent sales records _ ``an impressive $425 million
in gross revenues in the United States, which makes gross revenues
for the last nine months higher than any full year in the company's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   BMG, which had revenues of $4.7 billion in its last fiscal year,
owns more than 200 record labels in 53 countries, with Arista being
one of its largest and most prominent.
</P>
<P>
   Through his spokesman, Davis declined to comment on whether he
expressed anger over an announcement about Reid's appointment. But
Rubenstein said that Davis had ``made no statements directly or
indirectly about any announcement and it hasn't been on the table
in discussions with BMG.'' He said that the version of events that
had Davis upset about the planned announcement was inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   Another aide said that Davis still could attend the BMG music
gathering if one of his records is completed in time to present to
the executives.
</P>
<P>
   According to the record executive with ties to Arista, Davis is
involved in discussions with all the major record labels about
creating a new music venture, particularly Universal Music Group
and Sony Music. He said Davis is seeking to strike an agreement
that would give him nearly $300 million in financing along with
some artists from the label that he strikes an alliance with.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
