s f BC-CAR-SMART-CUSTOMS-$AD     04-06 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SMART-CUSTOMS-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURTING THE ONE YOU LOVE: CRASH TESTS AND U.S. CUSTOMS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Conn.)   By JOSEPH SIANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   All cars imported into the United States for use by Americans on
public roads must comply with the crash-safety standards of the
Imported Vehicle Safety Compliance Act, the bumper-protection
standards of the Motor Vehicle Information and Cost Savings Act,
and the pollution-control standards under the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   Although most developed countries now have pollution and safety
standards that differ from those in the United States only by
matters of degrees, foreign manufacturers still must certify that
all the cars they export to this country comply with American
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Some foreign cars, however, don't have to comply _ the most
common exemption is for cars more than 25 years old. Racing cars
and experimental cars that use new technology don't have to comply,
either, but can run only on tracks or on short demonstration trips.
A foreign national may also bring a personal car that does not meet
the standards here, for no more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, a car not on the Department of Transportation's
certified list would normally have to pass at least three crash
tests _ one each from the front and rear at 30 miles per hour, and
the more severe side impact at 33 mph. In effect, it would require
a potential importer to destroy at least three cars before one
could be approved. Then the car would have to be fitted with a
speedometer that reads in miles per hour, properly sealed
headlights, correct pollution equipment, damage-resistant bumpers
and other parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we usually tell people is that trying to retrofit a car
to our standards will probably be more expensive than a car is
worth,'' said Janice Mosher, a Customs Service spokeswoman. ``Make
no mistake, it is an ordeal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department is also concerned about people who
attempt to circumvent all import regulations by smuggling cars into
the country. Sneaking a car past a customs inspector might seem
like a job for Penn and Teller, but it's much easier with the
Smart, which will be on sale legally in 11 European countries by
the end of the year: Department officials say they think a number
of Smarts have been shipped into the United States _ most likely
piece by piece.
</P>
<P>
   Pre-assembled or piecemeal, the companies behind the Smart
aren't encouraging gray-market imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any importation of these cars has nothing to do with
Mercedes-Benz or DaimlerChrysler,'' said Jim Resnick, a spokesman
for Mercedes-Benz USA. Designed as a venture between Swatch and
Mercedes Benz, the Smart is now wholly owned by DaimlerChrysler.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of reasons why DaimlerChrysler and other
foreign manufacturers would not want a noncertified product to be
used in this country. The Smart was designed for the tight
maneuvering and limited parking of European cities _ and the lower
bumper heights of European cars; it probably wouldn't fare well in
an encounter with a New York taxicab.
</P>
<P>
   There are no factory-authorized service centers for the Smart,
which could create warranty disputes. And DaimlerChrysler could
face a product-liability lawsuit if anyone was injured or killed in
an accident involving a Smart.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, though, it may be possible to buy and drive a Smart
legally. The Department of Transportation has a list of approved
retrofitters who can _ for a price _ bring almost any foreign car
into compliance with American regulations (see
www.nhtsa.dot.gov/cars/rules/import).
</P>
<P>
   ``Each and every car has its own nuances,'' said David
Castelhano, president of U.S. Conformance, a government-approved
``importer,'' as the retrofitters are called, in Jupiter, Fla. What
makes it prohibitively expensive to retrofit a Smart Car, he said,
are such uniquely American twists as an on-board pollution
diagnostics system. ``Those systems are extremely expensive to
install,'' Castelhano said. To help combat theft, the government
requires that the vehicle-identification number be engraved in 14
places. ``The code of federal regulations is about as thick as your
wrist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard E. Fritz, president of Amerispec, a company in
Ridgefield, Conn., has retrofitted a McLaren F1, an exotic British
sports car with 627 horsepower and a top speed in excess of 200
miles an hour. He recently said that a businessman approached him
with a plan to import and retrofit thousands of Smarts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was over in Europe a few months ago to take a good look at
the car,'' Fritz said. ``If a car is relatively small like this,
the pollutants are not that big a factor This has a high-tech
engine and is very close to meeting the U.S. specifications.''
</P>
<P>
   The car has air bags and has passed European crash tests, he
said, but Europe does not have side-impact tests.
</P>
<P>
   The Smart will need numerous small modifications to pass United
States standards, Fritz said, none of which are too difficult in
themselves. ``The problem is not making it too expensive in the
process,'' he said. ``It sells for $12,500 for a really nice one.
But you can't spend another $10,000 to make it legal and expect to
sell many of them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
