u s BC-BKN-CARTER07-COX-1STL     04-06 0631
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CARTER07-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1ST UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Corrects teams in 7th graf
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Carter vies for title of Next Jordan
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There might never be another Michael Jordan. But just
for today, just for argument's sake, let's say there will be. If
such a player were to exist, wouldn't his career path look like
this?
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't the star of his college team. He wasn't the first
player drafted, or even the fourth. He isn't based in the United
States. He has been allowed to play his way into being the Next
Jordan, as opposed to having it thrust on him by the NBA's
star-making machinery.
</P>
<P>
   He is, in sum, Vince Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Lest we forget, Michael Jordan wasn't regarded as the first
Michael Jordan when he arrived in Chicago. He was the guy drafted
behind Sam Bowie. Jordan had Nike behind him, yes, but Nike then
shouldn't be confused with Nike now. Michael Jordan became Michael
Jordan by playing basketball better than anyone else who ever
lived. Carter, who will face the Hawks tonight in Philips Arena,
might or might not be the best player to come along since, but he
has things going for him that other heirs apparent did not.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill came prepackaged and was too circumspect to fit
inside the shrink wrap. Kobe Bryant landed in L.A., where hype is
bought and sold by the case. They were the Next Jordans only
because someone decided they should be, not because they actually
mirrored the man himself.
</P>
<P>
   Carter isn't a dead ringer, but he's the closest thing yet. He
has what basketball men call ``the explosion,'' which in laymen's
terms is the capacity to make you leap from your seat and shout,
``Whoo-weeeeeee!!!!'' He has the body and the vertical leap, and he
seems to have the timing.
</P>
<P>
   He was rookie of the year in strike-blighted 1999, meaning that
his reputation had a chance to grow by word of mouth. In his
ballyhooed first game on NBC, Carter stacked 51 points on Pheonix.
That was a Jordanian move _ surmounting the insurmountable. He
followed that with a 3-pointer at the buzzer to beat Boston,
followed that with a last-second dunk to beat Houston.
</P>
<P>
   He has done it without playing for a team in L.A. or New York
or, worse yet, Chicago. True, Carter did emerge from North
Carolina, same as Jordan, but he was always the secondary Tar Heel.
Antawn Jamison, who was drafted one spot ahead of Carter and then
swapped for him, was the consensus college player of the year.
Carter landed in Toronto, where overstuffed American egos go to
die, and managed to transcend the daunting border.
</P>
<P>
   For all Next Jordans, the first test is credibility. Can you
really imagine this person working half the wonders Michael
wrought? With Carter, maybe you can. That advances him to the next
developmental phase, which is the backlash. Orlando coach Doc
Rivers rails that refs have taken to rooting for Carter. Indiana's
Jalen Rose played tough against Carter on NBC last Sunday and said
afterward that the Pacers ``didn't want to be part of anybody's
sideshow.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past month Carter has dumped his agent and has had to
shoot more to get his points. His rickety Raptors have lost eight
of nine games and are being booed at home. We forget how long it
took Jordan to make the Bulls a champion _ remember, Chicago lost
that Sunday in Boston Garden when he scored 63 points _ and how
much criticism he ultimately overrode. Ten years from now, maybe
we'll have forgotten Vince Carter's shakedown spring of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe not. The NBA is already littered with Next Jordans who
were unmasked as simply very good players. What's different about
Vince Carter is that the mask hasn't yet slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
