<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9384 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-GENOME-ART-975(2T     04-06 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GENOME-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY SAYS IT HAS FINISHED MAP OF HUMAN GENOME
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Mo.)  (SUBS for complete write-thru; ADDS photo note; CHANGES byline,
ADDS 1,200 words) 
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dr. J. Craig Venter told a congressional committee
Thursday that his company, the Celera Corp., had finished analyzing
all necessary pieces of human DNA and would assemble the whole
human genome within three to six weeks, far earlier than expected.
</P>
<P>
   Completion of the human genome will be a milestone in the
history of science and medicine. The genome's 3 billion letters of
DNA, encoding the 80,000 or so genes needed to make and operate a
human being, are expected to provide the basis for a new generation
of medical treatments that will attack disease at the level of
genes and cells.
</P>
<P>
   Celera, which jumped into a race with a publicly financed
consortium of academic centers 22 months ago, now seems likely to
achieve a clear victory. Though Venter's claims have been
challenged in the past, his successful completion last month of a
pilot project, the fruit fly genome, demonstrated that his approach
works and seems at least for the moment to have silenced critics.
</P>
<P>
   No one challenged his forecast Thursday, which he made in the
presence of the president's science adviser, Dr. Neal Lane, and a
leading genome sequencer in the public consortium, Dr. Robert H.
Waterston of Washington University in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   The public consortium laid much of the technical and
computational basis for decoding the human genome, and made its DNA
sequences freely available to researchers in public databases. It
intends by the end of June to complete a ``rough draft'' of the
human genome, a set of DNA fragments that will contain about 90
percent of all human genes.
</P>
<P>
   Although assembling this material could take until 2003, the
rough draft will be a significant prize for researchers, since they
will be able to search the genome for genes reasonably well even
though it is in pieces. Celera is making use of the consortium's
public data in completing its own genome sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last three weeks, as they have entered the endgame of
the human genome race, Celera and the consortium have engaged in a
series of combative public announcements, interlaced with private
talks about collaboration. There is a strong logic for a joint
effort because the two sides are pursuing different but
complementary strategies to decoding the genome.
</P>
<P>
   First Celera disclosed its fruit fly results, proving the
effectiveness of its whole genome shotgun strategy. Then Dr.
Francis Collins, head of the Human Genome Project of the National
Institutes of Health, announced the June date for the consortium's
rough draft.
</P>
<P>
   Venter responded with Thursday's announcement. He added that he
was switching his 300 sequencing machines to analysis of the mouse
genome, knowledge of which will help researchers interpret what
human genes do.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   The genome decoded by Celera belongs to a man, so it has both X
and Y chromosomes (women have two X chromosomes). The man has not
been named, but his identify will become largely immaterial as
individual variations in DNA, called SNPs or ``snips,'' are
gathered by Celera and others. The public consortium's genome is
drawn from a mosaic of different individuals.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Venter said that after the human genome was assembled, he would
convene a conference of outside experts to annotate it, meaning to
identify where the genes lie on the DNA and what they do.
Annotation is achieved with computer programs that analyze the DNA
sequence, pinpoint the components of genes, and guess their
biological role from comparison with known genes of other species
that are already in the databases.
</P>
<P>
   Only 3 percent of the human genome codes for genes, and the
methods for identifying them are far from perfect. Once the
annotation experts have finished their task, sometime later this
year, Celera will make its human genome sequence freely available
to researchers, Venter said.
</P>
<P>
   Venter has a record of technical and managerial successes in
sequencing genomes, first of bacteria and now of animals, despite
assertions by critics that he would never succeed and whose
skepticism seems a necessary psychological spur to his
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Celera said that at a meeting last Friday with
officials of the National Institutes of Health, Venter proposed
that both sides publish their findings jointly, as was done with
the fruit fly genome sequence, to which the public consortium
contributed.
</P>
<P>
   Draft language of an unpublished Celera-consortium agreement
states that their goals ``are, in fact, complementary'' and that
the two sides are agreed on patent policy for the human genome
(essentially that genes should be patentable only after their roles
have been identified in detail, not on the basis of their sequence
alone).
</P>
<P>
   But Venter's testimony Thursday, before the energy and
environment subcommittee of the House Committee on Science,
included a sharp attack on the quality of the consortium's work and
criticism of the ``rough draft'' plan that Collins announced last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Venter described the consortium's human genome data as ``an
unordered collection of over 500,000 fragments'' that is ``nowhere
close to being done,'' as Collins had been quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago it was reported that Dr. Collins had said Celera
would produce the Mad Magazine version of the human genome,''
Venter said in his written testimony Thursday. ``From its
formation, Celera's goal has been to produce a high-quality human
genome sequence that will stand the test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Celera said officials of the national
institutes who saw the testimony earlier this week cited it as a
``deal breaker'' and cut off negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   But the real reason for the breakdown, these sources say, was
not the testimony but a disagreement over acceptable standards for
completing the human genome sequence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The definition is in question because unlike bacteria, in which
every letter of the genome can be sequenced, animal genomes have
large regions of DNA that cannot be decoded by present methods.
Fortunately, the regions contain few genes. But even the regions
relatively abundant in genes have gaps whose decoding will have to
wait.
</P>
<P>
   Celera argues that in a finished genome the coding regions
should be substantially complete and the order of all the fragments
on the chromosomes should be known. By this definition, Celera's
fruit fly and presumably human sequences would pass as complete,
but the institutes' ``rough draft'' would not. The many fragments
in its draft can be assigned approximate positions on the
chromosomes but cannot yet be placed in correct relative order.
</P>
<P>
   Still, scientists in both camps told the subcommittee Thursday
that they agreed on the standards the Patent and Trademark Office
should adopt for the patenting of genes. They criticized the
approach followed by two other genomic companies, Incyte
Pharmaceuticals and Human Genome Sciences, which they contended
were downloading the public consortium's genome data every night
and filing patent applications for any genes they found.
</P>
<P>
   Genes should not be patentable until a clear description of
their role and utility can be given, the two sides said.
</P>
<P>
   Venter said Celera's business plan was to offer subscriptions to
its genomic data for pharmaceutical companies and universities. He
said the fee for universities would be set very low, at $5,000 to
$15,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   In response to a question, Venter said several universities had
told him they feared their grants would be cut if they subscribed
to Celera's database because it was viewed as competitive to
Genbank, the database run by the institutes.
</P>
<P>
   Lane said he would look into the accusations and ``ensure that
all of our agencies are abiding by their rules and guidelines.''
</P>
<P>
   The hearing took place against the recovery leg of a dramatic
seesaw in Celera's stock price. Three weeks ago, Celera's stock
price was halved, in a $30 billion rout of the biotechnology
industry, after an announcement by President Clinton and Britain's
prime minister, Tony Blair, that had been orchestrated by the
consortium.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was viewed, at least by Venter, as a criticism
of Celera and was misinterpreted by others as meaning the White
House opposed granting patents on the human genome. The White House
said at the time, and Clinton reiterated on Wednesday, that no
change in patent policy was intended.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of PE Celera Genomics rose 23.9 percent in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange Thursday, closing at $140, a rise of $27.
On Wednesday, the stock rose 55 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other biotechnology stocks, including Millennium
Pharmaceuticals, Incyte Pharmaceuticals and Genome Therapeutics,
were also sharply higher Thursday as investors saw Celera's
announcement as a sign that the industry was progressing faster
than previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq biotechnology index surged 4.9 percent, helping the
overall Nasdaq market recover from its selloff earlier in the week
by another 2.36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The business fallout of the Clinton-Blair announcement served to
politicize Thursday's hearings, with Republican members asking
questions critical of the consortium and Democrats seeking to bring
out the public benefit of the consortium's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if publication of the human genome sequence would allow
hostile governments to devise biological weapons or target specific
populations, Venter said that ``the genome will not provide the
ability for targeting any ethnic groups'' and that any dangerous
knowledge was more likely to lie in the genomes of pathogenic
bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, D-Texas, asked in relation to decoding
the human genome sequence: ``Does this mean we can alter the race
of people? Can we design who inhabits this earth?'' Venter said it
would take a century simply to understand what each human gene
does, and that no attempt to alter the human germ line should be
made until then, if ever.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9386 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ELIAN-FAMILY-0407-1ST     04-06 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-FAMILY-0407-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: adds quotes, comments from psychologist beginning with 19th
graf, picks up with xxx The comment seemed sure to stir ...
 &HT;    BREAK DOWN IN TALKS, FATHER'S ARRIVAL LEAVE MIAMI FAMILY LITTLE
BARGAINING ROOM
 &HT;    With CUBA-ELIAN-0407.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ A day that began with hopes for a compromise sparked by
the dramatic arrival of Elian Gonzalez's father in the U.S. ended
with another tense stand-off as the Miami relatives of the
6-year-old Cuban shipwreck survivor refused to meet federal demands
to turn the boy over voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has made the decision that they will . . .
change custody to the father even though the government has never
even spoken to the boy or had the boy evaluated by psychologists,''
said Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, an attorney for the Miami family. ``What
the government has decided is a very dangerous thing for this
boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal immigration officials made no immediate comment after
their five days of talks with the family's lawyers broke down with
no agreement. They have insisted, however, that Elian will be
placed in his father's custody, with or without the help of the
Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   News of the impasse sent a stir through a crowd of about 100
protestors gathered outside the Little Havana home where Elian has
been living with his Miami relatives. Late in the day, a convoy of
dump trucks descended on the neighborhood, blocking some streets,
while about 50 women and children formed a human chain in front of
the house, vowing not to let federal officials take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers said they purposefully excluded men from the
group to avoid any angry confrontations near the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will sit on the ground and they will have to drag me out,''
vowed Doris Salazar, 51, who joined the protest earlier in the day.
``People in this country don't understand that he's not going back
to his father. He's going back to (Cuban President) Fidel Castro.''
</P>
<P>
   But any attempt to take Elian from the home likely won't come
immediately. With federal officials reluctant to confront the
protestors, the stage seemed set for further legal wrangling.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials have said that without the family's
cooperation, they would probably send a letter very soon informing
the family that they plan to transfer Elian to his father. A second
letter would then tell the family when and where they should
deliver the boy.
</P>
<P>
   The family's lawyers might respond by asking the 11th Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta to block the action until their lawsuit
over the case is resolved. The court is scheduled to hear arguments
in the case May 11.
</P>
<P>
   But late in the day, one of the Miami family's attorneys held
out hopes for a different scenario _ letting the family meet
without the boy, or lawyers _ to try to resolve their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for the lawyers and the government to walk away and
let the family sit down and discuss what is in Elian's best
interests,'' said Linda Osberg-Braun, an attorney for the Miami
family. ``We're hoping that (Elian's father) Juan Miguel will agree
to do this at any location.''
</P>
<P>
   But the first order of business at such a meeting would be to
heal the wounds from the increasingly heated rhetoric the two sides
of the family have exchanged in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, when Castro announced that Juan Miguel Gonzalez might
soon come to the United States, lawyers for the family aired
accusations that he had abused Elian in telephone conversations by
telling him his mother was still alive and waiting for him in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's mother drowned with 10 other people after the boat they
were using to flee Cuba sank. The boy was one of only a few
survivors, and was rescued Thanksgiving Day off the For Lauderdale
coast.
</P>
<P>
   On his arrival in Washington early Thursday, Elian's father also
blasted the Miami relatives, saying they have paraded his son
before the media and subjected him to a long television interview
without the father's permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an agonizing experience to see my son submitted to
cruel psychological pressures aimed at influencing his personality
already weakened by the terrible trauma,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez remained in the Washington, D.C. area Thursday, staying
at the home of a top Cuban diplomat. He planned to meet Friday with
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno and Doris Meissner, Commissioner
of the Immigration and Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami talks broke down when immigration officials refused to
budge on the family's demands, insisting that the only option is to
turn the boy over. The family's main demands were that Elian be
evaluated by a team of psychologists who would decide what is best
for him, and that the boy's father promise he would not take Elian
back to Cuba before the court appeal is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has said he would remain in this country until the
appeal is heard, but federal officials say there is no legal
obligation that he do so.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the family introduced a psychologist to the media
gathered outside their home, saying he had examined Elian and found
the boy fears being reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is not to yank him away from the
stability and security'' he now has with the Miami family, said
Mitch Spiro, a Broward County psychologist who said he is donating
his time to the family.
</P>
<P>
   To do so might cause ``irreversible emotional damage,'' Spiro
said.
</P>
<P>
   The comments echoed one of the family's main concerns, that
Elian has found a replacement for his mother in his cousin,
Marisleysis Gonzalez, who has cared for the boy since he was
rescued. To take him from her would further traumatize Elian, they
believe.
</P>
<P>
   The family also seemed outraged that federal officials would not
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would not even promise not to come to try to take the boy
in the middle of the night,'' Garcia-Pedrosa said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The comment seemed sure to stir an even more determined vigil
among Miami's exiles.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts said the words were a sign of the family's
increasing desperation _ and narrowing options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only leverage the family has is political pressure,''
Tammy Fox-Isicoff, a Miami immigration attorney, told reporters.
``All the chips are in INS's hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
