<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-GASOLINE-OUTLOOK-1STL     04-06 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GASOLINE-OUTLOOK-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. REDUCES FORECAST FOR GASOLINE PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Rewrites completely; note new byline and dateline.)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Energy Department said Thursday that gasoline would
cost a good deal less this summer than what had been forecast just
a month ago, though the typical household was still expected to
spend $170 more to fuel up the family car than last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Prices should peak this month at $1.52 a gallon for regular
unleaded gasoline, roughly what it averaged in March, before
falling to $1.39 by September. The average for the summer should be
$1.46, according to the Energy Information Administration, the
statistical agency for the department.
</P>
<P>
   That may offer little relief to drivers, who can still expect to
pay about 25 percent more this summer than last year. But the
outlook is far better than last month's, when forecasters predicted
average prices of $1.56 for the summer, with peak months reaching
$1.80.
</P>
<P>
   The new forecast, though, carries an important caveat; the
agency said that to meet the projection, the nation's refineries
would have to operate at close to capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Any major disruptions, which might include hurricanes,
explosions and extended maintenance shutdowns, could cause prices
to spike above the new predictions. The agency noted that refinery
problems early last year in California contributed to a spring jump
in gasoline prices there at a time when oil prices were far lower
than they are now.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also predicted that the price of imported crude oil
delivered to domestic refiners, which averaged $26.75 a barrel in
February and March, would drop to $23.50 by the end of this year,
and to $21.50 by the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The lowered forecast may take some steam out of efforts in
Congress to suspend 4.3 cents of the 18.4 cents-a-gallon federal
gasoline tax. That proposal, by Trent Lott, the Senate majority
leader, has not come to a vote. But in a nonbinding resolution
Thursday, senators signaled in a 66-34 vote that they lean against
lowering the tax.
</P>
<P>
   The government's sharply revised forecast was attributable to
the decision last week by OPEC member nations to raise their oil
output, said Dave Costello, an economist at the agency, and to the
market's surprisingly strong reaction to the increase.
</P>
<P>
   The cartel's production increase ``wasn't that much different
from what we had kind of been assuming,'' Costello said. But crude
prices fell by perhaps $1 a barrel more than what had been
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   The new forecast ``doesn't mean that all concerns are out the
window or anything like that,'' he said. ``It means the situation
has brightened up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline supplies have been helped, Costello added, because with
falling oil prices, refiners have enjoyed a wider spread between
what they pay for oil and the price they can sell gasoline, in
contrast to thin margins earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Also, he said, wholesale gasoline prices have dropped lately, in
part because of recent upward revisions in estimates of the
nation's gasoline inventories.
</P>
<P>
   The revised estimates suggest that stocks of gasoline, while
still quite low, have not fallen to the severe levels previously
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin J. Lindemer, a senior director at Cambridge Energy
Research Associates in Cambridge, Mass., said that the government's
assumption that domestic refineries can run at 96.8 percent of
capacity this summer is attainable, barring major disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   He also attributed part of the recent decline in prices, and the
hope for further declines, to psychological factors. ``We've taken
the heat out of the market,'' Lindemer said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new forecast still predicts the highest summer
gasoline prices ever, the agency noted that the situation is not as
severe when inflation-adjusted numbers are used. The average 1981
summer price of $1.35 per gallon, for example, translates to $2.52
today.
</P>
<P>
   That is not much solace, though, to motorists paying extra to
fuel their car. Lauren Merritt, a senior at Booker T. Washington
High School for the Performing and Visual Arts in Dallas, said she
spends at least $30 a week on gasoline commuting from Kaufman
County, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If they materialize, Merritt said, lower prices will help a bit.
But prices will remain high, crimping her efforts to save for
college. ``I can't spend as much as I want to on other things
because I have to budget for gas,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
