u e BC-DANCING-RADIOCITY-REV     04-06 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DANCING-RADIOCITY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`BURN THE FLOOR': INTERNATIONAL CROP OF PELVIS-SWIVELING BALLROOM
DANCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In case you haven't noticed, ballroom dancing is
back, and ``Burn the Floor,'' which opened a two-night stint at
Radio City Music Hall on Wednesday, is the latest entry to
capitalize on the current craze.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers are downright terrific, an international crop
recruited from amateur and professional championship dance
competitions. Look past the show's brassy facade, with its
rock-show production values and attitude (mock ecstasy is the usual
facial expression), and there is some complex footwork in what is
essentially a suite of deliberately souped-up social dances. The
pelvis-swiveling finale is led by Australians, backed up by a
conglomerate of Slavs and Scandinavians, and should give Ricky
Martin a run for his Yankee dollar.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, sturdy little companies like American Ballroom
Theater, seen at the Brooklyn Academy of Music and elsewhere in the
1980s, look somewhat tame. Yet that troupe and more recent ventures
did pioneering work in theatricalizing ballroom dances onstage.
``Burn the Floor'' is bigger and louder but not better: It fails to
make a virtue of the disco-drive energy that is its signature.
</P>
<P>
   When everything is performed at the same punchy level, subtlety
goes out the exit door, and sameness sets in. Even the six Gingers
in frumpy blond wigs, part of the Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers
number, have the rhythmic bounce of the frug rather than a class
act.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony van Laast, once seen in the United States as a modern
dancer in London Contemporary Dance Theater, is now in show
business as a successful choreographer. As director and
choreographer of ``Burn the Floor'' he breaks free of ballroom
conventions and plunges the dancers into ensemble patterns that
have nothing to do with social-dance partnering.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an admirable attempt to extend the idioms of current
ballroom dancing into a spectator sport; if only it didn't
sometimes look like a bad television special. More wit, less woe
was needed in a Latin number: bikers in leather jackets engaged in
homemade flamenco amid cape-swirling as Jason Gilkison and Bojan
Fesel dueled over Peta Roby, wearing cute little bull's horns.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cast in ``Urban Heat'' was decked out in chains,
slinking sexily to techno rock with a Latin beat or staying close
to the floor, all the better to climb out of an implied sewer. The
first two numbers, however, kept closer to set forms and were more
successful. ``Club Scene'' was high-voltage disco-derived dance.
``Fantasy Waltz,'' had the elegant Damon Sugden and Rebecca Walker
surrounded by masked couples with a theme of neo-romantic mystery
mercifully kept at a minimum. Best of all was the extended
jitterbug number in which the dancers could let loose. The title
said it all: ``Jump Jive and Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonita Bryg's sassy costumes, sometimes scanty, had a good
tongue-in-cheek Madonna touch, and touch was within reach as the
dancers occasionally gyrated in the aisles.
</P>
<P>
   Van Laast's lengthy list of associates include Gilkison
(artistic director and choreographer), Lindsey Hiller-Tate
(ballroom consultant and associate choreographer) and Nichola
Traherne (assistant director and assistant choreographer).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
