<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 21:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9393 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-AUCTION-CORRUPTION-AR     04-06 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUCTION-CORRUPTION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CHAIRMEN OF SOTHEBY'S AND CHRISTIE'S LINKED TO PRICE-FIXING 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT38 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 This article was reported by DOUGLAS FRANTZ, RALPH BLUMENTHAL and
CAROL VOGEL and was written by Frantz.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prosecutors in the federal antitrust investigation of
Sotheby's and Christie's have evidence that a scheme to limit
competition by fixing commissions charged to buyers and sellers was
set in motion not by subordinates, but by the chairmen of the
world's auction giants at the time, according to people involved in
the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders, A. Alfred Taubman of Sotheby's and Sir Anthony
Tennant of Christie's, discussed the arrangement in person and then
instructed their chief executives to meet to carry out the scheme,
according to the accounts from the people involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Sotheby's and Taubman have acknowledged privately
that Taubman met with Tennant in the early to mid-1990s, but would
not specify more precisely when. But the lawyers contended that the
conversations were innocent and had nothing to do with a
conspiracy. Christie's lawyers and Tennant declined to comment, but
people involved in the case say he also maintains that the
conversations were innocuous.
</P>
<P>
   The information _ including memorandums describing aspects of
the arrangement _ was turned over to prosecutors several months ago
by lawyers for Christie's, who had obtained the material from
Christopher M. Davidge days after he resigned as Christie's chief
executive, according to people involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   People involved in the case said that Diana D. Brooks, the
former chief executive of Sotheby's, has let prosecutors know that
with immunity she could support some of Davidge's assertions about
the scheme's origins and could say she met with him on instructions
from Taubman.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two houses _ Sotheby's, based in New York, and
Christie's, with headquarters in London _ control about 95 percent
of a $4 billion worldwide auction market. The allegation that a
conspiracy was devised at the very top of the venerable auction
houses raises the stakes in the investigation, which has already
roiled the world of art collectors. Until now attention had focused
on Davidge, who abruptly resigned from Christie's on Dec. 24, and
Brooks, who stepped down at Sotheby's on Feb. 21, the same day
Taubman resigned as Sotheby's chairman. He remains the majority
shareholder but gave up his seat on the board.
</P>
<P>
   Davidge acknowledged to prosecutors that he and Brooks met
secretly many times over three years in New York and London to work
out the details of the collusion and exchange information,
according to the people involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Davidge and Christie's have been granted conditional amnesty
from prosecution by the government for turning over evidence first.
Sotheby's and Brooks are engaged in a high-stakes battle to win
leniency from prosecutors, who are insisting that Brooks and
Taubman each plead guilty to a felony, which could leave them open
to prison terms and big fines, according to people involved in the
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been charged with wrongdoing, and prosecutors are
still evaluating the evidence provided by Davidge, who would have
something to gain by implicating higher ups, as would Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant has denied any involvement in the scheme and
characterized conversations he had with Taubman as innocent in
interviews with Christie's lawyers, according to one person
involved in the talks. A woman who answered the telephone Thursday
in his London office said he would have no comment on the
allegations, which were recounted to her.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman yesterday denied any wrongdoing and referred calls to
his lawyer, Scott W. Muller. `` Taubman has always acted openly and
aboveboard in everything he did related to Sotheby's,'' Muller
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' lawyer, Stephen E. Kaufman, said he would have no
comment on the investigation. William Joseph Linklater, who
represents Davidge, also declined to comment, as did lawyers for
Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Steven A. Reiss, a lawyer for Sotheby's, also would not comment.
``We haven't commented in three years, and we're not going to start
now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation into possible collusion within the secretive
auction world began three years ago, but it was thought to be
dormant until a few months ago. That is when the Justice
Department's antitrust office in New York received a cache of
memorandums and notes of meetings written by Davidge to Tennant as
well as a letter from Tennant to Davidge, according to those
involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Along with providing the documents, Christie's agreed to
cooperate with the federal investigation. In exchange for its help,
the company was granted a form of leniency called conditional
amnesty, with the provision that its cooperation be complete and
truthful. Christie's general counsel, Jo Backer Laird, disclosed
the cooperation agreement Jan. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Under antitrust law, the first participant in a cartel to agree
to cooperate with the government can receive leniency, including
reduced fines and the likelihood that no criminal charges will be
filed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the disclosure that Christie's was cooperating, there have
been numerous civil suits against both houses from art buyers and
sellers and from Sotheby's shareholders. Christie's is privately
held.
</P>
<P>
   Published accounts have said that prosecutors were investigating
whether the houses cooperated in establishing identical commission
charges for buyers in 1992 and sellers in 1995. The houses
exchanged confidential lists of top-drawer customers who were not
to be charged a commission. There also have been accounts that
Davidge and Brooks met secretly several times to work out details
of the collusion.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews in recent days with people involved in the
investigation have provided new details of the case being built by
prosecutors, and they help to piece together a clearer picture of
the events leading up to the decision by Christie's to cooperate.
None of those interviewed would be identified because the
investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Davidge, 54, who started at Christie's as a summer employee at
the age of 16, has told prosecutors that he got involved in the
conspiracy on orders from his boss, Tennant, and that it began
shortly after Tennant met with Sotheby's Taubman, according to
those involved in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   It could not be learned what was said by Taubman and Tennant at
the meeting, and lawyers have argued that any conversations between
the men had nothing to do with a conspiracy. It is also unclear
when the two first met or how often they talked. Tennant did not
join Christie's as chairman until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tennant, a former chairman at Guinness PLC, was brought into
Christie's at a time when there were fears the auction house would
become the target of a hostile takeover. He remained chairman until
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Taubman, 75, earned a fortune developing shopping malls in the
United States. He bought a majority stake in Sotheby's in 1983 and
has been credited with revamping the auction house by transforming
it into a retail enterprise with vastly expanded services. Though
he resigned as chairman in February at the urging of fellow board
members after word of the federal investigation broke, Taubman
remains the controlling shareholder.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, 49, has a background in banking and worked closely with
Taubman after he promoted her to president of Sotheby's America in
1987 and then to worldwide chief executive in 1994. Until the
scandal broke earlier this year, she was widely regarded as the
most powerful woman in the art world.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to win leniency, Brooks has contended that she
began meeting with Davidge on instructions from Taubman, according
to those involved in the inquiry. Brooks said that she reported
orally to Taubman on the the meetings and that to her knowledge no
one else at the company was aware of the collusion, according to
those involved in the inquiry. It is unknown whether anyone else at
Christie's was aware of the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Sotheby's have been trying to negotiate a settlement
with the Justice Department for several weeks. People familiar with
those talks said the government's antitrust lawyers in New York
have insisted that Taubman and Brooks plead guilty to at least one
felony each and that the auction house pay a huge fine.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the prosecutors want Sotheby's to admit that the
collusion began with a 1992 decision by both auction houses to set
identical commission structures for buyers, and continued with the
1995 agreement on sellers' commissions, according to those involved
in the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, at a time when the art market was in the doldrums,
Sotheby's announced an increase in the commission paid by buyers at
auction. Seven weeks later Christie's followed with an identical
commission structure. In 1995 Christie's announced it was changing
the fee charged to sellers, and Sotheby's followed suit within
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Taubman and Brooks were described as objecting
strenuously to any criminal charges, and the auction house is
resisting admitting that the anti-competitive action stretched back
to 1992. An admission of collusion in 1992 could significantly
expand the company's exposure to civil damage awards because there
are many more buyers than sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Sotheby's have argued that the conspiracy could not
have stretched back to 1992 because Tennant did not join Christie's
until 1993, according to a lawyer familiar with the talks. But
prosecutors still suspect that the actions may have been linked.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest evidence in the hands of prosecutors, according to
those familiar with the investigation, is the batch of documents
provided by Davidge. The documents are said to contain instructions
to him from Tennant regarding the collusion and detailed written
accounts by Davidge back to Tennant after his meetings with Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   According to those familiar with the investigation, Brooks
learned in January that Christie's lawyers had turned over
incriminating records to the Justice Department. Lawyers for Brooks
approached prosecutors with an offer to cooperate in exchange for
leniency.
</P>
<P>
   However, they were told by prosecutors that Christie's had
already reached an agreement, according to people involved in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ``She missed out by a week,'' said one of those involved in the
case. ``They beat her to the door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
