<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9400 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     04-06 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL TRAINER BLASTS BAFFERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Finally, one of the targets of leading
American thoroughbred trainer Bob Baffert's shotgun wit fired back
in public.
</P>
<P>
   It happened Thursday morning at the post-position draw ceremony
for Saturday's $1 million Santa Anita Derby. Baffert, trainer of
Captain Steve, sat at one end of the dais. Jenine Sahadi, trainer
of The Deputy, and Chris McCarron, that colt's jockey, sat at the
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the way,'' Baffert said to McCarron, with no apparent
provocation, as reporters and horsemen listened, ``who's training
The Deputy, you or Jenine?''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi glared back at Baffert as McCarron answered a question
from ceremony emcee Kurt Hoover. Then, when Hoover asked Sahadi
what pre-race instructions she would give to McCarron, she looked
in Baffert's general direction and said: ``I won't give him
instructions. Thank God my horse has class, because there's a lot
of people who don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi dropped the microphone on the table with a thud, got up
and exited stage right.
</P>
<P>
   ``That hurt,'' Baffert said softly.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at her barn, Sahadi blasted Baffert, whose antics have
helped to make him horse racing's most distinctive personality as
he recorded Kentucky Derby victories with Silver Charm (1997) and
Real Quiet (1998) and three consecutive Eclipse Awards as the
nation's outstanding trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not interested in sitting up there and getting degraded by
the guy,'' Sahadi said. ``He does that s--- all the time. He did it
with Sonny Hine. He's done it with everybody he's ever come in
contact with. I don't know why. I don't understand his mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, he never knew (Hall of Fame trainer) Charlie
Whittingham. If he did, he'd have gone to his barn and learned how
to win with a little bit of class. . . . All I know is that as
successful as he's been, he will never be in the league with some
of these other guys. You just don't behave like that. What is he, 6
years old, for Christ's sake?''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had to apologize a few years ago after referring to
Hine, trainer of 1998 Horse of the Year Skip Away, as ``Elmer
Fudd'' because of the way he looked and talked. Baffert hadn't
realized that Hine's face was partially paralyzed by Bell's Palsy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I meant to say he looks like Mr. Magoo,'' Baffert said at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert often hogs the spotlight at press conferences and public
events, talking over others and accepting cell-phone calls at the
dais. Usually, everybody else sits there and puts up with it. This
time, Sahadi didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert had hit a sore spot with Sahadi, the 37-year-old Los
Angeles native who took out her trainer's license in 1993, set a
national record for earnings by a woman trainer in 1995 and is the
only woman to saddle Breeders' Cup winners. Sahadi has faced
insinuations that she owes her success to her family, which is
prominent in California racing, to former boyfriend Julio Canani, a
Breeders' Cup-winning trainer, and to her husband, Ben Cecil, also
a trainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He picked a subject that is very sensitive to me, that I am so
sick of hearing about, I'm nauseous about it,'' Sahadi said. ``I
think I've tried to be OK with it for the last seven years, but it
gets to be a bore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a perfectly great day and now it's completely ruined.
Because of one guy. Because he took the biggest shot he could.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she thought Baffert has it in for her, Sahadi said:
``He has it in for everybody. He has the biggest ego of anybody
I've ever met.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi charged that reporters have ignored fellow horsemen's
complaints about Baffert's behavior: ``People have (criticized
him), but nobody's interested in hearing about it because he's got
all the best horses. He's ruling the roost right now. You don't
think half the backside doesn't think it, for Christ's sake?''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said he was ``joking'' and complained, ``People have no
sense of humor around this place.'' He later told Brad Free of the
Daily Racing Form that Sahadi hates him ``because of Kramer''
(Baffert's nickname for his friend Canani).
</P>
<P>
   He isn't giving himself enough credit. Sahadi hates Baffert
because of Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   __ The draw: If any of the six 3-year-olds entered in the 1-mile
Santa Anita Derby was helped or hurt by the post-position draw, it
was the lone filly Surfside, who will start from the extreme
inside. She and jockey Pat Day will have to use her early speed to
establish position.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, Surfside is the third consecutive filly to draw post 1
for the Santa Anita Derby. Sharp Cat led most of the race and
finished sixth behind Free House in 1997. Honest Lady stalked the
pace and finished seventh behind General Challenge in 1999. Neither
went on to the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Although Surfside has won four races in a row, she will go back
on Lasix and will wear blinkers for the first time to help her
``focus,'' trainer D. Wayne Lukas said.
</P>
<P>
   __ The weekend: General Challenge, last year's Santa Anita Derby
winner, is assigned 123 pounds, 11 more than any of his opponents
in Sunday's San Bernardino Handicap.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the horses who chased General Challenge in the March 4
Santa Anita Handicap, Budroyale (second) and Cat Thief (sixth),
meet Sunday in Arkansas in the Oaklawn Handicap.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
