</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  
 SPORTS COLUMN: McENROE EXPECTS NO SURPRISES AGAINST CZECH By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There were no heads of state surrounded by
armed guards here Thursday at the Davis Cup draw, only the
presidents of various tennis federations. Following the
African-inspired first-round intrigue in Zimbabwe two months ago,
it's back to more basic cup business, a conventional competition
that is likely to be as inspiring as a Lakers home date against the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Back in the 1980s, John McEnroe watched his share of blowouts
from a courtside seat in the Great Western Forum. He'll have the
same view Friday of Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi, tennis' Magic
and Kareem, when they face the Czech Republic's Jiri Novak and
Slava Dosedel in the opening singles of the cup quarterfinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weird things happen in Davis Cup,'' McEnroe said. ``That said,
I expect to win every match. If I start seeing naked guys dancing,
I'll start worrying.''
</P>
<P>
   The friendly fans in Zimbabwe, where Chris Woodruff saved
McEnroe's captain's debut in the decisive singles match in early
February, were far more clothed than the Laker Girls, who have
gyrated downtown to the new Staples Center. McEnroe's point,
embellished as usual, was that he's expecting the weekend to be
devoid of surprises, as scripted as a sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad after Zimbabwe, the rousing start to McEnroe's
mission to raise the visibility of Davis Cup here in the States.
Once Sampras returned to co-star with Agassi, there was one chance
for McEnroe to make this weekend more than a basic show of American
might. He could have put himself into Saturday's doubles match,
done what we all know he's dying to do.
</P>
<P>
   By the next round, a semifinal at either Russia or Spain, it
would be too risky, too late. Here, the moon and the stars and the
surface were perfectly aligned _ Sampras and Agassi on board, at
home, on the fast carpet, against a country that will be fortunate
to win one match.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe could have made Friday a happening, the promotional meat
sandwiched between what are likely to be short-work singles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how good that would be for team morale,'' said
McEnroe, fighting off his natural impulses with his newly developed
establishment bearings.
</P>
<P>
   Having gone with Alex O'Brien and Jared Palmer, the world's No.
1 doubles team, McEnroe said the scenario he had envisioned would
be for him to play with Sampras or Agassi. ``But that would mean
one of them would have to play all three days,'' he said. ``And to
have them believe deep in their hearts that I'm the best player to
play with.''
</P>
<P>
   At 41, he can't possibly be, though in his prime McEnroe was
considered the best doubles player ever, he remains active and in
shape and, as he said, ``You only have half the court to cover.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger and more relevant issue is that Davis Cup is not
about computer points and rankings, and McEnroe became captain
primarily to stir up interest in an event that had practically
fallen off the American sports landscape. ``It's a difficult sell
here in America,'' Agassi admitted.
</P>
<P>
   As a celebrity who is transcendent of his low-rated sport,
McEnroe has been a one-man marketing tour, turning up in the seats
opposite, among others, Jay Leno and Katie Couric. There is always
a window of opportunity for these gabfests, though. Sooner or
later, the angle and material wear thin.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe also knows better than anyone that Agassi and Sampras
aren't going to play Davis Cup forever, maybe not even beyond this
year.
</P>
<P>
   While Sampras nursed a muscle pull sustained at the Australian
Open, Agassi carried the United States in Zimbabwe, exhausting and
dehydrating himself in the high elevation of Harare. By the end, he
was vomiting into a bucket, and staggering off to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-six hours later, I landed back home and probably felt
worse,'' he said. ``I didn't feel better until two weeks later,
when I was able to hit the ball and move around. It was too long to
go without tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Back on tour, Agassi paid for his patriotism. He hasn't won a
tournament since Australia and even got blitzed a couple of times
in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has recovered, and his recently turned ankle feels
better, too. With Sampras making this trip all the way from his
home in the far Los Angeles suburbs, the story line here is that
McEnroe has the first- and second-ranked players in the world,
along with the No. 1 doubles team. The Czech coach, Jan Kukal,
called the Americans ``the best team ever because Agassi and
Sampras are not only No. 1 and No. 2 but I think they are the best
players that ever played.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe returned the compliment, calling the Czech players
dangerous because they often seem ``lazy, appearing not to give 100
percent.'' Not that we root for McEnroe tantrums, but he may not
even have to get out of his seat this weekend, except to applaud,
the way he used to for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, someone said, Sampras would lose his cool and do some
screaming at the umpire and linesmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I'm real worried about that happening,'' McEnroe said.
</P>
<P>
   He's not worried about anything, and he's not playing either.
Too bad. Kobe and Shaq could have sat courtside for him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
