<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9412 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS07-COX     04-06 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unfamiliarity breeds early lead for Paulson
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If the goal was to open the leaderboard to more
players and stir up Augusta National with more rough and pinched
fairways, then it's mission accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   After one windblown, wild round at the 64th Masters, where you
can't tell the old sightlines without a guide dog, here's where
things stand:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dennis Paulson, 37, a former long-driving champion who had
never seen the course in its former set-up and has yet to win a PGA
Tour event, leads by a stroke over Tom Lehman with a 4-under-par
68.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tiger Woods, after his highest round of the year (75) and his
first triple-bogey since November, has temporarily stumbled as the
odds-on favorite. Woods, 24, who is seven shots back, trails Jack
Nicklaus, 60, by one stroke and is a shot ahead of 64-year-old Gary
Player and three better than 70-year-old Arnold Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sergio Garcia, 20, who never broke par in four rounds last
year as an amateur, is two shots back after a 70.
</P>
<P>
   _ Steve Stricker, who has tied for 38th and missed two cuts at
the Masters, also opened with a 70.
</P>
<P>
   But when the winds gust near 20 mph, as they did Thursday,
things turn funky at Augusta National. Fortunately, for the field,
the greens were abnormally soft and not quite as swift. Even so, 12
rounds in the 80s _ including such notables as Greg Norman, John
Daly and Corey Pavin _ and a stroke average of 75.579 were
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, whose last victory was the 1998 Nike Huntsville Open,
eagled the third hole and double-bogeyed 11, then righted himself
toward the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe lack of knowledge is better, not knowing how hard this
course can be when the wind is really blowing,'' Paulson said.
``There's no question it was moving and bouncing around, and the
way the trees are set up there, it really messes with your head.''
</P>
<P>
   But compared to the winds that blew two years ago for two days,
Stewart Cink (75) called this a mere ``zephyr.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was tricky,'' Cink said, ``but the course was about
as easy as I've ever seen it. The greens were softer than I'd seen
them in years and not as fast as they usually are.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman seemed ready to spend the night with the first-day lead,
but double-bogeyed the 18th, starting the disaster with a drive
into the trees. He hit a large oak trying to find an opening,
eventually found the green and three-putted from 45 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good about the round,'' said Lehman, who finished
second to Jose Maria Olazabal in 1994 after holding the 54-hole
lead. ``It was a tremendous score under the conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods never made any noise on the leaderboard. He had bogeys at
4 and 5, followed by birdies at 6 and 8, then went downhill. He
bogeyed the 10th, then took 6 on the par-3 12. His 8-iron from 135
yards got caught in the wind and spun back into the water. He
pitched onto the green 12 feet past the hole, ran it 3 feet past
and missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably one of the more difficult days I've seen
here,'' Woods said. ``The wind is swirling and blowing and gusting.
... It was hard out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jones, the 1996 U.S. Open champion, got to 5-under,
bogeyed the 11th, then underclubbed at the 12th (9-iron) and rinsed
a ball en route to a double-bogey. Jones (71) was nearly flawless
earlier with five birdies and a bogey on the front nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``My round was a Dr. Jekyll and Mr. Hyde,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Also at 71 are Rocco Mediate, who double-bogeyed the 13th with a
hooked tee shot lost in the azaleas; BellSouth Classic champion
Phil Mickelson, Denmark's Thomas Bjorn and two-time champion
Bernhard Langer of Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hitting a lot of the same shots I hit last week,''
Mickelson said. ``I drove it well last week and I drove it well
today.'' Defending champion Olazabal opened with a 72 and is tied
for 10th in a group that includes 1997 British Open champion Justin
Leonard, three-time champion Nick Faldo of England and
Gainesville's Tommy Aaron, the 1973 champion. David Duval is tied
for 22nd with a 73, a stroke better than Nick Price and two better
than Sea Island's Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
