<SLUG> BC-GENERAL-SEX-CHARGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERSONAL FILE OF GENERAL BORE NO HINT OF HARASSMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: NYT Photo 5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the Army's top leaders appointed him deputy
inspector general, the personnel file of the general accused of
sexual harassment by the service's highest-ranking woman included
no indication that she had ever complained about his behavior,
officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Army has frozen the appointment of the accused officer, Maj.
Gen. Larry Smith, while its inspector general investigates the
charge, by Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy, that he made an unwanted
sexual advance in her Pentagon office in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy filed her formal complaint only after the Army announced
Smith's appointment last August. But officials familiar with the
investigation said she had complained informally to superiors at
the time the incident is said to have occurred, and believed then
that Smith had been reprimanded.
</P>
<P>
   Had an official record of some kind of discipline been placed in
Smith's file, the officials said, the secretary of the Army, Louis
Caldera, and the chief of staff, Gen. Eric Shinseki, would not have
approved the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all the elements apparent in his record, there was no
hint of this,'' a senior Pentagon official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both Caldera and Shinseki have declined to comment on either the
investigation of Smith or his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure in published reports Thursday that Smith was the
officer against whom Kennedy had filed a complaint and that he had
been appointed to the inspector general's office, which is
responsible for investigating wrongdoing by senior officers, has
created a new embarrassment for the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Now the service will soon be faced with a choice of dismissing
her complaint as unfounded or again punishing a senior officer. The
Army's inspector general is said to be winding down the
investigation, overseen by the Pentagon's inspector general, and
could issue a recommendation to the Army's vice chief of staff,
Gen. John Keane, within the next week or so.
</P>
<P>
   A senior Army official said Thursday that even if the charge was
deemed to be unfounded, it was unlikely that the service would go
ahead with Smith's appointment as deputy inspector general, because
of the highly charged nature of the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not be the right thing to do,'' the official said.
``The prudent thing to do would be to find another candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's appointment has prompted questions on Capitol Hill about
whether the Army tolerates sexual harassment and how it handles
misconduct complaints, especially against senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., called for a congressional
investigation of the Army's handling of this and other harassment
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Olympia J. Snowe, a R-Maine, who serves on the Senate Armed
Services Committee, said it was important for the Army to
demonstrate its commitment to what Pentagon officials maintain is
``zero tolerance'' of harassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their response, how they handle it,'' Snowe said of Kennedy's
complaint, ``clearly will give us an assessment of whether or not
they're responding to the zero tolerance policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kennedy, who has filed for retirement in August, also came
under attack, for having filed a formal complaint only last year,
after Smith's appointment, rather than at the time the incident is
alleged to have occurred, some three years earlier. Rep. Steve
Buyer, R-Ind., questioned her motives in filing a complaint so
late.
</P>
<P>
   ``They think they've resolved this, then she's retiring, he's
promoted, and she's not satisfied anymore,'' said Buyer, chairman
of the House Armed Services subcommittee on military personnel.
``It appears to make her look vindictive. It doesn't put her in the
best light. There's something that just doesn't seem right about
her allegation.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy's actions immediately after the 1996 encounter she
alleges have become a focus of the inspector general's
investigation, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   According to those officials, Kennedy chose not to file a formal
complaint against Smith then but instead raised the matter with
superiors, who evidently assured her that it would be dealt with.
The identity of those superiors is not publicly known, however, and
one top Army official said Thursday that it was unclear how senior
were the officers to whom she brought her concerns. The officers
who were then Army chief of staff and vice chief of staff have both
said she did not bring the issue to their attention.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kennedy and Smith have declined to discuss the accusation.
So have Army officials, for attribution.
</P>
<P>
   Commanders have considerable discretion in how they deal with
those accused of wrongdoing. In instances not involving
courts-martial, punishment can range from an oral admonishment to a
letter of reprimand that is not put in the accused's personnel file
to a letter that becomes a matter of record.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the officials said, there is no evidence that a
record was made of Kennedy's informal complaint.
</P>
<P>
   People who know Kennedy said she had never intended for even her
formal accusation to touch off a public maelstrom, but had simply
wanted to oppose Smith's appointment to so sensitive a position.
</P>
<P>
   Evelyn Foote, a retired Army brigadier general who served with
Kennedy on a committee that in 1997 investigated sexual harassment
in the military, said, ``I sincerely believe General Kennedy wanted
to handle this in the general officers' channels and not make it a
great harangue, or an embarrassment for the Army.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
