</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTICAL AUGUSTA WINDS WREAK HAVOC WITH FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ The wind was unpredictable, the conditions were
unnerving and the leader was unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   The opening round of the 2000 Masters made everyone pay a price,
with no one in the 95-player field enjoying a bogey-free day. Only
9 of the 95 players finished under par. Tiger Woods had his worst
round of the year, a three-over-par 75 that included his first
triple-bogey since November. Craig Stadler had a quadruple-bogey 9
at No. 15, dumping two balls into the water that knocked him off
the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   Even Dennis Paulson, who shot 68 to lead by one stroke, had a
double-bogey at No. 11. Players could forget shooting 65 Thursday.
With the lethal combination of fast greens, tricky winds and
narrower fairways at Augusta National Golf Club this year, many
players took a beating, particularly on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   When it was over, Paulson led by one stroke over Tom Lehman (69)
and by two strokes over Sergio Garcia (70) and Steve Stricker (70).
Six players were tied for fifth place at 71: Steve Jones, Bernhard
Langer, Hal Sutton, Thomas Bjorn, Rocco Mediate and Phil Mickelson.
However, with three rounds remaining _ and potential trouble on
every hole _ the leaders understood the situation. Some interesting
things had happened. But the excitement was just getting started.
</P>
<P>
   How did Paulson, a Masters rookie, manage to cope better than
anyone else?
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe lack of knowledge is better, not knowing how difficult
this course can be when the wind is really blowing,'' said Paulson,
who had a breakthrough year in 1999, finishing second at both the
Buick Classic and the Bell Canadian Open and 27th on the PGA Tour
money list with $1.31 million. ``Sometimes it's better playing
courses with less knowledge, because you'll do things not realizing
how difficult a shot is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paulson had no illusion that it would be easy to stay on
top. ``It's too early to worry about it,'' Paulson said. ``Let me
have the lead on the back nine Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   To reach that position, Paulson, who has yet to win a PGA Tour
event, will have to ignore history. No first-round leader has won
the Masters since Ben Crenshaw in 1984, and no Masters rookie has
won since Fuzzy Zoeller in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Paulson, a 37-year-old native of San Gabriel, Calif., spent
years shuttling between mini-tours and the Asian Tour. He
contemplated quitting the game before he reached the Nike Tour in
1997, then made the PGA Tour last year.
</P>
<P>
   Before Thursday, one of Paulson's bigger claims to fame was
winning the National Long Driving Championship in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was back when I weighed 175 and could bench 300,'' he
said. ``Now I weigh 300 and bench 175.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paulson fits the long-hitting profile of many players who
have done well at Augusta. And Thursday, he did a lot of things
well. After making a nervous bogey at No. 1, Paulson jump-started
his day with an eagle at the par-5 No. 2. Paulson then gained
control of his emotions, making birdies at No. 7, No. 8 and No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   He hit his second shot into the water at No. 11, leading to his
double-bogey, the regrouped to make birdies on No. 13 and No. 14 to
reach four under again. Then he made par on the final four holes.
</P>
<P>
   Friday would be another test. But Thursday, Paulson passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having the first-round lead is something I'll always be able
to say,'' Paulson said. ``But unless I play well the next three
days, who's going to care?''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman was even more solid than Paulson, but after no bogeys
through 17 holes, Lehman double-bogeyed No. 18 to lose the lead.
With birdies at No. 1, No. 2, No. 7, No. 8 and No. 16, Lehman
reached No. 18 at five under par. But his final tee shot went well
right into the trees, hitting a trunk and bounding even farther
right under the trees. He was forced to punch out from under the
trees. Then, after reaching the green, he missed a six-foot putt
that would have saved his bogey.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the way Lehman wanted to end the day. But with a
victory already this year at the Phoenix Open, Lehman is playing
his most consistent golf since 1996, when he won the British Open
and was the PGA Tour's player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to let one blip on the radar screen bother me,''
Lehman said of his double-bogey. ``I feel good about the round. It
was a tremendous score under the conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   How confusing was the wind? Mickelson, who played with Lee
Westwood (77) and Lee Janzen (76), described this scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing on the green watching Lee putt, and his pants
just started bristling back and forth from the wind,'' Mickelson
said. ``I'm standing 15 feet away and I didn't feel a thing. The
wind is howling five yards away from me and I didn't feel a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the type of mystical wind we have here at Augusta
National. It created angst for players. When shots were in the air,
many players held their breath, watching nervously to see what
would happen. Jones was cruising along at five under par until he
reached the par-four 11th, the start of the famous three-hole
stretch known as Amen Corner. He bogeyed No. 11, when he failed to
get up and down from right of the green, then his tee shot at the
par-three No. 12 was hit by a gust of wind and plopped into Rae's
Creek.
</P>
<P>
   After Jones finally made a 15-foot putt at No. 12 to save
double-bogey, he looked toward the sky in thanks. He was not the
first player to look toward heaven at Amen Corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some well-struck shots are being rewarded, but poor shots are
double-bogeys or even worse,'' Mickelson said. ``I thought it was a
fair test. But very difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
