<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SOREN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE JOURNALIST IS THE STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 (New York Times OpEd for use in papers of Friday, April 7.)  
 By TABITHA SOREN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ It seems that ABC may be shamed out of airing Leonardo
DiCaprio's interview with President Clinton on global warming,
apparently because it didn't live up to some notional idea of what
an interview with the president should be. ``We did not send him to
interview the president,'' David Westin, the president of ABC News,
said of DiCaprio in a press release. ``No one is that stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, a decision not to air it might seem like a
triumph of journalistic ethics. But I think it's at least worth
asking if it's not a triumph of the idea that politics should be
dull.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that the journalism police are so upset with the idea
of a movie star interviewing a politician? The real question isn't
whether it violates some abstract notion of journalistic propriety
but whether it serves the public interest. Look around at politics
today. More than half of Americans are not sufficiently engaged
that they bother to vote. Clearly, the problem is not that politics
is too entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   Do the journalists who are lamenting the breakdown of news and
entertainment really worry that viewers will not know the
difference between an actor with softball questions and a
professional journalist with hardball ones? Does anyone really
think the audience is going to mistake Leonardo DiCaprio for Wolf
Blitzer?
</P>
<P>
   Not only is interest in politics tepid, but the public's opinion
of journalists is also at an all-time low. Perhaps it's because
viewers are weary of being condescended to. Why can't we just admit
that politics exists alongside other cultural forces, like movies,
music and sports? For instance, few watched the presidential
debates in 1996, because the World Series was on TV at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting to keep the distinction between news and entertainment
is, after all, pretty self-serving for journalists. Cable TV and
the Internet have encroached on the turf of network reporters; they
don't need Hollywood getting in on the act, too. It's like any
cartel in action: the star of ``Titanic'' is as welcome here as a
new oil producer would be in OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   It's also worth pointing out that journalists seem concerned
about only one side of the wall between journalism and
entertainment. You don't see many turning down offers to appear in
Hollywood movies. (Nor do you hear Leonardo DiCaprio complaining
that journalists have no business being in movies.)
</P>
<P>
   My guess is that the deeper concern isn't that DiCaprio would
flop as a presidential interviewer, but that he'd succeed all too
well. (After all, his failure would only buttress the case of his
critics.) The real threat is that he might get something
interesting, that the president would respond differently to an
interviewer for whom he did not feel profound contempt. Maybe we'd
learn something new _ even if it wasn't about Clinton's 73-point
plan to save the environment. And that would be a disaster for the
journalism cartel.
</P>
<P>
   I first interviewed Bill Clinton in 1992 when I was a
24-year-old reporter for MTV. I got many strange looks and several
shoves out of the way before getting an audience with
then-candidate Clinton. Our conversation was quite different than
the one he would have had with Sam Donaldson. Our coverage did not
replace the traditional election reporting, nor was that our goal.
</P>
<P>
   But I think we helped show young voters something about Clinton
that otherwise they might not have seen, and a dialogue between
political leaders and a younger generation began. It wasn't all
frivolous _ we talked a lot about the earned income tax credit, for
heaven's sake _ but some of it was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boxers or briefs?'' was a question an MTV audience member
asked the president in our town hall forum in 1994. Of course, Sam
Donaldson would never have asked that question. But viewers,
witnessing Clinton's ability to roll with the punches, to take the
question in the joking spirit it was asked, learned a lot more
about their president than his choice in underwear.
</P>
<P>
   As far as I'm concerned, getting anything fresh out of a
politician's mouth is a victory for journalism and for voters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Tabitha Soren was a political correspondent for MTV from 1991
to 1999.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features. &QL;
</P>
