<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: GOLF'S BIG 3 TOGETHER AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ From tee to green for all 18 holes, the applause
of thousands serenaded the Big Three as if on a sound track, as if
it were the 1960s and each was trying to win another Masters.
Instead of each just trying to beat the other two.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three _ that's how they were known when Jack Nicklaus,
Arnold Palmer and Gary Player were dominating the PGA Tour and the
major championships. And with the wind swirling across Augusta
National in Thursday's sunny first round of the 64th Masters, the
Big Three were out there in a rare threesome. Together again.
</P>
<P>
   As friendly as their round was, each was hoping to shoot a
better score than his other two longtime rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always do,'' Palmer agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But the leader in this mini-Masters is Nicklaus with a
two-over-par 74, one stroke better than Tiger Woods and only six
strokes behind the leader, Dennis Paulson. Player had a 76 and
Palmer a 78, two strokes better than Greg Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, each of the Big Three knows he's not going to win
another green jacket. Not at their ages _ Nicklaus is 60, Player
64, Palmer 70.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't have paired the three of us together,'' Nicklaus
said of their rare appearance in a threesome, ``if they thought any
of us had a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But give all those official green jackets credit for marquee
thinking. And after being welcomed to the first tee with
appreciative applause, the Big Three were observed laughing. Asked
later what had prompted the laughs, Palmer said: ``I think we were
talking about how old we were. I really don't remember.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course you don't remember,'' Player said, smiling,
prompting another laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Player talked about how ``memories are the cushions of life''
and cited as a ``special moment the way the people received us.''
So did Palmer, but Nicklaus, always the competitor, was annoyed at
having bogeyed the 16th and 17th holes after having strung together
15 consecutive pars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't pay much attention to that nostalgia stuff,'' Nicklaus
said after hitting balls on the range after his round. ``It was
very nice, the gallery was very nice, but I'm a funny duck. I come
here to play golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Even at 60, even a year after hip-replacement surgery. But
that's Jack Nicklaus. That's why his 18 major pro championships put
him on a pedestal as the best golfer in history. And most of those
majors were won in tournaments in which Palmer and Player competed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Arnold and Gary,'' the Golden Bear said, ``are the two best
friends I've had on tour.''
</P>
<P>
   In their ``Big Three'' television series in the '60s, they were
always together on the course. And in recent years on the Senior
PGA Tour, they were occasionally in the same threesome. In their
best years as touring pros, they were never grouped together in a
threesome for the first two rounds of a tournament; it would have
clogged the flow of the galleries.
</P>
<P>
   But every so often two of the three would fall together with
similar scores among the leaders on a weekend. Not that they liked
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of just playing against the golf course,'' Nicklaus
often said of those occasions, ``we'd be playing against each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But for the first two rounds, the Augusta National green jackets
reunited the Big Three with a total of 13 Masters' victories _ a
record 6 for Nicklaus, 4 for Palmer, 3 for Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought at the end of the century,'' said Will Nicholson,
chairman of the Masters' competition committee, ``that we'd put
three of the greatest players on the golf course together.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost any other sport, the champions of 35 years ago could
not compete on equal terms with today's best. But in golf, skill
endures. No matter what the age, golfers of any age post real
scores in real tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   And the Masters, where a winner can tee off every year for as
long as he wishes, is the only major golf tournament where the Big
Three could form a threesome at their ages.
</P>
<P>
   Considering their Masters' accomplishments, they deserved to be
on display here as never before.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus is now a remarkable 53 under par for his 153 rounds in
his 41 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Player is only 107 over par for 146 rounds in his 43 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, whose scores have declined in recent years, is 280 over
par for 142 rounds in his 46 Masters.
</P>
<P>
   And in Friday's second round the Big Three will be together
again. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
