<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9422 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-2NDLD     04-06 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAKISTAN-SHARIF-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-790(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PREMIER OF PAKISTAN IS SENTENCED TO LIFE IN PRISON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDS: Rewrites graf 5 to give more precise background on the
coup.)  (SUBS for complete writethru to add details and reactions to
sentence. CORRECTS spelling of Jafri to JAFFRI; NOTE dateline
addition and byline change) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KARACHI, Pakistan _ Nawaz Sharif, ousted as Pakistan's prime
minister in a military coup in October, was convicted Thursday of
hijacking a commercial airliner, sentenced to life imprisonment
rather than death and ordered to forfeit all his personal property.
</P>
<P>
   Standing along with six co-defendants, who were each acquitted,
the balding, doughy Sharif barely blinked when the judgment was
read. A shriek from his daughter Maryam broke the silence. ``Have
fear of God!'' she cried. Her mother, Kulsoom Nawaz, attempting
stoicism, quieted her and other relatives who had begun to wail.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif, 52, was then quickly led away. His family and followers,
many clutching copies of the Koran, tried to chase after him,
shouting, ``Long live Nawaz Sharif!''
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's crime was not an ordinary hijacking, at least as most
of the world understands the term. No weapon was used. Sharif was
not even aboard the aircraft. His crime was to issue orders, which
he later rescinded, telling the airport's ground control to refuse
permission for landing to a Karachi-bound airliner, sending it out
of the country. The plane, according to the pilot, then found
itself low on fuel, and the lives of everyone on board were
endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 198 people on the plane was Gen. Pervez Musharraf, who
came to power that day in a coup. Hours earlier the prime minister
had fired the general as army chief of staff, while he was out of
the country. In reprisal, army officers began the coup. Once the
general was back safely on the ground, he took control and named
himself Pakistan's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Rahmat Hussain Jaffri took these unusual circumstances
into account in sparing Sharif death by hanging and meting out the
lesser penalty of two concurrent life terms _ one for hijacking,
another for terrorism. In Pakistan, a life sentence is defined as
25 years, though there is the chance of an early release for good
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Sharif's attorneys immediately said they would appeal, insisting
that too much weight had been given to the testimony of Aminullah
Chaudhry, the former head of the civil aviation authority and the
man who claimed to have received Sharif's orders to waylay the jet.
Chaudhry, at one time a defendant, won release by becoming a state
witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He purchased his freedom with the neck of another person,''
said a defense lawyer, Manzoor Ahmed Malik.
</P>
<P>
   In a 157-page decision distributed Thursday, the judge wrote
that the hijacking ``was committed at the spur of the moment and in
heat of passion'' after Sharif ``came to know that his authority
was eroded by some few army soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict, the judge said, fell within the confines of
Pakistan's penal code, which has an elastic definition of
hijacking, assessing guilt to ``whoever unlawfully, by the use or
show of force or by threats of any kind, seizes or exercises
control of an aircraft.''
</P>
<P>
   The case was heard in Pakistan's anti-terrorism court, a venue
for heinous crimes and speedy trials that had been instituted by
Sharif himself. Indeed, he had wanted to ban any appellate process,
though other lawmakers deemed that draconian. As it stands, an
appeal from the anti-terrorism court must be filed within seven
working days. A higher court then has a month to decide. A further
appeal can be made to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors too have a right to appeal, and chief public
prosecutor Raja Qureshi said he objected to the acquittals given
the six other defendants, among them Sharif's brother Shahbaz, who
had been chief minister of the state of Punjab. The government had
asked that Nawaz Sharif receive the death penalty, and Qureshi said
he may well request the higher court to consider the harsher
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   In general, however, the military government seemed pleased with
Thursday's events. Javed Jabbar, a special adviser to Musharraf,
lingered at the courthouse. He wryly and triumphantly said: ``This
was an extraordinarily bizarre situation _ a first in the history
of the world _ where a national leader had decided to become the
country's chief air traffic controller as well. It was a symbolic
expression of Nawaz Sharif's attempt to ruin Pakistan.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharif case has been an intensely watched political soap
opera. Pakistan is a nation of 150 million people, a developing
nuclear arsenal and a nearly bankrupt economy. It has spent half
its 52 years under military rule _ and half under inept and corrupt
elected officials. Musharraf is but the latest army officer to
overthrow the government only to then claim his intent is to make
Pakistan safe for democracy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sharif and Musharraf offered competing stories that raised the
question of which came first: the coup or the hijacking?
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to the court, Sharif explained that he and the
general had been at odds since last summer, after the prime
minister withdrew Pakistani-backed forces from a series of violent
battles with the Indian military in the mountains of Kashmir. He
said he ``had reliable secret information'' that an army coup was
in the works and he tried to head it off by replacing Musharraf
with someone more loyal.
</P>
<P>
   The general has told a far different story, calling Sharif a
corrupt and incompetent leader. He said his officers had reacted
spontaneously to save him and the other airline passengers from
death, taking over the air traffic control tower ``when
circumstances were created which would have forced our plane either
to land in India or crash.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was court testimony that Sharif had ordered the
aircraft diverted, witnesses also suggested that he had changed his
mind when repeatedly told of the plane's fuel problems. He then
decided the airliner could land within Pakistan, but only to be
refueled before leaving the country with everyone still aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge could not bear the pressure of this case,'' Sharif's
wife told reporters a few hours after the sentencing. ``He could
not rule against the army.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there have been international concerns about whether the
trial would be fair.
</P>
<P>
   Pakistan's criminal justice system has a reputation for shoddy
investigations, concocted evidence and outlandish perjury. Many a
trial, veteran observers say, often follows a formula where the
prosecution fabricates a phony case, the defense manufactures a
bogus rebuttal and then the judge decides in favor of the side
offering the bigger bribe.
</P>
<P>
   But most observers and participants, including Sharif and his
attorneys, said they thought the trial was conducted judiciously.
</P>
<P>
   ``The integrity of the judge cannot be questioned,'' said Malik,
the defense attorney. ``I congratulate the judge.''
</P>
<P>
   After Thursday's verdict there was little in the way of public
protest. The Pakistan Muslim League, Sharif's party, is badly
fractured, with some members wanting to cozy up to the army and
others wanting to ally themselves with long-time opponents. Kulsoom
Nawaz, a political neophyte, has been the most outspoken defender
of her husband.
</P>
<P>
   According to the verdict, all of Sharif's property is to be
confiscated. Additionally, the judge added various fines. One is
for about $40,000 to be divided among the 198 people who were on
the hijacked plane, including Musharraf.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
