<P>
   (NYT42) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-4 -- The scene
at Dulles International Airport as Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the father
of Elian Gonzalez, addressed reporters, accompanied by his wife,
Nercy Carmenate, and their six-month-old son, Hianny. Gonzalez
arrived in America Thursday morning to claim his son, accusing
Miami relatives of exploiting the 6-year-old boy and demanding a
halt to ``endless, confusing procedures'' in U.S. courts. (Paul
Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT41) GARDEN CITY, N.Y. (LEFT), NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 --
NY-SENATE-POLL -- Results of the latest New York Times-CBS poll on
the New York Senate race between Rudy Giuliani and Hillary Rodham
Clinton show the first lady is leading the New York mayor by eight
points. Giuliani receives his lowest approval rating ever in the
city and one-third say they are less likely to vote for him because
of his handling of the March shooting by undercover police of
Patrick Dorismond in Midtown. During a news conference on March 22,
Giuliani, right, explained his reasoning for the controversial
release of Dorismond's police record following the shooting.
Clinton spoke before an audience at Adelphi University in January.
(Vic Delucia, left, Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- NY-BANGLADESHI-COOKS-2 --
Immigrants from Bangladesh own many of the Indian restaurants in
New York. Shamsher Wadud, the owner of Nirvana on Central Park
South, changed career plans after deciding that he could run a
better restaurant than one he had visited in Manhattan as an
exchange student in the 1960s. Wadud lets it be known that he's
from Dhaka, and that his was a different experience from that of
the immigrant Sylheti restaurateurs in the city's less glamorous
neighborhoods. (Thomas Dallal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- NY-BANGLADESHI-COOKS-1 --
The signs may invoke India, but immigrants from Bangladesh own many
of the restaurants on Sixth Street - aka ``Little India'' - in New
York City's East Village. They say one reason for the choice of
names is to sell what people are familiar with. (Richard Perry/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- AUCTION-CORRUPTION --
Prosecutors in the federal antitrust investigation of Sotheby's and
Christie's have evidence that a scheme to limit competition by
fixing commissions charged to buyers and sellers was set in motion
not by subordinates, but by the chairmen of the world's auction
giants at the time, according to people involved in the
investigation. Prosecutors want one of the men, A. Alfred Taubman,
the former chairman of Sotheby's (Sir Anthony Tennant of Christie's
is the other), to plead to a felony. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT37) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-3 -- Following
his arrival from Cuba, Juan Miguel Gonzalez waits to address
reporters as his wife, Nercy Carmenate Castillo, holds their
six-month-old son Hianny on Thursday at Dulles International
Airport. The father of Elian Gonzalez arrived in America Thursday
morning to claim his son, accusing Miami relatives of exploiting
the 6-year-old boy and demanding a halt to ``endless, confusing
procedures'' in U.S. courts. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT36) SKOKIE, Ill. -- April 6, 2000 -- MARKET-MARGINS --
Michael Stummer, a day trader in suburban Chicago, said he was
watching intently when the market turned down earlier this week -
``for the bottom.'' After the Nasdaq composite had dropped 574
points and had begun to recover Tuesday afternoon, Stummer says he
jumped into the market. ``I bought a stock at $71 and sold it at
$87 an hour later,'' he said. ``I was screaming and yelling.''
(Steve Kagan/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT35) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- CONVENTION-MEDIA-2 --
While the broadcast networks are looking for ways to pare down
their coverage of political conventions this summer, CNN and its
politics-driven cable rivals, C-Span, MSNBC and Fox News Channel,
have unseated the old broadcast networks as the dominant conveyance
for the nation's political news. Steve Scully, senior executive
producer for C-Span, and Gary Ellenwood, director of field
operations, went over coverage plans from the 1996 political
conventions in preparation for the summer. (Susana Raab/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT34) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- CONVENTION-MEDIA-1 --
While the broadcast networks are looking for ways to pare down
their coverage of political conventions this summer, CNN and its
politics-driven cable rivals, C-Span, MSNBC and Fox News Channel,
have unseated the old broadcast networks as the dominant conveyance
for the nation's political news. From left, Stephen Hirsh, director
of special events for Fox News, met with Bob Torpey, senior
engineer, and David Futrowsky, director of field operations, to
look over a site map for the Republican Convention. (Susana
Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) PHILADELPHIA -- April 6, 2000 -- REPUBS-CONVENTION -- A
coaltion of more than 50 protest groups has sued over rules on
protests during the Republican convention. Officials of the groups,
from left, Tim Lachman, Stefan Presser and Michael Morrill, held a
news conference Thursday in Philadelphia. (Laura Pedrick/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- KENNEDY-WILKER --
Lawrence J. Wilker, the outgoing president of the Kennedy Center
for the Performing Arts, in front of its Millennium Stage. Wilker
said Thursday that he would leave his post at the end of the year
and, following the path of many other executives these days, would
join a new Internet venture. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) XIALING, China -- April 6, 2000 -- CHINA-FOLK-RELIGIONS
-- Local folk religions have spread all over China in recent years,
even while the Falun Gong sect is being hounded. In Xialing,
ancestor worship, which was banned for 40 years under Communism, is
having a revival. (Elisabeth Rosenthal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) PAWLING, N.Y. -- April 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9
-- ABOUT-CARS-RAPHAEL-2 -- The Smart, originally developed in a
joint effort by Swatch and Mercedes but wholly owned by
DaimlerChrysler since 1998, was designed for the tight confines of
European cities. For the brave, the Smart can hit 75 mph. (Richard
L. Harbus/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) PAWLING, N.Y. -- April 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9
-- ABOUT-CARS-RAPHAEL-1 -- The Smart, originally developed in a
joint effort by Swatch and Mercedes but wholly owned by
DaimlerChrysler since 1998, was designed for the tight confines of
European cities. The TV host Sally Jessy Raphael spent months
trying to free her 8.2-foot-long, 3-cylinder Smart from customs.
(Richard L. Harbus/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL 9 --
BIZ-ATMs -- If you are irked enough by ATM fees and don't want the
inconvenience of limiting yourself to your bank's automatic
tellers, there are some new ways to avoid the fees. One
alternative, Internet banking, can often can mean lower fees and
higher interest rates, it can also be ragged around the edges.
Another way to avoid ATM fees is to replace a checking account with
a particular type of asset management account at a brokerage firm.
(Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- SMITHFIELD-HAM-2 --
Smithfield Foods operates hog farms and slaughterhouses throughout
the country providing pork to the nation's biggest supermarkets and
fast food outlets like McDonald's. The company has come under
intense scrutiny from state and federal regulators who say that big
agricultural companies like Smithfield may wield too much control
over the nation's food supply, and too much pricing power in the
meatpacking industry. Joseph W. Luter III, chairman and chief
executive of Smithfield Foods, in his apartment in late March.
(George M. Gutierrez/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) TAR HEEL, N.C. -- April 6, 2000 -- SMITHFIELD-HAM -- The
Smithfield pork processing plant in Tar Heel, NC. Smithfield Foods,
operates hog farms and slaughterhouses throughout the country,
supplying pork to the nation's biggest supermarkets and fast food
outlets like McDonald's. The company has come under intense
scrutiny from state and federal regulators who say that big
agricultural companies like Smithfield may wield too much control
over the nation's food supply, and too much pricing power in the
meatpacking industry. (Edward Keating/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- CYPRIOT-ART-MET-3 -- A
visitor to the new Cypriot galleries at the Metropolitan Museum,
looks at one of the 600 objects on display in the exhibit which
ranges in size from colossal sculptures to poppy-size juglets. And
everywhere there are traces of the various superpowers -- Egypt,
Greece, Assyria, Rome -- that established a presence and
contributed to the sweetly unglamorous carnival of styles known as
Cypriot art. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- FORD-PARRY-JONES-2 -- Ford's
old advertising slogan may need some updating, to wit: Have you
driven a Parry-Jones lately? You have if you've been at the wheel
of the Lincoln LS or the Ford Focus in North America or the Ford
Puma or Ka in Europe. These cars bear the stamp of a single
engineer - Richard Parry-Jones, the Ford Motor Co.'s group vice
president in charge of product development and quality - as few
modern models do. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- FORD-PARRY-JONES-1 --
Richard Parry-Jones, the Ford Motor Co.'s group vice president in
charge of product development and quality, in a Jaguar XK180
concept car. As Ford's guru of driving dynamics, he tries to
engineer a driving experience that bonds a driver to his car. (The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) KHIMKI, Russia -- April 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
9 -- BIZ-WORLD-IKEA-2 -- At Ikea's new store on the outskirts of
Moscow, completion of an overpass that would ease traffic flow has
been blocked by the city government. The roadblock is a reminder of
the worst aspects of doing business in Russia, where laws and
bureaucrats can be arbitrary, rules can change quickly and
corruption is always a problem. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) KHIMKI, Russia -- April 6, 2000 -- ADV. FOR SUN., APRIL
9 -- BIZ-WORLD-IKEA-1 -- Vladimir and Lydia Tetelman looked at
furniture in Ikea's store in Khimki, just outside Moscow, which was
mobbed by 37,000 customers on opening day, March 22. Ikea is a
welcome relief for Russians who usually only encounter
top-of-the-line prices in the new, glitzy shopping malls that have
popped up in Moscow to offer foreign-made products - malls that
have mostly been empty since the financial crisis that followed the
devaluation of the ruble and the government's default on its debt
in August of 1998. (Jacqueline Mia Foster/The New York Times) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- April 6, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-DIPLO --
Katherine Koch of CNN prepares a report on the latest developments
from Washington on the case involving Elian Gonzalez outside the
Cuban Interest Section, Tuesday. The interests section, which is
formally affiliated with the Swiss Embassy, is larger than many
embassies here. It has a staff of about 20 diplomats and other
officials whose activities are supposed to be tightly monitored by
the State and Justice departments out of concern that some of the
Cubans are spies for the government of Fidel Castro. (Justin
Lane/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) CHANTILLY, Va. -- April 6, 2000 -- CUBAN-BOY-ENVOY --
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, second from left, and his wife Nercy
Carmenate Castillo, left, carrying their six-month old son Hianny,
look on as Fernando Remirez de Estenoz speaks to reporters after
their arrival from Cuba, Thursday. Remirez runs the Cuban Interests
Section in Washington, the de facto embassy for a government that
has not had full diplomatic relations with the United States since
1961. (Rick McKay/The Cox News Service)
</P>
