<P>
   (NYT16) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- SPAIN-FAITH-EXHIBIT --
``Procession of the Virgin,'' taken in Spain in 1930 by Ruth
Anderson, is part of ``Images in Procession: Testimonies to Spanish
Faith'' at the American Bible Society. The works include Baroque
sculptures, 19th-century paintings from New Mexico and documentary
photographs of religious pageants taken in the 1920's in Spain,
where the public, ceremonial display of religious art has a long
and fervid history. (American Bible Society/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- FEMALE-BODYBUILDERS-2 --
``Picturing the Modern Amazon'' at the New Museum of Contemporary
Art in SoHo, examines the relatively invisible, obsessive
contemporary subculture of female bodybuilding, ushering the
visitor into a world of high-definition muscles, low-definition
sex-linked characteristics and gender-bending ambiguity. Pat
Olliffe's illustration ``The Sensational/Savage She-Hulk'' for
Marvel Comics is among those works on display. (New Museum of
Contemporary Art/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) UNDATED -- April 6, 2000 -- FEMALE-BODYBUILDERS-1 --
``Picturing the Modern Amazon'' at the New Museum of Contemporary
Art in SoHo, examines the relatively invisible, obsessive
contemporary subculture of female bodybuilding, ushering the
visitor into a world of high-definition muscles, low-definition
sex-linked characteristics and gender-bending ambiguity. Andres
Serrano's photograph of Lesa Lewis is among those works on display.
(New Museum of Contemporary Art/The New York Times)
