release of Dorismond's police record following the shooting.
Clinton spoke before an audience at Adelphi University in January.
(Vic Delucia, left, Don Hogan Charles/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT40) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- NY-BANGLADESHI-COOKS-2 --
Immigrants from Bangladesh own many of the Indian restaurants in
New York. Shamsher Wadud, the owner of Nirvana on Central Park
South, changed career plans after deciding that he could run a
better restaurant than one he had visited in Manhattan as an
exchange student in the 1960s. Wadud lets it be known that he's
from Dhaka, and that his was a different experience from that of
the immigrant Sylheti restaurateurs in the city's less glamorous
neighborhoods. (Thomas Dallal/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT39) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- NY-BANGLADESHI-COOKS-1 --
The signs may invoke India, but immigrants from Bangladesh own many
of the restaurants on Sixth Street - aka ``Little India'' - in New
York City's East Village. They say one reason for the choice of
names is to sell what people are familiar with. (Richard Perry/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT38) NEW YORK -- April 6, 2000 -- AUCTION-CORRUPTION --
Prosecutors in the federal antitrust investigation of Sotheby's and
Christie's have evidence that a scheme to limit competition by
fixing commissions charged to buyers and sellers was set in motion
not by subordinates, but by the chairmen of the world's auction
giants at the time, according to people involved in the
investigation. Prosecutors want one of the men, A. Alfred Taubman,
the former chairman of Sotheby's (Sir Anthony Tennant of Christie's
is the other), to plead to a felony. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York
Times)
</P>
