<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS OUTPACE REPUBLICANS; CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR RAISES MILLIONS;
QUESTIONS OF RUNNING MATES; THE RACE IN TENNESSEE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS OUTPACE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee, which regularly bemoans the
financial superiority of Republicans, announced Thursday that it
had outraised the Republican National Committee in the first three
months of 2000 and ended the period with more money in the bank.
From Jan. 1 to March 31, the committee reported, more than $26
million flowed into the party's coffers and, it said, $22 million
was still on hand as of April 1. The Republican National Committee
reported, by contrast, that it had raised $24 million over the same
span and had $18 million on deposit as of April 1. Both parties are
fattening their soft-money accounts with big, loosely regulated
contributions from corporations, unions, interest groups and
wealthy individuals, the aim being to pay for campaigns on behalf
of their presumed nominees in the months preceeding the summer
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are wonderful figures,'' said Edward G. Rendell, general
chairman of the Democratic party.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the Republican chairman, was equally ebullient,
despite the second-place finish. ``There's never been such
excitement in the Republican ranks,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JOHN M. BRODER
</P>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR RAISES MILLIONS
</P>
<P>
   Though last year was his first in office, Gov. Gray Davis of
California nevertheless embarked on an early, relentless
fund-raising campaign for re-election, pulling in a record $13.2
million. Raising so much money so soon made him an easy target for
reformers seeking to change California's no-holds-barred campaign
laws. But if the criticism bothers Davis, he is not showing it. In
fact, he has just expanded his fund raising, starting an aggressive
telephone solicitation campaign that warns of ``strong right-wing
opposition'' to his re-election three years hence. Telemarketing
campaigns are relative rarities for major candidates in California,
especially candidates for governor. So does Davis have something
more in mind than running again for governor, maybe a federal
office? No, he insists. All he is trying to do, he says, is amass a
fund for 2002 big enough to ward off any other well-financed
hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   _ EVELYN NIEVES
</P>
<P>
   QUESTIONS OF RUNNING MATES
</P>
<P>
   With speculation steadily spreading about possible running mates
for Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush, Gore announced
Thursday that he had picked Warren Christopher, the former
secretary of state, to oversee his selection process. No big
surprise there _ it was Christopher who oversaw the process back in
1992 when Bill Clinton chose Gore as his No. 2. Gore has been asked
many times about names on his short list, but he has yet to drop
one. And in any event, he has been telling friends, he believes he
has a bit of leeway in the process, because Bush will have to pick
first.
</P>
<P>
   KATHARINE Q. SEELYE
</P>
<P>
   THE RACE IN TENNESSEE
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Democratic party tried for months to recruit a
strong candidate to take on Sen. Bill Frist, a Republican, this
fall. But the big names, such as Rep. Harold Ford Jr. of Memphis
and former Public Service Commissioner Sara Kyle, rejected all
pleas to run, even those from prominent Democrats like former Sen.
James Sasser. So when the final filing deadline for jumping into
the race passed at noon Thursday, the party was left with a
relative unknown, Jeff Clark, a former state party treasurer, as
its leading contender. The Tennessee Democratic chairman, Doug
Horne, said Frist's huge personal wealth scared off many potential
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   _ EMILY YELLIN
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
