<SLUG> BC-KENNEDY-WILKER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT OF KENNEDY CENTER IS LEAVING FOR INTERNET JOB 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT32 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The president of the Kennedy Center for the
Performing Arts, Lawrence J. Wilker, said Thursday that he would
leave his post at the end of the year and, following the path of
many other executives these days, would join a new Internet
venture.
</P>
<P>
   Wilker's announcement came a week after Nathan Leventhal said he
would leave his job as president of Lincoln Center in New York,
which creates the unusual circumstance of the nation's two leading
performing arts centers recruiting chief operating officers at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a coincidence,'' Wilker said about the two resignations.
``We are not worn down. Nat and I are ready to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Leventhal's job has a salary of $525,000 a year and Wilker's
$325,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I've got one more adventure in me,'' said Wilker, 56.
</P>
<P>
   The venture, which plans to present drama, dance, music and
other performing arts over the Internet, has not yet been named. In
it, Wilker will join Lou Reda, the major producer of television
programs for the A&AMP;E and History Channel cable operations.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his departure from a bricks-and-mortar arts center
for one made up of electrons marked a trend, Wilker said: ``I don't
think so. My whole life has been devoted to making the arts more
available. I see this as the next logical step: putting a stage
into everyone's living room.''
</P>
<P>
   Before coming to the Kennedy Center, Wilker presided over the
creation of Playhouse Square Center in Cleveland and before that
was director of properties (theaters and real estate) for the
Shubert Organization.
</P>
<P>
   James A. Johnson, the chairman of the Kennedy Center, said the
search for Wilker's successor would begin immediately. He praised
Wilker's accomplishments in improving the center's finances while
overseeing an expansion of its performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he leaves in December, he will have been here almost 10
years,'' Johnson said. ``It is a demanding job, with 3,300
performances a year. There are six or seven stages operating in an
evening when everything is full.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I deeply regret, but understand, Larry's decision,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   During Wilker's tenure, the National Symphony Orchestra, which
is now part of the Kennedy Center, hired Leonard Slatkin as its
music director, and it seems to have resolved its differences with
the Washington Opera, which is not part of the center but performs
there.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Center also eliminated its $7 million debt and began
a $170 million renovation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
