<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT'S BUYBACKS LEAVING FEWER TREASURIES TO GO AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A specter haunts mutual funds that invest primarily in federal
government debt: the Great Bond Buyback.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-January, the Treasury announced plans to buy back and
retire up to $30 billion in outstanding Treasury debt by the end of
the year; some $2 billion worth has already been bought.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, demand for Treasury notes and bonds has already
surged. Institutional investors have bid long-maturity prices up
and yields down _ no bad thing for investors holding Treasuries
directly or through funds.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter, according to Ryan Labs, the benchmark
30-year bond posted a total return of 9.06 percent _ a big
improvement from a loss of 14.78 percent for all of 1999. Rising
prices pushed the yield on the long bond down to 5.48 percent
during a time when short-term rates were rising.
</P>
<P>
   Impending scarcity is the reason. In the Treasury buyback, the
prime targets are notes and bonds with maturities of 10 years or
longer, especially those maturing from 2015 to 2025, according to
Gerald Lucas, senior government strategist at Merrill Lynch. Those
bonds were slightly cheaper than others when the buyback began; by
buying them, the Treasury intends to keep the overall maturity of
its outstanding debt between 5.5 and 6 years, Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill thinks the $30 billion is only the beginning. The firm's
analysts see potential for buybacks of up to $200 billion in the
next three to four years, with a wider range of maturities affected
in future years, beginning with the five-year note, Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   New Treasuries will still be issued at the same time, but in
smaller numbers. Merrill expects the volume of new 30-year bonds to
fall to $15 billion this year, half the total in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   No one is expecting the shrinking supply of longer-term Treasury
bonds to bring cataclysmic changes, but there will be important
effects for investors holding or interested in domestic taxable
bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   Just about all such funds will feel the impact, because so much
of the nation's overall fixed-income market is made up of
Treasuries, said David Schroeder, a fixed-income manager at
American Century Investments. The Lehman Brothers Aggregate Bond
index, a general benchmark for United States bond funds, has a 32
percent allocation for Treasuries.
</P>
<P>
   General bond fund managers who believe Treasuries will
outperform other taxable bonds, like corporates and mortgage-backed
securities, will give even more weight to Treasuries than the index
suggests, while those who think the opposite will underweight
Treasuries. The optimists did better last quarter: while the
aggregate index was gaining just 2.21 percent, the Treasury portion
of the index was up 3.79 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, long-term government bond funds will be affected most
by the buyback. Generally, government bond funds are required by
charter to keep at least 65 percent of assets in government
securities, a category that, in addition to Treasuries, includes
bonds issued by quasigovernmental agencies like Fannie Mae and the
Tennessee Valley Authority.
</P>
<P>
   These bonds have long been regarded as implicitly guaranteed by
the Treasury; though some proposals have been floated to scale back
the implied guarantee for some agencies, no change is expected
soon. As the supply of true Treasuries dries up or becomes
unattractively expensive, most of these funds can easily buy
so-called agencies instead.
</P>
<P>
   Not so for a small subset of the group, Treasury funds, whose
charters generally require that at least 65 percent of assets be in
true Treasuries alone. Some funds have even stricter limits: T.
Rowe Price U.S. Treasury Long-Term must keep 85 percent of assets
in Treasury bonds and the balance in either Treasuries or
securities issued by Ginnie Mae, the only one of the agencies whose
bonds are explicitly guaranteed by the government, according to Dan
Shackelford, a senior portfolio manager in taxable bond funds at T.
Rowe Price. By contrast, Dreyfus U.S. Treasury Long Term can invest
up to 35 percent of assets in any of the agency bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Morningstar Inc. tracks only 16 long-term Treasury funds, with
combined assets of $2.7 billion at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0529 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9434 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-BONDS-ART-2ND     04-06 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-BONDS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: of February.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are they endangered by the buyback? Probably not. ``You have to
put that $30 billion in the context of all the issues
outstanding,'' said Robert Auwaerter, head of taxable fixed-income
funds at the Vanguard Group. All told, some $3.2 trillion in
marketable Treasury securities are outstanding, and one-seventh of
them _ $455 billion worth _ have maturities of 15 years or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Treasuries grow scarcer and more expensive, the funds
that now must stick closest to them may ask shareholders to approve
charter amendments to give them more flexibility. None have done so
yet, but at least one fund company, American Century, is
considering the possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something we are thinking about, more on the back burner
than the front burner,'' Schroeder said. ``I feel we have some time
to make that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors who stick with the narrowly focused Treasury funds may
continue to find the Treasury buyback plan to their liking, but the
recent run-up is not attracting new money to Treasuries; quite the
opposite, in fact. In the first month of the year, $200 million in
assets flowed out of all Treasury funds, leaving $2.8 billion in
assets, and $1.5 billion flowed out of United States government
funds, leaving $27.7 billion in assets, according to the Financial
Research Corp., which tracks mutual fund cash flows. The company's
figures for all of 1999 show $215 million flowing out of Treasury
funds and $2.3 billion out of government funds.
</P>
<P>
   A Treasury bond's great advantage, safety, is not much on
investors' minds these days, riveted as they are by all the
excitement in stocks. ``People are not willing to pay up for a
risk-free asset, because there's so much going on everywhere
else,'' said Shackelford at T. Rowe Price. But when the climate
changes, he added, ``it will have its day in the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The government's buyback plans, meanwhile, at least offer the
prospect that Treasury bond funds will post stronger capital gains
than funds invested in agencies or long-term corporate bonds. And
Lucas at Merrill Lynch is confident that even an aggressive buyback
program will not extinguish the market.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he foresees the Treasury converting some of its $2.5
trillion of nonmarketable debt _ IOUs issued to entities like the
Social Security and federal retirement trust funds _ into tradeable
securities.
</P>
<P>
   Most government trust funds ``aren't actively managed,'' he
said. ``They are restricted to nonmarketable Treasuries,'' he
added. ``They hold them until they mature and then roll them
over.''
</P>
<P>
   Converting some of the trust funds' holdings to tradeable
securities would give the funds the flexibility to diversify into
other investments while satisfying investors' demand for
Treasuries, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   And there is a chance that the Treasury's buyback plans will
change radically after the November election installs a new
president and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The current buyback program is an outgrowth of a growing budget
surplus that the Congressional Budget Office expects to reach $1.9
trillion in 2010. New leaders may have other ideas for that
surplus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0530 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9435 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-2TA     04-06 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-ANNUITIES-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOME ANNUITIES, `FREE MONEY' WITH AN CATCH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   By JOSEPH B. TREASTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free money!
</P>
<P>
   That's the pitch being used by more than a dozen insurance
companies in a new campaign to sell variable annuities, those
complicated hybrids of mutual funds and insurance policies that are
widely criticized as having high fees and enticing, but often
unneeded features.
</P>
<P>
   Put $100,000 into one of their variable annuities and these
companies will hand over a so-called bonus of 3 percent or 4
percent of the investment _ that is, $3,000 or $4,000 cash. A few
companies offer 5 percent. It sounds great, and the response from
customers has been explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Sales at one company paying a bounty _ G.E. Life and Annuity _
nearly tripled last year. Even companies that say they find such
bonus annuities unsavory are starting to offer them to keep from
losing business.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the money is not really free; it comes with lots of
strings.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, long-term investors are very likely to pay back the
``bonus'' in higher fees _ and then some _ over the life of their
investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no free money,'' said Jon A. Boscia, the chief
executive of the Lincoln National Corp., a leading variable annuity
company that has been losing market share to companies that provide
bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is paying a bonus of 3 or 4 percent and they're
paying a sales commission of 3 to 8 percent, that money has to come
from somewhere,'' Boscia said. ``And it gets built into the prices
and fees inside the variable annuity contract.''
</P>
<P>
   In a business that has shown itself hardly averse to high-priced
financial products, some brokerage houses are refusing to sell the
new products. And executives at companies that are losing money to
the new catnip have complained to federal securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the Securities and Exchange Commission has
dispatched scores of investigators across the country in recent
weeks to comb through the sales records of brokers, bankers,
financial planners and career insurance agents _ the sellers of
variable annuities _ and to interview customers who have signed up
for the bonuses. And officials of the National Association of
Securities Dealers say they are looking into the matter as well.
</P>
<P>
   Paul F. Roye, the director of the SEC's Division of Investment
Management, says the agency suspects that sales representatives are
not telling customers how the bonus variable annuities really work
and may thus be violating disclosure requirements. After all,
critics say, why would people be rushing to invest in bonus
variable annuities if they were being told: We're going to give you
some money upfront, but you'll pay us back much more?
</P>
<P>
   Alone among the states, New York does not permit the sale of
bonus annuities. But Kevin Rampe, the general counsel for the New
York State Department of Insurance, said the state is working on
guidelines that would permit their sale. ``We want to make sure
that customers aren't misled on the true cost of the bonuses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As an example of the higher costs, Manulife Financial, which had
an increase in variable annuity sales of more than 40 percent last
year, charges an average annual fee of 2.63 percent of assets for
its product with a 5 percent bonus, according to the Variable
Annuity Research &AMP; Data Service, a research firm in Marietta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Golden American, a subsidiary of ING of the Netherlands, which
saw its variable annuity sales rise 35 percent last year, charges
an average of 2.53 percent for an annuity with the same 5 percent
bonus.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, two leading companies that do not offer bonuses,
Lincoln National and Hartford Life, charge just under 2 percent.
And companies that they do not pay sales commissions charge even
less: Fidelity Investments, for example, charges an average of 1.42
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The higher fees hit investors directly. ``Over time, the higher
fees more than offset the bonus,'' said Merry Mosbacher, who is in
charge of insurance sales at Edward Jones &AMP; Co., a brokerage firm
that refuses to sell bonus variable annuities.
</P>
<P>
   Here is an example of the math: Over 20 years, a $100,000
investment returning 10 percent annually in a Lincoln National
variable annuity with an annual fee of 1.98 percent would grow to
$467,870.90. But $100,000 plus the $5,000 bonus in the Manulife
variable annuity with an annual fee of 2.63 percent would yield
$435,402.52, or more than $32,000 less.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to charging fees that sometimes run more than 20
percent higher than the industry average, bonus variable annuities
often require investors to tie up their money for nine years,
versus seven years for most other variable annuities. Those who
take their money out sooner must pay a penalty of up to 8.5
percent, which is 1.5 percentage points higher than that imposed by
most other variable annuities. Under federal law, there is also a
10 percent penalty imposed on anyone who withdraws money before
reaching the age of 59{.
</P>
<P>
   The regulators are concerned that sales representatives are
pushing these investments to people who are nearing retirement and
may need to spend the money in their variable annuities long before
the penalty period is over. Such a transaction, Roye said, would
probably be in violation of S.E.C. standards of suitability and
could result in fines and other penalties for a sales rep.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, Roye said, are obliged to talk through the
ramifications of an investment with clients. ``A broker could say
to a customer, `This new bonus product makes sense if you're
willing to stay in it for the next eight or nine years,''' Roye
said. ```But if you want to get out in two years it doesn't make
sense.' If that discussion never took place, or the client didn't
understand, then maybe there's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   American Skandia, the company that first offered bonus variable
annuities four years ago, charges roughly the same 2.58 percent fee
on several variable annuities _ with or without the bonus,
according to Variable Annuity Research. The company, like some of
its rivals, has not cut its profits to offer the bonus, but instead
has scaled back benefits and sales commissions and increased the
penalties for early withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Wade A. Dokken, the chief executive of American Skandia, said
that to focus on lower fees was flawed logic. He pointed out that
among the nearly 50 separate funds that his variable annuity
customers can invest in are some of the best performers in the
industry. What is most important, he says, is not the size of the
annual fees, but the overall earnings of an investment. ``I'd much
rather have a return of 20 percent after you subtract our fees,''
he said, ``than a return of 15 percent from an investment with
lower fees. It's the total return that counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, returns are never guaranteed, while the fees are a
constant. The funds of several of American Skandia's variable
annuities are run by managers from white-hot companies like the
Janus Capital Corp. and Fred Alger Management, which have turned in
hot returns in large part because of big bets on the volatile
technology sector. But should those funds cool down, the annual
fees would take on greater significance.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, some funds without bonuses and with lower fees have
been doing well, too. Conseco, for example, had a return of 42.83
percent last year with a nonbonus variable annuity with annual
charges of 1.74 percent, compared with a return of 33.95 percent
for American Skandia's bonus variable annuity, according to
Variable Annuity Research.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators say bonus variable annuities were designed to entice
customers away from other companies. The idea was to pay a bonus
that would equal _ or at least partially counter _ the almost
universal penalties for early withdrawal. Indeed, Michelle A.
Giordano, an analyst at J.P. Morgan Securities, estimated that at
least half of the bonuses that were given out last year went to
customers who switched from one company to another.
</P>
<P>
   The driving force, experts say, is increased sales commissions.
By moving an old customer into a new variable annuity offered by a
different company, a sales representative earns a second commission
which, of course, is easier than going out and finding a new
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These products are ripe for abuse,'' said Elliott M. Server,
who is in charge of variable annuity sales at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter, another company that has refused to offer the bonus
products.
</P>
<P>
   One part of the sales pitch for existing customers is that they
can shift to a variable annuity with modern features _ say, for
example, one that locks in market gains as a hedge against future
declines for the benefit of the investor's heirs. The old way,
exemplified by American Skandia's bonus variable annuity, is to
guarantee only that an investor's heirs get back at least as much
as was put into the investment.
</P>
<P>
   But many variable annuities now step up the guaranteed amount at
a fixed percentage or as the market value of the investment rises.
Investors pay extra for these features, and financial experts say
they are probably not needed, because long-term stock investments
have historically gained at least 10 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson in all this: One way or another, customers pay for
everything they get in a variable annuity. ``There's only one place
to get the money to do everything we do with these products,'' said
Norse Blazzard, a lawyer who pioneered variable annuities in the
mid-1960s and is a foe of the new bonus versions. ``And that's from
the customer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
