<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9437 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-AR     04-06 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PORTFOLIOS-ART-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVOIDING THE LAND OF THE GIANTS, FIVE MANAGERS FIND SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Mass., N.Y., Ill., Fla.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most mutual fund investors opened the new century with smart
gains, though well below the double-digit returns posted in the
final quarter of 1999. Those who generally steered clear of the
giants in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index often outperformed
in a stock market led by technology and smaller issues.
</P>
<P>
   That was the winning approach for the five professional money
managers who built hypothetical retirement portfolios for The New
York Times. All five beat the S&AMP;P 500, which gained 2 percent
during the first quarter, and one beat the average of 6.5 percent
for diversified domestic equity funds tracked by Lipper Inc.
</P>
<P>
   A common theme among the five managers was unease about &UR;  &LR; the
market's recent violent swings. In response to that uncertainty,
all looked to diversified portfolios and long-term perspectives.
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks were a boon to Jack A. Brill, vice president
of Natural Investment Services in San Diego. His portfolio of
``socially responsible'' funds was the leader for the quarter, with
a gain of 6.6 percent, aided by stakes in Citizens Emerging Growth,
up 23.07 percent, and Calvert New Visions, up 18.54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the second quarter, Brill is dropping Ariel Appreciation, a
small- to mid-cap value fund. A sliver of the freed assets will be
added to Citizens Emerging Growth; the remainder, representing 4
percent of the overall portfolio, will go to Calvert New Visions, a
small growth fund he added in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``During these turbulent times, it is more important for
investors to be well diversified,'' he said. ``Market timing
becomes much more difficult. Taking a long-term perspective is
crucial.''
</P>
<P>
   The next-strongest portfolio last quarter was the one chosen by
Eric M. Kobren, president of Kobren Insight Group and editor of
Fidelity Insight in Wellesley, Mass. Kobren said his company was
staying ``cautiously optimistic'' about the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valuations remain at historically high levels for certain
areas of the market,'' he said. ``However, the economy remains in
very good shape, and corporate profits are growing. And when you
eliminate the technology sector, stocks are much more reasonably
priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the short-term volatility in the market ``is
unnerving,'' he added ``investors are well-advised to maintain a
diversified portfolio and not get unduly concerned about the wide
daily swings we've been experiencing.''
</P>
<P>
   Kobren's portfolio, which contains only funds from Fidelity
Investments, gained 5.95 percent for the quarter. He rode the hot
technology sector with stakes in Fidelity Aggressive Growth, up
14.42 percent, and Fidelity Small Cap Stock, up 12.59 percent. For
the second quarter, he is shifting 5 percent of the portfolio out
of Aggressive Growth, reducing it to 15 percent, and into Fidelity
Value, raising that fund's weighting to 25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   With a cumulative portfolio gain of 215.62 percent since the
contest began in July 1993, Kobren has almost caught up with the
longtime leader, Sheldon Jacobs, who edits the No-Load Fund
Investor in Irvington, N.Y., and whose cumulative return is 221.77
percent. Since the start, the five portfolios have returned an
average of 181.64 percent, compared with 281.49 percent for the
Vanguard 500 Index fund, which tracks the S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of the hypothetical portfolios is tracked each
quarter by Lipper Inc., the research firm in Summit, N.J. The
figures exclude sales charges and transaction costs _ as well as
taxes, because most retirement money is held in tax-deferred
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The five managers may choose from among all funds open to new
investors, and may shift money each quarter. The portfolios are
meant to grow until July 2013, some 20 years after the competition
began.
</P>
<P>
   Russel Kinnel, director of fund analysis at Morningstar Inc. in
Chicago, posted the third-best return for the quarter _ 4.86
percent, buoyed by a large stake in MAS Mid Cap Growth, which was
up 13.34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnel, who took Susan Dziubinski's place in the contest &UR;  &LR; in
January and has overhauled the portfolio, is making no changes for
the coming quarter. ``I should at least be able to stick with them
for three months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnel is sanguine about the market: ``We've watched a big rally
in the Dow, and Nasdaq stocks are getting barbecued, but so what?
The average value fund is still in the red for the year, and the
average growth fund has double-digit gains.''
</P>
<P>
   Harold Evensky, an investment adviser in Coral Gables, Fla.,
also plans no changes to his broadly diversified portfolio, despite
placing fourth during the first quarter with a gain of 4.98
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flip-flop in leaders and laggards continues, just as one
would expect with a diversified portfolio in a turbulent market,''
Evensky said. ``Because no one can predict what market to be in,
the game plan continues to be managing risk as well as return.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs's portfolio trailed the pack for the quarter, gaining
just 4.62 percent. Despite an impressive showing by T. Rowe Price
Science and Technology, up 11.57 percent, his return was pulled
down by stakes in Marisco Focus, up just 0.21 percent, and Strong
Asia-Pacific, up 0.67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Jacobs is cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to take something off the table,'' he said.
``Speculation is rampant, investors are complacent and many
valuations in the new economy are far too high. The risk-reward
relationship for equities isn't nearly as favorable as it was in
the '90s.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he is redirecting 15 percent of his portfolio out
of three stock funds, Vanguard Total Stock Market Index, Marsico
Focus and Janus Olympus, and into a new position in Vanguard Money
Market Prime. But he is standing pat with his Europe and Asia
funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
