<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FLORIDA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore touts importance of 2000 election in Florida
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Vice President Al Gore ate a late dinner at
the home of attorney Robert Montgomery, telling guests who paid
$10,000 each that this presidential election is one of the most
important in history.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke for about 20 minutes, giving his stock campaign
speech and breaking no new ground. He criticized Texas Gov. George
W. Bush for supporting school vouchers, a large federal tax cut and
plans to allow some privatization of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   He also urged the 65 dinner guests to become intensely involved
in the election because of the stark differences between
Republicans and Democrats. ``How hard are we willing to fight for
what we believe in?'' asked Gore.
</P>
<P>
   He warned that a Bush administration would dramatically change
the makeup of the U.S. Supreme Court. And he said that Bush would
be no friend of the environment, accusing the Texas governor of
having the worst environmental record in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore praised Israel and pledged his unwavering support,
one foreign policy issue he did not comment on was the fate of
Elian Gonzalez, 6. Gore has said in recent days that whether the
child should go back to his father should be decided by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gore heads for the gymnasium at Old School Square in
Delray Beach where he will talk to about 150 voters about his plans
for Medicare and making it easier and cheaper to buy prescription
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Both issues are particularly important to South Florida's
retirees who worry about the increasing cost of health care. If
Gore has any chance of taking the Sunshine State away from Bush, he
will need to build a strong base of support in Palm Beach and
Broward counties.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also will tell Democrats about a new plan to allow them to
read the party platform on Internet site Speakout.Com. Voters will
also be able to recommend changes to the platform which will be
approved at the July Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is tentatively scheduled to return to West Palm Beach on
Monday for another dinner raising money for the Democratic National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
