A9440 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-MUTFUND-REGIONALS-ART     04-06 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-REGIONALS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV09-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTING IN YOUR OWN BACKYARD: NO SURE BET FOR GROWING WINNERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn., Minn., Calif., Ill.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888 603-1036
or 888 346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 9) 
 By KATE BERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thinking about investing in a hometown mutual fund, one that
focuses on shares of local companies?
</P>
<P>
   If you live in San Jose or Seattle, you can find something. But
if you're in Chattanooga or Buffalo or just about anyplace else in
the country, don't even bother looking.
</P>
<P>
   In the history of great mutual fund ideas, the regional mutual
fund possibly won't rate more than a footnote. Parochialism, it
turns out, is a selling point that cuts little ice with many
investors, because arbitrarily restricting investments to companies
in just one area can hamper returns _ or magnify trouble, as
investors in Pacific Northwest-centered funds found out when
Microsoft melted down last week.
</P>
<P>
   Of the thousands of mutual fund portfolios tracked by
Morningstar Inc., just 34 are United States regional funds, and
only 13 of those had enough combined assets _ more than $30 million
_ to qualify for The New York Times's mutual funds tables as of
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 34 invest in small and midsize companies, generally
growth stocks not widely followed on Wall Street. Assets have grown
from $1.15 billion at the end of 1995 to $4.57 billion on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   As for returns, just 6 out of 34 outperformed the 25.73 percent
average annual gain of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index over the
last three calendar years.
</P>
<P>
   The regional funds take a geographical approach to following
Peter Lynch's advice about investing in what you know. Their
managers believe they know companies in their own backyards better
than out-of-town analysts do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a consumer of the products and knowing people that work
at local companies is important,'' said Bill Whitlow, manager of
the $163.8 million Safeco Northwest fund in Seattle, whose largest
holding should be easy to guess: Microsoft. The fund gained 54.2
percent last year, and 13.54 percent in the first quarter of 2000,
but gave back more than half that gain last week.
</P>
<P>
   Whitlow said he was a regular at Starbucks and a frequent flier
on Alaska Airlines, and boasted that he could see the headquarters
of Amazon.com from his office window. His fund has positions in all
three stocks in a portfolio limited to companies based in five
states: Alaska, Idaho, Montana, Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who believe that a regional fund gives them a pure
basket of home-baked goods may be surprised to learn that many
regional fund managers eye companies outside their borders.
Securities and Exchange Commission rules allow funds calling
themselves regional to invest as much as 35 percent of assets
outside their geographic area.
</P>
<P>
   That wiggle room allows Safeco Northwest to branch into stocks
like Intel. Though Intel's semiconductor operations in
Hillsborough, Ore., near Portland, make the company the state's
largest private employer, its headquarters are in Santa Clara,
Calif. Another stake outside the region is Kroger, the supermarket
chain based in Cincinnati, which the fund found itself owning after
Kroger acquired the Oregon-based Fred Meyer chain last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have that flexibility,'' Whitlow said. ``The
whole point of it is so I can maintain a diversified portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   The local heroes that turned in the strongest performances of
the last five years were driven, naturally enough, by strong
regional economies. But regional economic performance can swing
sharply down as well as up: Safeco Northwest had an anemic 3.5
percent return in 1998 because its home turf was hit harder than
other areas by Asian economic turmoil. And recent weeks have made
clear the risk inherent in the best performers' heavy reliance on
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad B. Herrmann, lead manager of the $2.93 billion Franklin
California Growth fund, which has its pick of 1,400 publicly traded
companies in California, believes strongly in the home-court
advantage. ``We're a drive down the road to Silicon Valley, so we
do have a leg up,'' said Herrmann, a native of Darien, Conn. ``It
has an appeal to the pride of people who live and work in the state
of California.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann points out that, standing alone, California would rank
as the world's eighth-largest economy and its fourth-largest stock
market. But though state spirit might be the motive to invest in
many regional funds, Franklin California Growth, the top-performing
regional fund over the last three years with an annualized return
of 46.3 percent, attracts fewer than half of its shareholders from
California.
</P>
<P>
   That offers proof that a regional fund can attract
out-of-territory investors, but is also a sign that few investors
consider supporting their local economy a top priority, at least
when it comes to choosing mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Edward S. Rosenbaum, director of research at Lipper Inc., said
funds like Franklin California Growth wind up being sector funds in
disguise, overweighted in technology stocks; by contrast, the
region around Minneapolis yields a much more varied portfolio for
the four funds that concentrate on that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any specialized fund, whether by geography or sector,
it's a step away from diversification,'' he said. ``That makes it
less appropriate for a substantial portion of your financial nest
egg. But it can be a way to engage in the economic life of that
region.'' (Of course, many investors already get all the exposure
they need to their home region's economic vicissitudes simply by
living and working there, and might be better served by a fund that
invests anywhere (italics)but(end italics) their region, just as
many financial planners advise against putting retirement savings
in the stock of one's employer, to avoid an overconcentration of
risk.)
</P>
<P>
   Begun in 1991, the California Growth fund roughly tracks an
index of the state's 250 largest companies ranked by market
capitalization, and is rebalanced each quarter. Two-thirds of its
assets are in networking and semiconductor companies, digital
hardware makers and biotechnology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look at where market flows might be going, so we can
acknowledge where money is shifting,'' Herrmann said by telephone
from the headquarters of Franklin Templeton in San Mateo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   California Growth was an early investor in Netscape and Yahoo
but trimmed its stakes in quarterly rebalancings after they soared
to high valuations. As of last week, Internet service companies
made up about 12.5 percent of the fund's 150 stocks, up from 6.5
percent in early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   These days Herrmann likes JDS Uniphase, the optical-networking
products maker based in San Jose; Versata, a software and service
provider in Oakland; and Vitria Technology, an e-business concern
in Sunnyvale. Other holdings include Applied Micro Circuits, a San
Diego maker of integrated circuits for telecommunications
applications, and Applied Materials of Santa Clara, a supplier of
chip-making equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the regional funds make sense from an investment
perspective, they are certainly suited to one purpose: They give
the sales forces at regional brokerage firms and investment banks a
product to pitch to local customers that fund giants like Fidelity
and Vanguard do not offer. Critics say that makes them pure
marketing gimmicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're kind of silly,'' said Russel Kinnel, director of fund
analysis at Morningstar. ``Generally, it doesn't really make sense
to limit an investment to an artificial border. Why settle?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
