<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9445 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BROWN--STOCK-SFCHRON &LR;      04-06 1320
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN--STOCK-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR BROWN HIT PAY DIRT ON 8 IPOS: THE QUESTION IS HOW DID HE  
 GET IN ON SO MANY GOOD DEALS 
 &HT;       BY DAVID LAZARUS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown says he participated in eight
red-hot stock offerings late last year because he had an
arrangement with brokerage Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to pick up
any ``IPO remnants.''
<P>
   If so, the mayor enjoys a highly unusual relationship with his
broker.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, there are no ``remnants'' left over from
much-sought-after initial public offerings of technology and
Internet stocks. Moreover, it is rare, indeed, for an individual
investor to get a taste of such action, let alone to participate in
numerous IPOs during a single four-week period.
</P>
<P>
   ``An individual investor who gets in on a lot of IPOs, that just
doesn't happen,'' said Les Childress of Childress Investment
Research in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are institutions that can't even get in the door on
IPOs,'' he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's investments came to light after the mayor filed a
financial disclosure statement with the city Ethics Commission on
Monday. Because financial reporting laws stipulate only that
investments be listed in broad ranges, the exact amount of the
mayor's investments is between him, his accountant and, eventually,
the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent news reports, including one in The Chronicle, stated
Brown's portfolio was worth as much as $1 million and quoted his
press secretary as saying that he had amassed this fortune
day-trading in his spare time.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Brown's earnings were considerably less, but
the fact remains that Brown enjoyed considerable luck on the IPO
market.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing illegal about participating in so many IPOs.
Nor is there any evidence that Brown has performed favors for
companies in which he holds stock.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the mayor's office denied yesterday that any
connection exists between the mayor's trades with Morgan Stanley
and Brown's 1997 selection of the brokerage to sell $100 million in
bonds to finance a proposed new stadium for the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the question remains: How did he get in on so many new
share offerings?
</P>
<P>
   Stewart Pillette, a San Francisco investment manager, said that
individual investors generally participate in popular IPOs only if
they are preferred clients for an underwriting brokerage and
generate substantial fees from transactions.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Traded With Charles Schwab
</P>
<P>
   In Brown's case, though, he told reporters on Wednesday that
while he maintained an account with Morgan Stanley, he had started
trading online with Charles Schwab because the commissions are
lower.
</P>
<P>
   He was, in other words, a casual customer at best for Morgan
Stanley, which served as lead underwriter for each of the eight
IPOs Brown participated in last year between early November and
December.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the mayor was able to purchase 400 shares of
United Parcel Service on November 9 for $20,000, according to
records released by his office. UPS' stock jumped more than 30
percent in value on its first trading day.
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Brown was given the chance to buy 100 shares of
Microsoft co-founder Paul Allen's Charter Communications for $19 a
share. That stock climbed nearly 20 percent in its market debut.
</P>
<P>
   And about a week later, the mayor scored 100 shares of
Hewlett-Packard spin-off Agilent Technologies for $3,000. Agilent
surged roughly 40 percent on its first day.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; No `Remnant' With Popular IPO
</P>
<P>
   One Wall Street financial analyst who asked that his name be
withheld because ``I don't want to be calling the mayor a liar''
observed that there is no such thing as a ``remnant'' for a popular
IPO.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's a remnant, that means nobody else wanted the shares,''
the analyst said. ``The reason a stock goes up on its first day is
because there are many people who want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he gets most of his stock tips from reading
newspapers and comparing notes with friends. ``It's a lot of fun,''
he said, ``but it drives you crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   A more plausible explanation for his IPO activities may be that
the mayor has a pal at Morgan Stanley who is funneling shares his
way.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Brownie Point Theory
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be that somebody there is trying to win some brownie
points with the mayor,'' said Alexander Paris, a market analyst at
Barrington Research in Chicago. ``Maybe this person is looking at
(managing) the city's pension fund.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley did not return calls on the matter yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative explanation would be that the IPO companies
instructed the underwriter to make shares available to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think anyone who could do this must be really
well-connected,'' said Richard Del Monte, who heads the Del Monte
Group, a financial planning firm in Danville. ``Someone has to be
giving him help.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Brown declined to further discuss his stock trading.
His press secretary said the mayor was ``too busy running the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   One financial analyst who asked to remain anonymous said it is
increasingly common for IPO companies to curry favor with VIPs by
having their underwriter make shares available before trading
commences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's payola,'' the analyst said. ``There's a lot of payola
going on with IPOs. They dole these things out as favors.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; No Connection to IPO Staffs
</P>
<P>
   Brown's press secretary, Kandace Bender, said the mayor has no
relationship, either business or social, with any employees of
companies in which he holds stock.
</P>
<P>
   One New York investment manager who has handled funds for public
figures said Brown misstepped by placing himself in a position
where there is even an appearance of ethical impropriety.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have a blind trust,'' the investment manager said.
``He should have someone manage his money for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm amazed Morgan Stanley didn't tell him this,'' the
investment manager added.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from IPOs, Brown purchased stakes in at least eight other
tech outfits between October 14 and December 9, records show. These
include a $32,000 investment in America Online, a $71,111 stake in
eToys and an $85,380 investment in software-maker Veritas.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 17 publicly listed companies in which the mayor said
he holds stock are based in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Stocks Bought While Campaigning
</P>
<P>
   Most of these stock transactions, by the way, were made as Brown
was embroiled in a surprisingly competitive mayoral election and
subsequent runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Brown declined yesterday to further discuss his stock trading.
But he said on Wednesday that he buys and sells shares just about
every day, although never while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work at work,'' Brown said. ``I'm the mayor at work. I do
this before work. And I have a good friend who is a nut on a
computer. And she's constantly pounding me.''
</P>
<P>
   Angered over news reports that he had made a killing in the
stock market _ reports that wildly exaggerated both the size and
performance of his portfolio _ the mayor volunteered on Tuesday to
show his full stock holdings to The Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, his press secretary, later said Brown actually meant
that he would reveal only the number of shares he bought in each of
the companies listed in his 1999 report to the city Ethics
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said that between October and December of last year, he
invested about $275,000 into the market. He placed his total
earnings at $11,000 _ a mere 4.4 percent gain.
</P>
<P>
   The tech-heavy Nasdaq composite index, meanwhile, rose about 28
percent in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made only 4 percent?'' asked Hugh Johnson, chief investment
officer at First Albany in New York. ``That's pretty poor
performance for what was a big period for tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor needs to get a stock picker on his staff.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at davidlaz &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
