<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-SALARIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOMMAS LET YOUR BABIES LIKE BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
Mommas let your babies like baseball 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For any parents with a secret long-range goal of taking early
retirement and living prosperously off their kids, there was a
clip-and-save item in yesterday's sports section.
</P>
<P>
   Major league baseball salaries now average just under $2 million
a year. That's the average. Almost half the players also earn $1
million or more per season. Paychecks are mushrooming. That average
salary has doubled in eight years, and at the current rate, it will
double again long before 2010. The $20 million-a-season ballplayer
is coming soon. And it won't stop there.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, you are now watching little Hector crawling around
on the floor, a mere toddler. The old American tradition was to
dream the right kind of dreams and provide the right kind of early
guidance for Hector. If all went well, he could grow up to become a
doctor, lawyer or dot.com geek.
</P>
<P>
   But when you combine everything _ the money, the glory, the
first-class travel, the working conditions, and with the strongest
union in the world providing protection _ there is no better way of
life than a major-league baseball player.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks owns the local baseball team. Hicks owns almost
everything else, too. He is big, big business. But baseball?
Nothing in the business world, testifies Tom, compares to the
amount of money it takes to cover payroll expense for a mere 25
employees.
</P>
<P>
   And here's the best part _ I've never known a player yet who
didn't get rich, then immediately provide a financial care package
for dear mom and dear dad.
</P>
<P>
   Even if all this sounds appealing, including the possibility of
early retirement, you are probably thinking it's a tad early for
little Hector, still in his diapers, to be exposed to the game of
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, says Chuck McMichael. Chuck knows, too. Chuck's job is to
find ballplayers, and as the Rangers' director of scouting, he
looks from the high school level on up. In 16 or 17 years, he wants
Hector to be on his short list of prospects, which is the very
first step on the road to baseball riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that can also start right from the cradle,'' McMichael
said yesterday. ``In my opinion, baseball lost a couple of
generations of fans to the other sports, and those fans are the
parents of today. We need parents who will put the miniature bat,
ball and glove right there in the cradle with the baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one, two, three years old, have them throwing the ball,
swinging a bat, whatever. Even encourage them to throw left-handed.
And when they start swinging a little bat, dad or mom might also
show them how to switch-hit. You never know, that could come in
handy later on.''
</P>
<P>
   That's what makes McMichael a darn good scout. He won't leave
even a pacifier unturned in his search for the player of today, or
tomorrow. Granted, the odds are rather staggering on Hector
eventually cashing in off baseball. There are only 750 major-league
jobs in the world, and players from the Latin America countries own
nearly 25 percent of those. That percentage grows each season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last 10 years, we've all seen a dynamic change in the
quantity and the quality of players available for the domestic
amateur draft,'' McMichael said. ``It's a direction our game has
gone, and we've got to change that direction, which to some degree
gets back to the parents becoming baseball fans again.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '50s and '60s, a kid would grow up dreaming about being
a major- league player. Now he might be dreaming more about playing
in the NFL, the NBA, hockey, and so on. Or he might be dreaming
about getting an academic scholarship to a big college, and there's
nothing wrong with that. But the young children of today are
smarter than ever _ they know by elementary school what is out
there in the world, and what's available to them later on. The
choices are many, but in baseball, we often aren't among the
choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why McMichael stresses parental recruitment by the
game. ``The baseball players of today in America are as good as
they've ever been, but there are just fewer of them at all levels,
starting in Little League,'' he said. ``If a country like the
Dominican Republic was involved in our amateur draft, only
California would have more players drafted. That's how much things
have changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the talent search goes on and on as baseball prepares for
the annual amateur draft in June. Yesterday, McMichael was on the
road, traveling to a small town in western Pennsylvania to scout a
high school pitcher. If that particular kid eventually makes the
big leagues, and becomes a success, the formula would have gone
something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``God-given athletic ability, an instinct for the game itself,
and maybe most of all, an unbending desire to reach a goal,''
McMichael said. ``Along the way, the distractions will have been
many, not only from the other sports but from so many outside
influences, some of them good, but some not so good.''
</P>
<P>
   The reward for the successful is the best and most lucrative
work in America. And also, of course, the thrill of buying that
palatial beach home where the parents can immediately retire.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's never too soon for little Hector to be
throwing the ball and swinging the bat. Just remember Chuck's
scouting tip for toddlers _ throw left-handed and swing from both
sides. Even in diapers, there's nothing wrong with gaining the
early edge.
</P>
<P>
   {Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram}. &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
