<HEADER>
A9448 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MUSIC--NET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-06 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC--NET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE WITH A BULLET: BMG TO PUT TOP HITS ON THE INTERNET 
 &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
In a major strike against online music piracy, BMG Entertainment
Thursday said it would start selling downloadable versions of top
hits from major artists on the Internet this summer.
<P>
   BMG became the first of the world's five biggest record
companies to announce specific plans to use the Internet as a new
way to sell music and head off the threat from widely available
programs such as Napster that allow free distribution of legal and
illegal songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're offering them is an effective alternative to the
existing marketplace, which is largely pirated music,'' said Kevin
Conroy, BMG's senior vice president for marketing and new
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're offering an alternative that works and will build what
we believe will be a very significant market for digital
downloading,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy would not disclose prices for the downloadable music. In
the past, BMG has sold singles of its promotional and test
recordings for $1.99 each, with three songs going for $3.49. By
comparison, BMG as well as any major record label typically sells a
CD, which carries a dozen songs, for $15 in a store.
</P>
<P>
   BMG is home to more than 200 labels, such as RCA Records, Arista
Records and Windham Hill, and a stable of popular artists that
includes Christina Aguilera, Santana, Toni Braxton and Lonestar.
</P>
<P>
   Conroy said the company would start offering singles from
as-yet-unspecified artists this summer, downloadable through the
Web sites of the individual labels and Web sites of regular
brick-and-mortar retail record stores.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to quickly expand the number of available
titles and, by the Christmas holiday season, have more full-length
CDs and a ``substantial amount'' of its catalogue &LR;  online.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said other record labels are expected to join BMG in
the world of digital downloading.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest commitment a big-five record label has
made to downloads, especially in terms of offering their most
popular, most lucrative content,'' said Malcolm Maclachlan, a media
analyst for International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to offer older works or `trial tracks' that
expire, quite another to sell current works by the most popular
artists. Others have made noise, but this is the first I know of
the promise of the most popular content.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, the growing popularity of the MP3 audio
compression format to copy and transmit popular songs has seriously
threatened the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the songs now available legally on the Internet in the
MP3 and other downloadable audio formats are either promotional
tracks from major artists or songs from unknown artists.
</P>
<P>
   But illegal copies of top hits are also freely shared and
traded, a process made even easier with consumer-friendly swapping
programs like Napster, which the record industry has so far been
unable to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Industry insiders and observers have long said the only
effective way to control so-called digital piracy was for the
record companies _ indeed, the media and entertainment industry as
a whole _ to offer their own selection of legally downloadable top
hits in a way that remained easy and cheap for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have any hope of stanching whatever losses they
perceive are out there, it has to be done by offering a legitimate
alternative,'' said Mark Mooradian, an analyst with Jupiter
Communications. ``To date, that just hasn't existed.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry, though, has been slow to respond because
its members have not been able to agree on technology to encode
music to prevent illegal copying and distribution.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called backshop digital-rights management technology to
handle this also ensures everyone in the chain, from artist to
retailer, gets their slice of the revenues. It's a tricky procedure
since royalty agreements even for one song can change from country
to country.
</P>
<P>
   Record and technology companies have been discussing those
standards during a yearlong, industrywide effort called the
Strategic Digital Music Initiative (SDMI).
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response to BMG's announcement, but the
other labels have all been taking steps toward offering music
online in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   This week, for example, a unit of Sony Corp., which includes
Sony Music, announced plans to start a company called Label Gate
Co. that will sell music over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Part of BMG's announcement takes the work of the SDMI into the
marketplace without waiting for an industry agreement.
</P>
<P>
   BMG has agreed to use digital-rights management tools made by
several competing companies instead of betting on one. BMG struck
deals with IBM, Santa Clara's InterTrust Technologies Corp.,
Microsoft Windows Media Technologies, Digital World Services and
Reciprocal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, BMG picked Liquid Audio Inc. of Redwood City to
make sure those proprietary and now incompatible tools work with
any format.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they've done is focus on creating a competitive
marketplace and not hand the keys to the kingdom to any one digital
download company,'' said Liquid Audio Vice President Andrea
Flemming.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers will determine the winner in a ``sort of bake-off''
once digital downloading starts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``BMG has been preparing for this for awhile,'' Maclachlan said.
``It will be interesting to see if the solutions they came up with
will work without being too cumbersome and confusing to
consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of BMG07 (107353 ) &QL;
</P>
