<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 NEW YORK: New York elections.
<TEXT>
<P>
   More voters also offered a negative view of Giuliani's record on
education, which Clinton has attacked at almost every opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found evidence of a racial divide in New York City
in perceptions of the Police Department. More than two-thirds of
blacks said that brutality against minorities by the Police
Department was widespread, compared with 23 percent of whites.
</P>
<P>
   In the last Times/CBS News Poll, conducted in February, Giuliani
and Clinton were statistically tied. In pulling ahead, Clinton has
gained support from male voters; the number of men backing Giuliani
has dropped to 43 percent from 54 percent. Her standing among women
has not changed; she is leading Giuliani, 52 percent to 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll came amid clear indications of concern in Giuliani's
camp about the state of his campaign. Thursday the mayor unveiled a
statewide television commercial that featured him campaigning on
Long Island with John McCain, the Arizona senator whose
unsuccessful campaign for the presidency attracted wide attention
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of advertisement that campaigns hold back until
the heart of the contest. And Giuliani's aides said he would step
up his previously lax campaign schedule.
</P>
<P>
   There were notable findings for Clinton as well. In particular,
there was an increase in the number of people who thought she was
spending more time attacking Giuliani than in explaining what she
would do in the Senate. The finding comes after two weeks in which
Clinton has turned up her attacks on Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   For the mayor, the most disturbing news was probably the drop in
his job approval rating in New York City, because his popularity
there has been central to his standing.
</P>
<P>
   In this latest poll, only 32 percent of the New York City
residents approved of the way he is handling his job as mayor. His
previous low point was 42 percent, in a poll conducted by The Times
in March 1999, after the shooting of Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani noted Thursday that his poll numbers had rebounded
after the Diallo episode, suggesting that he had time to recover
again. Still, even Giuliani's supporters have said that the mayor's
handling of the Dorismond case was more problematic, and follow-up
interviews with voters questioned in the poll suggested that a
number had been disquieted by Giuliani's actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still a big fan of Giuliani,'' said Frank Peskio, 57, a
Republican from Ulster County, ``but he's done some things in the
past year that I don't like, especially how he handled the
shootings. Coming up with the guy's criminal record right off the
bat was just totally uncalled for, and he continues to side with
the police all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Fulkerson, 42, a Republican from Suffolk County, said
that he had supported Giuliani early on, but was now having second
thoughts. ``The Diallo case, the Dorismond case _ to me he was very
insensitive to those cases. That rubbed me the wrong way.''
</P>
