<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9450 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH--SFCHRON &LR;      04-06 1182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH--SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE WARY WHEN FRIENDS, FAMILY, BUSINESS ASSOCIATES OFFER
IPO  SHARES 
 &HT;     BY KATHLEEN PENDER
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;         c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Everyone wants to get in on initial public offerings, but unless
you work for the company going public, there are only two ways to
get shares at the offering price. Both can raise ethical questions
if you get them as part of your job or if you're an elected
official.
<P>
   The first way is through a brokerage firm that's in on the deal,
but brokers generally reserve IPO shares for their biggest clients.
San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown says he got in on eight IPOs in
four weeks late last year through his broker, Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. There's nothing wrong with that, but the purchases raised
eyebrows partly because Brown says he wasn't using Morgan Stanley
much, since discount broker Charles Schwab was cheaper.
</P>
<P>
   The other way to get IPO shares is to know somebody at the firm
going public who will put you in the ``friends and family''
program. It's the equivalent of getting your name on the list at a
popular nightclub so you don't have to wait in line with the
masses.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies going public let some or all of their employees
allocate shares to certain people outside the company. These people
get to buy stock at the initial price. Because most IPOs start
trading at a higher price, this almost guarantees a profit if the
investors sell quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, these ``directed shares'' went to 10 or 15 people
who were truly friends and family of the company's top executives.
Today, they might include thousands of people ranging from
hairdressers to business associates.
</P>
<P>
   The phenomenon is growing so rapidly that friends-and-family
shares are becoming a new currency in the Bay Area. Some new
employees even negotiate friends-and-family shares as part of their
employment contracts.
</P>
<P>
   One company originally put 100,000 people _ essentially all of
its customers _ on the list, says Jim Creigh, an attorney with
Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the company was convinced that would be an
administrative nightmare, and pared the list.
</P>
<P>
   When a company offers IPO shares to people in other companies
they do business with, it can look like a gift or bribe. That's why
some companies forbid their employees from taking part in the
programs.
</P>
<P>
   SBC Communications, parent of Pacific Bell, says ``employees
should not participate in IPOs where the offer comes about because
of SBC's relationship to the company or underwriter,'' says
spokesman Selim Bingol.
</P>
<P>
   SBC worries that such programs ``could raise problems with our
code of conflict and possibly insider trading laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems and Hewlett Packard also have banned employee
participation, if it's work related. When Hewlett Packard spun off
its Agilent subsidiary in an IPO, it didn't even offer a
friends-and-family program.
</P>
<P>
   Most companies, however, haven't developed a policy because
until recently, it wasn't an issue. Also, the legal and ethical
questions are anything but clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, IPO shares are not necessarily a gift because they
require an up-front investment and could drop below the offering
price, creating a loss.
</P>
<P>
   And even if they are a gift, it is not illegal to give something
valuable to a person you do business with, as long as the person's
employer knows about it and there are no strings attached, says
Steve Freccero, an attorney with Morison &AMP; Foerster in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   However, offering or accepting IPO shares could in certain cases
violate California's commercial bribery statute.
</P>
<P>
   This law states: ``Any employee who solicits, accepts or agrees
to accept money or anything of value from a person other than his
or her employer ... corruptly and without the knowledge or consent
of the employer, in return for using or agreeing to use his or her
position for the benefit of that other person, and any person who
offers or gives an employee money or anything of value under those
circumstances is guilty of commercial bribery.''
</P>
<P>
   To be convicted under this law, Freccero says, the deal would
have to be made without the employer's consent, and with a quid pro
quo.
</P>
<P>
   If a client or business associate offers you IPO shares, the
easiest way to stay out of trouble is to simply notify your
employer.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of government employees, the laws are even stricter.
Freccero says federal workers ``not only have to avoid conflicts,
they have to avoid the appearance of conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, state and local officials and some employees must
disclose gifts worth more than $50 and are not allowed to accept
gifts from one source totaling more than $300 in one year, although
they can donate such gifts to charity.
</P>
<P>
   However, it is not clear whether stock in an IPO would be
considered a gift. Neither the city nor the state has a rule
regarding IPO shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is called the new economy, and the `new' is in there for
a good reason. It has raised a lot of issues the government hasn't
dealt with before, including this in particular,'' says Marc
Slavin, a spokesman for the San Francisco city attorney's office.
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission has begun to take an
interest in the plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be, you wouldn't get any questions (from the SEC)
about directed share programs,'' says Cori Allen, a partner with
Morrison &AMP; Foerster in Palo Alto. ``But in the last five deals
we've done, we've gotten questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen says the SEC is more interested in procedure than who
participates. ``They want to know how people sign up for the
program, how the company decides who participates and they want to
see the literature related to the program.''
</P>
<P>
   Creigh says companies need to be careful because, by law, a
stock offering can only be made with a prospectus. His firm advises
companies going public to privately come up with a
friends-and-family list, and then turn it over to the brokerage
firm doing the deal and let the brokers send out the proper
documentation.
</P>
<P>
   MORE ON DIVERSIFYING FUNDS: On Wednesday, after the market's
violent swing, I encouraged readers to see how diversified their
mutual fund holdings are and to calculate their exposure to
technology, by looking at each fund's largest stock holdings. The
easiest way to get this information on a large number of funds is
by going to www.morningstar.com.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the fund's name or ticker symbol and scroll down to ``Top
5 Holdings.'' Click on ``View additional holdings information'' and
you'll get a list of the top 25 holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Even more useful is the section right above the top 25 holdings,
called sector weightings. This will show what percentage of the
fund is invested in technology, energy, retail and other
industries.
</P>
<P>
   In the same article, I said that if you are in an S&AMP;P 500 index
fund, you already own a lot of tech stocks, including Intel and
Amazon.com. The latter company is not in the S&AMP;P 500 index.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at kpender &LR; sfgate.com
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
