<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9451 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-YOUTHS--TRAINING-SFCH     04-06 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUTHS--TRAINING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRACKERJACK TRAINING: NONPROFIT GROUP HELPS YOUTHS SHARPEN LIFE 
 SKILLS PITCHING SNACKS AT PACIFIC BELL PARK 
 &HT;     BY JENNIE YABROFF
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
Selling ice cream on a cold, miserable windy night at 3Com Park is
a vendor's worst nightmare.
<P>
   Muma Okochi knew he had to come up with an unusual pitch last
year to get the attention of the baseball fans. That's when the
teenager hit upon the idea. ``I got creative, yelling things like
`Get your nice hot ice cream!' It got people's attention, and it
showed me that the job can be what you make of it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the 18-year-old from Hunters Point was in the
stands at Pacific Bell Park, selling Ben and Jerry's ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   For Okochi, the invaluable work experience as well as the
assistance he got landing an academic scholarship to attend the
University of California at Berkeley this fall has come through the
efforts of a San Francisco nonprofit organization called Juma
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1994 by Diane Flannery, the former executive director
of San Francisco's Larkin Street Youth Center, Juma Ventures
provides at-risk youth from low-income neighborhoods with jobs
selling ballpark concessions.
</P>
<P>
   A steady job is just one of many tactics that Juma uses to move
young people out of poverty. The wide-ranging program also includes
an education component, in which students get tutoring and other
help to finishing high school and apply for college.
</P>
<P>
   Juma also offers money-management programs, workplace mentoring
and career development services. In addition, it provides
internships with multimedia and Internet companies to encourage
participants to seek employment beyond food concessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just having a job (selling ice cream) won't help these kids
make the transition out of poverty,'' said Kriss Deiglmeier, Juma's
chief operations officer. ``The job is a vehicle for impacting
change in all aspects of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   For Okochi, the work opportunity has provided learning skills
that will help him in college and beyond. ``This job teaches you so
much more than working at McDonald's,'' said the youth during
Saturday's Giants exhibition game against the New York Yankees.
Okochi sold more ice cream bars last year than any other
participant in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for Juma was born when Larkin Street's Flannery started
looking for business opportunities for high-risk youth who were
ready to join the workforce. The company bought the Chestnut Street
franchise of the Ben and Jerry's chain in 1994 and recruited
at-risk kids by working with schools and community groups in
low-income neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the company began selling ice cream at 3Com Park. When
the Giants moved to their new park, Juma got the concessions
contract from Pac Bell Park to move with them, adding Tully's
coffee to their concessions. The business expanded to include a
Castro Street location in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Juma's stores and ballpark concessions make enough money to
cover their expenses. The organization also receives funding from
grants and private donors to provide additional services. Juma will
employ 110 young people at Pac Bell Park this summer, many of whom
will return to 3Com Park in the fall to work at 49ers games.
</P>
<P>
   Under Juma's program, first-year employees go through nine hours
of preseason training. The youths can choose between working at
booths inside the park or roaming the stands with insulated freezer
packs of ice cream bars.
</P>
<P>
   Tully's vendors wear ``jet packs'' of hot coffee strapped to
their backs and carry packets of cream and sugar. Booth workers
earn a starting wage of $6.50 per hour, while vendors in the stands
earn $6.50 plus commission, sometimes making up to $25 per hour.
Returning employees can take on added responsibility in
assistant-management positions.
</P>
<P>
   Danielle Lewis, 17, is starting her fourth year with Juma,
having worked her way from being an ice-cream scooper at the Castro
Street Ben and Jerry's to an assistant supervisor of vendors at Pac
Bell Park.
</P>
<P>
   Like Okochi, Lewis comes from a disadvantaged background, and
like Okochi, she is unfailingly positive about her Juma experience,
crediting the company with changing her outlook on life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad attitude problem before I started working here,''
she said. ``The program taught me to maintain my composure, and get
along with all types of people. It built my communication skills
and management skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who attends San Francisco City College, interned at a
multimedia production company last year. She hopes to get a degree
in criminology and plans to pursue a law-enforcement career.
</P>
<P>
   Juma has worked with more than 760 youths during its six years
of operation. Deiglmeier estimated that about 20 percent of
participants drop out of the program and pointed out that the
program is not for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a youth has serious substance-abuse problems, he needs to
get involved with a treatment center. Then after that he might come
work for Juma,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Participants) must be motivated to be employed and making
changes in positive directions. They have to be ready to grab hold
of this opportunity and succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting a new job in an untested venue might seem a daunting
prospect, but none of Juma's employees admitted to feeling nervous
before the Yankees game. That upbeat attitude, Deiglmeier said, is
``key to helping young people envision a future.''
</P>
<P>
   The ice cream stands ran out of every flavor except Cherry
Garcia at the previous evening's game against Milwaukee, but
according to server Edward Johnson, who dropped out of school for
two years before becoming involved with Juma, ``it was no
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who spent his two years out of school caring for his
disabled mother, is back in class at Ella Hill Hutch county
community school. His Juma earnings will go to help his mother,
with additional savings earmarked for the prom. Although he said
selling ice cream is ``a very new experience'' for him, he was
``not nervous at all'' about his new job.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only worries Juma employees own up to are concerns
about rowdiness at the forthcoming opening series with the Dodgers,
who are much hated by Giants fans.
</P>
<P>
   As last Saturday's game neared the final innings and the Yankees
took the lead, Juma workers began closing up shop. Tully's vendors
returned from the stands, unstrapping their jet packs from around
their waists. Ben and Jerry's staff sold a final ice cream bar to a
grateful fan, who said, ``You guys are the best.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the end of 17-year-old Lana Baltodano's first night as a
Juma employee, and although she looked tired as she took off her
teal Ben and Jerry's visor, she said the evening had gone well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not nearly as hard as I expected,'' she said, adding
that she is looking forward to returning to the park for
regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Jennie Yabroff at  &LR; yabroffj &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
