<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0546 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9576 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CONSORTIUM-AD-COLUMN-     04-06 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSORTIUM-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: UNCONVENTIONAL MADISON AVENUE INITIATIVE WINS POSITIVE
REVIEWS
</HEADLINE>
  By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A year after the start of an unusual collaboration between a
giant agency and seven creative ``hot shops,'' the participants are
giving the experiment generally high marks despite some
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   As the consortium, called the Syndicate, begins its second year,
there are changes in the lineup. Two additional small independent
agencies are joining, one that specializes in campaigns aimed at
black consumers and the other the first member from outside the
United States. As they come aboard, one agency is leaving because
of conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   The Syndicate is indicative of the nontraditional ideas being
entertained by the Madison Avenue behemoths as they scramble to
counter the competition they confront from entrepreneurial
upstarts. At the same time, the mainstream agencies acknowledge
that change is easier to advocate than to carry out; after all,
despite the time and treasure devoted so far to the Syndicate, the
only work produced to date that has been approved to appear
nationally was a single print ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hit ratio wasn't great,'' acknowledged Rick Boyko, chief
creative officer at Ogilvy &AMP; Mather North America in New York, the
unit of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide that helped found the Syndicate
in February 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But because ``the goal of this is work that pushes in new
directions, tests the boundaries, we always knew that would be an
issue,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every member of the Syndicate has been tapped for something
and every Ogilvy North America office has used the Syndicate,''
Boyko said, for clients that included Ford Motor, IBM, Seagram and
Sears, Roebuck, ``so from our point of view this has been
resoundingly positive.''
</P>
<P>
   That also appears to be the predominant perspective among the
smaller Syndicate members, which are being compensated with
retainers and other nonequity investments for granting Ogilvy North
America the benefit of their unconventional creative thinking. The
hot shops also gain access to the more substantial resources of
Ogilvy, owned by the WPP Group, in realms like research and media
services as well as an opportunity to work for far larger clients
than their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been going very well,'' said Marc Kempter, managing
partner at Core in St. Louis, one of the seven original dwarfs
recruited by Snogilvy White. ``We worked on a Ford project with
Ogilvy Detroit for a big chunk of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest frustration for us smaller, independent agencies
has been how much slower things move than we're used to, but Rick
told us to expect that,'' he added. ``The kind of clients Ogilvy
works with want presentation after presentation, while we usually
produce work very quickly for our more entrepreneurially focused
clients.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyko identified Core as one of the busiest Syndicate shops,
along with two other charter members, Hunt Adkins in Minneapolis
and Work in Richmond, Va. The others are: Grant, Scott &AMP; Hurley in
San Francisco; Pyro in Dallas; Vitro Robertson in San Diego; and
Wong Doody in Seattle and Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   It is Wong Doody that is leaving the Syndicate, Boyko said,
because that agency is taking part in a review for a large account,
Safeco, that had been handled by an Ogilvy North America sibling,
Cole &AMP; Weber in Seattle. That conflict and the potential for
others, which could impede Wong Doody's growth, led the agency to
withdraw in a decision that Boyko termed amicable.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Wong, chairman and creative director at Wong Doody, said:
``Cole &AMP; Weber is right down the street, two blocks away, and it
was a problem. But for us it was more that it wasn't right for us
at this stage in our growth. And there was a lot of confusion from
people who asked, `Are you owned by Ogilvy?'''
</P>
<P>
   That has not daunted the two new Syndicate members: Fuse in St.
Louis, the multicultural shop that had worked with Ogilvy North
America before joining the consortium, and Rethink in Vancouver,
British Columbia, the first participant not from this country.
Indeed, it was a print ad by Fuse for a big Ogilvy client, IBM,
that is the only Syndicate work that has actually made it into the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ogilvy is trying to get the best resources to fit a brand,''
said Clifford Franklin, president at Fuse, whose clients include
the St. Louis Cardinals and the Schnuck's supermarket chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already starting on a new IBM assignment as well as on
another piece of business,'' he added. ``This has been a great
experience for us.''
</P>
<P>
   That was echoed by Ian Grais, one of three partners who opened
Rethink last fall after leaving Palmer Jarvis DDB in Vancouver,
part of the DDB Worldwide unit of the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the black and don't need the guaranteed revenue,''
Grais said. ``We see this as the chance to work with Rick and
develop closer ties with small agencies we respect in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a chance at bat in the big leagues,'' he added.
``There's always the hope we can hit it out of the park for a big
national American client.''
</P>
<P>
   Grais continued: ``Both sides are maybe using each other a
little bit, but it seems to make good business sense. If Ogilvy
wants to use our name, that's fine. And if the more aggressive
creative we do pushes Ogilvy clients, we can benefit from that down
the road.''
</P>
<P>
   The exchange aspects of the Syndicate may be expanded, Boyko
said, as he is considering a plan by which creative talent from the
smaller agencies ``would spend time here at Ogilvy and vice
versa.''
</P>
<P>
   However Year 2 of the Syndicate turns out, Boyko said, laughing,
one task has already been accomplished: ``We're able to avoid the
`Seven Dwarfs' label, because there are eight of them now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
