<HEADLINE>
U.S. ENERGY FORECASTER CHARTS FLOW OF OIL PRICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.C., La.)   By CARL HULSE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Dispatched to Florida during the fuel-starved
summer of 1979 to coordinate President Jimmy Carter's re-election
effort there, Jay E. Hakes learned first-hand about the volatile
mix of high gasoline prices and politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got down there, the gas lines hit again,'' said Hakes,
an Interior Department appointee at the time. ``Being identified
with the Carter White House, I was the closest target those people
had.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Hakes is deep into another fuel crisis, but this time he is
at the opposite end of the information pipeline. As head of the
federal Energy Information Administration, Hakes is the nation's
chief forecaster of oil prices and supplies, a position that in
recent months has left him dispensing gloomy predictions by the
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last winter has been mainly bad news,'' said Hakes, who
has overseen the agency since the early days of the Clinton
administration.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's decision to boost production did allow Hakes to deliver a
sunnier outlook Thursday as his agency's revised forecast showed
that gas prices will not now hit the unprecedented heights
predicted only last month and instead will average $1.46 per gallon
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are more optimistic today,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A quasi-independent branch of the Energy Department, the EIA
pumps out volumes of data on all types of U.S. energy production,
distribution and consumption. Hakes refers to it as the Census
Bureau of energy.
</P>
<P>
   Such dry, technical expertise is typically relegated to the
bureaucratic background of the capital. But the dramatic run-up in
fuel prices has made Hakes and the work produced by his 370
employees a hot commodity. One congressman recently hailed the
agency as the Paul Revere of rising fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Hakes traveled with Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson to Kuwait and Saudi Arabia, going ``toe-to-toe'' with
Middle Eastern oil analysts who reportedly came away impressed with
his knowledge of their inventories.
</P>
<P>
   He is regularly cited by administration officials as the last
word in price trends, summoned before House and Senate committees
and sought after by reporters. The agency's Web site recorded
35,000 visits in one day, and calls to a fuel hot line doubled in
February as truckers sought diesel price comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some in Congress do not believe the Clinton
administration did enough to sound the alarm about the prospect of
soaring petroleum costs. GOP lawmakers have scolded Hakes and
fellow Energy Department officials for being behind the curve.
</P>
<P>
   Hakes and others, however, say the EIA saw the price spike
coming last October, when its winter fuels report predicted sharply
higher fuel prices ahead, particularly for heating oil and propane.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not quite get the magnitude of it, but we put out
pretty solid warnings,'' said Hakes, who attributed the price climb
to a combination of OPEC production cuts, increased world demand
and low U.S. oil inventories.
</P>
<P>
   Hakes, 55, does not have the resume expected of an international
energy guru. He holds a doctorate in political science from Duke
University and was teaching the subject at the University of New
Orleans before getting involved in Carter's 1976 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   He first joined the Carter administration in the Agency for
International Development due to his expertise in African political
institutions, but he didn't like the job and shifted to the
Interior Department to work on energy issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost an accident in a way, but ever since that time I
have been very involved,'' said Hakes, who went on to run the
Florida Energy Office for then-Gov. Bob Graham and headed Graham's
state operations when the governor was elected senator. He took
over the EIA in 1993 and is the longest serving Clinton
administration appointee in the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   When Congress created the EIA in 1977, it was charged with
providing unbiased energy evaluations no matter who occupied the
White House. Hakes demonstrated his independence in 1998 when the
EIA forecast that energy prices would rise substantially if the
United States complied with an international treaty to reduce
global warming. The finding was at odds with both the White House
and environmentalists who argued the analysis was based on flawed
assumptions and did not account for technological advances.
</P>
<P>
   Hakes said he heard grumbling from the administration but faced
no pressure to revise the outlook.
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is Washington Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers. This article was distributed by The New York
Times News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
