<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BOARD-TECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BOARD SUGGESTS ENDING LINKS AMONG EXCHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX BERENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The torturous process of reorganizing U.S. securities markets
took another turn Thursday when the New York Stock Exchange called
for ending the aging system that provides rudimentary links between
the Big Board, regional exchanges and the Nasdaq stock market.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange also declared its opposition to creating a national
``limit-order book'' that would closely link markets nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board proposes scrapping the two-decade-old
``Intermarket Trading System,'' which it says has become unworkably
complex and is obsolete thanks to proprietary systems that brokers
use to find the best prices across markets.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange's stance was foreshadowed in February when the Big
Board chairman, Richard Grasso, told a Senate Banking Committee
hearing that he was wary of linking to a broader system.
</P>
<P>
   But by so firmly coming out against a central limit-order book,
the exchange appears to be at odds with Goldman Sachs and other big
securities firms, which have called for the Big Board to work more
closely with new electronic networks that match buyers and sellers
directly. A limit-order book is a single system that would allow
traders and investors to buy or sell stock at the best price, no
matter which market is offering that price.
</P>
<P>
   Unless the government requires close links between the new
networks and existing exchanges, trading is likely to fragment
across different markets, and investors will never know whether
they are getting the best prices.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the exchange's announcement Thursday, Goldman
said only that ``we are supportive of the New York Stock Exchange's
reinvention initiative. However, we remain strong advocates of a
level playing field that allows every exchange and qualified
trading venue to compete for best execution through a system of
linkages.'' Other large securities companies did not return calls
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a speech Thursday before the Economic Club of
Washington, Arthur Levitt, chairman of the Securities and Exchange
Commission, also appeared to take a view that differed from that
offered by the Big Board. ``Upstart electronic markets are
leveraging technology to challenge traditional exchanges, using
computers rather than humans to match buyers and sellers,'' Levitt
said. ``A fast expanding web of connections between customers,
brokers, and markets seems destined to weave our many and diverse
markets into a true National Market System.''
</P>
<P>
   In that environment, Levitt said, ``it would be a profound
mistake _ not to mention a dereliction of our statutory duty _ to
permit the isolation of any significant market from the rest of our
National Market System.''
</P>
<P>
   The Big Board highlighted several technological improvements
that it said would help keep the exchange the preferred place for
stock trading by executing small trades electronically and by
giving institutional investors more trading information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
