</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL PLANS EARLY PAYMENTS TO INTERNATIONAL LENDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ In perhaps the strongest sign yet that the
Brazilian economy is recovering from last year's currency crisis,
the country's central bank will repay early a large part of a $41.5
billion emergency loan package provided by the International
Monetary Fund and other lenders.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced late Wednesday, would redeem $10.3 billion
of loans due in October to the IMF, the Japanese central bank and
the Bank of International Settlements. Of the $32 billion offered
by these institutions, Brazil had drawn $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   After April, Brazil will owe $1.8 billion to the IMF and about
$9.5 billion to the World Bank and the Inter-American Development
Bank. These loans, which are considered nonemergency funds, have
lower interest rates and longer maturities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This measure shows that there is no crisis lurking around the
corner for which these funds could have been allocated,'' said
Octavio de Barros, the chief economist here for Banco Bilbao
Vizcaya Argentaria. ``Brazil's risk exposure has simply, and
drastically, been reduced.''
</P>
<P>
   Confounding most analysts' expectations, the economy of Brazil,
Latin America's largest, displayed surprising resilience after
currency devaluation in January 1999. Helped by strong farm
production and a record $30 billion in foreign direct investment,
the economy eked out nearly a percentage point of growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is only recently that data has begun to suggest that
Brazil is on its strongest economic footing in years. Industrial
production and automobile output are soaring while unemployment is
falling. And inflation has been kept in check by an austere
interest-rate policy.
</P>
<P>
   These indicators, combined with the success of President
Fernando Henrique Cardoso's government in raising taxes and cutting
spending, have again made Brazil an attractive destination for
foreign capital.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is following the example of Mexico, Latin America's
second-largest economy, in repaying funds provided by the U.S.
Treasury to ease the peso crisis of 1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``The improved scenario has allowed the financial team to pay
off its obligations early, which is just prudent financial
management,'' said Paul Bydalek, president of Atlantic Rating, a
Brazilian bank-rating company. ``What remains to be seen is whether
this effort pays off as it did for Mexico.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
