A9585 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NH-SUPREME-COURT-975(     04-06 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-SUPREME-COURT-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW HAMPSHIRE DIVORCE BRINGS LOW ITS HIGH COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Add to the casualty list of collateral
destruction by horrible divorces the New Hampshire Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court is in extraordinary crisis. It is temporarily hearing
no cases; its internal practices have been investigated, exposed
and criticized by the state attorney general; its very integrity is
under such fire that the chief justice held a news conference this
week to defend it, and its fate may be at the mercy of the
Legislature, which is expected to vote next week on whether to
investigate possible grounds for impeaching one or more justices.
</P>
<P>
   What precipitated all this was Justice W. Stephen Thayer III's
divorce from his wife, Judith, a former chairwoman of the state
Board of Education, a split so bitterly fought that Thayer appealed
it to her husband's territory, the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Thayer resigned last week in a deal that let him avoid
the criminal charge of improperly trying to influence his
colleagues' handling of his case.
</P>
<P>
   The central question now is not criminal but political: whether
the Legislature, where some members are still furious at the court
for a 1997 decision requiring the state to revamp its school
finance system radically, will come down hard on a court that has
otherwise been long respected. Several lawmakers said the call for
a pre-impeachment type of investigation was likely succeed, but
their responses would depend on the facts that came out.
</P>
<P>
   The main trouble with the court, as detailed in two special
reports by Attorney General Philip T. McLaughlin, was this: On Feb.
4, Chief Justice David Brock told Thayer and his colleagues that he
had appointed two new judges to a special panel that was needed to
hear the Thayer vs. Thayer divorce appeal because the Supreme Court
justices had recused themselves. Thayer, along with another
justice, vociferously objected to one of the judges, George
Pappagianis. Brock then tried to hold back the court clerk from
calling Pappagianis to inform him of his new appointment, but the
clerk already had him on the phone, so the appointment stood.
</P>
<P>
   But the trouble went further. When accusations of Thayer's
interference led to an investigation by McLaughlin, he ended up
accusing the justices of a pattern of commenting to other justices
on cases from which they had recused themselves over personal bias
or potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   The emerging picture ``casts a very serious shadow over the
impartiality and fairness of the process for the litigants,'' said
Richard Hesse, interim dean at the Franklin Pierce Law Center here,
``and certainly does leave a shadow over what we profess is the
central proposition of our legal system, and that is a rule of law,
not a rule of men.''
</P>
<P>
   Many politicians have been quoting the New Hampshire
Constitution lately: ``It is the right of every citizen to be tried
by judges as impartial as the lot of humanity will admit.'' And The
Manchester Union Leader said in an editorial Thursday, ``Even more
than clergy and police, judges need to hold themselves to
unimpeachable standards of conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   While investigating the divorce case, McLaughlin developed a
second central accusation. Thayer had recused himself from a case
involving a lawyer-friend and disclosed _ quite belatedly _ that he
had borrowed $50,000 from him. But he told the other justices that
his friend's opponent deserved harsher punishment than the justices
had given him.
</P>
<P>
   Brock, who a court spokesman said was not available Thursday for
comment, contended at his news conference on Monday that Thayer's
inappropriate statements had had no effect and complained that the
attorney general was suggesting ``that a few minutes of aberrant
behavior by a single justice constitutes the ongoing practice and
procedures of this court.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he said, as he stood flanked by two current and two
retired justices, ``In the collective experience of all the judges
standing here tonight, not one has ever seen any other member of
this court attempt to influence the merits of a decision in which
they were recused.'' Rather, he said, recused judges edited
decisions for things like grammar.
</P>
<P>
   Those statements seem contradicted at several points in the 120
pages of investigative interviews and documents that McLaughlin
released on Wednesday. In particular, an investigator quoted
Justice Sherman Horton as saying that ``another type of comment is
one made by a recused justice who speaks about the result and
offers an opinion about why, as a matter of law, he disagrees with
the result.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice Horton went on to say it's probably not right, but
it's done with a purpose to improve the outcome of the case,'' the
report said.
</P>
<P>
   It also quoted Thayer, who has had no public comments since his
resignation, as saying he was not the only one who made substantive
comments on cases from which he had recused himself.
</P>
<P>
   The report disclosed other highly unjudicious moments. It was
the Supreme Court clerk who set off all the fuss. According to
Brock, when Thayer saw the memorandum that the court clerk, Howard
Zibel, had written to report the ethical lapses, he said, ``If
Zibel files this, it's going to blow up the Supreme Court, and I'm
not going to hang alone.'' Brock also recalled that Thayer said of
the clerk, ``The words `lock and load' come to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   If Thayer's desperation about the divorce comes through in the
reports, so does his colleagues' empathy. Richard Winters, chairman
of the government department of Dartmouth College, agreed that ``in
some sense the court responded to sentiment when they should have
responded as Solomons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very humanizing story,'' he said, ``but you don't want
to humanize the court in this fashion.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Paul Mirski, one of the court's foremost critics in the
Legislature, said that if the report was correct, ``and the judges
did collude, and recused judges participated in the making of
opinions before the court, they're all sort of guilty of
maladminstration, and that's an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire judges are appointed until retirement by the
governor, and can be removed only by the Legislature. Mirski said
justices can also be removed by a less elaborate method known as a
``bill of address,'' under which most anything can be cited as
grounds. Mirski is submitting bills for both impeachment and
address, he said, and the facts that emerge will determine which
fits better.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court, which recently issued a new set of rules on
recusals, has promised a full accounting and response to all the
allegations in the attorney general's report. Political speculation
abounds about what might happen if more justices resigned or were
removed and Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, got to replace them. In
particular, some ask, would that mean the much-disputed 1997 court
decision, which held that the state could no longer pay for its
schools almost entirely through local property taxes, might be
reconsidered?
</P>
<P>
   Come what may, said Marshall E. Quandt, one lesson is already
clear: ``If you're a judge, be nice to your wife.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
