u f BC-SINGTEL-EXPAND-NYT &LR;      04-06 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINGTEL-EXPAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGAPORE TELECOM RENEWS EXPANSION EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ A month after losing a bid to buy Hong Kong's
leading telephone operator to an Internet start-up, Singapore
Telecommunications has renewed an effort to become the first
pan-Asian telecommunications company, this time by turning its
attention to neighboring Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   SingTel, as it is known, said Thursday that it was in talks to
buy a stake in Time Engineering, a financially troubled concern
with valuable telecommunications and Internet interests. It is a
unit of Renong, Malaysia's biggest company.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Singapore company said no definitive agreement had
been reached, it said it was considering a 14.5 percent stake in
Time Engineering for 649 million ringgit, or $171 million. In
addition SingTel said that it was considering buying 40 percent of
Time dotCom, a spinoff of Time Engineering. The deal is subject to
due diligence, and the companies will try to finalize the deal by
early May.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gaining access to Malaysia's $3.4 billion
telecommunications market, such a purchase would allow SingTel to
take advantage of a fiber optic network stretching the length of
peninsular Malaysia from Singapore in the south to Thailand in the
north, where SingTel already owns a stake in a large Thai cellular
telephone operator.
</P>
<P>
   For Time Engineering, which is under court protection from
creditors, the deal would help in repaying part of its $1.3 billion
in debts.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, analysts said the purchase would help SingTel
offset the effects of rapid deregulation in its tiny domestic
market by letting it offer more extensive services elsewhere in
Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The effort by SingTel partly reflects the pressure on
telecommunications companies throughout much of the region, where
deregulation and the convergence of data and traditional voice
communications are forcing them to innovate and expand.
</P>
<P>
   ``What telecom companies are running around struggling to figure
out is how to add value when access prices are plummeting,'' said
Joe Sweeney, director of research at the Gartner Group in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Government-controlled and run by the son of Singapore's former
prime minister, Lee Kuan Yew, SingTel is one of the nation's 10
largest companies and has a $3.5 billion cash pile.
</P>
<P>
   It had hoped to use some of that money as part of an effort to
buy Cable and Wireless HKT of Hong Kong, but in late February was
thwarted by a rival offer from Pacific Century CyberWorks, a Hong
Kong Internet company run by Richard Li, son of the Hong Kong
multibillionaire Li Ka-shing.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Century's offer has become significantly less valuable
since then because of the global rout in technology stocks, which
cut Pacific Century's market capitalization by more than 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no indication that SingTel might renew its effort
to buy Cable and Wireless HKT, however.
</P>
<P>
   SingTel's own stock price has dropped roughly a third this year,
largely because of concerns about the impact of increased
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Singapore government moved up the full
deregulation of its telecommunications market by two years to April
1, issuing 66 licenses for a variety of services that will compete
with SingTel.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, StarHub, a venture among British
Telecommunications, Nippon Telegraph and Telephone and two
government-linked Singapore companies, marked the end of SingTel's
monopoly with a street festival.
</P>
<P>
   SingTel has been fighting back with advertising and rate cuts.
Company employees have been wearing T-shirts that read ``We Are
Ready,'' with the first letters of each word aligned in red to
spell ``WAR.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000406.0553 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE-GIULIANI-NY     04-06 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
  
 McCAIN JOINS WITH GIULIANI FOR NEW TV COMMERCIAL  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's Senate campaign began
broadcasting a statewide television commercial Thursday that
starred the mayor's favorite political dance partner, Sen. John
McCain, and emphasized what the commercial said was Giuliani's
tolerance, truthfulness and humanity.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Giuliani's campaign advisers said the mayor
would campaign upstate at least three days this week and next, and
also appear at an upcoming series of statewide lunches aimed at
shoring up his support among female voters.
</P>
<P>
   The new energy of the Giuliani campaign comes as recent public
opinion polls, including a New York Times/CBS Poll, show the
Republican mayor slipping behind his Democratic opponent, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, after Giuliani's denigration of an unarmed black
man shot dead last month by police.
</P>
<P>
   The television commercial, called ``Integrity,'' was made in
less than 24 hours as a hurried attempt, Giuliani's advisers said,
to stanch the erosion of support. Produced by Adam Goodman, the
mayor's media consultant, the commercial is in effect a 30-second
documentary of a campaign bus trip to Long Island that Giuliani and
McCain made Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Integrity'' opens with a long shot of the traveling bus, cuts
to footage of the mayor and McCain smiling and talking cheerily to
reporters on the VIP Peter Pan coach, then moves to a town hall
meeting at the American Legion post in Northport. There are shots
of grinning veterans, several town hall participants asking
questions, and McCain and Giuliani heartily shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Together, they rode a bus _ to spread a message of hope and
humanity to the people of New York,'' the announcer says in the
opening narration.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who is seeking to appeal to the same independent and
Democratic voters who made McCain, an Arizona Republican, such a
phenomenon in the presidential primaries, was full of praise and
gratitude yesterday for the senator. Although Giuliani endorsed the
state Republican Party's choice, George W. Bush, in the March 7 New
York primary, the mayor infuriated the party by refusing to engage
in hardball tactics against McCain. Instead, the mayor spoke fondly
and often of the senator. McCain has speedily returned the favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used John McCain in my current campaign commercial because
he offered to be used,'' the mayor said at a news briefing at City
Hall. After McCain lost the New York primary and dropped out of the
presidential race, Giuliani added, the senator has ``repeated to me
over and over since then, `I want to help you _ you're my No. 1
priority.'''
</P>
<P>
   The commercial, Giuliani said, is ``not something that I had to
persuade him to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain did not return telephone calls to his office Thursday
seeking comment, but he said on Tuesday that he looked forward to
having Giuliani as a ``soul mate'' in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the commercial, the first that his campaign has
broadcast simultaneously in all major television markets in the
state, ``does not suggest at all that we're not going to campaign
with George W. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor also said he expected ``at some point'' to make a
commercial with Bush. But Giuliani, concerned about Bush's embrace
of religious conservatives, kept his distance from the Texas
governor during the New York primary. Bush is now running behind
Vice President Al Gore in opinion polls in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial seeks to emphasize similarities between Giuliani
and McCain. As the camera moves in for a close-up on McCain, a
former prisoner of war in Vietnam, the narrator says one of the two
men is ``an authentic American hero dedicated to integrity and
reform.'' Then, as a shot appears of Giuliani, speaking in his
shirt sleeves, the narrator says the other man is ``an authentic
New York leader, ready to make a difference for an entire state _
and, the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, the media consultant, said Thursday that he expected
McCain to join Giuliani on the campaign trail again soon and that
the point of the commercial was to show ``two true leaders'' who
``through synergy and by symmetry'' offer ``a fresh approach to
American politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Penn, Clinton's pollster, had a different opinion. ``I
don't think it meets the laugh test,'' he said. ``It runs counter
to everything everyone knows about Giuliani rather than confronting
his problems or the issues. He's pretending they don't exist.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
