u a BC-NY-INDIANS-CASINO-330     04-06 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-INDIANS-CASINO-330&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOHAWKS GET U.S. APPROVAL FOR CASINO IN CATSKILLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES V. BAGLI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Interior Department on Thursday approved plans for a
$500 million casino to be operated by the St. Regis Mohawk tribe in
the Catskills area of upstate New York, where local officials,
hotel owners and many residents have long hoped that gambling might
bring an economic revival to the depressed resort area once known
as the Borscht Belt.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, 30 acres of land next to the Monticello
Raceway in Sullivan County would be put in trust for the Mohawks
for a casino complex.
</P>
<P>
   The plan must be approved by Gov. George Pataki, but after 30
years of efforts to reverse the fortunes of a rural county where
many hotels are shuttered and one-third of the families earn less
than $26,000 a year, proponents said the federal letter of approval
was a huge step forward.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.8-million-square-foot casino complex, which would be 90
miles from New York City, is expected to draw more than 9 million
visitors a year, fueling jobs and businesses in Sullivan County.
Analysts predict that it will hobble the growth of the casino
market in Atlantic City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has said he's supportive of Indian casinos in
traditional resort areas like the Catskills,'' said Michael McKeon,
a spokesman for Pataki. ``But we want to give ourselves a chance to
look over the letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six months, Pataki has come under sharp attack
from anti-gambling forces in New York, as well as from Donald Trump
and other casino operators in Atlantic City. Union activists have
also been critical, because the Indian casino would not be bound by
labor or civil rights laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fun starts now,'' said Rusty Pomeroy, chairman of the
Sullivan County Legislature. ``We're going to make a final push on
this deal. All the anti-casino activists and Donald Trumps will
come out of the woodwork. Albany will be a battleground. If it's
approved, it will spur development the likes of which have never
been seen in Sullivan County before.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It is unconstitutional to operate a casino in New York state,
except on the sovereign land of Indians; the Turning Stone casino,
for example, is operated by the Oneida Nation 30 miles east of
Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   More than four years ago, a group of investors and local
business people in Monticello offered to donate 30 acres to the
Mohawks for a casino project.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawks, in turn, asked the Interior Department to take the
land in trust for the tribe under a seldom-used provision of
federal law. The trust would establish a tax-free sovereign Indian
territory where one did not previously exist. The Mohawks already
have a small money-losing casino at their tribal home on the
Canadian border near Hogansburg, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, Kevin Gover, the assistant secretary for Indian
affairs, sent a letter to Pataki saying that he had determined that
a casino ``would be in the best interest of the tribe and its
members, and would not be detrimental to the surrounding
community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always believed that the merits of the project would
lead to its approval,'' said Robert A. Berman, a financier and
local resident who leads the group that plans to build the casino.
``After close examination of the application and years of review,
it's not surprising that the federal government came to a positive
determination. We hope that Governor Pataki will agree.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement with the Mohawks, Berman's
group would build and operate the casino under a seven-year
management contract giving the tribe 65 percent of the revenue.
That percentage may change as the contract is reviewed by the
National Indian Gaming Commission. The tribe, in turn, would
contribute about $5 million a year to the county.
</P>
<P>
   Berman's partners include Ralph and Joseph Bernstein, developers
based in New York, and Alpha Hospitality, a casino operator.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time in years there's a buzz in Sullivan
County,'' said U.S. Senator Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y., who had
lobbied the Interior Department on behalf of the casino project.
``I'm going to try to persuade the Governor that the state should
stand aside and let it happen. This is the kind of shot in the arm
this area needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a casino in Monticello touched off a land rush
last year, in which politically connected developers spent more
than $40 million snapping up woodland, dilapidated hotels and golf
courses. But little construction followed.
</P>
</TEXT>
