u f BC-ISUZU-LAWSUIT-NYT &LR;      04-06 0563
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISUZU-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY DENIES ISUZU DAMAGES IN LAWSUIT AGAINST MAGAZINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW POLLACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A jury decided Thursday that Consumer Reports
magazine had not defamed and disparaged Isuzu Motors in an article
that called the Isuzu Trooper unsafe because of a tendency to tip
over during sharp turns.
</P>
<P>
   The jury in U.S. District Court here found that Consumers Union,
which publishes the product review magazine, had made false
statements about the Trooper, a sport utility vehicle. But the jury
ultimately ruled for Consumers Union, saying Isuzu had not proved
that the consumer group had acted with malice.
</P>
<P>
   The two-month trial was watched closely because a verdict
against Consumer Reports would have discouraged the media from
publishing negative reviews. It was also of interest to the auto
industry because the greater tendency of SUVs, as compared with
cars, to roll over has become a public safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed victory in the case. Consumers Union does not
have to pay any of the $242 million in damages that Isuzu had
demanded. But the Japanese automaker got some measure of
vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to court asking this jury to find that Isuzu was the
victim of false statements, and the jury so found,'' Christopher C.
Spencer, one of the lawyers representing Isuzu, said after the
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Rhoda H. Karpatkin, the Consumers Union president, said, ``While
we regret that the jurors did not find every one of the 17
published statements under consideration to be fully accurate,
their verdict generally acknowledges the honesty of our testing and
reporting staff and our belief in our procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Reports had rated the 1995 and 1996 Isuzu Trooper ``not
acceptable'' in an October 1996 review, saying it had a tendency to
tip over on two wheels in a driving test. The same vehicle was also
sold as the Honda Acura SLX.
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu charged Consumers Union with product disparagement and
defamation, arguing that it had essentially rigged the tests to
produce an attention-grabbing story and to further its campaign to
have the federal government mandate safety standards to reduce the
potential of the vehicle to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union maintained that it told the truth and that its
tests were valid. But the group also argued that its statements
were opinion, which cannot be proven true or false and which
deserve protection under the right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Because the judge, Richard A. Paez, had previously ruled that
Isuzu was a public figure, the automaker not only had to show that
the Consumers Union statements were false and that they had damaged
Isuzu. It also had to prove that Consumers Union had acted with
actual malice, meaning that it either knew its statements were
false or had reckless disregard for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found that in seven of the eight false statements,
malice could not be proved. In the eighth, in which Consumers Union
had said that the cars should never have been allowed on the road,
the jury found that Consumers Union had spoken with reckless
disregard for the truth. However, it found that Isuzu was not
damaged by that statement.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers Union, a nonprofit organization, still faces a lawsuit
filed by Suzuki Motor Corp. over a similar article on the tendency
of the Suzuki Samurai to tip over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-06-00 2330EDT &QL; 
