u f BC-QXL-STOCK-NYT     04-06 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QXL-STOCK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES OF BRITISH WEB AUCTION COMPANY LEAP
</HEADLINE>
 By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shares of QXL.com, a British Internet company, soared 132
percent Thursday after an analyst for one of the brokerage firms
that underwrote QXL's offering six months ago forecast that the
shares would rise more than tenfold.
</P>
<P>
   QXL.com leaped $29.484375, to $51.984375, in Nasdaq trading,
after trading as high as $117.375. Thomas R. Bock, an analyst for
SG Cowen, released a report saying that QXL.com was set to become
the dominant Internet auction company in Europe and that its price
could reach $330 within 30 months.
</P>
<P>
   The combined volume in London and Nasdaq trading Thursday
slightly exceeded the number of shares in public hands.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the investment opinion could not have been better
for some of the insiders at QXL.com, whose shares had been sliding
for the last month amid a general setback for European Internet
stocks. The lockup period, during which insiders were barred from
selling shares, ends Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday was also the day that a three-for-one split of QXL.com
shares took effect.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Thursday night, Bock said he had
released the report Thursday because ``that is when I got done with
it.'' He said he was unaware of the lockup expiration. ``I took a
fundamental analysis of the company,'' he said. ``Lockup periods
are not something I analyze.''
</P>
<P>
   The shares that trade in New York are depository receipts, equal
to five common shares as traded in London.
</P>
<P>
   QXL.com went public last October when it offered depository
receipts at $5.38 each, adjusted for Thursday's split. The
prospectus for that offering said that insiders would be free to
begin selling part of their holdings ``beginning on the date six
months after'' the shares were admitted to trading on the London
Stock Exchange. They began trading in London on Oct. 7. The lead
underwriter for the offering was Credit Suisse First Boston, with
Cowen one of three co-lead firms.
</P>
<P>
   Bock, who is 28, joined Cowen in February after being part of
the Internet analysis team at PaineWebber. ``He has U.S. Internet
experience and is looking at European Internet properties,'' said
Robert Lewis, a managing director of Cowen and head of its global
technology research group. ``We're thrilled to have him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bock is based in New York, but is planning to move to London
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Lockup provisions are common in initial public offerings,
providing some assurance to buyers that the supply of shares will
be restricted for some period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
