<HEADER>
A9605 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS &LR;      04-06 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEGOTIATIONS BREAK DOWN IN ELIAN CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
and ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Immigration officials on Thursday shut down
negotiations with family attorneys hours after Juan Miguel Gonzalez
of Cuba arrived in the United States and demanded the return of
Elian, his 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   In their decision to terminate discussions that spanned over
five days, government officials delivered a devastating blow to
efforts by the boy's attorneys who have been embroiled in a custody
battle over the child.
</P>
<P>
   Immigration officials refused to concede to any demands made by
attorneys involving the transfer of custody of the boy, the Miami
attorneys said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wallis, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service in Miami, said U.S. authorities were ``very
disappointed'' at the position taken by Elian's Miami relatives
after talks between the two sides foundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We urge everyone to put the well being of Elian before all
else in this process,'' Wallis said. ``We will soon provide the
relatives with a letter, setting forth the process for reuniting
Elian with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   After Gonzalez's long-awaited arrival to the United States,
tensions mounted in Miami. By evening, more than 300 people were
protesting in the Little Havana community where Elian is staying
with his great-uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez. More than 200 people marched
in a raucous but orderly demonstration.
</P>
<P>
   In a defiant statement shortly after he stepped off the plane
from Havana, Gonzalez _ with his second wife and baby son _ said
the custody battle over Elian has been ``an agonizing experience''
because he has seen him ``submitted to cruel psychological
pressures aimed at influencing his personality already weakened by
the terrible trauma'' of losing his mother.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said the pressures on the child by his Miami relatives,
Cuban exile leaders, U.S. politicians and the media amount to
harassment and has contributed to tension in Miami's Little Havana,
where Elian has been staying.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last few days, my family and I have been alarmed to see
the pressure exacerbated in Miami and dangerous displays that make
us fear for the safety of my son,'' said Gonzalez, referring to
protesters, who earlier this week broke through police barricades
around the home of Elian's great uncle, Lazaro Gonzalez, and vowed
not to allow Elian's return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian's been paraded and exhibited in public rallies and by
the media with a clear intent to obtain political advantage (over
Cuban leader Fidel Castro) from this tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am truly impatient to have him returned to me as soon as
possible and go back to Cuba together immediately,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   He signaled that he is willing to remain in the United States if
necessary to allow the case to be settled in court as long as he
can be reunited with his son and be allowed to care for him.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said Thursday the arrival of Gonzalez should
be ``a big help'' in resolving the controversial custody case.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the rule of law will prevail in this country,''
Clinton told CBS News anchor Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, a member of the relatives' legal
team, angrily denounced the U.S. government, saying the talks had
ended with Immigration and Naturalization officials willing to
discuss only how _ not whether _ to transfer Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys had asked for an independent panel of three
psychologists to determine how Elian would be affected by being
returned to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   More disappointing, the attorneys said, was the government's
refusal to guarantee that the boy will remain in the United States
while his appeals are pending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that any clear-minded person will realize that these
conversations should never have gotten to this point,''
Garcia-Pedrosa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, the government would not guarantee to us,
even if we made an agreement with them, that the father, Juan
Miguel, would not take the child to Cuba right away, even during
the pendency of an appeal. The government rejected the standard of
the best interest of the child.''
</P>
<P>
   What remains unclear, however, is how and when the transfer of
custody will take place.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said that reuniting Elian
with his father ``is not only a matter of federal law ... it is
simply the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder said Attorney General Janet Reno would likely meet Friday
with Gonzalez to hear ``his concerns.'' He said Reno hopes to
secure a legally binding commitment from him to remain in the
United States until the court appeals process pursued by the Miami
relatives has run its course. A hearing has been scheduled in early
May.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Holder said, every effort will be made to
ensure that father and son are reunited _ if not in Miami or
Washington, then in some other location that both sides agree on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
