<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING A GOOD THING GOING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Every challenge put before the Los Angeles
Lakers has been mowed down in rapid succession, leaving them but
one feat to achieve in the regular season:
</P>
<P>
   Stay focused with nothing left to play for.
</P>
<P>
   At 64-12, the Lakers have clinched the best record in the NBA
and homecourt advantage throughout the playoffs, with six games to
play. ``This makes it easier, actually, if guys can take a
breath,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``We're not going to let up on
our push to stay the top team and keep our winning going. But we
will reduce some guys' minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson now has the luxury of resting his older veterans (Ron
Harper, A.C. Green) and his big-minute stars (Shaquille O'Neal,
Kobe Bryant). But the Lakers want to maintain their intensty, too,
a task that will be made easier by the caliber of opponents: San
Antonio twice, plus Seattle, Sacramento and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once you get out there and play, you're not thinking about
anything, just thinking about the game, thinking about the the
competition, the moment,'' Bryant said. ``Our intensity comes from
our execution. We have to shift our mindset to that. Just improve
our execution, because playoff time, that's what counts. . . . I
think that's what should be our motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher said several Lakers are banged up and can use the
well-earned rest. Robert Horry, whose sore knees forced him out of
Wednesday's game, is day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think now realistically, coach can kind of maneuver his
rotation, maneuver certain ways that we play the game, make sure
that everybody's not necessarily rested but at least healthy going
into the playoffs,'' Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' last two victories, at Golden State and Phoenix,
were anything but smooth, requiring huge production from O'Neal (81
points) to offset 40 percent shooting from the rest of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shots just aren't going down,'' Fisher said. ``You start to
feel really weary in the legs about this time. It really gets
mentally tough to just bring it every single night and physically
get yourself going. You could tell we were dragging (Wednesday).
Hopefully, we've got these good quality teams coming and four games
at home, we'll be able to play with a lot more energy and kind of
get things going back in a more positive direction.''
</P>
<P>
   One last note on the homecourt advantage: In the last 20 years,
the team with the best record has gone to the finals 15 times.
Eleven of them won the championship.
</P>
<P>
   __ Milestone watch: If nothing else, the Lakers can continue
their season-long task of rewriting record books.
</P>
<P>
   At 27-1 since the All-Star break, the Lakers need just four wins
in the final six games to record the best post-All-Star winning
percentage (.912) in NBA history. Utah holds the mark, at .886
(31-3) in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' 64 wins are already the franchise's best since
1986-87, when the Lakers went 65-17 on the way to the championship.
With a 5-1 record down the stretch, they can tie the 69-win season
posted by the 1971-72 Lakers, who also won the title.
</P>
<P>
   And of course, a sweep of the last six games would extend their
winning streak to 17 and make them only the second team in history
to reach 70 wins. Only Jackson's 1995-96 Chicago Bulls (72-10) have
done it.
</P>
<P>
   __ Playoff tickets: Tickets for all Lakers playoff games go on
sale Saturday at 10 a.m. Tickets are available at the Staples
Center box office, with a limit of four per person, per game.
Random priority numbers will be distributed at 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets also will be available at all Ticketmaster locations and
by phone: 213-480-3232, 805-583-8700 or 714-740-2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
