<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE METS ARE STRUGGLING, ESPECIALLY WHEN IT COUNTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the New York Mets were shut out on Wednesday
night, one San Diego Padres coach noticed, it was obvious they were
not swinging the bat well. Some pitches that should have been
crushed turned into meek outs, and the Padres were hopeful that
trend would continue one more night. A lineup like the Mets', the
coach said, was not likely to struggle for long.
</P>
<P>
   But it is struggling now, and the rest of the team's play isn't
much better.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres beat the Mets Thursday night, 8-5, at Shea Stadium.
The Mets' starting lineup had only three singles, and the team's
batting average now stands at .193. Their No. 1 starter, Mike
Hampton, was not sharp for the second start in a row, failing to
get out of the sixth inning. And the Mets' defense made two errors,
leading to three runs for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego right-hander Matt Clement presented the Mets with
a different look from the finesse starters who befuddled them in
the first two games of this series. But the result was the same.
The Mets could not touch Clement, who was overpowering for six
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Only when Manager Bobby Valentine started inserting
pinch-hitters did the Mets' offense begin to stir, and by then the
Padres had a seven-run lead. With two outs in the seventh, Kurt
Abbott and Jay Payton singled, and Melvin Mora was hit by a pitch
to load the bases. The Mets got one run on a bases-loaded walk by
Edgardo Alfonzo, but Mike Piazza flied out to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   That made the Mets hitless in their last 24 at-bats with runners
in scoring position. Their last hit in that situation was the grand
slam by Benny Agbayani that won the second game in Tokyo last week.
</P>
<P>
   It was Agbayani who ended the Mets' futility Thursday night,
lining a pinch-hit double that scored Todd Zeile in the eighth.
Todd Pratt, the backup catcher, hit a three-run homer in the ninth
in his first at-bat of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by 2-0 in the fifth inning Thursday night, the Mets
started a rally in spite of themselves. With Rey Ordonez on first
and nobody out, Hampton failed on three attempts at a sacrifice
bunt. He ended up blooping a curveball into left field, giving the
top of the Mets' order a chance to drive in Ordonez from third.
</P>
<P>
   But Rickey Henderson grounded to third, and Ordonez was caught
in a rundown for the out. Then Darryl Hamilton grounded to first,
trapping Hampton in a rundown. Alfonzo grounded to short for the
final out.
</P>
<P>
   That was Clement's game: ground balls. He throws a sinking
fastball and a slider with dramatic movement, pitches that draw
frequent comparisons to those of Kevin Brown, the Los Angeles
Dodgers' ace. The assortment gets Clement a lot of ground balls,
and no National League starter averaged more double plays per nine
innings last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, who had never faced Clement, are the kind of team that
struggles against him: They have only two left-handed hitters in
their lineup, and Clement held right-handers to a .235 average last
year. The Mets had trouble driving anything off him, grounding out
12 times, striking out seven times and flying out just once.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres increased their lead in the sixth inning. Ordonez,
who did not commit an error in his final 100 games last year, made
his second error this season, overthrowing Zeile at first base
after fielding Ruben Rivera's leadoff grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera scored when Bret Boone rapped a single through the right
side of the infield, where Alfonzo, the second baseman, was
shifting to cover second on a hit-and-run. A sacrifice fly by Ed
Sprague brought home the fourth run, and Hampton left after walking
the next hitter. He walked three Thursday night after walking nine
in his first start.
</P>
<P>
   The night turned ugly for the Mets the next inning. With a
runner on second and two outs, Eric Owens lofted a ball to
right-center field that fell between Hamilton and Bell, who both
dived for it. Bell scurried over to get the ball, then overthrew
Alfonzo for an error, allowing Owens to circle the bases.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
