<SLUG> BC-GEN-MEDIA-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KMPC IS BACK BUT AS A GHOST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Afraid of ghosts? Not at One-On-One's all-sports
radio station 1540.
</P>
<P>
   Starting tonight at midnight, KCTD-AM will go back to the future
and change its call letters to KMPC, the latest nip and tuck of a
facelift that it hopes will give it a more feel-good acceptance in
what's again becoming a crowded and evolving Los Angeles
sports-radio market.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 50 years, Gene Autry's station on 710-AM went by
the KMPC brand, spinning pop music and later country music with
Dick Whittinghill and the Angels, Rams and UCLA games. But one of
the last attempts to save it was a format change to all-sports back
in the mid '90s with such on-air personalities as Joe McDonnell,
Jim Lampley, Brian Golden, Paola Boivin, Todd Christensen and Fred
Wallin.
</P>
<P>
   After bumbling decisions by station management, that version of
KMPC collapsed and was eventually sold off to Disney and the call
letters were ``retired'' when they the format changed to kids
programming.
</P>
<P>
   KCTD has brought them out of retirement, a process as simple as
buying them from the FCC for about five figures, said Nancy Cole,
the vice president and general manager of 1540.
</P>
<P>
   Cole, who has 22 years in L.A. radio, including the old KMPC,
says the the name is ``the most recognizable call letters in the
country. It has an incredible sports heritage in Los Angeles. And
the reaction we've had from making this change and bringing back
that name has really been positive.''
</P>
<P>
   For Cole, who came over to run 1540 a year ago, a positive image
keeps with her philosophy of how sports should be presented and how
it'll be successful in this market.
</P>
<P>
   She helped launch all-sports AM-1150 two years ago as the sales
director but became discouraged when the ``guy talk'' sophomoric
approach taken by the show's hosts (read in: she had a tough time
selling it to advertisers) began to drag the format down.
</P>
<P>
   As a single parent rearing two kids in Valencia one of them grew
up to be Campbell Hall's Larry Cole, the Daily News volleyball
player of the year in '98, who went on to UCLA Nancy Cole was a
believer in how sports provided a positive foundation for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not about showing Dennis Rodman facing a wall (at a urinal
as in the 1150 billboards and ads for the new morning show) and
thinking that's funny,'' said Cole. ``Why not appeal to a higher
common denominator? If I can help lift sports to a higher standard,
why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``At our station, the sports and the games are the stories, not
so much the personalities.''
</P>
<P>
   The One-On-One Sports Radio Network, based in Chicago, owns 1540
as well as stations in New York and Boston. It also broadcasts its
lineup that includes Jay Mariotti, Peter Brown and Joe Chevalier on
more than 425 affiliates.
</P>
<P>
   ``The criticism that we don't have a local show at least not yet
fails to take into account that because we're a network, we have a
travel budget that a local sports station can't possibly
maintain,'' said Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, 1540 has added the Arena Football League's Avengers
games, continues to act as a spillover station for the Angels and
USC football, is considering airing special events like auto races
and could begin rights-fee negotiations with other teams in the
future. It also increased its local sports reports to three times
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   It plans a move from its Burbank offices to Santa Monica by the
end of the year and has been looking into adding a local
sports-talk show. Who would host it? Refer to the list of the usual
suspects.
</P>
<P>
   And by the end of 2000, more changes will happen in this market.
In June, Fox Sports Radio Network and Sherman Oaks-based Premier
Radio will be have programming available for 1150's KXTA-AM, but
there's no guarantee that station will stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Most insiders are convinced that KXTA will merge programming
with KLAC-AM 570, creating a Lakers-Dodgers station, and possibly
move over to KFI-AM 640 for its 50,000-watt signal. All are
stations currently owned by the same group, Clear Channel.
</P>
<P>
   __ More female influence: The first woman driver at the
Indanapolis 500: Janet Guthrie, in 1977. So, if we're adding this
up right, it only took ABC 23 years to put its first female on the
marquee telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Gudel, the former anchor and reporter on Prime Ticket
``Press Box'' four years ago, will join the ABC's May 28 event as a
reporter keeping viewers up on the garage areas, hospital, talking
to drivers, owners, mechanics even some celebs. She'll start with
ABC's coverage of the Indy time trials May 20-21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea I was the first female until I read that
yesterday,'' said Gudel, who left L.A. in Oct. '96 after a year and
a half and eventually joined Philadelphia's Comcast Cable Sports
News show in October '97 as the city's first female sports anchor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe because there are so many women doing sports now, I
didn't think there were any `firsts' anymore. I went through the
same thing when I came here, so when it happens again, I think
everyone else makes more of it than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA grad has a two-year deal with ABC Sports after
impressing them with her sideline reporting during the recent
college football season. That included working the Fiesta Bowl as
well as the Wisconsin-Iowa game, when Ron Dayne broke the NCAA
career rushing record and clinched the Rose Bowl berth for the
Badgers.
</P>
<P>
   She's been most familiar with motor-sports viewers because of
her work on The Nashville Network's ``NASCAR Garage'' for the last
few years.
</P>
<P>
   __ A backup plan: If Tiger Woods by some miracle doesn't win
this weekend at Augusta, storyline No. 2 that CBS will pray for
during its 45th straight year of Masters coverage will be gasp a
Greg Norman victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg's performance since he arrived at Augusta in '81 has
played out closer to a Greek tragedy than anything we've seen in
sport,'' said CBS's Jim Nantz, on his 15th Masters telecast, 12th
as the host. ``If he was to ever find a way to win this, it would
be perhaps be the most emotional scene that golf would has ever
known.
</P>
<P>
   ``He rides into town this week with a lack of fanfare that's
very healthy. I wouldn't put it past him to be in contention for
the elusive green jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, with Sean McDonough finally out of the picture, CBS
has juggled its Masters' hole-coverage assignments again, moving
Bill Macatee into the lineup. Macatee, the USA Network coverage
host Thursday and today, will be at the 14th hole with Verne
Lunquist assigned to the 16th tower that McDonough kept warm since
the ouster of Gary McCord six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And covering his first Masters for the network, Dick Enberg will
do the interviews from Butler Cabin and wrap up the event Sunday
with one of his perceptive essays.
</P>
<P>
   __ Why it works: Every year, someone's going to complain about
the tight restrictions that the Masters committee puts on the
television people, such as no course reporters, no cameras on the
front nine, only four minutes of commercials per hour.
</P>
<P>
   But CBS continues to abide and thrive with these restrictions.
So why don't they try the same format with every PGA telecast?
</P>
<P>
   ``(Based on rights fees), we certainly wouldn't be able to be
competitive and responsible financially with our PGA Tour
relationship if we have only four minutes of commercials every
hour,'' said CBS Sports chief Sean McManus. ``The business model
used with the PGA isn't true here because the quality of the
coverage and the unique nature of this event is the model used
here.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT SMOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Back in the saddle: After three years at ESPN, Bill Seward,
one of TV's most knowledgeable horse guys, has returned to Santa
Anita to host the feature race every Saturday afternoon on KCBS
Channel 2's ``SportsCentral,'' which will be produced by the Santa
Anita Broadcast Center. First up: Next Saturday's Las Cienegas
Handicap race.
</P>
<P>
   __ KCBS adds two interesting golf shows as lead-ins to the
network's Masters coverage Saturday and Sunday particularly one
called ``The Life and Times of Bobby Jones'' narrated by Sean
Connery on Sunday at 11 a.m. But don't overlook the History
Channel's two-hour presentation of ``Golf: Links in Time,''
Saturday at 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Attention those who tend to follow the plotlines of ``Relic
Hunter,'' ``Zena: Princess Warrior,'' ``Le Femme Nikita,'' ``VIP''
and/or ``Cleopatra 2525'': The E! Channel has ``Inside Rollerjam:
The Women of Roller Derby,'' Sunday at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ The old college try: The two weekend games of the USC-UCLA
baseball series are on Fox Sports Net (1 p.m. Saturday) and Fox
Sports Net 2 (1 p.m. Sunday). In between, it's the NCAA hockey
final (ESPN, 4:30 p.m. Saturday). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WHAT CHOKES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   __ Tonight's Dodgers-Mets game . . . no TV? Oh, right. KTLA
needs that window for the ``Fresh Prince'' back-to-back re-runs and
Fox Sports West 2 has a Ducks game.
</P>
<P>
   __ Why would the horse racing establishment allow ABC to run a
one-hour package of the Blue Grass Stakes, the Wood Memorial and
Arkansas Derby go head-to-head with Fox's live coverage of the
Santa Anita Derby Saturday at 2 p.m.? Did someone miss a meeting?
</P>
<P>
   __ KCAL Channel 9 might have been excited to be doing the Angels
2000 opener Monday, but doing a live interview with the guy holding
his trained eagle meant that the game going on the background
became an endangered spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   __ And they've decided thatAl Michaels' partner will be . . .
Mary Hart. Oh, wait. That's for Saturday's ABC coverage of the
``Michael Douglas and Friends'' nine-hole celebrity golf
hack-a-thon taped in Palos Verdes. Douglas' pals: Sidney Poitier,
James Woods, Joe Pesci and, of course, Kenny G. Put us in charge of
this show and we'd call it ``Michael Douglas and Fiancee,'' then
not only do we watch, but we're making tapes of it for our friends.
</P>
<P>
   __ Can someone explain the concept of the Clippers'
fourth-quarter replay on Fox Sports Net 2? Maybe a first-quarter
replay, when at least the score started out 0-0. Or a
second-quarter replay. By the time the fourth quarter crawls
around, Kareem is transcribing notes for his next book, the
janitors are standing next to the team bench jangling the ring of
keys to Staples Center exit doors, like an employee at a real
Staples store waiting for the last customers at 10:15 to finally
quit picking over the scotch-tape bin and get the heck out. This is
more brutal than watching a Discovery Channel special when a pack
of hyenas are done picking over a zebra carcass trying to fend off
the vultures. At least rename this ``When Opposing Teams Attack.''
Tonight at midnight, this futile exercise continues. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
