<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GENERAL-SEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHARGES OF HARASSMENT BY A GENERAL  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, April 7:
</P>
<P>
   The sexual harassment charges filed by Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy,
the U.S. Army's highest ranking woman, against a male general shows
that much more needs to be done to end harassment in the military.
The case is particularly embarrassing to the Army because Kennedy
is one of only three women in the armed services who are three-star
officers, and the accused officer, Maj. Gen. Larry Smith, was
appointed last summer to be the Army's deputy inspector general, a
post that investigates allegations of sexual misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   Military leaders have properly put Smith's transfer into that
post on hold as an investigation continues. The case is complicated
by the fact that the alleged unwanted sexual advance occurred in
1996 but Kennedy did not pursue formal action at that time.
Instead, she complained informally to her superiors, perhaps in an
effort to avoid ruining another officer's career. It is unclear how
the situation was handled or resolved. She decided to file a formal
complaint last year when Smith was assigned to the inspector
general's office.
</P>
<P>
   The matter is reminiscent of the case involving Maj. Gen. David
Hale, who had also been appointed deputy inspector general when he
was accused of sexual misconduct with the wives of several
subordinate officers. Hale was allowed by the Army to retire
quietly when the complaint first surfaced. But ultimately he was
charged with misconduct, pleaded guilty and was demoted one rank.
</P>
<P>
   A thorough investigation in this case should determine the
merits of the complaint and whether any top officers involved in
Smith's appointment knew of Kennedy's informal accusation. If so,
officials need to determine whether Kennedy _ the only woman among
the Army's 45 three-star generals _ was given an opportunity to
object to Smith's new assignment. Just because an original
complaint was informally handled does not justify ignoring it
completely. The military may need to develop a way to allow
informal complaints to be considered and resolved prior to
promotions or new appointments.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen has said that the armed forces
will not tolerate any form of sexual harassment. This latest
episode shows that the Army needs to review how it responds to all
harassment complaints, whether formal or informal.
</P>
<P>
   The Army must show that it is prepared to respond strongly and
appropriately every single time. It must also prove to a skeptical
public that it will respond harshly if there is any evidence that
charges of harassment were improperly ignored.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
