u a BC-TERROR-BOUNTY-SPI &LR;      04-06 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERROR-BOUNTY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. PUTS $5 MILLION BOUNTY ON SUSPECTED BOMB PLOTTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SAM SKOLNIK  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The federal government has placed a $5 million bounty on an
Algerian man accused of playing a key role in a plot to smuggle
explosives into Washington state four months ago.
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials yesterday offered the reward to
anyone providing information leading to the arrest and conviction
of Abdelmajid Dahoumane.
</P>
<P>
   The failure to capture Dahoumane has frustrated federal
prosecutors and law enforcement officials, who consider him an
important link in an alleged plot to bomb U.S. buildings and
landmarks.
</P>
<P>
   Dahoumane and another Algerian, Ahmed Ressam, were indicted Jan.
20 by a Seattle federal grand jury on charges that they conspired
to commit acts of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department is backing its bounty on Dahoumane with an
advertising campaign of posters and fliers printed in French and
English that will be distributed throughout the United States,
Canada, Europe and Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Dahoumane is also wanted in Canada for allegedly making bombs
with Ressam, who was arrested by U.S. border agents at Port
Angeles, Wash., after they found explosives and timing devices in
his rental car.
</P>
<P>
   Dahoumane, 33, has lived in Canada, Germany and Algeria. The FBI
got a tip that he was spotted at the Bellingham, Wash., airport
less than a week after Ressam's Dec. 14 arrest, but State and
Justice Department officials said yesterday his current whereabouts
are unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Laine, a spokesman for the State Department's Diplomatic
Security Service, which issued the bounty, would not say why
federal authorities chose now to make the offer. ``We worked
closely with the FBI and the Canadian government and law
enforcement, and we believed this was the best time to proceed,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go under the assumption'' that Dahoumane is
dangerous, Laine added.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Malkin, spokesman for Seattle-based U.S. attorney Kate
Pflaumer, said offering a multimillion-dollar reward ``is not an
uncommon thing in certain high-profile cases. If it were to lead to
his capture, it would be a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dahoumane is not the first man to have had a $5 million U.S.
government bounty placed on him.
</P>
<P>
   The Diplomatic Security Service has launched reward campaigns
aimed at terrorists in 16 different instances. The bounty is
increased to $7 million in skyjacking cases, the maximum allowed
under federal law.
</P>
<P>
   Others making the $5 million list include Osama bin Laden,
indicted as the mastermind of the 1998 bombings of the U.S.
embassies in Tanzania and Kenya. The same bounty was placed on the
Libyan men charged in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 over
Lockerbie, Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the program, Laine said the government has paid
out more than $6 million in reward money since 1995. One notable
success was the case of World Trade Center bomber Ramzi Yousef,
arrested in Pakistan off a tip and ultimately convicted in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   In connection with the alleged bomb plot involving Dahoumane and
Ressam, Montreal resident Mokhtar Haouari and Abdel Ghani Meskini,
both Algerians, were charged in New York in January with providing
support to terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents have described the men as being a cell of the
militant Armed Islamic Group. The group, which goes by its French
acronym, GIA, blames the United States for its support of the
ruling regime in Algeria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
