<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-06 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     04-06 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ They call him the Cisco Kid, but Francisco Cordova is
hardly a friend to the Astros.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cordova took the Astros on a little trip down memory lane _
well, actually it was more like a hijacking _ holding them hostage
while he flirted with a no-hitter in the Pittsburgh Pirates' 10-1
victory Thursday afternoon at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Mitch Meluskey's one-out double in the eighth inning ended
Cordova's no-hit bid and put to rest any thoughts of deja vu. The
last time the Astros had a no-hitter tossed against them, it was at
the hands of Cordova and reliever Ricardo Rincon in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably the third-best game he's pitched against
us,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said of Cordova, who held the
Astros to a run on two hits in eight innings. ``That gives you an
idea of how good he's been against us. He's a tough pitcher to
beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova is 6-2 with a 2.78 ERA in 16 career appearances (11
starts) against the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably send a limo every time we're in town,'' Astros
first baseman Jeff Bagwell said.
</P>
<P>
   The Groundhog Day feeling didn't end with Cordova's flirtation
with a no-hitter. There was also Chris Holt getting bare-bones run
support in his first start of the season _ which was the case in
far too many of his starts in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   And who was on the mound for the Astros when Cordova pitched
nine no-hit innings in 1997? You guessed it _ Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even want to get into that,'' said Holt, who received
the lowest run support among Astros starters in 1999. ``Cordova
pitched a hell of a game, and you have to give him credit. I felt
good; I just threw a couple of bad pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   More specifically, he threw pitches in the direction of home
plate, which is about all a pitcher had to do to be victimized by
Pirates right fielder Brian Giles, who was 5-for-5 with four RBIs
and a pair of home runs, both off Holt.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't flip anything up there without him hitting it,''
Holt said.
</P>
<P>
   Between Cordova and Giles, the Astros didn't have a chance. They
were fortunate to win the first two games of the series, which
assured them of returning to Houston for tonight's regular-season
opener at Enron Field with a winning record.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you win the first two games, obviously you want that
sweep,'' said Bill Spiers. ``But you have to be happy to take two
out of three against these guys with the pitching they have.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros had three baserunners through two innings on a trio
of walks. But Cordova retired 16 consecutive batters from the third
inning until Meluskey's double off the center-field wall. Meluskey
scored on Tim Bogar's double to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just thinking to myself, `Make him get the ball up,'''
Meluskey said. ``I saw it was up, I swung, and luckily I got the
good part of the bat on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cordova kept the Astros off balance with an assortment of
pitches thrown from a variety of arm angles _ a combination that
made him more difficult to solve than the Elian Gonzalez dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't see any pitch in any at-bat that was up in the zone
that I could hit hard. He made some good pitches,'' Spiers said.
</P>
<P>
   Astros right fielder Moises Alou, who brought a career .417
batting average against Cordova into Thursday's game, wasn't
completely awed by the performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He pitched a good game, but I don't mind facing him,'' Alou
said of Cordova. ``He kept throwing (pitches) away, and we kept
swinging at them. You have to give him credit, but we helped him.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, all the help Cordova needed came in the third and
fifth innings, when Giles blasted solo homers off Holt. Giles also
drove in one of the Pirates' two runs in the sixth and had an RBI
triple in a four-run eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giles had a hell of a series,'' Alou said. ``Everything he
hit, he hit it hard. He can play. The only reason more people don't
know about him is because he plays (in Pittsburgh).''
</P>
<P>
   Giles, who was 8-for-11 in the series, certainly got the Astros'
attention. Cordova, of course, already had it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
